<SLUG> BC-WEBVAN-LOSSES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WEBVAN SEES REVENUES, LOSSES GROW  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Webvan Group has delivered groceries and other
goods to 87,000 Bay Area households so far this year, giving the
Internet grocer first-quarter revenues of $16.3 million, up 79
percent from the preceding quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Foster City, Calif., company spent more on marketing and
advertising to snare those customers. Its loss widened to $57.8
million (18 cents per share) from $11.7 million (21 cents) in the
fourth quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-forma loss, which excludes noncash compensation and
related expenses, was $38.7 million (12 cents), up from $25.7
million (9 cents) in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The results beat both Webvan's own forecasts and Wall Street's
expectations. Analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial had
predicted a pro-forma loss of 13 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Webvan opened for business in the Bay Area, its first market, in
June, so year-to-year comparisons are not applicable.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it is on track for rapid national expansion
that will put it in 15 markets by the end of 2001. Webvan will
launch its service in Atlanta in May; it said it is serving 200
test customers there. A Chicago opening is planned for the third
quarter. Seattle, Baltimore, and Bergen County, N.J., will come
online during the fourth quarter, executives said. The company also
has leases for distribution centers that will service New York
City, Dallas, Denver, Boston, Philadelphia, Washington, D.C., and
Orange County, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to build one of the largest companies to come out of
Silicon Valley,'' said chief executive George Shaheen. ``With
operating quarters like this, we feel well on our way to achieving
that vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Although groceries account for the bulk of the company's
business, Webvan is using its delivery system to sell a variety of
other goods. It added books, office supplies, premium pet food,
postage stamps, BART tickets and bridge toll cards during the
quarter. Shaheen said the company plans to introduce apparel,
prescription drugs, electronics, cosmetics, CDs and videos in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to give a breakdown for grocery versus
nongrocery items. It said the average order size was $90.33, up
from $81.31 last quarter. Seventy-eight percent of customers
repeated their business.
</P>
<P>
   During a conference call, analysts speculated that the company
is spending about $210 to acquire each new customer and is serving
about 2,200 customers a day. Shaheen said those estimates were ``in
the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Webvan's stock has taken the same Wall Street drubbing as other
Internet stores; it is down 61 percent for the year. But analysts
said it has brighter prospects than other e-tailers, pointing to
such factors as its door-to-door delivery, automated distribution
system, mix of products and good customer repeat rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe someone can give you a better deal on tuna fish over the
Internet but if you have to wait seven days for it, you're not
going to bother,'' said Peter Swan, an analyst with Pacific Growth
Equities in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   He considered the revenues ``fabulous,'' and was equally
enthusiastic about Webvan's 25 percent gross margins.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen predicted revenues would grow 40 to 50 percent in the
second quarter and would total $150 million to $160 million for all
of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Results were announced after the market closed. Webvan rose 81
cents, to $6.31. In after-hours trading it went up an additional 3
cents.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
