<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NET WORTH: BEAR MARKET SHUTTING WINDOW OF OPPORTUNITY FOR IPOS  &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Glub, glub, glub.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sound of more and more IPOs going underwater _ Wall
Street speak for stocks that sink below their initial public
offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 156 Bay Area companies that went public this year or
last, 41 are trading below their IPO prices. A full list is on Page
B2 and it includes high-profile sinkings like Palm, Webvan,
Pets.com, E-stamp, Salon.com, Fogdog, Quokka Sports, Women.com and
Next Card.
</P>
<P>
   The next sound you will hear is the IPO window slowly scraping
shut.
</P>
<P>
   Since last Tuesday, when the Dow and Nasdaq took investors on a
thrill ride, eight companies have postponed or withdrawn their
IPOs, including Rigel Pharmaceuticals and Linuxcare (both San
Francisco), Drugabuse Sciences (Menlo Park) and Lexar Media
(Fremont).
</P>
<P>
   Many deals are still getting done, but some at
lower-than-expected prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had nine deals priced this week. Four of the nine _
Corillian, Asiacontent.com, DDI and HealthStream _ were priced
below initial terms,'' says David Hirschkorn of IPO.com.
</P>
<P>
   And those outrageous first-day gains that IPO investors have
come to expect have shrunk to merely enormous.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of this year until the Nasdaq index peaked on
March 10, the average IPO soared 116 percent on its first day. From
March 13 through Wednesday, the average first-day return was just
42 percent, Hirschkorn reports.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the Nasdaq rebounds quickly _ it's down 27 percent from
its high _ experts predict that only companies with big brand names
or really novel ideas will be able to go public in the next few
months. And even some of those may not keep investors' attention
for long.
</P>
<P>
   Web portal AltaVista, scheduled to premiere next week, ``will
struggle to hold its opening premiums,'' predicts David Menlow,
president of IPOfinancial.com.
</P>
<P>
   The following week, AT&AMP;T is expected to float the biggest IPO
ever when it issues a tracking stock for its wireless division.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T Wireless will probably do OK at the opening,'' he
predicts, but will have to be a long-term hold for most investors.
</P>
<P>
   Menlow says outrageous valuations ``are not a thing of the past,
but they are not a thing of the present.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, where IPOs have become as common as monster
homes and traffic jams, a prolonged slump in the new-issues market
could have an impact on things like home prices, car sales and job
hopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised to see anything happen over the next few
weeks, but if we move into an extended bear market, in three or six
months from now it will clearly ripple through the economy,'' says
Todd Carter, head of investment banking for Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephen Levy, director of the Center for Continuing Study of
the California Economy, thinks the IPO market will have minimal
effect on the local economy, outside of housing prices in Palo Alto
and Atherton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever is going on relative to stock valuations is not
affecting long-term prospects for the real economy,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming amount of money that's earned by residents in
the Bay Area doesn't come from financial assets.'' And to the
extent that it does, most of it is coming from employees at places
like Hewlett-Packard, Cisco, Intel and Applied Materials, who got
their stock five or 10 years ago. ``The number of people who work
at these companies dwarf the number of people at startups,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't hold your breath waiting for Bay Area home
prices to go down.
</P>
<P>
   Many people view the IPO slowdown as a natural and even healthy
reaction to what had become an overheated market.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the market is a filter, it has been very coarse,'' Carter
says. ``A lot of companies have been able to go public earlier in
their life cycle, placing more risk on the public investor who is
not always able to evaluate that risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, when the IPO window is almost shut, only the best
companies can squeeze through it.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks and months, Menlow advises investors to
``look for IPOs that are priced at the upper end of filing range or
above it; those will get the most attention.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
