<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SQUEAK PAST PHILLIES, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Rick Reed has been rewarded with a victory only
once this season, but each time he has pitched, he has lifted the
New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   He worked eight innings in the second game in Japan, giving the
Mets a chance to win and making the 12-hour flight back to New York
bearable. In his next start, last Friday, he beat the Los Angeles
Dodgers to give the Mets their only victory over a span of nine
days.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday night in Philadelphia, though he was not the
winning pitcher, Reed worked seven innings. He allowed one run and
put the Mets in position for a 2-1 victory over the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   With Armando Benitez working a scoreless ninth for the save, the
Mets avoided being swept by the Phillies and won for the first time
since Reed's last start.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the ninth inning of a 1-1 game, Jay Payton
singled to center field off Scott Aldred, the losing pitcher. It
was Payton's third single of the game, and when Mike Piazza lashed
a double to left-center with two out off Amaury Telemaco, Payton
raced home from first.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ron Gant threw to second baseman Mickey
Morandini, whose relay to the plate arrived just late as Payton
slid in safely.
</P>
<P>
   Reed entered the game with an 0.57 earned run average, best in
the National League, and he left it after seven innings with an
0.79 ERA. He has allowed only two earned runs in 222/3 innings.
Both runs have been on homers, the first to Gary Sheffield of the
Dodgers in the 2-1 victory Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lieberthal hit the second home run off Reed's first pitch
in the seventh inning on Thursday night. Lieberthal is a nemesis of
Reed's. The Phillies catcher has a .353 career average against the
Mets right-hander, and all six of his hits have been for extra
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal was robbed of a hit in the fifth inning when right
fielder Derek Bell made a diving stab of his line drive. Bell made
another fine catch on the next hitter, racing in and rolling to
grab a shallow liner by Morandini.
</P>
<P>
   Bell also had three singles, his second game in a row with three
hits. He hit a home run to win the Mets' Shea Stadium opener, but
until Wednesday he had not been hitting like one of the best
players in the league. He entered the game Wednesday with a .138
average.
</P>
<P>
   Bell led off the second inning with a single off the Phillies
starter Randy Wolf, who walked Benny Agbayani and Rey Ordonez to
load the bases for Reed. Reed flied out to center field, scoring
Bell to give the Mets a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine used his first entirely right-handed
lineup of the season on Thursday night against the left-hander
Wolf. Melvin Mora replaced Robin Ventura at third base and batted
leadoff in place of left fielder Rickey Henderson. Agbayani made
his first start of the season in left field.
</P>
</TEXT>
