<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUVS-SALES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LOW MILEAGE DOESN'T SLOW SUV BUYERS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Jeanette Scott was poking around a Colma,
Calif., car dealership this week in search of new wheels for
herself and her 7-month-old son. Her interest was drawn to a Chevy
Astro van selling for about $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   Then she turned toward the vehicle at its side: a
brand-spanking-new Cadillac Escalade sport utility vehicle going
for $46,000 and boasting an unimpressive 12 miles per gallon in
fuel performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' 19-year-old Scott observed. ``But it's too
expensive, and it's a gas-guzzler.''
</P>
<P>
   What if money wasn't a factor?
</P>
<P>
   ``If money wasn't a factor,'' she mused, her face lighting up,
``I'd definitely get one of these.''
</P>
<P>
   While Scott remains bound in her decision making by economic
constraints, nearly all those who do end up buying an SUV nowadays
have no such worries.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the key reason sales of SUVs continue to soar in the
Bay Area and throughout the nation _ despite their hefty price
tags, despite gas prices hovering near $2 a gallon, and despite
safety concerns that the behemoths can endanger occupants and other
motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't looking at the gas crisis,'' said Lou Corbin,
sales manager at Serramonte Ford, the biggest Ford dealership on
the Peninsula. ``They aren't looking at inflation. They're taking
money from the stock market and buying SUVs.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, sales of SUVs jumped nearly 15 percent
during the first three months of the year, according to the
National Automobile Dealers' Association.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, SUVs costing about $35,000 and up now account
for roughly half _ and sometimes more _ of new-vehicle sales at
many dealerships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last month, we had our best month in four years,'' said
Michael Herrera, sales manager at Stewart Cadillac Oldsmobile
Chevrolet in Colma. ``People aren't saying anything about gas
mileage at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In Menlo Park, Calif., Mark Linton, sales manager at Anderson
Chevrolet, said fully three-quarters of all sales at his lot these
days are SUVs. ``We sell every single one we get,'' he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Being in Silicon Valley, Linton added that his customers pay
entirely in cash for their big, shiny new toys ``all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Moreno, a spokesman for the California State Automobile
Association, said concern about high gas prices doesn't even enter
the picture for most local SUV buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a booming economy,'' he observed. ``People feel
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   The average price of self-service unleaded gas in California
peaked a few weeks ago at a record $1.79 a gallon and has since
eased by a few cents, according to data compiled by the U.S.
Department of Energy.
</P>
<P>
   But many Northern Californians have yet to feel any relief.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent survey of pump prices, the automobile
association found that the average cost of a gallon of gas in San
Francisco rose 4 cents, to $1.94.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost in San Jose, Calif., increased 3 cents, to
$1.88, while Oakland, Calif.'s average gas price climbed 3 cents,
to $1.87, and Santa Rosa, Calif.'s was up 4 cents, to $1.82.
</P>
<P>
   One would think that such considerations would be very much on
the minds of Bay Area SUV buyers.
</P>
<P>
   One would be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not even discussed,'' said Frank Fragomeni, general
manager of Stewart Infiniti in Colma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy's the best it's ever been,'' he said. ``Wages are
at an all-time high. Unemployment is at an all-time low. People are
going to enjoy life as they see fit.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, dealers say, means the typical SUV customer is not
getting hung up on nagging questions about mileage. Nor is she (or
he; the gender breakdown among buyers is essentially even)
particularly troubled by reports that huge, road-hogging SUVs can
maul smaller vehicles during collisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``SUV drivers are looking out for themselves,'' Fragomeni said.
``They're thinking about themselves when it comes to the safety
aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   The safety aspect clearly favors those behind the wheel of an
SUV. With average weights running about 1,000 pounds more than cars
and body frames as much as 28 inches off the ground, SUVs are
almost scientifically designed to prevail in crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, however, this means an SUV will literally run over a
smaller vehicle. Studies have shown that in collisions between cars
and light trucks, including SUVs, 80 percent of subsequent
fatalities are to the car drivers.
</P>
<P>
   This has prompted automakers and federal regulators to debate
ways to improve road safety in light of the proliferation of SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   But for most if not all buyers, such issues are barely a blip on
the radar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard anyone say that they'd hate to get into an
accident because of what would happen to the other guy,'' commented
Herrera at the Stewart dealership. ``I never hear that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, dealers say they don't hear much from customers
regarding the way that massive SUVs all but blind trailing
motorists to impending road conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Not that SUV buyers are unaware of the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some say that they were looking forward to now
blocking someone else's vision,'' said David Dobby, a salesman at
Falore Chrysler Jeep Daewoo in Colma.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few facts regarding SUV safety, courtesy of the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration:
</P>
<P>
   -- About 36 percent of fatal SUV crashes in 1998 involved
top-heavy vehicles rolling over _ more than twice the rate for
cars.
</P>
<P>
   -- More than 2,000 deaths resulted that year when a light truck
or SUV hit the side of a car; only 276 deaths resulted when a car
hit a light truck or SUV.
</P>
<P>
   -- More than 1,500 fatalities were caused by light trucks or
SUVs hitting cars head-on; about 450 deaths occurred when a car ran
into the front of a light truck or SUV.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Perry, general sales manager at Serramonte Dodge
Mitsubishi, said nearly all his SUV customers say safety is one of
their main considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be durability and off-road capability,'' he noted.
``Now, the majority never take their SUVs off the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuel efficiency, Perry added, ``is never, ever a decision-making
factor,'' and ``very rarely is crash testing a subject that comes
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, these were not the most important points for 50-year-old
Evans Noble as she inspected a $39,000 Lexus SUV at Lexus of
Serramonte.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's roomy,'' she said of the large, plush machine. ``As long
as I'm comfortable, that's the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Katz, the dealership's general manager, said questions
about mileage or the safety of other motorists ``never come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, all dealers agree that SUVs are here to stay and
that the number of SUVs on the road will keep growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``BMW was the yuppie car in the '80s and '90s,'' said Serramonte
Ford's Corbin. ``People now want something they can get more use
out of.''
</P>
<P>
   He cast a satisfied look at the fat SUVs dominating his
showroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around here,'' Corbin said, ``everyone has money, and they
want to own what they want to own.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
