A6433 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GAS-GLUTTONS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-14 1634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-GLUTTONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DRIVERS COMPLAIN ABOUT GAS PRICES, BUT DON'T CUT BACK  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Carol Felton navigated traffic jams, open road
and twisting highway the other night during her 55-mile commute
home to Soquel, Calif., a seaside community just south of Santa
Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   Living near the country is more important to her than the
hour-and-20-minute drive to work in Redwood City, Calif., and the
extra costs that come with it.
</P>
<P>
   The recent gas price increase, which Felton calls outrageous,
has added significantly to those commute expenses. Although Felton,
a vice president at a public relations company, describes herself
as a thrifty person who cuts coupons, she drives as much now as she
did when gas was cheaper by nearly half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like paying this at all,'' Felton said after partially
filling her 1994 Infiniti with premium unleaded at $2.12 a gallon,
then merging into the heavy traffic on Highway 101. ``But what else
can I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months after gas prices in the Bay Area began to
surge, car owners are still complaining. But as much as drivers
talk about reducing their fuel cost, they have so far avoided the
most obvious solution _ consuming less gas.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Area public transportation agencies report increased
ridership, but that is true nearly every spring. Company van pools
are no busier than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, traffic on the Bay Bridge has increased.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of sport utility vehicles are strong.
</P>
<P>
   The American Automobile Association predicts a big summer travel
season.
</P>
<P>
   And tourists are still renting about 15 gas-guzzling Winnebagos
a day at Cruise America, a recreational home dealer in Oakland,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling fact is that gas deliveries, a key
indicator of gas consumption, have remained stable despite the
recent run-up in prices. Deliveries increased slightly, to an
average of 8.087 million barrels a day in the past two months
compared with 8.086 million barrels a day during the same period
last year, according to the American Petroleum Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Complex Reasons
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for this unyielding appetite for gas are complex,
according to drivers, economists, psychologists and oil industry
experts. While the lack of an alternative to gas explains a lot
about consumer devotion, so does the inconvenience of public
transportation, habit and the sentiment that gas at $2 a gallon is
still affordable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers don't believe that the high prices will last,`` said
John Mowen, a marketing professor who specializes in consumer
behavior at Oklahoma State University and is president of the
Society for Consumer Psychology. ``So the net effect is that you
don't see much behavioral change, but you see a lot of griping.``
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very slow to change a fundamental lifestyle,``
Mowen added, ``and part of the fundamental lifestyle in this
country is the love affair with the car.``
</P>
<P>
   Felton, the commuter, provides a window into why many consumers
appear to disregard simple economic rules of price and demand.
While she has a handful alternatives to driving 625 miles a week,
they are generally more inconvenient than leaving her car parked at
home.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most obvious ways for Felton to reduce her gas bill
to zero would be to use public transportation. Although such a trip
is feasible from Soquel to Redwood City, it would require taking
two buses, a train and then a shuttle, adding at least an hour to
her commute each way.
</P>
<P>
   Carpooling Won't Work
</P>
<P>
   Carpooling is another option that Felton has considered. But
arranging one, she said, would be difficult given her varying work
schedule and the frequency with which she needs a car during the
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with carpooling is that I never know until the
last minute if I'll have a client meeting,`` said Felton, who was
unaware that private carpool agencies could help match her with a
driving partner. ``And these meetings can be all over the place _
San Jose, Fremont, Palo Alto _ so I can't take public
transportation to get to them.``
</P>
<P>
   Home Office Alternative
</P>
<P>
   While stopped in one of several traffic jams during her drive
home, Felton mentioned the possibility of working at home one day a
week. Though it is an appealing idea that could save about $12 in
gas per week, she said, something always comes up to ruin it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell myself that I'll stay at home next Friday,`` Felton
said. ``But no matter what I do, a meeting always comes up. I need
to block a day out on the calender and not let anything stop it.``
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Felton fills her car with gas twice a week for a
total of $70. The higher gas prices during the past two months have
probably cost her an extra $120.
</P>
<P>
   That is taking into account Felton's modest attempts to reduce
her gas bill. At times, she fills her car with midgrade unleaded
gas instead of more expensive premium, contrary to her car
manufacturer's recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Felton also tries to buy gas near her home in Soquel, where
prices can be 10 cents a gallon cheaper than on the Peninsula,
where she works. On this evening, she bought gas near work, but
just a few gallons to get home.
</P>
<P>
   Such a measured reaction to high prices is not the tactic that
Felton, who often shops for bargains, takes in the grocery store.
When the price of fruit and meat rise, she simply stops buying.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have found that her pattern of gas buying is the one
followed by most Americans: Consumers tolerate higher gas prices
more than higher food prices.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a 10 percent increase in grape prices causes a
nearly 12 percent decline in demand, according to the U.S.
Department of Agriculture. A similar increase in gas prices softens
demand by only 2 percent in the short term, according to Carol
Dahl, an economics professor at the Colorado School of Mines who
specializes in the energy industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of Choice
</P>
<P>
   Felton's explanation for this phenomenon echoed that of the
experts. It all comes down to choice, she said, and a supermarket
is full of them while a gas station is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the price of chicken goes up, I buy turkey,`` Felton
said. ``With gas, the alternatives are not that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Severin Borenstein, director of the Energy Institute at the
University of California at Berkeley, agreed that reducing gas
consumption is difficult, especially for people who live in
outlying areas. But he added that today's prices are not high
enough to prompt most drivers to use less fuel.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, gas prices adjusted for inflation and taxes are
about $1 a gallon cheaper now than the peak of a big gas-price
spike in 1981. In addition, gas currently accounts for only a
little more than 7 cents out of the 31 cents a mile it costs to
operate an average car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuneups, new tires, repairs and insurance cost much more,
Borenstein said. ``If you are a family going on vacation, driving
is still a lot cheaper than flying.``
</P>
<P>
   Boom Is a Factor
</P>
<P>
   Many experts cited the nation's economic health as a big factor
contributing to unwavering gas consumption. The average family's
income has grown significantly during the past five years, making
spending a few more dollars on gas per tank relatively
inconsequential, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Consider who buys many of the gas-guzzling vehicles, Borenstein
said. The average buyer of a Lexus, a luxury car with relatively
low gas mileage, has an income of $200,000 a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, public reaction to high gas prices _ aside from
complaining _ is delayed by at least a year. Consumers often take
fuel efficiency into account when they are considering buying a new
car or moving to a new home that may be further from work.
</P>
<P>
   Dahl, the economist who said gas consumption declines only
marginally because of higher prices in the short term, said studies
show the long term is a different matter. The effect of people
buying smaller cars and moving closer to work causes gas
consumption to decline a total of 5 percent in the long run for
every 10 percent price increase, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a change in behavior would presumably hinder sales of sport
utility vehicles. Currently, sales of those cars are at record
levels because of the strong economy and low interest rates,
according to the National Automobile Dealers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller SUVs
</P>
<P>
   Yet within those results is perhaps a sign of things to come.
Sales of smaller, more fuel-efficient sport utility vehicles are
growing up to three times faster than the larger models.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a reaction to a 33 percent increase in gas prices
last year. Or it could simply be a change in consumer taste.
</P>
<P>
   Such a change in big car sales would follow a precedent set in
1996 and 1997, when gas prices rose by about 12 cents a gallon to
$1.30. Within a few months of the spike, cars with smaller engines
made up 5 percent more of total car sales than just before the
price increase, according to the National Automobile Dealers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't change the engine in the car they're driving,''
said Paul Taylor, an economist with the National Automobile
Association. ``They do it when they buy a new car later on.``
</P>
<P>
   Even though statistical data show that it takes consumers at
least several months to modify gas use, many people never change.
Felton, for example, said that she has no plans to move and that
her next car will probably be as large as the one she has now
because it is comfortable and spacious.
</P>
<P>
   Although she complains about gas prices now, she seems willing
to pay more, at least until BART comes to Santa Cruz. Asked whether
$3 a gallon would be too much, she said ``I don't know when I'd say
enough is enough.``
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at verne(AT)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
