<HEADER>
A6436 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-TAXDODGERS-TRACKDOWN-     04-14 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXDODGERS-TRACKDOWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES SEEKS STATE LAW TO TRACK DOWN TAX DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Desperate for new sources of revenue, Los Angeles
city officials are pressing for state legislation that would help
them track down thousands of tax-dodging businesses and collect as
much as $66 million more a year.
</P>
<P>
   Already the City Council has plans to spend the money, although
a taxpayer watchdog group asserts the city's new tax collection
plan would invade people's privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, an estimated 66,000 businesses avoid paying city
business taxes, but proposed legislation would give city officials
access to state Franchise Tax Board records to identify the
scofflaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we have responsible businesses paying their share and the
others basically thumbing their nose,'' said Councilwoman Laura
Chick. ``It's a very bad message to send to law-abiding citizens
and businesses that there's no consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles will collect an estimated $314 million in business
taxes this fiscal year from the more than 230,000 registered
businesses, ranging from small, home-based operations paying the
minimum $200 to major corporations paying more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, more than a third of businesses operating within city
limits simply don't pay - and the city has been ineffective in
getting compliance.
</P>
<P>
   To change that, the City Council is championing a new effort by
Assemblyman Gil Cedillo, D-Los Angeles, and the chances of passage
are good, officials said. Cedillo said the legislation likely won't
hit the state Senate floor until late summer.
</P>
<P>
   One statewide taxpayer watchdog group said the legislation
``smacks of big brotherism.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Coupal, president of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayer's
Association, said the release of the state's tax information to the
city amounts to a violation of privacy and that the cities will use
the information to go after tiny, home-based businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cities are flush with cash; they are just looking for
more,'' Coupal said.
</P>
<P>
   Not according to council members, who already have plans for the
new money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to have the businesses that are honoring their
obligation subsidize the businesses that aren't,'' said Councilman
Michael Feuer.
</P>
<P>
   The council sent a measure to two committees, including the ad
hoc Committee on Business Tax Reform, that proposes funneling most
of the anticipated dollars into a program to simplify the city's
maze of business tax codes.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Chick said, the city should use the bulk of the
dollars to upgrade its antiquated tax computer system and improve
city services to lure new business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good faith effort to say that the top priority for
these funds is to further business tax reform efforts,'' Chick
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, the architect of the city's business tax
reform efforts, supports dedicating the funds to the reform
movement, said Deputy Mayor Rocky Delgadillo. Plus, several local
business groups support the state measure, including the Central
City Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that there is a benefit if we can see tax reform as a
result,'' said Hilary Norton Orozco, legislative affairs director
for the group.
</P>
<P>
   One of the businesses that already pay taxes has other thoughts
on how to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Beck, owner of a bicycle repair shop, said the city should
use the money to provide low-interest loans and other aid to the
law-abiding small business owners who now are shouldering the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run, that's where the tax money comes from,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related issue, the council has lifted its longstanding
opposition to related legislation that helps shield free-lance
screen writers and musicians from paying local business taxes.
</P>
<P>
   After five months of negotiations with writers' union and
business leaders and city finance authorities, the council on
Tuesday unanimously agreed to support AB 83, which defines certain
types of employment that are sheltered from local government
business tax.
</P>
<P>
   Local writers, who objected to paying the tax as independent
contractors, were pushing the legislation. However, city officials
objected to an earlier version that limited the city's ability to
require permits and licenses from home-based workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened today is a great step,'' said Cheryl Rhoden,
Writers Guild of America spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
