<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6437 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-COACH-INVESTIGATION-K     04-14 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACH-INVESTIGATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTS REVEAL PERSONAL STRUGGLE BEHIND PLAYER'S SUMMER-LEAGUE
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and STEVE ROCK  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With its teal three-point arcs and tight,
bleacherless sidelines, the Guardian Angels Church gym on Westport
Road was familiar to Schlagle High School senior Andre Williams.
But the ``coach'' he met on the night of May 27, 1998, was not.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different type of coach for a different kind of game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of running drills with summer-league coach Myron Piggie,
Williams and an uncle met with private investigator Ted Knox.
Beginning at 7:30 p.m. and for the next two hours, they discussed
how to tape record Piggie offering Williams $100 a week to play on
his summer-league team.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting would ultimately lead to a two-year federal
investigation that would shake college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Knox had been hired by Tom Grant, the chief executive officer of
LabOne Inc. whose family foundation once sponsored Piggie's
summer-league team. Knox remembers Williams as skittish that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little nervous, but he listened to what he needed to
do,'' Knox told The Kansas City Star. ``I assured him we would be
there for him.... Andre just wanted to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox put a tape recorder on Williams' home phone the next day.
The ensuing tapes resulted in the indictments unveiled Thursday
against Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   Through his attorney, Williams, now a freshman at Oklahoma State
University, declined to comment for this article, saying it is time
to get on with his life. Piggie was in federal custody Thursday and
could not be reached for comment. Piggie's attorney declined to
comment after his initial court appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' account, however, is set out in detail in documents
prepared with his cooperation and released to The Star recently by
Oklahoma State. The letters and reports, based on interviews with
Williams by university officials, were prepared in December and
January as they appealed Williams' suspension for NCAA rules
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other interviews, Grant foundation records and
information from Thursday's federal charges, it's now possible to
paint the richest public picture yet of how authorities think
Piggie operated.
</P>
<P>
   And they show why the NCAA ended up suspending seven big-time
college players this past season amid a searing reassessment of
amateur basketball.  &LR; brk:Unlikely duo and the dream team
</P>
<P>
   Williams' meeting in Guardian Angels Church gym with the private
investigator had its roots at least three years before in the
flourishing relationship between an unlikely pair: Tom Grant and
Myron Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   The streetwise coach and the Johnson County multimillionaire had
teamed up to attract high school basketball players to teams
sponsored by Grant. Such nonscholastic teams have become
increasingly important to players eager to hone their skills.
</P>
<P>
   At times the two wrangled wayward players, making sure they made
it to practice, and class.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 through June 1998, Grant's foundation wrote checks to
Piggie totaling $184,435 covering salary and expenses, Thursday's
indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the focus of Piggie's and Grant's attention wasn't
Williams but rather JaRon Rush, a restless high school phenom whom
Grant had taken into his home and treated like a son.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 letter to the NCAA, Grant described his feelings about
Piggie:
</P>
<P>
   ``He has worked with me in trying to help JaRon become a
responsible adult,'' Grant wrote. ``Myron is not an educated man,
but he has a good heart and works every afternoon with JaRon on
helping him improve his game....Myron has been a positive influence
on JaRon....''
</P>
<P>
   By the spring of 1997, the grooming of Rush had begun to pay
off. Piggie assembled what is remembered as a summer-league dream
team _ including Rush, Williams and future NBA players Korleone
Young and Corey Maggette.
</P>
<P>
   That 1997 summer team appeared unstoppable as it began the
national circuit of Amateur Athletic Union tournaments and shoe
company events _ a whirlwind of games played before top college
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   With some of the country's best college prospects under his
wing, more money started coming Piggie's way. Nike Inc. signed him
to a consulting contract worth up to $425,000, and sports agents
began giving him money to represent their interests in the amateur
basketball community, according to the federal indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said in an interview last week that the attention began to
change Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a guy who suddenly had all these college basketball
coaches calling him on a daily basis,'' Grant said. ``And then (CBS
basketball commentator and Nike consultant) George Raveling would
call him three or four times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Raveling was unavailable for comment Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The money also had its effect. In 1997, Piggie bought two houses
and leased a Toyota Land Cruiser, Jackson County records show.
</P>
<P>
   But late 1997 also brought the first hints of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That fall The Basketball Times published an article that
contained allegations Piggie had taken the Nike shoes he was
supposed to pass on to athletes for free and instead sold them for
personal profit, an allegation Piggie has denied in the past. The
article also contained details of his criminal history,
specifically a felony drug conviction in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confronted him in the fall of 1997 about the article,''
Grant said in the interview. ``I knew he had a criminal background,
but I didn't know how extensive. He denied all the allegations
against him about dealing the shoes. I was close to the guy. I
believed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Piggie's denials, Grant withdrew support for Piggie's
traveling team, but agreed to pay him for six months under a
``severance'' agreement.  &LR; brk:`Lack of trust'
</P>
<P>
   Piggie soon started assembling his next summer team, then
sponsored only by Nike. Schlagle's Williams was a natural prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a supporting player on Piggie's dream team the
summer before, he had developed into a big-time college prospect.
He again began playing for Piggie in the spring of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams had worries off the court. According to the
Oklahoma State records, he was concerned that he didn't have the
grades to graduate from Schlagle that May, much less qualify
academically for college.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie's solution ultimately contributed to Williams'
disenchantment with his coach. He suggested to Williams and his
uncle, Al Collins, that Williams spend an additional year in an
East Coast prep school to sharpen his grades. Furthermore, Piggie
promised to ``get him into'' Hargrave Military Academy, Oklahoma
State letters assert.
</P>
<P>
   But as weeks passed, Williams and his uncle grew frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma State administrator wrote that ``whenever Andre or
Mr. Collins asked Piggie what Andre's status was at Hargrave,
Piggie would respond `I'm taking care of it.' To make a long story
short, Piggie made unfulfilled promises to Andre and delayed his
opportunities to get into a prep school or other education
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   To paper over the rift, according to the Oklahoma State
documents, Piggie began giving Williams money. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
