A6438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT     04-14 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT RANGERS, 5-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Baseball seemed like a burden to Paul O'Neill at the
beginning of last season. He did not hit the ball hard very often,
and when he did, there was always someone making a diving catch at
the other end. At the height of his struggles, he acknowledged he
had thoughts of retiring.
</P>
<P>
   But he is back at 37, hitting and running as if he might last
past his 40th birthday. O'Neill had three hits on Thursday night
against former teammate Kenny Rogers, spurring both of the Yankees'
rallies as they beat Texas, 5-1, at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A bases-loaded triple by Jorge Posada in the sixth capped the
second rally sparked by O'Neil, broke a 1-1 tie and thrust Orlando
Hernandez to victory.
</P>
<P>
   The only real blemish on the pitching line of Hernandez was an
unearned run: El Duque toyed with the Rangers, allowing just one
hit to the last 29 batters he faced, three hits in eight innings,
and improved his record to 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers loaded the bases with one out in the second inning,
on an error by Tito Martinez at first and two walks. Blowing on his
hand before each pitch, Hernandez fell behind in the count three
balls and one strike against Tom Evans, then pumped a high fastball
that Evans fouled off.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez fired his next pitch just a little higher, out of the
strike zone. Evans swung underneath and missed, a strikeout. It was
a classic example of Hernandez using a hitter's own aggressiveness
against him.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Clayton, the Texas lead-off hitter, followed and hit a
groundball at Alfonso Soriano, a relatively easy chance. But this
is Soriano's first week as a third baseman and once again he
misplayed the ball, which ricocheted off him and into the air. All
the runners were safe, a run scoring. The Yanks' third basemen have
six errors in the last six games.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez recovered, retiring Chad Curtis on a roller back to
the mound, and as Soriano ran off the field, he tapped Hernandez on
the backside.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hernandez needed reassurance. In his first three
starts, he has pitched in four bases loaded situations, all with
less than two out, and he has allowed just two runs _ the first on
an infield single last week, the other on Soriano's error.
Opponents are 1 for 10 against Hernandez with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers pitched pretty well, too, holding the Yankees to a run in
the first five innings. But O'Neill, who singled and stole a base
and scored in the first inning, singled to left field, his third
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams coaxed a walk from Rogers, and O'Neill and
Williams advanced to second and third on a groundout. Roberto Kelly
walked after falling behind 0-2 to load the bases, bringing Posada
to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Bosman, the Texas pitching coach, went to the mound to
speak with Rogers, and as he did so, Curtis sprinted to center
field, to speak with Ruben Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   What Curtis said to Mateo was unclear, but when play resumed,
the Rangers' center fielder was shifted toward right-center _ and
Posada slashed a line drive toward left center that Mateo could not
reach.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, Williams and Kelly all scored, Posada slid into third
with a triple and three runs batted in. Posada subsequently scored
when Shane Spencer grounded the ball through the Rangers' drawn-in
infield. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
