<HEADER>
A6444 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-PANTHERS-N     04-14 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS TOP PANTHERS IN FIRST GAME OF PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils started their
Stanley Cup playoffs in an ideal manner by scoring two goals on
their first four shots. When they built a three-goal lead later in
the first period, it looked as if they would treat their fans to a
lopsided victory. But the Devils' early intensity evaporated
quickly and they barely held on Thursday night for a 4-3 victory
over the Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Devils did not look convincing, the victory at
Continental Arena put them on the right track to shed their recent
history of early playoff exits. But their fans seem wary; they drew
a crowd of 15,024, which was 4,016 short of a sellout. The Devils
had asked their supporters to wear white, but only a small segment
chose to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils succeeded in limiting Pavel Bure, the league's
leading goal scorer with 58 goals, to only an assist. To neutralize
Bure, the Devils relied mostly on Scott Stevens, their captain and
spiritual leader, who also scored the game's crucial first goal.
</P>
<P>
   Petr Sykora, Sergei Brylin and Scott Gomez scored the other
goals for the Devils against Panther goalie Mike Vernon, who could
have prevented two of the goals. Vernon faced 33 shots and had no
memorable saves.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the ice, Martin Brodeur had an average game
by his standards. He allowed goals by Rob Niedermayer, Peter
Worrell and Mike Sillinger. Brodeur, who faced 23 shots, should
have prevented Worrell's goal, which eluded him over the glove from
far away on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Losing their intensity rather abruptly after gaining an early
lead is likely to be one of the matters Coach Larry Robinson will
discuss with his players, who engaged the Panthers in pushing and
shoving matches at the conclusion of the game. The Devils took a
1-0 lead in the four-of-seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils came out bursting with enthusiasm and mindful of
their stigma: early exits in the playoffs in the last three
seasons. Stevens, who scored two goals in last spring's first-round
elimination by the Pittsburgh Penguins, opened the scoring just 98
seconds into the game. Taking the puck from a face-off that Bobby
Holik won, Stevens found the upper right corner from the left
circle with a blistering shot that gave Vernon no chance.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd barely had time to settle down beforeSykora gave the
fans more reason to roar. He scored with a backhander as he came
around the goal from right to left, making the score 2-0 with 4:02
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Things got even better for the Devils with 4:32 left in the
first, when Brylin beat Vernon over the left shoulder from the left
circle after the Panthers had several chances to clear their zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils lost their focus for the rest of the period and paid
the price as goals by Niedermayer and Worrell closed the gap to a
goal before the first intermission. Niedermayer scored the first
from close range on the left with 4:05 left, and Worrell beat
Brodeur over the glove from the left circle moments after he came
out of the penalty box, with 16.5 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Worrell's goal, his first ever in the playoffs, was a shot that
Brodeur should have handled. The Devils' goalie made up for it by
denying Bure from point-blank range on the right just 72 seconds
into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   An unassisted goal by Gomez from the left circle that Vernon
should have stopped extended the Devils' lead at 7:21, but the
Devils looked unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   They had difficulty in their zone for most of the second period,
but the only blemish against them came with 6:10 left when
Sillinger jumped on a rebound from a shot by Bure to bring the
Panthers to within a goal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
