<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DALEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COMMERCE SECRETARY POSTPONES CHINA TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Commerce Secretary William M. Daley has postponed a
trip to China this weekend, apparently unable to round up enough
members of Congress willing to accompany him on the politically
sensitive visit.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was meant to sway members of the House of
Representatives who remain undecided about granting Beijing
permanent normal trade relations, a move that would pave the way
for China's entry into the World Trade Organization. But some House
members who were considering the trip were apparently spooked by
organized labor's demonstrations and intense lobbying against the
trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Without enough members to justify the visit, Daley has decided
to consolidate his visit with a similar mission planned later this
month by Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman, a Commerce Department
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to vote next month on whether to grant
China permanent trade status, an integral part of China's efforts
to join the World Trade Organization. China signed an agreement
with the United States last year granting wide trade concessions as
one of the terms of its membership in the organization, with the
condition that Washington remove what Beijing considers a
humiliating annual congressional review of its trade status. The
annual review was put into place after China's violent suppression
of pro-democracy activity in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress does not lift the annual review and grant Beijing
permanent trade status, China could still enter the World Trade
Organization with support from the Clinton administration. Allowing
China into the global trade group without lifting the annual review
would give Beijing the right to exclude the United States from
trade benefits offered to other members.
</P>
<P>
   But further delaying China's membership would strain relations
with countries that are eager to benefit from the trade concessions
that China would make as a member, and it would infuriate Taiwan,
whose membership in the group is being held up until China joins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
