<HEADER>
A6448 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     04-14 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO QUICK FIX FOR BAKER'S BLAHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vin Baker is calling this descent into basketball
oblivion ``a slump.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in a slump, however, would seem to indicate light at the
end of the tunnel. The end of this tunnel, for whatever reason,
does not seem near.
</P>
<P>
   If this were a slump, how come this downward spiral seems more
like a continuation of the dog days Baker had last season, when he
came back from the NBA lockout overweight and out-of-shape?
</P>
<P>
   How come, given an opportunity to put it back together last
summer during an Olympic qualifying tournament, Baker was dogged by
more criticism for his inconsistent play, his lethargy?
</P>
<P>
   What's going on doesn't seem like a player in a slump. This has
more the feel of a pattern, a trend. And it's looking like a long,
protracted problem for which neither Baker nor the people who pay
his $87 million contract have an answer.
</P>
<P>
   That is what makes this very uncomfortable public meltdown so
serious. Is Baker solely responsible for his woes? Or have the
Sonics failed to manage him effectively?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're honestly trying to help every way we can. We're still
optimistic something will work,'' Sonics coach Paul Westphal said
Thursday, one day after making good on his threat to remove Baker
from the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a normal ebb and flow for players to have ups and
downs. This is an extreme case. We still have confidence that he
will revert to form. That's what we're trying to do. In the
meantime, we have to march forward,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tough situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation just got tougher.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' 110-83 victory Wednesday over the Timberwolves was a
nice breakout game, stubbing a losing trend that had the Sonics
dropping nine of their past 11. But Minnesota was lackluster at
best. And what happens when rookie Lazaro Borrell and second-year
players Shammond Williams and Rashard Lewis aren't the answer?
</P>
<P>
   Once you bench a guy, how do you bring him back, especially if
the player's most glaring problem allegedly is confidence?
</P>
<P>
   Another question:
</P>
<P>
   What if Baker ultimately believes Westphal has made a value
judgment about Baker's lifestyle and that judgment has affected the
way Westphal is coaching Baker?
</P>
<P>
   Baker has little else left to believe. His game has disappeared,
not to mention his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, after Baker played 14 disastrous minutes
against the Timberwolves, the four-time NBA All-Star who will
represent the U.S. in the 2000 Olympic Games in Sydney could not
wipe his eyes fast enough to keep back the tears.
</P>
<P>
   He is in obvious pain, and some of it he will not open up about.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his feelings that not enough plays are being called for
him and that Westphal has failed to effectively manage him are
true.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe, these feelings are a form of denial. It depends on
which side is talking.
</P>
<P>
   Does Baker have set plays for him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course he does,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I don't discount anything (as to how Baker is
characterizing his lack of shots). Certainly, there's a lot of
frustration. I think we've tried a lot of different things. We'll
continue to try a lot of different things,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is wrong with Baker _ and it is something _ he is far
too easy, nice, unaggressive, soft or whatever to vent about the
root of his alarming problems, even if his representatives say it
is all about the lack of shots, the lack of plays called for Baker,
the way he has been allowed to drift into ineffectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal refused to talk about whether Baker has correctly
assumed that Westphal has stopped believing in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hypothetical question I'm not going to answer,''
Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to talk about whether he has backed off from calling
plays for Baker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no point in really getting into that. If that's the
way he feels, then there's not much I can do about that except help
make him be as successful as he can,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems clear. The drain of whatever problem Baker is
having has forced Westphal to make changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feelings are important but, at a certain point, winning is
more important than feelings,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anyone to feel I don't have confidence in them,
but I can only put five guys out there at once. If I'm doing the
best thing for the team and somebody loses their confidence because
of that, all I can say is I hope they play better and everyone will
have more confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the only comparable situation to this is when
Kendall Gill had what was disclosed as a case of manic-depressive
illness. Later, of course, it was discovered that a deep conflict
existed between Gill and George Karl. Karl did not like something
he saw in Gill. Gill knew the coach had no respect for him. The
relationship was damaged beyond repair. Gill was traded.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Sonics center Horace Grant was so stumped by team
chemistry and the string of losses he suggested the team needed Dr.
Joyce Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   How much of this chemistry and rotation confusion is about Baker
and how much is about a faltering relationship between the players
and the coach remains to be seen. A post-playoff dissection of what
happened is sure to come.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Westphal is at least publicly saying there is
hope Baker will return to form, which could be construed as some
measure of support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We projected Vin to be an All-Star player this year. I don't
think he's too old. I don't think there's any reason why he
shouldn't have great years ahead of him,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you talk to him, he would admit there's a
confidence problem. The criticism has gotten him down and makes it
even tougher. It's been a downward spiral. We hope to help him
reverse that. We've done everything we know to do to make that come
about. But his effectiveness has diminished for whatever reason.
We're hopeful it will increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Has Westphal ever seen an NBA player fall so far from his best
days?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty severe drop-off right now,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the pattern, who's to say it's over?
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
