r s BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLA     04-14 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JITTERY BUT NOT AT ALL INTIMIDATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Opening-night jitters. It was as big a concern as the
Red Wings' power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Kings naturally had a few before Thursday's Game
1 of the best-of-seven series at Joe Louis. And despite the 2-0
loss to open the series, Kings general manager Dave Taylor said he
was pleased the team remained aggressive against one of the NHL's
most explosive teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to stay away from the penalties early and we
did that somewhat,'' Taylor said. ``Our guys read the papers like
everyone else. They see that nobody gives us a chance in this
series. You can buy into that or you can work through it. That was
encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit is the league's best team with the man advantage,
converting more than 20 percent of the time. But the Kings held
them scoreless in six attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play is such a weapon for them,'' captain Rob Blake
said. ``We took a few bad ones and they were very physical early.
But we maintained our composure and that obviously is a good sign.
We were jittery before the game, but we weren't intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rookie's lament: Jere Karalahti, playing in his first playoff
game, allowed Detroit to score its first goal when Vyacheslav
Kozlov fired the puck off Karalahti's backside and passed Stephane
Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw it,'' he said. ``I've never seen one ever. It just
hit right here and went in.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Karalahti was trying to get into the NHL after his
career was derailed by drug charges in his native Finland. After a
shaky start at midseason, he has played well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little nervous at the beginning,'' he said. ``They
always talk about the intensity of the playoffs, but until you're
here you don't really know. It was incredible. I thought we played
well. We were ready for them.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Out of line:Down the stretch, the Kings most successful
combination was Jozef Stumpel and Glen Murray. But with the return
of Ziggy Palffy (sprained right shoulder) and Bryan Smolinski
(sprained right knee), the Kings' first two units returned their
regular lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel played with Palffy and Luc Robitaille, who did not get
shots on goal until the third period. Smolinski played 20 minutes
but also did not get off a shot until the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they were out of sync,'' Stumpel said of Palffy
and Smolinski. ``Detroit just controlled the middle and I think
they frustrated us. We need to take control of the middle more. But
that is always tough against the Red Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray didn't get a shot all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just played a little together,'' Stumpel said. ``That's not
the way it is lined up now. I think we did well together because we
go back a long way. We played together in Boston and here. We have
played well, but it is exciting to have Ziggy back. He means so
much to us and he will do something before this is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
