<SLUG> BC-FBC-SCFOOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC LOOKS FOR MORE KICK IN OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC coaches will officially be allowed to evaluate
high school talent May 1, but the Trojans coaching staff will have
another job when spring practice ends this weekend. Coach Paul
Hackett would like to see if there are any potential kickers left
who could join the team for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see if anyone is out there who fell through the
cracks,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have two scholarships available, and with the
kicking performances in spring inconsistent at best, they will
apparently try to see if there are any candidates who could help
the team.
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday's scrimmage, junior kicker David Newbury made just 1
of 4 field-goal attempts and senior David Bell was 0 for 1. At the
end of Thursday's practice, Newbury was 2 for 2 and Bell was 0 for
2.
</P>
<P>
   __ Nickels on track: There is a chance walk-on wide receiver
Matt Nickels could receive a scholarship, based on his impressive
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly a valid guy to consider changing the rule,''
said Hackett, who has never given a walk-on a scholarship in the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Nickels has created a niche for himself as a possession
receiver, and played well in both scrimmages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think I have a role,'' Nickels said. ``It's as a
blocking receiver and a possession receiver. I'm definitely not a
breakaway receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   He should enter fall training camp no worse than USC's fifth
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll be even higher than that,'' Nickels said. ``It
would be a dream come true (to get a scholarship). It would make
all the hard work worthwhile. I just want to be on the field, even
if I don't get a scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickels, a high school teammate of quarterback Carson Palmer at
Santa Margarita, played two years at Dartmouth before transferring
to USC.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury report: Several players are scheduled to undergo
post-spring surgery. Defensive tackle Ennis Davis (Reseda High)
will have arthroscopic surgery on his elbow, and defensive tackle
Ryan Nielsen (Royal of Simi Valley) will have arthroscopic surgery
on his shoulder. Hackett said both should be fully recovered for
summer workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Zeke Moreno (pulled groin) and free safety Kevin
Arbet (turf toe) will be held out of Saturday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Another player who recently underwent arthroscopic knee surgery
is Banning tailback Chris Howard, who will enter USC in the fall.
Howard is expected to compete for playing time with sophomore
Sultan McCullough and junior Malaefou MacKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   __ Most improved player? Hackett singled out defensive end Bobby
DeMars (Westlake) as a player who made one of the biggest
improvements this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't block him,'' Hackett said. ``He's made a move.
Bobby DeMars has had a spring-and-a-half.''
</P>
<P>
   Another player Hackett has been pleased with is defensive end
Sultan Abdul-Malik.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing the best football since I've been here,'' Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other players Hackett said have surprised him are linebacker
Kori Dickerson, offensive tackle Jacob Rogers, offensive guard
Trevor Roberts and center Lenny Vandermade.
</P>
<P>
   __ It's a wrap: USC concludes spring drills Saturday with an
11:30 a.m. practice. About 30 minutes will be spent scrimmaging.
</P>
<P>
   As spring winds down, USC seems to be doing better in the
penalty department. The Trojans had just eight in last weekend's
102-play scrimmage, and only one in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   __ Swim with Mike: USC's 20th annual ``Swim with Mike''
fund-raiser will take place Saturday at the McDonald's Swim Stadium
from 8 a.m.to 4 p.m. Proceeds go to scholarships for former high
school or college athletes who have suffered debilitating illness
or injury.
</P>
<P>
   __ Turf change: When USC plays Penn State in the Kickoff Classic
on August 27, there will be one major difference from the last time
the teams met in the game in 1996. The Meadowlands is installing
natural grass in the stadium and it will be ready for the game.
</P>
<P>
   USC will play just one game (at Oregon) on artificial turf this
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
