<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOG-OCEAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS THE SEA CONTRIBUTES TO OZONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The sun and sea that give Southern California its
healthy allure also help add to its dirty reputation for smog,
according to a report released today.
</P>
<P>
   Atmospheric chemists and mechanical engineers at the University
of California, Irvine, said they have discovered salty ocean air,
carbon monoxide and nitrogen react with the sun to create a noxious
pollutant, ozone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the winds are transporting these particles to the basin,''
said Donald Dabdub, co-lead researcher on the report published in
today's issue of the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty strong argument that there is a lot of salt
playing a role in this particular geographic area,'' said Dabdub, a
mechanical and aerospace engineering professor at UC Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   As influential as the South Coast Air Quality Management
District might be, officials said there is little they can do to
regulate the ocean as a pollution source.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing where the ozone is coming from, however, is invaluable
for predicting pollution, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for us, even though we can't control sea salt,
to account for all those things that make up air pollution,'' said
AQMD spokesman Sam Atwood.
</P>
<P>
   What is unclear is exactly how much ozone the ocean and sun
contribute. The differences between what ozone levels the AQMD's
computer models predict for any given day and what is actually
measured on those days is not great, Atwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that we have accounted for all the atmospheric
chemistry, but we do want to take a look at this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dabdub said the next step in the research, pioneered by
co-author Barbara Finlayson-Pitts, is to measure the impact of salt
air on the air quality of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The UCI team found that airborne microscopic droplets of salt,
known chemically as sodium chloride, split apart in sunlight. The
chlorine atoms in the salt air glom on to other chlorine atoms. In
a complex reaction, they mix with gases formed by auto and
industrial emissions to produce more ozone.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, said Dabdub, in unpopulated places like the middle
of the Pacific Ocean, the chlorine atoms split off but, by
themselves, reduce the amount of ozone in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Sidney Benson, a professor emeritus of chemistry at the
University of Southern California, said the finding is significant
``because it widens the net of what's going on around us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What it tells us is that we'd better not worry about needles
in the haystack,'' Benson said. ``There are plenty of things in
life that affect us.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 0039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
