<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6455 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-COACH-INVESTIGATION-K     04-14 2348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COACH-INVESTIGATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTS REVEAL PERSONAL STRUGGLE BEHIND PLAYER'S SUMMER-LEAGUE
CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and STEVE ROCK  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ With its teal three-point arcs and tight,
bleacherless sidelines, the Guardian Angels Church gym on Westport
Road was familiar to Schlagle High School senior Andre Williams.
But the ``coach'' he met on the night of May 27, 1998, was not.
</P>
<P>
   It was a different type of coach for a different kind of game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of running drills with summer-league coach Myron Piggie,
Williams and an uncle met with private investigator Ted Knox.
Beginning at 7:30 p.m. and for the next two hours, they discussed
how to tape record Piggie offering Williams $100 a week to play on
his summer-league team.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting would ultimately lead to a two-year federal
investigation that would shake college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Knox had been hired by Tom Grant, the chief executive officer of
LabOne Inc. whose family foundation once sponsored Piggie's
summer-league team. Knox remembers Williams as skittish that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little nervous, but he listened to what he needed to
do,'' Knox told The Kansas City Star. ``I assured him we would be
there for him.... Andre just wanted to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox put a tape recorder on Williams' home phone the next day.
The ensuing tapes resulted in the indictments unveiled Thursday
against Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   Through his attorney, Williams, now a freshman at Oklahoma State
University, declined to comment for this article, saying it is time
to get on with his life. Piggie was in federal custody Thursday and
could not be reached for comment. Piggie's attorney declined to
comment after his initial court appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' account, however, is set out in detail in documents
prepared with his cooperation and released to The Star recently by
Oklahoma State. The letters and reports, based on interviews with
Williams by university officials, were prepared in December and
January as they appealed Williams' suspension for NCAA rules
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Along with other interviews, Grant foundation records and
information from Thursday's federal charges, it's now possible to
paint the richest public picture yet of how authorities think
Piggie operated.
</P>
<P>
   And they show why the NCAA ended up suspending seven big-time
college players this past season amid a searing reassessment of
amateur basketball.  &LR; brk:Unlikely duo and the dream team
</P>
<P>
   Williams' meeting in Guardian Angels Church gym with the private
investigator had its roots at least three years before in the
flourishing relationship between an unlikely pair: Tom Grant and
Myron Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   The streetwise coach and the Johnson County multimillionaire had
teamed up to attract high school basketball players to teams
sponsored by Grant. Such nonscholastic teams have become
increasingly important to players eager to hone their skills.
</P>
<P>
   At times the two wrangled wayward players, making sure they made
it to practice, and class.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 through June 1998, Grant's foundation wrote checks to
Piggie totaling $184,435 covering salary and expenses, Thursday's
indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the focus of Piggie's and Grant's attention wasn't
Williams but rather JaRon Rush, a restless high school phenom whom
Grant had taken into his home and treated like a son.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 letter to the NCAA, Grant described his feelings about
Piggie:
</P>
<P>
   ``He has worked with me in trying to help JaRon become a
responsible adult,'' Grant wrote. ``Myron is not an educated man,
but he has a good heart and works every afternoon with JaRon on
helping him improve his game....Myron has been a positive influence
on JaRon....''
</P>
<P>
   By the spring of 1997, the grooming of Rush had begun to pay
off. Piggie assembled what is remembered as a summer-league dream
team _ including Rush, Williams and future NBA players Korleone
Young and Corey Maggette.
</P>
<P>
   That 1997 summer team appeared unstoppable as it began the
national circuit of Amateur Athletic Union tournaments and shoe
company events _ a whirlwind of games played before top college
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   With some of the country's best college prospects under his
wing, more money started coming Piggie's way. Nike Inc. signed him
to a consulting contract worth up to $425,000, and sports agents
began giving him money to represent their interests in the amateur
basketball community, according to the federal indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said in an interview last week that the attention began to
change Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a guy who suddenly had all these college basketball
coaches calling him on a daily basis,'' Grant said. ``And then (CBS
basketball commentator and Nike consultant) George Raveling would
call him three or four times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Raveling was unavailable for comment Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The money also had its effect. In 1997, Piggie bought two houses
and leased a Toyota Land Cruiser, Jackson County records show.
</P>
<P>
   But late 1997 also brought the first hints of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That fall The Basketball Times published an article that
contained allegations Piggie had taken the Nike shoes he was
supposed to pass on to athletes for free and instead sold them for
personal profit, an allegation Piggie has denied in the past. The
article also contained details of his criminal history,
specifically a felony drug conviction in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confronted him in the fall of 1997 about the article,''
Grant said in the interview. ``I knew he had a criminal background,
but I didn't know how extensive. He denied all the allegations
against him about dealing the shoes. I was close to the guy. I
believed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Piggie's denials, Grant withdrew support for Piggie's
traveling team, but agreed to pay him for six months under a
``severance'' agreement.  &LR; brk:`Lack of trust'
</P>
<P>
   Piggie soon started assembling his next summer team, then
sponsored only by Nike. Schlagle's Williams was a natural prospect.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was a supporting player on Piggie's dream team the
summer before, he had developed into a big-time college prospect.
He again began playing for Piggie in the spring of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams had worries off the court. According to the
Oklahoma State records, he was concerned that he didn't have the
grades to graduate from Schlagle that May, much less qualify
academically for college.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie's solution ultimately contributed to Williams'
disenchantment with his coach. He suggested to Williams and his
uncle, Al Collins, that Williams spend an additional year in an
East Coast prep school to sharpen his grades. Furthermore, Piggie
promised to ``get him into'' Hargrave Military Academy, Oklahoma
State letters assert.
</P>
<P>
   But as weeks passed, Williams and his uncle grew frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma State administrator wrote that ``whenever Andre or
Mr. Collins asked Piggie what Andre's status was at Hargrave,
Piggie would respond `I'm taking care of it.' To make a long story
short, Piggie made unfulfilled promises to Andre and delayed his
opportunities to get into a prep school or other education
institution.''
</P>
<P>
   To paper over the rift, according to the Oklahoma State
documents, Piggie began giving Williams money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre describes his relationship with Myron Piggie as one with
a lack of trust for each other,'' another university official
wrote. ``He feels the cash payments were given in order to try to
re-establish some trust.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the federal indictment, Williams in the spring of
1998 traveled to a Virginia tournament and received $100 from a
Piggie associate.
</P>
<P>
   Two more payments amounting to $150 came on trips to Indiana and
Kansas, the indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Oklahoma State letter, ``the other two payments
were given directly from Piggie to Andre when Piggie shook his hand
and the cash was in the palm of his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Williams said he received an offer of weekly stipends of at
least $100, the indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Williams refused the weekly stipends and quit Piggie's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre indicated that a term like `you scratch my back and I'll
scratch yours' may have been used, but that this phrase meant
little to him because of the lack of trust,'' an Oklahoma State
administrator wrote. ``That is, he had no intention of ever having
a future relationship with Myron Piggie.''  &LR; brk:Trouble sets in
</P>
<P>
   Nervous about his academic future and concerned that the
payments taken from Piggie might harm his college eligibility,
Williams appeared at Grant's Mission Hills home for a talk in the
spring of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was outraged,'' Grant said of the alleged payments.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, Grant had hired Knox, who met Williams and his
uncle at the Westport Road gym that May night.
</P>
<P>
   With the permission of his mother, Williams began recording his
phone calls with Piggie, Knox said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant doesn't apologize for asking an 18-year-old high school
student to tape record a convicted drug felon, though he's uneasy
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was somewhat naive,'' Grant said. ``I thought if I gave
these tapes to the NCAA, (Piggie) would just go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox said that because he has testified before a federal grand
jury he couldn't discuss the contents of the tapes, which are in
the hands of federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But the recordings show Piggie urging Williams to pass up a
summer job and receive money to play on Piggie's team, said John
Osgood, Grant's attorney. The indictment also says Piggie made such
an offer.
</P>
<P>
   With that success, Knox ratcheted up his surveillance plan.
</P>
<P>
   More than once, Knox wired Williams with a miniature body
microphone for personal meetings with Piggie. For one planned
meeting at the McDonald's restaurant on the Country Club Plaza,
Knox positioned telephoto cameras and video equipment in a van
parked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But Piggie missed each of the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   In early June, Grant said, he called Piggie, and taped the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm not going to give you any more money, you're
paying basketball players,' '' Grant recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Piggie denied it vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Myron, buddy, we taped you,' '' Grant said. ``He
wasn't very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Knox and Grant then approached the NCAA, hoping they could push
Piggie out of amateur basketball. They were disappointed with the
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they had no jurisdiction over a (summer league)
coach,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, in June 1998, Knox reported Piggie to
FBI agents, who took several months to review the information and
research the law. Grant first appeared before a federal grand jury
in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, FBI agents interviewed JaRon and his brother Kareem Rush,
a freshman at the University of Missouri, and uncovered the
information that eventually led to their NCAA suspensions for parts
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Moving methodically, prosecutors and agents from the FBI and the
IRS spent a year scouring tax records and documents from Grant's
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   And Piggie saw his fortunes wane.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, he was arrested and later convicted for
carrying a concealed weapon in Kansas City. A month later, Nike
canceled Piggie's consulting contract. According to the indictment,
Nike was convinced he had been profiteering on shoes. A Nike
spokesman says the company has never taken legal steps to recover
its loss.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Piggie faced a lawsuit from an unpaid creditor and a
repossession action for two leased Toyota Land Cruisers and a
Corolla. He also was convicted of misdemeanor assault for closing a
garage door on a Jackson County sheriff's deputy who came to his
home to take the cars.  &LR; brk:Question of fairness
</P>
<P>
   Despite the end of the relationship with Piggie, Grant's
interest in Williams continued. He underwrote the entire cost of
Williams' school year at an East Coast prep school, Maine Central
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   While there, Williams won a citizenship award and organized a
basketball tournament to raise money for the school's needy student
assistance fund. He also helped lead the MCI basketball team to a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   But Grant's tuition payments created new problems for Williams
after he enrolled at Oklahoma State University in 1999. While
school investigators investigated the payments to Piggie, Williams
voluntarily disclosed Grant's support.
</P>
<P>
   The school responded by suspending Williams from the basketball
team after only five games and reporting him to the NCAA for
possible rules violations. While the school argued for a mild
penalty, the NCAA appeared ready to extend that penalty to a year
and require him to repay $20,000 in MCI tuition.
</P>
<P>
   School officials mounted a furious effort to get him reinstated,
noting that Williams voluntarily disclosed the tuition payments and
had cooperated fully in a much more serious matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for Andre's commitment to eligibility rules, his honesty
and his courage, the current federal and NCAA investigations into
illegal and improper conduct into Kansas City-area, AAU-sanctioned
summer basketball might not be occurring,'' an Oklahoma State
official wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA relented, at least partly, limiting Williams'
suspension to the five games he already had sat out and ordering
him to pay a $5,000 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Williams rejoined the Cowboys for their run through March
Madness.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to disciplinary action against Williams and his
former Kansas City teammates, brothers JaRon and Kareem Rush, the
NCAA suspended five other big-time basketball players for taking
improper benefits while in high school or for dealing with sports
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Grant understands the Piggie saga still has a ways to run. He's
not completely happy with the way it has turned out thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Only the kids have been made to pay for the mistakes of the
grownups, he said, and he called on NCAA officials to apologize to
Williams and rescind the $5,000 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's reported (Piggie's) actions and this is the reward he
gets from the NCAA?'' Grant said. ``It's important they do that.
How can this be equitable?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
