<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6456 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-14 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANDY 'DOG OF AN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Baseball, hot dogs and Orel Hershiser. Bunting,
balloons and Orel Hershiser. Fireworks, marching bands and Orel
Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   Home opener at Dodger Stadium and the Bulldog on the mound. The
combination just feels so correct, at one stage in spring training
the club's braintrust let its heart take over and considered
setting up the entire pitching rotation to give the 41-year-old
right-hander the stage today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I killed that,'' Hershiser said this week. ``That's just not
the way you go about things. That doesn't make for good team
chemistry. That doesn't make for a good chorus.''
</P>
<P>
   But things like this just seem to magically work out for
Hershiser, and the pitching-staff juggling that followed Kevin
Brown's injury and Sunday's snow-out in New York have landed the
right man in the right place at the right time for the Los Angeles
Dodgers' game against the Cincinnati Reds this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After five years in the wilderness _ Cleveland, San Francisco,
New York Mets _ Hershiser should get a throaty welcome back from
56,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great for the fans to remember the Dodgers of
old,'' general manager Kevin Malone said, meaning the World Series
champion 1988 Dodgers. ``When you think of the Dodgers, you think
of winning, and he represents that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, as you might expect, prefers not to be thought of as
a museum piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't some victory tour or a nostalgia thing because I'm
wearing a Dodger uniform again. This is an intense athlete going
out to try to beat you,'' he said during the Dodgers' series
against the Giants in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Hershiser also is blessed with the kind of intense
self-awareness more common in politicians and artists than in
athletes, who tend to leave to others the task of putting their
accomplishments in historical context. So Hershiser understands
perfectly the nostalgia attached to his start today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first reason it exists is that there hasn't been a world
championship in Los Angeles since '88. Second reason it exists is I
was a big part of that team,'' said Hershiser, who struck out the
Oakland A's Tony Phillips to end that World Series, and all these
years later remains the last Dodgers pitcher to win a postseason
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third reason it exists is the club has been sold from Mr.
(Peter) O'Malley. Fourth reason it exists is there was a kneejerk
(public) reaction to the people who purchased the club from Mr.
O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the way we're going to erase that is we're going to have a
good year this year and there will be a new level of nostalgia.
That will erase most of what I represent. Or it will add to it, if
I'm a big part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you'd forgotten, Hershiser actually talks that way, in
organized thoughts and sentences, often leaving sportswriters
slack-jawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the '88 team succeeded, we kind of put the
Garvey-Russell-Cey-Lopes infield in the background,'' Hershiser
said. ``There hasn't been a new kid in town to draw the attention
away from the '88 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, two years after I left, (Hideo) Nomo would have had a Cy
Young year, and the Dodgers would have gone off and won the world
championship, and Pedro Martinez had stayed with the club, and this
dynamic pitching staff had carried them to three or four
championships . . . I'd be old news.''
</P>
<P>
   Old news with a Cy Young Award, a 23-win season and a record
59-inning shutout streak, all from 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball has a tendency to make you think about `Where were
you then?' '' said Hershiser, who, as he spoke, sat at a card table
in the Pacific Bell Park visitors' clubhouse. ``The game is so
long, and there are dead points in it, and conversations come up.
And people want to talk about positive things in contrast to the
negative that might be going on the field. So when is the last
positive thing they can talk about? Gibby's (Kirk Gibson's) name
comes up, I'm sure. Steve Sax's name comes up, my name comes up,
Mickey Hatcher's name comes up, Mike Scioscia's name comes up.
That's given us some life.''
</P>
<P>
   So Hershiser begins an unusual attempt to kick dirt into his own
deep footprints on Los Angeles baseball history. A 2000 Dodgers
championship, and the sweet memory of 1988 fades just a bit.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment the task is to make the bitter memory of 1998-99
fade just a bit. A new managing partner, Daly, and a revamped
Dodger Stadium, now boasting luxury suites, will greet the
opening-day fans.
</P>
<P>
   And an old Bulldog.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to restore whatever it is we're looking to
restore with one player in one day or over one homestand,''
Hershiser said, separating the nostalgia from the practical
significance of today's start. ``You're going to do it by
consistently having quality and integrity in the way you go about
your business, from Mr. Daly to the guys down in the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there's magic in the 2000 Dodgers, this is the day and
he's the man to find it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
