<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6457 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-14 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGERS SHUT OUT MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The easy move would be to dump on Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Price wouldn't do that.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mesa, after all, who brought a scoreless pitching duel to
an end by giving up an eighth-inning RBI double to Juan Gonzalez,
the key hit in the Detroit Tigers' 2-0 win over the Seattle
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Price, the Mariners pitching coach, isn't much for doing things
the easy way. He is mindful that Mesa can still be a force out of
the Seattle bullpen. Mesa, after all, saved 33 games last year and
still throws in the low 90s.
</P>
<P>
   If fact, Price said it's been Mesa's penchant to rely on
throwing hard that has ultimately made the veteran less dependable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't lost confidence in Mesa at all,'' Price said. ``He's
got the ability. He can throw the ball as hard as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got to get him back to pitching, not just throwing.
When he comes in throwing all hard stuff, he's not using all the
weapons he has in his arsenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa entered the game in the eighth inning. Reliever Arthur
Rhodes, who'd successfully used hard stuff to pitch the Mariners
out of a jam in the seventh inning, walked Shane Halter to start
the eighth. Enter Mesa to face Gonzalez, although Gonzalez had
never really solved the left-handed Rhodes in the past (2-for-23,
.087).
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle manager Lou Piniella is a great believer in the
percentages, which say a right-handed pitcher has the best chance
to get a right-handed hitter out. Hence Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   He missed with a fastball, then came back with another fastball.
Gonzalez, who won two league Most Valuable Player awards with Texas
by gobbling up fastballs, lashed this one to right-center. Halter
scored the game's first run, and later in the inning, Gonzalez's
pinch-runner, Karim Garcia, scored on a Dean Palmer sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I brought Mesa in, I told him that he had to keep the
ball down,'' Piniella said. ``Gonzalez can't run right now. If we
keep the ball down, we've got a good shot at a double play.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mesa's second pitch was mid-thigh hard stuff, the double
play became a double _ even for Gonzalez, who is essentially
playing on one leg because of hamstring troubles. And the game,
doable to that point for Seattle, slipped away from the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason for Jose to be hit hard like this,'' Price
said. ``To me, this calls for a change of plans. He needs to back
off throwing the hard stuff all the time. When you throw hard stuff
in the same zone all the time, you're not making it difficult
enough on the batter.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit pitching made it plenty tough on Seattle batters
Thursday night, although it could be said that the Mariners made it
hard on themselves by engaging the pitches served up by Detroit
starter Hideo Nomo with too much passion on a night when some
reserve was indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chased a lot of pitches,'' Piniella said. ``Too many.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle flirted with scoring from the first inning, when Mark
McLemore and Alex Rodriguez were each thrown out stealing, to the
last, when David Bell, who'd ripped the ball twice for hits early
in the game, bounced into a game-ending double play with two on.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, waiting in the on-deck circle when the game ended,
expressed the evening's frustrations by arching his back backward,
his bat still on his shoulder and his face locked in a grimace.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners left 11 men on base, but it seemed like they'd left
the 101st Airborne stranded out between first and third. Seattle
continued an early season trend to the downside by going 0-for-10
with men in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's best chance to score came in the sixth inning, when
the Mariners loaded the bases on a hit by Bell and two walks by
Nomo. That brought up John Olerud, who would wind up with six hits
in the three games. This time, however, the best that Olerud could
manage was a short fly ball to left field.
</P>
<P>
   With McLemore, one of the fastest of the Mariners, on third
base, third base coach Larry Bowa bucked the odds and challenged
outfielder Bobby Higginson's arm by sending McLemore. Catcher Brad
Ausmus took a perfect one-hop throw from Higginson, and even a
jolting shoulder from McLemore couldn't dislodge the ball from
Ausmus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the throw is left or right, then there's a chance (to
score),'' McLemore said, ``but the throw was right there. I was
trying to jar the ball loose, but he got the ball early enough that
he braced himself good.''
</P>
<P>
   If McLemore's effort was futile, it probably should never have
come into play. Bowa said he knew sending McLemore was a
low-percentage move, but given the state of the Mariners'
non-offense, a low-percentage move seemed to be the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the blame for that one,'' Bowa said. ``I thought I'd
try to make them make a perfect throw. They did. I was watching us
strand runners all night. If we'd been swinging the bats well, I
never would have even thought about sending Mac home.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's offensive slump isn't a one-time wonder. The Mariners
have a winning record at 5-4, but the club is hitting only .252,
11th in the 14-team American League. And with men in scoring
position, the average plummets to .087 (2-for-23).
</P>
<P>
   That's sickly under any circumstances, moreso for a club that
hit over .300 in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   As Piniella will be the first to attest, this is not spring
training. But the time for experimenting isn't over. Charles Gipson
will start at third base and Stan Javier in left field tonight in
Toronto in the endless quest for offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still playing around with the lineup, trying to find a
combination that will swing the bat,'' Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
