<SLUG> BC-HKN-OILERS-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL STEPS UP, STARS DOMINATE TO TAKE 2-0 LEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Deep down, the Stars knew they were kidding themselves
if they thought they could repeat as Stanley Cup champions without
getting Brett Hull involved.
</P>
<P>
   Well ...
</P>
<P>
   Consider him involved.
</P>
<P>
   Hull scored a goal and assisted on another in the Stars' 3-0
victory against the Edmonton Oilers in Game 2 of the best-of-seven
first-round series last night at Reunion Arena. The victory didn't
merely serve notice to the Oilers that their season is on the verge
of being over, but to the rest of the NHL as well that the Stars
are pretty serious about this whole ``The Cup Stays Here'' thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said when asked
if this season's team has a look of last season's. ``\RJamie
Langenbrunner\S said it before the playoffs. Everyone in this room
is going to be disappointed if we don't get to the end. I think we
have a team capable of getting to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have won nine consecutive playoff games against the
Oilers and take a 2-0 series lead into Sunday's game in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   What the Stars liked in Game 1 _ the stifling defense, timely
goaltending and a guy named Mike Modano _ were once again present
and dominant in Game 2. What was missing in Game 1 _ an involved
Hull, a flying Joe Nieuwendyk and more goals _ were added for Game
2.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and they're set to get their best puck-handling
defenseman, Sergei Zubov, back for Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   So is this Stars' team capable of repeating as Cup champions?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way \RDerian\S Hatcher is playing, the way Modano is
playing and Eddie is on the top of his game, they seem to be on top
of a lot of things'' Oilers coach Kevin Lowe said. ``But it's a
long, hard road.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Stars dominated the game from the get-go. But
late in the second period, they were a mistake away from a tie
game. While the Stars were playing quite well with a 1-0 lead, a
second goal had the power to totally demoralize the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Hull obliged.
</P>
<P>
   In a goal reminiscent of his Stanley Cup-winning goal in Game 6
against Buffalo, Hull floated right to the edge of the crease,
found the loose puck and put in over Oilers goalie Tommy Salo at
17:55 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   His feet weren't in the crease this time, not that it would've
mattered if they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him the other day, `Geez, Hully, you got the best shot
in the game. Use it,' '' Stars winger Kirk Muller said. ``We need
him contributing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull played a big role on the Stars' first goal, too.
</P>
<P>
   Modano started the play by carrying the puck into the Stars'
zone. As the Oilers' defense converged on him, he threaded a pass
between his legs to a waiting Hull. Hull faked the shot and passed
to winger Muller, who beat Salo high and stick side at 15:33 of the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hully's just a worker,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``This is not a series right now for the faint of heart and Hully
really dug in with the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back games were supposed to favor the younger,
spritely Oilers. They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Peguins had as many goals in their game against
Washington (seven) as the Oilers had shots in the first two
periods. Their power play was ineffective at best, demoralizing at
worst. They got one shot on four power-play opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars defense was that stifling. Captain Derian Hatcher
and Richard Matvichuk once again led the charge with 17 hits while
logging almost 60 minutes of ice. The game got chippier and
chippier as it went on, but the Stars didn't back down.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers finished with 17 shots. All of which were stopped by
Stars goalie Ed Belfour. He got his eighth career playoff shutout
and his fifth as a Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a lot pride in shots on goal,'' Modano said. ``We get
excited about it. We like that challenge. We like to smother them
and frustrate them. When you can roll four lines out there at them,
it's pretty robotic after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike in Game 1, the Stars weren't content with a one-goal
lead.
</P>
<P>
   After Hull scored to make it two, Stars winger Scott Thornton
added another. His goal at 6:22 of the third period all but
finished the Oilers and served notice to the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, of course, wasn't buying into talk of repeats just
yet. ``We've played two hockey games. That's where we are so far.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers on the other hand see that same something that helped
the Stars win the Cup last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's obvious,'' Oilers center Doug Weight said.
``That's no secret. That's why they won last year. And that's been
the story of the first two games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
