u a BC-LATIMES-EDITOR-NYT &LR;      04-14 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIMES-EDITOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TIMES EDITOR AND PUBLISHER TO STEP DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Parks, the editor of The Los Angeles Times, told his top
lieutenants on Thursday evening that he and the publisher, Kathryn
S. Downing, would leave their posts after the completion of the
sale of the newspaper's parent company, the Times Mirror Co., to
the Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune is expected to take control within the next two
weeks or so.
</P>
<P>
   John S. Carroll, the editor of The Baltimore Sun, has agreed to
replace Parks. John Puerner, the president and publisher of The
Orlando Sentinel, a Tribune Co. newspaper, will replace Downing,
Parks said, according to two Times editors briefed on the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Downing, who was appointed last June by the Times Mirror's chief
executive, Mark H. Willes, and Parks, who had served as editor for
more than two years, were both scarred by last fall's Staples
Center controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Downing had decided to share with the arena's owners the revenue
from special Sunday magazine covering the arena's opening. After he
discovered the arrangement, Parks made no move to scuttle the
magazine or inform readers of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   On March 17, after the announcement of Tribune's purchase of
Times Mirror, which also publishes The Sun, Newsday, and several
smaller newspapers, Jack Fuller, the president of Tribune's
publishing division, said at a Times staff meeting that The Times
newsroom would be run from Los Angeles, not the Tribune Co.'s
Chicago headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But he gave no guarantees that Parks and Downing would keep
their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll himself, asked to confirm the widespread rumor of his
appointment, said politely, ``I'm afraid I can't help you.'' Parks
did not return a phone call to his office late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One newsroom executive at The Baltimore Sun, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said Carroll's most likely successor would
be the managing editor, William Marimow, if Tribune executives did
not choose to look for outside candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of an official announcement in the next few days
seems unlikely, since the Tribune Co.y does not yet have legal
control of Times Mirror and its divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, who will have the job of rebuilding the confidence of
the Times' newsroom in its management, has been The Sun's editor
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   During six years at the newspaper from 1966 to 1972, he had
served as a reporter in Vietnam, the Middle East and Washington.
From 1972 to 1991, he worked as an editor for Knight-Ridder
newspapers, first at The Philadelphia Inquirer, and later as the
top editor of the Lexington Herald-Leader.
</P>
<P>
   John Arthur, a managing editor at the Times, said late Thursday
evening, ``Michael Parks was an excellent editor under very
difficult circumstances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
