<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-TEXAS-HIGH-SCHOOLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL HOCKEY WILL CONTINUE TO GROW IN TEXAS, SUPPORTERS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK MAUCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hundreds of spectators from North Crowley and Arlington wedged
into the stands, while face-painted fans from L.D. Bell and Trinity
waited for the next game.
</P>
<P>
   Pep rallies were held, banners were hung, and cheerleaders urged
on their teams.
</P>
<P>
   Your typical Texas high school football or basketball game?
</P>
<P>
   Nope, this is typical of high school hockey in Fort
Worth-Dallas, Houston, Austin, Midland-Odessa, and perhaps your
town in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that high school hockey is here to stay,''
said Jerry Nichols, coach of the Arlington Wolverines. ``They'd
better get used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport appears to be most popular in Fort Worth-Dallas, where
29 varsity teams participate in the Southwestern Bell Metroplex
High School Hockey League. In addition, the league is the only one
in Texas that has a junior varsity division, and it contains 25
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Houston has 18 varsity teams, Austin and Midland-Odessa each
have four. San Antonio has two and San Angelo, Temple-Belton and
Lubbock might have teams next season.
</P>
<P>
   Eight teams are scheduled to compete today through Sunday at the
Dr Pepper StarCenter in the Texas Amateur Hockey Association State
High School Hockey Tournament. That's twice the number of teams in
the entire state four years ago when the Fort Worth-Dallas league
started with teams from Carroll, Coppell, Dallas Jesuit and Plano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hockey is basically still something new and exciting to most
folks in Texas and everyone wants to be a part of it,'' said Kent
Holmes, director the Southwestern Bell League. ``Certainly the
success of the \RStanley Cup champion\S Stars has helped because a
winning team attracts attention to a sport, but the minor-league
teams around the state have to be commended as well for the way
they are marketing themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth of high school hockey has also caught the attention
of the University Interscholastic League, the state's governing
body for high school sports. Athletic director Charles Breithaupt
said his office regularly gets calls asking when the UIL will
sanction the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we'll have an official proposal in June,''
Breithaupt said. ``Our athletics committee and policy committee
will give us direction, perhaps ask for a survey, and report back
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leagues seem to be very well organized.''
</P>
<P>
   But the cost of the sport could be an obstacle for many school
districts, Breithaupt said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes said the average rate for ice time in Fort Worth-Dallas
is $250 an hour and the average cost for a player to participate in
the Southwestern Bell League is about $300 per season. Those
expenses, combined with the cost of equipment _ about $500 for
forwards and defensemen and around $1,500 for a goalie _ are
factors the UIL will consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the near future, I just don't see schools voting in a sport
so expensive,'' Breithaupt said. ``The demand may become so strong
some day that they have to, but now, budgets are tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Breithaupt suggested that more school districts in cities with
minor-league teams try to form teams since playing venues already
exist.
</P>
<P>
   New StarCenters are scheduled to open in Euless later this month
and in Duncanville in October, and one already exists in Irving.
Plus, Holmes said the Southwestern Bell League has potential use of
six other facilities for teams in Fort Worth, Grapevine, North
Richland Hills, Plano, Addison and a facility being built in
Frisco.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, there are four venues with perhaps one more on the
way, Interscholastic Hockey League director Bill Justice said, and
Central Texas Hockey League director Lance Kappell said Austin has
one high school facility with no more planned.
</P>
<P>
   A proposal to the UIL does not guarantee sanctioning. Wrestling
was the last sport the organization sanctioned, in 1998. Grapevine
wrestling coach Steve Wills said it took about 20 years for the
sport to reach that level and his advice to those wanting hockey to
be sanctioned is to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years is reasonable. If it takes less, they'll be
fortunate,'' Wills said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin wrestling coach Tony Warren said, ``It's simple. If the
demand is there, it will pass. School districts have to get
involved now.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of school districts kept saying when we were pushing
wrestling that they'd have a team if it went UIL. We kept telling
them that if they'd come along, it would go UIL.''
</P>
<P>
   Breithaupt said the UIL isn't looking for a specific number of
participating schools. He noted that soccer was basically a sport
played only by Class 5A schools when it was sanctioned in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   If the UIL sanctions hockey, changes will come. Among the most
significant, teams could no longer practice or play on Sunday and
coaches would have to be teachers employed by their district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caution people to be careful what they wish for,'' Trinity
coach Keith Andresen said. ``There's not a lot of teachers who can
coach hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, consolidated teams, such as those in Arlington and North
Crowley, would be broken up. The UIL would require each team to
represent one school.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwestern Bell League has a policy that consolidated
teams have to begin breaking up into school teams after three
years. In Houston and Austin, it's four years.
</P>
<P>
   Of the teams in the state tournament, six are one-school teams.
Dallas Episcopal and North Crowley are consolidated teams.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen teams in the Southwestern Bell League come from a
single school, while Houston has eight, and Austin has one.
</P>
<P>
   Kappell said his league strictly enforces a no-pass//no-play
rule, as does the Houston league. In the Southwestern Bell League,
the decision is left up to each team, but most coaches enforce
no-pass/no-play, Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the leagues are going to have to be on the same page
rules-wise for the UIL to seriously consider us,'' Kappell said.
</P>
<P>
   Elite players are taking the sport more seriously on the high
school level, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like club hockey, but high school is the coolest,'' said
Trevor Ludwig, the son of former Stars defenseman Craig Ludwig.
``It's just neat to know that your friends are in the stands
cheering you on and you're going to see them in school the next
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes coached Plano to a state championship last season before
becoming league director. He said his players received letter
jackets and that other schools such as Trinity and Dallas Jesuit
have followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   North Crowley coach Joe Cocchiarella said he believes the sport
will spread to smaller towns. Then, he said, the UIL will have to
take a long, hard look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the Springtowns, the Weatherfords and Aledos having
teams,'' Cocchiarella said. ``When they do, it'll be a UIL sport.
Popular public opinion is going to demand it be sanctioned.''
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:A growing sport Across the state, high school hockey
has grown rapidly in the past four years. In the 1996-97 season,
the Fort Worth-Dallas area had four teams. Houston started with six
in 1997-98. Here's a breakdown of high school hockey sites and the
number of teams today: Fort Worth-Dallas _ 29 varsity teams, 25
junior varsity Houston _ 18 varsity teams Austin _ 4 varsity teams
Midland-Odessa _ 4 varsity teams San Antonio _ 2 varsity teams
Possible for next season _ San Angelo, Lubbock and Temple-Belton
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
