<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS HAVE NO EXCUSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ They could have looked at Bryan Smolinski and Ziggy
Palffy and said it was not their night. They could have looked at
the Detroit Red Wings and said it's not their year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings know if they want to make the playoffs more than a
novelty, they can't make excuses about Thursday's 2-0 loss in Game
1 of their opening-round series at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski played on a torn right-knee ligament, Palffy played
with a sprained right shoulder. A year ago, they were New York
Islanders and far from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were homelast year, too, but rookie coach Andy Murray
made sure this year they were not just happy to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played well enough to stay close, but we didn't play well
enough to win,'' he said. ``It's encouraging to be competitive with
a team as good as Detroit with all their history. But we didn't
come here to just show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their fourth best point total (94) in franchise history,
the Kings did arrive as heavy underdogs. They also hadn't won in
the playoffs since Game 1 of the 1993 final against Montreal, a
string of eight games that now stands at nine.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings were second in the league with 108 points. They
also won the Stanley Cup two consecutive years before going out in
the second round last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't that far away tonight,'' said Smolinski, a Michigan
native. ``For the knee it seemed like business as usual, but it
will be better and so will the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the game, the Kings were smothered at center ice, and
that enabled Red Wings goaltender Chris Osgood to record his
seventh career playoff shutout. Osgood had been viewed as a weak
link for the Red Wings after an inconsistent second half. But
Detroit's defense made that all go away as they did about the
absence of league MVP candidate Steve Yzerman, who was out with the
flu and a tender knee.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two periods, they held the Kings top snipers _
Palffy, Luc Robitaille and Glen Murray _ without a shot.
</P>
<P>
   By then the Red Wings had a lead they would never give up.
Vysheslav Kozlov fired a puck off the backside of defenseman Jere
Karalati and past Kings goaltender Stephane Fiset just 1:43 into
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lucky goal,'' said Fiset, who stopped 29 of 31 shots.
``But he took a shot at the net and when you do that, you never
know what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiset also was spectacular in goal, turning back what could have
been a critical second-period break away by Sergei Fedorov.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a guy like that coming at you, you just stand your
ground,'' Fiset said. But it was Fedorov on defense that made a
difference, stopping Ian Laperriere on a breakaway in the second.
Fedorov also scored the Wings' second goal, an empty netter after
Fiset was pulled with 53 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Fedorov's goal was his 39th in the postseason. Kozlov's was his
37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are guys who have been doing this a long time,'' said
Palffy, who was playing in his first playoff game. ``Sure, we were
a little nervous at first, but I never thought we were intimidated.
We belong here, not doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Palffy, injured March 15 against the Mighty Ducks, said he was
happy to get five extra days rest when the Kings scratched him the
last Sunday's final regular season game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better,'' Palffy said of the shoulder. ``And Saturday
it will be even stronger. This game was everything people said it
would be. The intensity was incredible. But I never felt like we
didn't have a chance. We were in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille finally got a chance to tie the game with 6:43 left
when he whistled a shot from the point with Murray in front. But
Osgood made the stop and controlled the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy might have had the best scoring chance of the night
midway through the third period. He circled in front of Osgood and
had an open look at the net. But center Brent Gilchrist pulled him
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of game we play in the playoffs,'' Detroit
coach Scotty Bowman said. ``We play this way and then we break
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 0142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
