<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAMS PROVES A RELIEF FOR L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Terry Adams is a big part of what Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson keeps promoting as both a new and improved
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, the one-time Cubs closer, looked the part Thursday in the
conclusion of Wednesday's rain-suspended game.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander entered in the sixth with the bases loaded and
one out, and would have pitched out of the inning without allowing
a run if third baseman Adrian Beltre had cleanly handled a sharp
grounder and turned the double play.
</P>
<P>
   Adams did allow an RBI single to Rich Aurilia but finished off
the inning without allowing another run and then threw a perfect
seventh to earn the victory in the Dodgers' 6-5 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adams did a hell of a job,'' Johnson said. ``He came in a
tough situation and really gave them nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams is now 1-0 with a 2.35 ERA in four games, having allowed
four hits in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Because the first game picked up in the bottom the sixth inning,
Adams barely had time to sit before he was called on to take over
for Jeff Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ' ``You kind of feel like a starter,'' Adams said. ``As soon as
I sat down, I had to get up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first situation I've been in with the bases
loaded. I thought I pitched pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers rallied on an RBI single by Mark Grudzielanek,
Todd Hundley's sacrifice fly and a run-scoring Adrian Beltre
infield single, another part of the Dodgers revamped bullpen, Mike
Fetters, gave up one run on two hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants put two on with two outs in the ninth against closer
Jeff Shaw before he got Jeff Kent to fly out and earn his third
save.
</P>
<P>
   __ Work in progress: With Kevin Brown on the 15-day disabled
list, Johnson is attempting to figure out the various pieces to his
pitching staff. The Dodgers need a starter for Saturday, and
Johnson said he will likely call up right-hander Eric Gagne to
pitch against the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get him in the mix,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   A nervous-looking Williams, who lasted only a third of an inning
to open the sixth of the suspended game, could also start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne was expected to make the rotation out of spring but
suffered through a disappointing exhibition season (0-2, 15.63 ERA
in four games).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking to what I can do to strengthen and solidify the
rotation with some young arms,'' Johnson said. ``Who can stand up
and help this ballclub and burn some innings?''
</P>
<P>
   Someone will have to be sent down to make room for Gagne, and
Johnson said it might not necessarily be Carlos Perez. Johnson said
reliever Onan Masaoka (6.74 ERA in four games) has struggled and
might benefit from being sent down to get more work.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he would prefer to have a left-hander in the
rotation, but once again, they are at a premium in the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tidbits: Gary Sheffield has hit safely in all nine games and
Shawn Green in eight consecutive. . . . Devon White missed his
second game with a sore back. . . . In honor of Todd Hollandsworth
bizarrely going out to center in the fifth inning Wednesday night
sucking on a lollipop, the Dodgers PR staff passed out suckers to
the L.A. media corps Thursday.!dlim!!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
