<HEADER>
A6471 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HERTZBERG-SPEAKER-LAD     04-14 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERTZBERG-SPEAKER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERTZBERG SWORN IN AS CALIFORNIA ASSEMBLY SPEAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sacramento, Calif. _ The San Fernando Valley gained a key
political power hitter on its state team Thursday as Assemblyman
Robert M. Hertzberg, D-Van Nuys, was sworn in as speaker, promising
a bigger share of the budget for his home community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The San Fernando Valley did not lose an assemblyman today,
they gained a speaker,'' Hertzberg said at a stately Capitol
ceremony that drew scores of elected officials and business leaders
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg's leadership position in the state Legislature's lower
house gives the moderate Democrat vast new decision-making
responsibility over prioritizing bills and directing resources to
finance them.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech during the installation ceremony, he outlined a
long agenda from improving the legislative process to improving the
state's educational system, particularly community colleges, and
providing more affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of business leaders and elected officials from the Valley
made the trip to Sacramento for the swearing in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fantastic step for the cityhood struggle,'' said
Richard Close, who chairs Valley Voters Organized Toward
Empowerment and sees Hertzberg as a key ally in the effort to
secede from the city of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob is the crown jewel of the Valley in Sacramento, and
hopefully he'll be able to help us cut through so much of the
bureaucratic red tape for cityhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Close said Hertzberg can help the Valley get a fairer share of
state resources but can do little about the real problem: ``City
officials who decide on resource distribution still want to keep
all the good stuff on the other side of Mulholland Drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonny Herman, president of the Valley Industry and Commerce
Association, also came to the state capital to attend a
1,500-person party in Hertzberg's honor and shared Close's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Valley, the bottom line is that we need more dollars to
go into infrastructure improvements and if anyone can streamline
the process to make it happen, it's Bob,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg is the first speaker from the Valley since Bob Moretti
in 1974, and the first Jewish speaker in 73 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hertzberg's predecessor, Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, is
being forced from the Assembly after this year because of term
limits. He served two years as speaker and is running for mayor of
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Hertzberg has already been taking on the duties of his
predecessor, a close ally who helped drum up support that led to
Hertzberg's unusual unanimous election to the speaker post in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Hertzberg announced strong Assembly support
for an additional $1.4 billion in education spending on top of Gov.
Gray Davis' proposed budget plan. Even with the additional funds,
California would fall below the national average for per-student
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is infrastructure,'' Hertzberg said. ``It is an
embarrassment that in ... California, we invest less in our
schoolchildren than all but a handful of other states.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who attended the swearing in and has called education his
top priority, said in an interview that he supports Hertzberg's
spending proposal, especially since the 2000-01 state budget is
expected to yield a surplus in excess of $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we'll see increased spending on education and I think
we can expect to see more initiatives like the one Bob has
presented,'' Davis said. ``I look forward to working with him to
get the budget done on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after being sworn in, Hertzberg appointed
Assemblyman Dennis A. Cardoza, D-Turlock, to replace him as chair
of the Rules Committee, which mandates how the Assembly operates.
</P>
<P>
   At his swearing in, Hertzberg set several priorities for when
the Legislature reconvenes April 24, including setting up a special
watchdog office to ensure state departments are implementing laws
on time. He also said initiatives are forthcoming to increase
spending on affordable housing and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Another priority, Hertzberg said, will be to continue to take
steps to ensure that Democrats and Republicans in the Assembly can
work together to move laws forward instead of stalling them with
partisan bickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge to support a culture that honors each member of this
House as an individual - a member of this House first, and a member
of his or her own party, second,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who control 32 of the 80 seats in the Assembly, are
not expected to unseat enough Democrats in the upcoming November
elections to make the vote even.
</P>
<P>
   And for all his talk of bipartisanship, Hertzberg's No. 1
priority as speaker is to maintain the Democratic Party's
stranglehold on power in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
