<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SWEEP GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; SAN FRANCISCO _ The Los Angeles Dodgers survived snow, rain,
the opening of Pacific Bell Park, being gone from home almost two
months, and Carlos Perez.
</P>
<P>
   All and all, a pretty good trip.
</P>
<P>
   Now this afternoon they finally get to play a game at home,
feeling tired but pretty good about themselves after taking one
game from the Giants 6-5 Thursday night and then bringing off a
three-game sweep with an 11-7 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers assured themselves of a winning trip with the
victory in the first game, completing the game suspended because of
rain the previous night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to win a pennant in April, but you can look
back on these as big games later,'' said reliever Terry Adams, who
earned the victory in suspended game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers started Perez in the regularly scheduled game, and
if truth be told, crossed their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   With the Dodgers having to fly out immediately following their
mini-doubleheader to play an afternoon home opener, manager Davey
Johnson sat three normal starters in Thursday's second game _ Eric
Karros, Kevin Elster and Todd Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   But this new lineup quickly went after Giants starter Mark
Gardner, scoring six runs before Perez had to throw a single pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The first six Dodgers reached base before the Giants could
record an out.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield's single scored one, Adrian Beltre's hit drove in
two more, Dave Hansen's single scored another, Chad Krueter's
ground out scored a fifth and Jose Vizcaino's base hit scored the
inning's final run.
</P>
<P>
   Perez had his gift.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants got two more in a hurry when Barry Bonds hit a
two-run homer that landed two-thirds up the right-field foul pole
in the bottom of the inning, but Perez would skate out of trouble
for most of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was ticketed for the minors until Kevin Brown broke his
right pinkie finger, and Thursday's start was termed a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Before being lifted for a pinch hitter, Perez went six innings.
He allowed three runs on six hits and one walk. He struck out
three, was far from overpowering, but effective enough.
</P>
<P>
   The only other run he allowed came on Marvin Benard's solo home
run in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Calvin Murray hit a two-run homer off reliever Onan
Masaoka in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Before all that, they picked up Wednesday's game _ suspended
because of rain _ with the Dodgers leading 3-2 going into the
bottom of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   And the Giants immediately scored two runs off Jeff Williams,
who walked two and gave up a pair of hits before a quick exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the kid was a little nervous,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, though, quickly came back with three runs of their
own. The previous night _ stay with us, though, same game _ they
loaded the bases three times (twice with no outs), but scored but a
lone run each time.
</P>
<P>
   A new night brought a different result. Against reliever Ben
Weber, Todd Hollandsworth opened with a single, took second on a
wild pitch and scored on a Mark Grudzielanek single.
</P>
<P>
   A Sheffield single and a walk to Karros loaded the bases, with
Hundley's sacrifice fly scoring one and Beltre's infield single
driving in what would prove the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants scraped a final run against Mike Fetters after Beltre
failed to cleanly field a potential double-play ball for the second
time in two innings, but this game _ this series _ was going to
belong all to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were looking at 0-3 in their new park, and 58 days
after they last saw it, the Dodgers were headed home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
