<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CARNOTE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 
McCOMB MAKES BIG PUSH 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; When Doug McComb arrived at Irwindale Speedway on Saturday, he
had a feeling that little was going to stop him. The 23-year-old
Thousand Oaks resident brought his NASCAR Super Stock entry to the
track knowing his 1976 Chevy Nova needed some brake work.
</P>
<P>
   What he wasn't expecting was having to make an emergency trip to
an auto-parts store to buy a brake cylinder and then having to
install it between qualifying sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Quick-thinking adjustments in the pits led to victory lane for
McComb. He won for the first time this season at Irwindale, holding
off late-charging T.K. Karvasek from North Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very little time to set up,'' said McComb, a Thousand
Oaks High graduate. ``We qualified with no brakes and the car had a
bad push. We adjusted the rear stagger, but it still had a push for
the race.''
</P>
<P>
   The little push forced McComb into third place early in the 40-
lap race. But as he worked his way to the front, he could feel
pressure from Steve Gilmore of Granada Hills and Karvasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little bit of door-to-door racing,'' McComb said.
``I had a lot of fun watching the race in my rear-view mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's win was the third for McComb at Irwindale. He
won two races and finished fourth in points in 1999, the year the
half-mile track opened. In 1998, McComb was second in rookie points
in the NASCAR Super Street Stock division at Mesa Marin Raceway in
Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   In other action at Irwindale, Todd Burns of Riverside won the
NASCAR Late Model main event, Mike Mocaby of Bell Gardens won the
American Race Trucks main event and Mike Wright of Joshua Tree won
the MSRA Pro-4 Modifieds main event.
</P>
<P>
   Racing continues at Irwindale on Saturday with NASCAR Super Late
Models, Super Stocks, Grand American Modifieds, Legends Cars and
Ultra Wheel Spec Trucks. Gates open at 5 and racing starts at 7
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hornaday moving up: Ron Hornaday Jr. of Palmdale had his best
finish of the season in the NASCAR Busch Grand National Series on
Saturday at the Bell South Mobility 320 in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Hornady, the series rookie, finished third behind a pack of
first- year racers that filled half the top-10 spots. A trio of
rookies, including Kevin Harvick of Bakersfield, followed in fourth
to sixth. Harvick was fourth. Additionally, rookie Jimmie Johnson
was 10th.
</P>
<P>
   With his podium finish, Hornaday jumped into sixth place in the
series points standings and increased his lead in the rookie
standings to 23 points. Harvick is second in rookie points with 80.
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Busch series is Saturday for the Touchstone
Energy 300 at Talledega Speedway in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ventura Raceway: Clark Templeman III of Santa Clarita won for
the second week in a row in the Sprint division at Ventura Raceway
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In other action, Marty Desbrow of Ojai collected his first win
of the season in the I-4 Modified class and Craig Germanetti of
Carpinteria, the track's defending street stock champion, won for
the first time this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
