<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-14 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALRY GONE RETRO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Time was the Los Angeles Dodgers and Cincinnati
Reds would stage civic rallies and a series would break out.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers ventured to Cincinnati and Walter Alston would get
booed; the Reds traveled to L.A. and Pete Rose would get pelted in
the outfield with fruits and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s there was no richer rivalry in baseball than the
one between L.A. and Cincinnati. ``The Giants are supposed to be
the Dodgers' natural rivals,'' Reds manager Sparky Anderson said at
the time, ``but I don't think the feeling is there anymore. It's
not there the way it is with us and the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the two teams squared off, it was a clash of titans, of
cultures, of sensibilities. It was the Queen City vs. the city of
celluloid Kings; lunch-pail mores vs. laissez-faireism; small town
vs. sprawling city; superior pitching vs. peerless hitting.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the seven years between 1972 and 1978, Cincinnati or Los
Angeles represented the National League in the World Series. The
two teams distanced themselves from the rest of the West on the
diamond and also in the stands, where they routinely ranked one-two
in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   If not for the Dodgers, the Big Red Machine might have
steamrolled through the 1970s, its success so off the charts, those
Cincinnati teams would have gone down in pop culture as the Bee
Gees of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Reds were more like Andy Gibb, brightening
the era like a shooting star. In 1975, Cincinnati won the first of
back-to-back world titles, turning back Boston in a seven-game
World Series after streaking by the Dodgers on the wings of a
celestial midseason stretch in which the Reds won 41 of 50 games.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years later, many Cincinnatians are saying the
updated, upgraded Big Red Machine will tear through this decade and
leave more of a mark than it did in the `70s.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, interest in this year's team is so high that Elder High,
a Catholic school in the Western Hills section where Rose was
reared, scheduled a teachers in-service day on Reds' opening day
this year so the students wouldn't have to choose between classes
and history.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Cincinnati's (and Ken Griffey Sr.'s) prodigal son,
Ken Jr., was such a landmark event in the city, ``parents were
going to pull their kids out of school, anyway, so why have
school?'' reasoned Elder's principal, Tom Otten.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey Jr. is his father's son but not your father's Red. The
Reds of the '70s were so conservative the players were forbidden
from growing facial hair. Rose, the embodiment of the Big Red
Machine, was such a traditionalist he once cut short a photography
shoot when the photographer playfully turned the bill of Rose's cap
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Rose screamed, recoiling. ``I never, ever, wear a
baseball uniform like a clown.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey Jr., the new face of the franchise, has no such
compunctions. Since his Seattle days, he has tried to move fashion
forward by wearing his cap backward.
</P>
<P>
   When Griffey Jr. accepted much less than market value to return
to his hometown, it raised expectations to a level not seen in
these parts since Griffey's father's first full season with the
Reds in 1975. And not just among the local populace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the start of one of the greatest seasons any Cincinnati
team has ever had,'' said outfielder Dmitri Young before the Reds
lost five of their first nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Young's heart was in the right place even if he started the
season out of position, at first base, because of Sean Casey's
broken thumb.
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't worry about having to eat his words. Once Griffey
Jr. adjusts to National League hitting, the Kid and his supporting
cast ought to be all right. The Retro Red Machine's lineup, from
Pokey Reese to Michael Tucker, has the power to give opposing
pitchers fits.
</P>
<P>
   All eight players in the every-day lineup hit at least 10 home
runs in 1999, an executioners row not seen in Cincinnati since the
mid-1970s when George Foster, Cesar Geronimo and Ken Griffey Sr.
averaged 57 RBI collectively while batting sixth, seventh and
eighth, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder second baseman Joe Morgan was quoted at the time as
saying, ``I feel we have the perfect lineup. There are no outs
here.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Rose and Morgan got the hits and Johnny Bench and Tony
Perez got them home. Twenty-five years later, the Reds are counting
on Reese and Barry Larkin getting on base and Griffey Jr., Dante
Bichette and Casey driving them home.
</P>
<P>
   Those `70s Reds, anchored by Gold Glove givens Morgan, Bench and
shortstop Dave Concepcion, were airtight defensively.
</P>
<P>
   These Retro Reds have the Tupperware seal, to be sure. Reese has
been called ``the best fielding second baseman I've ever seen'' by
no less an authority than Marty Brennaman, who has been
broadcasting Reds games for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not you agree with him (Anderson, for one, does not,
deferring to Morgan), there's no disputing that Reese, like Morgan,
makes fielding look like ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Reese, Larkin and Griffey Jr. are Gold Glove winners. Together
they form a midsection as strong as a weightlifter's abdomen.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds could stand to beef up their starting rotation. Pete
Harnisch and Denny Neagle are fierce competitors, but they don't
command fear, fame or even fitness (both battled shoulder problems
last year).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jack Billingham, Don Gullett and Clay Kirby weren't
exactly household names in the `70s and they turned out to be
useful cogs in the Big Red Machine. The bullpen carried the
pitching staff then, and now Scott Williamson and Danny Graves
headline a relief corps that led the majors last year with a 3.36
ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Say this about the Retro Red Machine: It has a sleek look.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Griffey Jr., arguably the greatest player of his
era, makes all the difference. Like the new VW bug, these Retro
Reds look, on the surface, to be an improvement over the original.
</P>
<P>
   But don't take our word for it. ``Cincinnati is back,'' said
former skipper Anderson, now retired and living in Thousand Oaks.
``I've already said the Reds and the Yankees will meet in the
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Dodgers-Reds rivalry that will be renewed today? The
pitching isn't there anymore for the Dodgers so neither is the
feeling. While general manager Jim Bowden was busy recreating the
past, you see, the Dodgers were simply living in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 0206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
