<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, April 14..
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECT-ASSESS (Lima, Peru) _ News analysis: How opposition
leader Alejandro Toledo has risen to the point where he now
threatens to topple President Alberto Fujimori in the second round
of presidential voting. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POPULATE (Lufeng, China) _ In a country best known for its
excruciatingly tough one-child policy, large young families today
are scattered throughout the countryside. Although, technically,
rural families can have only up to two children _ and then only if
the first child is a girl _ families with three, four, five or more
children are now the norm in many areas, including this southern
coastal region of Guangdong. The size of the rural population boom
is unclear because many ``illegal'' children are born in secret,
their births never officially registered. And so, as China prepares
this year to conduct its once-a-decade census, the true size of the
world's most populous country remains in doubt. By Elisabeth
Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-LEECHES (Rodniki, Russia) _ Here at the International
Center for Medicinal Leeches, Gennadi Nikonov has a true
evangelical fire about blood sucking and is determined to restore
to the leech its good medieval name. He sees a great future for
leeches, and some big money along the way. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-STANDARDS (Undated) _ Preempting a growing national
movement to impose tougher standards on teachers, the American
Federation of Teachers, the nation's second largest teachers union,
will propose a national test and rigorous new standards for those
who want to become teachers. By Kate Zernike.
</P>
<P>
   COAL-ASH-ENVIRON (Farmersburg, Ind.) _ It is bad enough, people
here say, that their beloved Indiana countryside has been gouged by
strip mines. What could be worse, they fear, is what the coal
company wants to put back in the holes. What worries people is
something called coal ash, which is what is left after coal is
burned in the power plants that still generate more than half of
the electricity used in the United States. Across the country, more
than 100 million tons of the ash are produced each year, and until
now, it has been treated as essentially benign. But almost
overnight, the question of coal ash and how to handle it has become
the subject of a hot environmental debate. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MOST-DISTANT-OBJECTS (Undated) _ Astronomers working on a
vast survey of the heavens have discovered the most distant object
ever detected, a fiery, reddish dot called a quasar that emitted
its light less than a billion years after the universe was born.
But in a measure of how efficiently telescopes have begun plumbing
the deepest reaches of the cosmos, astronomers on the project said
that they could break their own record within days or weeks as the
survey continues its sweep across the sky. What made the find
extraordinary, they said, was the discovery of dozens of other
quasars that are nearly as distant, allowing scientists to begin
piecing together a kind of census of regions of the universe that
were once entirely inaccessible. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BASSANI (Rome) _ Giorgio Bassani, the author of the classic
modern novel ``The Garden of the Finzi-Continis,'' died Thursday in
the San Camillo hospital in Rome. He was 84. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ENVIRON (Washington) _ Republicans can barely control their
glee as Al Gore's ``Earth in the Balance'' is reissued, asserting
that it will cast the presumptive Democratic nominee as a dangerous
environmentalist extremist. Democrats counter such attacks have
failed before _ remember ``ozone man?'' in 1992 _ and Gore will
only look prescient for anyone going back to his 1991 environmental
manifesto. A look at the political maneuvering around this book,
which will be published with a new foreword next week, in which
Gore asserts that he stands by what he wrote. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-PRESS (Washington) _ Throughout the primary season George
W. Bush seemed almost reclusive in comparison with the
ultra-accessible John McCain. Though regular, his meetings with
reporters were quite controlled and he never held the sort of
free-wheeling sessions that McCain did. But since being assured of
the nomination, Bush has begun to open up, talking more often with
reporters and becoming, in stark contrast with his opponent, Al
Gore, the accessible candidate of the 2000 campaign. A political
memo by Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FARM-SUBSIDIES _ Congress once again is spreading billions to
fertilize American agribusiness. House and Senate negotiators
agreed on Wednesday to a new $7.1 billion bailout for farmers. But
that money was supposed to be drying up by now. Four years ago, the
Republican Congress proclaimed an end to what their speaker, Newt
Gingrich, called the ``East German socialist'' farm programs of the
New Deal. Congress passed, and President Clinton signed, the
Republicans' Freedom to Farm Act. But Congress has since repeatedly
passed emergency increases in spending for agriculture. And the
subsidies have been an unfailing spring, now flowing faster than
ever. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-DEFECTORS (Undated) _ In the mass exodus from established
companies to dot-com concerns, some people are finding the promised
land is not what they had expected. Not everybody finds it easy to
adjust to bosses who will not focus, workspaces that double as
kennels and a culture in which the fun is compulsory. Some are even
deciding that the toll they are being asked to pay for Internet
riches is too high. By Laura Holson and Katie Hafner.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clietns.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-COFFEE (Singapore) _ Only a few years ago, the fanciest
coffee around here cost 40 cents and looked like motor oil cut with
a dollop of Elmer's glue. This syrupy concoction can still be had
at old-fashioned places all over Singapore. But just as in America,
teenagers and older, upwardly mobile workers nowadays flock to
trendy cafes to ponder dating or dot-coms over pricey coffee
concoctions. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic have been sent sent to NYT
photo/graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-TELECOMS (London) _ When it comes to auctions, forget
bidding on the Internet, or even selling that Picasso stashed in
the attic: The big money is in the airwaves. For the last five and
a half weeks, some of the world's leading telecommunications
companies have been battling for licenses to operate a new
generation of mobile phones and other wireless devices in Britain _
something seen as only the precursor of a much broader war for the
airwaves of Europe. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   PALM-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Looking at Palm Inc.'s share
price since it went public last month, you might think something
funny was going on. The Palm saga involves ridiculous stock market
valuations and vanishing profits. The fact that there was no
cheating makes it one of the most amazing tales that Wall Street
and corporate America have served up in years. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   RECRUIT-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ A funny thing happened to a
leading creative executive on his way to San Francisco: He is
instead heading about 340 miles south. His movements are indicative
of the fierce competition among agencies for top creative talent.
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COlUMN (New York) _ Gail Collins examines Rudy
Giuliani's identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Thomas L. Friedman writes about the
various protests against the IMF.
