</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEVINSON-ART-REVIEW (Undated) _ C.R.W. Nevinson is often cited
as England's premier ``war artist,'' and the term, odd as it sounds
today, is apt. A retrospective of Nevinson's work is now at the
Yale Center for British Art in New Haven, the largest ever,
organized by the Imperial War Museum in London. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   NY-UPTOWN-ART (New York) _ Fifth Avenue's Museum Mile officially
stops at 104th St. and Museo del Barrio, implying that a cultural
wilderness lies beyond. In fact El Museo is the gateway to a
diffuse network of art spaces farther uptown, including some of
Manhattan's most distinctive museums and a scattering of hard
working and, in some cases, innovative galleries. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   WILD-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``The Wild Party'' at the
Virginia Theater. Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA (Undated) _ Present-day Virginia is a perfectly
respectable state, but in Colonial times and through the early 19th
century, Virginia was a powerhouse, unsurpassed in population,
wealth, political influence and taste. Later, during the Civil War,
it was the colossus of the Confederacy and the key battleground of
the war. A result, for visitors today, is that Virginia's
historical and architectural riches are inexhaustible. Nowhere is
this more apparent than in Fredericksburg (population 19,000), a
wonderful small town midway between Washington and Richmond. Its
compact historic district, attractions and accessibility make
Fredericksburg an ideal weekend destination. By Richard Ruda.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
