<P>
   EAST-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ As played by Om Puri, George Khan,
the owner of a fish-and-chips shop in Manchester, is like an
immovable object. ``East Is East,'' Damien O'Donnell's screen
version of Ayub Khan-Din's play, explores what happens when George
meets the irresistible force of modernity, as embodied by his seven
unruly children and the strange country, England in 1971, in which
he's trying to raise them. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   JAMAICA-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ About half of the dialogue in
``Third World Cop'' _ the highest grossing film in Jamaican cinema
_ is accompanied by subtitles, in case viewers have trouble
deciphering the characters' Jamaican accents. This is unnecessary,
since the film's true idiom is the universal language of cop-movie
cliche. Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
