<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6477 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-4THLD-WRITE     04-14 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-4THLD-WRITETHRU-645(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN'S MIAMI RELATIVES DEFY RENO AS COURT ISSUES STAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs 16th graf to say videotape of Elian was made and released by
family) 
 (See also CUBAN-BOY-SCENE, CUBAN-BOY-MEDIA, CUBAN-BOY-PSYCHE,
CUBAN-BOY-DOCTOR, EDIT-CUBAN-BOY and CUBAN-BOY-ESTEFAN) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Cuban flag was hoisted high by Cuban exiles Thursday
in a temporary victory over the governments of Fidel Castro and the
United States as Elian Gonzalez's relatives first defied a deadline
to give up the boy and then won an emergency stay that will delay
any action for at least the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   As 4,000 demonstrators cheered and chanted in the streets of
Little Havana outside the house of Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro
Gonzalez, the boy's relatives ignored the order by Attorney General
Janet Reno to take Elian from the home by 2 p.m. and deliver him to
a nearby airport.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just an hour or so later, lawyers for the great-uncle
obtained an emergency, temporary stay from the 11th Circuit U.S.
Court of Appeals, one that prevents Elian's father from taking the
boy back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   A single appellate judge ordered the emergency stay and asked
the Justice Department to delay any efforts to take the boy until
the entire court could review the emergency petition.
</P>
<P>
   The stay blocks Elian from leaving the country while the full
panel considers an injunction that would keep him in the United
States until a full hearing before the 11th Circuit on May 11. It
does not specifically bar the government from returning Elian to
his father. But government officials said Thursday that they would
not try to take the boy away in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   It should take the appellate court three or four days to rule on
the emergency stay, said a Justice Department spokeswoman. The
appellate court also asked the government to file an answer to the
family's petition by Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring the 2 p.m. deadline was just the latest, and the most
audacious, defiance of the federal government by a family that had
seemed reconciled to losing the boy just a day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But as the day came to comply with a government order to hand
over Elian, Lazaro Gonzalez just said no. The government did not
immediately move to take Elian, and the standoff of more than four
months continued.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the news, Cuban-Americans ran down the streets,
laughing and screaming ``Justice! Justice! Justice!'' An elderly
woman in Little Havana grabbed a stranger's arm and, making
fluttering motions in the air with one hand, asked: ``Elian no fly
away now? Good.''
</P>
<P>
   Car horns pounded the air in Little Havana. Demonstrators
produced a dummy of Fidel Castro, stabbed it with flags, and then
ripped off its head.
</P>
<P>
   It also seemed a clear, if temporary, defeat of an attorney
general who has been hung in effigy here for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am trying to work through an extraordinary tragedy without
having to cause further harm to the boy,'' Reno said at a news
conference two hours before the deadline, in which she made it
clear that the government would not try to remove Elian
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, where Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, is
waiting for a reunion with his son, more demonstrators called to
him to defect. He responded with a one-handed obscene gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Elian had appeared on television, speaking
directly to his father. ``Papa, I don't want to go to Cuba,'' he
said in Spanish, wagging his finger in the air like an adult
lecturing a child. ``I want to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Now and then Elian, who was chewing gum, looked off-camera to
someone standing nearby. ``If you guys want to, you guys stay
here,'' he said, apparently referring to his father, stepmother and
half-brother.
</P>
<P>
   The home videotape of Elian, which was released by the family
and shown on several networks, carried a logo from the Spanish
language channel Univision.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory B. Craig, lawyer for Juan Miguel Gonzalez, replied by
saying that the Miami relatives have exploited the boy and damaged
him, emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Lazaro Gonzalez defied the nation's chief law
enforcement officers and publicly and belligerently refused to turn
Elian over to his father,'' Craig said. ``Lazaro Gonzalez broke the
law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Almost from the beginning, when Elian was found floating off the
coast of South Florida after a failed crossing from Cuba resulted
in the deaths of his mother and 10 others, Reno has been flexible
with the Miami family, frequently extending deadlines for handing
over the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Reno flew to Miami to meet with Lazaro
Gonzalez, Elian and other family members, in what many political
experts called an extraordinary gesture.
</P>
<P>
   But talks late into the night produced no agreement, and left
Lazaro Gonzalez so angry that he vowed that, if government
officials were going to have Elian the next day, they would have to
come into his home and take him.
</P>
<P>
   That puzzled many people who have heard him say over and over
that he does not want to traumatize the child by having him endure
such an abrupt, ugly separation from the Miami family that has
cared for him, bought him clothes and toys and even built him a
swing set in their yard.
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez said that such a traumatic event would be better
than having the boy feel that he had been betrayed by his Miami
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has been criticized by many people, both in and outside
South Florida, for her apparent, seemingly fathomless patience.
</P>
<P>
   At the Justice Department, some officials expressed
disappointment over her failure to return with Elian and said that
her high-profile effort had apparently accomplished little except
to further galvanize Miami's Cuban-American community against the
government.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the aides said the government had been left to seem
impotent and vacillating. Reno had allowed the relatives to flout
the law without facing the consequences, the critics said.
</P>
<P>
   But the attorney general, who was much more hotly criticized for
the way federal agents responded to Branch Davidians in Waco,
Texas, in 1993, resulting in a deadly fire, said any effort to take
Elian from Miami will be thoughtful, reasoned and measured.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, however, seemed weary of the standoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried to do everything I can to stay out of it,''
Clinton said. ``But it is our obligation to uphold the rule of
law.''
</P>
<P>
   In the crowd of demonstrators, several people said they had
shown Reno and Clinton that they simply would not be allowed to
have Elian. Some even chanted ``War! War! War!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did it have to take all these Cubans to tell the
government that they're not practicing by their own rules,'' said
Jose Cabrera, a food service distributor in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, it was a peaceful, even carnival atmosphere,
where demonstrators stopped chanting to eat cherry snow cones and
take pictures of celebrities like Gloria Estefan and Andy Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez, along with Garcia and Estefan, pleaded with the
swelling crowd for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want no violence,'' said Estefan, the singer who is an icon
in Miami, her hometown. ``We are a peaceful community.''
</P>
<P>
   But every few minutes seemed to bring another contradiction.
Family members asked for peace from the crowd even as they said
federal officials would have to enter the highly charged atmosphere
to take the boy away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to have to come get him,'' said Marisleysis
Gonzalez, Lazaro's 21-year-old daughter and the person who has been
closest to Elian here in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But that confrontation never came. Even though police used
barricades to block miles of the Little Havana neighborhood and had
dozens of officers standing by, the worst that happened was sunburn
and sore feet and hoarse voices. The crowd dwindled as the night
wore on.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, however, the family must decide if it wants to have
federal agents come in and take the boy and carry him into a street
where thousands of people wait. They say they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing now depends on how the family handles it in
the last two minutes'' of that possible confrontation, said Angel
Calzadilla, a police officer in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators have said throughout the standoff that non-Cubans
would never understand why it is so hateful to them to have to give
up the child to a government that imprisoned and abused them and
their relatives and forced them into exile.
</P>
<P>
   To them, this is not just something that interrupts their
regularly scheduled programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is real life,'' said Yaumary Marin, an insurance sales
agent who lives in Hialeah, Fla., and took the day off to come to
Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   People carried signs that spelled out their long-running hatred
of the dictator. ``Elian's parole was signed by his mother's bloody
death.''
</P>
<P>
   The family's options seem to be running out. In Florida state
court, a judge rejected their request that the local court
intercede. The judge, Jennifer D. Bailey, ruled that she had no
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   But for a few more days, Miami's exiles are beating their
nemesis in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Amaro, an electrician who lives in Kendall, southwest of
Miami, brought her 5-year-old son and 12-year-old daughter to the
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have hope today,'' Amaro said.
</P>
</TEXT>
