<HEADLINE>
PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 400-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S A BIG COUNTRY: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised in the west, the west of Texas. It's pretty close
to California. In more ways than Washington, D.C., is close to
Texas.'' (George W. Bush touting his California credentials, Los
Angeles Times, April 8) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDORSEMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be damned if I'll have Bush in the White House. So I'm
going to back Gore even though it's killing me. Plus, I require
more than a 2.0 grade-point average for my president. You know, I
had better than that.'' (Dee Snider, lead singer of Twisted Sister,
a heavy-metal band once cited by the Gores as an example of what
was wrong with modern popular music, ``Equal Time,'' MSNBC, April
10) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GOREISM OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother always made it clear to my sister and me that women
and men were equal _ if not more so.'' (Al Gore, Associated Press,
April 10) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLL OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Glamour magazine to select their key issue, the young
women of America plumped for health care (24 percent), taxes (22
percent), education (14 percent) and abortion (14 percent). No one
chose foreign policy. Fewer than one in four wanted a woman on the
presidential ticket. Bush was more popular than Gore. The same poll
also revealed that 46 percent of women are ``always looking to try
new and different beauty products.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OUT OF THE CLOSET: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bush has agreed to meet prominent homosexual Republicans, but
not the national Log Cabin Republicans. He and they have been
aflutter ever since the party's leading homosexual group leaned
towards John McCain. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANDIDATE OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a race between someone who doesn't know himself _ Gore
_ and someone who doesn't know anything _ W.'' (Pat Buchanan,
Associated Press, April 8) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COUNTER-QUAYLE: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While visiting a class of first-graders in Ohio, Gore remained
silent as the teachers and pupils spelled ``sincerely'' as
``sincerly,'' perhaps mindful of what happened to the last vice
president who tried to spell in public. (New York Times, April 12) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND...: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The insider Ralph Reed, a Bush adviser, was hired by Microsoft
to lobby the Texas governor on the company's behalf. Reed, formerly
head of the Christian Coalition, subsequently apologized and
promised to stop lobbying Bush. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
