<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 05:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SLIPPERY-BP-AMOCO-ECO     04-14 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLIPPERY-BP-AMOCO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ETHICAL' BP AMOCO'S HALO SLIPS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 400-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not so long ago, BP Amoco was being feted by ``ethical
investment'' funds and environmental groups. In spite of being one
of the world's biggest purveyors of fossil fuels, the firm has made
some surprisingly green investments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, BP now controls Solarex, the world's biggest
solar-energy company. And it has voluntarily decided to curb
emissions of greenhouse gases, and is building an internal
carbon-trading scheme.
</P>
<P>
   It is surprising, then, that the firm should now be under attack
from activist groups on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In America, a curious coalition ranging from the American
Anti-Slavery Group and the International Campaign for Tibet to
Friends of the Earth is threatening a boycott of BP's gas stations.
</P>
<P>
   In London, a group led by Greenpeace barracked BP's annual
general meeting on April 13.
</P>
<P>
   These attacks are a bit unfair. The wrath of the American
groups, for example, is really directed at China National Petroleum
Corporation (CNPC), which they believe is involved in human-rights
atrocities and environmental misdeeds everywhere from Tibet to
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   This group mobilized opposition to last week's flotation of
PetroChina, a division of CNPC, and nearly sank it. BP attracted
their ire when, in a friendly gesture to Beijing, it bought a big
tranche at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Greenpeace usually throws tomatoes from the outside at annual
meetings of oil firms. This time, it won the support of Trillium
Asset Management, an American firm specializing in socially
responsible investment, which has become a big shareholder in BP.
</P>
<P>
   Trillium put forward a resolution at the AGM that BP's resources
should be redirected from Alaska to its solar-energy venture. Even
its sponsors acknowledged that the measure was never likely to
pass, but was designed to win publicity for the plight of cuddly
polar bears.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was meant to highlight how vulnerable the Arctic is
to global warming generally, and not just to BP's Alaskan projects,
which are not demonstrably dirtier than others.
</P>
<P>
   Does all this mean that BP's green credentials have faded? In
truth, no: the solar-energy company flourishes, and the firm's
commitment to carbon reduction still wins praise in many quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always knew it wasn't going to be easy to plough a straight
furrow, but we will continue to try,'' says one company official.
As these incidents show, it is not easy being green _ especially if
you are an oil giant. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 0555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 05:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6575 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-SOUTHAFRICA-SOFTWARE-     04-14 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHAFRICA-SOFTWARE-ECONOMIST-650&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEEKS OF THE BUSHVELD: SOUTH AFRICA'S IT BOOM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (NOTE: Two trims, total 225; 1,150 words uncut)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 From the Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Sometimes, obstacles create opportunities. So it
has been in South Africa's information technology (IT) business.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate South Africa hungers for new technology. Combined with
other cumbersome labor laws, ``affirmative action'' prompts
companies to replace people with machines wherever practical.
</P>
<P>
   A bank that fails to hire or promote a black cashier may be
subject to a racial-discrimination lawsuit. An automatic teller, by
contrast, works 24 hours a day and never sues.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Nedcor, the South African bank with the most
admired IT systems, has shaved 25 percent off its operating costs
over the past three years through automation.
</P>
<P>
   Stannic, the vehicle-finance arm of Standard Bank, recently
closed all 46 of its offices, laid off more than 900 people and
moved its operations to call centers and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Banking is not the only business using IT to replace people.
J.D. Group, a retailer of sofas, washing machines and other chunky
consumer durables, has so many branches in remote places with poor
telecommunications that it rented part of a satellite to let its
computers talk to each other uninterrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Many of J.D.'s skilled white managers have emigrated; the firm
has replaced them largely with software.
</P>
<P>
   Tasks such as controlling stocks and making sure that indebted
customers do not fall behind on payments are now largely automated.
The number of employees has been cut from 13,000 in 1993 to 9,500
today.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it just companies that yearn for IT. South Africa has
many more mobile telephones and computers than the rest of the
continent (indeed, there are three times as many mobile-phone
subscribers in South Africa as in the rest of Africa put together),
and that creates opportunities for innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Firms are already drooling at the prospect of wireless
application protocol (WAP) technology, which will allow people to
gain access to the Internet via their mobile phones.
</P>
<P>
   Old Mutual, an insurer, recently started to allow customers to
buy and sell unit trusts over the Internet, using WAP.
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Brozin, head of Nando's, a fast-food chain, believes that
WAP will reassure potential customers who fear to disclose their
credit-card numbers online. Since users already have a mobile-phone
account, he hopes to sell home-delivered chillied chicken burgers
via mobiles, and simply add the price to the monthly telephone
bill.
</P>
<P>
   IT also provides a flexible career path for young whites.
Unwelcome in the public service, they are more likely than blacks
to seek marketable skills, such as accountancy or computing.
</P>
<P>
   Young programmers can easily find work in South Africa. Or they
can emigrate. Or they can enjoy the best of both worlds by
telecommuting to California, earning dollars but paying rent in
rand.
</P>
<P>
   The IT firms that provide the know-how for all this are among
the most popular companies on Johannesburg's stock exchange.
Dimension Data (Didata), the country's largest IT firm, is valued
at 50.8 billion rand ($7.7 billion); Datatec, the fastest-growing
over the past five years, has vaulted from 40 million rand in 1994
to 12.6 billion rand today.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the escalating demand in South Africa, the industry
suffers from several of the handicaps that plague so many of the
country's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For example, both Didata and Datatec now do most of their
business overseas. Datatec does not plan to list abroad, but two of
its subsidiaries will probably soon list on Nasdaq and in London.
</P>
<P>
   Didata hopes to move its primary listing to London later this
year, because it is easier to raise money there, and because its
employees in Asia and Europe do not want their share options
denominated in rand.
</P>
<P>
   Also, South African IT professionals often emigrate. Jeremy Ord,
chairman of Didata, argues that it is easier to retain staff if he
can offer them jobs in London or Singapore. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 650) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More serious is the effect of Telkom, the state telephone
monopoly. In theory, the Internet ought to allow South African IT
companies to overcome the drawback of being far from big markets.
In practice, bandwidth is roughly 30 times as expensive in South
Africa as it is in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Telkom, not one of our South African clients is
globally competitive,'' complains Ord.
</P>
<P>
   The monopoly is due to end in 2002 or 2003, but real
deregulation may come slowly. The government is reluctant to lose
control of Telkom, partly because it is a useful way of delivering
contracts to black business. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helping the cluster of small IT firms to grow will be difficult.
South Africa has yet to see an Internet start-up boom like that in
America or Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Johannesburg's venture capitalists are fewer and less
venturesome than those in California. The most prolific backers of
small IT firms have generally been large IT firms such as Didata
and Datatec.
</P>
<P>
   There are still relatively few 20-something millionaires, such
as Mark Shuttleworth, a Capetonian whose Internet security software
firm, Thawte, is valued at 3.5 billion rand, or Nicolaas Vlok,
whose software firm, Idion, is valued at 1.3 billion rand.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttleworth sold his company to an American rival; he would
probably have raised far less by listing in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there is no vibrant growth of IT companies run or
staffed by blacks. Most of South Africa's successful IT firms are
as white as traditional cricketing trousers.
</P>
<P>
   Deprived of education under apartheid, few black South Africans
yet have computing skills. Those blacks who make it to university
tend to study literature or social sciences, often with the aim of
entering government. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 950, OR CONTINUE TO 1,150) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Most black-run IT firms survive by doing business with the
government or with state-owned firms, which give preference to
black tenders. Some of them were formerly white-owned, bought by
``black empowerment'' holding companies in order to leverage black
ownership into government contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Empowerment Trust (CET), a firm that has close links with
the ruling African National Congress, has one subsidiary that
supplies cables to Telkom, and another that is bidding for a
government contract to introduce electronic payment systems for
minibus taxis.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Nissen, the chairman, argues that South Africa needs a
black-run IT firm to rival Didata and Datatec. But he complains
that white IT bosses are reluctant to surrender control of their
companies. Odd, that. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
