<P>
   &UR; GREAT NEWS FROM THE IMF. BUT COMPLACENCY CAN BE DANGEROUS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROSY-PROSPECTS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aptly enough, 2000 looks set to be a wonderful year for the
world economy, predicts the International Monetary Fund in its new
global economic forecasts, published this week. America is still
booming. Europe, with lots of ground to make up, has begun to surge
as well. In East Asia, things are going better than almost anybody
expected even six months ago. Altogether, it is a marvelous
prospect. But it would be wise to remember a reliable law of
economics: the bigger the boom, the crueller the crunch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 900 words; total uncut is 1,050) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TUSK, TUSK: THE ELEPHANTINE PROBLEM OF RARE-SPECIES TRADE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRADE-VS-SAVE-SPECIES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuke the whales'' was a popular slogan among the
politically-incorrect in the 1980s. That is going a bit far, but
the issue of whether and how to protect ``charismatic megafauna''
(whales, elephants, tigers and so on) raises strong passions. These
passions are now on view in Nairobi, at a meeting of the Convention
on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHY AREN'T U.S. TAXPAYERS WHINING? IT'S THE ECONOMY, STUPID &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TAXES-US-SOCIALISM-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is spring and tax-filing season. This time last year, the
Internal Revenue Service collected $1.7 trillion _ a sum larger
than Britain's entire gross domestic product and enough to ensure
that America had a budget surplus for the third year running. So
why on earth isn't there a clamor in America to cut taxes? The
popular response is: it's the economy, stupid. Americans are doing
so well these days that they don't need a big tax cut. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Three trims, totaling 250 words; total uncut is 1,250) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIRE ANTS ARE COMING, THE FIRE ANTS ARE COMING! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIRE-ANTS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Schuman was on his knees, gardening, when he
accidentally invaded the space of a fire-ant colony. It was a
serious mistake. Weeks later, his legs still sported blotchy red
stings. The irony is that Dr. Schuman is one of the world's experts
on the ferocious creatures, and of the havoc they wreak. Each
spring some part of America panics about the arrival of fire ants,
and for good reason: they are spreading relentlessly; and they are
very nasty, indeed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: S.C., Southeast Editors) &QL;
</P>
