<P>
   &UR; A CRUDE REALITY FOR WEST TEXAS OIL FIELDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIDLAND-TX-OIL-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While much of the rest of Texas basks in high-tech euphoria _
Austin and Houston, in particular _ oil production in the Permian
basin of West Texas has declined for the past 25 years and little
new industry has moved in to take its place. The fortunes of ``the
oil patch'' depend on the countries around the Persian Gulf,
thousands of miles away, whose decisions set the price of oil. If
its oil-dependent economy is so troubled even when the price is up,
what can west Texas do? &QL;
