<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSSIA'S STRANGELY DEFIANT OPTIMISM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPTIMISTIC-RUSSIA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is an adage that Russia is never as strong, or as weak, as
it appears. Indeed, the Kremlin's new occupants may be repeating it
to themselves under their breath as they try to keep within
reasonable limits the surge of exuberance that often takes hold of
Moscow's ruling class in spring. President-elect Vladimir Putin and
his lieutenants have several reasons to be tempted into euphoria,
and several reasons to be cautious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TURKEY'S FUNKY, MIXED-SEX WHIRLING DERVISHES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEMALE-DERVISHES-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is another night of devotion at the ancient tekke, as
buildings that house dervish communities are known, in Istanbul's
Uskudar district. There is nothing odd about the scene, repeated
for centuries in tekkes across Turkey. But closer scrutiny reveals
that _ unusually _ these spinning figures include females, banned
from taking part in the rituals since the 17th century. And the
women are not swathed in traditional white but in bright pinks,
oranges and greens. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTH AFRICA'S ANXIOUS EYES ON ZIMBABWE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MBEKI-MUGABE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Thabo Mbeki bumped into Robert Mugabe during coffee breaks
at the G-77 summit of developing countries in Havana this week, the
air must have turned frosty. The presidents of South Africa and
Zimbabwe are not on good terms. Mbeki is the widely respected,
fairly elected leader of Africa's richest and most powerful nation.
Mugabe is, in the words of former Archbishop Desmond Tutu, ``almost
a caricature of all the things people think black African leaders
do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICO'S MONOPOLISTIC TELECOMS: STATIC ON THE LINE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEXICAN-TELECOMS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since it came into force in 1994, the North American Free-Trade
Agreement has transformed many aspects of economic life in Mexico,
and has helped the country to achieve several years of steady
growth. Yet some Mexican habits remain defiantly unreformed.
Nowhere is this more starkly illustrated than in the current row
over competition in Mexico's telecoms industry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `ETHICAL' BP AMOCO'S HALO SLIPS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLIPPERY-BP-AMOCO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, BP Amoco was being feted by ``ethical
investment'' funds and environmental groups. In spite of being one
of the world's largest purveyors of fossil fuels, the firms has
made some surprisingly green investments. Odd, then, that the firm
should now be under attack from activist groups on both sides of
the Atlantic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GEEKS OF THE BUSHVELD: SOUTH AFRICA'S IT BOOM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SOUTHAFRICA-SOFTWARE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, obstacles create opportunities. So it has been in
South Africa's information technology (IT) industry, where business
is booming. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Two trims, totaling 225; total uncut is 1,150 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
