<HEADER>
A6598 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-BOS     04-14 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN: NO STYLE POINTS FOR BURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden said
there is plenty of blame to go around for the team's disastrous
1999-2000 campaign, but in his opinion, a healthy amount belongs to
coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging interview Thursday, Sinden said he's had a
problem with the team's style of play for the three seasons Burns
has been at the helm. How that issue is resolved will go a long way
toward determining if Burns returns for the fourth year of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can continue to play the way we play,'' said
Sinden. ``What changes it requires will have to be discussed
between the coach, myself, and (assistant GM Mike O'Connell). I
think it's foolish to think we can play in the same manner and turn
21 wins into 40 wins. It's just a manner of play that didn't work
last year. The question we have to ask ourselves is, `Was it just
an aberration that it didn't work or will it continue not to work?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the system wasn't a trap nor a forechecking scheme.
He feels the defensemen backed up too often, taking the safe route,
and that the only way the Bruins were able to get possession of the
puck was behind their own net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say we never get it at center ice or at their blue
line but (we need to get it) more often,'' he said. ``And check the
puck carrier sooner than we do. I think it was very difficult to
play defense on this team and very difficult to play goal. When we
were able to get possession or a turnover from the other team, we
had 200 feet to go. That's a long, long way and you have to be
talented to carry it 200 feet and not lose it on the way down. Some
do it with forechecking, some do it with the trap . . . but we
didn't play the trap and we didn't really forecheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said he didn't say much in Burns's first two years for
two reasons _ the team was successful and management had given the
coaching staff an unusual level of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't liked it for three years but it worked and you kind
of overlooked a lot of it,'' he said. ``It's not that I detested
it. There are things about it. It happened with (Brian) Sutter, it
happened with Terry (O'Reilly). When you lose, you have to answer.
With Pat Burns, it was total autonomy, on everything. On every
single thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked why Burns had such power, Sinden said, ``He was coach
of the year twice (Burns won the award a third time in 1997-98),
you'd better let him do his thing. I'd had discussions with every
other coach about how the team was playing or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the Bruins didn't play five good games the entire
season. He said he discussed his concerns with Burns, but didn't
see any changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That may be because he didn't agree with me and that's fine,''
said Sinden. ``We had a couple of conversations about it, but I
didn't really feel that my input meant very much and that's not the
first time. Mike Milbury used to get mad at me in these meetings,
then he'd come back and say, `I'm going to try it, you could be
right but I hope you're not right because then I'd have to admit
you were right.' Some were right, some weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the lack of change angered him, Sinden said,
``When we lose, sure it does because you couldn't do any worse,
right? When we win, I still offer my advice but it doesn't mean
very much at that point. It might be the same advice.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to describe the style Burns employed, Sinden referred
to European systems that use terms such as a 1-2-1 or a 2-1-2
formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours as I saw it was a zero-five,'' he said, suggesting that
everyone was playing back. ``That may be the way we played the last
two years prior to it and got 90 points. I thought we were living
on a bit of borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some things where I don't feel we can be successful
unless we correct. That doesn't mean I'm right. If we don't correct
them, maybe we will be successful, but at this point, I don't think
we will. If the Patriots passed on first down every single time
they got possession for 16 straight games, you'd all say, `What the
hell kind of coach is that? What kind of system have they got?'
You'd demand a change but you can't see what I'm talking about on
the ice like we all can in football.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden acknowledged there was adversity all year, but said the
team overcame none of it. Even if the team had been healthy, which
it definitely was not, he said he'd still have a problem with the
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am upset with the way the team plays, who do I blame?''
he said. ``I mean the style, not the individual player and how good
they are, but the methods we use. If I don't think they're right
and we lose all the time, then someone has to at least take the
blame for the way we play. Not whether it's right or wrong, but he
has to be responsible for the way we played.''
</P>
<P>
   So what happens now? Burns has yet to talk with management to
try to resolve the situation. Sinden said that likely will come
early next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never said anything about (Burns) not being here,'' he
said. ``All the talk about him not being here is not coming from
me. We haven't made any decision; we're going to talk about the
future. Maybe he doesn't want to stay. After I meet with Pat, I'll
have a better idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect things to go pretty smoothly. I think some of the
things I've told you I think have to happen with the team that he
will dispute and show me why he disputes it and he'll probably make
a good point. I suppose if everything I think has to happen and he
wants the opposite to happen, then we have to think about that.
Somebody has to decide what way we're going here.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sinden finds out everyone's on the same page, he said that
would certainly be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to discuss it with (owner Jeremy Jacobs), as well. He
doesn't like the results of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much speculation we might say one thing or the
other just to remove the speculation. But as of now, at this point,
as far as I'm concerned, he's our coach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
