<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First, vitamins were our saviors; then the real truth came out
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ My local supermarket has row upon row of vitamins,
minerals, extracts, compounds and mixtures that hint at curing or
preventing all known health problems.
</P>
<P>
   The section for these concoctions is located across the aisle
from medicines typically used for headaches, colds, sore throats
and such.
</P>
<P>
   One side of the aisle is for people who have an ailment they
want to get rid of. The other side is for people who are trying to
not get something they'll want to get rid of.
</P>
<P>
   I've always figured that I'd wait until I got something unwanted
before I'd worry about it. Besides, I never trusted the claims that
swallowing so many milligrams of tree bark, weed pollen or
pulverized rock would be any better for me than the traditional
food sold in the store.
</P>
<P>
   For years I've listened to relatives, friends and even doctors
talk about antioxidants, free radicals and dietary supplements.
Back in the 1960s, free radicals were the hippies who hadn't been
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, I caved in and began taking some of the stuff
sold across the aisle from the aspirin, cough medicine and throat
lozenges.
</P>
<P>
   I now take a multivitamin tablet that contains most of the
elements in the periodic table. It's a huge pill.
</P>
<P>
   I also take a big vitamin C pill each morning. A motorcycle
racer out in California told me how important it is to take vitamin
C. I bought a big bottle.
</P>
<P>
   An ex-wife with several college degrees told me that I need to
take natural vitamin E and the mineral selenium.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what vitamin E is supposed to do or what the
difference is between natural vitamin E and unnatural vitamin E.
Nevertheless, I bought a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   I also bought a bottle of selenium. It sounds like a chemical
used to make nuclear weapons. It was on a shelf across from the
upset stomach medicine.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many pills, tablets and capsules on my bathroom
counter now that I take half of them in the morning and the other
half at night. This recent development comes after a lifetime of
resisting suggestions and warnings that I should take dietary
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to say whether the pills make any difference
except that they sometimes upset my stomach and cause me to buy the
upset-stomach medicine across from the selenium.
</P>
<P>
   About the time I lined my counter with supplements, a National
Academy of Sciences panel announced that there is no convincing
scientific evidence that taking large amounts of vitamins C and E
or the nutrients selenium and beta carotene can reduce the chances
of getting cancer, heart disease, diabetes, Alzheimer's disease or
other illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   This panel of scientific experts concluded that despite the
popular belief of ex-wives, doctors and others that high doses of
so-called antioxidants help prevent a variety of illnesses, there
is insufficient evidence to recommend that Americans get more of
these nutrients than is necessary to prevent basic nutritional
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said large doses of vitamins C and E and selenium can
be harmful rather than reduce the likelihood of cardiovascular
disease, cataracts, muscular degeneration, Alzheimer's disease,
Parkinson's disease, cancer and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   There also is no evidence that vitamin E or other supplements
can reduce the effects of aging, according to the Institute of
Medicine panel, a branch of the National Academy of Sciences. Too
much vitamin E, however, can cause uncontrolled bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that people should get their nutrients from
food, not pills. A balanced diet and adequate exercise should be
all most Americans need to maintain their health and prevent
disease.
</P>
<P>
   That's too easy.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
