<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Armed escorts ease fears of tourist roaming around egypt
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ For the benefit of any readers in danger of being
conscripted into distant and dangerous journeys, I am passing on
humanitarian advice gleaned from hard experience.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to join a tour group, make sure you know exactly
with whom you will be touring. When my wife signed on for a Nile
expedition, I was pleased to learn that our traveling companions
included Dr. Jim Waggoner, a noted Henry County veterinarian, and
his wife, Marjorie, a well-known goatkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   The Waggoners, fellow survivors of an arduous trip to China two
years ago, seemed to be sensible people. Mrs. Waggoner, unlike my
spouse, is kindly disposed toward goats and wouldn't be terribly
upset if a couple spent an afternoon snoozing on her bedroom
carpet.
</P>
<P>
   I was stunned when the Waggoners asked my wife if we would be
interested in joining them on a trip around the world next year.
Inviting my wife to go anywhere is tantamount to offering whiskey
to an alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't we just love to go around the world?'' she asked me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Possibly,'' I answered. ``That way we could get all our
traveling over with in one shot and never go anywhere else for the
rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   However, after being airborne through several time zones en
route to Cairo, over the icy, shark-infested waters of the
Atlantic, the Alps and the Mediterranean Sea, while squeezed into
seats designed for ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' I made up
my mind that if I ever have to circle the globe it won't be at the
fat part.
</P>
<P>
   The only around-the-world trip I'd consider would be to fly to
the northernmost airport in Canada and go from there. That way we
could leave on Monday, be back on Saturday and not have to miss
church on Sunday, which at my age is something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   Cairo is quite pleasant. People are friendly to Americans and
anxious to try out their English. The weather on arrival was sunny
and crisp and reminded me of San Francisco on a good day.
Mosquitoes that nearly devoured our Dawsonville friend Bill Burt
when he visited a few years ago never showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Palm trees, posh five-star hotels and the Nile River make the
new section of Cairo a mixture of Phoenix, Las Vegas and
Jacksonville, Fla. The Pyramids look pretty much like they do in
National Geographic, except bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Old Cairo is straight out of the picture books children study in
Sunday school. I half expected to meet Jesus and his 12 disciples
walking the dusty streets among camels, donkeys, bearded old men in
flowing robes and women cooking over open fires.
</P>
<P>
   Apprehensions about safety in Egypt were quickly erased. When we
boarded our van for an excursion to the Pyramids, our guide
introduced us to a handsome young man dressed in a blazer, white
shirt and tie, sharply pressed trousers and polished loafers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Ali,'' she said. ``He is our security officer from the
tourist police.'' Ali unbuttoned his coat, smiled, and flashed a
large pistol.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't it give you a comfortable feeling to be so
well-protected?'' my wife said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' I agreed. ``As Mrs. Sadat was saying to Anwar when the
parade was passing by ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean by that?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking. If the whole Egyptian army couldn't keep
their president from being assassinated, what can Ali do for us?''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pyramids in Giza, we were pleased to find a sizable army
of police officers, some afoot, some on horseback, all carrying
submachine guns. Outriders on camels patrolled a perimeter of sand
dunes.
</P>
<P>
   I caused a big commotion when I snapped a picture of four
tourist police in flak jackets standing beside an armored car. They
agreed not to take me into custody after Ali convinced them I was
only a dumb American tourist.
</P>
<P>
   When we reboarded the van the next morning to visit the tomb of
Mohammed Ali (not to be confused with the great boxer), our
personal Secret Service agent was missing. Our Egyptologist, a.k.a.
tour guide, explained that it was Ali's day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``But don't worry,'' she said. ``The others are still with us.''
She pointed at a sedan trailing our van. ``There are three
policemen with guns in the car,'' she said. ``They were behind us
all day yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, there's no need for tourists to be apprehensive
in Egypt. The only thing not safe is the water.
</P>
<P>
   You might watch out for Kentucky Fried Chicken, which along with
McDonald's and Pizza Hut, is a hit with young people, to the
chagrin of the older generation. According to a consumer reporter
on Cairo television, Kentucky Fried Chicken isn't the real thing.
The chickens are genetically engineered and produced in
laboratories in the United States. They don't have heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that true?'' asked our young Egyptologist, who admits an
addiction to American fast food. She keeps menus in her nightstand
but only orders home delivery when her parents are away.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
