<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6620 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ABS-FITNESS15-COX     04-14 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABS-FITNESS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Squeezing out lean abs for summer
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Summer is still two months away, but the season of
abdominal obsessions is in full swing at fitness centers.
</P>
<P>
   At Olympic Gym, owner Chip Marlin estimates that as many as 70
percent of his spring customers are trying to get lean and mean for
the upcoming swimsuit season. The goal for most of them is to lose
weight and add muscle tone. That includes sit-ups, crunches and leg
raises to develop flat, muscular stomachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working to tone up for the summer,'' Marlin said. ``I
can tell by their workout routines.''
</P>
<P>
   Print advertisements and television commercials for warm-weather
clothing are everywhere. Young models with washboard stomachs fill
magazine pages and dot television screens.
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn Cortes, a dietician at Providence Healthcare Clinic,
says striving to lose body fat and add muscle tone is a good goal,
but not everyone is cut out to have a washboard stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wonderful if we were all in perfect shape,''
Cortes said. ``But we have to be realistic. We have to say, `OK,
maybe I can't have a perfect stomach, but I can get in good
shape.'''
</P>
<P>
   Being realistic means understanding that as we get older, we
slowly lose muscle mass, she said. That means body fat percentages
tend to increase, making a ``six pack'' stomach harder and harder
to come by. Once people are out of their 20s, fighting against too
much body fat becomes a regular struggle for many, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, not everyone is built the same, Cortes said. There are
four basic body types for humans: ectomorph (tall and thin),
ovarian (pear shaped with larger hips), mesomorph (stocky, muscular
build), and endomorph (pudgy). No matter how much some people with
ovarian or endomorph body types exercise and diet, it may be
difficult to achieve the kind of washboard stomachs seen on
19-year-old models in print advertisements and on television shows,
trainers and dieticians say.
</P>
<P>
   Cortes said there's nothing wrong with eating healthy and
exercising for a better looking stomach as long as you don't get
carried away. The positives to staying thin are more than just
aesthetic. Recent studies show correlations between abdominal fat
and heart attacks. Even though the challenge of staying fit can
increase with age, Cortes said a balanced diet and exercise routine
can help anyone achieve good health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the individual,'' she said. ``(Your health) doesn't
have to get out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Clark, a personal trainer at Lakewood Tennis &AMP; Fitness
Center, estimates that business at his gym increases by 30 percent
in the spring. Most of his swimsuit-prep customers are looking to
trim extra fat from their waistlines.
</P>
<P>
   But transforming that trim stomach into a ``six pack'' is
another issue, Clark said. Not everyone is genetically cut out to
have a washboard stomach, but everyone can improve the way they
look and feel by watching their diets and exercising consistently,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone can achieve a better-looking body and see
improvements if they work at it,'' Clark said. ``But it can't be
something that for a short period of time you say, `I'm going to
work at it.'''
</P>
<P>
   To counteract flab in the abs, personal trainers and dieticians
suggest a workout regiment with a variety of activities. First,
general weight training does a number of things on the road to
becoming ``cut,'' Marlin said. First, it adds definition and tone
to particular parts of the body. It also adds more muscle mass,
which increases a person's metabolism, helping to burn fat 24 hours
a day.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin and Clark said the quick-fix ab machines sold on TV may
help develop abdominal muscles, but it takes much more than three
minutes a day on them to get a washboard stomach. Developing a
thin, muscular stomach requires two things: developed abdominal
muscles and lack of fat in the midsection.
</P>
<P>
   To focus on the midsection specifically, trainers suggest a few
simple exercises. Leg raises are one of the simplest ways to wake
up and develop those abdominal muscles. The raises involve laying
on your back with your hands beneath the hip area, near the small
of the back. Lift your legs 8 to 24 inches in the air and slowly
lower them to the ground. Repeat the motion eight to ten times. Try
a few sets, three or four times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Crunches also are highly recommended. For this exercise, remain
on your back, but pull your knees up, as if you're sitting in a
chair but your back should remain flat on the ground. Try putting
your feet up on a bench or chair to maintain proper posture.
</P>
<P>
   Now, crunch or squeeze your torso up to a half sit-up position,
then back down. Leave your knees and legs in the air. Do not pull
your torso all the way up, as if doing a traditional sit-up. This
tends to overwork your lower back and take the demand off your
abdominal muscles.
</P>
<P>
   To augment weightlifting and exercises, trainers recommend some
type of a cardiovascular workout four times a week. Each workout,
designed to raise the heart rate but not over-stress your system,
should last somewhere between 10 and 30 minutes, depending on the
person's level of fitness. The workouts can include power walking,
cycling, jogging or aerobics.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing Marlin and Clark suggest to help get a thin,
washboard stomach is to watch what you eat.
</P>
<P>
   Dieticians warn against high-sugar, high carbohydrate diets,
which can add fat to a physique. They suggest staying away from
things like soft drinks, fruit juices, bread and white rice.
Alternatives include oatmeal, brown rice, baked potatoes and sweet
potatoes, and green vegetables. Marlin also suggests steering away
from dairy products. If you can't stay away from milk, at least
switch to skim, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have the greatest abs in the world, but if you don't
shrink the layer of fat between the skin and the abs, you won't
ever see them,'' Marlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
