<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wood can be expensive and here's why
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A reader e-mailed a request recently searching for
places that sell hardwood outside of, rather than in, Atlanta, on
the premise that prices would be cheaper in the country.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help him, since I wouldn't drive the 50 to 75 miles
from the town he specified to buy wood unless I couldn't find it
closer. Also, I doubt that there's going to be any significant
difference in the price _ retailers in Hahira probably get their
wood from the same mills as retailers in Atlanta. The price of
wood, I've found, is pretty standard from store to store in a given
region.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a considerable amount of wood, and want the best
price for it, then the thing to do is buy it green. And if you live
in a rural area, or at least have a good bit of land on which to
construct drying facilities, you can do very well indeed.
</P>
<P>
   You might even want to get into the woodcutting business.
</P>
<P>
   Taking it from the top, most folks who decide they want to cut
their own wood buy a Wood-Mizer mill. Wood-Mizer
(www.woodmizer.com) makes a wide range of portable bandsaw mills
for turning logs into planks wherever the trees are felled. For the
most part, these remarkable mills will run a log through the blade
at a spacing you select, and do other fancy stuff. There is, of
course, the bare minimum of waste.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you want to think carefully before you invest in one of
these machines. Some folks have gotten caught up in the romance of
woodcutting and ignored the down side of the business, such as it's
a lot of hard and heavy work and you've got to do a lot of it to
make any money. If you just want some wood cut up once in a while,
you'd probably do better to hire someone who has a Wood-Mizer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the next two questions can be answered pretty much
together. First, where do you find a Wood-Mizer operator? And
second, where do you find green planks for sale?
</P>
<P>
   The best source I know of for both is the Georgia Agriculture
Department's Farmer's and Consumer's Market Bulletin. You can get a
free subscription to this wonderful little newspaper by calling the
Agriculture Department in Atlanta, or you can read it online at
www.agr.state.ga.us. There's always someone advertising hardwood
for sale, or raw logs or trees for sale, and often you'll find
Wood-Mizer operators offering their services.
</P>
<P>
   Now, assuming you have gotten this far, how do you dry your
green lumber?
</P>
<P>
   That depends on how fast you want it to get dry, and how much
expense and trouble you're willing to accept in the process. The
cheap, slow way is to sticker it in an open shed _ you just need
enough cover to keep the rain off _ for a year or two, depending on
the thickness of the planks, and when it has reached equilibrium
with the ambient moisture, bring it indoors in an unheated,
uncooled environment for another long stay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
