a lot of hard and heavy work and you've got to do a lot of it to
make any money. If you just want some wood cut up once in a while,
you'd probably do better to hire someone who has a Wood-Mizer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the next two questions can be answered pretty much
together. First, where do you find a Wood-Mizer operator? And
second, where do you find green planks for sale?
</P>
<P>
   The best source I know of for both is the Georgia Agriculture
Department's Farmer's and Consumer's Market Bulletin. You can get a
free subscription to this wonderful little newspaper by calling the
Agriculture Department in Atlanta, or you can read it online at
www.agr.state.ga.us. There's always someone advertising hardwood
for sale, or raw logs or trees for sale, and often you'll find
Wood-Mizer operators offering their services.
