r l BC-RELIGION-WEB15-COX     04-14 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-WEB15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photo exhibit captures ancient lessons of Bible, applies them to
modern times
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Ohio _ A chance Internet encounter has led a
Middletown congregation to become the first church in America to
host a beautiful and unusual international photo exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words of Yesterday, Photos of Today,'' a collection of
photographs inspired by ancient Biblical quotations, is on display
at the Breiel Boulevard First Church of God, an evangelical
Christian church associated with the Church of God in Anderson,
Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit juxtaposes ancient Hebrew texts with contemporary
scenes from the Holy Land that illuminate them _ often with
jarring, thought-provoking results. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ A field of colorful flowers blooming in the Negev desert is
matched with this text from Isaiah: ``The wilderness and the
solitary place shall be glad for them; and the desert shall
rejoice, and blossom as the rose.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A taxi driver arguing about a ticket he's being given by a cop
is described by these verses from Job: ``Should he argue with
useless talk, Or with words which are not profitable?''
</P>
<P>
   _ A flashy rock singer in concert in Israel is matched with this
text from Psalms: ``Sing unto him a new song, play skillfully with
a loud blast.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A photo of Israel taken by astronauts from the U.S. Space
Shuttle has this accompanying text from Genesis: ``And God called
the dry land Earth; and the gathering together of the waters He
called Seas; and God saw that it was good.''
</P>
<P>
   David Hogan, the church member responsible for bringing the
exhibit to town, says he can't help but believe ``there's something
bigger up there that's guiding all this.''
</P>
<P>
   It all started when Hogan and the other members of his committee
began working on their annual Easter musical multimedia
presentation. ``Jerusalem 2000 ... The Answer'' had been chosen as
this year's title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our thought was that we wanted to show how the things that
happened in Jesus' time are still the answers to today's
problems,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan got the task of coming up with the graphics for the
invitation _ an image that would that would illustrate both ancient
and contemporary Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Another committee member doing research on the Internet
discovered a photo of Jerusalem that seemed perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was photograph of new and old Jerusalem from the book,
`Testament of Israel','' says Hogan. He contacted the publisher and
requested permission to use the image for his church.
</P>
<P>
   The woman he contacted was Linda Majors, who represents the
publisher in America and wanted to know more about the
congregation's upcoming event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been my dream to start taking the exhibit to
churches,'' says Majors. ``It has had wonderful response in Jewish
communities, and it's going to be in three major cathedrals in
England this summer, but we hadn't yet scheduled it in an American
church.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the quotations are taken from the Old Testament, she
says, the book and exhibit are for Jews, Christians, Muslims,
``everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Majors says Hogan was so charming that she ended up suggesting
his church might want to host the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea, she says, came from John Wagner, former
president of Victor Hasselblad Inc., the Swedish camera company .
</P>
<P>
   ``His love of the Bible, Israel and photography came together to
create the book,'' Majors says. ``He worked with Professor Markham
Geller at the University College in London and together they picked
the quotations they loved. Then they went through 7,000 photographs
to find the perfect match for each one.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is made up of 30 of the book's images and represents
top Israeli and internationally known photographers. Majors says it
has proven particularly effective in motivating young people to
study the Bible: In some cities, youngsters have been asked to
enter a photo competition, digging up photos of their own and
matching them with appropriate biblical quotes.
</P>
<P>
   In Middletown, in addition to being on display before each of
the church's Easter performances, a community open house for the
exhibit will be held from 2-6 p.m. Sunday. The coffee-table art
book, priced at $60, will be available for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to extend an open hand to our brothers and
sisters of other backgrounds,'' Hogan says. ``It's exciting to see
pictures of things mentioned in the Bible that we don't often see,
like the Sea of Galilee, the Dome of the Rock, the streets of
Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his favorite photos, he adds, demonstrate that
friendships and personal connections can develop between people who
may be at odds in a larger sense. One example is a photo of a
Jordanian and Israeli soldier playing musical instruments together
accompanied by the text from Psalms: ``Behold, how good and how
pleasant it is for brethren to dwell together in unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan says the photos perfectly illustrate the concept his
church was trying to capture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea is to show how Hebrew scriptures written
centuries ago still fit today.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
