<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6630 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-DINOSAURS15-COX     04-14 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAURS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dinosaur program gives high-tech glimpse of prehistoric beasts
 &HT;    By Ron Rollins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ If nothing else, you have to give the folks who
made ``Walking With Dinosaurs'' credit for speaking with authority.
</P>
<P>
   The first line in the show, intoned by deep-voiced Avery Brooks,
goes: ``An asteroid plunged to Earth 65 million years ago. It ended
one of the most astonishing chapters in the history of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Boom! Nothing ambiguous about that. None of that
gosh-what-killed-the-dinosaurs head-scratching you get down at the
natural history museum. The producers of this rich, astonishing
program do indeed speak with authority _ an assurance of fact and
interpretation that becomes immediately, breathtakingly apparent in
just the first few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   We see dinosaurs _ what appear to be real, living, on-camera
dinosaurs _ going about the business of hunting, feeding, mating,
flying, swimming, nesting, hatching and fighting as though the
producers actually snuck up on the critters just as we're used to
seeing done in the educational nature shows we've grown up with.
</P>
<P>
   As any modern, movie-savvy kid knows, however, these
Brachiosaurs and Tyrannosaurus Rexes came out of a computer. The
quality-conscious producers of the three-hour show _ the Discovery
Channel, along with the BBC _ are well aware that their audience is
already used to seeing fossils spring to life on-screen, a la
``Jurassic Park,'' but wisely choose to let the story tell itself
without artificial jazzing up. ``Walking With Dinosaurs'' succeeds
because it never loses sight of the fact that it is trying to teach
more than entertain and recognizes that there is already spectacle
aplenty built into the subject.
</P>
<P>
   And they play that spectacle for all it's worth, making us
believe we're seeing it really happen. The team of consulting
paleontologists, sculptors, computer animators and digital guys
fashioned the prehistoric action in story cycles that focus on the
lives of animals who epitomize their period and all the change
going on around them.
</P>
<P>
   We go first to Arizona in 220 million B.C., in the area that
will be known much later as the Petrified Forest. It's the early
Triassic, and we meet four creatures and learn the ways of their
fascinating interactions.
</P>
<P>
   There are herds of slow-moving Placerias, distant ancestors of
the dinosaurs who look like hippos and are set upon by a 2-ton
early carnivore known as the Postosuchus. It, too, is lumbering and
sluggish _ able to prey easily on the Placerias, but unable to keep
up with a new kid on the block: The nimble, razor-toothed
Coelophysis, a streamlined hunter who is one of the first true
dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of the fast, relentless dinosaurs spells the
eventual end of the dull-witted reptiles who came before. But even
as we see the dinosaurs on the way up, we meet the doglike, hairy
Cynodonts _ half-reptile, half-mammal, the warm-blooded animals who
would eventually evolve into modern mammals.
</P>
<P>
   We watch as they pursue and feed upon each other, setting the
stage for what follows a few million years later _ the Age of
Dinosaurs in all its animatronic glory. Allosaurus does battle with
Stegosaurus; Diplodocus hatches from buried eggs and grows 2 tons a
year; Ornithocheirus and Rhamphorhynchus take to the air;
Tyrannosaurus does what we all know he does.
</P>
<P>
   But knowing a lot of this stuff already doesn't keep one from
enjoying seeing it all replayed in brilliant, living detail. Puffs
of steam billow from nostrils. Flesh sways with every heavy step.
Tails twitch, eggs glisten, eyes blink. A few of the animal sounds
_ yes, they all make noise _ sound a tad computerized, and at times
the John Williams-style score seems a bit too Hollywood for the
Discovery Channel. But the show is a winner, and you'll be
surprised at what you learn even if you thought you knew the
subject well.
</P>
<P>
   Parents will enjoy seeing how today's notions of dinosaurs vary
wildly from what we were taught years ago, when we were told these
thick-footed, plodding monsters needed to prop themselves on their
tails. Kids will enjoy finally getting an answer to the question
every one of them has asked at one time or another: What would it
be like to be able to go back and see the dinosaurs?
</P>
<P>
   Now they know.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
