<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, April 15
and Sunday, April 16, 2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   PSYCHOLOGY-TODAY _ Caregiver stress comes in many forms.
(LeCrone, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ABS-FITNESS _ WACO, Texas _ Summer is still two months away, but
the season of abdominal obsessions is in full swing at fitness
centers. (O'Brien, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SKIN-STRESS _ Fighting the good fight, when your skin is your
enemy. (Susman, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ ATLANTA _ The price of wood, I've found, is
pretty standard from store to store in a given region. (Warner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ESSAYIST-PROFILE _ YOUNG HARRIS, Ga. _ For 20 years, Steve
Harvey, a professor at Young Harris College in North Georgia, wrote
poems before finding his real voice in the personal essay. In two
collections, ``A Geometry of Lilies: Life and Death in an American
Family'' and ``Lost in Translation,'' he writes with fluent ease
about love and marriage, about change and loss. His tone is by
turns winsome and reflective. ``People ask me what my books are
about,'' he says. ``It's very hard to say.'' He will write of his
kids ganging up on him (``I marvel at the transparent guile of
their planning huddles, the determined looks as they gather courage
for the synchronized assault, their reckless confidence as they
throw their bodies at their father.'') or of discovering he is
perfectly happy living without a television (``Our mind connects
the dots, lending depth and perspective, and ultimately, meaning to
the electronic trompe l'oeil of the tube. And yet, the experience
sedates us, engaging just enough of our senses to lull us into a
stupor.''). He writes what's on his mind, but what's on his mind
always seems to lead somewhere else _ from the personal to what
might be called the universal. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 57. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, APRIL 16.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   CHARLES-OSGOOD _ NEW YORK _ A conversation with Charles Osgood,
host of the critically acclaimed CBS program ``Sunday Morning,''
which continues to have an almost liturgical appeal. One reason may
be because it has never varied from its initial conception: to be
like a Sunday newspaper. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
40. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   OSGOOD-BIO _ Bio box that goes with Charles Osgood story.
(Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 6. EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   HIP-HOP _ True to hip-hop's origins in battles between competing
artists, there is not one group but two attempting to honor the
music with a hall of fame. (SoMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   BEOWULF _ A hero for our time. Beowulf. IF you thought reading
the oldest poem in the English language was a bore, think again.
(Browning, Palm Beach Post). 60.
</P>
<P>
   JULIE-GOLD _ When you've written one of the most enduring pop
songs of the past couple of decades, what can you possibly do for a
follow-up? For Julie Gold, the composer and lyricist of ``From a
Distance,'' there's only one answer: You start singing it yourself.
(Passy, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   DINOSAURS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Walking With Dinosaurs'' succeeds
because it never loses sight of the fact that it is trying to teach
more than entertain and recognizes that there is already spectacle
aplenty built into the subject. (Rollins, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   PASSOVER _ According to the Bible, God wrote the 10 commandments
_ a listing of moral and ethical laws _ in stone and in Hebrew.
Now, as Passover arrives, the descendants of Moses and human rights
groups are using many languages, and modern tools like the
Internet, in an effort to induce people to keep the commandments
and other moral codes. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
40.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-LINCOLN _ Abraham Lincoln's love for the theater was
but one of his departures from his strict Calvinist parents,
according to Allen C. Guelzo, author of a new book looking at
Lincoln from a religious perspective, ``Abraham Lincoln, Redeemer
President.'' Lincoln died 135 years ago today and we take the
opportunity to take a look at a different side of this remarkable
president. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN-SERMONS _ With his assassination on Good Friday of 1865,
Abraham Lincoln took on mythic proportions, even to some people who
opposed him during his lifetime. Sermons, some now part of an
exhibit at Emory, preached immediately after his death reflected
this. We offer some excerpts. (White, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-MLK _ A handsome black granite monument dedicated last
week honors Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and makes West Palm Beach a
far better place. But the monument's inscription omits, arguably
the two most important words in King's life: The Reverend.
Unfortunately, that badly serves the man and the source of his
greatness. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is Gushee's weekly religion column.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSBOYS-ARENA _ The Christian pop-rock group the Newsboys
always have a musical or theatrical hook to grab audiences on their
CDs or their live performances. This time it is an inflatable arena
that they've taken on the road with them. It fits 3,500 people, and
it's the first time it's been tried in this country. (Dayton daily
News). 20. MOVED WEDNESDAY
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-WEB _ A chance Internet encounter has led a Middletown
congregation to become the first church in America to host a
beautiful and unusual international photo exhibition. ``Words of
Yesterday, Photos of Today'' a collection of photographs inspired
by ancient Biblical quotations, is on display at the Breiel
Boulevard First Church of God, an evangelical Christian church
associated with the Church of God in Anderson, Ind. The exhibit
juxtaposes ancient Hebrew texts with contemporary scenes from the
Holy Land that illuminate them _ often with jarring,
thought-provoking results. (Moss, Dayton Daily News). 25. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
