<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-HOLLYWOOD (Los Angeles) _ Bill Clinton has long been
treated like a star by Hollywood's movers and shakers, who have
opened their gilded pocketbooks and glamorous homes to the
charismatic president. Now that Clinton's understudy, Al Gore, is
angling to move up to leading man, some of Tinseltown's biggest
names appear ready to shower the same affection on the presumptive
Democratic presidential nominee. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-28DAYS-REVIEW _ A script by Susanna Grant (''Erin
Brockovich``) leads a boozer (Sandra Bullock) through the paces of
a drug-abuse camp, in the comedy-drama ``28 Days.'' Betty Thomas
(''Doctor Dolittle,`` ''Private Parts``) directed this film, which
is rated PG-13 for mature thematic elements involving substance
abuse, language and some sexuality. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FAITH-REVIEW (Undated) _ Two New York buddies _ one a hip
priest (Edward Norton), the other a hip rabbi (Ben Stiller) _ get
together with a childhood pal (Jenna Elfman) who has grown into a
smart, beautiful, sexy and single career woman. Both men find their
respective faiths challenged in ``Keeping the Faith,'' a thoughtful
romantic comedy directed by Norton. The film is rated PG-13 for
some sexuality and language. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PSYCHO-REVIEW (Undated) _ The screen version of the book
about 1980s yuppie serial killer Patrick Bateman (Christian Bale)
becomes a satirical look at Reagan-era greed and disassociation
from reality. Directed by Mary Harron (''I Shot Andy Warhol''),
``American Psycho'' is rated R for strong violence, sexuality, drug
use and language. It also includes a disturbing theme and images.
By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-GOULD (Undated) _ ``JOE GOULD'S SECRET'' asks
questions that may not have an answer, and it asks them more than
once. What's the difference be tween a starving artist and a
deadbeat? At what point does ``eccentric'' become ``grotesque''?
How much do artists owe to the guilt of the rich? Are we all
basically forgettable? By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CHONG (Undated) _ When Annabel Chong sits in front
of Gough Lewis' camera and complains about her need to have one of
those normal everyday lives, you want to tell her that having
intercourse on camera with more than 200 men is probably not the
way to get to normal. By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-BILL-RUSSELL (Undated) _ The Genesis of HBO's documentary
``Bill Russell: My Life, My Way'' occurred one day when Russell was
visiting with his grandchildren. They posed the question: ``Were
you better than Michael Jordan?'' Airs Monday night. By
</P>
<P>
   TV-RULES (Undated) _ Looking on with envy at the success of the
ABC mega-hit, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' the other networks
jumped to the obvious conclusion: We need our own game show. They
were wrong, and the shows stunk. The real door that ``Millionaire''
kicked in is that networks have to throw out the rigid rules that
have applied to broadcasting since the days of radio. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-REVIEW (Undated) _ A review of films ``The Insider,''
``Three Kings'' ``Superstar,'' ``Three to Tango'' and ``Happy,
Texas,'' which are being released on videotape. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTLYE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMPUTEE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Dean L. Johnson remembers the instant
he was struck by a tractor-trailer on the New York Thruway while
trying to aid a stranded motorist during Sunday's snowstorm. The
23-year-old soldier's Army instincts took over when both legs were
severed below the knee. By CAROL DeMARE.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENT-LIFE (Germantown, N.Y.) _ Lunch is ready for some 30
Carmelite Sisters For the Aged and Infirm, gathered in the
cavernous white dining hall attached to their Motherhouse. The nuns
show two sides _ the contemplative and the active _ that have been
their watchwords since Saint Albert wrote their guiding rule in
about the year 1206. By MICHAEL LOPEZ. (For release Sunday, April
16.)
</P>
<P>
   PLATFORM-SHOES (Albany, N.Y.) _ From the malls to the office to
the dance floors on Friday and Saturday nights, many women are
making the `70s-era platform shoes their shoe of choice. By KRISTI
L. GUSTAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARCHAEOLOGY-CELEBRATION (Washington) _ An archaeological
organization is marking its 100th anniversary at a time of growing
interest in civilizations and artifacts of the past. But the head
of the American Schools of Oriental Research, meeting this weekend
in Washington, says it is still difficult to get sponsors for
archaeological explorations. By BILL CRAIG.
</P>
<P>
   SEQUOIAMONUMENT (Undated)+_ President Clinton's plan to create a
355,000-acre Sequoia National Monument is disrupting the peaceful
forest life of the western Sierra Nevada. The president's
proclamation, expected Saturday, may not go far enough to preserve
the largest stands of unprotected giant Sequoias left in the world,
environmentalists warn. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-MONEY (Albany, N.Y.) _ The new one-dollar coins are turning
up in some boxes of breakfast cereal. Presidents Abraham Lincoln
and Alexander Hamilton are younger looking on the new $5 and $10
bills coming into circulation May 24. Says U.S. Treasurer Mary
Ellen Withrow, ``We have been changing more things in your money
than has ever been done before at any one time in history.'' By
JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Houston) _ L.M. SIXEL's working column will not
appear this week.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOFT-SHELL-CRABS (Undated) _ Soft-shell crabs are a delicacy
that arrive with the first full moon of spring. They can be fried
and eaten as a sandwich, or sauteed and served with capers. By RUTH
FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-BASTERS (Undated) _ Basters, those clever little manual
cooking accessories, not only help to make a roasting bird golden
brown, but can be used for a few other conveniences around the
house as well. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS. (For release Sunday,
April 16.)
</P>
<P>
   PASTA (Undated) _ Welcome to presto pasta. We called our latest
taste test the three-minute showdown. From the shopping bag to the
table in five minutes, tops. Prepared at home, too. Granted, we're
not talking gourmet dining. More like school cafeteria eats. But
our goal was not four-star (or three, or two) cuisine. It was
convenience and comparison. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ On Tuesday, Bessie Shum will be
the first Chinese American earthquake survivor to attend the annual
gathering of survivors at Lotta's Fountain on Market Street. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ As far back as February 1998,
executives at the mighty Seattle-based Starbucks Coffee Company
said they were ``exploring the possibility'' of offering customers
coffee beans that meet international fair trade standards for
non-exploitive labor. This week, exploration ended. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
