<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developing: The U.S. government responds to
relatives' request for an injunction to delay transferring custody
of Elian to his father. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story, by Edward Wong and undatelined,
will move by 2:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-CASTRO (Miami) _ For five months Elian has been
surrounded by anti-Castro rhetoric at school, at home and within
his Miami community. In Cuba, he will soon be exposed to
anti-American rhetoric. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   NADER-POLITICS (Minneapolis) _ The consumer advocate Ralph Nader
is mounting another radical campaign for the presidency. By James
Dao.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIAN-SAMOVAR (New York) _ Much of New York's Russian-American
population has funneled in and out of the Russian Samovar
restaurant for more than a decade. The restaurant has become much
more than a place to eat: The Samovar is an unwieldy and thoroughly
singular social club. By Kathleen O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ANTIQUARIANS (Undated) _ Ordinarily the antiquarian trade
is the dusty, genteel corner of the book market that attracts
fiercely independent booksellers. But now the dust motes are flying
with the emergence of Alibris, a virtual used bookseller with Wall
Street ambitions and Silicon Valley money. The hostilities that
Alibris has provoked among some traditional booksellers mirrors the
tensions that other industries are facing over issues of
consolidation and the loss of personal connections. By Doreen
Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-DEBT (Sao Paulo) _ The long-running financial scandal
surrounding the mayor of Sao Paulo has left the city mired in
billions of dollars in debt and at risk of insolvency. By Simon
Romero.
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-LOSSES (Mountain View, Calif.) _ The view from inside an
Internet company, HearMe, that has lost 40 percent of its value in
the last week (and 75 percent since the day it went public a year
ago) amid the general Nasdaq upheaval. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (London) _ BMW says it has received a second bid for
its Rover unit from a consortium led by a former chief executive of
Rover. The new bid may complicate BMW's negotiations to transfer
Rover Cars to Alchemy Partners, a London-based venture capital
group. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   BARZUN-CULTURAL-HISTORY (Undated) _ Jacques Barzun, one of the
founders of ``cultural history,'' taught history at Columbia for
nearly 50 years and led legendary seminars with Lionel Trilling. He
has written over 30 books, translated nearly a dozen more, and now,
at 92, has finished an epic chronicle of his historical forays, a
survey of 500 years of Western cultural life. By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   BACH-FUGUES (Undated) _ The fugue is a drama not about the
individual voice at large in a society of sound, but a drama about
a society of sound created by related individual voices. It is an
astonishing structure, constructed with intense concentration. Bach
was so renowned for his fugues that after King Frederick II of
Prussia challenged him to improvise a fugue based upon a
mischievously slithering theme, Bach countered with a masterpiece
of inventive play, ``The Musical Offering.'' By Edward Rothstein.
</P>
