<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CHICKEN-NUGGETS-$ADV1     04-14 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-NUGGETS-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALABAMA PLANTS OVERWHELMED WITH SICK CHICKENS, REPORT FINDS
 &HT;    790&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, April 16.
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Gold Kist Inc. poultry processing plants in
Alabama that supply chicken to school lunch programs nationwide
were overwhelmed earlier this year by diseased poultry, federal
investigators have reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many birds condemned that they were filling up
the 'USDA condemned' barrel and spilling onto the floor,'' the
report, obtained by Cox Newspapers, says of conditions at Gold
Kist's Boaz plant.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the chickens arriving on Feb. 9 were
infected with a respiratory disease called airsacculitis that
leaves pus inside the carcass, one federal worker told an
investigator for the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Office of
Inspector General (OIG).
</P>
<P>
   At a plant in Guntersville that is using an experimental food
inspection system, the report found that Gold Kist failed to
identify substantial numbers of diseased carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the experimental program, company workers instead of
federal inspectors are supposed to find and remove substandard
poultry. But the report cited government records showing that on
Feb. 7, 28 percent of birds selected in government spot checks
after being approved by the company were diseased, typically with
airsacculitis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite conditions inside the plants, the inspector general's
office said it was dropping the matter because ``there is no
allegation of any deliberate violation of law or direct threat to
public health.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bekkers, Gold Kist president and chief operating officer,
said in a statement posted on its Web site: ``As we have assured
our customers all along, Gold Kist Farms brand chicken products are
safe, wholesome and good to eat. We appreciate that this was
recognized in the OIG report.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Atlanta-based company refused to be
interviewed, offering instead to reply to written questions. Cox
Newspapers declined that offer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson at the inspector general's office in Washington
declined to discuss the March 3 report.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's office launched its investigation in
early February after Cox Newspapers detailed allegations by several
federal food safety inspectors at the Guntersville and Boaz plants.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to determining whether the inspectors' allegations
were true, the report says that Agriculture Department officials
asked the OIG to determine if ``internal agency documents (were
given) to the press.'' The report says it found ``no basis for
further investigation'' of leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors said that because of widespread disease in Gold
Kist chicken flocks, both processing plants were being inundated
with diseased poultry.
</P>
<P>
   While such birds are normally condemned, the inspectors said
that under the experimental food inspection system at the
Guntersville facility, some diseased poultry was being used to make
chicken nuggets for school lunch programs.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken nuggets are not considered a threat to human health
because the poultry diseases cannot be transmitted to human beings.
However, inspectors said they considered carcasses with scabs,
sores and pus to be ``unwholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the inspectors' allegations were published,
Bekkers issued a press release defending the quality of his product
and charging that ``the public is being misled by a few
union-activist USDA poultry inspectors.'' He said that there was
``no factual support for their claims.''
</P>
<P>
   But a week after Bekkers' statement was issued, a Gold Kist
official acknowledged to an OIG investigator that ``airsacculitis
... had been moving through the flocks and infecting chickens.''
The name of the executive was deleted in the copy of the report
obtained by Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Billy, head of the Agriculture Department's Food Safety and
Inspection Service, released a statement Feb. 11 saying the
government had ``excellent controls'' at the plant and that food
from the plant can be ``eaten with confidence.'' He also said, ``We
have no reason to believe products leaving these Gold Kist Plants
is anything other than safe and wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the OIG's report quoted federal inspectors who were
complaining that ``they are not allowed to remove birds at any
point.'' The report lists the results of inspections made at
Guntersville on Feb. 5, 7 and 8. A sampling of chickens made by
federal inspectors _ after Gold Kist workers had supposedly culled
out diseased carcasses _ found that between 11 and 28 percent of
the birds were diseased. Federal rules permit a maximum of 3
percent of a sample to contain diseased birds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Agriculture Department's press office did not
respond to repeated requests for an interview with Billy.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The OIG's report raises questions about what exactly the
government means when it says food products are wholesome.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law forbids the sale of poultry for human consumption if
it is ``adulterated or misbranded'' at the time of sale. If it is
``unsound, unhealthful, unwholesome, or otherwise unfit for human
food,'' it is considered ``adulterated.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the report said that the ``inquiry did not disclose any
adulteration of product.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department officials have declined repeated requests
over several weeks to provide an explanation of the meaning of the
term ``wholesome'' in the law.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Smith DeWaal, food safety director at the
Washington-based Center for Science in the Public Interest, said
wholesome ``is meant to describe conditions that would not only
make the food unhealthy or unsafe, but also would be unappealing.
It is not food a consumer would knowingly want to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The OIG report said that an inspector at the Boaz plant told
investigators about the chicken leaving the plant, ``as far as (he
or she) knows it is not unsafe, but (he or she) would not it it
personally. (He or she) thinks the public should know that sores
and scabs are going into it.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.goldkist.com/agknews041200oig.html
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Jaspin's e-mail address is elliotj(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
