a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     04-14 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S AN EXCITING TIME TO BE DULL  

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   April may or may not be the cruelest month, but it is without a
doubt the dullest.
</P>
<P>
   April 4-10 was National Reading a Road Map Week, ``dedicated to
promoting map-reading as an enjoyable pastime for drivers and
armchair travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not to be confused with National Folding Road Maps Week
(April 11-17), the motto of which is ``Happiness is knowing how to
fold a road map.''
</P>
<P>
   April 4 was Check Your Batteries Day, April 5-11 was Egg Salad
Week and April 19-25 is National Organize Your Files Week.
</P>
<P>
   If, after this, you have any energy left over (and I can't
imagine you would), you can celebrate the anniversary of the
invention of Teflon (April 6, 1938), the anniversary of the opening
of the first McDonald's (April 15, 1955) and, of course, the
anniversary of the metric system (April 7, 1795).
</P>
<P>
   This information is brought to you courtesy of my favorite
organization, the National Council of Dull Men, located,
appropriately enough, in Washington, D.C. (For those of us who find
writing a letter too stimulating, the group can be contacted on the
Web at http://dullmen.com/.)
</P>
<P>
   Like all worthwhile things in life, achieving a state of total,
irredeemable dullness requires a bit of effort. Men who are truly
committed to dullness travel all over the world, not to see the
sights or sample the cultures but to see if the airport
baggage-claim carousels turn in a clockwise or counterclockwise
direction. (They go clockwise at Washington's Dulles Airport, by
the way.)
</P>
<P>
   But just because we're dull, doesn't mean we don't like to
``party down.'' On New Year's Eve, for example, we spent the last
hours of 1999 practicing writing checks dated 2000 so we were able
to ``hit the ground running'' and make fewer mistakes when we wrote
out real checks with the new date.
</P>
<P>
   Many dull men are also rugged outdoorsmen, their favorite
activity being tractor-spotting. (Train-spotting is far too
reckless.)
</P>
<P>
   Dull men with a scientific bent tune in the Weather Channel at 6
a.m., watch for about an hour, then call around the country to find
out if the predicted weather is really happening.
</P>
<P>
   Of course dull men wouldn't be dull men if we didn't spend a lot
of time on the computer. One of our favorite Web sites is Cambridge
Coffee Pot - Live Cam Page, where you can watch coffee being brewed
and, if you're really lucky, watch it drip.
</P>
<P>
   Other favorite sites include Ice Fishing, the Journal of Mundane
Behavior, the National Association of Wheat Growers and, of course,
Spam.
</P>
<P>
   Although we may not look it, we dull men have active minds and
love to read. One of our favorite books is ``How to Rake Leaves''
by Leonard Koren and Suehiro Maruo. I am sad to report that this
book is currently out of print, despite finishing 1,828,062nd in
Amazon.com's sales ranking. It did, however, receive a 5-star
recommendation from reviewer Herb Stantwittle who called it an
``excellent reference work ... contains insight into bagging,
too!''
</P>
<P>
   Dull guys read dull books in order to collect dull tidbits of
information that they can share at parties that are insufficiently
dull. You probably did not know, for example, that nutmeg is
extremely poisonous if injected intravenously or that Heinz ketchup
leaves the bottle at a rate of 25 miles per year.
</P>
<P>
   If your dullness quotient were higher, you would probably know
that an ostrich's eye is bigger than its brain and that there is an
average of 178 sesame seeds on a Big Mac bun.
</P>
<P>
   Dull guys follow politics closely and are especially excited by
how dull this year's presidential race is shaping up to be. Dull
guys, as a group, feel sorry for President Clinton because he
wouldn't have had all that trouble with ``that woman'' if he had
been a duller guy.
</P>
<P>
   (Instead of cavorting about the Oval Office, a duller president
might have invited Monica to lunch with Janet Reno or helped her
write an essay on ``Her Proudest Achievement as a White House
Intern.'')
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, we dull guys are making ourselves heard, even if nobody
cares to listen.
</P>
<P>
   It's an exciting time to be dull, which is why I can't wait
until June, which is National Rest Areas Month. In the meantime,
I'll have to amuse myself the best I can, perhaps by watching some
paint dry.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
