<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COL     04-14 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Southern Exposure is the weekly political notebook from the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspapers) &HT;    
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN  
SOUTHERN LAWMAKERS FACE CONFLICTING INTERESTS ON CHINA TRADE DEAL 
 
NYT Regional Newspapers  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington Bureau
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Despite the absence of a sizable union presence in
the region, some Southern lawmakers find themselves sympathetic to
labor's opposition to granting China permanent favorable trading
status.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Republicans and Democrats object to China's poor
record of human rights abuses and its restrictions on religious
expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year I look for any signs that China will stop these acts
against humanity,'' said Rep. Robert Aderholt, R-Ala., who has
voted against previous bills that have granted enhanced trading
status for China. He is still mulling this latest measure. Many
Republican leaders, along with President Clinton, argue that an
increased American presence in China through trade will expedite
reform there as well as open sales opportunities for American
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other lawmakers say that previous trade agreements, such
as NAFTA, have cost Southern workers jobs, particularly in the
textile and apparel industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Southeastern North Carolina, free trade has been anything
but free,'' said Rep. Mike McIntyre, D-N.C. He said thousands of
textile jobs have been lost in his district since the NAFTA trade
deal was enacted with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been very costly to many families,'' McIntyre said,
adding that a trade deal with China could bring much more of the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Cramer, D-Ala., has supported an enhanced trade status
with China on an annual basis, but remains undecided about any
permanent status because that ``brings up entirely different issues
that we need to think through and discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE MARKET
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to win support for strengthening U.S. trade ties
with China and admitting China into the World Trade Organization,
the Clinton administration has compiled a report detailing how such
a development would benefit each state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do not grant China (permanent trade status) then our
competitors in Asia, Europe and Latin America will reap the very
benefits we negotiated,'' Commerce Secretary William Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   The possible benefits? Alabama, Florida and North Carolina,
where chemical products make up the bulk of exports to China, would
face low tariffs for such products, including insecticides.
Louisiana, where agricultural products make up 52 percent of its
exports to China, would no longer have to compete against export
subsidies on China's own farm products.
</P>
<P>
   And South Carolina, where industrial machinery and computers
comprise the single greatest share of exports to China, would face
an elimination of duties on most of those products.
</P>
<P>
   SPLIT PERSONALITY
</P>
<P>
   As the House quickly passed a measure that would funnel money to
states that crack down on criminals who possess guns, the White
House took a unique view.
</P>
<P>
   First spokesman Joe Lockhart assailed Republicans for engaging
in a ``cruel political trick'' by pursuing legislation that would
make law-enforcement money available to only a handful of states
while bottling up White House-backed gun controls. Florida, South
Carolina and Louisiana are among states that could get the money
due to their sentencing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Then Lockhart took credit for the approach, known as Project
Exile, calling it an administration idea first launched in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Project Exile started down in Richmond with our U.S.
attorney,'' bragged Lockhart. ``It has been replicated in other
cities around the country. These are programs that we support.''
</P>
<P>
   RAGIN' CAJUN
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., looks like the winner in what has been
a spirited battle to claim the helm of the influential House
Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert recently endorsed Tauzin's claim
that he enjoys the most seniority on that committee, in spite of
the fact that most of Tauzin's time there was as a Democrat before
he switched parties in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert's show of support for Tauzin comes at the expense of
Republican Michael Oxley of Ohio, who is also lobbying for the
slot. Tauzin has also won friends in the GOP by hosting
fund-raisers for his colleagues and the GOP over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy's confident that he's done everything necessary to
ensure that he'll be the next Commerce Committee chairman,''
spokesman Ken Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, one small hurdle. Republicans most stave
off what's expected to be a strong effort by Democrats this fall to
reclaim their majority in the House, an outcome that would render
Tauzin's own plans moot. Unless he switches parties again.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
