<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 12:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6703 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w BC-ARCHAEOLOGY-CELEBRATI     04-14 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHAEOLOGY-CELEBRATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ARCHAEOLOGIST PREDICTS NEW SURPRISES FROM THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By BILL CRAIG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Are there any more buried cities and treasure-laden
ancient tombs still waiting to be uncovered for science and the
popular imagination? A prominent archaeologist thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you settle on the fact that there can't be anything
bigger, something shows up,'' said Joe Seger, who teaches at
Mississippi State University and is president of the American
Schools of Oriental Research (ASOR). He will be in Washington this
weekend, joining other archaeologists and those interested in the
ancient Middle East, to celebrate the Boston-based ASOR's 100th
birthday and the sensational archaeological discoveries made in
that part of the world in the past century.
</P>
<P>
   Activities include a seminar Saturday at the Smithsonian
Institution cosponsored by The Smithsonian Associates. A series of
television programs on the Public Broadcasting System this spring
features famous excavations in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Capacity audiences at lectures, the appearance of new popular
magazines, and frequent television programs on archaeological
subjects are evidence of the high public interest, Seger said.
College-level classes on archaeology fill up in a hurry, and
graduate students who pay their own way or have scholarships are a
valuable source of labor on archaeological digs that typically cost
$150,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   But historically, funding has been a perennial problem for
archaeologists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporate America is not very interested,'' Seger said, noting
that arts and historical foundations and some government sources
help scholars to ``cobble together'' support.
</P>
<P>
   Another ongoing and seemingly unsolvable problem for
archaeologists worldwide has been looting of sites, especially in
areas where nearby residents are poor and are tempted by the
lucrative international art market. To complicate the situation for
archaeologists, some collectors also finance excavations. Seger
said the disappearance of items from museums in Iraq, the site of
ancient Mesopotamia, as a result of the Persian Gulf War has been a
tragedy for science.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these and other problems, ``our enterprise is
flourishing,'' he said. New developments in computer technology
have brought dramatic changes to the field. On one recent
excavation, it was possible to be in contact with the dig team as
soon as discoveries were made. On a project at Petra, in Jordan,
excavators could reconstruct the image of a collapsed ancient
building as its toppled columns were uncovered, a job that used to
take months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen amazing things in terms of recording projects, as
well as gene and pollen analysis, and we're going to get more and
more of them,'' Seger said. ``We try to recover not just bones and
stones, but the character of materials and how people lived that
used them. I am an optimist. I think that, given the resources,
there are plenty of new frontiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Syria, for example, is an unknown region, he said, and there are
thousands of sites in Israel awaiting scientific examination.
</P>
<P>
   Three research centers are operated in association with ASOR, in
Israel, in Jordan and in Cyprus. The organization also supports
American archaeological research in Syria and Iraq and is working
on cooperative projects with the Palestine National Authority and
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   ASOR is involved with 30 sites now under excavation and 28
publication projects.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the centennial celebration it will sponsor a
symposium in Jerusalem May 26-31, and receptions in Nicosia,
Cyprus, on June 5 and in Amman, Jordan, on June 7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Craig can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address bcraig(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
