<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-SOFT-SHELL-CRABS-HNS &LR;      04-14 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFT-SHELL-CRABS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WITH SOFT-SHELL CRABS, THE SECRET'S IN THE MOON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a romantic story, orchestrated, say watermen, by the moon
and the tides.
</P>
<P>
   Soft-shell crabs are a delicacy that arrive with the first full
moon of spring. They are merely blue crabs that have shed, a
necessary process called molting that allows the crabs to grow.
Once a crab has filled its hard, outer shell, it splits at the back
seam (think Incredible Hulk) and struggles out of its old shell.
The new shell, already underneath, is soft and pliable and the crab
is left naked, without protection until the new, bigger shell
hardens, about 72 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency Web site explains that young
crabs, less than an inch across, molt every three to five days;
older crabs shed only once every 20 to 50 days, depending on water
temperature and available food. But any crabber who has been plying
the waters more than a couple of years will tell you more crabs
molt just before, during and after a full moon, than at any other
time during the lunar cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They use the moonlight to undress,'' jokes Rich Panella of The
Cousins Fish Market in Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   And while that may not be entirely true, there is a little game
of seduction going on.
</P>
<P>
   Male crabs continue to grow with each molting, according to the
EPA. But the females, once sexually mature, cease growing. Instead,
as the mature female crab approaches what is called the ``terminal
molt,'' she'll secrete a pheromone to attract a male. For three or
four days before and after her shedding, the male cradles her
beneath him to protect her from harm and shares his essence to
ensure crab lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Once mating has been achieved, the female crab rides the tides
offshore to saltier waters, more conducive to hatching.
</P>
<P>
   In order to prevent shells from hardening, watermen will place
crabs that show signs of molting in tanks of shallow, brackish
water. Once the crabs have shed, they are yanked from the tank
before their shell can begin to harden, usually within four hours.
Still alive, they are packed in wet sea grass and sold.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, soft shells are shipped from South Carolina.
As spring progresses, the harvest will move up the coast into the
Chesapeake Bay, where the full moon in May marks the height of soft
shell season.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you don't know where they come from, you have to really
love eating soft shells in order to cook them.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the price. This season, soft shells are selling
for as much as $4.75 per crab. Fortunately, most people only eat
two crabs per serving, and if you make a soft-shell sandwich,
you'll use only one.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the cleaning process, something you'd be wise to
ask the fishmonger to do if you plan on cooking and serving them
the same day. If you need to keep them longer, leave them whole,
covered with moist newspaper or wet grass and refrigerate for up to
three days.
</P>
<P>
   Soft shells are most often served battered and fried, or floured
and sauteed in butter and oil. Since both methods involve placing a
hydrated product in hot fat, two things are inevitable: smoke and
splatters. Open the windows and grab the aloe. When cooking soft
shells, odds are you'll set the smoke alarms off and burn yourself
at least once. But many people would jump in the fryer themselves
for the taste of hot, tender soft-shell crab.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SOFT SHELL CRAB SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared barbecue sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 soft shell crabs, (have fishmonger clean them)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   4 Kaiser rolls, split in half
</P>
<P>
   8 lettuce leaves, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   Slices of ripe tomato, optional
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine the mayonnaise with the barbecue sauce
and garlic and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a shallow bowl or on a plate, combine the flour with the salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Pat the crabs dry with paper towel. In a 12-inch skillet over
medium heat, heat the oil and butter. As the oil is heating up, dip
the crabs in flour, on both sides, and shake off any excess. Saute
the crabs, shell side down, over medium heat, for 3 to 4 minutes,
averting your face from the skillet as the crabs begin to cook
because they spatter like a volcano (after a few minutes the
sputtering settles down).
</P>
<P>
   With tongs, turn the crabs over and cook for another 3 to 4
minutes or until slightly red and firm. Spread both sides of the
roll with barbecue mayonnaise, set lettuce and tomato on one side
of the bread, top it with a crab and other half of the roll.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: Virginia Street Cafe, Urbanna, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEED SOFT SHELL CRABS WITH DIJON COGNAC SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 2)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup capers
</P>
<P>
   Oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Cognac
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 cleaned soft shell crabs
</P>
<P>
   Drain capers and pat dry with paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 1/2 inch of oil into a heavy frying pan. Heat oil until
hot. Add capers, cover and fry capers until crisp, 4 minutes.
Drain.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium saucepan, heat cream to a boil and reduce by half,
stirring frequently. Add Dijon mustard, mixing thoroughly. Remove
from heat, stir in Cognac. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat butter and 1/4 cup oil in a large frying pan.
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, salt and pepper in a large bowl. Dust soft shells
in flour mixture and shake gently to get rid of excess. Add to
oil/butter mixture, placing back-side down. Cook for 1 1/2 minutes.
Turn and cook for another 1 1/2 minutes. Remove from heat, drain on
paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Serve immediately with sauce and capers.
</P>
</TEXT>
