<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. CURRENCY GETTING YOUNGER, FUNKIER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The new one-dollar Sacagawea coins are turning up
in some boxes of breakfast cereal. And presidents Abraham Lincoln
and Alexander Hamilton are younger looking in the portraits on the
new $5 and $10 bills coming into circulation May 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been changing more things in your money than has ever
been done before at any one time in history,'' said Mary Ellen
Withrow. She should know: as U.S. Treasurer, Withrow's job is to
run the U.S. Mint and Bureau of Engraving and Printing.
</P>
<P>
   Withrow, who spoke earlier this week to about 235 credit union
managers in Albany, delighted the crowd with behind-the-scenes
money tales, including stories about the designs of the $100 and
$20 bills, and the changes in store for the $10 and $5 bills.
</P>
<P>
   She recounted the biography of Sacagawea, honored on the new
dollar coin released in January. Sacagawea acted as a guide to
explorers Lewis and Clark as they traversed new American wilderness
from 1804 to 1806. Withrow said she marveled at ``a 15-year-old
girl with a 2-month-old baby, taking off with a group of men, not
knowing where her next meal was coming from.''
</P>
<P>
   The government wanted to ensure the popularity of the coin, so
it made sure the brass-copper-manganese dollar works in vending
machines. Some coins were released through Wal-Mart stores to get
into broad circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Sacagawea is also showing up as a prize in some cereal boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One in every 2,000 Cheerios boxes have them,'' Withrow said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6706 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-RULES-HNS &LR;      04-14 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RULES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NETWORKS NEED TO BEND THE RULES TO SURVIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here should be the first, last and only rule posted on the desk
of every network executive:
</P>
<P>
   There Are No Rules.
</P>
<P>
   No question, ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' opened the door.
The problem is, the networks walked through the wrong one.
</P>
<P>
   Looking on with envy at the success of the ABC mega-hit, the
other networks jumped to the obvious conclusion: We need our own
game show. They were wrong, and the shows stunk.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of ratings, ``Falcone'' _ the CBS mob drama that ran
in eight installments over nine nights _ and last Sunday's live
production of ``Fail Safe'' on the same network, are closer to the
right idea.
</P>
<P>
   The real door ``Millionaire'' host Regis Philbin kicked in is
that networks have to throw out the rigid rules that have applied
to broadcasting since the days of radio. These edicts, written by
long-dead guys from the black-and-white era, should no longer apply
_ but do _ in the Technicolor, 500-channel universe:
</P>
<P>
   _ Series shows should run just once a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Miniseries are the only alternative.
</P>
<P>
   _ Summer is a wasteland of reruns and should be ceded to cable.
</P>
<P>
   _ The nightly formula of comedy/comedy/drama/drama can't be
juggled.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ultimate goal is trotting out shows that have the best
shot at a long run and syndication (god bless ``Wings'').
</P>
<P>
   _ Cable is an entirely different animal, with programming that
can't be replicated on the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Throw the rules out. Every one of them. Cable never had 'em, and
is now putting on much of the best _ and most talked about _
programs on television, featuring movie actors who otherwise would
not deign to do television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever (a network) broke those rules, it was a stunt or an
event,'' said Robert Thompson, director of the Center for the Study
of Popular Television at Syracuse University. ``The network era of
what we knew is over. Cable never had to follow (those rules) in
the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Event television'' is now the beacon, which is fine, except
it's mostly an artificial light. Everything on television is the
``event of the season/year/generation/millennium,'' so nothing is
an event. The networks should change that. They should offer real
events, and not of the Fox ``let's blow up a jet'' variety.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a series that features the best talent from television _
or the movies: A Tom Fontana or John Sayles or Oliver Stone behind
the camera, and your pick of talent _ a Samuel L. Jackson, a
Cameron Diaz, a Kevin Kline _ in front of it. Tell these talented
people to go out and make the best television series they can.
</P>
<P>
   But they have only eight or so episodes to do it.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. That will be the series. The absence of a long-term
(usually five-year) commitment that a regular series commands will
draw in bigger and better names. The short run and quality will
earn the show event status, which will attract viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the bucks: The attraction will be a chance to tell a taut
story in more time than miniseries, movies, God or Kevin Costner
allow, without having to worry about keeping the engine going _ or
shackles on _ for two, three or four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a limited, or capped, series. ``The Prisoner''
essentially did it. ``Fawlty Towers'' did it. We are not asking for
something entirely new, only the discipline needed to make it, walk
away and make it truly an ``event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The temptation is, `Hey, let's go on,''' said Kelly Kahl, vice
president for scheduling at CBS. ``The toughest thing, as in all of
this, is fighting these rules that have been around television.
Once you have the courage to break some of these rules, a lot of
them can come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about how much more revered ``Twin Peaks'' would be had it
lasted only for that first riveting season. Same goes for ``Oz'' on
HBO. You have to know when to fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could make it work,'' said Todd Lituchy, vice president of
scheduling for UPN. ``You could attract bigger talent and it could
work because you could make an event out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason why it wouldn't work,'' he added, ``is if you
couldn't find production companies to deficit-finance when they
would have a lesser chance to recoup at the back end.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Recouping your investment through syndication, the
golden parachute for production companies.
</P>
<P>
   To do these short series, they could be packaged under an
umbrella ``franchise,'' somewhat akin to what NBC did in the 1970s
with its ``NBC Sunday Mystery Movies'' (``Columbo,'' ``McCloud,''
``McMillan and Wife'').
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more opportunity to take risks and try new shows and
new scheduling strategies,'' Lituchy said.
</P>
<P>
   Take the risks in the summer, if you want. Cable has already
eroded the currency of the moribund fall/mid-season schedule.
``There are 52 seasons,'' Thompson said. ``They are called the
weeks of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   In network television, innovation has usually and understandably
come from the network lagging in the ratings. It was third-place
NBC in the early 1980s that launched the genre-shaking ``Hill
Street Blues'' and ``St. Elsewhere.'' It was flailing ABC that
provided ``thirtysomething,'' ``Roseanne,'' ``The Wonder Years and
``Twin Peaks'' in the late '80s and early '90s. And CBS was later
playing catch-up with quirky shows like ``Northern Exposure'' and
``Picket Fences.''
</P>
<P>
   So look to UPN _ the wrestling network _ to attempt to mix it up
next season. The network is looking at a program called ``The
Choppy Show,'' which just as aptly could be called ``The
Chopped-in-Half Show'': The live-action half-hour comedy would in
fact be two 15-minute episodes bundled together, a la cartoons like
``Rugrats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rules are changing somewhat,'' Lituchy said. ``The
networks are looking for event programming. Programmers are not
afraid to challenge the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   And such a challenge would surely qualify as an event.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
