<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BASTERS ARE FOR MORE THAN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 16)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basters, those clever little manual cooking accessories, not
only help to make a roasting bird golden brown, but can be used for
a few other conveniences around the house as well.
</P>
<P>
   A baster is a tube with a removable rubber bulb on one end for
sucking up cooking juices to squirt over a roasting fowl, or to
remove unwanted juices or fat.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, there's more than one type of plastic baster
(prices are about $3.95).
</P>
<P>
   A metal baster ($19.95) with a rubber bulb is favored by many
chefs, because it's more durable, sanitary and won't absorb juices
and discolor.
</P>
<P>
   Basters also come in tempered glass with a rubber bulb ($9.95).
</P>
<P>
   Most basters suck up fat along with flavorful juices.
Tupperware's Healthy Baster ($13.50) has a dripless tip to keep fat
and liquids separate. The baster can also be used to pour crepe
batter, to artfully drizzle sauces, syrups and other liquid
toppings on desserts, or to decorate plates.
</P>
<P>
   A metal baster (or plastic, if you keep it away from the direct
flame) can also come in handy for barbecuing.
</P>
<P>
   Basters can also be used beyond the kitchen:
</P>
<P>
   _ A squirt of hot (not boiling) water can thaw the trouble area
of frozen pipe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tips maven Heloise advises using a plastic turkey baster to
dispense controlled doses of a water/fertilizer mix to houseplants.
Just be sure not to use the same baster for the turkey.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rinse soap from your baby or pet's head by controlling the
direction and flow of the water with a baster.
</P>
<P>
   Between uses, wash the baster with warm sudsy water and a small
bottle brush to keep any bacteria from growing inside the bulb or
tube.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Frances Ingraham Heins writes weekly about items in, on and
around the home. Write to her c/o Details, Features Department,
Albany Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
