<HEADLINE>
WHEN IS A `HACKER' NOT A `CRACKER'?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am a hacker. That is to say, I enjoy playing
with computers. I am not a cracker; I don't make a practice of
breaking computer security. Columns such as yours misuse the word
``hacker,'' giving the impression that it means ``security
breaker'' and nothing else. You are giving hackers a bad name.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hacked Off
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HACKED: Face reality, friend: When people think ``hacker''
these days, they think ``bad guy.'' Language is a living, vital
thing, and words change meanings.
</P>
<P>
   And calling these weasels ``crackers'' at your little meetings
and in your newsletters is not the answer. I spend as much time _
if not more _ as you do in front of a computer, but I'd be insulted
if anybody called me a hacker. You should try coming up with a new
label, or, better yet, not even advertising the sad fact that, like
me, you spend most of your waking hours with a mouse in your hand.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I occasionally view Jennifer Lopez and other
scantily clad ladies on the Internet. I have a great fear that one
day the police will break down my door and find all the ladies on
my hard drive. What do you think? I don't download, just view.
</P>
<P>
   _ Casual Observer
</P>
<P>
   DEAR OBSERVER: Even if you only view the bare naked ladies, they
are on your hard drive nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   All the graphics on a Web page, including Jennifer, are stashed
on your drive so they can be used the next time you call up that
page instead of being downloaded all over again. It's called a
browser cache.
</P>
<P>
   If you're truly worried that Janet Reno has even a passing
interest in what's in there, you can dump the contents. In Internet
Explorer, go to the Tools menu, then Internet Options. Click the
General tab, then Delete Files. In Netscape, Go to the Edit menu,
then Preferences. Select Advanced, then Cache, then Clear Disk
Cache. So long, Jennifer!
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: A mark of good writing is that the reader
understands, without effort, what the writer is trying to
communicate. Using three different words to mean the same thing (in
a recent column) leads the uninformed to confusion. ``E-mail
files,'' ``photos'' and ``programs'' were all used to mean ``photo
attachments.'' When I learned composition, we learned rules that
made the intent of the writer clear to the reader. The young
editors today do not know proper composition; they pass atrocious
writing in ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   _ All Bent Out of Shape
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BENT: Sorry it took so long to respond, but none of us here
could figure out what you were trying to say. Look, diss me all you
want if you can't understand things, but lay off my copy editors.
Even so, I think we all do a pretty good job for a bunch of
uneducated huckleberries.
</P>
<P>
   And, clearly, you didn't realize that when I used three separate
phrases, I meant three separate things. I love to trick readers
like that. You know, I've always found that repetitive use of words
and phrases gives a piece of writing all the charm and vitality of
an Army training manual, but considering your penchant for
pedantry, maybe that's what you'd prefer. May I recommend ``Field
Manual FM22-5'' in lieu of this column?
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay occasionally throws nonsense words chosen
entirely at random into his column to confuse his readers and
editors. Send your drelbats to drbombay(at)star-telegram.com
(snail-mail: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101). Fax: (817) 390-7257. In the nonvirtual world, Dr. Bombay is
Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-07-00 1644EDT &QL;
</P>
