<HEADLINE>
IBM'S WIRED HOME STRIPS USER OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.2000 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ There are two trends in computing of which I
have long been skeptical. The first is the so-called thin client,
in which most of the computer power resides on a server instead of
the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   The second is a first cousin to the thin client known as the
information appliance, a simplified device for sending and/or
receiving information over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Both concepts run counter to the way personal computing has been
developing since its start in the late 1970s. They take power away
from the end user and put it back in a central location. The end
user relies on power within the network, rather than in the power
built into the machine at his or her fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   This strikes me as counter to how people _ particularly at home
_ are using their computers. Most users want more muscle at their
immediate disposal, not less.
</P>
<P>
   So when IBM invited me to get a first look at a new laboratory
devoted to using both thin clients and information appliances in a
networked home, I was intrigued. Maybe by seeing this technology in
a real-world setting, I'd become a believer.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that IBM is chanting this mantra. The company
grew to prominence in the days of the mainframe, when all computing
power was stored in hulking machines that filled entire rooms.
Humans interacted with the computer via terminals that were little
more than keyboards and monitors. There was little or no muscle in
those terminals.
</P>
<P>
   All that changed with the advent of the personal computer, of
which IBM was one of the early proponents, along with Apple and
Tandy. The original IBM PC _ the precursor to the computer found on
most desktops _ was designed by a group whose mission was to
deliberately run counter to IBM's culture. According to Paul
Carroll's excellent book ``Big Blues: The Unmaking of IBM,'' the
company's executives never felt comfortable with what they'd
created. That partly explains why they lost the lead in the PC
market to clone-makers such as Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The facility at IBM's Austin campus is dubbed the Pervasive
Computing Lab, and the idea is that computing is built into just
about everything.
</P>
<P>
   For those who've made jokes about networked refrigerators, you
can stop laughing: This lab has one.
</P>
<P>
   The lab is set up like three rooms in a home _ the living room,
kitchen and garage. In the living room is a wide-screen TV, stereo
system and a server about the size of a cassette deck. This server
communicates with the other computing devices either wirelessly or
through electrical and phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in this homelike setting is connected to the server,
from the ceiling fan in the kitchen to the Venetian blinds in the
living room to the car sitting in the garage. As just one example
of what the lab does, instead of getting up and adjusting the
blinds, you can make the adjustment with a Web page viewed on the
TV or a touchscreen next to the phone in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Want to select some music for your long commute to the office? A
Web page on the TV allows you to select a CD from your collection,
have it converted to MP3 files and then wirelessly downloaded into
the computer in your car.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite device is the refrigerator. Built into the door is a
thin-client computer that lets you synchronize family schedules,
surf the Web, browse recipes and display digitized family photos.
If your family's refrigerator looks anything like mine, you can
understand how much paper and clutter you could clean off the door
with this feature alone.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a food-storage component to this as well. You can
put a tag on each piece of food you place in the refrigerator. The
computer reads the tag and knows what it is. You can be warned when
it is no longer safe to eat _ even before it becomes fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   All the goodies in the lab were cool, though some were more
useful than others. I don't need or want to have my window blinds
controlled by a computer. On the other hand, beaming my MP3
collection to my car stereo gets a thumbs-up.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of what I saw struck me as techies designing cool devices
for other techies. And most of the equipment would be prohibitively
expensive for the vast majority of homeowners today.
</P>
<P>
   Mark F. Bregman, general manager of IBM's Pervasive Computing
initiative, agrees that people may not want everything in the lab,
but getting feedback is what the facility is all about. IBM will be
running focus groups through the simulated room to see how everyday
folks react.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from all three rooms is a full-fledged PC.
Bregman believes that, while the PC has its place, most tasks are
best handled by specialized devices, rather than one that can take
on many different functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't use a Swiss Army Knife to cook with in the kitchen,
do you?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   True. But tools like a knife are extensions of our physical
capabilities, which by definition have limitations. A PC, on the
other hand, is a tool that extends the human mind _ and thus what
it can do is limited only by our imagination. Because of that, the
PC's vast utility extends from its flexibility. It becomes whatever
you need it to be, based on the software you load into it.
</P>
<P>
   Bregman argues that the pervasive computing model is better
because it puts utility up front and maintenance in the background
where it belongs. Bregman said ``trained professionals'' will
manage the software on the back end, even uploading new
capabilities to home devices automatically as they are available _
for a fee, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? To me, IBM's current vision smacks of an attempt
to return to the days when computing was controlled by a kind of
high priest _ the technical overlords in white coats behind the
locked system-room door. I see it as an attempt to re-establish
control, wresting it back from the end user.
</P>
<P>
   It's an attempt to undo the personal computer revolution, which
IBM started reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   (Have a question about your computer? Send e-mail to Dwight
Silverman at dwight.silverman(at)chron.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-07-00 1510EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
