<HEADLINE>
PREPARATION IS KEY TO KEEPING LAND MINES OUT OF LAN PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.2000 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My friends and I have really gotten into multiplayer games,
and we play over the Internet all the time. But it's slow (several
of us use America Online), so we'd like to get together and have a
LAN party. I figure we'll have to set up a network. Is there
anything we should know before we try this? A. I've hosted a couple
of LAN (Local Area Network) parties at my house, and recently
attended a giant one with 100 other people, and it really is a lot
of fun. You're going to have a blast.
</P>
<P>
   But you're right to wonder if there's more to a LAN party than
just setting up a network, and, of course, providing drinks and
food.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, a LAN party is people bringing their
computers to a central location, linking them in a network and
playing online games. It usually involves first-person shooters
such as Command &AMP; Conquer, Quake III Arena or Unreal Tournament,
but now that most games have multiplayer components, the trend is
growing quickly. Flight simulators, tank games, racing games or
strategy titles are all good fodder.
</P>
<P>
   Your first move should be to visit www.lanparty.com, a site
devoted to the topic. Here you'll find an excellent guide to
hosting a party. Among the points the site makes:
</P>
<P>
   Think hard about electricity. This is one of the key elements
that can blow a LAN party _ literally. Remember that a computer and
monitor draw a lot of power. Don't expect to put six or seven
computers on the same circuit in a house. Three is probably the
maximum. Be prepared to run heavy-duty extension cords to other
rooms to spread the load among various circuits. And, of course,
make sure the cords are arranged so no one will trip over them.
</P>
<P>
   If your friends are bringing their computers, make sure they
understand what is required of them. You'll need network cards in
each computer and an Ethernet cable. You'll also need a way to link
the computers, and that means you'll need a hub. If you don't own
one, you'll need to have a friend bring one, or buy one. Make sure
the hub you have has enough ports for all the computers at your
party.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure everyone has a copy of the games that will be played.
Don't rely on installing one copy of the game on all computers.
Some games have copy restrictions that check for duplicated CD keys
or serial numbers, and then won't run if more than one copy is on a
LAN.
</P>
<P>
   Your friends should not forget the little things. When bringing
their computers, they should also bring mouse pads, power cords
(someone always forgets a power cord!) and headphones. In fact,
it's a good idea to leave speakers behind, and insist on headphones
only. At large LAN parties, where it can get very noisy, that's
almost a requirement.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not a computer whiz, make sure at least one of your
friends at the party is. There are always technical problems at LAN
parties _ and you'll need someone there who lives and breathes PCs.
If no one in your group of friends meets that criterion, find
someone who does and invite him or her. Look at it as a useful way
of expanding your social circle.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that not everyone is going to want to play games all
the time, so you might have some alternatives available.
</P>
<P>
   (Have a question about your computer? Send e-mail to Dwight
Silverman at dwight.silverman(at)chron.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-07-00 1504EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
