<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-14 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A GREAT SURVIVOR OF THE GREAT QUAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``During the 1906 earthquake and fire I was only
2 years old, so I don't remember it, but my family told me about
it,'' Bessie Shum said.
</P>
<P>
   We were about a block from where the family's home stood before
the earthquake, in Shum's neat little Chinatown apartment crammed
with pictures of her family, which includes eight grandchildren and
eight great-grandchildren, the latest born just three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   What family stories they'll hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother had bound feet, do you know what that means?'' Shum
said. ``Her feet were very small and she had trouble walking, but
my father said, `No time to pack anything.' We walked over to Van
Ness, and later went to Oakland on the ferry.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bessie Shum will be the first Chinese-American
earthquake survivor to attend the annual gathering of survivors at
Lotta's Fountain on Market Street.
</P>
<P>
   She says she's an ordinary person, but what a life she's led
since her parents took her away from their devastated home near
Portsmouth Square.
</P>
<P>
   One of Shum's photographs from an unidentified San Francisco
newspaper shows young Bessie Wong (her maiden name) baking biscuits
at the YWCA to raise money for Herbert Hoover's relief fund for
European children displaced in World War I. The headline is
``Biscuits, China Style.''
</P>
<P>
   Shum, whose grandfather came to California with the Gold Rush to
work on rail lines, was reared in a family steeped in newspapering
and Chinese reform politics.
</P>
<P>
   She helped found the Chinatown women's service organization, the
Square and Circle, to raise relief money for the 1924 floods in
Canton. Shum and her friends started with a 10-cent raffle. Now
they raise money for many causes, including college scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a chance to go to college,'' she said. ``I
worked all my life to support my family.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, she married Edward Shum, a graduate of New York
University, in a military ceremony. A picture on her wall shows the
bride and groom walking under the crossed swords of Army cadets.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't a citizen and when they moved to China in 1931, she
lost her U.S. citizenship. During the Japanese-Chinese war, she had
to leave her husband and three children with relatives in China,
return to San Francisco and get naturalized as a citizen, while
submitting affidavit after affidavit to get her family back to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   All the while she worked two jobs as a waitress to send money
back to them. When her kids finally arrived, she worked as a
nightclub waitress so she could be with the kids during the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of sailors and soldiers came and danced at the
nightclub, and they always dropped dollars on the floor,'' the
96-year-old said playfully. ``You don't know who dropped the money,
so I kept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another newspaper clip Shum keeps is from a 1963 issue of the
San Francisco Examiner. It's an article by Frank Herbert (who later
became famous for the science-fiction novel ``Dune'') about her
father, Wong Bock Yue.
</P>
<P>
   Wong returned from Oakland and San Jose with the family after
the earthquake. He worked at the Sing Fat Co. import house, then
became an aide to the Chinese revolutionary Dr. Sun Yat Sen when
Sun moved to San Francisco. Wong became publisher of the Young
China newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun asked my father to recruit men to raise money to go back
to China and topple the Manchu dynasty,'' she said. ``At that time
we had discrimination and the Chinese Exclusion Act. He could send
this paper to Chinese all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Shum if there still is discrimination against Chinese.
She leaned toward me, nodded seriously and said, ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   If many leading San Franciscans had had their way after the
earthquake, Wong Bock Yue and his family never would have come back
to Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Chinese earthquake refugees like Bessie Shum's
family made their way to Oakland. Chinatown was looted by National
Guardsmen, and civic leaders like Abe Ruef and James Phelan talked
about ``the Chinese problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, Chinatown had been leveled and they wanted the
valuable land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, they wanted to put the Chinese in Hunters Point,''
said historian Him Mark Lai of the Chinese Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese returned to rebuild businesses and homes.
</P>
<P>
   Even in death, the Chinese didn't get any respect. In 1980,
historians Gladys Hansen and Deanna Paoli Gumina compiled the names
of the earthquake dead for the San Francisco Archives. They
questioned the official 1907 casualty lists of 674 dead and
missing: ``With the complete destruction of Chinatown, it is
difficult to believe that only 12 Oriental names appear on the
compiled list of the dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese earthquake experience was even unhappier than the
experience of other nationalities, so it's understandable why
survivors haven't commemorated its anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was one of the big anniversaries of the earthquake, we
tried to find some (Chinese) survivors,'' said Manny Liu, director
of the Chinese Cultural Center, ``but we couldn't find any.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we have one, and what a survivor she is.
</P>
<P>
   We stood looking at the walls covered with pictures of her
children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how it is,'' Bessie Shum said. ``One family gives me
pictures, another gives me pictures. If I don't put them all up,
you know what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
