<SLUG> BC-CPT-BRITAIN-QUEEN-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO STAKE IN A DOT.COM, THE ROYAL PORTFOLIO IS THRIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ With regal insouciance, Britain's Queen Elizabeth II
rode this week's dot.com roller-coaster, held on to her stake and
emerged as one of her land's newest Internet millionaires Friday
when an Internet company she backed went public.
</P>
<P>
   Her $160,000, 1.5 percent stake in Getmapping.com PLC soared
almost ten-fold in paper value to beyond $1.56 million _ just shy
of 1 million pounds _ when the company began trading on the
Alternative Investment Market with an initial offer price of $3.20,
closing at around $3.60.
</P>
<P>
   The queen chose to invest in Getmapping.com after the company _
which plans to produce the first full aerial map of her realm _ was
permitted to dedicate to her replicas of the Domesday Book, ordered
by William the Conqueror around 1086 as a survey of all the lands
in England.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, not quite the accepted thing to discuss Her
Majesty's wealth. ``The position as far as this is concerned is
that we never give details of the queen's portfolio because it
would lead to commercial endorsement,'' said Penny Russell-Smith, a
Buckingham Palace spokeswoman. But all indications were that
Friday's profits were little more than a dot.com on the landscape
of her personal wealth, which was estimated recently by The Sunday
Times of London at $440 million _ excluding priceless art works.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Getmapping.com said the queen's stake had been
worth some $1.39 million at the offer price, and had closed at a
12.5 premium. Tristram Cary, Getmapping.com's chief executive, said
the company had sought a ``sensible'' offering price after recent
swings in technology stocks. One closely watched British Internet
stock, Lastminute.com, was offered with much fanfare at around
$6.08 recently but plummeted and was trading Friday at $3.84.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Getmapping.com says it has so far mapped 85 percent of Britain
and plans to make a profit by selling aerial maps to real estate
companies and local government offices. It also wants to create
three-dimensional games that will permit internet users to simulate
a flight around Britain. It plans to use the proceeds from its
share offering to develop its Web site and start aerial mapping of
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The queen's interest in the company has inspired newspaper
reports that she is an avid user of the Web, but Buckingham Palace
has sought to play down the idea of the 73-year-old monarch
spending time on the computer. However, she does have her own Web
site _ www.royal.gov.uk _ launched in 1997 to provide news and
biographies of the royal family, Russell-Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-07-00 1520EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
