<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-$ADV09-     04-14 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    FOR MICROSOFT, THE ROAD AHEAD LOOKS MORE DIFFICULT
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Robert Byrd, a Democrat from West Virginia,
happened to walk by a meeting room Wednesday where Microsoft
Chairman Bill Gates was defending his company's behavior over lunch
with a clutch of Senate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   When he heard who was visiting, Byrd quipped, ``Send him to see
me with his checkbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd recalls the time Gates spent as a Senate page, only a few
years before he co-founded Microsoft, now the world's biggest
software firm. Down the road, Gates, still the world's richest man
despite last week's steep selloff in Microsoft stock, could be
obliged to write some big corporate checks, although not to Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   The checks might cover a stiff criminal fine if U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson decides to include monetary penalties
among the remedies in the punishment phase of the federal antitrust
trial against Microsoft. That phase is the last remaining piece of
litigation before the historic case is appealed, presumably all the
way up to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Or they may be necessary to cover the triple damages that
Microsoft could be forced to pay as fallout from hundreds of civil
lawsuits that could expose the software giant to more than $7
billion in damages, according to legal experts.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, Intel, Netscape Communications Corp., now part of America
Online Inc., and Sun Microsystems are among the firms Jackson said
were wronged by Microsoft. All could sue Microsoft for damages and
rely heavily on the government's case to prove their own case.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many of these lawsuits, the government has already done 90
percent of the legwork,'' noted University of Baltimore School of
Law professor Bob Lande.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Judge Jackson has issued a judgment on the findings
of fact, they potentially become legally significant in our case,''
said Dan Small, a partner with Cohen, Milstein, Hausfeld &AMP; Toll.
The Washington-based firm is striving to coordinate many of the 120
suits filed to date and lawsuits and consolidate them into larger
class-action suits.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the judicial onslaught and the further dangers it
poses for Microsoft, Gates &AMP; Co. continue to take a confident,
almost defiant stand, maintaining the company will be vindicated in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, when Gates visited Capitol Hill and the White
House _ at one point driving by the federal courthouse where
Jackson was meeting with both sides to map out the next steps in
the case _ he issued a letter to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was co-signed by Steve Ballmer, Microsoft's chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We respectfully disagree with the court's ruling, and
ultimately believe the American justice system will affirm _ as it
has in the past _ that Microsoft's actions have been both lawful
and good for consumers,'' the letter read.
</P>
<P>
   That key point was reinforced on the following day by William
Neukom, Microsoft's dapper executive vice president and chief
counsel, who sat at the head of the defense table during the 76-day
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable in our position to bring the case to the
appellate court. ... We like our prospects,'' Neukom told the
litigation section of the American Bar Association's annual meeting
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   First, Neukom is scheduled to spend at least one more day next
month in Jackson's courtroom while the company's top hired
litigator, John Warden, presses Jackson to mitigate the punishment
Microsoft faces for having broken the 1890 Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   But the government lawyers, seated at the prosecution table,
will hold the high cards at the May 24 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, in line with the scorching ``findings of fact''
Jackson issued last November, the judge is fully persuaded that
Microsoft has behaved as predatory monopoly. The evidence, Jackson
has held, amply demonstrates a pattern of abuse in which Microsoft
has done violence to the competitive process and placed ``an
oppressive thumb on the scale of competitive fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the company's past conduct, the Justice Department and
the 19 states that joined it in the action view Microsoft as a
repeat offender that cannot be trusted. As the courtroom drama
moves on to consider remedies, that same lack of trust is sure to
lead them demand severe and far-reaching penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that any antitrust remedy in a monopoly case has to
be forward-looking, because otherwise you would forever be playing
catch-up,'' says Justice Dept. antitrust chief Joel Klein.
</P>
<P>
   There have been plenty of antitrust cases in the past in which
the government has imposed forward-looking remedies. ``The relief
does not have to be confined to the exact offenses,'' said
Brookings Institution scholar Robert Litan, a former federal
antitrust official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that settlement talks have broken down, we are back to
square one. I would be surprised if the government didn't ask for
some form of structural relief,'' said Stephen Houck, who served as
lead lawyer for the states before returning to private practice
late last year.
</P>
<P>
   In pronouncing his sentence, Jackson no doubt will address the
core issue raised in his ``conclusions of law'': The leveraging of
Microsoft's Windows operating system monopoly to foreclose
potential competition, stifle innovation and gouge consumers.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson is also under pressure to apply these remedies in a
way that will preserve Microsoft's ability to innovate in one of
the most dynamic sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Jackson will examine the final settlement package
presented by the government and rejected by Microsoft, which has
been handed over to the court under seal.
</P>
<P>
   They call upon Microsoft to stop pricing Windows in ways that
favor cooperative personal computer makers, to stop tying its
products to Windows in its sales contracts, to set aside all
exclusionary contracts, and to stop driving sales up by raising the
price of older versions of Windows whenever a new version comes
out.
</P>
<P>
   Under the government's settlement offer, Microsoft would also
have had to publish a version of Windows without its Internet
Explorer browser and to make available the programming details of
new versions of its system to outsiders at the same time as they
became available to its own applications developers.
</P>
<P>
   One problem with the proposals in the proposed settlement is
that they are essentially backward-looking, and therefore unlikely
to stimulate new competition. Anything short of an outright breakup
would also almost certainly require permanent and intrusive
policing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, the facts of this case were outdated before
the case even began,'' said Jonathan Zuck, president of the
Washington-based Association for Technology, whose list of 6,000
corporate members is headed by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the merits of the litigation, it is also evident that
hand-held devices, smart cell phones and so-called information
appliances, including sophisticated game-playing machines, are
increasingly rendering the personal computer merely one of many
ways to access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They all represent, to varying degrees, shifts in products and
services. Microsoft is an actor in all these fields, but does not
dominate them.
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft, the situation poses a business challenge. For the
courts, however, struggling to solve an antitrust issue without
unduly harming the economy, the challenge could prove to be even
deeper.
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.microsoft.com, www.usdoj.gov
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
