<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE INTENDS TO GROW WITH THE INTERNET ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By COURTNEY KANE  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when swings in technology stocks are feeding a debate
about the Internet economy, The Industry Standard, a magazine
devoted to e-commerce, is starting a campaign to attract a broader
range of readers.
</P>
<P>
   When the magazine began in April 1998, it was aimed at the
people who were responsible for developing and putting into effect
their companies' Internet strategy. As e-commerce has exploded, so
too has that pool of potential readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more people now who need the kind of information
we've been providing,'' said Kerry G. Zeida, vice president for
marketing and brand development for Standard Media in San
Francisco, which publishes The Industry Standard.
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million television and outdoor campaign _ the magazine's
first _ comes at a time when circulation growth is already strong.
The Industry Standard's circulation has risen to 150,000 from
60,000 when it began. The number of advertising pages, marketing
everything from alcohol to cars to technology, has grown even
faster: to 1,678.12 pages in the fourth quarter of last year from
251.17 pages in the fourth quarter of 1998, an increase of 568
percent, according to the tracking service Adscope Inc. in Eugene,
Ore.
</P>
<P>
   While researching an angle to speak to the magazine's expanded
audience, Zeida said the magazine found that its readers appreciate
a competitive advantage they get from reading the publication.
Three 30-second commercials, which start Monday, take that notion
to a humorous extreme by showing Internet business leaders making
an effort to keep the information they get from The Industry
Standard confidential.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, two men are seated at tables in a nondescript cafe,
with their backs to one another. In a spoof of spy movies, the two
exchange a series of quirky code phrases to assure each other that
they have the right contact: ``Does your wife sleep in the nude?''
``Actually she prefers flannel.'' ``Little Bo Peep has lost her
sheep.'' ``Leave them alone and they'll come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the two exchange their top-secret information. One man
quickly passes the magazine, which is concealed in a folder, to the
other and says, ``See you next week.''
</P>
<P>
   A second commercial features a man hustling to enter an empty
elevator. As he starts to open The Industry Standard magazine he
feels the presence of a security camera and backs up out of its
range. He then takes out a can of spray paint and blackens the
lens. Both spots close with an announcer saying: ``Read it. Learn
from it. Don't let it fall into the wrong hands,'' followed by the
company's tagline, ``The Industry Standard. Your weekly
intelligence report on the Internet economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials will begin running Monday in 10 markets,
including Atlanta, Dallas, Miami, New York and San Francisco,
during cable business programs including those of Bloomberg News,
CNBC, CNN and MSNBC. The work is the first from TBWA/Chiat/Day in
Playa del Rey, Calif., part of the TBWA Worldwide unit of the
Omnicom Group, since that agency was awarded the account in
January.
</P>
<P>
   In the spots, ``we're saying this magazine is just chock full of
information all geared toward the Internet economy,'' said Jerry
Gentile, managing partner and creative director at TBWA/Chiat/Day.
``I think what we've tried to do is to personify it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of don't let it fall into the wrong hands,'' he
added, is one of ``making this your edge to e-commerce, trying to
make everybody feel they have their own little personal source to
understand e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   The outdoor portion of the campaign will feature billboards in
New York and San Francisco. One ad is a spectacular, a gigantic
electronic display located just off the Bay Bridge en route to San
Francisco. That billboard features an enlarged masthead of The
Industry Standard, accompanied by a live feed of
Internet-business-related news headlines for commuters.
</P>
<P>
   Other billboards show a copy of the magazine accompanied by
headlines including, ``We never met a bubble we couldn't burst''
and ``Sugar coating is for cereal.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for the magazine is the first component of what
will become a branding campaign to promote the entire company,
Standard Media. Subsequent ads for the other ventures and services
will be introduced later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Media, which is referred to simply as, ``The
Standard,'' is majority-owned by International Data Group. The
company also produces a Web site (www.TheStandard.com) and 18
online newsletters including Media Grok, in addition to hosting
national and international conferences and events.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-09-00 1726EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
