</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-ETAILERS-GO-PUBLIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK SHOCK IS A SIGNAL: TOUGH TIMES FOR E-TAILERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, a short-term battering of technology stocks and a
drumbeat of financial distress signals from e-commerce retailers
reminded the world that even dot-coms cannot assume a never-ending
flow of money.
</P>
<P>
   Not that David Friedensohn needed reminding. He still recalls a
lean week in late 1996 at SonicNet, the music Web site he was
running, when after meeting the payroll he had $50 left in the
bank. SonicNet escaped insolvency by being bought.
</P>
<P>
   Now Friedensohn runs an online video store called BigStar
Entertainment, which went public last August and by last Friday had
seen its share price sink to $3.75 _ 62 percent below the offering
price.
</P>
<P>
   He knows, like many e-tailers these days, that he cannot expect
to raise more money any time soon through a secondary offering. So
Friedensohn has taken what, for an Internet company at least, is
drastic action: He has slashed BigStar's marketing expenses 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of burning through his $25 million in cash in a year,
Friedensohn said, he now will survive 18 months _ long enough to
hope the company will be able to move into the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only smart thing I can do right now is take the cash I
have and assume I can't get any more,'' he said. ``I'm not going to
run into a brick wall like some of these companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's market volatility made it painfully clear that many
Internet companies, especially the electronic retailers that
operate online stores, may be heading toward that wall. As a
sector, the so-called e-tailing companies' stock prices are now off
60 to 90 percent from their highs last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Such a drop is depressing for any business. But it is life
threatening for most e-tailers because nearly all of them went
public with the explicit plan of losing money for years while they
were building their brands and systems. And it seems doubtful that
many will be able to raise the second and third installments of
cash they had been counting on _ and that they will need for
carrying out those ambitious business plans.
</P>
<P>
   So now what?
</P>
<P>
   Like a Formula One race car driver who finds himself heading
into a sharp turn too fast, the choice is between hoping that luck
and skill can prevail over physics _ or slowing down to see whether
more reckless rivals spin out of control as they pull ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to make tough strategic choices to survive in this
environment,'' said Jonathan V. Diamond, chairman of CDNow, a music
e-tailer that has seen its own stock crater and now finds itself
back on the auction block after its merger with the Columbia House
record club was canceled last month.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies, like BigStar, are slamming on the brakes. Others
are making painful compromises to press ahead. Egghead.com, for
example, has been forced to seek private financing, at a discount
to the price of its publicly traded stock, which is now at $7.3125,
compared with more than $39 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, PlanetRX, an online drugstore, is one of the
companies that is moving ahead in full knowledge that its cash
cannot hold out until it breaks even. PlanetRX had planned a
secondary stock offering, William J. Razzouk, its chairman said,
but will not take that step as long as its stock remains 88 percent
below its October high of $36.50.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Razzouk's company will fine tune spending, in his
words, and defer plans to raise more money until its stock price
rises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you manage your cash flow, and things that are not
absolutely, positively critical, you do without,'' he said. ``But
we will earn the opportunity to refill the gas tank one or two more
times, so long as investors see that we are making progress to
profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are so many e-tailers in such dire straits? It is not
because people do not like shopping online. If anything, Internet
sales are ahead of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But the online stores are finding it much more expensive than
they had expected to find and serve customers, while at the same
time the frantic pace of competition is depressing prices and
forcing costly giveaways like free shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder that investors have shifted their fancy from
online retailing to so-called business-to-business commerce, which
involves the market for raw goods, industrial parts and corporate
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Wall Street finds that a business is not up to its
expectations, it just moves on to something else.'' said George
Orban, the chairman of Egghead, the online electronics retailer
that has tried to stay afloat in a tough business by merging with a
competitor, Onsale Inc. ``You're going to see a lot of businesses
flame out.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Nova, a partner with Highland Capital, a venture firm, said
the companies he had invested in _ including e-tailers like eToys
and Staples.com _ are hardly going to flame out. But some, he said,
certainly have had to modify their approaches in the current
investment climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dance partners to Wall Street, and they changed the
tempo,'' Nova said. ``Nine months ago, investment bankers were
telling us we were showing profits too early and not investing
enough in the brand. Now we have to scale back our plans to show
profits earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   This vulnerability to the fickle folly of Wall Street,
particularly when much of the market's tone is being set by online
day traders, highlights just how risky it was for these companies
to go public with little more than a Web site and a dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the dark side of going public early,'' said Alec
L. Ellison, a merger specialist with Broadview, a New Jersey
investment bank. ``A lot of companies will have to be restructured
because they don't have a steady and patient source of capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris MacAskill, chief executive of Fatbrain.com, an online
professional bookstore, blames investment bankers and venture
capitalists for forcing his company to go public much too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we waited until we had a few more quarters under our belt,
we could have had a great public offering,'' he said. Fatbrain went
public in November 1998, with its share price closing near $25 the
first day. It is now at $10.8125. ``Your entrance to the grand
stage sets the standard for how you will be measured,'' MacAskill
said.
</P>
<P>
   But many other executives say they had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies are going public very early and are under
intense public scrutiny,'' CDNow's Diamond said. ``But I would do
it all over again,'' he said. ``We needed to go public to raise the
money to build a brand quickly.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Diamond was an executive at the music retailer N2K when it
raised $103 million in an initial public offering in October 1997.
CDNow, with which it merged early last year, raised $65 million
when it went public in February 1998. Each also raised more in
secondary offerings before their merger.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry executives now say it was better to have gone
public perhaps too soon than wait until now, when the changing mood
of Wall Street may have made it too late for other e-tailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going public was the best thing we could have done,'' said
Kenneth E. Kurtzman, the chief executive of Ashford.com, an online
jewelry store that went public with an $81 million offering last
September. ``We raised enough capital to see us until we get
profitable, and it established our name as the leader in the space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even better,'' Kurtzman added, ``I felt like the door was
closing behind us. Our competitors are running out of cash, and
they can't go public.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists and investment bankers say it may be that
the only online retailers that are able to raise money in today's
market will be those affiliated with traditional retailers, like
Kmart, Wal-mart Stores and Toys ``R'' Us.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be a new stand-alone business-to-consumer
dot-com created again,'' predicted Robert Lessin, co-chief
executive of Wit Capital, a New York investment bank active in
Internet offerings. ``Three years ago, you could create a brand for
$10 million. Now it costs $1 billion. With the lifetime value of a
customer, it just doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   This judgment may be a bit too harsh, in the view of Michael
Moritz, a partner with Sequoia Capital, a Silicon Valley venture
firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that a lot of companies were formed and got
financed that didn't meet the great litmus test of being a good
business,'' he said. ``And people are only now waking up surprised
to find out what they had invested in. But a lot of nice, cherubic
little babies are being thrown out with the gray bathwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he argues, the babies, at least those in his
portfolio, will be rescued. ``I don't go to sleep at night worried
about cash,'' he said. ``Good companies can always raise money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-09-00 1701EDT &QL;
</P>
