<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE0411-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Easter sites brimming with information
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Easter is a holiday that _ just as is true for
Christmas _ has both a deep religious meaning and also has become a
day for games and family activities.
</P>
<P>
   The Web offers information and guidance for both. So no matter
how your family celebrates the day, you should be able to find
something helpful. Unlike the Easter eggs hidden deep in the far
bushes, these sites are easy to find and use.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop on the Bunny Trail is a site called Eggs-otic
Easter. You'll find the site at
www.invision.net/easter/easterinside.html. If you'd like to share
your feelings about the day, there's a place where you can leave a
note for all the world to see. You'll find links that take you to
an Internet Easter egg hunt so, even if it rains on Easter, you can
still find eggs. Plus, there's a way to color Easter eggs online _
no mess, no fuss, all thanks to computer wizardry.
</P>
<P>
   No holiday worth its salt, or flour and sugar, is complete
without special meals, and that's certainly true of Easter. No
matter whether you celebrate the day with a fancy baked ham or a
backyard cookout while the kids hunt for eggs, there's help
available with holiday recipes.
</P>
<P>
   You'll want to check out a site at
holidayrecipe.com/features/easter.asp called Holidayrecipe.com
Easter Recipes for some good cooking ideas. Besides the expected
ham recipes, you'll find some advice on creating your own Easter
baskets from scratch and then even more help on preparing goodies
to fill them. Even the humble boiled egg gets some attention here.
</P>
<P>
   The page also offers you a way to share your own recipes. You'll
be glad to know there's some advice on what to do with the leftover
ham.
</P>
<P>
   For a look at the Christian celebration of Easter, there is a
page at www.gospelcom.net/peggiesplace/easter.htm called Christian
Easter Celebration that is worth a visit. Another site at
www.rockies.net/(tilde)spirit/sermons/easterpage.html offers
information for ministers on the holiday, along with help in
planning sermons.
</P>
<P>
   If you realize, as you began to discuss the holiday with your
family, there are parts of the tradition and history that are still
mysteries to you, there's an excellent resource at
www.geocities.com/Athens/Parthenon/1502/easte.html. It's called
Christine O'Keeffe's Easter page. You'll find links that take you
to sections explaining the egg's importance to the holiday, as well
as sections with traditional Easter games (including hiding the
eggs) and ancient history of the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   This page also has an excellent collection of links to Easter
pages on other parts of the Web. So you'll want to spend some time
investigating these pages as well.
</P>
<P>
   Another traditional Christian page, called Carolyn's Universe,
has some truly beautiful religious graphics as well as sections
that offer the traditional Christian story of Easter, plus
information on the Easter lily, Easter eggs and the Easter bunny.
One story that may not be familiar to all is the story of the
butterfly. That legend compares the metamorphosis of the
caterpillar into the butterfly to the stages of Christ's life.
You'll find Carolyn's Universe at
www.carolynsuniverse.com/easter.html.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
