<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WAKE UP AND SMELL THE FREE-TRADE COFFEE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As far back as February 1998, executives at the
mighty Seattle-based Starbucks Coffee Co. said they were
``exploring the possibility`` of offering customers coffee beans
that meet international fair-trade standards for non-exploitive
labor.
</P>
<P>
   This week, exploration ended.
</P>
<P>
   By autumn, Starbucks has promised, it will add ``fair-trade
certified'' coffee to the inventories of its 2,000-plus retail
stores and e-commerce Web site. Among other things, such
certification means individual farmers are guaranteed a minimum of
$1.26 per pound of beans.
</P>
<P>
   That guarantee will triple the incomes of thousands of
small-farm growers, mostly in Central America, who live below
subsistence levels with their tiny shares of the volatile
coffee-bean market.
</P>
<P>
   Although the move will affect only a small percentage of
Starbucks' multibillion-dollar retail business, the promise is
historic. Despite years of lobbying by international labor rights
groups, no other major U.S. coffee company has made such a
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great victory for the farmers,'' said Paul Rice, the
executive director of TransFair USA, a nonprofit agency based in
Oakland, Calif., that will certify the coffee. ``We've been working
on Starbucks for about eight months, trying to get them on board.
The agreement they have made is truly visionary; it shows true
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   TransFair USA is a recent off-shoot of a 12-year-old European
fair trade organization and part of a 19-member international
consortium. All are independent monitoring and information agencies
that seek to protect and promote the livelihoods of some 500,000
small-farm coffee growers in Central America, Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   TransFair does this primarily by helping small-farm families
establish large cooperatives to sell beans directly to huge coffee
companies. Shut out are the commercial middlemen whose exorbitant
fees reduce the farmers' per-pound price to about 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   So successful is TransFair USA's European parent, about $300
million in ``fair-trade certified'' coffee was sold on the
continent just last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starbucks didn't just do something that would make the problem
go away,'' Rice said. ``They're making this coffee available in
every store, every day for a full year. And they have promised to
place the certification labels front-and-center and provide posters
and brochures that will educate their customers about fair trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have gone a different way. They could have dug in the
way Nike did when their labor practices were challenged. But they
decided instead to work with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Starbucks is hardly taking out thank-you ads, it's
likely that some of the credit for the company's decision goes to
the same labor rights groups that did indeed hound Nike into
humiliation and eventual submission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been meeting with Starbucks for two years, and all we
kept getting was how they were this big ship that just couldn't be
`instantly' turned around,'' said Medea Benjamin, the founding
director of the San Francisco-based human rights group Global
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we addressed their board on Feb. 14 and met privately
with their executives, we still felt they weren't taking us
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Global Exchange folks told Starbucks they were organizing
a 30-city, April 13 protest in front of Starbucks stores from
Buffalo, N.Y., to Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On April 4, Starbucks senior vice president Dave Olsen sent Paul
Rice a letter outlining the company's agreement with TransFair USA.
</P>
<P>
   Global Exchange activists gladly called off the Starbucks action
and redirected their freed-up energy to increase pressure on other
coffee giants like Maxwell House (owned by the Philip Morris Cos.),
Folgers (owned by Procter and Gamble) and Peet's coffee in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, timing of the Starbucks-TransFair agreement could not
be better for workers rights activists with a long view:
</P>
<P>
   The annual Specialty Coffee Association of America trade show
opens Saturday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme of this year's show is `Quality, Sustainability and
Social Responsibility,'' Rice said. ``Starbucks' decision to carry
`fair-trade certified' coffee sends a powerful message to the
entire industry that this theme can be more than words on a
banner.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
