<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUN ADVOCATES MAY SHOOT THEMSELVES IN THE FOOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A newspaper columnist who wants lots of letters, e-mails and
phone calls can get them easily enough. Just write a column about
gun control.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter whether you're for gun control or against it.
Both sides will respond _ and respond vehemently. If you're really
clever _ and slightly ambivalent about the issue _ you can
infuriate gun lovers and gun haters in the very same column.
</P>
<P>
   My recent column suggesting that pro-gun forces hurt their own
cause by questioning President Clinton's motives for seeking new
gun laws _ and for refusing to compromise in the gun-law debate _
earned me the wrath of those who oppose restrictions on guns. But
the column also annoyed the anti-gun crowd because it included my
longstanding opinion that gun laws are of minimal value in reducing
crime and violence _ that the real problem isn't guns, but
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-gun:
</P>
<P>
   ``You should be proud; your column ... is posted prominently
today at www.freerepublic.com. Unfortunately, it's the subject of
much derision, and worse. You see, the universal conclusion is that
you're an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think gun owners should compromise? We've BEEN
compromising for 32 years. Why doesn't the other side ever
compromise? I thought the 1968 ban on `small guns' (AKA `Saturday
night specials') was supposed to make us safe. Or was it banning
`assault rifles'? Or was it the ban on high-capacity magazines?
Whatever. How come we're not `safe' yet?
</P>
<P>
   ``NO MORE COMPROMISES!''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-gun:
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think you fall into the NRA `trap' too readily with
respect to the effectiveness of gun controls, since statistically,
only a minority of gun deaths and injuries are inflicted by
criminals who set out to rob or kill, whereas most are accidents,
crimes of passion, or unintended consequences of the ready
availability of guns. Registration and licensing requirements,
trigger locks, etc., would not `infringe' the ability of a merchant
or homeowner to obtain means of self protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky me, I don't have to decide which of these readers is right
and which is wrong. And I don't have to cast a vote in any
legislature, federal or state, on the many gun bills that are
constantly being proposed.
</P>
<P>
   I have my point of view, of course, and I have consistently
supported the right to keep and bear arms _ although I might be
tempted to re-evaluate my position if the pro-gun folks insist on
calling me an idiot every time I disagree with them.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me back to the previous column. The point I was
trying to make was that the combative intransigence of the National
Rifle Association and its devotees could result in more damage to
the rights of gun owners than the occasional compromise ever could.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I understand the ``slippery slope'' argument, which says
that every new restriction on the rights of gun owners leads
inexorably toward the day when those rights are abolished. I agree
that a free society must be vigilant to the menace of
incrementalism where essential rights are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Once the voracious jaws of government start nibbling at precious
freedoms, there is the constant danger that liberty will be totally
and irrevocably consumed.
</P>
<P>
   However. The refusal of gun-rights proponents to even consider
the possibility that some gun-control measures might be worthwhile
could turn out to be self-defeating.
</P>
<P>
   As the NRA shouts down more and more attempts to reduce the
availability of guns in this country, many Americans are becoming
more and more frustrated. When U.S. Rep. Carolyn McCarthy of New
York declared recently that ``the moms of America'' were growing
impatient with the gun lobby, she was issuing a warning that those
who value the Second Amendment should heed.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates such as Clinton and McCarthy have the
public's attention on this issue, and they are winning the
argument. If the NRA isn't careful, gradual erosion of gun rights
could turn out to be the least of its worries; the American people
might just decide to skip the incremental restrictions and go
straight for the all-out gun ban.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the gun lovers can hold off the gun haters forever by
refusing to give an inch. But if they bet the farm on it and lose _
well, who's the idiot then?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
