<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET CASTS A DOUBTFUL EYE ON SOVEREIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the good news: Sovereign Bancorp.'s deal to take over
hundreds of bank branches divested during the merger of Fleet
Financial Corp. and BankBoston Corp. has already generated millions
of dollars in new loans.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the catch: The loans were actually written for Sovereign
executives, to cover brokerage margin calls as the value of their
company stock continued to sink.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has been skeptical of Sovereign's big New
England divestiture grab since Day One. The stock, down nearly 60
percent over the last year, barely registered a pulse as financial
shares began to rally back last month.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent document, Sovereign said that it loaned millions to
a handful of key executives in November, to cover bonus-related
taxes and margin calls on bankers who had borrowed to buy withering
company stock.
</P>
<P>
   Top on the list: chief executive Jay Sidhu, who took a $6.2
million loan. Two other officers borrowed a combined $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign's stock was already in a serious funk well before
rumors got around that it might be the big winner in the
Fleet-BankBoston divestiture last year.
</P>
<P>
   The shares moved higher for one day in September, right after
Sovereign officially won the right to buy 278 bank branches for
$1.4 billion. Since then, Sovereign shares have lost another 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The big March financial stock rally hasn't budged Sovereign
shares. While FleetBoston Financial Corp. has rallied 44 percent,
Sovereign stock has shed another fraction of a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't the huge divestiture victory for a relatively
small Pennsylvania institution translate into investor optimism? It
is precisely this scale issue, the enormity of the job, that makes
people nervous. Can they actually make the mechanics work, and will
the regional economy remain rosy long enough, probably for a couple
of years, for Sovereign to establish itself in good times?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sovereign is a long-term show-me situation,'' said analyst
James Ackor of Tucker Anthony Cleary Gull.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign's stock woes have not been endured in a vacuum. Most
bank stocks have been badly depressed, and company executives note
that the market has been even worse for midsize institutions like
Sovereign.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good chunk of our decrease is sector-related,'' said Mark
McCollom, chief accounting officer at Sovereign. ``While we can't
control certain market influences, we believe we can control our
core growth rate in earnings _ and that's what we're trying to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fleet divestiture, originally planned as a single
transaction, has been reorganized as a staggered transfer, easing
Sovereign capital issues and making the actual change in operations
more managable.
</P>
<P>
   Sovereign took over operations in Connecticut, Rhode Island and
parts of Western Massachusetts late last month. The balance of the
transfer, involving Eastern Massachusetts offices, will take place
in June and July.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good, Sovereign reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through a third of it, and that's a good sample,''
said John Hamill, chief executive of Sovereign New England.
</P>
<P>
   If the rest of the conversion is smooth and New England's
economy remains strong, some analysts believe Sovereign stock will
be poised for a rally. It is so cheap now, selling a bit over six
times earnings, that a healthy Sovereign has to be worth more, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming the conversion goes reasonably well, this stock
should be a double,'' said analyst Bruce Harting of Lehman
Brothers. ``There's not another name that represents this kind of
upside.''
</P>
<P>
   But that assumption will take time to play out. Sovereign's
quarterly earnings report, due next week, will reflect only a
sliver of the Fleet divestiture. A full picture could take several
quarters to develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is negligible, but there's no compelling
near-term catalyst to move this stock up in the next six months,''
said Ackor, the Tucker Anthony analyst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Former UST Corp. chief James V. Sidell is back in the banking
business. Sidel has joined Capital Crossing Bank in Boston as
director of relationship banking. Capital Crossing, which has about
$800 million in assets, changed its name from Atlantic Bank &AMP; Trust
last fall.
</P>
<P>
   --Fidelity Investments fund manager Brad Lewis, 45, has decided
to retire from ``professional protfolio management.'' Lewis was
well-known as a leading ``quant'' investor inside Fidelity, relying
on computers and other tools for quantitative analysis of stocks.
Lewis will be succeeded as manager of the Fidelity Disciplined
Equity fund by Steven Snider and by Bobby Kuo as manager of
Fidelity Stock Selector.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
