<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ARMS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN DUMA APPROVES ARMS REDUCTION TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
(ART ADV: A graphic showing the timetable for arms reduction under
START II is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Russian Duma Friday approved the long-delayed nuclear arms
reduction treaty with the United States, laying the ground for a
reduction of several thousand nuclear missiles on both sides and
opening the way to even more dramatic cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty, known as START II, passed in the Duma, the lower
house of the Russian parliament, by a lopsided vote of 288-131,
with four abstentions. The Federation Council, the parliament's
upper house, is expected to approve it April 19, after which
President Vladimir Putin will sign it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Putin went before the Duma Friday to press the legislators to
approve the treaty, which was signed in 1993 but has been stalled
in Russia since the U.S. Congress ratified it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Delaying the treaty any further, Putin warned, ``can prompt a
nuclear arms race that Russia can ill-afford and whose consequence
would be even worse than the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Putin also warned that Russia would pull out of START II and
other arms treaties if the United States changed the anti-ballistic
missile treaty that it reached with the former Soviet Union in
1992. Congress wants to amend that treaty to allow the United
States to build a new anti-ballistic missile shield as protection
against accidental launchings and attacks by ``rogue'' states.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States does that, Putin assured the Duma
legislators, ``we will withdraw not only from the START II treaty
but from the whole system of treaties on limitation and control of
strategic and conventional weapons,'' according to the Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   START II would reduce the number of missile warheads on each
side from 6,000 to 3,500 by the end of 2007. It would also ban
multiple warheads on land-based missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. position is that the current treaty must be ratified
before any deeper cuts can be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   START II was supported by the Russian military, which has been
drained of funds to maintain its nuclear arsenal because of
Russia's economic problems and war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing through the treaty's ratification, Putin demonstrated
his ability to prod the Duma into action and made a positive
gesture toward the West before he visits Britain on Sunday. The
vote Friday removes an irritant in Russian-U.S. relations, which
have also been strained by the U.S.-led bombings in Iraq and
Yugoslavia and Russia's war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   In accomplishing within a month of his election what his
predecessor, Boris N. Yeltsin, had failed to do in six years in
office, Putin benefited from the more centrist legislature that
emerged from Russia's parliamentary elections last December. The
Communists, who lost the majority they previously enjoyed in the
Duma, had obstructed passage of START II for nearly five years,
contending that it would only enhance the military superiority of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who is visiting
Ukraine, hailed the Duma's ratification of the treaty as historic
and a boost for international security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6811 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-BELICHICK-2     04-14 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BELICHICK-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING THROUGH BELICHICK'S PAST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ One thing Bill Belichick would like to make
clear as he prepares to run his first draft for the New England
Patriots _ and his first draft in five years _ Saturday is that the
phones in the war room are safe.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the legend that has grown up around his final draft with
the Cleveland Browns, he insisted this week on at least this: he
never threw the phone. Honest he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the story goes, Belichick was ready to take Penn State
tight end Kyle Brady with the 10th pick, a selection many in the
organization backed. But the New York Jets grabbed Brady out from
under the Browns' noses and what happened next has been the subject
of some debate ever since.
</P>
<P>
   According to both ESPN and published reports at the time, an
enraged Belichick grabbed a phone and hurled it into the wall.
According to Belichick and his drafting aide at the time, Mike
Lombardi, nothing like that happened. According to others in
Cleveland, it's gospel. Considering the way Brady's career turned
out, he wasn't worth denting the phone any way, but that's a
separate issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that was true,'' insisted Lombardi this week. ``I'll
take a lie detector test on that. Were we upset that he was taken
right ahead of us? Yeah, but Bill wasn't really that crazy about
Brady.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's story coincided with that of his former assistant.
``Some people in the organization wanted Brady,'' he said. ``How
badly, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   What Belichick does know is what followed, which was his
decision to trade out of the 10th slot all the way down to No. 30,
where he selected an undersized Ohio State linebacker named Craig
Powell, who did little in football after suffering a severe knee
injury that summer and is no longer in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Whom he could have taken at No. 10, however, is of more
importance, because he could have taken someone who became one of
the best defensive linemen in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I learned from that draft, and I think Bill learned
as well, was that we were not prepared to make the right decision
on a certain player,'' recalled Lombardi, who now works in
personnel with the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Warren Sapp. We'd lost James Jones to Denver and
Michael Dean Perry, too, so we were looking for defensive linemen.
If we were prepared and known if Sapp was a good or bad guy, we
would have taken him and things would have been fine. But we didn't
know so we traded back and took Powell, who wasn't a very good
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, you have to learn from your mistakes. There's no
Draft Management 101 course. I know I learned from that case and I
believe Bill did, too. That will not happen again to either of us.
One thing about Bill, he analyzed every draft and studied our
mistakes. He doesn't make the same mistake twice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mistake that day _ putting the telephone aside _ was that
his organization lacked enough information on one player and
gambled on another. During the five years Belichick was the Browns'
head coach and general manager (1991-95), he drafted some good
players but missed on what seems like more than the norm. What that
bodes for the Patriots' future is impossible to determine. All that
is sure is that Belichick once again has the final say, so the
credit _ not to mention the blame _ will fall on him one way or the
other.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same in Cleveland, a team Belichick rebuilt from the
slovenly 3-13 group he inherited into an 11-5 playoff team four
years later. But his drafts were not as helpful as one might figure
considering where Cleveland picked, which is a concern of many
Patriot watchers as Belichick tries to reinforce a team that went
into a second-half free fall last season and now seems in need of
more help than it should have needed considering the favorable
drafting position it owned the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year of selecting, Belichick got a Pro Bowl player
in safety Eric Turner, the second pick overall, and another
productive one in the sixth round in wide receiver Michael Jackson,
who twice led the Browns in receptions. He hit again in 1994 on
Derrick Alexander, a receiver who remains the Chiefs' best pass
catcher, and got some solid years out of center Steve Everitt,
cornerback Antonio Langham (until he lost his confidence),
linebacker Gerald Dixon, defensive linemen James Jones and Pio
Sagapolutele, and a good season from Mike Frederick before being
fired after the 1995 season.
</P>
<P>
   But Belichick also had some spectacular misses, such as Powell,
guard Ed King, defensive lineman Bill Johnson, and wide receiver
Pat Rowe, all second- and third-round choices no longer in
football. Several of those failures suffered serious injuries early
in their careers, which is more a case of bad luck than bad
analysis, but the most glaring deficiency in Belichick's Cleveland
drafts came near the end of them.
</P>
<P>
   From the fourth round on, he seldom seemed to pick a serviceable
player with the exception of Jackson in 1991; in fact, only nine of
his picks from those rounds remain in the league. That is a
deficiency Belichick seems to recognize as he enters the second
phase of his head coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to know what you're taking,'' Belichick said
this week. ``If I learned anything, I learned to cut down on the
risks you take. If a guy has all the variables of size and speed
but wasn't a good college player, you can make excuses for why that
was and convince yourself you can change it. But what I learned is
if you take a guy who didn't do much in college, regardless of the
reason, you're betting against the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Cleveland we did it more than we should have. What I
learned was that good athletes who are not good players in college
generally continue not to be good players in the pros.''
</P>
<P>
   That realization alone should save him from making more
selections like Johnson, a fat defensive lineman with a bad
attitude who never did a thing in the NFL, or Rico Smith, a fast
wide receiver with bad hands, or Isaac Booth, a tall cornerback (6
feet 3 1/2 inches) who simply couldn't play in a uniform as well as
he looked wearing one.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think he and I both came to understand is why do we
think we're going to get a guy to play if the coach at Purdue or
somewhere couldn't?'' Lombardi said. ``We all want to say they
screwed him up and we can coach him. What we learned is that isn't
often the case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What will be the case throughout his future drafts is that there
are certain principles Belichick believes in and will generally
adhere to.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that he builds his teams from the middle out,
believing that players in the middle of the field are closer to the
ball and hence have a greater impact on the game. That means he
looks for safeties, centers, middle linebackers, quarterbacks, and
running backs first, although that assumes such needs exist.
</P>
<P>
   If one looks at his Cleveland drafts, a clear pattern emerged,
as he took a safety, guard, and two interior defensive linemen with
his first four picks in 1991, a fullback type in Tommy Vardell No.
1 the next year, a center with his first pick in 1993, and a
linebacker and quarterback with his first two picks in 1995. That
doesn't mean he will go that way, but it is a sure sign of how he
believes a team is built.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different here than it was in Cleveland,'' Belichick
said. ``There's a much better base to build from, but some of the
same principles apply. I do believe if you've got good players in
the middle of the field they're involved in every play. The farther
out you are the less involved you become.''
</P>
<P>
   The next area of focus for Belichick is in high-production
players who fit a size-speed ratio. That does not mean he won't
ever reach for an undersized player or one slower than he might
like, but, as he learned in Cleveland, production and speed are two
sound indicators of a player's chances of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Size and speed is the place to start,'' Belichick said. ``If
you want a big, fast team, you need big, fast players. You draft a
lot of slow guys you can only end up with one kind of team. There
are always exceptions but I do put a lot of emphasis on size and
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
