<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-SLAVE-MEMORIAL-ART     04-14 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SLAVE-MEMORIAL-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SUPPORT GROWS FOR SLAME MEMORIAL IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAPHAEL LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDFORD, Mass. _ The old brick wall slouches by a wooded glen
along busy Grove Street, a crumbling divider between present and
past, memory and ignorance, freedom and servitude.
</P>
<P>
   It's said that in 1765, 18 years before Massachusetts outlawed
the owning of human beings, an enslaved African-American named
Pompeii built the wall, making the bricks from local clay.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-foot wall formed half of an entry gate to a 400-acre
plantation owned by the Brooks family, whose well-known
contributions to Medford stand in stark contrast to those of
``Pomp'' and the dozens of slaves who once toiled there.
</P>
<P>
   As a monument to those who suffered the horrors of slavery, the
wall may seem a perplexing choice _ especially since Medford is
home to the well-preserved Royall House, site of the only remaining
slave quarters north of the Mason-Dixon line. The ``Old Slave
Wall,'' by comparison, appears ready to topple, and its cracked
face is marred by generations of graffiti, moss, and whitewash.
</P>
<P>
   But to a growing number of people, the Slave Wall is an ideal
candidate for a memorial to the un-heralded achievements of Pomp
and his fellow slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The wall, its admirers say, offers testament to the workaday
activities slaves were forced to do _ and is a stark reminder that
even in the cradle of abolition, slaves toiled for generations.
</P>
<P>
   The admirers, both black and white, are seeking public and
private money to shore up the wall, erect a plaque, and create a
small park behind it where visitors could view it comfortably. The
project would cost at least $25,000, said Jay Griffin, head of the
Medford Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I, like all of us, owe the wall some
recognition,'' said Pamela Goncalves, 47, an African-American
Medford resident who is leading the fledgling campaign. ``I owe
something to the people who suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Goncalves, who learned of the structure while researching for
her historic drama troupe called ``The Colored Ladies,'' has
touched on a topic that has been a sensitive issue in parts of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In Winthrop, battle lines have been drawn over the erecting of a
sign that calls attention to the slave trading and slave ownership
of Deane Winthrop, son of the state's first governor, whose home
gave the town its name.
</P>
<P>
   In Framingham, a controversy has flared as citizens prepare for
the town's 300th anniversary celebration, which will include a
reenactment of a Civil War battle. Some are saying that the
inclusion of a Confederate Flag in the festivities is offensive and
inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   For a state that trumpets its role in the abolition of slavery,
Massachusetts has a ways to go before it comes to terms with its
role in American history's uglier chapters, some observers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's ironic is that the people at the forefront of
preserving the history of slavery are all down South,'' said Byron
Rushing, a state representative from Boston and the former
executive director of the Museum of Afro American History in
Boston. ``In Massachusetts, you would not think that we would have
a problem talking about slavery, since we were the first state to
abolish it. You would think that would balance out the concern that
this is so negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Medford, which had slaves since the area was settled by British
colonists in the 1630s, has not escaped the now predictable strife
that follows discussions of slavery's place in local history. For
the past several years, some in the city have fiercely debated the
merits of a Depression-era mural in the post office that depicts a
black slave laboring in shackles. And about a decade ago, there was
also discussion about pulling down the slave quarters at the Royall
House.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, it seems, the city's historic
preservationists, political leaders, and community leaders appear
to agree: the Slave Wall should get its due.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Victorian houses, but there's only one
Slave Wall,'' said Thomas Lincoln, head of the Medford-Brooks State
Land Trust, the city-owned property where the wall stands. The
wall, he said, ``is a reminder that slavery is part of Medford's
history, that we hope we're doing better, and that we've hopefully
learned some lessons. It's not celebrating slavery. It's
celebrating the fortitude of slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Michael J. McGlynn said he has yet to hear from Goncalves
or others, but said that creating a permanent slave memorial at the
wall was ``a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should stand as a monument for what should never happen
again,'' McGlynn said. ``You have to bring these things up front,
you have to let people discuss it, then take direction from the
community at large to see what they want to preserve. . . . But you
can't bury history, no matter how bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to make the wall a monument come at a time when
Medford's connections to slavery are under more scrutiny than ever,
said Griffin, the historical society head and a Medford High School
history teacher who lives with his family in the Royall House slave
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a team of Boston University archaelogists conducted
a dig at the Royall House to try to better understand the lives of
the 27 slaves who lived there. And currently, a team of Tufts
University scholars are busy preserving 19 letters owned by the
Medford Historical Society penned by 18th century slave ship
captains from the area.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Gittleman, president of the Royall House Association and
director of interpretation and education at the Society for the
Preservation of New England Antiquities in Boston, said he finds
the new focus on slavery important and refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do much more to explore and interpret that
history,'' Gittleman said, adding that he hopes to convert the
slave quarters into an educational center about slavery in New
England. ``We don't want to wait until we have it perfect. We want
to start right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For Goncalves, a program director for a social service center in
East Boston, the Slave Wall stands out as the most important
restoration project in Medford. Its obscurity and bad condition,
she says, is an affront to all of the African-American slaves of
the area, and it should shoot to the top of the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't find landmarks like that every day,'' Goncalves
said. ``It deserves recognition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
