r d BC-PASTA-HNS &LR;      04-14 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRESTO! QUICK PASTA DISHES STILL NEED WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Welcome to presto pasta.
</P>
<P>
   We called our latest taste test the three-minute showdown.
</P>
<P>
   From the shopping bag to the table in five minutes, tops.
Prepared at home, too.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, we're not talking gourmet dining. More like school
cafeteria eats. But our goal was not four-star (or three, or two)
cuisine. It was convenience and comparison. An old standby vs. a
brand-new product, two corporate giants going head to head.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner, Franco-American Spaghetti in Tomato Sauce with
Cheese. Pasta in a can. Open, put it in a bowl with a lid or cover
and microwave for 4 minutes (for a 26-ounce container). The
Campbell Soup Co. item has been a supermarket staple since before
the invention of the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   In the other corner, Classico It's Pasta Anytime. Pre-cooked
spaghetti and sauce in a microwave container. Peel top film off,
pour pasta into tray, pour sauce around edges, lay film back across
top and zap for three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It's Pasta Anytime is new, first available in early March.
Albany, N.Y., five other Northeast metropolitan areas and Denver
are test-market sites. The non-refrigerated product is not
scheduled to go national until June. You'll find this Borden Co.
offering on the same shelves as boxes of dry pastas.
</P>
<P>
   We recruited six eager lunch eaters to sample the two side by
side, not knowing what they were about to eat.
</P>
<P>
   The winner: It's Pasta Anytime. Which might just prove that you
get what you pay for, because It's Pasta Anytime is five times more
expensive than its Franco-American counterpart, 16 cents an ounce
vs. a mere 3 cents per ounce. The suggested retail price for a
15-ounce package of It's Pasta Anytime is $2.99 while a 26-ounce
can of Franco-American costs 84 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of our six samplers preferred Franco-American to It's
Pasta Anytime. She particularly liked the appearance of
Franco-American, giving it an 8 grade (out of 10) compared with a 2
for It's Pasta Anytime (which she said looks ``like spaghetti in
tomato soup.'')
</P>
<P>
   The final question in our taste test was: ``I'd buy this one,''
with a chance to check either dish. The woman who graded
Franco-American higher said she would buy It's Pasta Anytime for
her children, Franco-American for herself.
</P>
<P>
   However, the yellow-orange color of the sauce that comes out of
the Franco-American can was off-putting to a majority of our
tasters. Two of the six tasters likened it, appropriately enough,
to Chef Boyardee, another Campbell's product. Needless to say, this
comparison was not intended as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, It's Pasta Anytime received a number of
favorable comments for its appearance. ``Like it could be
homemade,'' wrote two of our panelists, while another said ``looks
like spaghetti in a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   As for taste, those who preferred Pasta Anytime said ``Like
regular pasta, some interesting spices even. Not overly gooey with
sauce,'' and ``sweetish, with more of a sun-dried tomato flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to nutritional content and the actual
ingredients in these two products.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these presto pasta dishes would receive high praise
from a dietitian. Both are made with far more salt (37 percent of
the daily value of sodium in a serving of It's Pasta Anytime, 43
percent in Franco-American) and sugar (18 grams for It's Pasta
Anytime, 14 grams for Franco-American) than a tomato sauce I would
make at home in less than a half hour.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains why two of our six tasters claimed they
would buy neither dish. Said one of these diners about Pasta
Anytime: ``Sour and tangy, but has some tomato flavor.'' Another of
our tasters, commenting on Franco-American, said, ``Like flour
that's not quite cooked and vaguely salty and tomatoey goo.''
</P>
<P>
   While neither presto pasta dish received rave reviews, it should
be noted that both lived up to their billing in terms of
preparation time. Both were out of the bag, into the microwave and
on the table in five minutes or less.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America has at least mastered the presto part of this
experiment. Now it's time to concentrate on improving the pasta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
