<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6826 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RADKE-BOS &LR;      04-14 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RADKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE TALK CONTINUES TO SWIRL AROUND RADKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Even before he trotted in from the visiting bullpen,
the Fenway Park crowd began talking up a Red Sox trade for
Minnesota righthander Brad Radke. The low-budget, cost-conscious
Twins are likely to make him available before season's end.
</P>
<P>
   The question is at what price? And do the Red Sox feel a
pressing need to add a pitcher to the rotation while taking another
hit to the farm system?
</P>
<P>
   Radke got a no-decision Thursday night, yielding three runs on
six hits in 6 2/3 innings for his best outing in three starts this
season. Outings like that are good enough to draw interest from
potential playoff teams, even though Radke will be a free agent
after this season.
</P>
<P>
   With a hard sinker and tantalizing changeup, Radke is a bargain
this year with a $3.2 million salary. But there is no guarantee a
trade will come now, or when the trading deadline approaches this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered,'' Radke said of the interest he has drawn.
``But you don't carry that out to the mound. You have to stay
focused to get guys out. I thought I did a pretty good job of that
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked about it in every city thus far. But it's no big
deal. I'm under contract until the end of this season. I have an
obligation to do my best for these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have never been shy about tracking pitching talent
and would love to have a Radke around if the price is right. But
there is more than money and statistics to evaluate, said general
manager Dan Duquette. In April, you look at your own talent first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some starters who should be able to do a decent
job,'' said Duquette. ``We'd like to look at them before we have to
give up half our farm system for another pitcher. We have to
explore those items, too. Let's say a Bret Saberhagen comes back
and these other guys we have out there are pitching good. That's a
pretty good rotation. Maybe Rod Beck will come back and help our
bullpen situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an ace. Hopefully, we can get a No. 2 situation out of
Ramon Martinez or Saberhagen. A lot of things can happen between
now and the closing months of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're talking pitchers or position players, the Red Sox
want to maintain a strong flow from the farm system. Pitching depth
is essential, so a solid pitcher like Radke can expect to at least
double his annual pay on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   A strong farm system is important not only to fill your own
lineup, but to have talent to deal for established veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody around here complained when Boston gave up two pitching
prospects, Carl Pavano and Tony Armas Jr., to Montreal for Pedro
Martinez. But until Carl Everett won over the Fenway Faithful with
his fast start, there was some grumbling about giving hot shot
shortstop prospect Adam Everett to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Where are the home-grown pitchers? Brian Rose, a second-round
draft choice, will pitch tonight. But gone are can't-miss prospects
like Frankie Rodriguez (drafted in 1990, now with Seattle), Aaron
Sele (1991, also in Seattle), and Jeff Suppan 1993, Kansas City).
In the last two years, the Sox have traded more than a half-dozen
minor league pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Replacements are coming. The ballyhooed pitching prospects this
spring were Koreans Sun-Woo Kim, Sang Lee, and Jin Ho Cho, and
Tomokazu Ohka of Japan. Cho is injured, the rest are in Pawtucket.
Not to be forgotten is righthander Juan Pena, who suffered a torn
ligament in his right elbow in spring training and is out for the
season. Whether and when the Asian contingent contributes remains
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   So where might Radke fit in with the Sox?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful,'' said Duquette. ``You build up your
system and will use some of those players and trade some of them.
But there is a strategy to what we do. It was a trade that brought
Pedro here. We gave up value for value.''
</P>
<P>
   Trades are made to help the entire organization, added assistant
general manager Ed Kenney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's movement is not like a Jeff Bagwell-for-Larry Andersen
trade we made back in 1990,'' he said. ``You have to consider
everything. The game has changed because of the wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a big difference. People talk positively about the
Red Sox because they made the playoffs two consecutive years. Well,
the only reason they were able to do so was because of the wild
card. You have so many opportunities. There will be years in which
you've got a chance to win the whole thing. If that is the case,
you've got to trade a prospect to get that starting pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams are still calling about Dernell Stenson and Donnie Sadler.
They've called about Wilton Veras, but he's on duty at third base
these days, replacing the injured John Valentin. There are others
in the lower minors who find scouts charting their every move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely unfair the way the system works now,'' said
Twins manager Tom Kelly. ``You get a good young player, develop
him, and then see his success spoil what he's trying to accomplish.
(Radke's) the only player people want to talk to. Everything is on
his shoulders but all we've ever asked him to do is go out and give
us a chance to win the ballgame. He did that tonight. That's all we
can ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a chance he will stay in Minnesota. He likes it
there. But he doesn't want to talk contract with anybody until the
season ends.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have to find out about Pete Schourek, whose pitching
line was strikingly similar to Radke's (6 2/3 innings, 6 hits, 3
runs, 2 earned), and Saberhagen, Duquette said. If both do well,
the Sox might never have to consider a trade for a Radke. By July
or September, somebody else may be a better fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have time to wait and see what happens,'' said Duquette.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
