<HEADER>
A6830 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-BELICHICK-2     04-14 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BELICHICK-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 FOXBOROUGH, Mass.: ... and speed.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can also count on Belichick drafting several defensive and
offensive linemen in nearly every draft. In addition, he'll sign
several more linemen as free agent rookies, something he had
stunning success with in Cleveland with the likes of Orlando Brown
and Wally Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Although Belichick and Lombardi did not have great success
drafting in later rounds, they did have success when the scramble
was on for free agent rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always takes a couple of defensive linemen,'' said one NFL
personnel man familiar with Belichick's past drafts. ``You can't
find them so he's going to pick one or two every year and try to
develop them. He believes it takes two years to develop those young
linemen and he has a program to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to pick offensive linemen early (although he
took Everitt in the first round and King in the second) very often
because he believes if a guy is taken on the fourth round or sooner
he has to play and a lot of these guys aren't ready to play for
several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick began looking for developmental players as free agents
in Cleveland beginning in 1993 and admits he began to have his
organization concentrate a bit too much on that area and not enough
on the draft's fourth through seventh rounds. This time around he
will try to balance the two, knowing the rookie free agent route is
something his system of evaluation and player development already
has proven works well for him and his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned how to do that,'' Belichick said. ``We learned how
to identify developmental players and bring them along.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belichick almost always stands by his draft board's ratings
unless there is an overwhelming need to fill. If a bunch of players
are graded about the same, he might take the one that fills his
biggest priority. But if one player's grade is substantially better
than the others on the board, the decision is made not by Belichick
but by the evaluation system he has in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do whatever you can to improve your team so if you have a
severe need you draft the guy, especially if it appears there's no
one else who will be there later who can help,'' Belichick said.
``Otherwise, you take the higher rated guy if you can live with
what you've got at other positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't generally reach too far (down the board). You spend
a lot of money to scout these players so why would you pass 20 guys
you've rated ahead of somebody to take him? What are we evaluating
them for if we do that?''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the one thing Belichick will surely be is
prepared. He and his staff will not make the Warren Sapp mistake
again. They will be what he will ask his team to be next fall. They
will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is preparation,'' Belichick said. ``You have to
be sure you know all the players on the board and what they can do
for your team. I ask my scouts before we take someone `Is he a
potential starter? Is he a special teams player? What exactly can
the guy do for our team?' I don't care what he can do for somebody
else. What can he do for the New England Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take somebody and the scouts tell me he should be a
certain type player and it turns out otherwise, then they're
accountable. I ask them, `What were you looking at?' That's the
accountability side of it. If I elect not to use a guy in the role
they said he'd fill, that's a different issue. Then it's my fault
if he's not successful. So the main thing before we take a guy is
knowing what we're going to ask him to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drafting is far from an exact science. A lot of these players
are far different two years after they've been in the league then
they are coming out of college. They're often not the same player
at all. You have to be able to project that.''
</P>
<P>
   As he learned in Cleveland though, you also have to be able to
restrain yourself from projecting something else too often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the signs are there that a player has been
unproductive because that's who he is, but you see something you
like and it's gold dust,'' Belichick said. ``What I learned in
Cleveland is it usually turns out just to be dust. That's why, with
the exception of linemen who I believe develop more in their first
two years in the league than most other players, I prefer to take
players who were productive over a long period of time in college.
You can't base everything on production, but it counts for a lot.
Hopefully I have a better handle on that aspect of drafting this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   That and perhaps on the phone handles if something goes wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
