<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-USOC-BLAKE-BOS &LR;      04-14 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-USOC-BLAKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE ADDS GREEN TO THE OLYMPIC MEDAL MIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ His language comes not from Olympus but from the
boardroom. ``Value-added.'' ``Portfolio management.'' ``Resource
allocation process.'' ``Brands and franchises.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Blake is a businessman and he made his money and his
reputation as a turnaround artist, taking over troubled companies
like USF&AMP;G and making them profitable.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the company is the non-profit US Olympic Committee,
which was ripe for a shakeup even before last year's Salt Lake City
payoff scandal. And during his first two months as the USOC's first
chief executive officer, the 58-year-old Blake has been driving
home his bottom-line agenda: Less bureaucracy, more accountability,
and more medals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone recognized that something needed to be
done,'' Blake said in a wide-ranging interview Thursday on the eve
of the USOC meetings at the Westin Copley Place. ``I believe I was
brought in as a mandate for change. We're looking at a fundamental
transformation of the USOC in virtually every respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake has been streamlining and ``flattening'' the USOC's
unwieldy corporate structure, bringing in his own top staffers and
preparing to lay off as many as 70 of the committee's 500
employees. He's undertaken an unprecedented top-to-bottom review of
each of the 45 national sports governing bodies, from archery to
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   And now Blake will ask the executive board to put the USOC's
money where the medals are, taking funding away from sports that
don't produce at the Games and giving it to those that do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine the American people getting excited about us
finishing fifth at the Olympics,'' Blake said. ``They expect us to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   While Blake's bottom-line approach is routine in America's
boardrooms, it's revolutionary among Olympic purists, who believe
founder Baron Pierre de Coubertin's credo that the most important
thing about the Games is not winning, but taking part.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who say that just being at the Games is
enough,'' said Blake. ``I'm saying, it's being there and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   National governing bodies for some sports, such as those of
track and field, swimming, and figure skating, are medal machines
that crank out gold, silver, and bronze quadrennium after
quadrennium. Others, like biathlon, team handball, and men's
weightlifting, haven't been near the award stand in years.
</P>
<P>
   If the USOC was a Fortune 500 company, it would sell off its
non-performing units or shut them down. The USOC can't do that, but
it will impose what Blake calls ``business discipline'' on NGBs
that spend millions of dollars to finish 49th. ``Eighty percent of
our funding was going out without any strings attached,'' said
Blake.
</P>
<P>
   With this summer's Games in Sydney only five months away and the
USOC's $160 million in grants already awarded, it's too late to
rework the deal. ``Any standing commitments we have, we will
honor,'' Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Blake gets his way, future funding will depend on
performance and potential. Sports that always win medals will get
what they need. ``Like synchronized swimming,'' Blake said. ``We'll
want to protect those medals.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports that could produce multiple medals, like rowing and
canoe-kayak, probably will get strings-attached cash. Sports that
have never won medals, probably never will, and have little
following among American fans (like men's field hockey) probably
will see their funding chopped. ``We won't let a small-size NGB
fail,'' said Blake. ``But they'll have to do more for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   That's merely Business 101 for any profit-and-loss outfit but
it's radical thinking for the NGBs, which have grown used to
cashing USOC checks with few questions asked. Blake has already
gotten several outraged earfuls about the money-for-medals approach
(``It's still a sell job,'' he conceded), so he's not expecting an
all-in-favor rubber stamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like trying to get a resolution through the United
Nations,'' Blake said. ``You have to appeal to the greater good.''
</P>
<P>
   That's always been a challenge with the USOC, an ``organization
of organizations'' that includes everybody from USA Basketball to
the Catholic Youth Organization to the Dwarf Athletic Association
of America and which makes Balkan politics seem simple by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC has always been about fiefdoms jostling with other
fiefdoms and jealously guarding their turf. Few of them agree on
anything and most don't consider winning Olympic medals as their
primary mission. ``You have some entrenched volunteer leaders that
love the limelight of being volunteer leaders,'' Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   And some of them will be howling into open microphones when the
full board meets this weekend. ``There have been some noses out of
joint,'' Blake admitted. But the old USOC, which used to be little
more than a quadrennial travel agency, is dead. The structural
reforms voted through in February made sure of that.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC president is now a board chairman. Blake has all the
day-to-day power and he hasn't been bashful about using it. When he
says ``fundamental transformation,'' he's not just rearranging
boxes on a flow chart.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Blake spent more than three hours running his 30-page
plan by the USOC's transition committee. ``What I found most
reassuring,'' he said, ``was that everybody recognized there's an
opportunity to do better than we have. If that was any indication,
I think we can come out of today's meeting with an agreement in
principle.''
</P>
<P>
   Even that much would be a radical breakthrough for the USOC,
which has traditionally downplayed the medal chase as the central
part of the Olympic experience.
</P>
<P>
   If Blake gets that agreement, the NGBs will enter an unfamiliar
_ and unsettling _ world of business plans, fiscal accountability,
and a bottom line measured in precious metal. De Coubertin didn't
calculate that way, but Blake is a CEO managing a turnaround. ``I
never enter a fight,'' he says, ``unless I think I can win it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
