<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-IMF-PROTESTS-BOS &LR;      04-14 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-PROTESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS CLAIM IMF DOES WORLD MORE HARM THAN GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The front page no longer carries daily news of the
Thai baht, the Indonesian rupiah, and other arcane currencies.
Southeast Asia is out of recession and growing once again. Amid
American prosperity, it can be hard to remember that only two years
ago the world faced the very real prospect of a global financial
meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   And yet this weekend, protesters will gather outside the offices
of the agency that led efforts to stop the crisis _ the
International Monetary Fund. Many believe the IMF does more harm
than good in the world, and they are willing to be arrested to make
their point.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters have a range of complaints. They say loans by the
IMF come with conditions that free up money for debt service by
cutting government investment in schools, health programs, and food
subsidies. They say some loans by the IMF and its sister agency,
the World Bank, encourage development that harms the environment.
They claim IMF programs lead to increased poverty, and debts held
by the poorest nations should be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters also take issue with the way the IMF handled the
Asian crisis, which was one of the most significant economic events
of recent times and one of the most important challenges in the
IMF's history. Even some prominent economists say the protesters
have a point; however, there is no consensus on why this startling
disruption in the economy began, or on whether the IMF's efforts to
stop it actually worked.
</P>
<P>
   How the debate sorts out could affect the world's response to
the next crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The fingerpointing starts with the cause of the Asian crisis,
which began in July 1997, when Thailand devalued its currency. That
helped spark currency and stock crashes in Indonesia and other
neighbors, including Korea, the world's 11th-largest economy.
Financial markets around the world became more jittery as the
crisis spread to Brazil. Then it hit Russia, whose nuclear arsenal
added a scary element to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Why did it all begin? One school blames Asia itself and its
``crony capitalism,'' or the clubby relationships between
governments, banks and corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Thai real estate speculators were allowed to overbuild without
proper scrutiny of their books, this argument goes. The Korean
government wanted to become a world force in such industries as
shipbuilding and semiconductors, so it guided loans from foreign
banks into the giant Korean industrial conglomerates to build
factory capacity. When the market became glutted with chips, ships,
and capacity, the factories failed, which bankrupted companies and
stressed any local banks that had loaned them money.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF itself makes this argument in oblique language, blaming
the crisis on ``weaknesses in financial systems,'' ``governance,''
and ``government involvement in the private sector and lack of
transparency in corporate and fiscal accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Stiglitz, the Stanford economics professor who was
chief economist at the World Bank during the crisis, says ``crony
capitalism'' cannot have been the cause. ``These countries had
three decades of the most impressive growth of anywhere in the
world,'' he said in an interview, ``and they were getting less
secretive, more transparent, more independent in their banking
systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiglitz points the finger not at Asia, but at the IMF and the
United States. They pushed Asian nations to liberalize their
capital rules in the last two decades so foreigners could invest
more easily in Asian businesses.
</P>
<P>
   This ``hot capital'' fueled the real estate boom in Thailand, he
argued, and the new rules allowed the money to flow out at the
first signs of trouble. Ironically, he said, Thailand and Korea did
not want to open the doors to fickle investors, and they did so
only under IMF and US pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if you ask the question, `What changed in Asia in the
1990s?' the answer was capital- and financial-market
liberalization,'' Stiglitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Equally contentious is the IMF prescription for how to solve the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF touchstones were currency reserves, government spending,
and interest rates. By maintaining a reserve of dollars, yen, or
deutsche marks, a country can buy its local currency and maintain
its value. But the troubled Asian currencies fell so steeply that
nations quickly ran out of reserves. As the local currencies sank,
companies that had borrowed money overseas found themselves having
to pay dollar-denominated loans with baht and rupiah that were
worth less and less.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF arranged cash infusions for these nations, in part to
help them defend the currencies. More than $36 billion went to
Korea, Indonesia, and Thailand alone, which grew to $118 billion as
other agencies and individual nations chipped in.
</P>
<P>
   But in return for the loans, the IMF asked borrowers to take
steps designed to induce investors to send their money back to
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   These steps included raising interest rates and cutting
government spending, attempts to give investors a high return on
their money and assure them inflation would not eat away their
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF also forced some nations to close their most troubled
banks, a step designed to force the banking system to acknowledge
bad loans on its books and to end ``crony capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   But these measures exacted a heavy price, the critics say. ``I
was shocked by the closure of 16 banks in Indonesia when there was
no deposit insurance there,'' said Jeffrey Sachs, an economic
adviser to foreign governments and director of the Harvard
University Center for International Development. ``Lo and behold,
as anyone with some sense and experience would know, it led to a
banking crisis and helped trigger a full-fledged panic.''
</P>
<P>
   By ordering nations to hike interest rates, the IMF drove
troubled companies out of business and boosted unemployment,
critics say. And cutting government spending also put people out of
work and slowed the economy further. The IMF's prescription became
dangerous in places like Indonesia, the critics say, as the
recession caused riots and attacks on the ethnic Chinese minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot address the issue of restoring confidence just by
focusing on interest rates or deficits,'' Stiglitz said. ``You have
to have a broader perspective. The riots did more to damage
confidence (in Indonesia) than anything that could have been done
to the trade balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiglitz and Sachs said the IMF should have allowed governments
to boost spending so people continued to work and spend money,
which would have minimized social tensions.
</P>
<P>
   They say the IMF was correct to push Western banks to roll over
their loans to Asian banks and companies, but the IMF should not
have forced nations to restructure their financial sectors. While
``crony capitalism'' may be undesirable, solving it is beyond the
IMF's mission.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Asian economies are no longer in recession, though
they are not back to the robust health they enjoyed before the
crisis. Sidney Weintraub of the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, a Washington think tank, says the rebound
validates most of the IMF approach. But critics like Sachs say the
rebound is due to foreign investors returning to Southeast Asia,
which happened only because foreign banks rolled over their loans
to Asian banks and companies.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the debate, many economists say there is general but not
universal agreement the crisis taught several lessons.
</P>
<P>
   One is that countries should not be forced to cut budgets in the
middle of a financial crisis, as the social cost is too high, said
Robert Litan, director of economic studies at the Brookings
Institution, who is not a particularly harsh critic of the IMF.
Even some IMF officials back this view, though it is uncertain how
it would guide them in a future crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson is that fixed exchange rates are a mistake, Litan
said. Several Southeast Asian nations pegged their currency to the
US dollar in the late 1980s and early 1990s, Litan said. That
helped keep inflation in check and gave exporters certainty amid
the volatile international currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   But fixed rates force countries to spend reserves at times to
prop up the value of a local currency and maintain the peg to the
dollar, a burden some countries cannot bear.
</P>
<P>
   Fixed exchange rates also encourage investors to borrow in
dollars and lend in the local currency, as they believe there is
little risk of having to repay the loans in baht or rupiah that
have lost value, Litan said. When a nation abandons its fixed
exchange rate, these investors quickly pull their money from the
country and try to repay their dollar loans, which can spark a
currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
   More controversial is whether countries should limit their
exposure to foreign investors. Litan said many economists now
believe that, for some countries, it makes sense to bar short-term
investments and to require anyone investing in a business to keep
the money there for a certain period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we recognize today that short-term capital flows can
be highly destabilizing,'' Stiglitz said. ``I'd say there's general
consensus on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6835 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-YEMEN-HOLLYWOOD-BOS &LR;      04-14 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YEMEN-HOLLYWOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEMENESE INCENSED   OVER IMAGE PORTRAYED BY `RULES' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A key scene in America's current No. 1 box office
hit, ``Rules of Engagement,'' shows an angry mob outside the US
Embassy in Yemen. US Marines scamper on the roof. One falls dead.
</P>
<P>
   In the instant before a Marine colonel, played by Samuel L.
Jackson, orders his men to fire into the crowd, he looks at the mob
and sees Yemenite women and boys and girls firing rifles at them.
</P>
<P>
   As the scene unfolded in a Washington movie theater Thursday,
Yemen's ambassador to the United States, Abdulwahab Al-Hajjri,
cringed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little girl shooting at Marines! Can you believe it?''
Al-Hajjri said. ``This movie reaches millions of people. It's a
total ruin for us. It ruins our image. Why Yemen? Even if we launch
a public campaign, how do you fight Hollywood?''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount Picture's portrayal of Arabs isn't drawing the ire of
just Yemenis. Hussein Ibish, spokesman for the American Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee, Thursday said that ``Rules of
Engagement'' was ``probably the most racist film ever made against
Arabs by Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It can only be compared to films like the ``Birth of a
Nation'' and ``The Eternal Jew'' in so far as the principled
purpose seems to be the demonization and vilification of an entire
people,'' Ibish said. ``There aren't any positive images of Arabs
in that movie. Instead, there is an explosion of hatred.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Paramount Pictures said: ```Rules of
Engagement' is a dramatization and a fictional account of the
consequences of extremism in all its forms. The film is not an
indictment of any government, culture or people. Rather, it
explores the human tragedy and consequences that can result when
people of any society are put in extreme situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount did not respond to a question from the Boston Globe on
why it decided to identify a country, and why it chose Yemen in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which was released April 7 and earned $15 million
last weekend, is about upholding Marine honor in the line of fire.
The story involves an evacuation of the US ambassador to Yemen in
Sana'a under sniper fire, the Marines' return of fire that kills 83
Yemenites and court-martial proceedings of the colonel for ordering
the shooting into the crowd. Tommy Lee Jones also stars in the
film.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's negative portrayals of Arabs has long been a point
of contention among Arab-Americans, many of whom believe it fuels
the malacious image of Arabs as terrorists. The Arab
Anti-Discrimination group has sharply criticized several other
recent movies, including ``The Siege'' and ``True Lies,'' while
finding only one film, ``The 13th Warrior,'' portraying a major
Arab character in good light.
</P>
<P>
   Ibish predicted ``Rules of Engagement'' will spark
demonstrations in coming weeks in several cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even stooped to portraying Arab children _ even paralyzed
little girls _ as hateful, vicious anti-American fanatics,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But for Ambassador Al-Hajjri, the problem also includes his
country's image. For many Americans, the fictitious film will be
their first exposure to Yemen _ even though the film was shot at
the other end of the Arab world, in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of Yemen, population 16 million, desperately poor,
sitting on the southeastern tip of the Arabian peninsula, is that
it may be a traveler's last window into the all-but-disappeared
Arab world of ``The Thousand and One Nights.'' Sana'a boasts some
of world's most beautiful architecture, with many of its houses
built in the 1600s.
</P>
<P>
   Yemen also is not on the US State Department's list of countries
sponsoring terrorism, and there have been no anti-American protests
there recently. But the country is well-known for its spate of
hostage-taking. Tribes often take travelers as hostages and release
them unharmed, although four hostages were killed in one incident
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens rarely,'' Al-Hajjri said. ``It's a bad thing, but
we hear of worse things all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Hajjri, 40, who received a master's degree in law from
American University, has tried to build Yemen's reputation in his 2
1/2 years in Washington. He has invited hundreds of high school and
college students to his embassy. He has raised his country's
profile in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie, he fears, could be a huge setback in public
perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a friend going to Yemen, and his mother just called
him, saying she was worried about him going now,'' the ambassador
said. ``I think what I'll do is invite the producer and all the
stars to Yemen so they can see for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador saw the movie for a second time Thursday so that
he could read the fine print at the end of the film.
</P>
<P>
   As the movie showed the street scene outside the fictional US
embassy, Al-Hajjri blurted out, ``This is not Yemen! This is
Morocco!''
</P>
<P>
   With each scene, he kept muttering, ``This is completely
unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, mercifully for him, the movie ended, and he stayed in
his seat as the rest of the moviegoers filed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's here to see the last line _ that it's all fiction,''
he said, looking around at the empty moviehouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
