<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV1     04-14 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 16, 2000)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My mouse problem may not be unique, but it sure is driving me
up the wall. I think the mice are coming in a gap where the siding
meets the foundation. Then they get between the suspended basement
ceiling and the floorboards above. They skitter-skatter on the
ceiling and that is what is bugging me. How can I get rid of them
and keep them out?
</P>
<P>
   A.M., Westford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Get a cat or two and have them live in the basement. They
certainly would be a deterrent, but if the mice stay in the ceiling
space, they may not make much of a difference. You will have a lot
of nervous mice. Or, take the ceiling down.
</P>
<P>
   OK, seriously, here is what to do. You can use traps or D-Con,
the poison that makes them seek water and forces them outdoors,
where they die. This generally happens, but there is no guarantee
that some won't die in the ceiling space. Lift some of the panels
and place the D-Con on the ceiling in strategic places. If you
don't like the idea of D-Con, you can use the snap traps (messy and
slow, but effective) or sticky traps (cruel, slow, and effective).
</P>
<P>
   Those are the ways to get rid of mice.
</P>
<P>
   To keep them away, seal the house. To check the suspected
entries between siding and foundation, take off some ceiling panels
near the foundation, turn off all the lights, and see if you see
daylight through that joint. If you do, you have big gaps to fill.
If you don't, you still may have gaps that are big enough to allow
mice in, and they too must be filled. Those gaps don't have to be
large; a mouse can go through a hole the size of a dime.
</P>
<P>
   It is easiest to fill the gaps from outside; simply insert oakum
or a rope-like caulking into the gap, filling it completely. For
bigger spaces, stuff steel wool into the hole. But instead of using
steel wool, use something called Stuffit, a copper wool or gauze,
that will not rust. It is called Stuffit, from Allen Special
Products (800-848-6805) or Creative Expressions (316-788-6290).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My house is 50 years old with aluminum siding, a brick front
on the first floor, and with insulation blown in 25 years ago,
which I think has settled. What can I do about those gaps where the
insulation has settled, especially in light of that brick front and
aluminum siding?
</P>
<P>
   GENEVIEVE McCULLOCH, Roslindale, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, check to see how much the insulation has settled. The
only way to do that is to cut holes in the inside walls near the
ceiling, and make a visual and probing check. You may be surprised
that the gaps are minimal, just a few inches, and you can cut the
wall finish, put in fiberglass, and recover the wall. You could do
this yourself, even if the gaps are bigger, maybe 12 inches. Or,
have cellulose blown in. Find an insulator in the Yellow Pages who
will do this relatively small but highly fussy job for a reasonable
fee.
</P>
<P>
   Your biggest project if you do it yourself or if you have it
done is filling the holes you made to get at the wall cavity.
Insulators are not very good hole fillers, and you may have to
improve on their work. But given time, you can make invisible
patches.
</P>
<P>
   If the walls are papered, you can do this: Wet the paper
slightly and try to pull down a foot or so of paper; let it hang in
place. After you do your project, and fill holes or put on a new
plasterboard, you can repaste the paper and no one, not even you,
will be able to tell the difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I hired a roofer to reroof my house, but I am still waiting
for him to show up. And now it's winter. Is it safe to reroof in
winter?
</P>
<P>
   JOHN LEACH, Sandwich, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. Roofing or reroofing can be done any time of the year,
as long as it is not deluging, snowing up a storm, or is 15 or 20
degrees, or colder. I remember when I had my roof stripped of
shingles nearly 30 years ago, the November day they started it
snowed. Not a lot, but enough to cover the roof.
</P>
<P>
   I panicked, and asked, ``What are you going to do?'' ``We're
going to sweep off the snow and get to work,'' the roofer replied.
They did just that and the shingles lasted 25 years, five years
beyond their warranty.
</P>
<P>
   So, rest easily in winter. One of the reasons roofers are
reluctant to work in very cold weather is that fiberglass shingles
(the most popular of roof shingles) are very brittle, and more
brittle in cold weather, and are difficult to store, handle, and
install. For this reason, I think organic shingles (those with a
felt core instead of fiberglass) are better to use. They are still
made and your roofer can get them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our electric dryer now exhausts into our old cellar. We plan
to put in one that will exhaust outdoors, but in the meantime can
we put a lint catcher at the end of the duct that is there now?
</P>
<P>
   H.M., Milton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, but clean it out every day, or every time you use the
dryer. A lint catcher like that can block the duct, and could cause
a fire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
