<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOOD SAMARITAN PLANS TO WALK, DANCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL DeMARE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dean L. Johnson remembers the instant he was
struck by a tractor-trailer rig on the New York Thruway while
trying to aid a stranded motorist during a recent snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old soldier's Army instincts took over when both
legs were severed below the knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medic, medic,'' Johnson cried as other motorists rushed to
help him. He then instructed them on how to use a belt as a
tourniquet to stop the bleeding in his legs. The motorists kept him
warm until paramedics arrived.
</P>
<P>
   With high spirits and a vow to run, ride his bike and dance
again, Johnson talked about the incident for the first time
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Without hesitation, he said he didn't regret pulling over to
help because there was a small child in the stranded car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do the right thing,'' Johnson said during a news
conference at the Albany Medical Center Hospital. `'I saw these
people and they had a kid, and I at least had to give them a
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who holds the rank of specialist 4, returned from
Bosnia in early March. He was headed back to Fort Drum near
Watertown on Sunday when he was struck about 3:40 p.m. by a
tractor-trailer unable to stop on the slick highway. The truck
clipped the soldier as he attempted to dive into the median area
out of its path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember running or diving,'' he said. `'All I
remember was I took two steps, and I was airborne.'' He said the
truck jackknifed and he got hit by the trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and my legs were gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope for the future is just to be able to walk again, and
after that everything is gravy,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier is deemed an excellent candidate for prosthesis
because of his good health, his age and the fact the legs were
severed below the knees, said Jeffrey Schoenig, the registered
nurse attending Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ``overwhelming'' extent of the injuries and the
shock, Schoenig said he advised Johnson to take ``one step at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me `I don't want small steps, I want big steps,'''
Schoenig said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is expected to be transferred to Walter Reed Army
Hospital in Washington on Monday where he will remain until well
enough to return home to Warwick, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   His family has a ``big 4th of July bash, and I want to be able
to walk into that,'' he said. He expects to leave the Army and
enter college to possibly pursue a career as a teacher. He has
$40,000 toward his tuition, a bonus from the Army when he enlisted
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wasn't always as upbeat about his future as he was on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got hit, I was ready to give up, but I love my
family too much,'' he said. His mother, Deena Phillips and paternal
grandmother, Joan Johnson, were at his side during the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to describe her son, Phillips said, ``This is what you
see, right here. We are very proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is a radio operator assigned to Company B of the 10th
Signal Battalion for the 10th Mountain Division, Light Infantry.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John Batson and 1st Sgt. Don Sarringer, both from his
company, were among the soldiers from Fort Drum who visited him
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's well liked by the other soldiers in the unit,'' said
Batson, his company commander. ``He's a very competent soldier and
is good at his job.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been flooded with cards and phone calls from
strangers wishing him well.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers who patrol the Thruway have also visited, and Johnson
was wearing a Troop T cap Thursday, a gift from the New York State
Police.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier's 1996 Chevrolet pickup was totaled. His glasses
also were smashed, but troopers brought him a new pair after they
found an eyeglass prescription in his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had visited his family in Rhode Island over the weekend
and was en route to base when he saw the stranded motorist on the
Thruway near the Taconic Parkway interchange in Columbia County.
</P>
<P>
   The car had spun out and was sideways across the lanes. Johnson
said he later learned it had broken its rear axle.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the car told Johnson, who had stopped in the
passing lane, that troopers were on their way, but before the good
Samaritan could drive off, he saw out his rear-view mirror that a
tractor-trailer was rounding a curve and wasn't going to be able to
stop. Instinctively, he jumped out of the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has not heard from the truck driver, nor the family he
stopped to help. The trucker, Harold E. Feltt, 57, of Rock City
Falls, N.Y., was ticketed for driving at an imprudent speed, having
faulty windshield wipers and failure to keep a log book, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The child in the car, Johnson later learned, was 4 years old and
was with grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been too selfish not to stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While he knows he has a long road ahead of him, Johnson said he
was prepared to fight once he was hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a good outlook on life,'' he said. He thought of his
family, and ``I didn't want to die by the road somewhere.''
</P>
</TEXT>
