<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN'T STOP GLOBALIZAION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 16)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I never met Charlene Barshefsky but I'm sure I know her.
</P>
<P>
   She was the smartest girl in high school. Knew all the answers.
Didn't try to hide it. Talked to everybody in the same slow,
measured,
I'm-only-going-to-say-this-once-so-you-better-get-it-the-first-time
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Never lost her cool. Didn't have to. She was always the smartest
one in the room, and she allowed time for the rest of us to catch
up. Now she's doing the same kind of thing, only on the world
stage.
</P>
<P>
   As the Clinton administration's lead dog on trade, the 49-year
old lawyer has rocketed around the planet, wheeling, dealing,
wheedling, needling, giving here, holding out there, clinging to
the slippery back of the globalization tiger.
</P>
<P>
   She may be Clinton's best appointment, though most Americans
couldn't pick her out of a lineup. Over the past five years, US
exports went up 50 percent, and while the world economy is too
massive a peak to be responsive to any one individual's will, she's
one of the most important folks on the planet when it comes to
buying, selling, shipping and consuming stuff.
</P>
<P>
   When 50,000 demonstrators descended upon Seattle to hoot at the
harried World Trade Organization, Barshefsky's became one of the
public faces of globalization. With steady nerve and a persistently
even temper, she has tried to smooth out the wrinkles in the social
fabric as unions and human rights groups and environmentalists
blast away at this plank or that plank of the Noah's Ark that is
world trade.
</P>
<P>
   So, Charlene, how do you do it? ``I nag,'' replied the Chicago
native simply to a Chicago newspaper. Her mother was a teacher and
her father a chemical engineer who became a rabbi. And all the
strains of the family DNA come into play in the trade negotiator's
job.
</P>
<P>
   With so many of the Clinton administration's traditioanl allies
in labor, liberal causes and the environment pounding the tom-toms
on the other side of the globalization issues, Barshefsky needs to
be able to teach, to appeal to scientific logic, and ultimately to
invoke the help of the Almighty.
</P>
<P>
   As Vice President Al Gore has discovered, it is a very tricky
business to run for president when the unions, liberals and
tree-huggers whose votes you need are bellowing about trade
policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bull----,'' screamed the chief of the United Auto
Workers at a rally Wednesday that drew as many as 10,000. Organized
by John Sweeney, chief of the AFL-CIO, the rally heard Harry Wu,
imprisoned for 19 years in China, denounce the idea of granting
permanent membership to China in the World Trade Organization.
That's what Barshefsky is pushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please say no,'' appealed Wu. Barshefsky is pushing ``yes.''
At a separate Teamster rally, Pat Buchanan showed up in a Teamster
jacket, peddling his patented brand of talk-show braggadocio: ``I'd
tell (China) to stop threatening my country, persecuting the
Christians, and if you won't, you have sold your last pair of
chopsticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney's mainstream protest was lively but not disruptive. The
street action in downtown DC has drawn the interest of the cops,
the administration, and the concern of merchants and shopkeepers
worried about another series of riots like Seattle suffered.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make their voices heard midst the tumult of street
demonstrations are the leaders of the institutions under fire, the
World Bank, and International Monetary Fund chief among them. The
World Bank and IMF have been rocked by increasingly harsh attacks
on their ususal business practices.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing momentum to force even greater forgivness of
Third World debt, though lending authorities plead that if they
wipe out all the red ink, there's no money being repaid and there
won't be any more to lend.
</P>
<P>
   The vast and towering achievements of the second half of the
20th century have been left largely unremarked upon. With all the
turmoil of what's been going wrong, on ugly human rights abuses and
persistent sub-Saharan poverty, what has been done right is left
uncelebrated.
</P>
<P>
   I was reminded of this Thursday afternoon in the auditorium of
Brookline High School. As the driver and hefter of the one-woman
BHS tuba section of the school orchestra, I was there to see the
fruits of my labor in action.
</P>
<P>
   It was a remarkably uplifting ceremony titled ``Operation
Recognition,'' where 37 high school diplomas were awarded to old
men who'd left the Massachusetts high school before graduating to
join the military. Twenty of them went in the Navy, 11 in the Army,
four to the Air Corps, and two to the Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Now in their 70s, the survivors marched sprightly up the steps,
in some cases, limped on their own, came up supported by a son or
grandson, and two of them came with canes. For some of the names,
the diploma was accepted by a widow, a daughter, an old comrade.
</P>
<P>
   These men, pronounced keynote speaker Robert McKean of the
Massachusetts Department of Veterans' Services, ``are the men who
saved the world.'' About 500 people, many of them still in high
school, applauded warmly. ``Not only did they give up their
diplomas,'' said McKean, ``but the friendships, the football games
and the proms.'' Ticking off the storied battles of the Great War a
half-century back, he told the old vets, ``You didn't learn
history, you made history!''
</P>
<P>
   Amid prolonged applause, the orchestra played in turn the
signature tunes of each military service, and the vets marched out
with pride and grins and a few tears for lost comrades.
</P>
<P>
   And it struck me that one of the things that has made the world
a safer place is the incredible explosion of world trade, that has
stitched together the peoples of the planet with economic ties that
never previously existed.
</P>
<P>
   So I sympathize with the union workers fearful of being
undercut, with the human rights advocates who rightly call our
attention to the vicious abuses that still exist, and the
environmentalists who document the debauchery of our earthly
resources. But I also know that more young boys would be thrown
into wars if it were not for what trade does. And you cannot stop
globalization.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
