<HEADLINE>
AVON TAKES TOO MUCH CREDIT FOR CHARITY WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad publicity for a breast cancer benefit? Astonishing, but
true.
</P>
<P>
   Avon Products, the $5.3 billion cosmetics giant, has been
recruiting walkers for its June 2-4 Leominster-to-Boston ``3-Day,''
a group walk that has attracted over 4,000 participants. First
launched in California in 1998, the walks are now held in seven US
cities, and, according to Avon, have raised ``over $20 million for
the breast cancer cause.''
</P>
<P>
   But Avon's promotion has come under fire from an unexpected
quarter: Breast Cancer Action, a small advocacy organization based
in San Francisco. In a stinging op-ed article published earlier
this year in the San Francsico Chronicle, BCA's executive director
Barbara Brenner attacked Avon's 3-Days head-on.
</P>
<P>
   Brenner had three main criticisms: 1. Only affluent people could
afford to raise the $1,800 donation required for participation. 2.
Too much of the money raised _ 36 percent _ was spent on
administrative and marketing overhead. 3. Avon was giving the money
to the National Alliance of Breast Cancer Organizations, which
itself takes a cut of the proceeds, and then redistributes the
money to promote ``breast health'' awareness. ``None of the funds
may be used for actual (breast cancer) screening,'' Brenner wrote.
``The money can only be used for programs that encourage women to
get screening.''
</P>
<P>
   Avon, which is enjoying something of a resurgence under a young,
female chief executive, has gone bananas at Brenner's critique.
Director of public relations Susan Heaney says the participants
aren't necessarily rich, but ``come from every walk of life.'' As
for Brenner's criticism of how the money is spent, Avon announced
important changes in their funding choices about a month after her
article appeared. CEO Andrea Jung said $11 million will be donated
directly to five leading academic health centers working on breast
cancer research. Also, Avon will disburse its support through its
own foundation, which does not charge a fee. Company officials
emphasize that these decisions were not influenced by Brenner's
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, understandably, Avon is silent on the question of
excessive overhead. Like similar mass expressions of charitable
feeling _ the Walk for Hunger comes to mind _ the 3-Day is
expensive to stage. The event is actually produced by
California-based Pallotta TeamWorks, which also puts on the New
York-to-Boston Tanqueray bike ride for AIDS, and backstopped by
outside and in-house public relations staffs. On its web site
(www.breastcancer3day.org/news.htm), Avon says 59 percent of all
money raised is going to the breast cancer cause.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Avon cites the approval of the Council of Better
Business Bureaus, a 60-40 fundraising-to-expenses ratio is pretty
awful. The local United Way told me they burn up 14 per cent of
donated monies on overhead; the Boys and Girls Club, 18 per cent
and so on. ``Avon is taking enormous credit for not doing very
much,'' Brenner says. ``If the walkers want to have an impact on
breast cancer, this isn't it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Go Fetch
</P>
<P>
   Much hilarity attends the search for a ghost-writer for Lycos
boss Robert Davis' book, tentatively titled, ``Speed is Life,'' to
be published by Random House/Doubleday. New York-based literary
agent Daniel Greenberg _ 212-337-0934 if you're looking for work _
has approached every half-reputable business hack in Boston to do
the Davis book. Davis wants the book done ``at Internet speed,''
according to one writer, and have it available by the end of the
year. Greenberg initially offered $75,000, then bumped the asking
price to 100 large. He says he has a few candidates.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine who has actually made money doing this advises:
get $300,000 up front, and ask for a share of ``imputed
royalties,'' a term he may have coined. The point is, no one has
ever heard of Bob Davis, and no one is going to buy his book. But
Lycos will probably pay for a print run of 30,000 or more to hand
out to employees and customers. So get those corporate purchases
treated as if they were retail sales, and collect a small royalty
on each unit. And don't take payment in stock options.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Free Plugs
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florist Dan Nygaard sent me a nice note (Good grief! Is that all
it takes?), so maybe you'll think about buying some flowers from
him. He sells over the web, at www.home.earthlink.net/dansflowers/.
. . . Train buffs alert: Los Angeles-based Pine Tree Press has just
published ``Boston and Maine: City and Shore,'' a gorgeous picture
book celebrating the 157-year history of the old railroad. It's
expensive _ $80 _ ``and it doesn't come with a coffee table,''
jokes author Robert Jones. To order it, call 323-665-3970, or
e-mail willough(at)pacbell.net
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
