<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AVANTI-REVAMP14-COX-1     04-14 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVANTI-REVAMP14-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A reborn Avanti
 &HT;    (Eds: Fixes typos in first two grafs.)
 &HT;    By Karl Ritzler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLA RICA, GA. _ Few cars have captured aficionados' attention
like the Studebaker Avanti, and few cars have shown the Avanti's
catlike ability to survive.
</P>
<P>
   The marque has gone through at least four generations and five
ownership changes since the original car with the distinctive raked
grille flowed from the studio of Studebaker's design wizard,
Raymond Lowey, in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Studebaker may be long gone as an automaker, but the latest
edition of the Avanti is taking shape in a converted hosiery mill
in Villa Rica under the guidance of former Avanti consultant, sales
representative and collector John Seaton.
</P>
<P>
   The new Avanti Motor Corp. hasn't built the first production car
yet, but its prototypes have been seen at several major auto shows.
Another prototype is being prepared for government certification
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The newest edition ``has the Avanti essence,'' Seaton said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a new design by Tom Kellogg, a member of Lowey's original
Avanti styling team, based on the original 1963 Lowey studio
designs but incorporating modern technology and amenities. It
retains the forward rake, wedge shape and asymmetrical hood.
</P>
<P>
   The mechanicals come from General Motors. The engine is the
5.7-liter, 305-horsepower V-8 used in the Chevrolet Corvette; a
four-speed automatic or six-speed manual transmission will be
available. Other features will include air conditioning; cruise
control; four-wheel anti-lock brakes; leather interior; power
windows, mirrors and locks; AM/FM stereo with CD and a 500-watt
sound system and eight speakers. In other words, each new Avanti is
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new; there's nothing from the old car,'' Seaton said.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-built rear-wheel-drive coupes and convertibles will
have fiberglass bodies. The coupes are priced at $69,000, the
convertibles at $83,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for colors: whatever you want.
</P>
<P>
   Seaton said the first cars will be painted to order, and that
there will be some spec vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants their own color,'' he said. ``It's a personal
fingerprint.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaton expects the car's appeal to cross generations, both to
original Avanti aficionados and to younger drivers. The target
market is people with substantial disposable income who are seeking
individuality in their automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   While there is plenty of competition in the luxury roadster
market, Seaton called Avanti an American icon. ``It's like seeing
an old friend,'' Seaton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Avanti name is well-known and popular. The car has been
around so long, people have fond memories of it. We're taking the
sting out of owning an exotic car.''
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to build about 300 cars a year when production
begins, expected in the last quarter this year. Although hiring
hasn't started yet, Seaton said he hopes to employ 50 to 100 people
in the assembly plant in the next 18 months or so.
</P>
<P>
   Seaton is bringing a background in auto and clothing retailing
to the business, along with a nearly lifelong love of Avantis. He
moved to Carrollton about 11 years ago, but he kept alive his hope
for one day manufacturing Avantis. The company is owned by three
investors: Seaton is president and chief executive officer; Michael
Kelly, a former Avanti company owner in the 1980s, is chairman; and
John Hull, a former corporate tax manager, is chief financial
officer. The new company acquired the Avanti name and assets; the
assets of AVX, builder of an Avanti experimental car; the building
in Villa Rica; and ``all we need to build the car,'' Seaton said.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Avantis were built in 1991 in Youngstown, Ohio,
where Kelly moved the firm from the original Studebaker home in
South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   The new Avanti Motor Corp. is starting from the ground up, but
it is keeping in touch with the past, too. Seaton's company
purchased the parts and molds for the last generation of Avantis
with the idea that the company might be a parts supplier for
current owners. From the 1960s through 1991, more than 8,000
Avantis were built.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
