<SLUG> BC-MOVIE28DAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERFICIAL `28 DAYS' NEEDS REHAB, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
28 DAYS 
Directed by: Betty Thomas 
Screenplay by: Susannah Grant 
Starring: Sandra Bullock, Viggo Mortensen, Dominic West, Diane
Ladd, Elizabeth Perkins, Steve Buscemi, Alan Tudyk, Michael
O'Malley, Azura Skye, Reni Santoni, Marianne Jean-Baptiste, Margo
Martindale 
Running time: 103 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (mature thematic elements involving substance abuse,
language and some sensuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's going to take more than ``28 Days'' to jump-start Sandra
Bullock's stalled career. In her new vehicle, Bullock tries to move
off her sweetie-pie persona to play a wild thing, a downtown girl
who drinks herself into a rehab unit after wrecking her sister's
wedding by first falling into the cake, then commandeering the
honeymoon limo, jumping the curb, and broadsiding a neighbor's
porch. Faced with jail or rehab, she chooses the latter. But the
title of the new film is the first indicator of what's wrong with
it.
</P>
<P>
   It wants us to believe that Bullock's character, Gwen, can
overcome her alcohol abuse problem, roots and all, in 28 days. It's
detox as summer camp. Nestled in the Blue Ridge Mountains in North
Carolina, the rehab center is a virtual country club, even if all
the chanting and touchy-feely stuff that go on there become a
little much. They mirror this film that isn't nearly gritty or
tough-minded enough. It shies away from presenting Bullock's
character as anything really frightening, or even unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, she's a bit unruly. When she vomits, it's always into
a toilet. She's vaguely described as a writer, but all we get of
her past are spinning, blurry flashbacks evoking her drunken
behavior, patterned on that of her mother. In short, it's a
sanitized _ and therefore unconvincing _ brand of drunkenness we
see here. Bullock is at her best in the beginning and end.
Initially, Gwen's response is glib denial and brittle contempt for
the others who are trying to get with the program. But after one
convenient perspective-altering incident _ she falls three stories
trying to retrieve some discarded pills _ she sees the light.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the 28 days are up, she gathers her resolve to face
up to her party animal boyfriend, well-played by Dominic West as a
big-time enabler and a large part of her problem. In short, this
superficial and lightweight look at alcoholism hardly enables the
ever-likable Bullock to dance on the wilder shores of substance
abuse. Susannah Grant, fresh from delivering an invigorating script
in ``Erin Brockovich,'' here falls back on safe, bland
predictability that doesn't even allow the secondary characters
much scope. While Bullock seems reined in, staying button-cute,
even to the extent of flapping her hands helplessly when her
roommate overdoses on drugs, most of the others hardly seem there
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Buscemi is wasted as a savvy counselor and ex-addict. So
are the others, with the exceptions of West's bad influence and
Viggo Mortensen's fellow addict, a star pitcher in rehab. Despite
his babe-magnet behavior, he's savvy enough to talk some straight
talk to Gwen. Their avoidance of sappy, mutually dependent romance
is the script's sole departure from a facile glibness that seems a
more advanced case of denial than any exhibited by the characters.
For a much more convincing take on the same subject than this
screenful of wine and poses, check out ``Clean and Sober'' with
Michael Keaton and Kathy Baker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
