A6864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-KEEPING-BOS &LR;      04-14 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-KEEPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTON'S `KEEPING THE FAITH' RINGS FALSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
KEEPING THE FAITH 
Directed by: Edward Norton 
Screenplay by: Stuart Blumberg 
Starring: Norton, Ben Stiller, Jenna Elfman, Anne Bancroft, Eli
Wallach, Ron Rifkin, Milos Forman, Holland Taylor 
Running time: 131 minutes 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Keeping the Faith'' will be remembered as the film with which
actor Edward Norton made his directing debut. That's about all
it'll be remembered for. The romantic comedy starring Norton and
Ben Stiller as boyhood buddies who fall in love with a third grown
buddy _ Jenna Elfman _ is bland, prefab, and overextended. It's not
nearly as interesting as any of the films in which Norton has
acted, and sounds like something of a bad joke if you begin with
the fact that Norton plays a priest and Stiller plays a rabbi. The
rabbi can get married, although he's under pressure to marry a
Jewish girl. The priest can't marry. So who'll wind up with
Elfman's high-powered businesswoman with a cell phone grafted onto
her wrist?
</P>
<P>
   The question can't quite lift the film out of the conventional
rut into which it sinks with self-deceiving comfort pretty early
on, never to rise out of it. The romantic consternation escalates
when the rabbi and the priest, both modern, innovative types, meet
the third member of their childhood trio at the airport after not
having seen her for years. When they do, they both fall for her.
It's the rabbi who gets lucky in that she falls for him, too. To
avoid discomfort, they hide their involvement from their pal, the
priest, and, for that matter, from the rest of the world as well.
From this the romantic complications arise as Jake the rabbi and
Brian the priest agonize over their respective feelings.
</P>
<P>
   But the film isn't really interested in making the kind of
trouble it promises. It doesn't want to make trouble at all. It
wants to resolve everything conveniently. That's what's wrong with
it. It simply never plugs into the unruliness that drove the best
screwball comedies. There are some laughs to be derived from
Stiller's weaselly behavior, but they come at the cost of what
might have provided some emotional conviction. Elfman's Annie says
she loves him for his spirituality. But spirituality is the one
thing he doesn't project. Norton's Brian seems an awfully nice guy,
but a bit of a lightweight. Before long, you wonder what Annie
would see in either of them.
</P>
<P>
   Although she isn't given much to work with, Elfman walks away
with ``Keeping the Faith.'' She's that vibrant a presence.
Actually, for all of its modernity, the film is a curious throwback
to those old Hollywood comedies where the assumption is that an
accomplished woman would cheerfully give up a high-powered career
to pursue love with Mr. Right. Annie's biz wiz has a lot more going
for her than Brian or Jake have going for them. Norton's direction
is proficient, but the film does tend to move as if it's
permanently stuck in second gear. His attempts to add texture by
including multicultural surrogates come out pretty cliched. So does
Jake's Jewish mother, played by Anne Bancroft. So, in fact, does
the whole film. It settles for slickness instead of sparkle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0161 </DOCNO>
