A6867 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-PSYCHO-BOS &LR;      04-14 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PSYCHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLICKER `AMERICAN PSYCHO' ON SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AMERICAN PSYCHO 
Directed by: Mary Harron 
Screenplay by: Guinevere Turner (based on Bret Easton Ellis'
novel) 
Starring: Christian Bale, Willem Dafoe, Jared Leto, Reese
Witherspoon, Samantha Mathis, Chloe Sevigny, Justin Theroux, Josh
Lucas, Cara Seymour 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence, sexuality, language and drug use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``American Psycho'' is one of the rare cases of a film improving
upon a book. But then it would be almost impossible not to improve
upon Bret Easton Ellis' trashy novel that seems too busy drooling
over its misogynistic frenzies to ever get around to pillorying
them. As there's no end of aggressiveness built into our
market-driven world, there's a certain bleak logic in inventing a
Wall Street serial killer, a soulless cipher who takes his identity
from the labels in his expensive clothes, having none himself.
Patrick Bateman, Ellis' Freddy Krueger figure out of GQ, first
hacks a business competitor to death, then extends his rage to a
string of women and homeless people. In the right hands, he could
have seemed an embodiment of the Reagan or Thatcher years, a Jack
the Ripper of capitalism, trying to hide his hollowness in
conspicuous consumption as he grows ever more unhinged.
</P>
<P>
   But ``American Psycho'' is no critique of Reaganomics. Ellis
went off the tracks. Instead of maintaining the distance essential
to satire, he seemed to blend into the excess, losing himself in
litanies of upmarket labels, punctuated by sadistic swoons. Mary
Harron's film avoids a couple of traps Ellis fell into simply
because she has images at her disposal. The long riff on skin care
rituals that numbingly begins the book on a dual note of narcissism
and insecurity is efficiently handled by a shot of Bateman's
oversized medicine cabinet, stuffed with bottles and jars of
creams, gels, lotions, and other emollients palmed off at top
dollar to the obsessive-compulsive. Bateman's apartment looks like
something out of Kubrick _ expensive, cold, white, hard-surfaced,
antiseptic _ a squash court gone co-op.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Bateman loses control and starts swinging the ax and
wielding the chainsaw, the film starts sounding like Hitchcock's
``Psycho,'' with a shrieking soundtrack that pays repeated homage
to Bernard Herrmann's aural handiwork in the Bates Motel.
Meanwhile, Christian Bale's Bateman schleps to Wall Street each
day, where he fights a constant state of terror at being one-upped
by his equally shallow and nervous contemporaries. They travel in
packs to ridiculously expensive, pretentious clubs where they look
down their noses at Bellinis, snort cocaine, dine on
self-satirizing dishes like ostrich filets with cactus mayonnaise,
and zombie through sex with drugged-out socialites.
</P>
<P>
   Bale looks both buffed and vapid as a rudderless mannequin who
never knows whether to sedate himself into obliviousness or flog
himself into sensation with coke or killing. The settings and
production design do a lot of the work of the film. Harron
efficiently limns the world of these self-styled masters of the
universe in such moments as the one when four platinum credit cards
hit a serving tray in unison with _ their owners hope _ studied
insouciance as a three-figure tab arrives. Harron gets more mileage
than Ellis did out of the frequent moments when the young hotshots'
lack of distinct identities is underscored every time one is
constantly mistaken for another. The film is a smarter, sharper
take on their world than the book.
</P>
<P>
   Bateman's most anxious moment comes when he and the others
exchange business cards, and the card of his that he thought was so
cool is eclipsed by an even more coolly designed one. After every
such puncturing, an act of rage follows. When a snooty maitre d'
laughs at his last-minute reservation request, we know some new
victim's going to pay. The film got its rating changed from NC-17
to R when Harron trimmed a few seconds from a sex scene involving
Bateman and two prostitutes. But what does it say about where we
are now that the violence that follows _ a far greater obscenity
than the sex _ was unquestioned? During the so-called sex, Bateman
isn't looking at either of the women. Rather, he's looking at
himself in the mirror at the head of his bed.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he's making love to himself, supplying a
self-immolating metaphor for the book. It can't be said that Harron
is oblivious to its themes. She is in fact more inventive in her
handling of them than Ellis was. Yet she and the film remain boxed
in. They deliver the satire more efficiently, but they're still
stuck with the book's misogynism, and it doesn't play any less
revoltingly on screen than it did on the page. In both senses of
the word, ``American Psycho'' wastes its women. Harron softens the
harrowing ending, raising the possibility of a moral escape clause
the book does not. In this respect, at least, the novel has the
courage of its meretriciousness. The film is no more successful in
supplying resolution, much less catharsis. The book seems a case of
the prurient condemning the prurient. It's cynical junk
masquerading as social comment. The film is, finally, only a
slicker packaging of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
