<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-WHERE-BOS &LR;      04-14 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WHERE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWMAN, FIORENTINO CAPER STYLISHLY IN `MONEY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
WHERE THE MONEY IS 
Directed by: Marek Kanievska 
Screenplay by: E. Max Frye &AMP; Topper Lilien, Carroll Cartwright 
Starring: Paul Newman, Linda Fiorentino, Dermot Mulroney 
Running time: 89 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (some sexual content) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Where the Money Is,'' Paul Newman is cool, Linda Fiorentino
is hot, and that's all the film needs to put the joy back into
larceny. Connoisseurs of bank robbery will immediately recognize
the source of the film's title. When real-life midcentury bandit
Willie Sutton was asked why he robbed banks, he replied, with
impeccable logic, ``Because that's where the money is.'' In the
film, Newman's cagey old-timer, Henry Manning, shares this view.
When he's wheeled out of prison into a nursing home, doubled up
into a wheelchair by a supposed stroke, Fiorentino's nurse is
convinced he's faking his way out of stir.
</P>
<P>
   She's right. She knows Henry is a veteran bank robber. What she
doesn't know is that Henry is planning one last big score. But her
heart is in the right place, namely a larcenous one. Soon, she and
Newman's old-timer bond and her blue-collar husband, Dermot
Mulroney's Wayne, is in on the caper, too. Think of ``Where the
Money Is'' as a modest, blue-collar version of ``The Sting,'' with
Newman an aging Butch Cassidy, or Hud, a guy who wears a lot of
experience in his face, is in no hurry to make his move, but is
savvy and decisive when he does.
</P>
<P>
   The film never drags, but one of the enjoyable things about it
is its way of taking its time letting us get to know and savor the
characters. This takes the form of Carol trying to get the old guy
to stop playing possum and teach her what he knows so she can blast
free of the grubby small-town life that's weighing her down. Liking
her spirit, and realizing he can't do the job alone, he cuts her
and Wayne in for a piece of the action. The action, in this case,
involves hijacking an armored car, going around town picking up the
night's take from various establishments, then making off with it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it doesn't quite go as planned. Henry's cool and his
improvisatory abilities are tested several times, and it's a
pleasure to watch Newman unfurl them with the relaxed authority he
brings to the character acting that has occupied the latter part of
his life after he spent decades feeling ambivalent about being cast
as romantic leads. Fiorentino, that delectable panther of an
actress, has film's sultriest purr since the golden age of Lauren
Bacall. She convinces us that in Henry, Carol's restlessness has
found just what it needs to move to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun watching her awaken to new possibilities she had only
half acknowledged before Henry's arrival. Mulroney holds up his end
of the collaboration, too, as the husband who likes the idea of the
heist, but is jealous of his wife's fascination with the
experienced older man. The film is tense when it has to be, but
mostly it's jaunty, kept aloft by a playful mix of energies, except
when the thieves are backed into a couple of tight corners. ``Where
the Money Is'' is as much about character as about the caper. But
the test of any caper movie is whether you like the crooks enough
to root for them. This one aces the test effortlessly as Newman and
Fiorentino project more than enough charm to melt any mere armored
car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-POITIER-BOS &LR;      04-14 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-POITIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POITIER'S BIOGRAPHY MEASURES UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
The Measure of A Man: 
A Spiritual Autobiography 
By Sidney Poitier. HarperCollins. 236 pp. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sidney Poitier learned when to fight and when to cool it,
something many of us never master. He developed the knack on a
rather fantastic journey that took him from his native Cat Island,
a tiny slip of land in the Bahamas, all the way to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   That's the gist of this book, whose 72-year-old author reflects
on his long odyssey. Cat Island, 46 miles long, three miles wide,
was where the actor, born prematurely while his struggling parents
were traveling to Miami to sell tomatoes, learned his first
important life lessons. By age 10, he'd had so many childhood
misadventures that, he recalls, he'd become almost enamored of
``flirting with risk,'' flirtations that continued throughout his
life.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived in Jim Crow Miami at 15 as an immigrant kid with an
``inner eye'' that showed him, as had his ``Cat Island
curriculum,'' when trouble loomed. At barely 16, he recounts, he
approached two white policemen in an unmarked cruiser, seeking
directions home. The police struck a deal with him. They'd follow
him if he walked the 50 blocks to his home. If he didn't look back,
they suggested they'd shoot him. He complied.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing his first movie as a child, Poitier wanted to go to
Hollywood and become a cowboy. Eventually, he went and became the
first _ and only _ African-American to win the Academy Award for
best actor. He won it for his role in ``Lilies of the Field'' in
1963, a picture made on a shoestring by a studio that was
interested in developing a relationship with its director.
</P>
<P>
   Poitier's book is full of the detours he took before
establishing himself. His original bestselling 1980 autobiography,
``This Life,'' described his life in Hollywood. This book is a
personal history striving for something deeper, trying to give
contours to a full life in which Hollywood played only a part,
albeit a major one.
</P>
<P>
   At 19, after leaving the South for New York, the inexperienced
Poitier naively answered an ad for actors, placed by the American
Negro Theater. Since he didn't know how to perform, he recalls, he
was contemptuously advised to take a dishwashing job. He did. He
learned to read from newspapers with the help of an old Jewish
waiter. He went back to the Negro Theater and was hired as a
janitor before graduating to acting jobs there.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 23, Poitier had made a couple of films and
performed in a couple of major theatrical productions. He was
married, expecting his second child, and was a partner in a
struggling rib restaurant at 127th Street and 7th Avenue. He was
still washing dishes to keep the place going.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many stars, Poitier is able to discuss thoughtfully the
values in some of his film work, which, besides ``Lilies,''
includes ``A Patch of Blue,'' ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner,'' and
``To Sir, With Love.'' He effectively previewed his role in
``Dinner'' before filming it when he was invited to a dinner party
at Spencer Tracey's Beverly Hills home at which Katharine Hepburn,
who'd invited him to her home for an introductory meeting, was a
guest.
</P>
<P>
   It was Poitier who suggested the powerful scene in ``In the Heat
of the Night.'' In that film, he's a Philadelphia detective working
in the South with the redneck lawman Rod Steiger. Poitier questions
a local businessman who slaps him in the face for impertinence.
Poitier slaps him back.
</P>
<P>
   He recounts how he survived a tense situation in the
extraordinary Lorraine Hansberry play ``A Raisin in the Sun.'' By
the end of the run, Claudia McNeil, who played the mother, wasn't
speaking to him. She believed the production was best when played
from the mother's point of view; Poitier thought it was best when
played from his character's, the son's.
</P>
<P>
   Poitier took a giant step forward in his career with the help of
an agent, Marty Baum. Poitier refused an acting role that would
have paid him a princely $750 a week; this came at a time when he
was so broke that he'd borrowed $75 from Household Finance Co. on
the furniture in his apartment to pay for his child's birth.
Poitier declined the job because his character was too passive.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Baum called him. He had to get something straight. He had
no jobs for Poitier but still didn't understand why the actor had
turned down the kind of money he'd been offered earlier. Poitier
explained. Then, Baum blurted out why he'd called. ``I don't know
what's going on with you, but anybody as crazy as you, I want to
handle him,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
