<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6872 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HOUSTON-OPERA-TEX     04-14 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-OPERA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBITIOUS OPERA COMPANY CONTINUES BLAZING TRAILS WITH `COLD SASSY
TREE'
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by OPERA-NOVELS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In the past quarter of a century, Houston opera
audiences have seen singing vampires, science-fiction epics, the
meeting of Nixon and Mao, the assassination of a gay-rights
pioneer, the evolution of Jackie Kennedy into Jackie O, the coming
of age of Meg, Jo and Beth _ and lots of other things you don't
expect to see in an opera.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such strange goings-on, or more likely because of them,
the icons of the musical world, from Leonard Bernstein to Michael
Tippett to Philip Glass, as well as numerous lesser-known composing
lights, have made the pilgrimage to Houston to present their latest
efforts to the Bayou City's operatic connoisseurs.
</P>
<P>
   A bastion of conservative musical tastes just 30 years ago,
Houston has since built an international reputation as a center for
innovative opera production and established itself beyond doubt as
the leading performing-arts organization in Texas. That success
story continues this week with the company's 25th world premiere,
Carlisle Floyd's ``Cold Sassy Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   This production epitomizes Houston Grand Opera's long-term
commitment to new opera. The company was once identified with a
trendy movement toward ``current events'' operas, such as ``Nixon
in China,'' ``Harvey Milk'' and ``Jackie O.'' Now there's a
stronger move toward adapting contemporary or classic fiction for
the operatic stage, as in the company's recent premiere of an opera
based on Louisa May Alcott's ``Little Women.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd has been associated with Houston Grand Opera for more than
20 years. The company premiered the composer's ``Bilby's Doll'' in
1976. The company staged his ``Willie Stark'' (based on Robert Penn
Warren's Pulitzer Prize-winning novel ``All the King's Men'') in
1981 and a revised version of his ``The Passion of Jonathan Wade''
in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   A highly literate composer who has written all of his own
librettos, Floyd first became acquainted with the novel ``Cold
Sassy Tree'' when his sister gave him a copy. Written in 1984 by
Olive Ann Burns, who died in 1990, it narrates the maturing of a
teen-age boy in a small Georgia town at the turn of the 20th
century, following him as he falls in love with a girl of lower
social class, while at the same time observing his widowed
grandfather's marriage of convenience unexpectedly develop into a
true and noble romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it and enjoyed it thoroughly, without thinking of it as
an opera,'' Floyd says. ``Then I reread it, thinking that it might
become an opera.''
</P>
<P>
   When Houston Grand Opera's general director, David Gockley,
approached Floyd about the possibility of commissioning another
opera, Floyd presented the idea of ``Cold Sassy Tree,'' but with
some doubts because of the challenges the book presented.
</P>
<P>
   Gockley was not the least reluctant. ``Our audience has gotten
larger, younger, more diverse,'' he says of Houston Grand Opera's
willingness to stage unusual and nontraditional productions. ``It's
not a homogeneous group.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, diversity has become a strength in the company's march
to prominence: It never alienates everyone in its audience at the
same time. Some of the ``Traviata'' crowd may balk at ``Nixon in
China,'' and some of the fans of ``The Making of the Representative
for Planet 8'' may complain about another ``Carmen,'' but at least
a large part of the audience is enthusiastically with the program
at any given time _ and all seem proud of the company's burgeoning
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   So Floyd got a commission for his challenging project.
</P>
<P>
   And the challenges were significant. The plot was largely
episodic, based on isolated events and vivid characters. And
several key events _ the arrival of the first automobile in the
town, a train accident _ were impossible to stage.
</P>
<P>
   But Floyd took to the task, slimming down the cast and
concentrating on the romances.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an opera that's the flip side of ``Susannah,'' the
opera that skyrocketed Floyd to fame in 1956 when he was still in
his 20s. That opera, which the Fort Worth Opera will stage in the
fall, is pessimistic, presenting the story (inspired by a book in
the Old Testament Apocrypha) of a young woman in a rural Southern
setting who is seduced by a preacher and condemned by a
sanctimonious community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Sassy Tree,'' however, paints the brighter side of an
isolated Southern town; even with its clearly painted faults, the
community ultimately provides love and support to the protagonists
and a setting for growth and transformation.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with its commitment to quality, Houston Grand Opera
hired Australian film director Bruce Beresford _ who directed
``Breaker Morant,'' Crimes of the Heart'' and ``Tender Mercies'' _
to direct ``Cold Sassy Tree.'' An avid opera fan, Beresford has
directed stage versions of Puccini's ``Girl of the Golden West,''
Strauss' ``Elektra'' and Robert Ward's ``The Crucible.''
</P>
<P>
   Beresford is most impressed by the depth of emotion in ``Cold
Sassy Tree.'' The setting is distinctly regional, and the company
had to bring in a diction coach to get the Southeastern accent _
especially the word ``Love,'' which is the name of one of the main
characters _ just right.
</P>
<P>
   But, according to Beresford, the emotions transcend region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic passions are the same all over the world,''
Beresford says.''People behave the same in Nigeria, where I lived
for three years, as they do in New York or London or Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Cold Sassy Tree''
</P>
<P>
   Houston Grand Opera performances: 2 p.m. Sunday and April 30;
7:30 p.m. Wednesday and April 22, 25, 28 and May 6 at Wortham
Theater Center, Texas at Smith streets, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $22-$182
</P>
<P>
   Information: (800) 828-2787
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay is classical music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7756, or e-mail:
wlgay\Nstar-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6873 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-TV-CORNER-BOS &LR;      04-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CORNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX-PART MINISERIES PORTRAY GRITTY STREETCORNER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CORNER 
Starring: Khandi Alexander, T. K. Carter, Sean Nelson, Tyra
Ferrell, Glenn Plummer 
Directed by: Charles S. Dutton 
On: HBO, Sundays at 10 p.m. 
Rated: TVMA 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a few minutes watching ``The Corner,'' a bleak and bracing
and beautiful new HBO miniseries, you are crystal clear on a few
issues. 1) This drama won't be must-see TV for those who like to
watch human suffering healed by an angel's touch. 2) The inner-city
realism, unrelenting and darkly poetic, is unequaled on TV. 3) The
acting is so seamless and unflattering to the actors it will
probably scare Emmy voters back to their tapes of ``3d Rock From
the Sun.'' 4) HBO is definitely not running this uncompromising
six-part miniseries about drug addiction and poverty in order to
pump ratings.
</P>
<P>
   And by the final minutes of ``The Corner,'' which airs Sundays
at 10 p.m. for the next six weeks, you are clear on one last point:
This is an unforgettable piece of work. If you stay with it,
through the hours of junkie desperation and defeated hopes and
fleeting victories, you probably won't say, ``I just loved it.''
But you will feel something even more powerful: compassion,
insight, and the intensity of having watched an ensemble of actors
completely inhabit their roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Corner'' is set in a hollowed-out West Baltimore
neighborhood, picked clean of anything that might return a few
dollars at the junkyard. Fran Boyd and Gary McCullough, once a
couple but now just drug buddies, move along the streets always
with a mission _ to score, to get money to score, or to get home
and shoot the latest score. They sleep in separate places _ she
lives with her siblings, he lives with his parents _ but they
continually cross paths, just as they also intersect with their
16-year-old son, a dealer named DeAndre. The movie is held together
by a lovely, natural choreography that keeps throwing the members
of this broken family together. They care about one another, for
sure, but Fran and Gary are fixated on their drug needs, and
DeAndre, with his distinctive dreadlocks, is caught up in making
big money and hanging with his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether Fran and Gary will kick drugs,
particularly as Fran builds up the courage to get into detox, and
the question of whether DeAndre will land in jail or worse, hang
over ``The Corner.'' And the answers to these question do arrive.
But it isn't plotted in the way we generally think of plot. It's
more like a collection of everyday moments in the life of a
neighborhood _ Fran stealing drugs from DeAndre while he has sex
with his girlfriend; Gary struggling to keep from spending his
mother's errand money on drugs; the gold-rush fever that sweeps
through the neighborhood when furniture is left on the sidewalk
after an eviction; a touchingly innocent teen sock hop at a
recreation center; and the unshakable image of junkies taking
needles in their knuckles, their necks, their behinds. Shuffled in
with these vignettes are random flashbacks to Fran and Gary's
promising middle-class life, and how they lost it.
</P>
<P>
   We also get to know a large cast of indelibly acted secondary
characters, from Tyra Ferrell's idealistic recreation-center
director to Clarke Peters as a neighborhood elder with a liver
problem. Gradually, all these characters, with their lost paradises
and momentary triumphs, add up to a remarkably full, revelatory
social portrait. I should also add that there are indeed moments of
humor, particularly an ongoing riff about bumming cigarettes. No
one would ever call ``The Corner'' a comedy, but it does contain
needed occasions of respite from the grimness.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is strongly directed by Charles S. Dutton, known for
his years as TV's ``Roc,'' for supporting roles in movies such as
``Cookie's Fortune,'' and for an early personal history that
includes prison time for manslaughter. It's only Dutton's second
time behind the camera (the first was HBO's ``First Time Felon''),
but he has enough directorial patience to let his characters'
humanity emerge slowly and surely, without any stylistic gimmickry.
His faux documentary approach is neutral and straightforward, and
he avoids the instrusive, self-conscious stylizations of verite
dramas like ``NYPD Blue.'' (Actually, the movie has its roots in
nonfiction, in a book of the same title by Edward Burns and David
Simon). Dutton also avoids _ mostly successfully _ the sort of
manipulative earnestness meant to nudge us into sadness or
political anger about America's inability to cope with drug
addiction. He simply lets the mundane world of ``The Corner'' speak
for itself.
</P>
<P>
   As Fran, Khandi Alexander is stunningly real. Best known as
Benton's sister on ``ER'' and as one of the ensemble players on
``NewsRadio,'' she seems to become Fran, a woman who is wily and
amoral when it comes to getting drugs and drug money, but who
passionately wants to keep her son clean. She's a fearless force of
nature, and most of the humor in ``The Corner'' is thanks to her
raging cynicism. Even when she looks like a ghost, as drug-infested
and characterless as the buildings on the corner, she's a fountain
of edgy zingers. As Gary, comedian T. K. Carter perfectly captures
the gentleness and passivity that can be addiction's easiest
conquest. He's beaten down and he knows it, and in his shame he
prefers to shoot dope without being watched. And as DeAndre, Sean
Nelson, from the movie ``Fresh,'' delivers a subtle mix of cocky,
resigned attitude and the desire for a better life.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Corner'' may sound like just more preachy TV cliches
about drug abuse and African-American self-destruction, it is so
much more than that. It is about the life and death forces at war
in that inner-city staple, ``The Corner,'' and it is a jarring
introduction to the people behind the statistics and the cliches. I
hope it finds an audience, despite its rawness. No one ever said
great drama had to be pretty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
