<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL HOLDS COURT AND SPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
AN ALL-STAR TRIBUTE TO JONI MITCHELL 
On: TNT 
Time: Sunday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Actors don't seem to be particularly dazzled by one another. But
the moment they lay their eyes on a genuine rock icon, their
perfectly sculpted jaws tumble to the floor and all kinds of mush
comes gushing out. And when that icon is Joni Mitchell, goddess,
musician, painter, and poet, well the gush factor is significant.
And so it happens that, in the course of TNT's ``All-Star Tribute
to Joni Mitchell,'' host Ashley Judd can't seem to stop nattering
on about her earliest Joni memories, while the likes of Goldie
Hawn, Susan Sarandon, and Laurence Fishburne sit staring wide-eyed
from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   And it's hard not to identify with their awe. Few artists
deserve tribute as much as Mitchell, for her perfect lyrics, for
her expressive voice, for her musical adventurousness, for her
career stamina, and, of course, for her famously uncompromising
nature. Over the course of her 30-year-plus recording life, she has
created one of the most personal and fully realized musical
statements in pop, from the simple confessional pleasures of
``Blue'' and ``For the Roses'' to the more complex visions of
``Court and Spark,'' ``Hejira,'' ``The Hissing of Summer Lawns,''
and later albums like ``Night Ride Home'' and ``Turbulent Indigo.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with ``All-Star Tribute to Joni Mitchell,'' which
airs Sunday at 9, has everything to do with Mitchell's strength as
an artist. Filmed in New York last week, the concert is a series of
musical guests performing Mitchell songs. Not only do all of the
performances fall short of Mitchell's own versions _ that is to be
expected, but none of the guests seems able to make the song his or
her own for even a few minutes, despite the fact that most of the
selections are from Mitchell's earlier, more conventional albums.
</P>
<P>
   Cyndi Lauper gives an oddly flat, slinky version of ``Carey,''
Shawn Colvin and Mary Chapin Carpenter work painfully hard to
harmonize on ``Chelsea Morning,'' and k.d. lang never takes off
with her sultry go at ``Help Me.'' Elton John comes up with an
earthbound, uninspired ``Free Man in Paris,'' the song Mitchell
wrote about David Geffen, and Richard Thompson steps a little too
heavily on ``Woodstock'' and ``Black Crow,'' although he does
manage some effectively predatory riffs on the latter. ``I've
played before the queen of England,'' Elton announces, as if to
explain why the performers have been missing the mark, ``and it's
not so intimidating as having such a great musician there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, who watches the show from a side balcony, does her
best not to be intimidating, greeting each performance with a
genuine smile. She closes her eyes to enjoy James Taylor's
unsuccessful attempt to Taylorize ``River,'' and she rocks her head
to Bryan Adams and Wynonna Judd singing the raucous ``Raised on
Robbery.'' She is a warm front of good vibes, and the many camera
shots of her are the best part of the show. At the end, she takes
the stage to offer thanks for the ``surrealistic'' event and to
provide the concert's most heartfelt performance, a contented,
resigned version of ``Both Sides Now'' with a full orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's the best kind of celebration: when the subject of
homage walks away with the night without even trying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
