<HEADER>
A6880 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-SECRET-BOS &LR;      04-14 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SECRET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SECRET' VENTURES INTO NEW YORK'S LITERARY PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
JOE GOULD'S SECRET 
Directed by: Stanley Tucci 
Screenplay by: Howard A. Rodman (based on Joseph Mitchell's
stories) 
Starring: Ian Holm, Tucci, Patricia Clarkson, Hope Davis, Susan
Sarandon, Patrick Tovatt, Steve Martin, Celia Weston 
Running time: 108 minutes 
Rated: R (some language and brief nudity) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Joe Gould's Secret'' is such a loving evocation of the
Manhattan literary scene of the 1940s, at least insofar as it
stretched from Greenwich Village to the offices of The New Yorker
on 43d Street and back again, that I found myself cutting its
stiff-legged direction a lot of slack and enjoying its characters
and atmosphere. Joe Gould was a Greenwich Village bum and lifelong
sponger, but one with intelligence, style, and panache, who claimed
to be writing the longest book ever. It was an oral history of the
world, in which he said he was recording snatches of overheard New
York vernacular in notebook after marbled school notebook,
interspersed with autobiography and philosophical observations.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time until New Yorker writer Joseph
Mitchell ran into him, which in the film he does in a coffee shop.
Mitchell loved New York's eccentrics and specialized in writing
about them for the magazine's Talk of the Town section and in
occasional Profiles. In a time when the world wanted to believe the
bohemian tradition was still alive in the Village, Mitchell's 1942
piece made a lot of people happy, including Gould, who became a
minor celebrity and something of a tourist attraction, with his own
table at the Minetta Tavern. He filled notebook after notebook,
which he stashed with friends, and wasn't shy about soliciting
donations to the Joe Gould Fund.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the work of the film is done with the casting of Ian
Holm in the title role. Holm is wonderful, unobtrusively calling
upon his Shakespearean background to paint Gould as a vest-pocket
Falstaff, filled with bluff and bluster, shrewdly exploiting his
snappish Yankee manner and salty speech, spicing them with the
occasional wild-man routine he claimed to have absorbed from
Indians he once lived near in Montana. Yet Holm's Gould is not
entirely a humbug. He lets people know he graduated from Harvard in
1911. To bestow upon him an anachronistic phrase, he talked the
talk, even when his frequent drunkenness prevented him from walking
the walk.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Tucci's Mitchell provides a couple of kinds of
counterpoint. Quiet, reserved, proper, murmuring mouthful after
mouthful of Southern courtliness, it's easy to imagine the
transplanted North Carolinean in his suit, collar, tie, and hat
leaving his wife and two daughters each morning and riding the
subway uptown to The New Yorker, fitting perfectly into its
somewhat prissy atmosphere, typing away methodically in his
cloistered office each day for years. He loved New York and its
characters, became a legend himself by writing about them, but
wasn't quite prepared for the way Joe Gould invaded his life.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Holm does a wonderful job of showing us why people
believed in Joe Gould even as they noticed his calculating,
appraising glances, so does Tucci as it begins to occur to Mitchell
that he's being suckered by Gould. We learn what he found out, and
wrote in 1964, after Gould's death in 1957. Tucci the director may
have damped Mitchell a little too much. And while he fills the
screen with yeasty characters, they don't often behave in a yeasty
way. There's something almost stilted in some interactions. We feel
he's got the right people up there, but hasn't encouraged them to
cut loose enough.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if there's some shortfall in the spontaneity department,
the individual portrayals are marvelous, fully worthy of occupying
the almost tenderly evoked settings. Susan Sarandon is a standout
as the artist Alice Neel, who painted a scandalous portrait of
Gould. Patrick Tovatt is terrific as Harold Ross, the gruff genius
who edited The New Yorker. Hope Davis adds dimension as Mitchell's
photographer wife, who contributes additional views of New York,
and Patricia Clarkson provides grace and heart as a generous
gallery owner and benefactor. ``Joe Gould's Secret'' isn't all it
could have been, but there's a lot to like in it. It's of a piece
with ``Mrs. Parker and the Vicious Circle'' and ``Cradle Will
Rock,'' which means that if you're up for a bit of time travel to a
vanished New York, it's indispensable viewing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
