<HEADER>
A6881 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OPERA-NOVELS-TEX     04-14 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-NOVELS-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Accompanies HOUSTON-OPERA) 
NOVEL APPROACHES TO OPERA (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plays, legends and famous historical events have always been
common fodder for opera composers.
</P>
<P>
   Novels, too, are getting their operatic due, the latest being
Carlisle Floyd's ``Cold Sassy Tree,'' based on the novel by Olive
Ann Burns.
</P>
<P>
   But while operatic adaptations of novels are in vogue, it isn't
a new phenomenon. In the traditional repertory, the first famous
opera based on a full-length novel was Donizetti's ``Lucia di
Lammermoor'' in 1835 _ although it's easy to forget that this
thoroughly Italian piece is based on a thoroughly British novel by
Walter Scott. Bizet's ``Carmen'' is based on a novella by Prosper
Merimee, and, in the early part of this century, Gershwin's ``Porgy
and Bess'' was inspired by DuBose Heyward's ``Porgy.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel has become an even more popular source in recent
decades. Bernard Hermann, best known as the composer of numerous
film scores for Alfred Hitchcock, produced a setting of Emily
Bronte's ``Wuthering Heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Prokofiev took on the hefty challenge of Tolstoy's ``War and
Peace'' to produce a mammoth work whose dimensions discourage
performance. British composer Benjamin Britten loved to turn short
novels into operas, and did so with Herman Melville's ``Billy
Budd,'' Henry James' ``The Turn of the Screw'' and Thomas Mann's
``Death in Venice.'' Puccini's good friend Franco Alfano set
Tolstoy's ``Resurrection'' early in this century, with the book
still hot off the presses; American composer Tod Machover set the
same novel for the Houston Grand Opera in 1999. And, in keeping
with Houston Grand Opera's tradition of new works, Mark Adamo
adapted Louisa May Alcott's ``Little Women'' in 1998 on commission
for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, in particular, loves to use novels as source material.
Along with ``Cold Sassy Tree,'' he has set Robert Penn Warren's
Pulitzer Prize-winning ``All the President's Men'' (retitled
``Willie Stark'', John Steinbeck's ``Of Mice and Men'' and Esther
Forbes' ``A Mirror for Witches'' (retitled ``Bilby's Doll'') _ no
doubt making him, along with Oprah Winfrey, a Christmas card
favorite of struggling authors around the country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wayne Lee Gay
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
