<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6888 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     04-14 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO YOU KNOW WHAT LABEL I'D LIKE TO PUT ON THIS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just what America's youngsters don't need _ another set of
labels.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Search Institute's profile of developmental
assets amounts to _ labeling youth as lacking certain elements that
grown-ups think are important for maturing into well-adjusted
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, designed to allow communities to ``assess the health
and well-being of middle and high school age children,'' asks 156
questions about everything from homework and grades to drug use and
sexual activity. The results are supposed to provide ``important
insights'' about the challenges that young people face and the
``internal strengths and external supports they have to overcome''
them.
</P>
<P>
   The spin on the Minneapolis-based institute's survey is that it
reportedly focuses on what assets young people have _ ``the
essential building blocks for adolescent development'' _ rather
than on what's lacking, but any time you ascribe specific numerical
values to a child who has the ``assets'' that make him likely to
succeed vs. one who is lacking said ``assets'' and is likely to
have a hard time, that's labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the three Tarrant County, Texas, school districts
who took the survey scored 18.8 out of a possible 40. The national
average is 18, so kids in the Everman, White Settlement and Fort
Worth school districts are above the national average _ barely.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a condemnation that our children are like children
everywhere else in America, but the local score has some folks in
the youth services arena passing peach pits because it's so low. (A
cynic might say: ``Of course they're reacting with alarm. Future
grants ride on whatever plan is devised to combat this terrible,
terrible problem.'')
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, there aren't that many gee-whiz findings in this report
that adults who take more than two minutes to think about it
couldn't figure out for themselves. It's just been packaged in a
way to make the information appear innovative.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the survey is totally without merit. It
is another bit of information that adults can consider when taking
a broad-brush look at today's youth. A very, very broad brush.
</P>
<P>
   But one has to question the survey's validity when children's
answers are filtered through adult eyes and adult mind-sets.
</P>
<P>
   One set of questions that are supposed to determine a child's
``positive identity'' asks whether the students feel they have
``control over things that happen to me.'' As a colleague of mine
said, junior high or high school age kids who believe they have
control over what happens are suffering from severe perception
problems.
</P>
<P>
   My stepdaughter, who is a charming, well-adjusted, intelligent
21-year-old completing her junior year at Texas Tech, would have
scored low on this category if she perceived her public school
years the way the adults in her life did. Teachers controlled her
school hours; coaches controlled her after-school hours; parents
controlled the majority of the remainder of her waking hours.
Alexis in control? You gotta be kidding.
</P>
<P>
   And exactly how does a sixth-grader or even an 11th-grader
define ``control''? Does that mean they decide what they wear? What
they eat for dinner? What they watch on TV? How late they get to
stay up _ or out? Most parents who are involved in their children's
lives would view a young person's total control over these things
as bad.
</P>
<P>
   And the notion that ``high self-esteem'' is necessary for a
positive identity _ please. I've known more than one kid with
``high self-esteem'' who could stand to be deflated a few notches.
Adults who value self-esteem over actual achievement are placing
the emphasis on the wrong area. A youngster who achieves in school
will automatically have increased self-esteem, and it will be based
on something other than squishy ``all hat and no cattle'' rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Caution needs to be exercised so that this survey doesn't take
on the status of divine wisdom, a 21st-century Rosetta stone for
figuring out young people.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7599. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
