<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-CONVENT-LIFE-$ADV16-H     04-14 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENT-LIFE-$ADV16-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRAYER HELPS GUIDE THOSE WHO MANAGE NURSING HOME NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 16)   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GERMANTOWN, N.Y. _ Lunch is ready for some 30 Carmelite Sisters
For the Aged and Infirm, gathered in the cavernous white dining
hall attached to their Motherhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Mary Suzanne, their superior general, is leading them in
grace, a prayer as familiar to devout Christians as the cool wood
of a pew. At once, the nuns bow their heads in prayer. Bless us, O
Lord, and these thy gifts, which we are about to receive, from Thy
bounty through Christ, Our Lord ...
</P>
<P>
   Their uniformity, of gesture and of brown habit, reinforces the
simple reverence, all the more striking when the nuns conclude,
Amen, and turn about-face.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Suzanne explains that a visitor is here and that they
should be themselves. This room, built to hold 100 novices, as it
once did in the 1960s, suddenly echoes with the laughter and voices
of the Carmelites.
</P>
<P>
   In one moment, they have shown two sides _ the contemplative and
the active _ that have been their watchwords since Saint Albert
wrote their guiding rule around 1206.
</P>
<P>
   It is the community's prayerful and joyful character that
resonates from one end of the motherhouse, where the nuns are
hashing over the news _ ``Well, poor Darryl Strawberry'' _ to the
other, which holds a shrine to their founder, Mother M. Angeline
Teresa.
</P>
<P>
   Mother M. Angeline ``felt that joy is always an important part
of religious life. She wanted there to be laughter in the convent.
She wanted there to be happiness in the convent,'' said Sister
Joseph Catherine.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholic religious communities are defined by their
``charism,'' or faith-inspired philosophy, which for the Carmelites
is the compassionate care of the elderly _ in their words, ``to
clasp the hand of an older person and give meaning to the autumn of
life.'' Charism also describes a community's personality, and for
that, meet Carmelites like Sister Madeline Angeline, who as
vocation director is on the frontline of the Carmelites'
recruitment.
</P>
<P>
   When Sister Theresa, one of two young novices here, first called
the Carmelites in this upstate New York community two years ago,
she got Sister Madeline. Sister Theresa's first question was
whether the Carmelites continued to wear the habit, a sign to her
of ``the consecrated life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Madeline's response: ``Yes, we wear it 25 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Madeline, by traveling to schools and college career
days, or navigating the Internet, also is responsible for putting a
human face to religious life. So, it is she who naturally relates
the story of a recent basketball game, between visiting nuns and
the Carmelites here. Complete with cheerleaders, the game, she says
as a finale, ``was to behold.''
</P>
<P>
   For a woman who carries the imposing title of superior general,
Mother Suzanne has a welcoming, natural presence as she and Sister
Joseph Catherine, the vicar general, the second-highest
officeholder, walk through the motherhouse.
</P>
<P>
   From here, Mother Suzanne oversees an order of 259 nuns, whose
community owns, co-sponsors or runs 31 nursing homes or related
facilities, in nine states and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The motherhouse, a monumental 19th-century Italianate villa
bought by the Carmelites in 1946, was one of the Hudson River
mansions built by the manorial Livingston family.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounding it are acres of rolling green and maple trees, their
bark shaggy with age, and behind the white stucco motherhouse, the
Hudson unspools in a thread of pearl blue.
</P>
<P>
   A breezeway connects the 1858 estate to a neo-classical chapel,
in turn connected to 1950s buildings where the 30 nuns do most of
their living and working.
</P>
<P>
   These buildings represent an era of flourishing growth. Founder
Mother M. Angeline during the 1950s and 1960s replaced a renovated
garage that housed novices with the three-story modern building,
built a retreat house and chaplain's quarters, and added the chapel
in place of the one that now holds her relics.
</P>
<P>
   Her presence is everywhere at the motherhouse, and the tone she
set when she founded this Carmelite order, in a vacant New York
City rectory in 1929, remains in her motherhouse and nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Born Brigid Teresa McCrory, this Irish immigrant originally
joined the French order of Little Sisters of the Poor. By the
1920s, Mother M. Angeline in her Bronx nursing home began
introducing small reforms, such as changing diet plans and allowing
residents to make homey touches to their quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes, made in a country with a higher standard of
living, caused a gulf between Mother M. Angeline and the order,
rooted in France's more institutional care of the poor, according
to her biographies. She and six nuns left the Little Sisters in
1929, two years later affiliating with the Carmel order, named for
the ridge in Palestine where the Virgin Mary is believed to have
visited the faithful hermits.
</P>
<P>
   In Carmelite nursing homes, Mother M. Angeline united married
couples, threw parties and dances, gave the elderly free run of
their rooms to decorate with their own furniture _ innovations from
a practical, witty woman who once characterized herself to The New
York Times as ``an adult Irish lady past 21.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to pass through the motherhouse, a gleaming
place with a floral scent, without seeing the serene-looking Mother
M. Angeline in various portraits. The Carmelites, too, have
transformed the first chapel into a heritage room. It is a stunning
collection of one person's life, with glass cases that display the
mundane, such as hairbrushes, passport, eyeglasses, and the sacred,
including the white mantle and habit she wore all her life and the
crown of white roses placed on her head when she died, on Jan. 21,
1984, her 91st birthday.
</P>
<P>
   One of her close associates, Sister Mary Gabriel, pointing to
the various ephemera, quotes one of the order's six original nuns.
``You save this because Mother is going to be a saint someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Her upstairs living quarters, too, have been converted to a
chapel; it is a contemplative place, and here, Mother Suzanne
prays, silently, momentarily, before an altar that holds a
sculpture of the Last Supper.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' she says simply, ``is holy ground.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the historic motherhouse, Sister Joseph Catherine and Mother
Suzanne discuss the days when the novitiate here brimmed with new
vocations. Mother Suzanne in 1968 entered the Carmelite order with
23 other postulants, or new applicants, in their first months of
religious life. In the early 1970s, the Carmelites numbered nearly
500 women. There are now 259, and the population is aging.
Typically, the Carmelites now accept one or two postulants each
year. Sisters Celine and Theresa, who were raised Roman Catholic in
Vietnam, are the latest, first-year novices.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 nuns live at the motherhouse, based there to administer
the community, to direct the novitiate, and to run the motherhouse
as a retreat and center of prayer for the whole congregation. Most
of the other nuns, however, live in convents at the nursing
facilities they run.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days of the 1950s, when women would enter the
convent directly after high school. Now, women are deciding about
religious life later, after they've experienced college and career,
much like their counterparts who delay marriage and family as they
pursue numerous options. And, indeed, among the Carmelites are
health administrators, registered nurses, physical therapists and
social workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for people to know we are alive and well and
happy in what we're doing, and to give them pause to think that
such a life is something they should consider,'' Mother Suzanne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, their recruitment also is rooted in prayer. ``I'm
hope-filled. Our mission in the church is a very needed one. It
certainly is the work of God. Because it's such a needed ministry,
I think the Lord will continue to provide for our needs, maybe not
in the same way as in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
