<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-PLATFORM-SHOES-HNS &LR;      04-14 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLATFORM-SHOES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PLATFORM SHOE LOVERS ARE ON TOP OF THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRISTI L. GUSTAFSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ When Ashlee Danford, 16, makes her way through
the halls of Averill Park High School, she's eye-to-eye with about
half of her fellow students, standing ``tall'' at 5-feet-5-inches.
But when she returns home to play with her Shih Tzu, Rascal, she
shrinks down to 4-feet-11-inches.
</P>
<P>
   Danford has joined the ranks of young women who are wearing
platform shoes. From the malls to the office to the dance floors on
Friday and Saturday nights, many women are making the `70s-era
stompers the shoe of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Skelly, 26, of Schenectady even wears platform sneakers
_ she has three pairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate wearing flat shoes,'' Skelly said. ``They're not only
yucky and plain, but uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Skelly owns 75 pairs of shoes, most of them platforms, and only
one pair of flats.
</P>
<P>
   The flats are a requirement for Skelly's culinary studies at
Schenectady County Community College. For safety reasons, she is
not allowed in the school's kitchen in her platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I get out of school, I kick them off,'' Skelly
said. ``There's no way I'm wearing them in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the platform shoe falls into two categories _ the
wedgie, where the entire bottom is one chunky piece, and the true
platform, where the sole and heel are separate.
</P>
<P>
   Skelly has mastered the balancing act of platforms and only
feels comfortable in the chunky sole. When she's cooking away from
school, she wears her platform shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be running around in my chef's apron and hat cooking
dinner for a big group of family and friends and everyone always
makes fun of me,'' Skelly said. ``They think it's funny that I
manage not to slip or trip when I'm trying to do so many things at
once.''
</P>
<P>
   Skelly goes from 5-3 to what she calls a more desirable height
in her platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize I'm short until I have to take my shoes
off at someone's house,'' she said. ``At least one person always
comments on how I shrank.''
</P>
<P>
   Danford echos Skelly. ``I'm not even at the 5-foot mark, but no
one really notices because my shoes make me 5-4 to 5-5 every day,''
she said. ``That's good, though, because even though I'm used to my
height, I want to be taller.''
</P>
<P>
   Platform shoes, which were popular in the East for centuries,
were introduced to Europe in the 16th century. Known as chopines,
the shoes had soles up to 2 feet high. Customarily, two servants
would support a woman wearing these shoes, reinforcing the image of
a woman as frail and dependent.
</P>
<P>
   Today, seeing men in platforms is uncommon, but it was popular
in Europe in the 17th century. King Louis XIV was unhappy with his
height and began a movement to platform shoes among men. Some had
soles as high as 5 inches and were decorated with battle scenes.
</P>
<P>
   The ancient Romans wore platform shoes to keep their feet out of
the mud and water. The style was revived in the 1930s, the `70s and
again in the `90s in the United States, but strictly for fashion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Platforms have been a cause for arrest in Tokyo, where many
traffic accidents are blamed on women's inability to properly sense
the pedals and to react quickly while driving.
</P>
<P>
   Skelly used to find driving difficult and would drive in one
bare foot, but no longer feels the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Platform shoes can be just as tough for pedestrians, reducing
some women to lying sprawled on the sidewalk. Still, fashion reigns
supreme and women keep wearing the high-risk shoes.
</P>
<P>
   And they are slightly safer and more comfortable than
skinny-heeled stilettos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Platforms can cause back, hip and knee pain. It is usually
short-term,'' said Dr. Michael Dudick, a chiropractor, ``but the
foot damage that comes along with stilettos is not so much a factor
with platform shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudick said the height of the sole should be a factor in
choosing to wear platforms. He has seen girls as young as 15 in
shoes stacked to what he called a comical level.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a young girl is walking around looking like Herman
Munster, she runs the risk of twisting, or even spraining her
ankle, and that's probably the biggest problem associated with the
shoes,'' he said. ``For a singular event, they're fine, but I
strongly discourage women from wearing them on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Bad Fads Museum (http://www.badfads.com),
platforms are often referred to as ``the Elevated Orthopedic
Nightmare.'' In the 1960s, the shoes were only one or two inches
high but grew in height and variety until hospital emergency rooms
were routinely treating people for twisted or broken ankles.
</P>
<P>
   The media have always helped to both dictate and rule fashion.
Sally Struthers wore platforms on the popular 1970s sitcom ``All in
the Family.'' Struthers wore the shoes to shorten the height gap
between her and co-star Rob Reiner, but had to practice walking in
them before wearing them on the air, according to Barbara Williams,
curator at The Shoe Museum of the Temple University School of
Podiatric Medicine in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent addition to the museum is a pair of 6-inch blue
satin platform sandals worn by Struthers, as Gloria, on the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm addicted to platforms,'' Skelly said. ``If I have money to
spend, the shoe store is the first place I go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CHICKEN-NUGGETS-1STLD     04-14 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-NUGGETS-1STLD-$ADV16-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALABAMA PLANTS OVERWHELMED WITH SICK CHICKENS, REPORT FINDS
 &HT;    Eds: For background, adds new graf 11 starting ``At the same
time ...,'' adds sentence to graf 3 starting ``The report did
not....''
 &HT;    790&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories
for release Sunday, April 16.
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Gold Kist Inc. poultry processing plants in
Alabama that supply chicken to school lunch programs nationwide
were overwhelmed earlier this year by diseased poultry, federal
investigators have reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many birds condemned that they were filling up
the 'USDA condemned' barrel and spilling onto the floor,'' the
report, obtained by Cox Newspapers, says of conditions at Gold
Kist's Boaz plant.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the chickens arriving on Feb. 9 were
infected with a respiratory disease called airsacculitis that
leaves pus inside the carcass, one federal worker told an
investigator for the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Office of
Inspector General (OIG). The report did not say how many chickens
arrived at the plant tat day, but typically it processes tens of
thousands of birds a day.
</P>
<P>
   At a plant in Guntersville that is using an experimental food
inspection system, the report found that Gold Kist failed to
identify substantial numbers of diseased carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   Under the experimental program, company workers instead of
federal inspectors are supposed to find and remove substandard
poultry. But the report cited government records showing that on
Feb. 7, 28 percent of birds selected in government spot checks
after being approved by the company were diseased, typically with
airsacculitis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite conditions inside the plants, the inspector general's
office said it was dropping the matter because ``there is no
allegation of any deliberate violation of law or direct threat to
public health.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bekkers, Gold Kist president and chief operating officer,
said in a statement posted on its Web site: ``As we have assured
our customers all along, Gold Kist Farms brand chicken products are
safe, wholesome and good to eat. We appreciate that this was
recognized in the OIG report.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Atlanta-based company refused to be
interviewed, offering instead to reply to written questions. Cox
Newspapers declined that offer.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson at the inspector general's office in Washington
declined to discuss the March 3 report.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's office launched its investigation in
early February after Cox Newspapers detailed allegations by several
federal food safety inspectors at the Guntersville and Boaz plants.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, school districts in a number of states stopped
using Gold Kist chicken nuggets, and a test by the Ohio Department
of Agriculture found Listeria, a deadly pathogen, in one lot of the
product. Gold Kist issued a recall of its chicken nuggets on Feb.
23, but no illnesses were linked to the product.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to determining whether the inspectors' allegations
were true, the report says that Agriculture Department officials
asked the OIG to determine if ``internal agency documents (were
given) to the press.'' The report says it found ``no basis for
further investigation'' of leaks.
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors said that because of widespread disease in Gold
Kist chicken flocks, both processing plants were being inundated
with diseased poultry.
</P>
<P>
   While such birds are normally condemned, the inspectors said
that under the experimental food inspection system at the
Guntersville facility, some diseased poultry was being used to make
chicken nuggets for school lunch programs.
</P>
<P>
   The chicken nuggets are not considered a threat to human health
because the poultry diseases cannot be transmitted to human beings.
However, inspectors said they considered carcasses with scabs,
sores and pus to be ``unwholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the inspectors' allegations were published,
Bekkers issued a press release defending the quality of his product
and charging that ``the public is being misled by a few
union-activist USDA poultry inspectors.'' He said that there was
``no factual support for their claims.''
</P>
<P>
   But a week after Bekkers' statement was issued, a Gold Kist
official acknowledged to an OIG investigator that ``airsacculitis
... had been moving through the flocks and infecting chickens.''
The name of the executive was deleted in the copy of the report
obtained by Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Billy, head of the Agriculture Department's Food Safety and
Inspection Service, released a statement Feb. 11 saying the
government had ``excellent controls'' at the plant and that food
from the plant can be ``eaten with confidence.'' He also said, ``We
have no reason to believe products leaving these Gold Kist Plants
is anything other than safe and wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the OIG's report quoted federal inspectors who were
complaining that ``they are not allowed to remove birds at any
point.'' The report lists the results of inspections made at
Guntersville on Feb. 5, 7 and 8. A sampling of chickens made by
federal inspectors _ after Gold Kist workers had supposedly culled
out diseased carcasses _ found that between 11 and 28 percent of
the birds were diseased. Federal rules permit a maximum of 3
percent of a sample to contain diseased birds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Agriculture Department's press office did not
respond to repeated requests for an interview with Billy.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The OIG's report raises questions about what exactly the
government means when it says food products are wholesome.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law forbids the sale of poultry for human consumption if
it is ``adulterated or misbranded'' at the time of sale. If it is
``unsound, unhealthful, unwholesome, or otherwise unfit for human
food,'' it is considered ``adulterated.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the report said that the ``inquiry did not disclose any
adulteration of product.''
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department officials have declined repeated requests
over several weeks to provide an explanation of the meaning of the
term ``wholesome'' in the law.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Smith DeWaal, food safety director at the
Washington-based Center for Science in the Public Interest, said
wholesome ``is meant to describe conditions that would not only
make the food unhealthy or unsafe, but also would be unappealing.
It is not food a consumer would knowingly want to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The OIG report said that an inspector at the Boaz plant told
investigators about the chicken leaving the plant, ``as far as (he
or she) knows it is not unsafe, but (he or she) would not it it
personally. (He or she) thinks the public should know that sores
and scabs are going into it.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.goldkist.com/agknews041200oig.html
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Jaspin's e-mail address is elliotj(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
