   &UR; FOR SATURDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, April 15:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks took a beating as investors reacted
to the inflation data. At 2:30 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 429 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 57 points, and the
Nasdaq composite index down 230 points, extending its losses for a
fifth consecutive session. European stock markets were also lower:
London was down 2.64 percent and Frankfurt down 2.88 percent. In
Japan, the Nikkei closed down 0.45 percent; Hong Kong's Hang Seng
ended down 1.28 percent. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ Consumer prices accelerated more than
expected in March, reviving fears of higher inflation and putting
pressure on the Federal Reserve to step up its series of interest
rate increases. The Consumer Price Index rose 0.7 percent last
month, the biggest increase in 11 months. More important, the core
index _ which excludes food and energy, which accounted for half of
the gain in the CPI _ rose 0.4 percent, as costs increased for
clothing, housing, medical care and airfares. The gain, which
follows a 0.2 percent increase in February, was the largest since
January 1995. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ANTIQUARIANS (Undated) _ Ordinarily the antiquarian trade
is the dusty, genteel corner of the book market that attracts
fiercely independent booksellers who savor the musty fragrance of
brown-spotted rag paper and the Eureka moment of spotting a rare
first edition dumped in a garage sale heap. But now the dust motes
are flying in the rare and used book market with the flashy
emergence of Alibris, a virtual used bookseller with Wall Street
ambitions and Silicon Valley money. The hostilities that Alibris
has provoked among some traditional booksellers mirrors the same
tensions that other industries are facing over issues of
consolidation and the loss of personal connections. Virtual
bookselling has been a boon to used book dealers because it opens
the market to customers around the world and offered freedom to
sell these books from isolated outposts. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ-REORG (New York) _ The National Association of Securities
Dealers members vote overwhelmingly to turn the Nasdaq stock market
into a private, for-profit company. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-PAYOUT (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Ford Motor says it will pay
shareholders as much as $10 billion and spin off its Visteon
Automotive Systems parts unit this summer. It appears to be the
largest single special payout to shareholders ever. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-LOSSES (Mountain View, Calif.) _ The view from inside an
Internet company, HearMe, that has lost 40 percent of its value in
the last week (and 75 percent since the day it went public a year
ago) amid the general Nasdaq upheaval. Hope springs eternal. By
Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   TRIBNUE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ The Tribune Co. plans to name John
Puerner of The Orlando Sentinel publisher of The Los Angeles Times
and John Carroll of The Baltimore Sun, editor of The Times, after
the company takes control of Times Mirror. The Tribune also reports
an 18 percent rise in first-quarter earnings before one-time items,
matching analysts' estimates. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-DEBT (Sao Paulo) _ A look at a long-running financial
scandal surrounding the mayor of Sao Paulo, which has left the city
mired in billions of dollars in debt and risking insolvency. By
Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (London) _ BMW says it has received a second bid for
its Rover unit from a consortium led by a former chief executive of
Rover. The new bid may complicate BMW's negotiations to transfer
Rover Cars to Alchemy Partners, a London-based venture capital
group. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMS (Moscow) _ Russia's parliament on Friday approved
the long-delayed START II treaty on scrapping thousands of U.S. and
Russian nuclear warheads, clearing the way for further arms
reduction. Final approval, from the upper house, is seen as
assured. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-AFRICA-TRADE (Washington) _ A deal struck in the U.S.
Senate paves the way for action on a trade bill that would extend
new trade benefits to African, Central American and Caribbean
nations. (Summary from wires) By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   IMF-PROTEST (Washington) _ An examination of just who will be
among the protesters at the International Monetary Fund and World
Bank meetings in Washington this weekend. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as needed.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-POLITICS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The opposition was
scheduled to hold its first major anti-Milosevic rally this year on
Friday. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   REDCROSS-ISRAEL (Geneva) _ The International Red Cross decides
to try to get members to adopt a ``neutral'' emblem that would pave
the way for Israel to enter the group. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Day's developments: The government responds
to a request for an injunction delaying the transfer of Elian
Gonzalez to his father. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-CASTRO (Miami) _ At school, at home and in the
community, Elian has been surrounded by anti-Castro rhetoric for
five months. Soon he will be in Cuba, exposed to anti-American
rhetoric. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   Other sidebars as appropriate.
