<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN CHILD DRAMA IS BACK IN COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The relatives of Elian Gonzalez appeared Friday to have
temporarily thwarted government efforts to reunite the boy quickly
with his father by forcing the custody fight into the arena where
they had always wanted it: the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said Friday that they would not try
to take Elian from his Miami relatives until a federal court in
Atlanta reviewed a temporary stay order issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Judge J.L. Edmondson of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
in Atlanta had said Elian could not leave the United States for
now, effectively barring the 6-year-old's father from immediately
taking his son back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The order came Thursday, shortly after Lazaro Gonzalez, the
boy's great-uncle, defied government instructions to take Elian to
a waiting airplane by 2 p.m. on Thursday for a reunion with his
father in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family is now in non-compliance to federal instructions to
them,'' Maria Cardona, a spokeswoman with the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said in a telephone interview Friday. ``So
we will be moving forward with an enforcement action plan to
enforce our order at the most appropriate time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cardona said the government would not act until a
three-judge panel reviewed the temporary stay, which could happen
as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of mounting tension, emotions cooled Friday in the
Little Havana neighborhood where protesters choked the streets
daily this week. Friday morning, a cluster of people waited in a
steady rain outside the Gonzalez family home as the focus of the
custody fight turned to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Edmondson also gave the government until Friday
morning to respond to a court injunction request filed on Monday by
lawyers for the Miami relatives. U.S. officials filed a brief at
10:45 a.m., asking the court to order the relatives to hand over
Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   The brief said that the relatives had violated government orders
to surrender the boy by Thursday, and that the court should not aid
the relatives until they handed over Elian, Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   If the boy is turned over immediately to his father, Cardona
said, the government would bar the father from taking Elian out of
the country until a court appeals process is resolved. The father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who flew from Cuba to claim his son, has said
he would remain in the United States if the custody fight became a
prolonged legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of Cuban-Americans, Elian's great-uncle is
reluctant to see the boy returned to his homeland. For weeks, he
has been defying government efforts to claim the boy, hoping to
stall until the Atlanta appellate court can review his case. He has
asked the court to compel the INS to grant the boy an asylum
hearing, and oral arguments are scheduled to begin on May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials said Friday that they did not know when a
three-judge panel would review the temporary stay or when it would
rule on the injunction request. The injunction asked the court to
prevent Elian from leaving the country until an appeals process
initiated by the Miami relatives starts in mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Miami relatives have also gone to a federal
court in Washington to try to prevent the boy from being taken out
of the country, arguing that such an action might violate the boy's
human rights. Judge Henry H. Kennedy Jr. of U.S. District Court in
Washington said Friday that he will review the request on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials had told the family to take Elian by 2 p.m. on
Thursday to Opa-Locka Airport, near Miami. But the deadline came
and went, and Elian's relatives remained in their home with the
boy. When the government took no action, a crowd of about 4,000
supporters, mostly Cuban-Americans who are opposed to the
government of President Fidel Castro, pumped their fists in the air
and shouted ``Justice! Justice! Justice!''
</P>
<P>
   Some tore apart stuffed dummies of Castro. Others called the
Atlanta court's intervention a ``miracle.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said on Thursday that U.S. marshals
would not immediately try to take the boy if the deadline passed,
and that a government response would be ``reasoned and measured.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday night, Reno failed in a nearly three-hour meeting
with the boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, to elicit promises to
hand over the boy. The Justice Department immediately issued its
ultimatum.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Doris Meissner, the INS commissioner, flew to Miami
Wednesday to try to persuade the family to accompany them to
Washington. But after Reno met Elian and negotiated with his
great-uncle at the Miami Beach villa of Sister Jeanne O'Laughlin, a
Roman Catholic nun, the attorney general left the home
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was given temporary residency status and placed in the
care of his great-uncle after fishermen discovered him floating in
an inner-tube off the Florida coast on Nov. 25. The boy was one of
three survivors of a capsized refugee boat. His mother, who was
divorced from the boy's father, and 10 other Cubans had drowned.
</P>
</TEXT>
