A6908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-CO     04-14 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: They don't make chili like this
anymore
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Neighbor, can I borrow a cup of suet?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if you can spare it, I need a little more than a cup.
</P>
<P>
   Say, three pounds?
</P>
<P>
   It's for a recipe that's come my way for homemade chili.
</P>
<P>
   Doggone if I haven't let my supply of suet run low. And you
never have too much suet.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you of the tofu persuasion, I'm talking about pure
rendered fat, the stuff that used to make everything from turnip
greens to fried green tomatoes taste all the better for it.
</P>
<P>
   I say used to.
</P>
<P>
   Folks who have given up the joys of living in an effort to live
forever have forsaken staples such as suet in our more enlightened
times.
</P>
<P>
   This particular recipe comes from a different time.
</P>
<P>
   It's from the old Eat-A-Bite Cafe which, long, long ago, was
located downtown on First Street in a miniature, cottage-like
building, so small there was no room for tables, only stools at the
counter.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, most all the stools were occupied.
</P>
<P>
   You could get a good hamburger there, but the Eat-A-Bite Cafe's
homemade chili was what it was famous for.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, it was a secret recipe presumed to have been lost
years ago when the little cafe finally closed its doors for the
last time, an eventual casualty of the highway bypass having routed
traffic and business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   I would imagine that the cook has long since departed this
world. For that matter, so have most of the people who ate there,
particularly those who ate there regularly, casualities in need of
a bypass themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But now it turns out that the chili recipe has survived after
all.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow I know passed along the details, scribbled onto a 3x5
card by, I'm told, a waitress who had wanted the recipe for
herself.
</P>
<P>
   How he came by it, he didn't say and I didn't ask.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, in the interest of preserving history _ though
perhaps not lives _ I have acquired a copy, which I hereby pass
along to posterity:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Eat-A-Bite Cafe's Homemade Chili
</P>
<P>
   12 pounds chili meat
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds of suet (rendered out fat)
</P>
<P>
   Add meat to fat, cook for 30 minutes. Stir often on low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add to meat:
</P>
<P>
   2 tbs. salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tbs. garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tbs. cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 qt. water
</P>
<P>
   Cook 30 minutes. Stir occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl, mix 1/2 pound chili blend mix, 1 small box
paprika, 2 pounds flour.
</P>
<P>
   Add water to make a paste thin enough to pour, add to meat
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Add between 1 pint and 1 qt. water to desired consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Cook on low heat, stirring occasionally, for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Skim excess fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   That's assuming there is such a thing as excess fat.
</P>
<P>
   Eat at your own risk. Enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. The recipe doesn't suggest how many it'll feed. But any
culinary concoction that requires two pounds of flour most likely
will take care of a fair-sized crowd.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. I checked with a local meat market. Suet is still
available, at 89 cents a pound. You have to wonder how they can
sell it so cheap.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(AT)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
