<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-BILL-RUSSELL-HNS &LR;      04-14 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BILL-RUSSELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HBO TO AIR PROGRAM ON BASKETBALL STAR BILL RUSSELL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The genesis of HBO's documentary ``Bill Russell:
My Life, My Way'' occurred one day when Russell was visiting with
his grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   They posed the question: ``Were you better than Michael
Jordan?''
</P>
<P>
   And in typical there's-never-an-easy-answer Russell fashion, he
pointed out two things: A) They got the question backwards; and B)
Grandpa was the one the young Michael Jordan wanted to be when he
grew up.
</P>
<P>
   It was an exchange that compelled the man who has a longstanding
reputation of being private and reclusive to agree to sit in front
of a television camera and discuss his legendary life and career.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the one-hour HBO documentary, which debuts Monday
at 10 p.m. and airs four more times by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Russell and longtime friend and business associate Alan Hillburg
took the idea of the show to HBO and with HBO's track record of
compelling sports programming, it seemed like a good fit. There
are, it can be argued, few more personalities in the history of
sport more compelling than Russell.
</P>
<P>
   As per usual with HBO sports shows, it is an interesting,
insightful hour which will satisfy older viewers' cravings for
nostalgia and will give younger viewers an increasingly rare view
of an athlete who had aspirations beyond individual achievement and
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The show begins with Russell's Monroe, La., roots and his move
to Oakland, Calif., as a young child. It moves on to document his
illustrious but not always glorious career as a college star at the
University of San Francisco (two national championships) and his
even more illustrious professional career with the Boston Celtics
in which he won 11 NBA titles in 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's years at USF come across as a bittersweet time for the
team's star player. Russell said he felt that part of the show was
accurately portrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like that,'' Russell said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the show is light on the basketball, or as Russell
put it ``It doesn't show why I was as good as I was. The focus was
not as much on Russell the player, as on Russell the leader, the
social activist and the sometimes prickly personality.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Russell's ever-present perspective _ he is
interviewed throughout the program _ other interview subjects
include former Celtics coach Red Auerbach, former teammates Bob
Cousy, John Thompson, John Havlicek, K.C. Jones and Sam Jones; and
Russell's daughter Karen.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his input, Russell isn't sure how well the show reflects
who he is and who he was as a basketball player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very serious,'' Russell said Thursday morning. ``I'm not
that serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor does he view himself as a recluse, a label he couldn't
manage to escape even in a show that he helped to initiate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that as being true,'' Russell said. ``I don't know
anyone who has a completely open life. I like to keep things as
small as possible. If they are smaller, they are less complicated.
I just do what I like to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
