<HEADER>
A6949 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-CONGO-335&AMP;ADD-NY     04-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CONGO-335&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLBROOKE TO LEAD SECURITY COUNCIL DELEGATION TO CONGO AHEAD OF
PEACEKEEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. representative to
the United Nations, has agreed to lead a Security Council
delegation early in May to Congo, where the council plans to send a
peacekeeping operation this year.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for the Security Council trip and the deployment
of a monitoring and peacekeeping mission are still in some doubt,
however, as fighting was reported in Congo Friday, a day after a
cease-fire was to go into effect. The war, in which about half a
dozen African countries are involved, pits the Congo government of
President Laurent Kabila against rebels backed by his former
allies, Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   As the council was meeting Friday, there were also reports of a
series of explosions at the international airport at Kinshasa, the
capital of Congo. U.N. officials said they were told a Boeing 707,
possibly a military plane, had crashed into a fuel truck, setting
off the explosions. News reports from Kinshasa said that stores of
ammunition had exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations was told that there had been numerous
injuries, but there was no information on casualties. Officials
here were told that half the airport complex had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of a Security Council mission to Congo _ one of
the riskiest in a series of trips that council members are making
to view the organization's work in the field _ was made Friday
during a council debate on Rwanda six years after the genocide
there that left hundreds of thousands dead.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the debate was a tough report last December that
held both the United Nations and leading member countries, in
particular the United States, responsible for a failure to prevent
or stop the 1994 genocidal campaign by Hutu militias against ethnic
Tutsi and their Hutu supporters. The report, prepared by a team led
by Ingvar Carlsson, a former Swedish prime minister, was
commissioned by Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who had been the head
of U.N. peacekeeping.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Holbrooke said Friday of his Congo mission that ``I believe it
is a mission that we hope will avoid another meeting like this one
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all Security Council members drew lessons Friday from the
Rwanda report about the lack of good information and analysis on
warnings of planned genocide, along with a tendency to hide behind
the limited instructions U.N. peacekeepers had in Rwanda and the
promises by parties involved in ethnic conflict to observe a
ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
   ``From its inception, the United Nations assistance mission for
Rwanda,'' said Patricia Durrant, Jamaica's ambassador, ``was
hindered by a poorly conceived mandate, the lack of the necessary
resources to carry out that mandate and the political will on the
part of the Security Council to take critical decisions at a time
when the forces on the ground could ill afford undue delay.'' Too
often, she added, peacekeeping operations are made too small for
the sake of ``political expediency.''
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda's ambassador, Joseph W. Mutaboba, had the last word in
Friday's debate. ``Thanks for the statements,'' he said, ``but what
next?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My country, Rwanda, wishes to hear from you all about the
policies and measures this body has taken or has intention of
putting in place to make sure that what happened in Rwanda _ and we
witnessed through the screens of our television sets _ does never
again occur elsewhere on this globe,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Congo operation of 5,537 people, most of whom would be
ceasefire monitors and support workers rather than troops, is not
intended to be deployed until a cease-fire holds. But even that
distant hope could be jeopardized if the U.S. Congress blocks U.S.
financial contributions to the force and others that are already
deployed. Such a move is now under way in a committee that
appropriates money for several departments including the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke, who is working hard to reduce congressional antipathy
toward the United Nations by trying to win a reduction of U.S. dues
to the organization, is also having to fight in both houses of
Congress against opponents of U.S. backing for international
peacekeeping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
