<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARZUN-CULTURAL-HISTORY (Undated) _ Jacques Barzun, one of the
founders of ``cultural history,'' taught history at Columbia for
nearly 50 years and led legendary seminars with Lionel Trilling. He
has written over 30 books, translated nearly a dozen more, and now,
at 92, has finished an epic chronicle of his historical forays, a
survey of 500 years of Western cultural life. By Edward Rothstein.
(1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   BACH-FUGUES (Undated) _ The fugue is a drama not about the
individual voice at large in a society of sound, but a drama about
a society of sound created by related individual voices. It is an
astonishing structure, constructed with intense concentration. Bach
was so renowned for his fugues that after King Frederick II of
Prussia challenged him to improvise a fugue based upon a
mischievously slithering theme, Bach countered with a masterpiece
of inventive play, ``The Musical Offering.'' By Edward Rothstein.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NSYNC (Undated) _ A Critic's Notebook: Why 'N Sync is so
popular. By Jon Pareles.
</P>
<P>
   TV-COPPERFIELD-REVIEW (Undated) _ On PBS, ``David Copperfield.''
By Neil Genzlinger.
</P>
