<HEADER>
A6956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.S.-AFRICA-TRADE-NYT     04-14 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-AFRICA-TRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS AGREES ON TRADE RULES FOR AFRICA, CENTRAL AMERICA,
CARIBBEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of tough negotiations, Senate and
House leaders have agreed on new trade terms for countries in
Africa, Central America and the Caribbean, setting the stage for
congressional approval in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators reached a breakthrough late Thursday, agreeing to
provide a measure of protection for U.S. textile manufacturers,
though not as much as the industry and its allies in the Senate had
sought.
</P>
<P>
   Senate negotiators yielded a bit to their House counterparts on
that issue, accepting an arrangement on imports of African clothing
that would gradually open more markets to African weavers over the
next eight years. Senators had earlier pressed for a requirement
that clothing made in Africa be fashioned from U.S. fabric and
thread.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the talks said Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois and Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader,
personally intervened late Thursday to revive the discussions.
Those close to the talks said that many details remain to be worked
out, but that with the backing of Lott and Hastert they can be
resolved in time for final passage. That is expected to take place
when lawmakers return from their spring recess late this month.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative accord was heartening for President Clinton, who
has made legislation extending new trade benefits to Africa,
Central America and Caribbean countries a top priority. The White
House hopes an accord on countries in those regions will be a
prelude to an agreement on a far more contentious issue,
normalizing trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from textile-industry states have been fighting the
current legislation, as have some unions and environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   The House originally backed a bill dealing only with several
dozen sub-Saharan African nations. Senators favored a bill that
covered those countries plus two dozen in the Caribbean and Central
America. People familiar with the deal reached Thursday said House
negotiators agreed to cover those additional nations.
</P>
<P>
   As a concession to U.S. textile interests, T-shirts made in
Caribbean and Central American countries would be subject to some
barriers not applied to other clothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6957 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-REVIEW-GOULD-HNS     04-14 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-GOULD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `JOE GOULD'S SECRET' ASKS THE UNANSWERABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Joe Gould's Secret'' asks questions that may not have an
answer, and it asks them more than once.
</P>
<P>
   What's the difference between a starving artist and a deadbeat?
At what point does ``eccentric'' become ``grotesque''? How much do
artists owe to the guilt of the rich? Are we all basically
forgettable? Does a writer steal the soul of people he puts down on
paper, or do they end up stealing his soul?
</P>
<P>
   This movie is about the sometime friendship between Joe
Mitchell, a writer for the New Yorker, and a graying
poet-bohemian-bungler-drunk named Joe Gould, a tirading bowser who
lives in the prewar oddness of Manhattan, wearing two shirts at a
time, finding shelter in midnight sitting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, whose New Yorker pieces were compiled in the
best-selling ``Up in the Old Hotel'' in 1992, follows Gould around,
getting glimpses of a lifestyle that includes ritual begging,
seagull-like honks and tics, bare-chested war dances for giggling
drinkers at midtown parties and a 1,000-page project called ``The
Oral History of Our Time.''
</P>
<P>
   When the New Yorker prints an article on Gould in December 1942
titled ``Professor Seagull,'' both men's lives are changed. Gould,
who strutted around with Mitchell during interviews, talking about
``my biographer,'' clings to Mitchell long after the article comes
out. He tries to grow into the Gould of ``Professor Seagull,''
becoming both larger and smaller in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The good looks, sounds, sights and acting in ``Joe Gould's
Secret'' owe a lot to director Stanley Tucci, who plays Mitchell.
Tucci insisted that Gould be played by Ian Holm, the English actor
he starred with in ``Big Night,'' a highly praised 1996 film of
Italian immigrants opening a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Holm and Tucci are as brilliant in ``Secret'' as they were in
``Big Night,'' offering that same sense of falling face-down into a
vat of life, sending globs of it across the faces of everyone
within splashing distance. Holm, especially, is memorable,
agonizingly true to a character who is half artist, half phony.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is outstanding, from Hope Davis to Vivian Marquie to
Susan Sarandon. But the movie belongs to Tucci and Gould with no
room, really, for anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take long to get a sense of Gould. He orders a bowl
of soup at his regular corner cafe and slams half a bottle of
ketchup into it before the owner grabs it out of his hands. At the
Minetta Tavern, a bartender leans over to tell Mitchell that Gould
is ``good for business. You know, the tourists come in, you tell
'em you've got a real Bohemian over there, and they go, 'Oooooooo.
'''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Gould sits in the cafe complaining about a lack of
respect, reciting his knowledge of books and Indians and the
beauties of everyday life ``and all they can do is rag me about
ketchup!'' Gould makes sure Mitchell knows, up front, that he
graduated from Harvard in 1911, magna cum laude, and that he
numbers Ezra Pound and e.e. cummings among his pals.
</P>
<P>
   As with most self-styled eccentrics, a little of Gould goes a
long way. Mitchell is eventually faced with the fear all writers
live with _ that someone they write about will dog them, day and
night.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's beautifully ordinary existence, a waltz of quiet days
with his wife and two daughters, is constantly disrupted by Gould,
who comes by to cadge drinks or dollars or donations to ``The Oral
History of Our Time,'' the secret at the heart of ``Joe Gould.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mitchell balks at the disruptions, his wife reminds him
people's lives don't exist in 10-page vignettes _ ``their story
doesn't end just because you're finished writing.'' It frightens
people, she points out, to be thought of and forgotten, that
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Once Gould appears in the New Yorker he becomes a favorite of
the well-to-do, picking up an anonymous patron in the process.
Gould, who has spent his entire life living on the edge, is
suddenly comfortable. It's his undoing.
</P>
<P>
   At one point he bares sore-encrusted legs to a longtime friend
and painter (Sarandon). The woman washes his feet _ Mary Magdalene
scouring the feet of Jesus _ but Gould is all too human. He wants
her to see the sores, to feel her pity. At the end of his rope,
he's still half artist, half phony.
</P>
<P>
   While Gould is wasting away, his friends wring their hands,
wondering how much will be lost if the anonymous voices in ``The
Oral History of Our Time'' are never heard. But there are anonymous
voices all around, every day, every minute. Damon Runyon and Studs
Terkel wrote about that.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gould, himself, was anonymous. His gift, his whispered
secret, his two-shirts, bohemian rapture, stands out because he
fought for so long against the anonymity he knew was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   For all his artistry, Mitchell was pretty anonymous, as well.
There was a drought between Mitchell's work of the '40s and ``Joe
Gould's Secret,'' which appeared in the New Yorker in 1962.
Mitchell continued to work for the magazine as writer and editor,
but he did not have another article printed in the 32 years left in
his writing life.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves open that last question: Whose soul is it that was
being stolen?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1549EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     04-14 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL TV FORECAST: WHO WILL STAY, WHO WILL GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As network programmers assess which shows must be kept, which
will be discarded, and how the holes will be filled, it's clear
that ABC is sitting on its newly minted throne all fat and content.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' has become the glory and curse
of this TV season, but ABC is, understandably, only concerned with
the former. With such a ratings provider _ and killer _ at its
disposal, ABC surely isn't breaking much of a sweat in the search
for fall pilots to fill slots vacated by dead-and-goners like
``Wasteland'' and painfully wounded shows such as the uneven, but
still-smarter-than-most ``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   But the competition certainly is. ``Millionaire'' figures
prominently in the plans of not just ABC but every other network
competitor _ except, perhaps, UPN, which, with its desperate desire
for young men (that didn't come out right, did it?) is playing its
own game.
</P>
<P>
   As the networks prepare the 2000-2001 fall lineups, which will
be announced by mid-May, they're being careful to avoid
``Millionaire,'' both with new shows and with many shows they're
planning to bring back.
</P>
<P>
   It only adds to the tension of this annual chess game of what's
in, what's out, and what should go where. With less than a month
before fall lineups are announced, the usual suspects _ ``Law &AMP;
Order,'' ``The Practice,'' ``Touched by an Angel,'' ``ER'' and
``X-Files,'' if David Duchovny re-ups _ are safe while the comedies
have been far less impressive, with the exception of NBC's ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' and, to a lesser extent, a few other top sitcoms like
``Friends'' and ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, having rewarded its cast with Porsches, NBC has now
given ``Will &AMP; Grace'' a two-year commitment and the unofficial
stamp of Comedy of the Future. ``Friends'' remains a bona fide hit,
in ratings and episode-by-episode quality, but let's face it: How
long can those actors remain together? How long can NBC afford
them? How long can NBC keep ``Will &AMP; Grace'' off Thursday night?
</P>
<P>
   The network, as well as its competitors, are suffering from the
current drought of decent half-hour comedies, which helps explain
the number of comedies that could very well get the ax. Aside from
Fox's hilarious ``Malcolm in the Middle,'' which has managed to
attract 16 million viewers a week AND the blessing of critics, new
sitcoms this season have, for the most part, fallen flat.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the comedies are along the lines of ABC's midseason
hopeful ``Talk to Me,'' with film actress Kyra Sedgwick portraying
a talk radio host; NBC's ``Battery Park,'' a ``Barney Miller''-type
police station comedy; and ``Daddio,'' also on NBC, with Michael
Chiklis as a househusband. All of these series arrived with a
rather loud thud, partly because they're trying far too hard to be
wacky rather than funny.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of ``King of Queens'' and ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' the twosome carrying Monday nights on CBS, even
established shows in the genre are in trouble. While I have yet to
see a second of Charlie Sheen on ``Spin City,'' there's little
doubt that the series will suffer terribly without Michael J. Fox
next season, and even the scripts of the once feisty ``Dharma and
Greg'' have been noticeably lifeless lately.
</P>
<P>
   There are, to be sure, a batch of shows whose cancellations
would only be met with satisfaction, if not outright glee. NBC
Entertainment President Garth Ancier decided to give the struggling
sitcoms ``Veronica's Closet'' and ``Suddenly Susan'' opportunities
to revive this season since, according to him, its wiser to tinker
with programs that have ``built some equity with viewers'' than to
launch new ones into the unknown. Seeing that neither series
improved, say bye-bye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stark Raving Mad,'' the other Thursday-night occupant, has
placed among the top 20 shows on television, but the significance
of its ratings is questionable because NBC scheduled it in the
weakened but still-powerful Thursday-night lineup anchored by
``Friends'' and ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ``Jesse,'' the Christina Applegate series that follows
``Friends,'' could get canned. Different cast members haven't made
a difference; the series has lost an additional 4 million viewers
from last season. Other likely cancellations: ABC's ``Norm'' and
``Then Came You,'' and The WB's supremely awful reincarnated
``Zoe,'' which now has the distinction of failing as both a high
school and a college comedy.
</P>
<P>
   As for dramas facing extinction, Fox plans to give Jennifer Love
Hewitt's ``Time of Your Life'' a last-ditch test by airing new
episodes over the summer. The network will probably also finally
yank ``Get Real,'' as well as its game show ``Greed'' and the
reality series ``World's Wackiest Police Chases.''
</P>
<P>
   On CBS, ``Falcone'' looks all but dead, as does the restructured
``Chicago Hope,'' ``Early Edition,'' ``Martial Law'' and the
amazingly durable ``Diagnosis Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   While I'd understand CBS' cancellation of ``Now and Again'' _
its mediocre ratings no longer yield even the cult following
necessary to keep it afloat on a major network _ its disappearance
would still be a disappointment. Few series offer such playful
poignancy, and Eric Close, as a human brain encased in a ripped bod
created by the government, and Dennis Haysbert, as his guardian,
have developed the kind of fun, zippy chemistry we haven't
experienced since Bruce Willis and Cybill Shepherd in the early
days of ``Moonlighting.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the deaths of ``Freaks and Geeks,'' the splendid high
school-is-a-nightmare dramedy on NBC, and Wonderland,'' a drama set
in a psychiatric ward of a hospital, all bets are off.
</P>
<P>
   While last season the networks set a precedent of growing hits
slowly by standing by them through the early, tough times, that
doesn't appear to be the case this year. ABC's ``Wonderland''
lasted two episodes. But when you have a ``Millionaire,'' what's
another discarded drama?
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
