A6960 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     04-14 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PIERCING LOOK AT A FAD SO UGLY THAT IT HURTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allergies, unsightly scars, rejection, infection _ I knew there
were good reasons why the very thought of pierced body parts give
me the heebie-jeebies. Until now, I just couldn't seem to get past
the primary one: terrifying pain.
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than 20 years and a month of Sundays since my
sisters and I showed up at Selman's Jewelry store in Summit, Miss.,
to have my ears pierced, but I remember the horror as if it were
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six of us, I was probably the last to work up enough
nerve. As I remember it, they'd already gotten their ears pierced
the old-fashioned way: Deaden the ear with ice, thread a needle,
and sew. In some instances, more than once.
</P>
<P>
   They were with me for moral support. But I was scared.
</P>
<P>
   They laughed so much we caused a scene. To this day, Dianne
swears I turned white. Yes, white. I had to get the other ear done,
but I promised myself that that would be it for me. If the good
Lord hadn't already put it there, not another hole would ever be
put in my body with my approval.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe you can understand if I shudder to even lay eyes on
someone with a hole drilled in a place other than the earlobes,
tremble if there's more than one piercing and nearly faint when I
spy a pierced tongue, nose or eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, then, my terror when I read the other day in the
Science section of The New York Times that people are even piercing
their genitals.
</P>
<P>
   The very thought makes me hurt. All over.
</P>
<P>
   Why in the world would anyone want an ornament there?
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to seem like a prude, because the truth is I'm more
a chicken than anything else. But what could these people be
thinking? I mean, how does one decide to put an earring in their
tongue or navel or nipples? What kind of conversation, if any,
could go on in their heads?
</P>
<P>
   It's so tempting to be sarcastic, but this is no laughing
matter. Along with being a very popular fad, especially among
teen-agers, body piercing can be quite hazardous to your health,
not to mention your social standing.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, The Times reported that one young woman was fired
from a law firm because the rest of the staff was so repulsed by
her facial piercings.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough to make me weep, because I'm against
discrimination of any kind. At the same time, this is an example of
just the thing to do if you don't really want your job.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, I was in a restaurant and the person taking my order
had a ring in her tongue. She has a right to work, but I have a
right to my appetite. One look and suddenly I didn't feel hungry
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   I mentioned health risks. The list is long.
</P>
<P>
   Allergic reaction to jewelry is the most common culprit. Far
more serious are infections caused when sterile techniques aren't
used.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible for piercing to introduce bacteria and viruses
into the bloodstream, including hepatitis B. The list is so long, I
stopped reading for fear I'd start experiencing the symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, I know my limitations. But apparently, some people don't.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7400, or e-mail:
gstaples(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6970 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-TREATY-0415-CO     04-14 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TREATY-0415-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA RATIFIES START II, WARNS AGAINST 'STAR WARS'
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With last-minute urging from President-elect Vladimir
Putin, Russia's lower house of parliament ended years of deadlock
Friday and ratified the START II treaty to scrap thousands of
nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin and lawmakers warned that Russia will abandon all arms
control pacts if the United States goes forward with plans to
implement a space-based ``Star Wars'' anti-missile system.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-and-half hour closed-door debate, attended by Putin
and a phalanx of military brass carrying the ``suitcase'' with the
country's nuclear launch codes, the State Duma voted 288 to 131 to
approve the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting off the ratification of START II on which the future
of our strategic nuclear forces depends would be undesirable and
harmful,'' Putin said. ``We don't need an arms race. We faced one
before, and if we allow it again it will be worse than last time.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Communists and hard-liners in the Duma had blocked
the pact. It now goes to the Federation Council, the upper chamber
of parliament, which is expected to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is a victory for Putin, who has tried to shrug off
criticism for Russia's brutal war in Chechnya and to bolster his
image as a West-looking politician with plenty of political muscle.
</P>
<P>
   For the Clinton administration, however, the news is a mixed
bag. While it gives President Clinton his first foreign policy
victory in the area of arms control, it complicates a decision he
faces this summer over whether to forge ahead with the
controversial multibillion-dollar Star Wars national defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma expressed its opposition to such a system by passing a
separate resolution stating that Russia would pull out of all
nuclear and conventional arms control agreements if the United
States does not adhere to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The ABM Treaty forbids the ``Star Wars''-type missile defense
system that Washington wants to build. U.S. officials believe such
technology is the best defense against nuclear attacks from rogue
nations, a scenario seen as more likely in the post-Cold War era
than an all-out nuclear war with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was hoping to soften Russia's opposition to the
new anti-missile system when officials meet in Washington at the
end of the month. But Putin, echoing the Duma lawmakers, said
Russia would nullify all arms treaties if the United States goes
forward with the Star Wars system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stress in this case, we will have the chance and we
will withdraw not only from the START II treaty, but from the whole
system of treaties on limitation and control of strategic and
conventional weapons,'' Putin told the Duma shortly before the vote
</P>
<P>
   START II, negotiated between former Russian President Boris
Yeltsin and former President George Bush in 1993, would cut nuclear
stockpiles from 6,000 warheads on each side to no more than 3,500
by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate ratified the agreement in 1996, but Yeltsin
couldn't get the treaty approved by the previous
Communist-dominated Duma.
</P>
<P>
   After new Duma elections in December, the balance of political
power swung in favor of moderates. Putin was able to lead his party
and a host of other political blocs to approve the treaty, which is
backed by Russia's military and national security leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials had said that approving START II would
strengthen Russia's position in the ABM debate.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Ivan Ivanov said Friday he would propose
several alternatives to changing the ABM treaty in talks at the end
of the month in the United States, according to the Interfax news
agency. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. and Russian diplomats said in Geneva they would
hold talks there next week to assess the prospects for launching
talks on START III.
</P>
<P>
   START III was agreed to in outline form three years ago. But the
hard work is to agree how deep the further cuts should be.
Washington is looking to cut arsenals to 2,000-2,500 warheads each,
while Russian officials say they are ready to go lower to 1,500
each.
</P>
<P>
   Putin highlighted to the Duma the economic benefits to ratifying
START II, telling lawmakers that the money saved on the maintenance
of the nuclear arsenal would be spent in upgrading the country's
conventional weapons and army.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker can be reached by e-mail at:
megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Arms Control Association: http://www.armscontrol.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
