<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CHONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `ANNABEL CHONG STORY' IS POWERFUL, WITTY AND FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WESLEY MORRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Annabel Chong sits in front of Gough Lewis' camera and
complains about her need to have one of those normal everyday
lives, you want to tell her that having intercourse on camera with
more than 200 men is probably not the way to get to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex: The Annabel Chong Story'' is the opposite of everything
you might think it is. This includes, but is not limited to, good,
arousing, powerful, witty, academic, reserved, humble, nicely
photographed, riveting, fun and, yes (or no) titillating.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Hughes Brothers' ``Pimp,'' ``Sex'' was part of a
tag-team of self-styled raunchumentaries at Sundance '99 that
everyone wanted to see but no one left talking about. How, you
might ask, could a movie about a popular dirty-movie star that's
been shot in a porn-friendly video format fail?
</P>
<P>
   Well, porn stars are like models and most sock puppets: Nobody
really cares what they have to say. Anyway, the only time the
Singapore-born, London-raised, American-educated sex artist bothers
to speak coherently is when she's making what she would call a
``real'' movie. The director gets all up in Chong's business,
interviewing her equally stoned and pretentious friends, spending
time with her Catholic Singaporean mother, who, incidentally, is
unaware of her daughter's porn life.
</P>
<P>
   The first time relatively mainstream America got a taste of the
terribly uncompelling Chong was with her seemingly doped-up
appearance on ``Jerry Springer'' in 1995, though, recognizing how
on top of things Jerry's audience is, she was probably a household
name.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent her girlhood in a convent as a child named Grace,
one supposes Chong wanted to get out and break all the sex laws.
Chong's docu-autobio shares its name with the singer's coffee-table
book full of tawdry erotica, and she spends most of Lewis' movie
looking like Madonna in her ``Borderline'' days, magically
transported to the set of the ``Justify My Love'' video.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis gives us interviews that look like high-8 outtakes from
``Boogie Nights'' with Ron Jeremy and porn execs who call Chong ``a
super winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The coup of Lewis' profile appears to be his being present to
witness the taping of Chong's tour de force in which she has sex
with 251 men over the course of 10 hours. But as it turns out,
``The World's Biggest Gang-Bang'' is also the lamest.
</P>
<P>
   (Wesley Morris can be reached at the e-mail address of
morris(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
