<HEADER>
A6974 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SHRAKE-TEXASHISTORY-T     04-14 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHRAKE-TEXASHISTORY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHRAKE ADDS TEXAS HISTORY TO HIS LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a colorful career that has spanned half a
century, Edwin Shrake, more familiarly known to friends and readers
as ``Bud,'' has written nearly everything that can be put into
print.
</P>
<P>
   First came newspaper stories for the Fort Worth Press, Dallas
Times Herald and Dallas Morning News. Then came worldwide ramblings
for Sports Illustrated; a spate of critically acclaimed, if never
bestselling, novels (the classic ``Blessed McGill'' among them);
screenplays (''Tom Horn'' and ``Kid Blue''); sports how-to's
(including ``Harvey Penick's Little Red Book,'' the bestselling
sports book of all time); and, currently, a stage play co-authored
with Britain's Michael Rudman.
</P>
<P>
   But experience and success haven't banked the writing fire in
Shrake, a 68-year-old Fort Worth native now living in his beloved
adoptive hometown of Austin. He's out hustling ``The Borderland''
(Hyperion, $24.95), a novel about the Republic of Texas in 1839.
It's a work combining historical perspective, vivid imagination and
not a little mysticism _ a book that, even by Shrake's exacting
standards, pushed him to the limits of his ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always tried to make everything I wrote as good as it
could possibly be,'' Shrake says between bites of chicken tacos at
a north Fort Worth restaurant. ``I've never taken being a writer
for granted. I've never gotten tired of writing. But this book is
different for me. It was a long time coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Shrake originally conceived the novel in the late 1970s and
worked through a draft centered on the epic Texan-Comanche battle
of Plum Creek, when the Indians unsuccessfully tried to stave off
white occupation of their favorite tribal lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some New York editor took a look _ a brief look _ and told
me nobody wanted to read a historical novel about Texas,'' Shrake
growls, still irritated by the comment two decades later. ``Of
course, just a year or two later Larry McMurtry comes along with
`Lonesome Dove,' and (James) Michener has a bestseller with
`Texas.'''
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged, Shrake relegated what he was then calling Plum
Creek to the bottom of a soon-forgotten box and carried on with his
life, which, at the time, was as notorious for nonstop partying as
for writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was drinking at that time,'' Shrake says, eyes twinkling at
the understatement. (In his recent autobiography ``Gypsy Songman,''
hedonistic singer/songwriter Jerry Jeff Walker devotes dozens of
pages to descriptions of megaparties he and Shrake hosted during
the 1970s and speculates why either should have survived them.) ``I
think now that the book (`Borderland') wasn't supposed to come
then. I wasn't prepared to do the research I needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Years passed. Shrake took on other book projects; the Penick
book and its sequels made him enough money to take financial
concerns out of his life. In the mid-'80s, he was found to have
diabetes and quit drinking. Shrake became the full-time companion
of former Texas Gov. Ann Richards. But ``Plum Creek'' was never
quite expunged from his memory. In particular, Bill Wittliff, an
old pal involved in producing the epic ``Lonesome Dove'' TV
miniseries, urged Shrake to get back to the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept saying `No,' and then one night about four years ago I
was sitting out on my balcony,'' Shrake says. ``I live in West Lake
Hills in Austin, and from my balcony you can look out across the
Colorado (River). So I was sitting there thinking about how Austin
has changed over the years _ hippie Austin, dot-com Austin _ and
then it occurred to me that, back in 1839, Comanches might have
been in the same place with the same view, wondering like me why
strangers were coming to change a place they dearly loved the way
it was.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first new scene when Shrake started rewriting,
combining his old ``Plum Creek'' plot with reams of new material.
Now his tale encompassed early political conflict in the fledgling
Republic of Texas and how the capital was moved from relatively
civilized Houston to Austin, an outpost in the heart of Comanche
territory. Shrake populated his saga with colorful characters real
and imagined and threw in all sorts of mystical allegories that
further elevated the renamed ``The Borderland'' from interesting
western drama to mesmerizing existential heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I confess to being mystically inclined,'' says Shrake, who, by
virtue of a ministerial license he acquired by mail, has officiated
at weddings. ``I'm a little bit of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Released this month, ``The Borderland'' has so far sold solidly,
if not spectacularly. Shrake believes it is coincidence, not bad
luck, that he and fellow Austinite Stephen Harrigan have published
massive novels of Texas history within weeks of each other. (They
even have the same literary agent.) Harrigan's ``The Gates of the
Alamo'' has just climbed onto the New York Times bestseller list.
Shrake hopes that's a good sign for ``The Borderland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope `The Gates of the Alamo' sells a jillion copies,''
Shrake says. ``There could be a coattail effect, and my book could
sell half a jillion. Honestly, I believe there's always room for
two successful books.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Borderland'' sells enough copies, Shrake is eager to
attempt a sequel. Meanwhile, he and London-based Rudman are
finishing the seventh draft of their play via e-mail, and Shrake is
also finding time to stay in touch with colorful former colleagues
from Fort Worth's Paschal High and the long-defunct Fort Worth
Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dan Jenkins was my best friend from high school on, and I
still see Blackie Sherrod, Jerre Todd, Gary Cartwright, all the old
Press people,'' Shrake says. ``It's not too strong a word to say we
love each other. The old days were golden times, though we never
made enough money to sit back and realize they were golden then.
But I still have lots of things I want to do; I have no interest in
just stopping where I am and remembering instead of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is books editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7720, or e-mail:
jguinn(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
