<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6975 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-TRENDYRUM-TEX     04-14 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENDYRUM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST, SALSA. THEN, LATIN MUSIC. NOW, RUM IS HOT.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ At Samba Room, the nuevo-Cuban restaurant in Dallas
where the white-jacketed waiters and the Tito Puente soundtrack
make you feel like you stepped into a club Ricky Ricardo might have
opened, rum seems to be in everything at the bar: The mojitos
(fresh lime juice, rum, sugar cane extract, mint). The caipirinhas,
sweet cocktails made with a Brazilian liqueur that tastes just like
rum. The special Crazyy martinis, made with Bacardi Limon flavored
rum, Cointreau and cranberry juice.
</P>
<P>
   And at Cuba Libre, a cavernous 2-story, Caribbean-flavored bar
and restaurant that opened in Dallas two months ago, rum is the
specialty of the house. They stock fruit-flavored rums and
specially aged sipping rums; bartenders mix it into pina coladas
and martinis. And on weekend nights, the bar sells at least 100
servings of its most popular drink, the house-special frozen Cuba
Libre, a slushy concoction of rum, Coke and lime _ ``like a Slurpee
with a real kick,'' says bar manager Rodney Caprio.
</P>
<P>
   Single-malt scotch and cigars? That's so '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmopolitans? Um, they were over last year.
</P>
<P>
   Tequila? OK, that's still a big deal, but some think its moment
has peaked.
</P>
<P>
   No, the drink of the moment, the trendy liquor of choice, is
rum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love rum. Rum is fun, rum is tropical, rum is hot,'' says
Park Kerr, of the El Paso Chile Co., who is not given to
understatement, and who has reasons of his own to say this: His new
``Rum &AMP; Tiki Cookbook'' (William Morrow; $12.95) just hit stores,
full of interesting recipes like lemon rum martinis, garlicky crab
fettuccine in rum cream sauce, and ginger-rum balls.
</P>
<P>
   Sales figures back Kerr up; rum now sells about 50,000 gallons
more a year in the United States than it did five years ago. Sales
of vodka, the most popular hard liquor in the United States, are
still more than twice those of rum, but rum is in fourth place for
hard-liquor sales, according to figures supplied by the Distilled
Spirits Council of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kerr credits rum's resurgence to its adaptability (its
relatively light flavor makes it a good mixer, both in drinks and
in main dishes and sauces) and to food trends (the increased
popularity of Latin and Caribbean fusion cuisines). And he likes
the nostalgia factor, too _ the same movement behind such new-again
trends as swing dancing and retro fashions like capri pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents drank rum in the '50s and '60s. My mother imported
banana daiquiris to El Paso,'' says Kerr, a native Texan. ``So it
has that whole '50s and '60s thing going, too.''
</P>
<P>
   More cynical observers, however, might credit marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the early '90s, rum sales declined, until about 1995
_ coincidentally, about the time that rums flavored with fruit
juices, like Bacardi Limon, were introduced. Flavored rums now
account for 25 percent of the rum market, says John Gomez, a
marketing executive at Bacardi.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez attributes rum's new popularity partly to the shift in
consumer tastes over the past 20 years away from dark liquors
(whiskey, bourbon) and toward clear liquors (rum, vodka, gin).
</P>
<P>
   ``People are moving away from drinking (liquor) that is an
acquired taste,'' he says. ``They don't want something that burns.
They're looking for easy-to-drink cocktails'' such as flavored
rums, which don't even need mixers.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true of under-30 drinkers, he says. About 18
months ago, Bacardi started aggressively courting these
twentysomething consumers with its Bacardi by Night campaign,
featuring hot young rum drinkers and such taglines as ``Cubicle by
day; Bacardi by night.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other end of the trend, Gomez says, is the growth in more
expensive, aged rums, costing $30 a bottle or more, compared to the
traditional rum that costs up to $15 a bottle. Gomez compares the
pricier rums to a cognac, in that their smooth taste appeals to an
older, more affluent, more sophisticated crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's market-driven or marketing-driven, local businesses
are embracing the trend.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's Angeluna, for instance, serves a specialty drink
called Blame it on Rio, which is particularly popular in the
summer. It's essentially a rum martini, made with cachaca (the
Brazilian liqueur that's similar to rum), Cointreau, and fresh lime
juice, served straight up in an oversized martini glass.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' Westin Galleria earlier this year introduced a special
Nuevo Latino menu that features mojitos, daiquiris and Caribe
Cosmopolitans, made with cranberry juice, rum and Grand Marnier.
And local Latin-themed restaurants as El Paraiso, a Cuban
restaurant and bar in Euless, also stock plenty of rum at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Local liquor stores are being a little more cautious, but even
they carry more flavored rums and more expensive rums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly they expect rums to take off like tequilas have, and
there are a lot more expensive rums on the market, but they're not
selling all that well yet,'' says Harry Labovitz, an executive vice
president at King's, the Fort Worth liquor store chain. ``It takes
time for these to catch on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, two years ago, Labovitz stocked just one or two rums that
sold for more than $30 a bottle; now he has nine labels at or above
that price, including Pyrat Cask 23, which costs $260 for a
750-milliliter bottle. And yes, he sells them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have them in the store just for window dressing,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   A Cuba Libre, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
