<HEADER>
A6978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT &LR;      04-14 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SWEARS OFF AN INSECTICIDE IN WAR AGAINST MOSQUITOES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City has decided not to spray malathion, the
pesticide it used against mosquitoes last year, in its campaign to
prevent another outbreak of West Nile virus, and to use helicopter
spraying only as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the city will begin an effort to kill mosquitoes
before they hatch, and if neighborhoods do become infested, health
officials will opt for three other insecticides sprayed primarily
by trucks. The city will use helicopters to spray those
insecticides only if the other methods fail. Both the use of
malathion and helicopter spraying greatly unnerved residents and
environmental groups last year.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to avoid using insecticides, the city plans an
aggressive effort to kill mosquito larvae, and it will drop
millions of tiny larvae-eating fish into the city's waste treatment
plants. The so-called mosquitofish, Gambusia affinis, which will be
confined to the plants, multiply rapidly and are considered a
vacuum for larvae, consuming hundreds an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The city's health commissioner, Dr. Neal Cohen, said the city
had decided not to use malathion because it was under a safety
review by the federal Environmental Protection Agency. ``Our
confidence needs to be deferred until questions raised by the
review are resolved,'' he said. Malathion has in fact been under
review by the agency for well over 18 months, under a 1996 law
enacted to review all pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major victory,'' said Laura Haight, an environmental
associate for the New York Public Interest Group, a public advocacy
organization. ``This is the first time the city has made any
statement whatsoever like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Haight's organization and other environmental groups have
contended that the effects of malathion have not been fully
studied. Thousands of city residents also clamored for the end of
malathion spraying last year, worrying about possible effects on
children, pets and roof gardens, and annoyed that chemical droplets
often fell without warning during summer evenings outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani scoffed at the idea that
malathion was harmful and vowed to keep spraying as long as it was
necessary. Most scientists believe that malathion, if used
properly, is harmless to humans.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, neither Giuliani nor Cohen
mentioned the city's decision to abandon malathion. The plan to use
other insecticides was on the fifth page of a five-page news
release on the city's extensive plan to ward off another West Nile
outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning next week, city workers will squirt poison along the
city's cracks and crevices. Government officials will press
residents to clean out their birdbaths. And the larvae-eating fish
will presumably use their appetites to help keep calamity at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito eradication plan is part of a multimillion-dollar
program to ward off the West Nile virus, a mosquito-borne virus
that can cause swelling of the brain and that killed 7 people and
sickened 62 in the metropolitan region last year. After that
outbreak, the city and other municipalities embarked on a costly
insecticide campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the fish program, the city plans to treat storm drains
and other areas of standing water with larvicides that inhibit
mosquito breeding and the maturation of mosquito larvae. The
application is to begin next week and continue through April.
</P>
<P>
   The city will also begin a major advertising campaign urging New
Yorkers to get rid of standing pools of water, change the water in
their birdbaths, drain unused pools and apply bug spray when
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city will do its part to control mosquito breeding,''
Cohen said Thursday during a City Council hearing. ``However, we
can only truly succeed in significantly reducing mosquitoes if
everyone pitches in to mosquito-proof New York City by eliminating
areas of standing water where mosquitoes lay their eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was jeered by several environmental advocates at the
hearing when he announced that the city would, if needed, use other
chemicals for spraying: Scourge, Anvil and Agrevo Permanone. Many
environmentalists oppose the use of any insecticides.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement came almost a month after the state
health commissioner, Dr. Antonia Novello, outlined a plan to battle
mosquitoes statewide.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Westchester was one of several suburban counties
that chose a different pesticide, sumithrin, sold under the trade
name Anvil, for its aerial attack on mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it has made no decision on which chemical to spray
should an aerial assault become necessary, said Mary Landrigan, a
spokeswoman for the County Health Department. She said the primary
focus remained on finding and eliminating breeding mosquitoes and
larvae so that no spraying would be necessary later. Connecticut
cities will be left to make their plans as they choose, an official
there said. New Jersey and Long Island officials could not be
reached Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The use of mosquitofish is common all over the world, and they
are most often found in the southeast United States and in the
Caribbean, said Christopher Andrews, executive director of the
South Carolina Aquarium in Charleston. In 1905, about 150 of the
fish were introduced into Hawaii from Texas to test their
effectiveness in preying on mosquito larvae, according to a Web
site run by the Department of the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fish are not indigenous to New York, some have
thrived for years in a wastewater treatment plant near Wards
Island. No one seems to know how they got there, said a spokesman
at the City Department of Environmental Protection. If mosquitoes
are found to be breeding in other treatment plants in the city, the
fish will be called to dinner at those plants.
</P>
<P>
   In some circumstances, the fish are not harmless _ they have
been known to prey on natural fauna and overtake other fish
populations when introduced in foreign areas. But since they will
be limited to the waste treatment plants, this should not be an
issue in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor proudly clutched a jar of the minnowlike fish at his
news conference Thursday. ``See them, here they are,'' he said.
``They eat larvae. See? They eat that,'' he added, pointing to a
wee bit of larvae. ``They're going to be in our treatment plants,
and they're going to eat them. Maybe a month from now, they'll be
quite a bit fatter.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, whom the mayor derided last year as
alarmists, applauded the city's efforts to ward off mosquitoes'
hatching. ``We do have concerns about the health effects of all
pesticides,'' Haight said. ``But over all, this plan contains many
of the elements we have been calling for that prevent their
unnecessary use.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
