<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HIGHWAY-SAFETY-NYT &LR;      04-14 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN SENTRA: WILL MORE, MORE, MORE BE ENOUGH? 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The preliminary statistics for highway deaths in
1999 are out, and they show substantial safety progress, if you
look at them the way the Department of Transportation does. Looking
differently at the same numbers, though, some safety analysts see
stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   And buried in the numbers are some contradictory trends.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, released earlier this month by the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, the number of
people killed in vehicle accidents last year was 41,345, down from
41,471 in 1998, a 0.3 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
   A drop of 126 people out of more than 40,000 may not sound like
a success, but the Transportation Department called that an
improvement when measured by vehicle miles traveled: The 1999 rate
was 1.5 deaths per 100 million vehicle miles traveled; the rate in
1998 was 1.6 deaths per 100 million miles.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said the drop in the
death rate was historic. ``This continued reduction in traffic
fatalities is encouraging news,'' he said in a statement. ``Safety
is President Clinton's and Vice President Gore's highest
transportation priority, and these statistics show that our
commitment to safety is paying huge dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the number of deaths per 100 million miles is down
sharply; 20 years ago it was 3.4, or more than twice the current
rate, and 30 years ago it was 4.7, or three times what it is now.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual number of fatalities is shrinking far more
slowly. For each year of the 1990s, it has varied from 39,250 to
44,599. The rate is dropping because vehicle miles traveled jumps
by about 2 percent each year, now approaching 2.7 trillion miles,
up from 2.6 trillion last year, and 1.8 trillion in 1970. ``The
number of deaths could be stable or rising and you divide by this
huge number, and it looks like things are always getting better,''
said Dr. Robert Scopatz, a statistician and road safety expert at
Data Nexus Inc., a public safety consulting firm in Kissimmee, Fla.
``It's always going to look like an improvement, because vehicle
miles traveled rises.''
</P>
<P>
   Scopatz said the statistical method used by the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration, called the Fatality Analysis
Reporting System, produced the best data available. But he added
that vehicle miles traveled _ an estimate based on states counting
cars at various spots _ was not the ideal number on which to make
safety calculations. A better method for measuring safety, he said,
would use the number of people miles _ meaning the total number of
miles that people travel, whether alone or with others _ although
currently there is no way to measure that. (Scopatz said he was
also curious about the number of deaths per million cell phone
calls.)
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary numbers, some reached on the basis of direct
counting and others through sampling, show that the total number of
crashes reported to the police, 6.3 million, is also down, by about
0.7 percent. But the number of injuries, for reasons that are not
clear, rose to 3.2 million, an increase of about 8,000, or 0.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   New cars that include more safety features and the wider use of
seat belts may be reducing fatalities, and thus increasing the
number of people who are counted as injured, but that shift likely
represents hundreds, not thousands, of people. Stephanie Faul, a
spokeswoman for the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety, said better
emergency medical care has also spared lives, if not injuries.
</P>
<P>
   One category that experienced disappointing results was
motorcycle fatalities, which reached 2,537 last year, up 11 percent
from 1998. The 1998 number was about 8 percent higher than 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Again, no one is sure why. Julie Rochman, a spokeswoman for the
Insurance Institute for Highway Safety, said, ``In a good economy,
more people may be purchasing motorcycles as a toy.'' And, she
said, helmet laws were being relaxed. Further analysis may show
whether the death rate is highest in states that have eased their
helmet laws.
</P>
<P>
   And continuing to fuel the debate over higher speed limits, the
transportation department's preliminary 1999 data showed that the
number of deaths on roads with posted speed limits of 55 and above
rose by 2 percent, and the number on roads with speed limits below
55 fell by 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, that makes it sound like faster highway traffic is
causing more deaths. But there are complicating factors. According
to Dr. Steven Bloch, a researcher at the Automobile Club of
Southern California, an AAA affiliate, higher freeway speed limits
are inducing drivers to change their routes from back roads to the
interstates, increasing traffic there, and, as a result, the number
of accidents. And the federal data did not account for the miles of
roadway where the speed limit was shifted from under 55 to 55 or
over.
</P>
<P>
   If a past pattern holds, the number of deaths in 2000 might be
significantly lower: Deaths dropped sharply in 1974, 1980 and 1992
_ years when the price of gasoline spiked. But some people think
the consumer reaction to the current increase in gas prices will
not be so strong.
</P>
<P>
   Shashi Nambisan, a professor of civil engineering at the
University of Nevada at Las Vegas, said the scarcity of fuel could
make people drive less or slower. Still, she added, ``I don't think
a significant portion of the population is driving significantly
less.''
</P>
<P>
   2 Views on Side-Impact Air Bags
</P>
<P>
   In an echo of the crisis over air bags killing or injuring
children in the front passenger seat, the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration said last October that side-impact air bags
on the rear seats could also be a hazard to children. And since
parents were being urged to put children in the back seat to keep
them away from the front air bags, the carmakers who offer
side-impact air bags in the rear seats should ship those cars with
the bags disabled, the agency said, leaving it to the buyer and the
dealer to decide if they should be activated.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction has been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for BMW, Karl-Heinz Ziwica, said his company had
shipped cars that way even before the October letter from the
safety agency. But at Mercedes-Benz USA, James Resnick, a
spokesman, said, ``It's our belief that the rear side air bags
provide a very significant safety benefit, both for adults and
children.'' Children should be in appropriate seats or booster
seats, he said, and if they are properly positioned, there is no
threat to them.'' Based on that position, Mercedes ships its cars
with the side air bags activated.
</P>
<P>
   Only ``a very small handful'' of buyers have asked to have the
bags deactivated, Resnick said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
