<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, April 15. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ARMS (Moscow) _ In his first legislative initiative as
elected president, Vladimir Putin on Friday won ratification of the
START-2 treaty, which the parliament had blocked for seven years.
The treaty calls for cutting the American and Russian nuclear
arsenals by half. The passage was seen as a sign that Putin seeks a
constructive relationship with the West, but also that he intends
fight hard to block American efforts to revise or abandon earlier
arms-control treaties. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-AFRICA-TRADE (Washington) _ House and Senate leaders have
reached broad agreement on a bill to give African and Caribbean
countries wide-ranging trade benefits designed to help their
flagging economies by opening new markets. Speaker J. Dennis
Hastert and the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, personally
intervened on Thursday night to resolve differences that had
deadlocked the trade bill. Left unresolved, the impasse imperiled
the China trade bill that the House is to vote on next month. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-POLITICS (Belgrade) _ At least 100,000 people jammed a
sunny central Belgrade on Friday for an opposition rally demanding
early elections to oust the government of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ In a breakthrough, House and
Senate negotiators said Friday that they had reached a tentative
agreement on an appeals process for patients denied care by health
maintenance organizations _ a major issue in legislation to define
patients' rights. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE (Washington) _ The Defense Department's
inspector general decided Friday there are no grounds to formally
investigate a misconduct allegation against the Army's
highest-ranking female officer. The allegation, made last week by a
retired Army officer whose identity has not been made public, had
added a further twist to the already tangled affair involving Lt.
Gen. Claudia Kennedy. She caused a stir by accusing a fellow
general of sexual harassment. The Army is investigating her charge.
(Summary from wires) By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ Developments. The government asked a federal
appeals court Friday to order Elian Gonzalez's Miami relatives to
return the boy to his father, who agreed to stay in this country
until it rules. The relatives, turning to another court for help,
invoked the U.N. human-rights charter in asking that Elian stay.
(Summary from wires) By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (Westbury, N.Y.) _ Highlighting what has emerged
as perhaps the sharpest policy difference between them, Hillary
Rodham Clinton today attacked Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's proposal
to use the nation's surplus for deep tax cuts as a threat to
prosperity. Mrs. Clinton unveiled a plan that would eliminate the
national deficit by 2013, while offering a much more modest menu of
tax reductions. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks went into free fall on Friday as
investors had to digest surprisingly bad news on inflation and the
fear of higher intetrest rates. The beleaguered Nasdaq index
plunged a near record 10 percent while the Dow Jones industrial
average and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell more than 5
percent each. The fall ended the worst week ever for the Nasdaq
composite. Almost no company survived unscatherd. All 30 stocks in
the Dow fell while all but 16 stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 index were down
in late afternoon. The impact of the decline is even greater
because it comes on the back of several weeks of wild daily market
swings and the plunge of the Nasdaq earlier this week into bear
market territory. By Jonathan Fuerbringer and Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
