<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6996 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-STUDENTS-STEROIDS-HNS     04-14 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-STEROIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOVERNMENT TO ADVISE TEENS AGAINST STEROID USE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in the ``w'' and ``s'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government launched a campaign Friday
to publicize the risks of anabolic steroids amid indications that
the use of muscle-enhancing drugs among young athletes and
body-builders is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``About a half million young people are using anabolic
steroids,'' Dr. Alan Leshner, director of the National Institute on
Drug Abuse, told a news conference. ``And the numbers are going to
get worse unless we do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five percent more 10th-graders reported trying steroids
at least once in their lifetime in 1999 than in 1998, according to
an institute study released in December. The study also found that
eighth-graders were equally as likely as 10th-graders to have tried
steroids, and that nearly one percent of students in the eighth,
10th and 12th grades had used steroids within a month of the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   The institute, which is part of the National Institutes of
Health, launched an educational Web site about the potential risks
of using steroids, www.steroidabuse.org, and will distribute nearly
one million information sheets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The information includes 500,000 postcards that will be
available at selected gyms, movie theaters and shopping malls,
among other places, in major cities such as Los Angeles and
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Anabolic steroids are manufactured substances that act like
testosterone, the male sex hormone, in building muscle mass. Some
teen-agers use steroids, which are available over the counter, to
enhance their physical appearance, their athletic performance or
both.
</P>
<P>
   But Leshner and several doctors who joined him at the news
conference said steroid use by young men can also cause acne,
stunted growth and the development of breasts. For teen-age girls,
who several doctors said are using steroids more than in years
past, short-term side effects include facial hair, increased body
hair and acne.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said long-term use can result in various types of
cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of performance-enhancing drugs in competitive sports
is bad for our health, bad for the sports, bad for the youth and
bad for our country,'' said Dr. Gary Wadler, an associate professor
at the New York University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Linn Goldberg of the Oregon Health Sciences University
unveiled the results of a coach- and peer-training program for high
school boys that reduced the use of steroids and other drugs
significantly in its first test case. Football players from 31
Oregon high schools participated in the program that was funded by
the National Institute on Drug Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of anabolic steroids was reduced by 50 percent as were
the use of athletic-enhancing supplements,'' Goldberg reported,
adding that the program also has helped decrease alcohol and drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1637EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
