<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7003 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BOY-CRAZY-NYTR &LR;      04-14 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY-CRAZY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY BANKS ON GIRLS GOING BOY CRAZY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Nancy Pasternack writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.,
a New York Times Regional Newspaper.) 
 By NANCY PASTERNACK    
 Sarasota Herald-Tribune    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Brittany Beatty, 10, stares intently at the
face on a trading card. She has found one she says she really
likes.
</P>
<P>
   The Hernando County fifth-grader reads the name, ``Brian,''
beneath the photo of a blue-eyed boy in a baseball cap. Brian,
according to the card, is a Sagittarius. He likes hockey and girls
who have a sense of humor. He's 13.
</P>
<P>
   Boy Crazy, the product that holds Brittany spellbound, is the
latest offering from Decipher, a Norfolk, Va., company that also
produces ``Star Wars'' and ``Austin Powers'' trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   Subjects of Boy Crazy cards, the slogan boasts, are ``real boys
for real girls.'' A pack of nine cards retails for $3.
</P>
<P>
   One month after making their debut on the display counter of
Quality Collectibles in Sarasota Square Mall, their draw is still
limited.
</P>
<P>
   But store manager David Baker says it's just a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girls are just finding out about them,'' he says. Soon, he
predicts, the cards ``will be like Pokemon. Once they (kids) learn
about it, it'll really take off.'' This would not surprise
Brittany.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' photos, she says, are cute, ``and the set up is
neat.'' Boy Crazy cards feature photos of boys _ age 12-22 _ taken
during a search of 15 malls last year. Virginia teen-age
cheerleaders helped sift 363 from thousands photographed, according
to Decipher officials.
</P>
<P>
   The cards hit markets in Europe and Australia, too, in recent
weeks. And though it may be too early to tell how sales have gone,
the Boy Crazy Web site (www.boycrazy.com) _ which offers game
rules, opportunities to vote for favorite cards and inquire about
individual photo subjects _ gets 1.6 million hits per day on
average, according to Decipher spokeswoman Leslie Hellerman. The
site's registered membership, she says, numbers 90,000.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of mall rats?
</P>
<P>
   ``They wear glasses,'' says Hellerman. ``They have braces on
their teeth. They're more realistic than the pretty boys on the WB
(Warner Brothers) Network.'' But some parents say they would prefer
a little less reality for children approaching or enduring puberty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a meat market for kids,'' says Donna Marks of
Chicago, who shopped at Sarasota Square Mall on a recent Saturday
with her 11-year-old son. ``They remind me of personal ads.'' Some
of the girls the cards are meant to appeal to also are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Lawrenz, 11, a Sarasota Middle School student, throws her
mother a look of disappointment as she flips through a stack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if they were the Backstreet Boys,'' she says, shrugging.
``These are complete strangers.'' Hellerman says the company
protects the anonymity of its young subjects by listing the boys'
first names and states of origin only.
</P>
<P>
   And information from Web site visitors, she says, is entered
under the strictest codes of confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a dating service. There's not a lot this would
offer someone whose ideas are anything but wholesome.'' Not
everyone takes comfort from such assurances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inappropriate,'' says Dan Bafia of Bradenton, whose
daughters are 15 and 12 _ both within the ideal age range targeted
by Boy Crazy. ``I'm not too keen on them getting into stuff like
that online,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Sarasota High School teacher Donna Burkhart says Boy Crazy cards
are the last thing teens and pre-teens need.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hormones are raging enough,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But the cards pique her niece's interest. The 7th-grader looks
at each boy's face carefully. While she doesn't offer her own
opinion, she says her peers are likely to go in for the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandmother, Jean Klaus, shows even more interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty cute, huh? This one needs a shave,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had some cute older guys like Paul Newman I'd be
trading these at the health club,'' she says. A second national
mall tour is underway to search for next year's batch of ``real
boys,'' according to Hellerman. No Florida malls have made it on
the itinerary yet.
</P>
<P>
   Hellerman says it's still a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds good to Said Lissone, a 10th-grader at Riverview
High. ``I'd like to be on one of those,'' he says, looking at the
Boy Crazy display at Quality Collectibles. Then another thought
occurs to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' he says. ``Do they have cards with girls on them?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
