u l BC-SUCCESS-STRESSED-$ADV     04-14 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUCCESS-STRESSED-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY IRA NEEDS VIAGRA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 16) 
 By BOB MORRIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people have hip financial managers. I have an accountant
named Ronald McDonald, of all things.
</P>
<P>
   He hates money, or to be more precise, people who are making too
much of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day the media hits you with another new rich guy who
made a billion dollars,'' he's saying as he adds up my tax
deductions. ``I mean, who are these people on TV, telling you some
stupid Internet stock is so important? Karl Marx was right when he
said capitalism will eat itself alive. It'll destroy the planet,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Because I don't make much money or own much stock, I usually
find his harangues refreshing, if not validating. But now he's just
making me anxious. This tax season something has changed, even for
people far more affluent than I; we can't help comparing ourselves
with all the skinny young eco-conscious philanthropically correct
e-people who don't even have to wear ties to make their killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time you had to work your way up,'' says a friend who
took the slow road from business school to banking to marketing to
Internet-venturing, shedding his expensive suits in the process.
``These new people skip the meal and go straight to the dessert,
and it's annoying.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. But, honestly, I'm kind of ashamed to be so
despairing, because in addition to having a great career and a
rent-controlled apartment, my income is 10 times what it once was.
In this new compare-and-despair culture, I don't need a Marxist
accountant. I need therapy to work out my envy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing from a lot of stressed-out successful people who
don't think they're doing well because others are making
millions,'' says Suzanne Marcus, a psychologist in La Jolla,
Calif., who tells me that success isn't measured by finances and
cites a recent article in American Psychologist that asks, ``If
we're so rich, why aren't we happy?''
</P>
<P>
   She adds that real happiness is reflected in one's ability to
lose track of time while engaged in meaningful ``flow activities,''
like music and sports. ``What a rich life,'' she coos when I tell
her that I'm about to sail to Cuba on assignment (not for this
column).
</P>
<P>
   So if life's so good, why am I so upset by what Vanity Fair and
Vogue are calling the e-Establishment and Dot Com Society, even
after Microsoft lost, Nasdaq dipped, and Dana Giacchetto, the young
financial guru to the stars, was charged with stock fraud? ``If you
really want what others have,'' Marcus says, ``use your jealousy,
and stretch yourself to be more like them.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day I'm in the office of my Chase bank manager. My
modest retirement savings, she's telling me sternly, are earning
nothing. When she asks about my meager investments, I don't know if
the Pfizer stock I bought when Viagra was first marketed has split
or not, nor do I know what my Dreyfus fund is worth since I hate
pie charts. CD? IRA? P/E ratio? What's it mean? ``I'm such a
loser,'' I say. ``You're not a loser, you have some money,'' she
says. ``You just need to get your portfolio in order.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, I'm in with the bank's senior financial investor, who has
a leopard-print belt that matches her handbag. ``So you're single,
42, disappointed in Viagra,'' she says, ``and you have money
issues. What else?'' I tell her that I'm tired of rooting against
new-technology celebrities and that although I still object to cell
phones, maybe there's a way to invest in all the satellites
facilitating all the yakking. She listens, calls up charts, runs
figures and rejects my investment interest in fashion and extreme
sports. One mutual fund she likes makes me cringe when I see a
cruise line on its list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do you think all these retired people with money are
going?'' she scolds. ``Snowboarding?''
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy my need for something trendy, she finds a fund that
invests in communications infrastructure. ``It'll give you
something to talk about at your cocktail parties,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   So what if I'm investing in social cachet more than anything
else? This is the makeover I've needed. It's 7 p.m. when we finish,
and all my CD's and IRA's are now in stocks, where they belong. I
feel wiped out, yet invigorated, as if we've just engaged in sex or
some other kind of flow activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want a cigarette?'' I ask Ms. Investor. She laughs.
</P>
<P>
   When I return to Ronald McDonald the next day, he tells me I owe
a lot in taxes. But for the first time in my life, I feel happy to
pay up, because in my own small way, I'm now a player who's engaged
in the conversation that has taken over the culture.
</P>
<P>
   Is this what's meant by a correction?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
