<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, April 16, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DICAPRIO-IMAGE (Undated) _ The image of Leonardo DiCaprio, circa
April 2000: the chairman of Earth Day, leading a four-hour rally in
Washington next Saturday to raise awareness of global warming, a
subject about which he says in a Web chat, ``I personally feel this
is the most highly ignored, yet important issue facing the world
today.'' In recent years, few Hollywood stars have worked to
transform their off-screen image as strikingly as DiCaprio, the
``Titanic'' heartthrob who seems intent on exchanging the
hard-partying persona for that of an activist alarmed about the
fate of the Earth. By Michele Willens. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALLERGY-WEBSITE (New York) _ The proof of the hotness of
respiratory ailments can be found _ and purchased _ at
Gazoontite.com. A Web site and a catalog, not to mention a new
retail store on Broadway near 75th Street, Gazoontite.com sells
everything from $699 Miele vacuum cleaners and hypo-allergenic
comforters covered in 230-thread-count cotton to a rubber Bart
Simpson that fits over an inhaler. Everything for the allergy,
asthma and status-symbol victim. By Rick Marin. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JEANS-FASHION (New York) _ Jeans are back, and they have left
Woodstock decidedly behind. They are the season's biggest fashion
trend, running the gamut from sequined to studded, dark to light,
hot pants to cropped to full length. The trendiest part of the
trend, dirty denim, reflects the rest of our instant theme park
culture: it has been dirtied for you in advance _ prestained,
preburnt or prepainted. By Alex Witchel. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-KERRIGAN (New York) _ When the Welsh hyphenate
writer-director-actor Justin Kerrigan blew into New York on Sunday
night, the people at Miramax, which is releasing ``Human Traffic,''
his film on the rave scene, must have gone for the Advil. It's not
that Kerrigan, 26, is one of those bad boys who trash hotel rooms.
It's that he's candid about his decadent drug-fueled lifestyle,
which is celebrated in his film. Which means it's pretty
entertaining to meet him flying without a conversational governor
in a bar in Greenwich Village, just off the plane from London, as
he sets out to party through the night. By Linda Lee. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESS-STRESS (New York) _ This tax season something has
changed, even for people far more affluent than I; we can't help
comparing ourselves with all the skinny young eco-conscious
philanthropically correct e-people who don't even have to wear ties
to make their killings. ``At one time you had to work your way
up,'' says a friend who took the slow road from business school to
banking to marketing to Internet-venturing, shedding his expensive
suits in the process. ``These new people skip the meal and go
straight to the dessert, and it's annoying.'' By Bob Morris. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIAMOND-JEWELRY (New York) _ While it's true that the diamond
has never gone out of style, this season the ultimate rock _ which
happens to be April's birthstone _ has transcended its own
perennial appeal. Diamond jewelry is so much in vogue that even the
engagement ring has become a fashion item. Once upon a time diamond
rings represented husbands. (Just ask Elizabeth Taylor, who
received both the 33.19-carat Krupp diamond and a 69.42-carat
Cartier rock as gifts from Richard Burton.) But now ``they are
considered not just tokens of affection but accessories,'' said
Anne Slowey, Elle magazine's fashion news director. By Hadley
Davis. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Flowering quince is a spectacular
sight in the early spring, with its bare branches covered in waxy,
inch-wide blossoms in shades of rose, red, pink or orangey-red.
There are single, semi-double and fully double flowers, all a
credit to the rose family, to which flowering quince belongs. The
fact that gardeners are willing to devote space to flowering quince
_ and often to several varieties of flowering quince _ is a tip-off
to how spectacular those spring flowers are. By Cass Peterson. &QL; 
 &QL;
