A7031 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-570(T     04-14 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-570(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL NEGOTIATORS REACH TENTATIVE AGREEMENT ON HMO
APPEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., this story may update later) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a breakthrough, House and Senate negotiators
said on Friday that they had reached a tentative agreement on an
appeals process for patients denied care by health maintenance
organizations _ a major issue in legislation to define patients'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, patients could obtain ``an independent
medical review'' of any decision in which an HMO denied care or
coverage on the ground that a particular service was not medically
necessary or was experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Patients could also obtain an independent review whenever an HMO
concludes that a particular item or service is ``not a covered
benefit.'' The review might be done by lawyers if it involved only
the interpretation of an insurance contract. But it would have to
be done by doctors if the dispute involved a medical question _
whether, for example, a surgical procedure is purely cosmetic or is
needed to correct a medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   After six weeks of negotiations, Republicans and Democrats from
the House and the Senate issued a detailed summary of what they
called a ``bipartisan bicameral agreement'' on the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cautioned that it was an agreement in principle, a
conceptual agreement, to be translated into legislative language
over the spring recess, but they confirmed that the conferees had
made substantial progress on one of the most important provisions
of the legislation to define patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three states have laws or regulations that require
managed-care plans to have some type of ``external review''
procedure so patients can challenge a denial of care of coverage.
In general, HMOs, state officials and consumer groups say the
appeal procedures have worked well, ruling for patients in about
half the cases and for insurers in the other half.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers say the appeal procedures can raise the standard of
medical care, by requiring doctors to consider the views of outside
experts on whether a particular treatment is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal process, by resolving disputes promptly, can reduce
the need for litigation, consumers and insurers say. The number of
appeals averages one for every 16,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, the Oklahoma Republican who is chairman of the
conference committee, called the appeals process ``a very
significant provision'' of the patient's bill of rights. He said it
would let patients in ``every employer-sponsored plan in the
country'' _ 125 million people _ have the right to an external
review.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives like Nickles and liberal Democrats like Sen.
Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts found they could agree on the
proposition that medical decisions should be made by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ernie Fletcher, R-Ky., a member of the conference
committee, described the agreement as ``a major bipartisan
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Under this agreement, said Fletcher, a family doctor, ``if your
HMO denies the care you need, you will be able to appeal that
decision to ensure that physicians make medical decisions, not
insurance bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement sets forth a wide range of factors that would have
to be considered by medical reviewers. Specifically, it says, their
decisions shall be based on patient's medical condition and medical
records; ``valid, relevant scientific evidence and clinical
evidence, including peer-reviewed medical literature''; and the
consensus of experts on what treatments are appropriate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agreement includes these provisions:
</P>
<P>
   _Patients could appeal if the denial of a benefit poses a
significant risk to a patient's life or health, or if the value of
the benefit exceeds ``a significant threshold,'' to be specified by
the government.
</P>
<P>
   _A patient filing an appeal could be required to pay a $50 fee.
The money would be refunded if the patient prevailed. Low-income
people could have the charge waived.
</P>
<P>
   _The secretary of health and human services would set standards
to make sure reviewers had no conflicts of interest and no
financial incentive to rule in a particular way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
