<HEADER>
A7035 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-ALLERGY-WEBSITE-ART-$     04-14 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLERGY-WEBSITE-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASS THE INHALER: I FEEL A CHIC ATTACK COMING ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT11  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (For release Sunday, April 16)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tree season 2000 is upon us, the harbinger of pollen
counts to come. But I say to you, my fellow allergy and asthma
sufferers, do not be ashamed or embarrassed by your wheezing, runny
noses and rheumy eyes. Own your symptoms! These most geeky of
afflictions are on the verge of becoming chic.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the anti-allergy drug commercials on television.
Blissed-out models with flowers coming out their ears, in some kind
of psychedelic reverie Timothy Leary would have dreamed up if he
had worked on Madison Avenue. Who needs Zoloft and Atavan when
you've got Allegra and Claritin?
</P>
<P>
   On May 4, Teresa Hale of the Hale Clinic in London _ an
alternative medicine center founded by Prince Charles and once
frequented by Diana, Princess of Wales _ will be in New York.
Hale's practitioners will be conducting a three-day, $500 workshop
propounding a wholistic treatment for asthma, through a series of
breathing exercises. A disease has not really arrived until there's
a wholistic cure.
</P>
<P>
   But definitive proof of the hotness of respiratory ailments can
be found _ and purchased _ at Gazoontite.com. A Web site and a
catalog, not to mention a new retail store on Broadway near 75th
Street, Gazoontite.com sells everything from $699 Miele vacuum
cleaners and hypo-allergenic comforters covered in 230-thread-count
cotton to a rubber Bart Simpson that fits over an inhaler.
Everything for the allergy, asthma and status-symbol victim.
</P>
<P>
   As a lifelong asthmatic who is allergic to pollen, cats and the
women who love them, I can attest that these have never been
glamorous ailments. And there has always been the suspicion among
less tolerant nonsufferers that all that annoying sneezing and
wheezing is really just psychosomatic.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the embarrassment factor. When I was a young nipper, the
last thing I wanted was for someone to know I got shots or needed
an inhaler, much less catch me sneaking a puff. You don't want to
arm other small boys with that kind of information. This continued
into my 30s. Not long ago, a friend and I were on our way out of
his apartment when my bright yellow Proventil dispenser fell out of
my jacket pocket. We both stared down at where it lay on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa, `Afterschool Special' moment,'' he said. It was as if he
had found out I couldn't read.
</P>
<P>
   It amazes me that today's youngsters would want to advertise
their handicap with a rubber Bart Simpson. An article in Spin a few
years ago said rappers were customizing their inhalers, encasing
them in model low-rider cars and the like.
</P>
<P>
   Gazoontite.com is sort of the same idea, upscaled. The company
started in 1998 in San Francisco. It has stores there and in Costa
Mesa, Calif. The catalog eschews the medicinal, hospital-supply
look of its predecessors in favor of a sleek Pottery Barn effect.
In the sparely modern bedroom on Page 4, the blond-wood Eames chair
and white $160 Honeywell HEPA air purifier are both triumphs of
allergy-friendly design (``avoid upholstered furniture,'' the copy
counsels). Lying on the bed is a washable yellow plush duck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our signature duck,'' explained Soon Yu, the company's founder
and chief executive, as he gave me a tour of the 750-square-foot
store. ``He's kind of a noble duck with allergies.''
</P>
<P>
   Yu, 34, has an MBA from Stanford and was a product manager at
Clorox before starting Gazoontite.com. And he has allergies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing to be embarrassed about,'' he said. ``There's no
stigma. We're taking a positive approach with a way you can manage
your lifestyle to act healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked about the sleek, minimal design. The floor and walls are
bamboo plywood, the products presented in simple, uncluttered
display cases. The $99 black Vornado 750 fan somehow looks sexier
here than it does at Bed, Bath and Beyond for $89.99.
</P>
<P>
   Yu told me his creative director came from Swatch. The McCall
Design Group, whose credits include Banana Republic and Pottery
Barn, gave Gazoontite.com its mall-ready in-store architecture.
``It's a cross between the Body Shop and a Brookstone,'' he said.
Focus groups did not recognize the German word when it was spelled
gesundheit and helped determine the name.
</P>
<P>
   There are also, as you may have guessed from the name, plans for
an IPO within a year, Yu said. He rattled off business-plan data.
``There is 20 percent-a-year growth in the air purification
business alone,'' he said. ``And 38 percent of the population has
allergies, versus 20 percent in 1990.''
</P>
<P>
   These statistics turn out to be mostly accurate, according to
Dr. Ira Finegold, chief allergist at St. Luke's Roosevelt Hospital
Center and a past president of the American College of Allergy,
Asthma and Immunology. A survey by the college in June 1999 asked
1,004 adults if they had allergies. Of those, 38 percent said yes.
They hadn't necessarily been diagnosed by a doctor, but the figure
was still surprisingly high. ``The figure people used to always
talk about was 20 percent,'' Finegold said.
</P>
<P>
   We think of allergies as an outdoor problem. But in fact, the
more adults and children stay indoors, the doctor said, the more
susceptible they are to the allergens that get trapped inside the
hermetically sealed modern home.
</P>
<P>
   I asked my own allergist, Dr. Arthur M. Lubitz, to examine
Gazoontite.com and give me a second opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's legit,'' he said, after stopping by the store
last week, with some caveats for allergic emptors. The HEPA (High
Efficiency Particulate Air) purifiers ``do next to nothing'' unless
you have a pet, he said. And changing the filter on a window-unit
air conditioner is as effective a guard against airborne pollens.
Pillow and bed covers, the store's top sellers so far, are useful
if you're allergic to dust mites, but not every allergic person is.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction is, I'm jealous,'' he added ruefully.
``Every allergist always says how much money there is in
allergies.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that Mayor John Lindsay pledged during his
administration to eliminate ragweed from New York City, but this,
like many such pledges, did not pan out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get rid of ragweed, and every single person in New
York has a cat,'' Lubitz noted. ``Allergies are an urban disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Make that urbane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
