<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, April 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorms will erupt later Saturday from Kansas to
Texas as a dry line, which marks the boundary between very humid
air from the Gulf of Mexico and dry air from the Rockies, is
activated by a potent jet stream disturbance. Large hail, damaging
winds and tornadoes are likely.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, showers and thunderstorms will develop along a
cold front stretching from the western Great Lakes to the central
Plains. Deep in the cold air north of the front, pockets of
generally light snow will likely develop from parts of South Dakota
to the upper peninsula of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture associated with the heavy rain in Florida Friday will
flow into the northern Middle Atlantic states, setting the stage
for moderate to locally heavy rains in parts of Northern Virginia
and the Delmarva Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WET TRANSITION
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2.5 inches of rain fell in 90 minutes at Miami
International Airport Friday as heavy showers and thunderstorms
bombarded South Florida. The rain prompted flood advisories for
metropolitan areas of Broward and Miami-Dade Counties. April is the
transition from the dry season in South Florida to the wet one.
While winter is the dry season, occasional cold fronts produce
modest rains. From May to October, frequent thunderstorms
associated with se-breeze fronts and tropical systems bring more
than two-thirds of Miami's annual average rainfall of about 60
inches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BEOWULF15-COX     04-14 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEOWULF15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Beowulf: A hero for our time
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is a scene in Woody Allen's 1977
film, ``Annie Hall,'' in which the comedian gives academic advice
to his girlfriend:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't take any course where they make you read `Beowulf','' he
counsels.
</P>
<P>
   The whole history of ``Beowulf,'' the oldest poem in the English
language, is one of hairbreadth escapes from fire, bombardment,
disdain, neglect, the yawning boredom of undergraduates and the
stony indifference of the English-speaking public. ``Beowulf'' is a
powerful, jagged poem, but it is usually considered too remote, too
outlandish to interest anyone but scholars. The names are
especially confusing: Hrothgar, Hygd, Hygelac, Heorot, Heothalaf,
Hunferth, Hnaef, Hengest and Hildeburh.
</P>
<P>
   But now there's Heaney, and suddenly ``Beowulf'' is back with a
vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   Pulitzer Prize-winning Irish poet Seamus Heaney has rescued and
re-created the 3,182-line Anglo-Saxon epic in a powerful new
translation that has soared to 13th place on The New York Times'
best-seller list _ a dizzying success for a book of verse. Heaney's
achievement is to place ``Beowulf'' before the eyes of a mass
audience for the first time in history, without watering it down,
tarting it up or turning it into Ye Olde Englysshe jingles.
</P>
<P>
   There have been approximately 65 English translations of
``Beowulf'' by now, with most students relying on Francis Gummere's
1910 version, or R.K. Gordon's 1926 prose rendition, published by
the Everyman library. Heaney's, put out this year by Farrar Strauss
and Giroux, has a sticker price of $25 but can be had for less than
half that from online booksellers. It has won the prestigious
Whitbread Award in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beowulf'' is available in a comic book version, and in 1976,
author Michael Crichton reworked the story in his ``Eaters of the
Dead,'' recently reissued as ``The 13th Warrior,'' which is
available in video and DVD. But Heaney's version is extraordinary
for its clarity and immediacy. The original Anglo-Saxon text is
printed on facing pages.
</P>
<P>
   Heaney began working on ``Beowulf'' 30 years ago, tried doing 20
lines a day, gave up and put the project aside. Then one day, as he
relates in a thoughtful preface, his memories of Ulster and the
simple gravity of the common, everyday speech in Northern Ireland
made him realize suddenly that he had a special affinity for
Anglo-Saxon poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I am saying is that I consider `Beowulf' to be part of my
voice-right,'' Heaney says.
</P>
<P>
   In brief, `Beowulf' is a poem broken into two parts, which deals
with a hero's battles against three monsters. The first is Grendel,
``a kind of dog-breath in the dark,'' Heaney calls him in his
preface, ``some hard-boned and immensely strong android frame.''
Beowulf waits for Grendel to emerge from his foul fen and raid the
hall, seizes the creature's hand with his own bare hand and _ such
is the strength of his grip _ rips Grendel's hand off. Grendel
flees and bleeds to death.
</P>
<P>
   This arouses the wrath of Grendel's mother, an underwater
creature described in the original Anglo-Saxon as ``merewif,
brimwylf, grundwyrgen,'' (''water-woman, she-wolf of the sea,
accursed she-monster of the deep''). She visits the hall on an
errand of murder, and Beowulf pursues her, plunging underwater to
slay her with a massive sword he finds hanging on the wall of her
lair. So poisonous is her blood that the blade dissolves in it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in the third part, which happens 50 years later, the
aging Beowulf confronts a dragon that menaces his people. He and
the ``fire-drake'' kill each other. The poem ends with Beowulf's
funeral pyre, his entombment in a ship within a great mound, and
the keening of the hero's tribeswomen.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the work deals with a succession of fantastic
monsters, even though it is written in a high, heroic, allusive
style _ the sea, for example, isn't called ``the sea'' but instead
``the whale path'' _ Heaney insists ``Beowulf'' is a serious,
direct poem that is ``always, paradoxically, buoyantly down to
earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The description of the hero's funeral pyre at the end of the
poem, the crackle of the flames, the bursting of his ribs in the
heat, the lamentation of the women ``could come straight from a
late-20th-century news report, from Rwanda or Kosovo,'' Heaney
asserts. They provide ``a nightmare glimpse into the minds of
people who have survived traumatic, even monstrous events and who
are now being exposed to a comfortless future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were disconsolate
</P>
<P>
   and wailed aloud for their lord's decease.
</P>
<P>
   A Geat woman too sang out in grief;
</P>
<P>
   with hair bound up, she unburdened herself
</P>
<P>
   of her worst fears, a wild litany
</P>
<P>
   of nightmare and lament: her nation invaded,
</P>
<P>
   enemies on the rampage, bodies in piles,
</P>
<P>
   slavery and abasement. Heaven swallowed the smoke ... ``
</P>
<P>
   Fire consumes Beowulf, and fire almost consumed the ``Beowulf''
manuscript. The poem is preserved in one single manuscript written
on parchment, the tanned hide of a sheep, about the year 1000. Its
whereabouts for 700 years are unknown. It turns up first in a 1705
catalog of the library of an antiquarian, Sir Robert Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   A disastrous fire broke out in Cotton's library on a winter
evening in 1731, and servants flung smoldering books from the
windows to save them. Much was destroyed, but the ``Beowulf''
manuscript survived, though so grievously charred around the edges
that many words were lost. The fire dried out the parchment, which
crumbled more and more as the years passed.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, an inquisitive Danish scholar, G.K. Thorkelin,
traveled to Cotton House in 1787 and made two careful
transcriptions of the manuscript, one in his own hand, the other
commissioned. The burnt edges of the parchment were in somewhat
better condition in Thorkelin's time, and his copies have proved
invaluable to subsequent scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Thorkelin took his copies back to Copenhagen _ where they nearly
perished in a British naval bombardment in 1807, during the
Napoleonic Wars. Thorkelin's translation of the poem perished in
flames, but his two valuable transcriptions of the text survived
and are still in the Royal Library in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   The bombardment set Thorkelin back eight years. He had to redo
his translation from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the first published translation of ``Beowulf''
appeared in 1815, not in England, but in Denmark. Nor was it called
``Beowulf.'' Instead, it bore a ponderous Latin title that
signified ``Concerning the History of the Danes, in a poem of the
Danes in the Anglo-Saxon Dialect.''
</P>
<P>
   A facsimile of the manuscript was published in 1882. In 1931,
the precious manuscript was rebound and the parchment leaves inset
in paper to protect their edges. Today, it is in the British
Museum, under glass.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the poem remained a curio, dismissed by critics like the
distinguished W.P. Ker, who wrote: ``The fault of `Beowulf' is that
there is nothing much in the story. The hero is occupied in killing
monsters ... It is too simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Two things happened in the 1930s to turn the tide in
``Beowulf's'' favor. The first was a 1936 essay by J.R.R. Tolkien
(famed today as the author of ``The Lord of the Rings''), called
``Beowulf: The Monsters and the Critics.''
</P>
<P>
   Tolkien, who had served at the front in World War I, pointed out
that monstrous evil and random murder were not just things that
lived in a swamp, like Grendel, or at the bottom of a pool, like
Grendel's mother, or atop a hoard of jewels, like the dragon. They
were _ they are _ lurking still on the dark edges of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   Reading ``Beowulf,'' Tolkien says, ``We look down as if from a
visionary height upon the house of man in the valley of the world.
A light starts ... and there is the sound of music; but the outer
darkness and its hostile offspring lie ever in wait for the torches
to fail and the voices to cease. Grendel is maddened by the sound
of harps.''
</P>
<P>
   The second event was the discovery in 1939 of a vast, rich
ship-burial at Sutton Hoo in Sussex. Armor, a glorious helmet, a
shield, an entire ship dating to the seventh century were excavated
from ancient mounds lying on the property of Edith Pretty, a local
landowner. Suddenly, the age of ``Beowulf'' came brilliantly to
life.
</P>
<P>
   A legal battle followed, over whether the treasures belonged to
the government or to Pretty. If they were a ``treasure-trove,''
buried with the intent to dig them up again some day, they were
forfeit to the government. But if they were buried with no intent
to recover them, then they were not Crown property.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 14, 1939, a coroner's jury heard testimony that included
a reading from ``Beowulf,'' lines 3156-68, describing how the
hero's burial mound was built and filled with ``rings and jewels
... the wealth of nobles ... gold in the earth, where it still
exists as useless to men as it was before ... ``
</P>
<P>
   The gold wasn't meant to be dug up. It was buried as a mark of
honor. It was meant to be ``useless.'' The jury ruled in Pretty's
favor. The hoard was hers.
</P>
<P>
   Edith Pretty then donated the entire Sutton Hoo trove to the
British Museum, where it can still be seen today.
</P>
<P>
   Heaney's translation is another leap forward for ``Beowulf.''
The translator confesses his especial love for the lines describing
the great hall of Heorot, where there are the echoes of
</P>
<P>
   `` ... the harp being struck
</P>
<P>
   and the clear song of a skilled poet
</P>
<P>
   telling with mastery of man's beginnings,
</P>
<P>
   How the Almighty had made the earth
</P>
<P>
   a gleaming plain girdled with waters;
</P>
<P>
   in His splendour he set the sun and the moon
</P>
<P>
   to be earth's lamplight, lanterns for men,
</P>
<P>
   and filled the broad lap of the world
</P>
<P>
   with branches and leaves; and quickened life
</P>
<P>
   in every other thing that moved ... ``
</P>
<P>
   All of which Grendel hears, and hates: Roused by the music, the
monster wends his way in darkness, toward the bright hall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
