u e BC-JULIE-GOLD15-COX     04-14 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JULIE-GOLD15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Idealistic composer bridges `Distance' by performing live
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ When you've written one of the most
enduring pop songs of the past couple of decades, what can you
possibly do for a follow-up?
</P>
<P>
   For Julie Gold, the composer and lyricist of ``From a
Distance,'' there's only one answer: You start singing it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the 44-year-old Gold isn't grateful to Bette Midler for
her hit rendition _ or to the countless other artists who have
claimed the song for themselves. It's just that Gold has her own
particular idea about how to perform ``From a Distance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it exactly the way I wrote it,'' she says of her simple,
declarative approach, speaking by phone from her New York home.
``It never gets tired or old for me. It's like a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the story of the song's genesis speaks to the very
heavenly ideals behind it. Although Gold, a Philadelphia native
reared in a Jewish home, insists she never attached any religious
significance to the words _ ``Writing about God is easy and normal
for me. It's the same as writing about love or a flower,'' she says
_ she admits there had to be a bit of divine inspiration. At the
time she composed it in 1986, she was a struggling songwriter,
paying the rent through odd jobs as a secretary, waiting for her
big break. To help her along, her parents agreed to ship her
childhood piano to her Manhattan apartment to replace the cheap
electronic keyboard she had been using. A day after it arrived _
she was warned by the movers to let the instrument rest _ she wrote
``From a Distance'' in about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just poured out of me,'' Gold recalls. ``It had been
ruminating inside of me for a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The song was not an easy sell at first. Gold got a handful of
rejections from various publishing houses and artists _ and has
hanging in her apartment the pitch letter she sent to Midler that
initially went ignored. The first to finally claim it was
country-folk singer Nanci Griffith. In 1990, when a still
struggling Gold was getting by with financial support from her
parents, Midler's people finally called.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, the single sold more than one million copies and
earned Gold the Grammy for ``Song of the Year.'' The songwriter,
who still didn't expect Midler's name to guarantee a place for
``From a Distance'' on the top of the charts, describes the
phenomenon like this: ``It really burned its way through the heart
and soul of humanity.'' To the dismay of Gold, an ardent pacifist,
the song was even used as a rallying cry for the American troops in
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Gold was able to devote herself to music full time after the
success of ``From a Distance.'' Although she's never had another
song achieve the same degree of commercial recognition, her music
has been performed by artists ranging from R&AMP;B diva Patti LaBelle
to Broadway star Lea Salonga to chanteuse Andrea Marcovicci. But
the focus of Gold's work in the past decade has been on performing.
She's developed her own cabaret show, appeared as a member of the
singer-songwriter revue Four Bitchin' Babes and recorded an album,
``Dream Loud,'' of 12 of her songs, including, ``From a Distance.''
(Her version, by the way, will easily make you forget everyone
else's.) A second album is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Gold, whose musical influences range from classical to Broadway
to '60s rock, admits her lyrical style, both as a singer and
songwriter, is out of fashion in today's musical scene. Her
compositions range from a gentle musing on her mother's struggle as
an immigrant (``Goodnight, New York'') to a charged ballad that
touches upon recent political events (``Tiger in New Jersey''). Her
belief is in the power of the song, not the sales figures. ``The
joy is in the birthing process,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   And what does Gold do when she finishes giving ``birth'' to a
song? ``I kiss the keys and I say, `Thank you, God,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
