<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-RELIGION-MLK15-COX     04-14 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-MLK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King monument lacks 2 key words
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A handsome black granite monument
dedicated last week honors Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and makes
West Palm Beach a far better place.
</P>
<P>
   But the monument's inscription omits, arguably the two most
important words in King's life: The Reverend. Unfortunately, that
badly serves the man and the source of his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Most people today know that King was a clergyman. Future
generations may not. Doctor is an academic title. The Reverend is a
title of commitment, discipline and promise.
</P>
<P>
   King's gift to us is rooted in Christian ministry.
</P>
<P>
   He did represent a legion of cultural symbols. He was, among
other hot-button icons of the '60s, an outspoken Southern black
man, Baptist preacher, civil rights leader and practitioner of
nonviolent protest.
</P>
<P>
   But King fundamentally was a man of God, a disciple of Christ,
rooted in the grand heritage of thundering Old Testament prophets.
They proved that the pen is greater than the sword. King's words
did the same and will endure as his greatest monument.
</P>
<P>
   The gleaming granite wall at the north end of Currie Park
overlooking the Intracoastal Waterway on Flagler Drive is a
marvelous addition to both the landscape and the spirit of West
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   It was dedicated Saturday, April 8, to mark the 32nd anniversary
of King's assassination in Memphis on April 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Prophets are often victims of violent death. They speak a
simple, unsettling truth that can neither be denied nor embraced by
those who would preserve an unjust status quo. So most prophets are
killed.
</P>
<P>
   King, convinced he was called to the terrifying task of speaking
God's word, did so in the mold of classic Hebrew prophets such as
Isaiah and Jeremiah.
</P>
<P>
   Most prophets, King included, generally make only two points.
</P>
<P>
   They condemn, in the name of God, flagrant injustice they see
taken for granted in a self-satisfied society. They point out
glaring contradictions between a people's words and their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Hebrew prophets called Israel to account for honoring the God of
the poor while trampling the poor underfoot. King exposed, as few
had, the blatant racial inequalities abroad in a land that claimed
all men were created equal.
</P>
<P>
   Prophets then offer hope. Hebrew prophets told a chastened
nation that God would act to bring new life to Israel. Christians
claim God did that in the birth of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   King's hope was a dream of brotherhood, equality and peace among
all races. He denounced injustice and gave us promise in the name
of a righteous and compassionate God.
</P>
<P>
   This giant of a man is better remembered as The Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
