<HEADER>
A7043 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-JEANS-FASHION-ART-$AD     04-14 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEANS-FASHION-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW OLD THING: DOCTORED DENIM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(For release Sun., April 16) 
 By ALEX WITCHEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In ancient times, when I was a teen-ager, parents had
two perennial questions: ``When are you going to cut that hair?''
and ``When are you going to wash those jeans?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never'' was the usual answer to both, though mothers had a
sneaky way of absconding with the jeans while we overslept,
answering wailed complaints with comments like ``They were so dirty
they could stand up without you.'' The fact that the pants had
molded perfectly to your imperfect body after long weeks of wear,
that the dusty, ragged hems had to be that way because everyone's
were, that each day of adolescent angst was so traumatizing that
just putting them on in the morning offered the same solace that
slippers did at night _ none of that seemed to matter.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help remembering those times last week as I stood at
the Denim Bar at Barneys New York with Megan Mitchell, the
department's buyer. It seems that while I was sleeping, I missed
more than the laundry. Jeans are back, and they have left Woodstock
decidedly behind. They are the season's biggest fashion trend,
running the gamut from sequined to studded, dark to light, hot
pants to cropped to full length.
</P>
<P>
   The trendiest part of the trend, dirty denim, reflects the rest
of our instant theme park culture: it has been dirtied for you in
advance _ prestained, preburnt or prepainted. After all, with
trends moving so fast, who has time to wear them in?
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of despairing when you see white pull marks shoot
across your thighs, you must rejoice. It's not that you're too fat;
the manufacturer has ``whiskered'' the pants for you. Hems, pockets
and waistlines are ripped and frayed _ distressed is the fancy word
for it. At $195, you can buy a pair of pants that look as if you've
been road-tripping with Thelma and Louise, coated triumphantly in
dust. No longer do you own jeans forever and fondly remember when.
The manufacturer has gotten there first, and retailers say they
can't keep the product on the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been building up to this,'' Mitchell said. ``We've
noticed increased sales in denim during the last few seasons. Denim
is comfortable, it comes in a variety of fits, people especially
like stretch denim, and you can dress it up or down.''
</P>
<P>
   Why dirty? ``It's just another way to express yourself in
denim,'' she said with the placid acceptance of the absurd that all
successful fashion executives employ. ``It looks newer to me. We
had dark denim a couple of years ago. Now we need another option.''
She also said that denim's versatility _ mixing and matching it,
dirty or otherwise, with beaded tops or ostrich skirts _ adds to
its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell could only describe the paint-spattered and burnt
jeans, however: they had already sold out. The stained jeans were
still available, by Helmut Lang in black ($162) and blue ($195).
There were also Anna Sui jeans, cropped and full length with an
antique wash (sort of faded), that were studded and decorated with
sparkles for $435.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just pocket change compared with Bergdorf's. There,
you can take your jeans to J. Mendel, its in-house furrier, which
will rework them with sable or mink trims for $2,350 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Herman, the owner of Ron Herman at Fred Segal Melrose in
Beverly Hills, who has been selling cutting-edge jeans since 1970,
dismisses the dirty denim trend as ``a meaningless, superficial,
insignificant flash in the pan.'' His store would never stoop to
dirty denim, he said, only authentic vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Less incensed was Jack Markus, the owner of Cheap Jack's, the
used clothing mecca on Broadway. Genuinely ``dirty'' jeans sell
there for $19 to $60. ``In the mid-'80s I used to slice up the
jeans, rip, dye and patch them,'' Markus said. ``The worse they
looked, the better they liked them. Designers always follow street
fashion, and street fashion starts when there's too much of
something that people can buy for cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   With this wisdom in mind, I went to Intermix on Madison Avenue.
Debbie Baron Rosen manages this boutique, where Helmut Lang dirty
jeans sell for $189 ($6 less than at Barneys), and when I cited
high school visits to the Army Navy for $25 jeans, her look was as
dirty as the denim. ``Have you been shopping lately?'' she asked
sharply, dumping me in the dressing room as an assistant informed
her that someone from a public relations firm was out front. First
though, she quickly assessed my behind in the jeans (the length was
ridiculous, way too long) and nodded approvingly. ``If you find a
pair of jeans that fit well, you pay anything,'' she advised.
``Everybody has jeans. People want to look different somehow, and
these are a great fit and make your legs look long.''
</P>
<P>
   How six inches of extra material flapping around my ankles made
my legs look long was not a subject she wanted to pursue, and she
took off for the greener pastures of pulling clothes for an unnamed
celebrity client while her representative squealed appreciatively
at every tank top that was presented.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at some denim dresses with embroidered hems and a denim
bandeau top with matching skirt and tried on a $138 Earl Jeans
jacket, which I had no interest in buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't faint from the prices!'' Baron Rosen called as I left. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ha, ha, ha, I waved back. What did I expect, shopping for jeans
on Madison Avenue?
</P>
<P>
   At Saks Fifth Avenue, I found a simpatico soul in Michael Macko,
its publicity manager, who had pulled some dirty denim pieces for
me to borrow for the weekend. Two things fit: a Helmut Lang jacket
for $350 and a DKNY cropped shirt with three-quarter sleeves for
$125. Both looked reasonably filthy, though because of the shirt's
sleek cut, the dissonant effect was more pronounced. I decided I
would wear it out for a night of cocktails, theater and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   As Macko wrapped them up and answered my smart-alecky question
about how to wash dirty denim to keep it dirty (in the washing
machine _ the dye won't come out), he explained denim's appeal in
general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denim nowadays is all about what you can do to make it look
different,'' he said. ``It all started with Gucci when Tom Ford did
beaded and feathered jeans. We're seeing a lot of studs lately,
too; Dolce &AMP; Gabbana has studded denim bustiers.'' He stopped to
inhale with alarm at a hapless, middle-aged woman, trying on an
enormous denim ball skirt.
</P>
<P>
   He turned away hurriedly, as if to wipe the image from his mind.
``Denim is a basic fabric now,'' he continued. ``We have denim
halter dresses and hot pants, even denim hair accessories. Stila
makes a denim makeup collection in shades of blue and the packaging
looks like denim. Denim is the great equalizer, a common
denominator, a great fabric.''
</P>
<P>
   I was sold, all the way until I got dressed to go out that
Sunday night. I had matched the DKNY top with a straight black
skirt and black boots, and started to worry that I might be too
underdressed for a cocktail party celebrating ``Now This,'' the new
book by Judy Muller, an ABC correspondent. But even though the help
was dressed better than I was, no one looked askance at my outfit,
and I made it to the Manhattan Theater Club ego intact. In that
crowd, I was certainly no more underdressed than anyone else, and
during intermission I realized why no one I encountered had
registered the impact of this latest fashion trend: they were all
my age or older and had all grown up with the same dirty jeans, the
same long hair, the same nagging parents I had. Dirty denim wasn't
new and exciting to them. It was old and familiar. They all had the
same stuff at home. Whether it still fit them or not.
</P>
<P>
   That must be what makes a trend, I thought, taking my seat for
the second act. You have to be young enough to believe that it's
new.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7046 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV16-     04-14 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANTS THAT SPEAK FOR THEIR SEASONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 16)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nature puts no particular premium on perfection _ least of all
as it's defined by gardeners _ so it should not count against
flowering quince and beautyberry that they are essentially
one-season plants.
</P>
<P>
   Trees aside, there aren't many outdoor plants that can be truly
called all-season ornamentals. Blueberry bushes, maybe, and
hollies. Russian sage comes close. Most other ornamental plants
look gorgeous for a brief period each year and then fade drably
into the background. Even evergreens get the blahs in midwinter,
when they look good only because the alternative is no green at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Consider forsythia. For a few weeks in early March (or a little
earlier or later, depending on latitude and the severity of
winter), forsythia is a fountain of gold to gladden the heart _
assuming that it hasn't been sheared into a fat gumdrop shape in
some misguided attempt at tidiness. The rest of the year, forsythia
is at best a humdrum bush, green but otherwise nondescript.
</P>
<P>
   Every July, I itch to rip out the forsythia bushes and replace
them with something that has more oomph. But I don't. I just prune
out about a third of their tangled branches and ignore the boring
green blobs until the following March, when I am very happy to see
them.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with flowering quince. It's a spectacular sight in the
early spring, with its bare branches covered in waxy, inch-wide
blossoms in shades of rose, red, pink or orangey-red. There are
single, semi-double and fully double flowers, all a credit to the
rose family, to which flowering quince belongs.
</P>
<P>
   Out of bloom, though, a flowering quince is just a leafy, thorny
thing in the yard. The fact that gardeners are willing to devote
space to flowering quince _ and often to several varieties of
flowering quince _ is a tip-off to how spectacular those spring
flowers are.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes flowering quince will set a few hard, greenish fruits.
The fruit isn't much to look at, but it makes good jam and it
smells nice. Some gardeners put quinces in the linen closet to
scent the sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Some varieties can grow to 10 feet, but quinces grow so slowly
that they're even favored by bonsai enthusiasts. A small plant will
take 10 years to grow 3 or 4 feet tall.
</P>
<P>
   Cultivars or hybrids of Chaenomeles japonica, or Maule's quince,
(known in the South as Japonica bush) are naturally dwarf. But the
taller C. speciosa varieties offer a broader range of flower
colors, and you can prune the shrub at any time of year to keep it
the height you prefer.
</P>
<P>
   Beautyberry wisely squanders its single season of splendor in
the autumn. Spring is already overcrowded with splashy
short-timers. Beautyberry can also grow to 10 feet, with foliage
that is pleasant but not showstopping. Its summer flowers are so
tiny you practically have to squint to see them.
</P>
<P>
   But in autumn, it bears fat clusters of shiny berries in a
preposterous shade of metallic lavender. Hence, its genus name,
Callicarpa, from the Greek kallos (beauty) and karpos (fruit). The
berries would probably last well into the winter, making
beautyberry a two-season or at least a season-and-a-half plant, but
what I don't cut for flower arrangements the birds eat.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two, flowering quince is the tougher plant. It is hardy
into New England and is often described as carefree. That means it
isn't fussy about soil conditions and, once established in a sunny
spot, will survive even if you never get around to watering,
fertilizing or pruning it.
</P>
<P>
   It is, in fact, very easy to ignore flowering quince once it's
done blooming, but you will get more of the lovely spring flowers
if you prune lightly every year to encourage the growth of new
wood. Flowers appear only on new growth.
</P>
<P>
   There are any number of fabulous cultivars. Jet Trail has snowy
white flowers, Texas Scarlet is bright red and Cameo is a lovely
salmon, the most common color of flowering quince. Apple Blossom
has white flowers that age to pale pink, and Simonii has dark red
blossoms. Winter Cheer, one of the earliest quinces to bloom, has
scarlet flowers.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad idea to buy quinces in bloom. Unlike some
flowering plants, they don't require stressful forcing to be in
bloom during the prime spring sales season. So the plants you see
in garden centers will probably be blooming at their natural time,
and you'll get a chance to see what the flowers look like.
</P>
<P>
   Beautyberry, in the verbena family, is a little less hardy than
flowering quince. It will survive and bear fruit as far north as
Boston, but gardeners in colder areas will need to put it in a
protected spot and mulch it. It likes sun or a partly shady area
and is ideal under trees like locusts that don't cast impenetrable
shade.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeast, and as far west as Oklahoma, the beautyberry
species C. americana grows wild on roadsides and at the edge of
woodlands. C. americana boasts large berries, but it is tall and
rangy-looking. Nurseries more commonly offer the species C.
dichotoma, a shorter plant that rarely grows taller than about 4
feet.
</P>
<P>
   I've grown C. dichotoma successfully in a perennial border,
cutting it back to the ground each winter and letting it sprout
anew in the spring. It's quite at home with the herbaceous
perennials, most of them also plants that attract little attention
outside their prime season.
</P>
<P>
   When the right moment arrives, they perform their roles
flawlessly, which might be nature's definition of perfection and
ought to be mine as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
