<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, April 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorms will erupt later Saturday from Kansas to
Texas as a dry line, which marks the boundary between very humid
air from the Gulf of Mexico and dry air from the Rockies, is
activated by a potent jet stream disturbance. Large hail, damaging
winds and tornadoes are likely.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, showers and thunderstorms will develop along a
cold front stretching from the western Great Lakes to the central
Plains. Deep in the cold air north of the front, pockets of
generally light snow will likely develop from parts of South Dakota
to the upper peninsula of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture associated with the heavy rain in Florida Friday will
flow into the northern Middle Atlantic states, setting the stage
for moderate to locally heavy rains in parts of Northern Virginia
and the Delmarva Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WET TRANSITION
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 2.5 inches of rain fell in 90 minutes at Miami
International Airport Friday as heavy showers and thunderstorms
bombarded South Florida. The rain prompted flood advisories for
metropolitan areas of Broward and Miami-Dade Counties. April is the
transition from the dry season in South Florida to the wet one.
While winter is the dry season, occasional cold fronts produce
modest rains. From May to October, frequent thunderstorms
associated with sea-breeze fronts and tropical systems bring more
than two-thirds of Miami's annual average rainfall of about 60
inches.
</P>
</TEXT>
