<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7059 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-SENTRA-ART     04-14 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-SENTRA-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NISSAN SENTRA SE: WILL MORE, MORE, MORE BE ENOUGH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT12 to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nissan, having struggled in recent years to carve out its place
in the sun, has landed on a formula that has long worked with
consumer products from toothpaste to dishwashing soap: new,
improved and more.
</P>
<P>
   With every model it has introduced in the past two years, from
the compact Altima to the mid-size Maxima to the Pathfinder sport
utility, Nissan has offered a much-improved car or truck over the
previous one. In general, those vehicles have delivered more space,
more power, more substance and more features than the earlier
generation. While that recipe is typical of all automakers today,
Nissan has thrown in another ingredient: to be tops in horsepower
performance within the class.
</P>
<P>
   The latest model to adopt the more- is-more formula is the
entry-level Sentra, which began arriving in dealerships in
February. Indeed, the Sentra has moved from its previous life as an
econobox to a refined small car that has more room, more power and
more features than its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   After a pleasant weeklong test drive of the sporty,
top-of-the-line Sentra SE, however, I wondered if more would be
enough in the intensely competitive small-car market.
</P>
<P>
   The Sentra is up against a large and expanding list of
competitors in a market that has been in a slump for nearly three
years. There are the usual suspects: Chevrolet Cavalier and Prizm,
Dodge Neon, Mazda Protege, Mitsubishi Mirage and Ford Escort, to
name only a few. In addition, some innovative new contenders have
cropped up, like the cute Volkswagen Beetle, the flashy Ford Focus,
the funky Toyota Echo with its under $10,000 sticker price, and
even, it could be argued, the retro-looking Chrysler PT Cruiser
just hitting the market. To top it off, Honda will redesign its
segment-leading Civic later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan says the 2000 model is the first Sentra designed
exclusively for North America. The new Sentra appears more ample
than its predecessor. Its body has been stretched by more than six
inches, widened by almost an inch and its height raised an inch.
</P>
<P>
   Its beefier, raised back end gives the impression that this car
has substance. Still, the Sentra, compared with the Focus or the
Beetle, is bland. No one will call it ugly, but no one will turn to
take a look either.
</P>
<P>
   The new Sentra is also more substantial inside. The chassis has
been bulked up for improved ride and handling and enhanced
crashworthiness. Nissan engineers say the side-to-side rigidity of
the vehicle has been increased by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While I couldn't measure it, I could certainly feel it. I
distinctly recall my last test drive of the previous-generation
Sentra. I was suburb-bound on one of Detroit's heavily traveled and
well-worn freeways. Driving the Sentra was downright scary. It felt
tinny and vulnerable in the rush-hour traffic, with which it could
not keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The interior of the new Sentra is roomier than its predecessor
by more than two cubic feet. In fact, it has moved up a class from
subcompact to compact, according to Environmental Protection Agency
classifications. The interior was a collaborative effort of
Nissan's worldwide design offices led by its European studio.
</P>
<P>
   Materials, including the seat cloth, appeared to be of higher
quality than the previous model, which had a rental-car feel.
Storage compartments, including an odd one that lifts open on the
center dash, have been added to the cabin. The front seats were
raised slightly to make it easier to climb in and out.
</P>
<P>
   The Sentra comes as the base XE, mid-level GXE and
top-of-the-line SE as well as the environmentally friendly CA. Side
air bags and anti-lock brakes are available on the GXE and SE for
$699 in the same option package. The SE also adds four-wheel disc
brakes, instead of the front disc and rear drum combination of the
other models.
</P>
<P>
   The front-wheel-drive Sentra offers a choice of two twin-cam,
four-cylinder engines. One is 1.8 liters rated at 126 horsepower;
the other is 2 liters at 145 horsepower, 5 more than on the
previous version. A five-speed manual transmission is standard; a
four-speed automatic is optional.
</P>
<P>
   The tested Sentra SE was outfitted with the larger engine and
the manual transmission. This fun-to-drive package would be my
choice, though I haven't driven the other versions, and, at
$16,397, it would likely would not fit the budgets of many
small-car buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sentra SE reminded me of the Dodge Neon. The peppy engine,
among the top in its class for horsepower, provided confidence for
merging onto freeways, passing on the highway and darting in and
out of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Even the noise level reminded me of the Neon. While not quite as
noisy as the raucous Neon, the Sentra, despite the claims of Nissan
engineers to the contrary, it did not seem nearly as quiet as the
Toyota Corolla and its twin, the Chevrolet Prizm. The noise was not
from the engine but from the road. It resonated rather loudly
throughout the interior cabin on Michigan's choppiest freeway
pavements. I also wondered while driving on the rough asphalt if
the suspension was tuned too firmly for mainstream buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the added horsepower, the Sentra still achieves
respectable fuel economy, ranging up to nearly 30 miles per gallon
on the highway in some versions.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Sentra does not have more of is price. A goal of
the Sentra development program was to reduce the cost to design,
engineer and build the car so the savings could be put into
features the customer notices. To that end, the Sentra's basic
architecture will be shared with six other models sold in Europe
and Japan, with more variations in the works.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Sentras intended for the United States market
are being assembled in Aguascalientes, Mexico, where wages are low,
instead of in Smyrna, Tenn., where it was previously built.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the basic Sentra starts at $12,169, including
delivery charges, about $150 less than its predecessor; the Sentra
SE starts at $16,219.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the new Sentra, with its increased roominess, higher
horsepower and more substantial styling, is a competent contender
among small cars. But it lacks a hook, a necessary ingredient even
among the industry's lowest-priced vehicles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: More room, power and substance, but is it enough?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1728EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
