u e BC-TV-COPPERFIELD-REVIEW     04-14 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COPPERFIELD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DAVID COPPERFIELD': ABUSED CHILD LUCKS OUT DICKENS-STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By NEIL GENZLINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Copperfield's world, as envisioned in the new
``Masterpiece Theater'' treatment of the Dickens classic, is
louder, earthier, more vivid than life as we know it. Whiskers and
sideburns defy laws of gravity and grooming. Canes make a noise
reminiscent of a Concorde at takeoff as they whoosh toward young
knuckles or backsides. Faces are rounder and ruddier than any
today; food must be chewed longer and more ominously.
</P>
<P>
   Such tidbits suggest both the delights and the dangers of trying
to put ``David Copperfield'' on film. The story is so full of
detail and eccentric characters that it begs to be played to the
hilt, but those same attributes give it a sort of gravitational
pull that constantly tries to drag everyone over the line into
cartoonish caricature.
</P>
<P>
   In this two-part rendition, to be broadcast Sunday and Monday on
PBS, the director Simon Curtis does an admirable job of not letting
his big-name cast get sucked into the forbidden zone, or at least
not for very long.
</P>
<P>
   In ``David Copperfield'' Dickens mixed a bit of autobiography,
splashes of high humor and a lot of melodrama to tell the tale of a
boy who bounces from an abusive stepfather to a nightmarish
boarding school to a sweatshop to, finally, a peaceful adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the people David meets along the way would fit
comfortably into ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest,'' beginning
with his donkey-despising great aunt, Betsey Trotwood, played to
delightful perfection by Dame Maggie Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Ian McNeice needs almost no dialogue to capture the daffiness of
Mr. Dick, Betsey's not-quite-all-there companion, and Bob Hoskins
seems unencumbered by the ghost of W.C. Fields as he dives
enthusiastically into the role of David's verbose friend Mr.
Micawber, which Fields played in the 1935 film version.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this ``Copperfield,'' while enjoying the novel's frivolity,
is far from frivolous. Murdstone, David's stepfather, is played so
darkly by Trevor Eve that young viewers, and a few older ones,
might find themselves cringing right along with David. And when the
boy, trying to stave off a beating, gives Murdstone's finger the
bite that gets him banished to boarding school and sets all else in
motion, it is no casual nip.
</P>
<P>
   From the earliest scenes, Curtis makes clear that he means to
give Dickens' light and dark sides equally unflinching treatment.
</P>
<P>
   His actors join that spirit, creating characterizations that
linger long after the closing credits. Some may overindulge _ Ian
McKellen's Creakle, the cold schoolmaster, is almost distractingly
unbalanced, and Nicholas Lyndhurst as the distasteful Uriah Heep at
times lets his expressive eyes do a little too much talking.
</P>
<P>
   But on balance the roles are full without becoming foolish.
Pauline Quirke as Peggotty, the beloved nanny, and Amanda Ryan as
Agnes, David's soul mate, both find the power in their
comparatively quiet _ and normal _ characters.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the character who makes the least impression is
Copperfield himself, both as a boy (Daniel Radcliffe) and as a
young man (Ciaran McMenamin). But David Copperfield is a person
things happen to more than he is a person who makes things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Any attempt to streamline a novel as sprawling as ``David
Copperfield'' for television, even two parts' worth of television,
of course involves choices, and analyzing the ones that went into
this production could make for a lively discussion among Dickens
devotees.
</P>
<P>
   Someone, for instance, might propose this rule for future
adaptations: Never add; only subtract. The proof is a stagecoach
ride that features a gluttonous passenger who munches an impossibly
huge leg of _ well, what? Ostrich? It is a drumstick that looks as
if it came from the Monty Python prop closet, and it probably
should have stayed there. In the novel, the coach passengers are
napping.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with the power of subtraction, chillingly
demonstrated in an early scene. Murdstone and David's mother
(Emilia Fox) are arguing, and back talk was obviously not something
Murdstone expected from his new wife. In the novel, he tells David,
``As this is not a fit scene for the boy _ David, go to bed,'' a
line that could be read with varying severity. But Eve truncates it
to a cold command, delivered as he levels a look of pure fury at
his wife: ``David, go to bed.'' There is little doubt what awaits
the woman once the boy is out of the room.
</P>
<P>
   Subtraction doesn't always work so well. In this production,
David's early friendship with his schoolmate Steerforth is reduced
to a fleeting encounter, though their relationship will be central
later. But it is a forgivable gap in an otherwise rich and
rewarding treatment.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MASTERPIECE THEATER'
</P>
<P>
   David Copperfield
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Sunday and Monday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   A co-production of BBC America and WGBH/Boston. Adapted by
Adrian Hodges from the novel by Charles Dickens. Kate Harwood,
producer; Simon Curtis, director; Jane Tranter of the BBC and
Rebecca Eaton of WGBH, executive producers; Tom Wilkinson,
narrator; Russell Baker, series host.
</P>
<P>
   With: Daniel Radcliffe (Young David Copperfield), Ciaran
McMenamin (Adult David Copperfield), Bob Hoskins (Mr. Micawber),
Maggie Smith (Aunt Betsey), Ian McKellen (Mr. Creakle), Nicholas
Lyndhurst (Uriah Heep), Pauline Quirke (Peggotty), Emilia Fox
(Clara Copperfield), Amanda Ryan (Agnes Wickfield) and Trevor Eve
(Mr. Murdstone).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
