<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST WITH FUNDS WATCH AND THIS WEEK'S MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fundamentals To the Rescue? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the latest leg of the technology route left many
of the sector's longtime bulls scratching their heads.
</P>
<P>
   After all, last week's plunge came just as most United States
companies were preparing to report first-quarter earnings, which by
all accounts are likely to be spectacular. And ``confession
season,'' the period at the end of every quarter when companies
whose earnings will fall short of expectations disclose the bad
news to Wall Street, ended without much pain.
</P>
<P>
   Now the good news is beginning to flood out, as company after
company soundly beats sell-side analysts' expectations (a process
made easier when analysts cooperate with the companies they cover
to set profit estimates a few pennies a share below the companies'
internal projections). Many technology companies are expected to
report year-over-year profit growth of 30 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be another record-breaking quarter as
earnings go,'' said Joseph Kalinowski, equity strategist for IBES,
which tracks analysts' earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   All this has technology stalwarts gnashing their teeth. They are
complaining that investors have turned away from fast-growing
new-economy companies just as the companies have begun to deliver
on their promises.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say the timing of the sell-off makes perfect
sense. Sure, earnings are great _ but the mere fact that earnings
are being reported has forced investors to take another look at the
enormous valuations they have given to technology and Internet
companies like JDS Uniphase and Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a stock's most basic fundamental is its
price-to-earnings ratio. And in the last two years, those ratios at
many new-economy companies have risen to 100, 200, 300 or even
more, implying that it will take centuries for the companies to
achieve cumulative earnings equal to their current valuations.
</P>
<P>
   Even bulls agree that in the long run, P/E ratios that high are
unsustainable _ either earnings must rise or prices must fall to
bring them back to historical norms.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening now is a little of both, as prices go down
while earnings rise, said Hugh Johnson, chief investment strategist
at First Albany. ``We're very very slowly and very very painfully
closing the gap between companies that are overvalued and those
that are undervalued,'' Johnson said. ``The `E' is just fine. The
`P' is too high.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Berenson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Portfolios That May Need A Diversification Push &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're wondering why your diversified stock fund seems to be
tracking the fortunes of the fast-imploding Internet sector, it may
be because (surprise) it is not particularly diversified.
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent data from Morningstar Inc., the
average mid-capitalization growth fund had a fat 48.1 percent of
its assets invested in technology stocks. Not surprisingly, such
funds have suffered in the great Nasdaq sell-off, losing 23.5
percent of their value from March 10, Nasdaq's peak, through
Thursday. Small growth funds, with 45.1 percent of their assets in
technology, are down even more, 25.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Large-cap growth funds, with 42.1 percent in technology, have
held up relatively well, however, losing just 7.9 percent over the
period.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar calculated its sector weightings on Thursday by
using funds' latest available portfolio disclosures. As such, they
can be months out of date.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors, of course, did not care about the heavy
weighting in technology until recent weeks. In the first quarter,
many were overjoyed to see their actively managed funds beating the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index, which has about a one-third
weighting in technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd guess that they were not aware to the degree that the
typical mid-cap growth and small-cap players have been weighted in
tech,'' said Russel Kinnel, director of fund analysis at
Morningstar, adding that investors should concentrate on the sector
weightings of their entire portfolios, not individual funds. ``If
its 50 percent in technology, that's an extremely volatile
portfolio,'' Kinnel said.
</P>
<P>
   Among value-oriented funds, the percentage of assets in
technology stocks was in the low teens. For blend funds, which
typically use a combination of value and growth styles, it was in
the 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
