u s BC-NASCAR-ZIER-COLUMN-NY     04-14 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-ZIER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE BEST MAN _ AND CAR _ WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When NASCAR decided it was going to use its rule-making
authority to even up competition, its intentions were good.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as it tried to do this within broad parameters _
making sure the cars weighed the same, limiting everybody to the
same size fuel cells, things like that _ it could put down a base
for everybody to build on.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that general guidelines won't produce
equal competition because everybody isn't equal to start with. Some
people are smarter than others. Some are stronger. Some are more
instinctive. Some think and perform better under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   To make up for that, in its efforts to produce equality, NASCAR
often has to blunt creativity. And this has caused problems.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac is a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the year, Chevy teams began hollering
because they couldn't produce the downforce they felt was necessary
to compete with the new Fords. Eventually, a NASCAR rule change
made the Fords and Chevys almost equal.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, NASCAR's own numbers, taken from wind tunnel
tests, clearly show that Pontiac is at a distinct disadvantage in
downforce, having significantly less than either Ford or Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   In the modern era, Pontiac has never had much influence with
NASCAR, which seems more concerned with keeping the Chevy-Ford
battle under control.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't a lot of good Pontiac teams. In fact, Pontiac could
become extinct soon. But it does have one powerhouse entry, Joe
Gibbs Racing. With two of the best drivers in the business in Bobby
Labonte and Tony Stewart, Gibbs' team started kicking butt late
last year.
</P>
<P>
   And the two cars are still competitive; Labonte leads the
current point standings.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, though, the Gibbs team has been grumbling, and
rightfully so, about the handicap it has to work with.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, NASCAR should do something so that Pontiac has as
much downforce as the other makes. But it won't.
</P>
<P>
   And it won't because if it did, you might have another Jeff
Gordon situation with Labonte and Stewart dominating competition.
</P>
<P>
   This is unfair. Gibbs' team got where it is through its own
creativity. Now it's being penalized.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR can only do so much to ensure equality. It should give
everybody the same base and let the best man _ and car _ win.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
