<HEADER>
A7082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BACH-FUGUES-NYT &LR;      04-14 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BACH-FUGUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: A GORGEOUS TAPESTRY WOVEN AS YOU LISTEN: THE ART OF FUGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to Johann Sebastian Bach, I would be just as happy
commemorating the 251st anniversary of his final illness or the
277th anniversary of his employment at Leipzig. But given our
preoccupation with numbers divisible by 50 or 100, I am content
with using the 250th anniversary of his death as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   So while reading a fine new biography, ``Johann Sebastian Bach:
The Learned Musician'' by Christoph Wolff (W.W. Norton), I have
also been listening to several sets of recordings, packaged in
honor of the occasion. These recordings, released by Teldec and
Harmonia Mundi, offer some of the finest Bach performances now
available.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians like the conductors Philippe Herreweghe (Harmonia
Mundi) and Nicholas Harnoncourt (Teldec) or the harpsichordists
Kenneth Gilbert (Harmonia Mundi) and Gustav Leonhardt (Teldec) have
spent most of their lives trying to reconstruct and reimagine the
musical universe of Bach's time. And though these recordings
actually filter the music through a modern sensibility, no
emotional chord is left unsounded: the exquisite pain of the
cantata arias, the spunky energy of the orchestral music, the
spritely dances of the suites, the pungent despair of the passions.
But above all, there is the spirit of the fugue.
</P>
<P>
   The fugue now seems a strange musical form: with its imitating
and intertwining voices it embodies the tastes of an antique era.
For the last two centuries, we have been preoccupied elsewhere.
Much concert music has been thought of as having two ingredients: a
melody and an accompaniment. The melody is the solo voice: the
instrumentalist or the singer expressing emotion, demanding
attention. The accompaniment is the background, emphasizing a
melody's tensions or commenting upon them, embracing a voice or
confronting it. But melody reigns supreme. When we praise music, we
are often praising its melody. Even symphonies, with their hundred
instruments, are often remembered mainly through their themes.
</P>
<P>
   The fugue is an entirely different story. It is all melody, or,
perhaps, all accompaniment. It does not have an individual voice;
it has many individual voices. And each voice is an image of the
others, accompanying them by echoing them. A fugal theme may not
even be distinctive as a melody. It might seem awkward, incomplete,
lacking resolution or purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But set that theme in motion. Then, after a few measures, set
another voice to work, singing the same theme, perhaps at a
different pitch; then a third, or a fourth, or a fifth. Build
tension as these voices echo each other in cascades of fresh
entrances; release tension as they break into free-form episodes.
Invert a voice so it moves up where it once went down and down
where it once went up. Fracture the theme or expand it. Keep the
separate voices in a state of nearly perpetual motion and then
confound the ear by allowing them to intertwine.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the fugue _ a drama not about the individual voice at
large in a society of sound, but a drama about a society of sound
created by related individual voices. It is an astonishing
structure, constructed with intense concentration. In the midst of
that musical society, combinations can never be random or
arbitrary. Rules govern these interactions. And the character of
the theme helps determine the character of the fugue itself.
</P>
<P>
   This is not really how we commonly think about music and its
effects. If the fugue were our primary musical model we would have
no song, no opera, no symphonic drama, no pop tunes. Of course, the
fugue is still a presence in musical life. There are 20th-century
fugues, by, say, Bartok and Shostakovich.
</P>
<P>
   The fugue has also served as a provocation for contemporary
composers. Elliott Carter, for example, has created what might be
thought of as counter-fugues: many of his compositions are composed
of seemingly autonomous voices; the only catch is that instead of
imitating each other, these voices contradict and avoid each other.
But such enterprises remain at the margins of musical culture.
Elsewhere, melody and accompaniment reign unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   So where does this leave Bach? Bach was so renowned for his
fugues that after King Frederick II of Prussia challenged him to
improvise a fugue based upon a mischievously slithering theme, Bach
countered with a masterpiece of inventive play, ``The Musical
Offering.'' And during his final years Bach worked on a nearly
encyclopedic exploration of fugal possibilities in ``The Art of
Fugue''; it was left unfinished at his death, but not before the
composer had begun work on a fugue that included a theme based on
the letters of his name.
</P>
<P>
   The current anthologies of recent Bach performance provide one
way of understanding the fugue's manifold meanings. Aside from
performances by the pianist Glenn Gould, whose glinting brilliance
upended all critical categories, earlier recordings of Bach fugues
tended to have a ponderous, weighty character, properly proclaiming
the music's intellectual and emotional grandeur. But in these
recordings, grounded in what was once called the ``authenticity''
movement, the fugue has a quicksilver quality. It does not proclaim
its profundity or insist on attention. It dances, lightly and
clearly, every step guided by reason and taste. The Bach fugue
becomes a product of the Enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? Each fugue's theme has a distinctive character;
each character constructs its own society; and each society is
bound by law while allowing extraordinary liberty. The fugue is a
model of an ideal society in which obligation and independence
coexist, in which the individual is incomplete without the society
and the society unthinkable without the individual, in which
passion erupts but reason rules. Such an 18th-century-Enlightenment
vision couldn't last _ not in the face of the desires and demands
of the individual voice finally freed from the old world's social
strictures. But the fugue, in all its antique, sublime intricacy,
reminds us of what was once imagined, and what, someday, may be
hoped for again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1740EDT &QL; 
