<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 16, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   CONFESSIONS-REVIEW (Washington) _ As the Supreme Court prepares
to revisit the landmark Miranda decision on confessions by criminal
suspects, there is something appropriate about the timing.
Confession _ by almost anyone to almost anything _ seems to have
become a national obsession. There are memoirs on the best-seller
list, revelations of appalling intimacy on TV. Politicians are
expected to admit to all manner of personal transgressions. Now,
long after other milestones of the Warren Court were absorbed by
the criminal justice system, Miranda still stirs passions. By Linda
Greenhouse. (Moving in the `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-POVERTY-REVIEW (United Nations) _ On all sides of the
debate about globalization, in rich and poor nations alike, there
lurks a disturbing, shared sense that even as Internet millionaires
are being made and industry expands around the Third World,
something is going very wrong in the poorest economies and most
disadvantaged societies. The dispute is about how and why this is
happening, or what can be done about it. By Barbara Crossette.
(Moving in the `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVES-DEATHPENALTY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Several
prominent law-and-order conservatives have recently raised
questions about the death penalty. Some urge more DNA testing to
help acquit the unjustly convicted. Others seek more procedural
safeguards. Pat Robertson wants a moratorium on executions because
the death penalty discriminates against minorities and the poor.
George Will thinks ``skepticism is in order'' about capital
punishment. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CEO-PAY-REVIEW (Undated) _ In 1992, Bill Clinton decried the
soaring salaries of America's chief executives. In the eight years
since then, CEOs' average pay has more than tripled to $11.9
million, but this year's presidential candidates have not mentioned
it. The populist issue has paled. The changing American attitude
toward money may have something to do with it. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   WEAPONS-COSTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Pentagon has always
insisted that there can be no price tag on national security:
weapons represent America's global superiority, and if they are
costly, so be it. But the issue of how wisely the Pentagon spends
money persists. Little has changed since 1969, when an Air Force
financial analyst told Congress that the 77-aircraft C-5A program
was $2 billion over budget _ an unheard-of sum back then.
Billion-dollar cost overruns are now commonplace at the Pentagon.
And telling the truth about costs still comes hard. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSTUDENT-STOCKSCAM-REVIEW (Undated) _ To cynics, the news that
three Georgetown law students had settled SEC charges of running an
Internet stock manipulation scheme probably came as no surprise.
After all, lawyers have had an image problem at least since
Shakespeare. But even people who think the phrase legal ethics is
an oxymoron may have been surprised by Georgetown's announcement
that it would take no action against the students, who did not
admit or deny wrongdoing. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-GENOME-REVIEW (Undated) _ The human genome project could
enable medicine and medical research to return to some of its best,
and most old-fashioned, traditions. In fact, the emerging gene
sciences will reunite the patient, doctor and researcher, in ways
not seen since the 19th- and early 20th centuries. By David A.
Shaywitz and Dennis A. Ausiello
</P>
<P>
   WWII-ART-THEFTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Art institutions and private
and governmental agencies around the world are beginning to publish
catalogs on the Internet describing artworks in their holdings that
could have been confiscated or looted by one of the belligerents in
World War II and, if so proved, should be returned to their
rightful owners. By William Honan.
</P>
<P>
   PSYCH-VIOLENCE-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Psychiatrists say
predicting violence accurately is impossible, but there are tools
that help them make clinical judgments. Most important is the
individual interview. A sampling of some notes from such an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   XFL-FOOTBALL-REVIEW (Undated) _ Vince McMahon has turned his
attention from the raunch of his staged World Wrestling Federation
events to creating the XFL, a high-octane, ``smash mouth'' football
league, in partnership with NBC. But for the strategy behind Vince
McMahon's secret plan to turn himself into Vince Lombardi with
bulging pectorals, let's turn to his manifesto, ``The XFL: An
Accident Waiting to Happen.'' By Richard Sandomir.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-CUBA-REVIEW (Seoul, South Korea) _ Cuba's Fidel Castro
has been the intellectual scold of the powerful, preaching to the
world's rich nations about their obligations to the world's poorest
nations. North Korea has been seen as intransigent, introverted and
unpredictable and un-worldly-wise. But judging by recent events,
it's the North Koreans who seem to have come first to a reluctant
understanding of how the world really works these days: That what a
desperately impoverished communist outpost sitting next to a
capitalist hotshot needs most is not an enemy to rail against but a
partner to join futures with. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORY QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: &LR;
