<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7096 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CHARLES-OSGOOD16-COX     04-14 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARLES-OSGOOD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bow-tied anchor of CBS Sunday A.M. news program is an affable
everyman
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Walk down a street in Midtown Manhattan with Charles
Osgood, and you see smiles. Not stares, not whispers, not snickers
... smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood returns each one in kind. As the veteran broadcaster
strolls down West 57th Street on a mild spring afternoon, near the
anonymous building where he anchors CBS News' ever-classy ``Sunday
Morning,'' a man at a fruit stand nods to him pleasantly and Osgood
replies, in his mellow baritone, ``How are ya?'' And it's
impossible to tell whether the grocer is acknowledging Osgood as a
celebrity _ known 'round the world from the TV newsmagazine and his
``Osgood File'' on CBS radio _ or simply recalls him as the fellow
who, say, bought a newspaper and a navel orange from him last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That's the genius of Charles Osgood, broadcasting's most regular
guy. Every ``Sunday Morning,'' when he smiles into the camera with
his bow tie and mischievously arched eyebrow, and speaks through
vocal cords that sound as if they've been warmed with Irish coffee,
the 66-year-old brings to mind the hearty favorite uncle who used
to come to your house for holiday dinners. The uncle with the
stories to tell. Whether Osgood narrates his own ``Sunday Morning''
report or introduces another reporter's segment (he edits them all,
deftly), or delivers an ``Osgood File'' or one of his celebrated
poems on TV or radio, he's above all a storyteller. Osgood
convinces you so completely that he's telling the tale to you, now
_ as you stew in traffic, dress for church _ that you forget about
all the people at that moment who feel exactly the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood binds America together in a million tiny audiences of
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't talk about Charlie without using the word
`comfortable,''' says ``SM'' reporter Bill Geist, ``but he's more
than that. There's a sophisticated man under those little poems.
There's wit. Integrity. Charlie never hypes you or tries to sell
you any snake oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Rand Morrison adds: ``What you see on the
screen is exactly what you get with Charlie. Working with him is
beyond joy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Having lunch with him is pretty good, too. Osgood chooses a
quiet, unassuming French bistro a few blocks from the studio _ an
``old CBS haunt'' _ and recalls seeing Mike Wallace and Harry
Reasoner there at their ease. Osgood looks like a man who enjoys a
good meal, and does not disappoint. Pitching into a plate of calf
liver and onions with a glass of cabernet (no bean sprouts and
sparkling water for this celeb) he recounts an undying love affair
with radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember this, but my mother tells me that when I was
barely old enough to talk, I used to walk around the house banging
a frying pan and singing the theme song from `Omar the Mystic,' a
popular radio show of the time,'' says the New York native.
</P>
<P>
   Osgood's first assignment as a reporter for ABC radio in New
York was a nightmare: interviewing Atlanta Mayor Ivan Allen Jr.
after the 1962 Paris air crash that killed dozens of Atlanta arts
patrons. Allen got on the phone and calmly began asking technical
questions about what kind of tape equipment the cub reporter would
use, etc. Finally, after a countdown, Allen went on-the-record with
a lightning switch to a tragic mood. Osgood relishes imitating the
mayor's bombastic tones: ``My heart ... is heavy ... tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   When Osgood started making up humorous rhymes to comment on the
news, at New York's ``Newsradio 88'' in the 1960s, an order came
from CBS chairman William Paley: ``Send me a tape of Osgood's
poem.'' The station's news director was so rattled at the presumed
displeasure of the big boss that whenever such a memo arrived, he'd
cancel Osgood's remaining segments for the day, even though it
always turned out that Paley loved the poems.
</P>
<P>
   Which helps to explain why Osgood rose to become a CBS star in
the 1970s, anchoring weekend newscasts on TV but spending more of
his time on radio. Even now he describes himself as ``a radio guy
who finally stopped being terrified of the camera.'' He produces
four ``Osgood Files,'' brief but entertaining, per day. Phil Chin,
his producer for more than 20 years, pulls story ideas off the wire
services and the Internet in the evenings and faxes them to Osgood
at his New Jersey home so that he can see them when he rises at
2:30 a.m. He gets to the studio at 4 and starts writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never fails to amaze me how that writing shines every
day,'' Chin says. ``Once, I gave him an idea about people mistaking
eye drops for glue, and Charles whipped up a poem with the phrase,
`Old Glue Eyes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since he also prepares ``Sunday Morning'' segments late in the
week and goes on the air live Sundays, it makes for a punishing
schedule. The payoff, Osgood says, is plenty of time at his
vacation home on the French Riviera, but even there he tapes radio
spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me if I wear my bow tie at the mike,'' he cracks,
``and I tell them they'd be surprised what I don't wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Osgood is proud that all five children he's raised with the
former Jean Crafton speak fluent French. Which is more than can be
said for Osgood pere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was in trouble the day I took my youngest son into a
French shop and he said, `Ehhhh, let me do the talking, Dad.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   While Osgood was still a rare sight on TV, in 1979 the network's
other Charles, Charles Kuralt, similarly beloved for his touch of
the poetic, helped launch CBS' ``Sunday Morning.'' It became one of
television's best magazines for feature stories _ certainly
commercial TV's best showcase for the arts. With its bracing
musical intro on classical horn, its visual signature of beaming
sun faces, ``Sunday Morning'' has the sunniest of dispositions but
plenty of hard news, too. It's an oasis of intelligence in a TV
landscape that's come to resemble Oz's description of the Tin
Woodman: a clinking, clanking collection of caliginous junk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `60 Minutes' guys make all the money,'' ``SM'' reporter
Geist cracks, ``but we get all the time (the show is 90 minutes
long) to tell our stories, and that's another kind of gold.'' He's
joined by Rita Braver, Martha Teichner, Billy Taylor, John Leonard
and others in one of TV's finest reporter stables.
</P>
<P>
   When declining health forced Kuralt off his high anchor stool in
1994, ``There was a lot of consternation,'' Geist says. ``I mean,
would they hire Geraldo Rivera?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an immense relief when they brought in Charles Osgood,
and I say that personally because he and I share a sense of
humor,'' Geist continues. ``Evening newscasts avoid humor like the
plague. At `Sunday Morning,' we don't tell you about the latest
hatchet murder _ we like you to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only after Osgood had been named ``SM'' anchor that he
found out that Kuralt, who died in 1997, lobbied on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles was a very private man,'' Osgood says, on a day when
the papers carry news of the legal settlement between Kuralt's
widow and longtime Montana mistress over his estate. ``As much as
we respected his talent, I don't think any of us really knew him
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Osgood cracks, ``Kuralt was a good predecessor for me _ not just
another pretty face.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Jokes aside, it's hard to imagine any other anchor donning the
Kuralt mantle as superbly as Osgood has done. He was lead reporter
in a show devoted entirely to the legacy of Ernest Hemingway, his
home in Cuba, the changes in that country. He visited a British pub
and played World War II-era songs so rousingly on the piano that
everyone came and sang along with him.
</P>
<P>
   Even Osgood's narration of the sports highlights has his own
charming inflection (``There he goes again: slam-dunk!''), as if he
were on a small-town, low-watt station, bragging about the school
team to a few dozen of his neighbors. In an age where viewers' only
sense of ``community'' may be a subdivision behind locked gates,
Osgood is a great connector _ a rallying point for frayed nerves
and sagging optimism on a day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   Geist says his only piece to be ``killed'' by Osgood was a
humorous take on O.J. Simpson, showing the editor's determination
to keep the show above the tide of TV tabloidization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no other show less pressured by ratings,'' Geist
declares. Still, ``SM's'' audience ``skews old'' in an industry
that lusts after ever-younger viewer flesh. Producer Morrison,
while cherishing ``the great traditions of the show,'' is making
gentle changes that he hopes ``will get us noticed more.'' One
couldn't help noticing that in a recent interview with Sophia
Loren, the Italian guest interviewer harped on the star's sex life
more than the show's regular correspondents would ever do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You aren't going to get many teenagers tuning in at 9 a.m.
after a date night,'' Morrison says. ``But we may have a piece on
`body art' that brings in new viewers. We'll always have the great
piece on Matisse.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;   &QR;   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Osgood's final Sunday duty is to introduce the footage of
outdoor scenes, nature's beauty. Without inflicting any music or
narration (not even PBS is so generous), this hugely popular
segment leaves the viewer feeling restored by the chuckle of a
mountain stream, the eerie cry of an elk or the rustle of the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Who better to bring this real world into our homes than that
realest of hosts?
</P>
<P>
   Nudging his glass playfully back and forth across the tablecloth
_ so that the wine sloshes up to the lip but never quite out _
Osgood says, ``Most TV executives don't even hear what's being said
on the air. They look at their little monitors (he imitates them,
staring into space with mad-scientist intensity) and say, `Does it
have enough reds? Enough yellows? And is it moving?!'''
</P>
<P>
   He lets out a deep, ironic chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, `Sunday Morning' has beautiful pictures. The words
are pretty special, too. That's why we're a friend of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
