<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hip-hop's contribution finding home in museums
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 16.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   True to hip-hop's origins in battles between competing artists,
there is not one group but two attempting to honor the music with a
hall of fame.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, an organization in Manhattan formally introduced
itself as the Hip-Hop Hall of Fame. Like the Rock and Roll Hall of
Fame in Cleveland and the Georgia Music Hall of Fame in Macon, it
plans to have annual induction ceremonies for artists before it
builds an actual museum.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Mayor Ernest Davis of Mount Vernon, N.Y., announced
that he is converting an old firehouse into a Hip-Hop Hall of Fame,
which will be unrelated to the Manhattan project.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame has been showing for
five months what it claims is the world's first major museum
exhibition on hip-hop culture. Through August, on three floors,
artifacts ranging from Run-DMC's signature hats, sunglasses and
Adidas sneakers to the handwritten lyrics of ``Tennessee'' by
Atlanta act Arrested Development will be on display.
</P>
<P>
   All of this for a genre that only turned 20 last year, when
pundits and fans alike marked the 1979 release of the first
commercial rap record, the Sugar Hill Gang's ``Rapper's Delight.''
It's a genre still very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hip-hop culture has a serious hold on American culture right
now,'' says Ramona DeBreaux, music director and midday announcer at
Atlanta hip-hop station Hot-97.5. ``To sell Pop-Tarts, people are
rapping. Sports network ESPN uses hip-hop terminology to talk about
sports. It's everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapper Chuck D, whose group Public Enemy brought blistering
politics to hip-hop and who contributed artifacts to the Rock and
Roll Hall of Fame's exhibit, thinks the recognition should have
come a long time ago. Establishing an infrastructure to recognize
hip-hop and chronicle its evolution is important: ``I wish the two
places in New York would put their heads together and consolidate
and maybe have branches all over,'' says the Atlanta resident.
``But there's more than 20 years of recorded hip-hop _ yeah, give
it the respect that it's due.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Manhattan, the spokesman for the ``official'' Hip-Hop
Hall of Fame says it will have its first induction ceremony of
artists _ voted on by fans _ by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have heard about other people with ideas,'' says Steven
Burns, ``but we own the rights to the name _ lock, stock and
barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, this is a big world,'' said Davis, who wants his museum,
which he expects to be under construction for a year, to be a
combination hall of fame, history exhibit and job training center.
``But we are the original.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound like fighting words?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it sounds like hip-hop.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Strauss of The New York Times contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : The site for the Hip-Hop Hall of Fame in
Manhattan: www.ihiphophalloffame.com.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
