r l BC-PASSOVER15-COX     04-14 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASSOVER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Human rights groups are fighting anti-Semitism and other forms
of bigotry found in cyberspace _ using their own Web sites as an
antidote to online venomBy Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina _ A new site on the World Wide Web has
been launched in tiny offices in this Argentine capital to battle a
dramatic rise in anti-Semitism and other forms of bigotry in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Shalom Online, a newly-formed human rights group, is particulary
concerned that, while most of the Ten Commandments still are
largely ignored around the world, the admonition against ``bearing
false witness'' is causing new problems, thanks to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   And that includes murder, says Gabriel Avram, chief executive of
Shalom Online.
</P>
<P>
   Though Shalom Online just launched a new Web site in Spanish
(shalomonline.com), he says the page will be available later this
year in Portuguese, English and French.
</P>
<P>
   The group monitors ``an alarming rise'' in Web hate sites from
Mexico to Argentina, he says, many of which have links to similar
``anti-everything'' pages in the United States and Europe.
Monitoring such hate sites is critical now, he says, because
anti-Semitic and other hate propaganda picks up around Jewish
holidays such as Passover, which starts Wednesday at sunset.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the eight-day Passover holiday is freedom, a
commemoration of the Hebrews' exodus from slavery in Egypt
thousands of years ago. It's a time when Jews are asked to reflect
on slavery and the joys of freedom at a festive meal called a
Seder.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Jewish belief that is recalled during the Seder that
no one is truly free unless everyone is, and that means freedom
from prejudice as well as slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, says Avram and other human rights activists,
prejudice of all kinds seems to be rising.
</P>
<P>
   So Shalom Online and other groups are using the Web as a forum
not only to monitor those who hate, but as a way to fight them.
People spotting hate groups online are encouraged to contact the
Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery; HateWatch in Cambridge,
Mass.; Amnesty International and the Anti-Defamation League in New
York; and B'nai B'rith in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Avram says it's easier to reach the targets of hate than its
purveyors _ thus the new Web site. Like other hate group watchers,
Shalom Online monitors prejudicial pages on the Web and offers
advice for adults and children on how to deal with bigotry, as well
as information on Passover and other holidays.
</P>
<P>
   When new sites are reported by Web users, the Southern Poverty
Law Center and other human rights groups complain to Internet
service providers, some of which try to control the pages they
host, says law center spokesman Joe Roy.
</P>
<P>
   But Randy Blazak, an Emory University sociologist and expert on
hate groups in Atlanta, Ga., says it's hard for service providers
to do anything about them, even though some have rules against hate
language on pages they host.
</P>
<P>
   His students have told him they've found venomous hate sites
while doing research papers on the Net. Some human rights groups,
such as the Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles, headed by well-known
Nazi-hunter Simon Wiesenthal, and HateWatch, actually make it easy
for Net surfers to find such sites by providing links.
</P>
<P>
   Blazak agrees with Avram that the growth of hate sites is due in
part to America's First Amendment, which shields skinheads,
Klansmen and other racists, homophobes and xenophobes in countries
like Germany where it's illegal to stir up prejudice. Many Latin
American and European hate group sites are registered in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the number of hate sites has been blamed for
numerous atrocities in Latin America, Avram says, including the
1992 bombing of the Israeli Embassy here, which killed 28 people,
and a blast that killed 82 at a local Jewish community center two
years later. No suspects have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Hate sites have been blamed for terrorism in the United States,
says Jordan Kessler of the ADL in New York. People who knew the two
youths who killed 13 fellow students and teachers in Littleton,
Colo., last year described them as Net experts who'd made
``visits'' to neo-Nazi sites. The massacre took place on Hitler's
birthday, April 20. Also, one of two brothers suspected of killing
a gay couple in Redding, Calif., and of torching several Sacramento
area synagogues reportedly scanned racist Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina has at least 15 such hate sites, and a similar number
are posted in Brazil and Chile, says Sergio Widder, head of the
Wiesenthal Center in Buenos Aires. But the big problem is in the
United States, says Jay Kaiman of the ADL in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're monitoring 250 pages in (the United States)
and in the Southeast, where we know of about 15,'' including some
in Georgia, he says. ``For the first time, hate groups don't have
to rally at a Stone Mountain. They can go into their apartment or
house and rally on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Poverty Law Center has tracked 305 hate sites in
the United States this year, up from 254 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Internet grows, we can expect this to grow,'' Kaiman
says. ``The number of hate groups had started a downward trend
until the Internet caught on.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy says a big concern now is that kids surfing the Net often
stumble onto such pages while researching papers on the Holocaust
or World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Leon Klenicki, a native of Argentina who now works for the
ADL in New York, says ``intolerance is the essence'' of his
homeland, but it's not directed just against Jews. Foreigners,
trade unions, Protestants, homosexuals and immigrants also are
targets, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Dina Siegel Vann, Latin affairs director for B'nai B'rith, says
intolerance is hard to fight in a country that openly sympathized
with Germany until two months before the end of World War II. She
says Shalom Online is ``a great initiative,'' a good first step.
</P>
<P>
   Blazak says hate groups in other countries often set up links to
sites in the United States, which can be done as easily as
e-mailing a page to a like-minded person in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cyberspace,'' Blazak says. ``There are no boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's hopeful that by monitoring and reporting hate sites,
Internet service providers may be forced to take more stringent
actions.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Simon Moguilevsky, who presides over the oldest
congregation in Argentina, Congregacion Israelita de la Republica
Argentina, says Net hate is ``a big problem'' in Latin America in
part because of its legacy of harboring Nazis after World War II.
But if groups like Shalom Online stay vigilant, he adds, ``we hope
for better.''
</P>
<P>
   David Goldman, founder of HateWatch in Cambridge, contends the
best way to hurt hate groups is to fight fire with fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, people were saying the Internet was the
greatest thing that has happened to hate,'' Goldman says, because
it allows hate groups to operate in anonymity and saves them money
on mailings. ``But we think it's also the worst thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, who's forever vigilant, contends most Net users are
smart enough to know what's right and wrong when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, the vast majority of caring, concerned but
politically uninvolved Americans are now becoming aware of the
situation, concerned enough to act,'' Goldman says. ``We're saying,
`Go and look for yourself.' Then come and talk to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
