<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7103 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-RELIGION-LINCOLN15-CO     04-14 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-LINCOLN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Redeemer President' offers religious view of Lincoln
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Had Abraham Lincoln adhered to the norms of his strict
Protestant upbringing on that Good Friday evening, history may have
been different.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he went to the theater.
</P>
<P>
   There, he was shot.
</P>
<P>
   He died the next day, on April 15, 1865, exactly 135 years ago
today.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln's love for the theater was but one of his departures
from his strict Calvinist parents, said Allen C. Guelzo, author of
a new book looking at Lincoln from a religious perspective,
``Abraham Lincoln, Redeemer President'' (William B. Eerdmans
Publishing Co., $29).
</P>
<P>
   Guelzo took the title of his book from an editorial by Walt
Whitman calling for such a figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``He redeemed the country from slavery, disunion and from a
general sense of disillusion with popular government,'' said
Guelzo, dean of the Templeton Honors College at Eastern College in
St. Davids, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Often portrayed as a rough frontiersman, Lincoln was actually an
intellectually and theologically complex man as Guelzo paints him.
He had both a strong optimism about the ability of the populace to
function in a democracy and a deep pessimism about the capacity for
individual choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man who was working out complexity in his own life,''
said the author.
</P>
<P>
   The future president was born into a severely Calvinist Baptist
family in Appalachia. His parents were ``utterly
predestinationists,'' Guelzo said. ``They believed people didn't
make choices for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln rebelled against his father's religion and immersed
himself in Thomas Paine, Robert Burns and the other authors of the
Enlightenment. The contrast with Lincoln's beginning is not as
great as it seems, said Guelzo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Enlightenment thinkers were ... captured by the
beauty of science, especially Newtonian science,'' said Guelzo.
``And what did Newtonian science preach? Order in the universe,
things happening in certain ways human will could not interrupt.
That sat very naturally beside Lincoln's inherited Calvinism.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln gained a reputation as a scoffer and an infidel that
softened later in his life. By the 1860s, Lincoln described himself
as a religious seeker.
</P>
<P>
   A ``real change'' came upon Lincoln during the Civil War, Guelzo
said. The president concluded that there was a purpose at work
greater than that of humans.
</P>
<P>
   With the Emancipation Proclamation after Antietam, Lincoln was
fulfilling a covenant with God that he would take Gen. Robert E.
Lee's retreat from Maryland as a sign that he should free the
slaves, according to the diaries of two of his Cabinet officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it, this is staggering,'' said Guelzo.
``Here is the president of the United States in the midst of the
greatest civil crisis in American history, about to make the most
important social decision in the history of the country, and his
justification is 'God told me to.'''
</P>
<P>
   Guelzo added his own volume to the stack of Lincoln biographies,
he said, because he wants to ensure that Lincoln is seen as a man
of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern American discourse really concentrates on the nuts and
bolts,'' Guelzo said. ``It's good to make the traffic lights work,
but it impoverishes something in government when you can aspire to
nothing higher than traffic lights. The American popular government
after all was founded not on solving problems, but on articulating
ideas _ a proposition that all men are created equal.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle White writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7111 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-ESSAYIST-PROFILE16-CO     04-14 1507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESSAYIST-PROFILE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Professor and essayist practices the art of living well in the
mountains of North Georgia
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 16.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOUNG HARRIS, Ga. _ He props himself on the corner of a desk,
looking more companionable than professorial, and asks, ``So what
do you think Herrick is saying here? Is this poem about waking up
in the morning?''
</P>
<P>
   A hand shoots up, then another and another, all females.
</P>
<P>
   Boys, especially big boys, don't like to think themselves
bashful about sexuality, but the half-dozen who had taken their
stations in the rear of the room were sitting this one out.
</P>
<P>
   What ensued while they held their counsel was a discussion
between a 50-year-old father of four and a handful of young women,
students in English 102 at Young Harris College. ``If you wait in
life to seize the opportunity for love,'' Steven Harvey asked by
way of dropping a clue, ``is the natural world going to wait for
you? No, it's going to go on. So the bed is a retreat from the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Other hands were soon petitioning their turn, still all females.
</P>
<P>
   In the front row a young woman said the poet, Robert Herrick,
seemed to be implying an awakening to sex.
</P>
<P>
   Hands folded over a raised knee, Harvey weighed her words in the
noncommittal way that signals ``OK, but. ...''
</P>
<P>
   You could see him wanting her to go deeper, explore her thought
one step further. Thirty years separated teacher and student, but
Harvey was willing to meet her halfway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you think Herrick is really talking about the whole
array of activities that are part of the physical side of love?''
Harvey asked her.
</P>
<P>
   Half-sentences ricocheted in rapid response, and the subject was
seen as a larger and more interesting one than mere coupling.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Harvey would confirm the impression that poetry of a
certain kind speaks more to women than to men. ``I find that the
women are more open to these things,'' he said. ``The men are a
harder crust. They don't take to it as easily. But then you'll come
across the exception, and you see those feelings run very deep.''
</P>
<P>
   The poem they were reading was a minor one _ ``Corinna's Going
A-Maying'' _ by a minor poet, but all the better for making
Harvey's point: ``I think too often we define things in the
negative,'' he told his class. ``But it is a sin not to embrace
life, and that includes the physical as well as the spiritual. Not
living is the real sin here.''
</P>
<P>
   He let the point settle in, and then deftly brought in the
leavening. ``I heard from one of my little spies,'' he said, ``that
you all are tired of these love poems and you want some drinking
poems. But Herrick is one of our great drinking poets. He'd meet
his friend Ben Jonson and they'd recite poems while drinking
flagons of ale.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a ripple of muffled amusement, and a husky fellow in
the rear raised his head from a page that might as well have been
Greek grammar and saw a glimmer of light where before there had
only been darkness.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Harvey himself wrote poems before finding his real
voice in the personal essay. In two essay collections, ``A Geometry
of Lilies: Life and Death in an American Family'' and ``Lost in
Translation,'' he writes with fluent ease about love and marriage,
about change and loss. His tone is by turns winsome and reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me what my books are about,'' he says. ``It's very
hard to say.''
</P>
<P>
   He will write of his kids ganging up on him (``I marvel at the
transparent guile of their planning huddles, the determined looks
as they gather courage for the synchronized assault, their reckless
confidence as they throw their bodies at their father'') or of
discovering that he is perfectly happy living without a television.
(``Our mind connects the dots, lending depth and perspective, and
ultimately, meaning to the electronic trompe l'oeil of the tube.
And yet, the experience sedates us, engaging just enough of our
senses to lull us into a stupor.'')
</P>
<P>
   He writes what's on his mind, but what's on his mind always
seems to lead somewhere else _ from the personal to what might be
called the universal.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Pickering, one of the best-known practitioners of the
personal essay, is among Harvey's admirers. ``I've never met
Harvey, but his writing is musical and lyrical, with a firm sense
of place and an awareness of the small things that appoint our
days,'' Pickering says. ``Although his pieces are set in a small
place, it transcends where he lives. In some ways, looking at
something closely expands rather than narrows it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey has also edited a collection of essays by men on middle
age, ``In a Dark Wood,'' and in June the University of Georgia
Press will publish ``Bound for Shady Grove,'' in which his love for
mountain music and its instruments _ the banjo, the fiddle, the
guitar _ becomes a means for exploring the changing seasons of
one's life.
</P>
<P>
   He had been assigning his classes to read essays for years. ``I
imagine the essay,'' he says, ``as the solitary thinking mind
allowing you a glimpse of itself, a rarity in our time.''
</P>
<P>
   The writing of them was more personal still, an unburdening that
freed him of the obligation to write of a central event in his life
_ his mother's suicide when he was 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my mother's suicide was one of the reasons I first
began to write, although I don't think it's the source of my
writing. I don't think I could write about it. I don't think I
could get it back. I tried to write a novel about it and that
didn't work. I tried to write a poem about it and that didn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   The best he could do was write about trying to write about it.
In the essay ``Suicide Notes'' in ``A Geometry of Lilies,'' he
begins by recalling himself at 17: ``I let my hair grow long,
wandered downtown late at night, hid poems in my desk, gave
recitations aloud in empty schoolyards, and filled 89-cent
composition books with the usual undergraduate drivel.'' He was
drawn to images of ``crows, stubble fields and winter trees.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotions were deeply felt, but the art forced. Remembering
her was enough; he did not have to embalm her in words. And so, by
the end of the essay, he is writing of his daughter Neesa _ born on
April 6, the same day his mother died. She is 6 or 7 at the time,
skipping on ahead of him, ``kicking up gravel as she goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, you lose what you love, Harvey wrote in another
essay, so best to hold onto it while you have it. He was telling
his class this, in so many words, knowing they might be too young
to fully appreciate the transitory, fragile moments that make up
the unseen life.
</P>
<P>
   If the essay is the form in which Harvey found his real voice,
it was in the classroom, he says, that he found his vocation. ``I'm
a teacher more than I am a writer,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He says it like a man telling you which way is north and which
is south. They have meaning only in relation to one another, but he
doesn't want you to get lost.
</P>
<P>
   Bettie Sellers, the outgoing poet laureate of Georgia, claims
credit for the discovery, and no one disputes her. ``I guess it's
been 20 years now,'' she says. ``I sat beside him at a seminar at
Callanwolde there in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 24 years, to be exact.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers was head of the humanities department at Young Harris,
and Harvey was teaching eighth-graders at Charlotte Country Day
School in North Carolina. ``I was looking for someone to teach
English,'' Sellers says, ``and my good angel said, `Bettie, this is
a real teacher.' He loves the teaching and he loves the kids. He's
very good at bringing out the best in them.''
</P>
<P>
   The social atmosphere of a well-to-do private school wasn't
entirely to Harvey's liking, but he came to Young Harris for an
interview with no expectation that he'd spend half his life here.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor his wife, Barbara, had ties to Georgia _ she grew
up in North Carolina, he in New York, Chicago, Kentucky and New
Jersey _ and neither was sold at first sight on this mountain town
just beyond Blairsville. (Pickering, uncertain of its name, said,
``That place where he lives _ Young Harvey or whatever it is.'')
Georgians know it _ if they know it at all _ as the hometown of
former Gov. Zell Miller, not as the site of Young Harris College.
</P>
<P>
   Walking from the campus to show a visitor where they first
lived, Barbara Harvey says there still are moments when she feels
isolated. But it was here that they became middle-aged, saw three
more children follow the infant they brought with them and in time
saw their two oldest move off to pursue their dreams, young in the
same way they once were themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Barbara Harvey, in fact, were even younger than oldest
son Matt, 25, and studying for a Ph.D. in mathematics at John
Hopkins University, and daughter Neesa, 22, married and living in
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1968, the pivotal year of a pivotal decade. A student at
East Carolina University, Barbara was waiting tables
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
