<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7115 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER15-COX     04-14 1518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Check the hardware at the church door
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pushing a popular election-year issue, Al Gore wants to ban guns
from churches and other places of worship. Gore, in a speech in San
Jose, Calif., was announcing support for legislation banning
firearms in churches, synagogues and mosques, as well as where
school events are held. Gore: ``I believe we need to seize upon the
growing consensus that it is time to get guns away from those who
should not have them.'' Gore said he has always believed in the
right of hunters to carry weapons _ ``but America cannot afford
another Columbine, or another Paducah, or another Jonesboro.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GAYS MEETING IRKS BAUER ...
</P>
<P>
   While George W. Bush was praised by gay leaders for reaching out
and meeting with them for an hour, the gathering drew immediate
fire from the religious right. Gary Bauer, the former GOP
presidential hopeful, said: ``Just by meeting with this group of
gay supporters, Gov. Bush has elevated the gay rights agenda to a
level of recognition ... that contradicts our long-standing
commitment to pro-family values.'' Gays who attended the private
gathering, all hand-picked by the Bush campaign, said they wanted
to ``raise his consciousness'' on certain issues _ and report
achieving that goal. Bush said the meeting made him a ``better
person,'' buy did not change his opposition to gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ... AS DOES RIDGE'S PLATFORM POSITION
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer Friday also criticized Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge's
comments regarding the anti-abortion plank in the Republican Party
platform. Ridge ``is disastrously wrong about a central issue in
the Republican Party when he says the right-to-life plank of our
platform should be removed or watered-down, Bauer said. Ridge made
the comments a day earlier as he unveiled the on-line press room at
the Republican convention site this summer in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   BETTER TO GIVE THAN ... RIGHT?
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Hillary Clinton paid $92,104 in federal income taxes
and contributed $39,200 to charity this time around, according to
tax returns released Friday. Al and Tipper Gore paid $59,178 in
taxes and gave $15,000 to charity. Following their usual practice,
George W. and Laura Bush will seek an extension while awaiting
information from a blind trust that manages his assets. He'll make
an estimated tax payment Monday to cover any money owed.
</P>
<P>
   UH, BETTER GIVE THAT REPORT ANOTHER LOOK
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights, smarting from news that its
leader contributed to Hillary Rodham Clinton's campaign, postponed
public discussion of a report said to criticize Mayor Rudy
Giuliani's New York Police Department. The commission denied any
connection. Mary Frances Berry contributed to the first lady's
campaign. Berry gave $250 last year to Clinton and another $300 to
the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee. Said Giuliani: ``It
doesn't take much to figure out this is a political operation.''
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK, IT'S RUDY PULLING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Giuliani has moved back ahead of Hillary Rodham Clinton in
the latest poll, but within the margin of error. The survey by
Zogby International found the mayor leading the first lady 45
percent to 44 percent; the margin of error is 3.8 percentage
points. Giuliani had fallen behind Clinton in recent polls,
apparently because of a backlash over his handling of the latest
fatal police shooting of an unarmed black man.
</P>
<P>
   TURNING TIDE IN CONNECTICUT
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore has moved ahead of George W. Bush in
Connecticut, according to a just-released presidential poll. The
Quinnipiac College Poll (3.2 percentage point margin of error)
found gave Gore a 48 percent to 39 percent lead. In February, the
race was considered a dead heat among Connecticut voters, while
back in October Bush led Gore.
</P>
<P>
   TIT FOR TAT, TALLY FOR TALLY
</P>
<P>
   The Bush and Gore campaigns are crunching some serious numbers
as each scolds the other for ducking separate issues: Al Gore, the
media; Republican George W. Bush, a candidate debate. ``Al Gore
today canceled a scheduled news conference, which would have been
the first in 54 days,'' declared a news release by the Bush
campaign. Gore ducked reporters in North Carolina, it charged, so
as to avoid questions about 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez . Not to be
outdone, Gore aides released their own statement showing off some
math as well: ``George W. Bush has managed to bob and weave away
from debating Gore for 30 days in a row,'' referring to an e-mail
debate challenge sent last month.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RAPPORT WITH REPORTERS
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, when the presidential race was gathering steam,
the reporters covering George W. Bush flew in a different plane
than he did, run by a company with a name just begging to be
spoofed. Access Air, the charter outfit's title, became No Access
Air, the passengers' lament. Bush insisted for months that his
visits with traveling reporters be off the record. But that was
then; this is now. With John McCain out of the running now, Bush
has reached boldly for the mantle of Chattiest Candidate. He talked
and talked and talked, about the serious and frivolous, everything
and nothing, for an hour during one flight and nearly 90 minutes
during another recently, underlining a striking evolution of his
methods.
</P>
<P>
   HE COULD HAVE LOTS OF TIME TO GOLF WITH O.J.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest political race in Southern California is looking
lopsided these days, with Los Angeles County District Attorney Gil
Garcetti lagging so far behind challenger Steve Cooley that some
say he can't come back. Amid a burgeoning police scandal, a Los
Angeles Times poll this week showed Garcetti trailing Cooley, his
deputy, 55 percent to 18 percent. The rest were undecided. Some say
the gap is insurmountable, with voters intent on showing
disapproval of him. But who knows? After all, he he won re-election
in 1996, when the acquittal of O.J. Simpson was still fresh in
voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   TOO MUCH HEAT IN THE KITCHEN
</P>
<P>
   Blaming ``personal attacks'' on his personal life, George Grogan
abandoned his quest for the Nebraska Senate seat left open by the
retirement of Democrat Bob Kerrey. Grogan, a businessman whom polls
had running second to state Attorney General Don Stenberg in the
primary contest, said his family had been hurt by news disclosures
about his three divorces, a business bankruptcy and an arrest on a
charge of disorderly conduct _ a charge he said was eventually
dismissed. The Democratic nomination is expected to go to former
Gov. Ben Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   WASTE NOT, WANT NOT
</P>
<P>
   A demand by top congressional Republicans that President Clinton
sign a newly passed bill creating a national nuclear waste disposal
site in Nevada is making life politically difficult for John
Ensign, a former congressman running for retiring Democratic Sen.
Richard Bryan's Senate seat. Ensign is a Republican, too, but one
who adamantly opposes the waste site, as do many Nevada voters and,
not least of all, Ensign's Democratic opponent, Ed Bernstein.
Ensign led Bernstein, a lawyer, by more than 20 points in the last
poll and, in an effort to hold that edge, he accused his fellow
Republicans the other day of ``wasting time and energy'' by pushing
for passage of a bill that Clinton has promised to veto.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRACY AND THE TELEPHONE
</P>
<P>
   Brian Schweitzer, a Montana Democrat and rancher running for the
seat of Republican Sen. Conrad Burns, has accused a polling company
of illegally using automated telephone messages to fight his plan
to lower drug prices. Montana law prohibits the use of automated
systems to dial telephone numbers and play messages designed to
sell a product or promote a political campaign. Schweitzer said the
polling company was hired by Citizens for Better Medicare, which
supports Burns. The group acknowledged that phone calls had been
made, but said people called were asked only for their their views
on health care, and if any violation had occurred, the calls would
be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRACY AND THE INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Some Web sites are trying to make money by turning Internet
users into armchair political activists. About a dozen for-profit
democracy portals have popped up in the last few months, bringing
with them the technology to track the interests of users and then
sell that information to politicians and special-interest groups
trying to target potential supporters. Some of these Web sites are
vote.com, bettervote.com and grassroots.com. Project Vote Smart, a
nonprofit organization that runs a similar democracy site, has
assumed the role of watchdog _ trying to encourage debate about
where to draw the line between privacy and money-making.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
