<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-SAFRICA-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURMOIL IN ZIMBABWE WORRIES SOUTH AFRICAN BUSINESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ In a warning that underscores the
widening reach of Zimbabwe's economic and political meltdown, the
biggest business and trade organization in South Africa this week
urged its 40,000 members to delay any new investment in the
crisis-ridden neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Already a number of South African companies with significant
interests in Zimbabwe have taken steps to shield themselves from
the escalating problems there, said Kevin Wakeford, the chief
executive of the trade organization, the South African Chamber of
Business.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of farms in Zimbabwe have been raided in recent weeks
by black squatters, raising concern about the state of the
country's important agricultural sector and heightening fears
around the nation's deeply unsettled political situation.
</P>
<P>
   The squatters, led by veterans of the 1970s guerrilla war
against white minority rule, say they are reclaiming land stolen
decades ago from their ancestors by white settlers.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe, who has made little progress in
redistributing land during his 20 years in power, has condoned the
farm invasions despite a Zimbabwe court order against them. Mugabe
considers the squatters disenfranchised peasants who make up most
of the country's population and who have been the base of his
party's power.
</P>
<P>
   Trade with Zimbabwe, South Africa's largest trading partner in
the region, makes up about 3.5 percent of South Africa's total
exports and heavily favors South Africa. Still South Africa, with
its far bigger economy, sees trade with its neighbor, though small
in total volume compared with the European Union and the United
States, as strategically important.
</P>
<P>
   The economic troubles have hobbled that trade, in both
directions. Zimbabwe has been short of cash, and after
international donors alleged government mismanagement and cut off
loans, the shortage worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Currency and credit problems have followed, and now the volatile
atmosphere has added another obstacle, with traders in recent days
finding it increasingly difficult to insure goods.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, after days of futility, National Ingredients
Supplies, a South African food-processing company and a subsidiary
of Anglovaal Industries Ltd., finally found an underwriter for the
$8 million of soybeans it bought earlier this year. Only Lloyds of
London was willing to insure the stockpile, much of it sitting in a
silo on an occupied farm. The insurance will cost the company five
times the normal price, said Steve Brooks, National's logistics
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders said such problems, if they persist, would
erode all of southern Africa's reputation among investors and
donors.
</P>
<P>
   The depth of Zimbabwe's economic problems is reflected in the
basic financial data on the country.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation in Zimbabwe soared 70 percent last year and is
projected at 65 percent this year, according to the World Bank.
Gross domestic product growth was zero last year and is forecast to
fall 1 percent this year; the fiscal deficit is growing and the
value of the Zimbabwe dollar has fallen by half in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign exchange reserves have plunged, making it much harder
for the country and its businesses to pay for imported goods,
notably fuel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   African Oxygen Ltd., a South African producer and distributor of
industrial gases and a subsidiary of BOC Group, sells supplies to a
sister company, BOC Zimbabwe, and the effects of the foreign
currency shortage have been severe, said Jimmy Marriott, the
executive director for industrial operations at African Oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are certainly not getting the level of foreign exchange
that they used to in the past,'' Marriott said. ``It hasn't been
available to them.''
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's Tongaat-Hulett Group Ltd., a large producer of
sugar and a unit of Anglo American Corp. of South Africa, employs
8,000 people in Zimbabwe and for the last three years has been
sitting on plans for a $100 million expansion in Zimbabwe. The
country's unpredictable land politics, the crumbling economy and
now the breakdown of law and order have kept Tongaat-Hulett from
moving forward with its plans, the company's chief executive,
Cedric Savage, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically, it's still one of the best places to invest in
agriculture,'' Savage said. ``It's the lowest cost producer of
sugar in the world. It's a place where economically you'd want to
invest money, but politically just about every political action
taken discourages that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
