r a BC-HUMOR-FACTOR-NEW-SCIE     04-14 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMOR-FACTOR-NEW-SCIENTIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FUN  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF APRIL 17, 2000)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By HAZEL MUIR  
 Copyright 2000 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your sense of humor has nothing to do with your genes, and
everything to do with your upbringing, according to new finding by
biologists in London.
</P>
<P>
   They were surprised to find that whether you love or hate Gary
Larson cartoons depends on the way you were raised. Genes don't
seem to shape appreciation of this kind of humor at all.
</P>
<P>
   Most personality traits, such as being a shrinking violet or the
life and soul of the party, are at least partly determined by your
genes, so researchers suspected the same applies to our sense of
humor. To find out, Tim Spector, Lynn Cherkas and their colleagues
at St. Thomas' Hospital in London tested the humor of 71 pairs of
identical twins and 56 pairs of fraternal twins. Each pair had been
raised together.
</P>
<P>
   The team asked each pair of twins to go into separate rooms and
rate five cartoons from Gary Larson's ``The Far Side'' on a scale
of 0 to 10. A zero deemed the cartoon a waste of paper, while 10
meant it was one of the funniest cartoons the subject had ever
seen.
</P>
<P>
   The results showed that siblings tend to have similar views on
the degree to which a cartoon is funny. But identical twins, who
have exactly the same genes, were no more likely to agree on this
than fraternal twins, who share only half of their genes on
average, like ordinary siblings. That suggests it's a shared
environment, rather than shared genes, that makes brothers and
sisters laugh at the same things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a surprise, because most personality traits have genetic
components,'' Spector said. ``This implies that there's a lot of
cultural influence on humor.'' That might explain why popular jokes
vary so much between nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is interesting, because twin studies of personality
traits almost always show genetic effects,'' said Robert Plomin, a
behavioral geneticist at the Institute of Psychiatry in London.
However, he would like to see a larger study confirm the findings,
and it may be that the results depend heavily on the specific
nature of the study.
</P>
<P>
   Spector agrees his team has studied only one type of humor _
so-called cognitive humor, which involves a blending of
contradictory ideas. They now hope to tackle the task of testing
other kinds of humor, such as sexual innuendo, possibly using
English saucy seaside postcards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
