<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-FAITH-REVIEW-HNS     04-14 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FAITH-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIX OF COMEDY AND RELIGION IS ODDLY EFFECTIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theater previews for ``Keeping the Faith'' promise a pratfall
movie about religion.
</P>
<P>
   A young Catholic seminarian (Edward Norton) catches his robes on
fire and puts them out in the holy water.
</P>
<P>
   A young rabbinical student (Ben Stiller) attends a circumcision
and faints.
</P>
<P>
   Ha ha, cheap laughs. You can understand why the movie is sold
that way. But there is more than fall-down comedy to ``Keeping the
Faith.'' Trust me.
</P>
<P>
   For his first film as director and producer, and his first major
comedy lead, Edward Norton, our best young dramatic film actor, has
tackled an unlikely subject and come up with a winning, thoughtful
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Schram (Stiller) and Brian Kilkenny Finn (Norton) are pals
who grew up on New York's Upper West Side. As boys they shared an
interest in sports (they were crummy), in girls (they were
crummier) and religion (they were great). Jake was Jewish and Brian
was Catholic, but they supported each other's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Their only childhood female success was smart, independent Anna
Reilly. ``She was that magical blend of Johnny Quest and Tatum
O'Neal in `Foxes,''' Brian says. Anna became their pal and for a
glorious time they were like the Three Musketeers. Then Anna's
family moved away.
</P>
<P>
   Jake and Brian grow up to be religious leaders in their old
neighborhood, worshipping ``an old-world God with a new-age spin.''
Brian is the hippest priest, popular with youth, though he makes
some of the elders uncomfortable. Jake is the coolest rabbi. All
the mothers want him to marry their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Brian and Jake still work together on community projects and
interfaith understanding.
</P>
<P>
   At a crucial point in their careers, just as they are about to
advance to major positions, Anna (Jenna Elfman) moves back to town.
</P>
<P>
   Anna was great as a kid, but now she's something more. She's
attractive, yes, but more than that, she's attitude on legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work harder than God,'' she tells the boys. ``If he'd hired
me I would have made the world by Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a corporate whizbang and woman of the world, Anna still
likes to play tomboy and flirt.
</P>
<P>
   The boys adore her, but that's all they can do, right? Brian is
a priest, and Jake knows he'd darn well better marry within his
faith or kiss advancement goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   If only life, religion and human emotions were that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Director Norton and screenwriter Stuart Blumberg (``Mad TV'')
have enriched the inevitable complications, not only with a lot of
laughs but also with a respect and affection for the characters and
for their faiths.
</P>
<P>
   We can guess right away that both Jake and Brian will find their
traditions or vows challenged, that they will have a falling-out
over Anna, and so forth. What is far less expected is how deftly
and sincerely it is handled.
</P>
<P>
   On a Central Park walk, Anna asks Brian if he'll answer a few
personal questions all priests hear eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we gonna have the sex talk here?'' he asks her with
patience. ``I know you've got a list of questions. Come on.''
</P>
<P>
   A comic scene becomes thoughtful as Brian explains why he places
his spiritual needs above his physical ones.
</P>
<P>
   There are several such moments of underlying seriousness in
``Keeping the Faith,'' but we're not shortchanged on laughs.
</P>
<P>
   The ending gets a little too cute, and isn't true to Anna's
independent nature. Oh well, to forgive is divine.
</P>
<P>
   Actors say good comedy comes out of drama, so it should be no
surprise than Norton, twice Oscar-nominated (``Primal Fear'' and
``American History X''), can handle it just fine. Stiller's comic
talents also shine.
</P>
<P>
   The film's real treat, however, is Elfman. Her Anna is the
antithesis of the sweetly daffy love interest we find as the female
lead in too many Hollywood romantic comedies. Rather than cute,
Elfman makes her sassy, brainy, competitive, outspoken and sexy.
She's even taller than both men. Movies need more women like her. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Keeping the Faith'' &QL; 
Starring: Jenna Elfman, Ben Stiller, Edward Norton, Anne Bancroft &QL; 
Rating: PG-13, for some sexuality and language &QL; 
Running time: 131 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B plus &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
