<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7143 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST-2TAK     04-14 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENEWED FOCUS ON HOLOCAUST VICTIMS' UNTRACED ASSETS IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a basement meeting room in the Israeli
Parliament, a committee of legislators is trying to unravel a
tangled and troubling legacy of the Holocaust that has gone
unexplored for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, led by Colette Avital, a lawmaker from the
governing One Israel Party and former Israeli consul-general in New
York, is investigating what happened to bank accounts, plots of
land and other assets that were held in Israel by Jews who died in
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Begun in February at Avital's initiative, the parliamentary
inquiry reflects a growing sense here that Israel should practice
what it has preached.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Jewish organizations, backed by Israel, have
demanded, with considerable success, disclosure by foreign banks
and governments of accounts and other property of Holocaust victims
and survivors they may be holding, so the assets can be returned to
the victims' relatives and the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland agreed more than a year ago to pay compensation of
$1.25 billion after more than 54,00 dormant accounts traced back to
World War II or earlier were found in Swiss banks.
</P>
<P>
   An international panel investigating insurance policies held by
Holocaust victims announced last week that it would publish 19,000
names of policyholders who are owed money.
</P>
<P>
   But it has also emerged that there are untraced assets of
Holocaust victims in Israel. Although the scope of the property is
thought to be far smaller than the assets held in Europe, its very
existence here has raised unsettling questions, especially among
survivors and their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come with clean hands when we make demands on
foreign institutions,'' said Gil Raveh, a lawyer from Tel Aviv who
is trying to trace what became of 1,000 pounds deposited in the
1930s in British-ruled Palestine by his great-grandfather and a
business partner.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Moshe Sanbar, chairman of the Center of Organizations of
Holocaust Survivors in Israel, said that when it came to tracing
property of Jews who died in the Holocaust, ``Israel has a greater
moral responsibility and should set a good example, not a bad
one.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Jewish investments in Palestine were of a different nature than
the money transferred to Swiss banks for safekeeping. Jews in
Europe bought plots of land and opened bank accounts in Palestine
in the 1920s and 1930s as a way of taking part in the Zionist
enterprise or as a nest egg for possible immigration by them or
their children.
</P>
<P>
   The sum of the investments has never been determined, with
estimates ranging from $40 million in deposited money to land
believed to be worth tens of millions more, including prime real
estate in the heart of Israel. European Jews also bought stocks and
bonds from Zionist agencies and kept money in safe deposit boxes
whose whereabouts are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   After the outbreak of World War II, land and bank accounts held
by Jews from countries under Nazi rule were seized by the British
mandate government in Palestine as enemy property, and most of the
money was transferred to England.
</P>
<P>
   Under a settlement with Israel in 1950, the British government
paid back 1.4 million pounds as compensation for the removed funds.
Records of the seized accounts and land were turned over to the
Israeli government and some restitution payments were reportedly
made, but the fate of other accounts and properties remains
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   For decades the matter generated little interest here. Holocaust
survivors who came to Palestine and later to the nascent state of
Israel were focused on rebuilding their lives and tracing missing
relatives, not recovering lost property.
</P>
<P>
   In those early years of nation-building and in subsequent
decades there were other priorities, said Dr. Yossi Katz, a
professor at Bar-Ilan University near Tel Aviv whose study of
Holocaust-era assets in Israel, ``Forgotten Property,'' was
published this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the '90s the issue didn't trouble the public,'' Katz
said. ``Other matters were seen as far more important, such as
security and absorption of immigrants. It's safe to assume that had
the issue not come up recently in Europe, it would not have come up
in Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a reluctance here to deal with the the Holocaust in
economic terms,'' Katz added. ``It was inconceivable to turn the
Holocaust into a material issue. A younger generation had to come
along that was not directly linked to the Holocaust and could deal
with it less sentimentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Avital said that on the official level, bureaucratic inertia had
prevented effective action to trace and return the unclaimed
assets. ``There was a lot of neglect and lack of sensitivity,'' she
said. ``The attitude was, why bother?''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Holocaust-era claims were pressed loudly in Europe,
concerns were voiced that a similar campaign to find assets here
would provoke foreign demands that Israel first put its own house
in order, undercutting the drive for full disclosure abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``My argument was exactly the opposite,'' Avital said. ``We have
a much better moral position when we can go to the Swiss banks and
say we're asking of you what we're asking of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank disclosures abroad led to similar steps in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by hearings in a parliamentary banking committee,
Israeli banks last year handed over lists of 5,000 dormant accounts
to the administrator-general, a Justice Ministry official who
manages unclaimed property. In 1997 the administrator general's
office published a list of more than 11,000 unclaimed bank accounts
and real estate holdings it manages.
</P>
<P>
   Bank Leumi, an Israeli bank that succeeded the pre-independence
Anglo-Palestine Bank, where many of the deposits by European Jews
were made, published on its Internet site in January a list of
accounts that have been inactive since 1955 or earlier. The Jewish
National Fund, a land development agency, published on its site a
list of plots it holds that were sold to Jews before World War II
and remain unclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli lawyer, Roland Roth, has filed suits on behalf of
relatives of Holocaust victims against Bank Leumi and the privately
owned Israel Land Development Co., originally set up by the Zionist
movement to buy land in Palestine. Arguing that the bank has not
reported all of the dormant accounts in its possession, Roth is
demanding full disclosure of the accounts and of lands bought by
Jews who died in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Israeli banks and the land company have resisted
opening their records to outside scrutiny, their stance and the
government's inaction are not seen here as comparable to past
attempts in Switzerland and elsewhere to deny the existence of
Holocaust-era assets and to even cover up their traces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it was negligence at best; in Switzerland it was a
crime,'' said Yona Yahav, a former legislator who as chairman of
the parliamentary banking committee pressed for the Israeli bank
disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Even if no moral equivalence can be drawn between banks in
Israel and Switzerland, the banks here are motivated by a similar
desire to preserve their assets, Roth argued. ``Every economic body
has an interest in holding on to what it can,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet it remains unclear how many Holocaust-era assets are
unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   Shmuel Tsur, the administrator general, says there are few if
any Jewish-owned bank accounts and properties that were not
confiscated by the British in wartime Palestine as enemy property
and later either returned to their owners or transferred for
management by his office. Of the list of unclaimed accounts and
properties published by his office, fewer than 10 have been
recovered after claims to them were confirmed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that there is no real problem here,'' he said in an
interview. ``I don't know of any reservoir of money or property
that is hidden away somewhere in Israel. The public sense that
property is being concealed is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when he was questioned in March by Avital's committee, Tsur
acknowledged that he could not be sure that he had received full
reports from the banks of all dormant accounts, adding that he was
not authorized to audit bank records. ``I start from the assumption
that the bank reports are correct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure to to do more to find properties of Holocaust
victims, Tsur's office has begun an examination of the 15,000 files
of unclaimed property in his office to find evidence of land or
bank accounts that belonged to Jews who perished in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary committee is considering ways to empower Tsur
or an independent auditor to examine bank records, as part of a
more active government policy to find heirs to property owned by
Holocaust victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a moral obligation towards these people,'' Avital
said, noting that in some cases sums returned by Tsur's office were
absurdly low, an indication that deposited money had not been
invested by the banks or maintained at its real value.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Holocaust victims who have gone to court to claim
their inheritance say they are not motivated by a desire for
material gain.
</P>
<P>
   Eleazar Shafrir, 76, a retired biochemistry professor who fled a
Nazi labor camp in Poland and fought in Israel's war of
independence, is trying to locate a plot of land bought in 1938 by
his father, who died in Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get rich from this,'' he said. ``I just want
justice to be done. The state should give people back what they
deserve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
