<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS OUT OF IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The fact of the matter is the New England
Patriots have no idea what they are going to do when they make
their first selection in the annual NFL cattle call.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should they.
</P>
<P>
   When you are picking 46th, as the Patriots will be unless they
do some difficult wheeling and dealing in a climate where they have
little to offer but a need to move up, no one who is honest about
things can hazard a guess who will be left on the draft board when
New England is called for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The only sure thing at that point: Somebody will have been
picked whom the Patriots expected to be there and somebody
unexpected will still be available.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start picking in the second round, there's so little
predictability,'' said coach and draft master Bill Belichick this
week. ``When you pick 46th, you don't really know who'll be there.
Someone will appear, though. There's good talent in this draft and
some depth in it (at certain positions).''
</P>
<P>
   So, what do they do when it's time to do something?
</P>
<P>
   If Arizona State running back J.R. Redmond is still on the board
they should grab him because he has the kind of speed and
elusiveness they lack at that position. In addition, Redmond
catches the ball well coming out of the backfield, which is
important in a Charlie Weis offense.
</P>
<P>
   But Redmond will likely be long gone by then because most teams
feel he is the best of the second-echelon backs, the ones behind
Thomas Jones, Jamal Lewis, Ron Dayne, and Shaun Alexander. Which
brings us to Travis Prentice, a 220-pound production machine out of
Miami of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice more than fits the Belichick size-speed ratio
requirement, as well as the one for production. He was second in
the nation in rushing in 1998, gaining 1,787 yards on 365 carries.
And last year, he didn't take a backward step _ he ran for 1,667
yards on 354 carries and did so with speed and an uncanny ability
to get into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly also has run as fast as 4.37 in the 40, so what's
the problem? Take him and be done with it, right?
</P>
<P>
   Whoa, big fella.
</P>
<P>
   Many NFL scouts believe Prentice has straight-line speed rather
than explosiveness, which is of more importance in the NFL because
the men trying to tackle you are often as fast _ not to mention
bigger _ than you are.
</P>
<P>
   So, what do the Patriots do if faced with no Redmond, a hole in
the running game the size of the Grand Canyon, and a productive
small-college player like Prentice staring them in the face?
</P>
<P>
   If there's an equally rated defensive lineman or offensive
tackle they should go in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice is considerably more of a gamble than Redmond and the
Patriots have taken too many gambles in the draft the last three
years and seldom hit on them. Belichick admits having made the same
mistake in his days picking players for the Cleveland Browns and
says he won't make that mistake again.
</P>
<P>
   When the 46th pick comes up, he may get his first chance to
prove he has a new philosophy. If he does, and Prentice is there
with all those yards behind him in the Mid-American Conference, the
temptation will be to grab him.
</P>
<P>
   It's a temptation that should be fought if there is a
higher-rated player, especially if he is an offensive lineman.
Generally, Belichick does not like to take offensive linemen that
high because they take several years to develop and he believes he
can get players who will be just as good later in the draft, or
even as free agent rookies. He proved he could do that in
Cleveland, but if Southern Cal's Travis Claridge happens to be
there, the Patriots should grab him.
</P>
<P>
   New England has scouted Claridge a great deal, an indication the
Patriots might be leaning in his direction. But if he is gone, they
should still have a shot at someone like 310-pound Cosey Coleman
out of Tennessee, who once was projected as a first-round pick, or
320-pound Hawaii tackle Adrian Klemm.
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, Klemm will be gone by the late first round, as
will the prime defensive linemen. So, New England's choices will
probably boil down to running backs and linemen like Claridge.
</P>
<P>
   If that back is Redmond, the Patriots should grab him and hope
he helps improve a running game that was 28th in the NFL a year
ago, in large part due to their backs not hitting holes quickly
enough and the holes not being open for long enough, a deadly
combination.
</P>
<P>
   But if Redmond is gone and Prentice is there, they should think
seriously about getting a road grader to create some much-needed
running room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
