<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-COX15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds: Thursday is CQ
 &HT;    MP3.com buying Cox Interactive Media's share of MP3Radio.com
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MP3.com said Thursday it is buying Cox Interactive
Media's share of MP3Radio.com, an 8-month-old joint venture
designed to help radio stations make their Web sites better.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, Cox Interactive, based in Atlanta, bought a 10
percent stake in San Diego-based MP3.com, for $45 million. Part of
the agreement called for Cox and MP3.com to develop what became
MP3Radio.com, a company designed to help radio stations beef up
their Web sites. Cox Interactive is a unit of Cox Enterprises,
which also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com wanted to syndicate a radio show and promote MP3.com
musicians, said Gregg Lindahl, MP3Radio.com's president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com decided that its efforts overlapped those of
MP3Radio.com, according to a news release issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. But MP3Radio.com's
headquarters will move to San Diego. Lindahl will not make the
move. He is staying with Cox Interactive but did not say what his
new job will be.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 is a program that compresses digital music so it can be
downloaded from the Internet more quickly. Some musicians see the
format and the Internet as a way to cut out the middleman _ the
record publishing industry _ and reach customers directly, letting
fans download bargain-rate CDs from musicians' Web sites. The only
piece missing with the MP3 format is something called digital
rights management technology, a way to make sure everyone who gets
paid now when a CD is sold still will get paid when the music is
delivered digitally.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com and several major record labels were sued in federal
court this week by musicians seeking royalty payments for the
distribution of their songs over the Internet, according to
Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit comes nearly four months after a trade group
representing the record labels sued MP3.com for distributing songs
online.
</P>
<P>
   Cox is still a minority investor in MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   MP3Radio.com has developed Web sites for 118 stations, 28 of
which are Cox-owned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
