   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-AFRICA-TRADE (Washington) _ After months of tough
negotiations, Senate and House leaders have reached agreement on
new trade terms for countries in Africa, Central America and the
Caribbean, setting the stage for congressional approval in the next
few weeks. Negotiators reached a breakthrough, agreeing to provide
a measure of protection for American textile manufacturers, though
not as much as the industry and its allies in the Senate had
sought. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   NADER-POLITICS (Minneapolis) _ Forget six year's of booming
economic growth and skyrocketing stock markets. Globe-trotting
corporations are sucking the life out of small business owners and
family farmers. Pollution is poisoning our rivers, lakes and air.
Inner city schools and health clinics are crumbling. And while the
nation burns, the rich are buying and selling politicians like
cheap baseball cards. ``Big business is on a collision course with
American democracy, and American democracy has been losing.'' Those
are the words of Ralph Nader, who is mounting another radical
campaign for the presidency. But this time things are a little
different. He's raising money this time and enlisting the help of
left-leaning celebrities like Jackson Browne and Warren Beatty.
He's also managed to pluck some of the supports of Bill Bradley who
can't quite stomach the thought of supporting Al Gore, and he's set
his sights on winning at least 5 percent of the vote for the Green
Party. So far he seems to be succeeding, elbowing out Pat Buchanan
for third place in some recent polls. And if that happens, Nader
may be Al Gore's worst nightmare. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Developments. The government asked a
federal appeals court Friday to order Elian Gonzalez's Miami
relatives to return the boy to his father, who agreed to stay in
this country until it rules. The relatives, turning to another
court for help, invoked the U.N. human-rights charter in asking
that Elian stay. (Summary from wires) By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT14.
</P>
<P>
   (Early version has moved)
</P>
