<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-MOCK-DRAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2000 NFL mock draft
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig and Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. Cleveland: DE Courtney Brown, Penn State _ Only natural that
Browns draft Brown. Cleveland had NFL-low 25 sacks in '99. Brown
had 13.5. He provides instant pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   2. Washington: LT Chris Samuels, Alabama _ Like a rock ...
Gibraltar, that is. The big guy didn't give up a sack or QB
pressure in '99. He'll turn offense into a crimson tide.
</P>
<P>
   3. Washington: LB LaVar Arrington, Penn State _ How badly do
Redskins want leapin' LaVar? Very. Adding Arrington to this defense
has franchise thinking ``Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Cincinnati: WR Peter Warrick, Florida State _ Bengals can't
believe Warrick is still available. He joins QB Akili Smith as
back-to-back potential No. 1s spurned by Browns.
</P>
<P>
   5. Baltimore: WR Plaxico Burress, Michigan State _ Perfect guy
to help Ravens upgrade skill positions. Here's your prototype
receiver. He's a big, strong leaper who dominates.
</P>
<P>
   6. Philadelphia: DT Corey Simon, Florida State _ Eagles want
Warrick, but need a tackle to anchor defensive front. At 6-1, 297,
he has a 41-inch vertical leap. Simon says, ``Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   7. Arizona: TB Thomas Jones, Virginia _ Cardinals need premier
runner, so Jones is a good fit. Built like Emmitt Smith, the 5-10,
216-pounder hits the hole fast and explodes.
</P>
<P>
   8. Pittsburgh: WR Travis Taylor, Florida _ Coach Bill Cowher
needs to win, so he can't take QB Chad Pennington and groom him.
Taylor can jump-start Kordell Stewart's career.
</P>
<P>
   9. Chicago: OLB Brian Urlacher, New Mexico _ Defense is a huge
priority and Urlacher gets the call because he's a wonderful
athlete with the versatility to play strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   10. Baltimore: TB Jamal Lewis, Tennessee _ Freakish combination
of size (5-11, 240) and speed is too tempting to pass up. But
injury-riddled past makes him a little risky.
</P>
<P>
   11. New York Giants: TB Ron Dayne, Wisconsin _ NCAA career
rushing leader (6,397) fits team's smash-mouth style. The power
back runs over defenders. Can control a game.
</P>
<P>
   12. New York Jets: DE Shaun Ellis, Tennessee _ Jets need help in
several areas. They'll start on defense with the second best end in
the draft. Has good strength and explosion.
</P>
<P>
   13. New York Jets: WR Sylvester Morris, Jackson State _ Keyshawn
Johnson's trade leaves a huge void that the tall, athletic Morris
can fill. He scored 32 TDs last two years.
</P>
<P>
   14. Green Bay: DT Chris Hovan, Boston College _ Packers want
defensive line help and Hovan, with 21 tackles for loss in '99,
gives them a run-stuffer similar to Gilbert Brown.
</P>
<P>
   15. Denver: OLB John Abraham, South Carolina _ Broncos are
tempted to take a WR, but LB is vital with John Mobley coming off
torn ACL and Bill Romanowski slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   16. San Francisco: QB Chad Pennington, Marshall _ Niners are
ready to tap him as Steve Young's replacement. He's a quick enough
study to come in and start as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   17. Oakland: FS Deon Grant, Tennessee _ Raiders need safety help
to go with superb corners. Grant led nation with nine
interceptions, but needs to improve in run support.
</P>
<P>
   18. New York Jets: TE Bubba Franks, Miami (Fla.) _ Franks' stock
slipped after disappointing workouts, but he's a monster who can
carry load as blocker and receiver.
</P>
<P>
   19. Seattle: ILB Rob Morris, BYU _ He's 25 years old, which
scares some scouts. But Pro Football Weekly calls this sure, hard
hitter the best inside 'backer of past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   20. Detroit: LT Chris McIntosh, Wisconsin _ ``Big Mac'' is a
huge, strong, four-year starter who will provide running room for
James Stewart and protection for Charlie Batch.
</P>
<P>
   21. Kansas City: TB Shaun Alexander, Alabama _ Answered
questions about speed by clocking 4.4 in workouts. Bengals could
trade Corey Dillon and grab Alexander right here.
</P>
<P>
   22. Seattle: WR Dez White, Georgia Tech _ He's the perfect speed
receiver to replace Dallas-bound Joey Galloway. Scouts knock his
hands, but White's a physical specimen.
</P>
<P>
   23. Carolina: RT Stockar McDougle, Oklahoma _ McDougle is a
devastating drive blocker who crushes defenders, but struggles in
pass protection against speed rushers.
</P>
<P>
   24. San Francisco: CB Rashard Anderson, Jackson State _
Rebuilding the defense starts with a corner and this 6-2, 206 pound
athlete has the size and speed the 49ers need.
</P>
<P>
   25. Minnesota: DE John Engelberger, Virginia Tech _ An
outstanding pass rusher who will work well with Ellis. He parlayed
terrific speed and quickness into 30 career sacks.
</P>
<P>
   26. Buffalo: CB Ahmed Plummer, Ohio State _ The steadiest of all
the corners, look for Plummer to become Bills' nickel while
ex-Buckeye Antoine Winfield grabs starting role.
</P>
<P>
   27. New York Jets: RT Todd Wade, Mississippi _ This massive
blocker has the strength and bulk (6-7, 326) to move people. He
also has the frame to protect Vinny Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   28. Indianapolis: LB Keith Bulluck, Syracuse _ The Colts don't
have a proven middle LB, so they'll tap Bulluck, who has all the
tools. He's fast, quick, smooth and tenacious.
</P>
<P>
   29. Jacksonville: OG Cosey Coleman, Tennessee _ When a team has
everything, what does it do? It continues to stockpile offensive
linemen. The huge Coleman is a nice fit.
</P>
<P>
   30. Tennessee: DT Steve Warren, Nebraska _ The AFC champs need
some help on the defensive front. Warren will excel playing next to
speed rusher Jevon ``The Freak'' Kearse.
</P>
<P>
   31. St. Louis: LT Adrian Klemm, Hawaii _ Although the Rams are
tempted to take PK Sebastian Janikowski, they'll turn to Klemm to
provide depth behind Orlando Pace.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
