<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7171 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NITEOUT-KERRIGAN-ART-     04-14 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-KERRIGAN-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NITE OUT WITH JUSTIN KERRIGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By LINDA LEE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Welsh hyphenate writer-director-actor Justin
Kerrigan blew into New York on Sunday night, the people at Miramax,
which is releasing ``Human Traffic,'' his film on the rave scene,
must have gone for the Advil.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Kerrigan, 26, is one of those bad boys who trash
hotel rooms. It's that he's candid about his decadent drug-fueled
lifestyle, which is celebrated in his film.
</P>
<P>
   Which means it's pretty entertaining to meet him flying without
a conversational governor in a bar in Greenwich Village, just off
the plane from London, as he sets out to party through the night.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan is emblematic of a batch of ravequake directors who
have established a new genre of beach party movies set in the club
world of the '90s. A night with him seemed like a live-action
version of his film, jarringly unabashed and slightly blurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human Traffic'' details 48 hours in the lives of five
20-somethings in Cardiff, Wales, who are stuck in dead-end jobs and
live for Saturday night, when they can take drugs and dance. It is
based on him and his friends, and the subplot about impotence is
based on his own experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had sexual insecurity big time,'' he offered. ``But I got
over it.''
</P>
<P>
   The working life of the characters in the film is also familiar
ground. Kerrigan worked in the British Home Stores when he wasn't
on the dole. That was before Miramax flew him business class on
British Airways to New York, after giving him a three-picture deal.
</P>
<P>
   As for drugs, another subplot in the movie, Kerrigan not only
likes them, he makes no secret of doing them. At 11 p.m. he broke
away from sipping Jack Daniel's and Cokes to slip into the
limousine to call a friend. He just wanted to make sure that when
he was finished drinking Jack Daniel's and Cokes he could drop by
and get stoned.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude has taken Kerrigan from Cardiff to the highest
circles. He refers to Harvey Weinstein at Miramax, which bought the
film last fall, as ``the Al Capone of the movie industry.'' Last
year, he met the Queen at Windsor Castle after ``Human Traffic''
won some awards. ``And I wanted to say, `Have you seen this
film?'''
</P>
<P>
   There he was, he said, in the Great Hall, and in came the queen
``and her posse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly she's there and I didn't know what to do, so I stuck
out my hand,'' he said. ``You're not supposed to touch the queen or
make the first move. But she was nice and she took my hand. And
then she stayed to talk. And finally I said, `So do you rent this
place out for parties?'''
</P>
<P>
   He shared the information that he smoked a joint in the Great
Hall, and that ``I woke up in Bayswater with no money, no cab fare,
and I had to stop and say, `What happened?'''
</P>
<P>
   By midnight, the car was headed uptown to party sites unknown,
and it was time for this reporter to be dropped off. Sharing his
gen-Ecstacy philosophy about success, Kerrigan made clear that
people can get all they need from the visual environment. ``I've
only read four books in my entire life,'' he said. They are
``Conversations With Woody Allen,'' ``Conversations With Martin
Scorsese,'' Douglas Coupland's ``Generation X'' and `` Nice Guy,''
by Howard Marks, a pot dealer.
</P>
<P>
   He fretted about his schedule. The next day he would leave for
other cities. ``Miramax is giving me two days off in Houston,'' he
said. ``They're turning me loose in John Wayne territory. What are
they going to make of me in Houston?''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, anyone who can handle Harvey Weinstein and the queen can
handle Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
