<P>
   FBN-DRAFT-REVIEW _ NFL draft preview. There could be a lot of
wheeling and dealing before the Cleveland Browns pick a player with
the No. 1 draft choice. (Schlabach, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DRAFT-BROWNS _ How the Browns plan on attacking the draft.
Who might they select and why. Peter Warrick? Courtney Brown?
Arrington? (McClelland, Dayton Daily News). 18.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DRAFT-BENGALS _ How the Bengals plan on attacking the draft.
Who might they select and why. Peter Warrick might be available.
(Ludwig, Dayton Daily News). 18.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DRAFT-COWBOYS _ IRVING _ By the time the Washington Redskins
rake in two of college football's elite players in today's draft,
Jerry Jones and the scouting staff of the Dallas Cowboys will just
be rolling out of bed. This will be a benchmark day for the
Redskins. About 1,500 miles away in Valle Ranch, the braintrust of
the Cowboys will be watching the clock, wondering who will be
available with the 49th pick. (Cantu, Austin American-Statesman).
22.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS _ Falcons coach Dan Reeves said it is
essential to build a team chiefly through the draft, but there is
evidence to debunk that theory. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL
</P>
<P>
   BKC-KNIGHT-GARECRUIT _ A.J. Moye, last season's Mr. Georgia
Basketball who signed with Indiana University last fall, says that
the recent controversy surrounding coach Bobby Knight's treatment
of former players has not changed his mind about attending the
school. (Lee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-EQUESTRIAN _ LOXAHATCHEE, Fla. _ Planning for an unexpected
influx of Olympian hopefuls and their finely tuned horses comes
down to small details _ the flagpoles, the flowers, the finger food
_ and big ones: seating the spectators. The U.S. Equestrian Team
decided in March to move the Olympic dressage trials from its New
Jersey headquarters to Palm Beach County because the West Nile
Virus, which attacks both people and horses, had reappeared in the
Northeast. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
