<P>
   COXNET INSIDE NASCAR 0413 _ At Daytona, NASCAR controlled the
rear and front shocks put on every Winston Cup car. At Talladega,
the sports governing body has said it will only be in charge of the
rear shocks, leaving the front up to the team. What do drivers
think about all of this? Do they think this will cause the cars to
perform better or worse than Daytona? What difference will it make
to be able to put in your own front shocks? NASCAR already controls
the restrictor plates at Talladega, how do drivers feel about
giving up more control with shocks? Why is NASCAR doing this?
(Minter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ELLIOTT MILESTONE -- Driver Bill Elliott will reach 600
career starts when he races at Talladega this weekens. The Alabama
track has special significance for the racer from Dawsonville, Ga.
Art includes a 2-column photo of Elliott.ON THE RISE _ A look at
who's hot and who's not on the NASCAR circuit. (Carvell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
