<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-DIAMOND-JEWELRY-$ADV1     04-14 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAMOND-JEWELRY-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE DAYS A DIAMOND IS FOR .... ME! 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 16) 
 By HADLEY DAVIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a recent sunny afternoon, I ventured through the
Art Deco doors of that fabled jewelry store at 57th and Fifth.
Inside, I approached a saleswoman and, in the hushed tone of a
teen-ager requesting condoms, inquired about Tiffany's latest: the
``Lucida.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I've been looking for a diamond ring, and no, I don't have
a fiance (or even a potential fiance, for that matter). As the
sleek square stone was removed from the case, I thought: ``You can
have your Prada bowling bag; keep your Gucci python-print pant!'' I
had found my spring fashion fling: a diamond ring.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that the diamond has never gone out of style,
this season the ultimate rock _ which happens to be April's
birthstone _ has transcended its own perennial appeal. Diamond
jewelry is so much in vogue that even the engagement ring has
become a fashion item.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time diamond rings represented husbands. (Just ask
Elizabeth Taylor, who received both the 33.19-carat Krupp diamond
and a 69.42-carat Cartier rock as gifts from Richard Burton.) But
now ``they are considered not just tokens of affection but
accessories,'' said Anne Slowey, Elle magazine's fashion news
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're about fashion and status,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At this year's Oscars _ where 5,000 carats of diamonds strolled
the red carpet _ Tyra Banks, Cameron Diaz, Salma Hayek, Lauren
Holly and Ashley Judd were among the fashionable single starlets
sporting borrowed diamond rings. And the invitation to Tuesday's
flashy W Hotel opening in Los Angeles was a fake diamond solitaire
in a velvet box with a note that read, ``We're no longer a diamond
in the rough'' and instructed the recipient to ``wear this ring to
gain admission.''
</P>
<P>
   Rings are not the only diamond jewelry shimmering in the
spotlight. In recent months, Vogue has trumpeted colored diamonds,
W has had a six-page diamond spread, and Elle has guided readers
interested in diamond shopping online. The fashion designer Michael
Kors had models dripping with the gems on his fall runway.
</P>
<P>
   In the hip-hop world, diamonds even have a new alias coined by
B.G. of the Hot Boys: Bling Bling. While hip-hop cognoscenti also
refer to them as ``ice,'' Carmen Borgonovo, the accessories
director at W, said, ``Diamonds are hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at Tiffany, I slipped the princess-cut bauble over my right
middle finger (the one that we single women favor so as not to
confuse potential suitors), and sneaked a self-conscious glance at
the saleswoman to gauge her reaction. She didn't bat an eye.
Chances are she had seen the likes of me before; I'm what the
industry has come to call a ``self purchaser,'' and I may represent
the most dazzling diamond trend of all.
</P>
<P>
   The self-purchase market for diamonds increased 41 percent from
1998 to 1999, according to the Diamond Information Center at J.
Walter Thompson, the advertising agency for De Beers, the world's
largest diamond producer. ``The self-purchase market is now a $3.75
billion business in the United States,'' said Greg Distefano, a
spokesman for the center. ``Rings are the single largest type in
this market. They account for two out of every five pieces of
self-purchased jewelry.''
</P>
<P>
   More women are buying diamonds for themselves because they are
earning more, marrying later and have more disposable income to
spend on self-indulgence. But it also helps that big jewelers are
right behind them, encouraging single women to splurge on trophy
trinkets as symbols of accomplishment and success. As a De Beers
advertisement puts it: ``On my left hand you will see a symbol of
my commitment. But my right hand is my independence, my uncaptured
spirit, that also wants to shine.''
</P>
<P>
   Juliet Boghossian, marketing director at the jeweler Fred
Joaillier U.S., said her company has begun to cater to the
career-oriented professional woman age 25 to 37. ``We are making
lots of contemporary, bold middle-finger rings in the $3,000 to
$5,000 range,'' she said, ``And we advertise now in Mirabella
instead of Town &AMP; Country like we used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Cartier, Piaget and Bulgari are also shooting for
a younger, trendier clientele with ``hipper, fashionable,
interesting new pave designs that don't look like wedding rings,''
Borgonovo said. Why the close-set look of miniature pave diamonds?
``Because pave offers the same luxurious glitter,'' she said, ``but
is more accessible'' _ meaning less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Pave was certainly the look for Lady Luck, a 17-year-old rapper
who signed a Def Jam record deal last year: she bought three
interlocking pave strands for her right ring finger after the deal
was closed. ``A woman who buys herself a diamond,'' she said on a
cell phone from Teaneck High School in New Jersey, where she is a
student, ``is a woman who is rising.''
</P>
<P>
   This winter, Sharon Dorram, the chief colorist at the John
Frieda Salon in New York, bought a yellow and white gold and
diamond Buccellati ring for her 40th birthday. ``It was time to
spoil myself,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I may only be in the twilight of my 20s, but I felt ready
to make my own latter-day L'Oreal declaration. (``Because I'm worth
it!'') I returned from my trip to Tiffany with ``How to Buy a
Diamond,'' the store's free printed guide and videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Cracking open the robin's-egg-blue guide, I discovered that
finding the right diamond ring is just like finding the right guy:
there are plenty of sizes, shapes and colors to pick from. Each
stone is ``unique,'' but few are ``flawless.'' (Tell me about it.)
One must compare, to learn to distinguish the ``ordinary'' from the
``exceptional.'' (Easier said than done.) A diamond is meant to
``reward you for a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   The romance of the ``How to Buy a Diamond'' book, however, went
from sugar-sweet to NutraSweet in the video, a depiction of
cuddling couples describing their own down-on-one-knee blue-box
moments in sequences that recalled ``When Harry Met Sally.''
</P>
<P>
   I ejected the tape, a bit depressed. Maybe the Tiffany
``Lucida'' wasn't for me after all. Even on my middle finger the
single carat suggested that I was, at the very least, engaged to be
engaged. I realized that buying a diamond ring wasn't as simple as
it seemed. If it resembled an engagement ring, my self-purchase
would serve not as a fashionable badge of what I have, but as a
daily reminder of what I don't.
</P>
<P>
   Needing guidance, I consulted Plum Sykes, a Vogue fashion writer
who replied via e-mail. ``Colored diamonds are very in,'' she
wrote, naming pink, canary yellow, blue and brown as options. I
immediately went to Mondera.com, a diamond Web site, where I
pointed and clicked on ``fancy colored diamonds,'' and discovered
they're called ``fancy'' for a reason: a marigold and pink combo
ran $74,260.
</P>
<P>
   Too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   In search of a more affordable alternative, I went to Cartier,
whose Collection Paris Nouvelle Vague is for self-purchasers like
me. But when I tried on a striking gray, black and white pave
Jetton ring, it appeared as if a flying saucer had landed on my
Size 4{ finger.
</P>
<P>
   Too big.
</P>
<P>
   Down the block at Van Cleef &AMP; Arpels, I found a daintier style.
Shaped like a flower, with pretty pave petals and a tastefully tiny
center stone, the ring was pure girly glitter. As a Goldirocks
might say, this one was ``just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesmerized, I pondered the eternal question of why diamonds make
women melt. It's as mystifying as love itself. All I knew was that
I wanted that 0.74-carat $5,800 ring. I needed those itty-bitty
chips of ridiculously overpriced rock, and left Van Cleef all set,
with a Polaroid picture of the pave pansy and the salesman's
engraved business card. I promised to call _ but never did.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, it seemed I was not yet ready to join the postfeminist
ranks of self-purchasers. Or at least my bank account wasn't. The
financial reality of single-girldom had by this time sunk in. The
money for the ring went instead for April rent, phone bills, a new
computer and hair highlights.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
