<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-DEBT-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAO PAULO'S MAYOR IS AT CENTER OF FINANCIAL SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Paulistanos have delighted during the past
month in the saucy details of a scandal rocking this city's
government, as Celso Pitta, the mayor, has been relentlessly
attacked in the media by his estranged wife, Nicea Pitta.
</P>
<P>
   Celso Pitta was spotted in Paris during the Carnival holiday
dining with a mysterious blonde. His wife, furious, described
schemes in which the mayor's colleagues allegedly bought votes in
the city council and told how a wealthy patron maintained the
mayor's princely lifestyle with a loan worth nearly $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the possibility of Celso Pitta's impeachment looming
before municipal elections are held later this year, the most
pressing crisis gripping the world's third-largest city is
apparently not over politics or passions, but in borrowings from
years past that municipal government cannot repay.
</P>
<P>
   Home to 17 million people, Sao Paulo is facing the prospect of
drowning in about 7 billion reals, or $4 billion, in money it
cannot repay, as details of an illegal bond issuance operation
masterminded by Pitta and his political mentor, former Mayor Paulo
Maluf, come under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Sao Paulo's next mayor will absorb a municipal debt of $9
billion, or more than double the municipal budget. Nearly half the
debt came from the issuance of bonds needed to service debts
resulting from lawsuits, according to the Brazilian Lawyers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   However, federal prosecutors, who indicted Pitta and Maluf this
week on charges of providing false documentation in the scheme,
said only a fraction of the proceeds from the bond sales, conducted
in 1994 and 1995, was used for such stated purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, much of the money is now thought to have been used on
the public-works projects of Maluf, who preceded Pitta as mayor
from 1992 to 1996. During that time he extended the city's concrete
sprawl, leveling shantytowns to construct highways and futuristic
tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the most perplexing example of pharaonic economic policy
in modern Brazil,'' said Raul Velloso, an independent expert on
public spending. ``The richest city of Latin America issues these
bonds, and services in the city are still horrible, so it leads one
to ask where the money really went.''
</P>
<P>
   It increasingly seems that most of the money from the bonds was
not used to settle lawsuits. O Estado de S. Paulo, a newspaper,
recently described cases in which people who won legal settlements
against the city have been waiting for years to receive their
money.
</P>
<P>
   Effectively, this means that Sao Paulo's overburdened legal
system becomes more strained by residents who seek other legal
avenues to recover their settlements. ``It is a bureaucratic
nightmare,'' said Isabel Thompson, an attorney. ``Maybe one in 15
cases is settled on time and in full.''
</P>
<P>
   There are indications that the federal government will take
steps to reschedule Sao Paulo's debt over a 30-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whether such a rescheduling plan is approved is beside
the point since the central government will probably end up
absorbing the city's unserviceable debts, said Velloso, the
public-spending expert. ``Not doing so would leave our largest city
crippled,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With corruption allegations against Pitta's administration
growing, many of Sao Paulo's residents already feel as if this has
happened. Pitta has received a court order removing him from
office; it was soon overturned and is working its way through the
labyrinthine legal system.
</P>
<P>
   The latest chapter in the scandal came this week when it was
revealed that a Brazilian telecommunications company owned by
Fidelity Investments is under investigation by the U.S. Justice
Department for irregular payments allegedly made to municipal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The company, MetroRED, reportedly sought to quicken approval in
1998 of a $200 million plan to build a fiber-optic network in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   That an American company could also become embroiled in Sao
Paulo's economic and political problems has elevated the
international visibility of ``Pittagate,'' as the scandal has been
dubbed in the Brazilian press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sao Paulo's corruption has been transformed into a public
horror from the whispered-about horror it always was,'' said Jose
Carlos Sebe Bom Meihy, a professor of history at the University of
Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the very least this means the tools of Brazilian
democracy, notably the media, are working better to reveal the
interests that have plundered this city.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
