<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7196 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-28DAYS-REVIEW-HN     04-14 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-28DAYS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLOCK'S WAIT FOR BETTER MATERIAL COULD TAKE LONGER THAN `28
DAYS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandra Bullock's refusal to take the safe route in movies is
admirable. She could spend the next five years cruising through
cute romantic comedies.
</P>
<P>
   But she needs to wait for better breakout material than ``28
Days,'' a well-intended but punchless lesson on substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock is Gwen Cummings, an alcoholic sentenced to a drug
rehabilitation center after she drunkenly drives a limousine into a
house.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows someone like Cummings. When she drinks, oh boy!
She thinks she's the life of the party, unaware that she's become a
loud bore actually ruining everyone else's fun.
</P>
<P>
   With her heavy-drinking boyfriend in tow, she is 45 minutes late
as bridesmaid at her sister's wedding. She disrupts the reception
with her uninhibited dancing. ``Watch out for the wedding cake!''
</P>
<P>
   Stealing the bridal limo to find a cake shop, she locates a
front porch instead.
</P>
<P>
   The judge says jail or a rehab center. She may be a drunk, but
she's not stupid. Still convinced she does not have a problem and
cannot benefit from drying out, Cummings arrives at Serenity Glen,
a rural facility that seems like nowheresville to this hip New York
writer.
</P>
<P>
   She has a point. The choices are saying the Serenity Prayer
several times a day or chanting, not to mention hearing ``Lean on
Me'' again and again. It's enough to drive a teetotaler to drink.
</P>
<P>
   A little TLC is just what Cummings needs, however. So is meeting
new ``friends'' who are in the same boat _ if not worse.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings has a few false starts. Her enabler boyfriend smuggles
in pills and sneaks her out to get drunk early on.
</P>
<P>
   She finally gets sober long enough to discover what a mess she
is. But can she save herself? As one patient says, only a third of
the patients stay sober after they leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``28 Days'' comes off as earnest, with some moments of humor and
a few poignant scenes. Sometimes the goings-on threaten to get just
too precious, like when the patients put on a cute little show for
a patient who is leaving. But there is enough taste at work here to
keep it in check.
</P>
<P>
   It's not bad, but it's not very good, either. It follows a
predictable path from beginning to end. It would be unfair to call
the movie heavy-handed, but it feels like an essay on the social
problems of drinking and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Thomas (``Doctor Doolittle,'' ``The Brady Bunch Movie'')
directed from a screenplay by Susannah Grant, who did a lot better
job with ``Erin Brockovich'' and ``Ever After.''
</P>
<P>
   A solid cast plays the inevitable assortment of quirky inmates:
Viggo Mortensen, Azura Skye, Diane Ladd and Marianne Jean-Baptiste.
Steve Buscemi, in surprise casting, shows up as head of the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock does a good job with the dramatic demands of the role.
She never makes Cummings adorable, which would have undermined the
film's intentions. Bullock's likable qualities are enough to keep
this film afloat _ if just barely _ without pandering. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``28 Days'' &QL; 
Starring: Sandra Bullock, Viggo Mortensen, Azura Skye, Elizabeth
Perkins, Dominic West &QL; 
Rating: PG-13, for mature thematic elements involving substance
abuse, language and some sensuality &QL; 
Running time: 103 minutes &QL; 
Grade: C &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
