<HEADER>
A7203 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CLINTON-EDWRITERS-COX     04-14 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDWRITERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton pushes for better pay for teachers
 &HT;    By James Salzer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton urged states Friday to use their
hefty budget surpluses to boost teacher pay in a major way, a move
Georgia didn't make during the 2000 legislative session despite
overflowing coffers and a year-long push to improve public
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to demand more of our teachers, but we need to reward
them better,'' Clinton said in a speech to members of the Education
Writers Association in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a couple of million teachers retiring in
the next few years. We already have the largest student population
... in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're going to have to work very, very hard to get
more qualified teachers in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey by Gov. Roy Barnes' Education Reform Study Commission
last year found 113 of 141 local superintendents who responded said
they were experiencing difficulty filling teacher positions in one
or more subjects.
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia, the shortage may only get worse. The U.S.
Department of Education has projected that Georgia's schools will
have the fastest enrollment growth rate during the next decade of
any state east of the Mississippi River. In addition, the state
Board of Education this week began implementing class-size
restrictions mandated by Barnes' school reform bill that may force
districts to hire more teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The president said now, while the economy is still fairly hot
and tax revenues are flowing, is when states should be hiking
salaries to attract top job candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most states are in terrific (financial) shape,'' Clinton said.
``Every one of these states are facing the prospect of too many
teacher retirements. With very low unemployment, they are having
the same problem recruiting teachers we're now having with military
personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the education writers, ``When the budget surpluses
are there, the money is there, now is the best time states have had
in generations to make dramatic increases in teacher pay, and I
hope they will do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' spokeswoman, Joselyn Butler, responded, ``It sounds like
the president is trying to get other states to do what we in
Georgia are proud to have already done: lead the Southeast in
teacher salaries and be at the national average.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there were grumbles at the Capitol this session that
Barnes' 3 percent teacher pay hike for the 2000-2001 school year
didn't stack up well against the gains Georgia educators have seen
of late. It was the lowest raise since the mid-1990s and was
approved despite a surplus in the neighborhood of $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers received a 4 percent raise from Barnes and lawmakers
for the 1999-2000 school year after getting 6 percent pay hikes for
each of the last four years of Gov. Zell Miller's second term.
</P>
<P>
   Before Miller began his salary drive, the average pay for a
public school teacher in Georgia ranked 34th in the country. The
latest survey from the National Education Association ranked
Georgia 19th last year in teacher pay and tops in the Southeast.
The NEA estimated the average salary for teachers in Georgia at
$41,327 this year, and it's even higher in the Atlanta area.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Christmas, director of the state's largest teacher
group, the Professional Association of Georgia Educators, called
Barnes' 3 percent raise this year ``modest,'' and said Clinton's
got the right idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``A sizable raise needs to be a high priority so we don't lose
the ground we've gained,'' she said. ``In order to attract and
retain the best teachers, we've got to have competitive salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good example of needing to put our money were our
mouth is because there is a lot of rhetoric about needing improved
teacher quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes also could use some help politically with teachers. Many
of them were angered by the tenor of his call to rid classrooms of
bad teachers and his successful bid to kill fair dismissal hearing
rights for new educators.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to regain some support from teachers. That's a block
of 87,000 votes,'' said state School Superintendent Linda Schrenko,
one of the governor's most vocal critics.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent has called on the General Assembly to approve
a 10 percent pay increase for teachers next year, and 15 percent
more for those willing to teach in low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   She said her Department of Education saw out-of-state teacher
applicants increase from 1,000 to 15,000 annually just two years
after Miller began his series of pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is going to be a teacher shortage,'' the
superintendent said. ``They have been shortchanged for two years in
a row. I want to make up for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
