<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BARZUN-CULTURAL-HISTO     04-14 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARZUN-CULTURAL-HISTORY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACQUES BARZUN: A SOJOURNER IN THE PAST RETRACES HIS STEPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Before coming to the United States to begin his
studies at Columbia University in 1923, Jacques Barzun perfected
his English by studying Jonathan Swift's ``Gulliver's Travels.'' It
was an unusual primer, but Barzun's childhood, like Swift's, had
been shattered by war, and disarray and darkness were on his mind.
A few years earlier, at the age of 12, the young Barzun had
contemplated suicide. The First World War had left many he knew
dead or maimed. His parents' salon in their house in Creteil, near
Paris, at which artists and writers like Apollinaire and Cocteau
gathered, had come to an end. The French universities at which he
would have studied were decimated. So he devoted himself to
learning English under the tutelage of the sardonic Swift, before
beginning his own travels among peoples that were to him only a bit
less exotic than Gulliver's Yahoos and Brobdingnags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had read a lot of books about the Indians,'' Barzun recently
explained in an interview at his daughter's apartment in Manhattan,
``I thought that I would come here and see Indians galloping across
the plains.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, as he settled into New York, he began a series of
intellectual journeys, turning his back on any chance he might have
had to become a French diplomat and writer like his father. He
became, instead, one of the founders of the modern discipline of
cultural history. He wrote about 18th-century France and
19th-century Europe, about the art of the detective novel and the
life of the composer Hector Berlioz. For nearly 50 years, he taught
history at Columbia, eventually becoming its provost, and led
seminars with Lionel Trilling that were legendary for their rigor
and range. He wrote over 30 books, translated nearly a dozen more,
and now, at the age of 92, he has finished an epic chronicle of his
historical forays, a survey of 500 years of Western cultural life,
``From Dawn to Decadence'' (HarperCollins), to be published in May.
</P>
<P>
   Its 800 pages condense his teaching career, surveying the
tumultuous mixing of intellectual, religious and cultural
traditions that make up what we now call the West, creating, as
Barzun puts it, ``the mongrel civilization par excellence.'' When
he talks about his vision of this civilization and its discontents,
his conversation ranges as widely as the book, touching on Kant,
amateur musicianship, Trilling, the Rhodes Scholarship, the
counterculture and the Protestant Reformation.
</P>
<P>
   Barzun's face is leaner and more lined than it once was, his
voice is less vigorous and he walks carefully with a cane. But the
only other sign that he is in his 10th decade is that he has
accumulated a long lifetime of literary references and historical
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls the atmosphere at Columbia during the 1920s, when
cultural history was just taking shape as a discipline. During the
1890s, he explains, the social sciences underwent ``a great
upheaval.'' Emile Durkheim was transforming sociology and William
James psychology not by defining narrow professional boundaries
but, as Barzun puts it, by starting to pay attention to ``the most
generalized form of cultural activity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthropologists put the final touch to it,'' he continues,
``by defining culture among primitive peoples as everything they
did: the way they ate, their canoes, their marriage customs _
nothing was left out. When that idea is applied to history, you
find that the arts, social customs, government, religion and so
forth all become part of cultural history.''
</P>
<P>
   At Columbia, Barzun recalls, C.J.H. Hayes, the author of a
widely used two-volume textbook ``The Political and Social History
of Modern Europe,'' was planning its revision as ``The Political
and Cultural History of Modern Europe.'' Barzun, Hayes' student,
assisted in the research and was, as he says, ``launched.''
</P>
<P>
   The cultural study of history has now become so thoroughly
mainstream _ even mutating into contemporary forms like cultural
studies _ that it might seem strange to hear just how novel it once
was. What made it distinctive, Barzun explains, was that it refused
to be bound by categories of politics, economics or philosophy.
Every thinker, Barzun suggests, ``is born into a cultural
situation, and we must find out why he picks up the thread here and
not there, and why he modifies it and how it is related to what
else is happening at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cultural history creates a web of interrelationships.
Understanding the past does not just mean, say, tracing a
philosophical idea through time, but seeing how that idea is woven
into a cultural fabric. And cultural history, as Barzun thinks of
it, traces the evolution of that fabric through time. It creates a
coherent view of the past and its relationship to the present. By
showing continuities and transformations in a tradition, it makes
sense of the idea of a civilization.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the cultural historian, watching these complex
relationships unfold, is even more difficult because the frame of
reference for judging those past eras is the constantly shifting
present. In his book ``Classic, Romantic, and Modern,'' Barzun
points out that a cultural historian ``must lead a double life'':
he must ``see the strivings of past epochs with generous fellow
feeling'' and must also feel ``the needs _ which includes the lacks
_ of his own time.'' The fellow feeling means that the past is
understood in comparison with the present; the present is
understood in comparison with the past.
</P>
<P>
   This is also what Barzun tries to accomplish in ``From Dawn to
Decadence,'' which focuses on a series of evolving ideas _ ideas he
capitalizes throughout the text like EMANCIPATION, ABSTRACTION,
INDIVIDUALISM, SECULARISM.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that there have been four principal eras in recent
Western history. The first, which started with the Protestant
Reformation in 1517, dealt with the issue of ``what to believe in
religion.'' The second, which encompassed most of the 18th century
and ended with the French Revolution in 1789, dealt with the issue
of ``what to do about the status of the individual and the mode of
government.'' The third, which started with 19th-century
Romanticism and ended with Modernism after World War I, tried to
determine ``by what means to achieve social and economic
equality.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth is ending now. As Barzun sees it, the fundamental
themes are less clear than they were in past eras, partly because
old certainties are unraveling. The West may be politically and
economically triumphant, but it is plagued by doubts. Postmodern
assertions that there are no absolute truths and that all cultural
suppositions are relative displace the rigors of scrutiny that
marked the development of the West. The nation-state, which evolved
out of Western political thought during the last 500 years, is
being challenged by separatist passions. The central Western notion
of emancipation has now come to mean that ``nothing stands in the
way of every wish,'' in Barzun's words. And in the arts, creativity
is celebrated as a universal talent, diminishing the achievements
of genius. Our age is, in Barzun's words, decadent.
</P>
<P>
   A decadent era, in Barzun's lexicon, is a period in which there
is a kind of ``falling off,'' a restless period in which ``there
are no clear lines of advance.'' ``When people accept futility and
the absurd as normal,'' he writes, ``the culture is decadent. The
term is not a slur; it is a technical label.'' And though it often
seems a slur in Barzun's book, its intimations of decay also
provide some reason for hope.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Barzun suggests, other more extreme periods of
decadence _ which include the corrupt 17th-century universe of
Swift or the 15th century before the Reformation challenged the
corruption of the medieval Church _ were followed by periods of
reconstruction, in which Western culture was re-examined and
reconstituted.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he says, the Romantic movement of the early 19th
century is too often considered a celebration of passion,
irrationality or sentiment. Instead, Barzun argues, it was an
attempt to construct a cultural order out of the wreckage of the
French revolution. Romanticism did not destroy an order; it created
one.
</P>
<P>
   That is also, in Barzun's view, what the West may be looking
forward to. If Western traditions are worn and frayed, that is
``all to the good, because it clears the ground,'' he says, leaving
the way open for future construction. This tension between
destruction and creation is also, he suggests, an essential aspect
of Western culture. The West has itself been so successful, Barzun
says, partly because of ``continual debates between orthodoxy and
rebellion and the strange ability of individuals to stand out for
their accomplishments.'' Out of such tensions, decadence may lead
to a new dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Mankind is resilient, Barzun believes, despite his mordant view
of the present. What is to come can only be imagined: ``It is only
in the shadows; when some fresh wave, truly original, truly
creative, breaks upon the shore, that there will be a rediscovery
of the West.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
