<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-PSYCHO-REVIEW-HN     04-14 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PSYCHO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN PSYCHO' IS MORE A GORY SATIRE THAN A GRISLY SLASHER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Two dots needed over e in Chloe) 
 
By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You are Patrick Bateman, an immaculately groomed, financially
successful, well-educated vice president of a Wall Street firm. In
a meeting with your fellow vice presidents, you show off your
elegant new business card.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very nice,'' says another VP, ``but check this out.'' His new
card has whiter, finer paper, and even more gold fleck in the
lettering.
</P>
<P>
   You're stunned. Humiliated. Sent mentally reeling. So you invite
the offending fellow to your apartment, put on a raincoat, and chop
him up with an ax.
</P>
<P>
   Gross horror? Or satire?
</P>
<P>
   The makers of ``American Psycho,'' especially writer and
director Mary Harron, are betting most viewers will automatically
understand the satirical bent in such outrageous material. Blood
drips on the opening titles of American Psycho, but what threatens
to be a grisly slasher movie quickly proves to be merely a
belligerent sheep in wolf's clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Like the notorious Bret Easton Ellis book from which it is
adapted, the film of ``American Psycho'' arrives preceded by a vile
reputation. The movie, however, while hardly tame, never tries to
set records in gore or horror, and has had thoroughly excised the
misogyny.
</P>
<P>
   Is there violence? Oh, yes. There are maybe 20 killings in
``American Psycho,'' or about a third of the number in a typical
Arnold Schwarzenegger film.
</P>
<P>
   And there are horror images. A brief glimpse of a head in a
freezer, some bodies hanging in a closet. If your gross-out level
is low, you've been warned.
</P>
<P>
   But if you saw, say, ``Seven,'' you'll find the tone here _
exaggerated, ironic _ less threatening. If you saw ``Saving Private
Ryan,'' you saw more violence and a lot more gore than you will in
``American Psycho.''
</P>
<P>
   Like last year's ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' ``American Psycho'' arrives
with false expectations. Those who rush to see it anticipating a
slasher film are going to be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1987, ``American Psycho'' is a harsh, stinging satire
(not comedy) on the greed of America's so-called ``me generation''
for whom serving ``self'' became an acceptable excuse for any
behavior. Christian Bale portrays Bateman as iconographic, an
overblown representation of this self-indulgence taken to absurd
levels.
</P>
<P>
   The movie makers assume audiences will understand this without
being told. There's no point at which anyone says, ``Gee, killing a
dozen people on a whim is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But people view movies differently. Since Bateman is the main
character, narrator and protagonist, some will take this literally
while others may appreciate its satiric tone.
</P>
<P>
   Bateman, a mid-20s New York executive, spends his workday
watching TV or hassling his secretary (Chloe Sevigny) about her
shoes. (He prefers high heels.)
</P>
<P>
   He can never set a date to marry his rich fiancee, Evelyn (Reese
Witherspoon), saying he can't find the time to take off work.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his nights are spent carousing in expensive restaurants,
bars and clubs, having rambling conversations with ``friends,''
sometimes briefly getting away from their favorite topic,
themselves, to discuss important issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sikhs are killing tons of Israelis in Sri Lanka.''
</P>
<P>
   His main sport is figuring how to get reservations at more
exclusive places than his friends can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking of reasonable, the bill was only $570. Not bad,''
Bateman says after one dinner.
</P>
<P>
   He spends hours a day in personal grooming, dousing his body
with one outrageously expensive body enhancer after another, or
toning his already sculpted physique into zones beyond perfection,
while watching porn videos.
</P>
<P>
   These material things are his only identity, and he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Patrick Bateman,'' he tells us. ``There is an idea
of a Patrick Bateman, an abstraction, but there is no real me. I
simply am not there.''
</P>
<P>
   We are not sure when Bateman began killing, but the first we see
is when he stops in a dark alley to talk with a street person
asking for a handout. Chatting in a friendly manner, Bateman opens
his briefcase and instead of giving the guy money gives him a knife
in the gut.
</P>
<P>
   Bateman moves on to co-workers, friends, casual dates,
prostitutes. Most are just people who have offended him in some
mild way. Bateman hates them, himself and everything around him.
The killings seem an attempt, increasingly futile, to make his
unreal world real.
</P>
<P>
   Like those in the book, some of the murders are gross or
bizarre. A man is killed with an ax, a woman with a chainsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Where the book delivered gory details, the movie mostly avoids
them. We see blood splash on Bateman's raincoat, rather than the
man as he's hit with the ax.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this satire rather than horror? The film's tone, its
exaggerated realism. The prissy, ``aren't I clever?'' way Bateman
moves as he puts on the raincoat. The way he lectures his intended
victims on the great artistry of the vacuous pop music he plays as
he prepares to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Or the ridiculous way Bateman preens for the video camera he has
set up to record the sex he'll have with two prostitutes _ so
self-absorbed that he never notices they find him a total bore.
</P>
<P>
   Willem Dafoe plays Kimball, a detective investigating a murder,
but Kimball's occasional appearances only build Bateman's mounting
insanity. The only suspense in the film comes when we are waiting
to see if Bateman will kill a character we care about.
</P>
<P>
   Bale gives an absolutely creepy, self-mocking performance. He's
outrageous, without ever trying to be comic or funny or winking at
the audience. He never wants us to like this guy, even in the
frightened way we like Anthony Hopkins in ``The Silence of the
Lambs.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, because we see everything from his eyes and hear his
thoughts, it's hard not to relate to him at times, which is
genuinely uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Harron, who co-wrote the movie with Guinevere Turner (``Go
Fish'') keeps it way out there, never veering far from her harsh,
hip tone.
</P>
<P>
   So effective is she in making ugly the absurdity of our
name-brand consumer culture that we leave the theater wanting to
rip the designer labels off our clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is not comedy, but it is joyously mean and evil,
somewhat in the tone of ``Blue Velvet.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, the movie depends on the novelty of its
outrageous subject and its repugnantly shallow characters for its
entertainment value. We run low in interest in both before the
movie winds to its intentionally ambiguous ending.
</P>
<P>
   And even while appreciating the guts in making this project, one
can't help but wonder about the need to adapt such an ugly premise,
even sanitized of its most vile elements. Is this really the best
way for talented folks to express the idea that society is
misguided? Surely not. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``American Psycho'' &QL; 
Starring: Christian Bale, Chloe Sevigny, Willem Dafoe, Reese
Witherspoon &QL; 
Rating: R, for strong violence, sexuality, drug use and language.
Also: Male backside nudity and fleeting female nudity. &QL; 
Running time: 97 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
