A7213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-PREVIEW15-C     04-14 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-PREVIEW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Browns may be leaning toward end Brown as top pick
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This weekend's NFL draft figures to be as
unpredictable as the stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   The only things that seem certain in the two-day, seven-round
draft are the players who will be chosen with the first four picks.
And that Washington, Baltimore _ thanks to Atlanta _ and the New
York Jets are all in positions to greatly improve their teams.
</P>
<P>
   No one really seems to know the order in which the top four
players will be selected. The Cleveland Browns, who have the No. 1
pick, were negotiating Friday with the agents of two Penn State
stars _ defensive end Courtney Brown and linebacker LaVar
Arrington. It is believed that Cleveland will take Brown, who would
be greeted in New York by Cleveland quarterback Tim Couch, the No.
1 pick in last year's draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a strong leaning toward Courtney Brown in terms of how
the building is divided,'' Browns President Carmen Policy told a
Cleveland radio station. ``I'm not talking about 70 percent or 80
percent. I'm probably talking 65 percent. But there's a very vocal
element in this building that feels LaVar Arrington deserves the
position and we certainly shouldn't rush to judgment, and we should
stick with this evaluation down to the bitter end.''
</P>
<P>
   That would probably leave the Redskins sitting on pins and
needles. The Redskins covet Arrington, an explosive linebacker who
could shore up the league's second-worst defense last season.
Washington has the second and third picks of the draft and will
probably take Alabama offensive tackle Chris Samuels with one of
them. The Redskins also are considering Florida State receiver
Peter Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go wrong with either Brown or Arrington,''
Washington coach Norv Turner said. ``Most people say this draft has
three or four great players available _ we know we're going to get
two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Redskins and Ravens have a pair of top 10 picks. Since
1970, only 12 teams have been in the same position. Of those
previous 12 teams, only the 1976 Bengals had a .500 record or
better the previous season. The Redskins were 10-6 last season and
made the playoffs; the Ravens finished 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who this week traded All-Pro receiver Keyshawn Johnson
to the Buccaneers, are the first team in league history to have
four picks in the first round. The Jets were trying to move up for
a chance at drafting Samuels or Warrick, but they hadn't found any
suitors as of late Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the real winner of the draft figures to be Washington,
which, barring an unexpected trade, will become only the fifth team
in 30 years to make two picks in the top five. The Colts were the
last team to have two top five choices, and they improved from 4-12
to 8-8 after drafting running back Marshall Faulk and linebacker
Trev Alberts in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins already have added Buffalo defensive end Bruce
Smith, Detroit safety Mark Carrier and Minnesota quarterback Jeff
George to their roster through free agency. But Washington might be
saving its real fireworks for June, when the Redskins might make a
serious offer to All-Pro cornerback Deion Sanders, who could be
released by Dallas on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little early to be talking about the Super
Bowl,'' Turner said. ``What we're talking about now is doing the
work to become a good team.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When; where: Today-Sunday; Felt Forum, New York City.
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: ESPN (today, noon-7 p.m. and Sunday 11 a.m.-1 p.m.), ESPN2
(today, 7-10 p.m. and Sunday 1-6 p.m.)
</P>
