<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors for publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service that are
scheduled for release on  &UR; SUNDAY, APRIL 16, &LR;  of particular
interest. We plan to move these stories by 2 p.m. EST on Saturday,
April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Please note that this budget is prepared from an advance list of
stories, and some items may later be eliminated. Please consult the
following budgets for updated information:  &UR; STYLE-BUDGET &LR; ,
 &UR; SUNBIZ-BUDGET &LR; ,  &UR; REVIEW-BUDGET &LR;   &UR; and SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY AND BUSINESS &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-TECH-BILLIONAIRES (Tel Aviv, Israel) _ The land of milk
and honey is fast becoming a land of money, as the technology
billionaires minted by the bull market rise to become Israel's most
important business figures and cultural heroes. Their
entrepreneurship is transforming a sclerotic economy _ and promises
to alter society and culture as well. By William A. Orme Jr. WITH
GRAPHIC and PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-CINAR (Undated) _ What went wrong at Cinar Corp.,
Canada's leading animation house and creator of the popular
``Arthur'' television series. By James Brooke. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-EBAY (Undated) _ The state of Oregon and a lot of other
local governments are auctioning items on Ebay. Why? People who
show up for sherrif's sales are savvy professional bargain hunters,
but Ebay pulls in the free spenders. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEK IN REVIEW &LR;  (Will move in `a' or `i' categories, as noted)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-POVERTY-REVIEW (United Nations) _ On all sides of the
debate about globalization, in rich and poor nations alike, there
lurks a disturbing, shared sense that even as Internet millionaires
are being made and industry expands around the Third World,
something is going very wrong in the poorest economies and most
disadvantaged societies. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVES-DEATHPENALTY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Several
prominent law-and-order U.S. conservatives have recently raised
questions about the death penalty. Some urge more DNA testing to
help acquit the unjustly convicted. Others seek more procedural
safeguards. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   CEO-PAY-REVIEW (Undated) _ In 1992, Bill Clinton decried the
soaring salaries of America's chief executives. In the eight years
since then, CEOs' average pay has more than tripled to $11.9
million, but this year's presidential candidates have not mentioned
it. The changing American attitude toward money may have something
to do with it. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   WEAPONS-COSTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Pentagon has always
insisted that there can be no price tag on national security:
weapons represent America's global superiority, and if they are
costly, so be it. But the issue of how wisely the Pentagon spends
money persists. Billion-dollar cost overruns are now commonplace at
the Pentagon. And telling the truth about costs still comes hard.
By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-GENOME-REVIEW (Undated) _ The human genome project could
enable medicine and medical research to return to some of its best,
and most old-fashioned, traditions. In fact, the emerging gene
sciences will reunite the patient, doctor and researcher in ways
not seen since the 19th- and early 20th centuries. By David A.
Shaywitz and Dennis A. Ausiello
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   WWII-ART-THEFTS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Art institutions and private
and governmental agencies around the world are beginning to publish
catalogs on the Internet describing artworks in their holdings that
could have been confiscated or looted by one of the belligerents in
World War II and, if so proved, should be returned to their
rightful owners. By William Honan.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-CUBA-REVIEW (Seoul, South Korea) _ Cuba's Fidel Castro
has been the intellectual scold of the powerful, preaching to the
world's rich nations about their obligations to the world's poorest
nations. North Korea has been seen as intransigent, introverted and
unpredictable and un-worldly-wise. But judging by recent events,
it's the North Koreans who seem to have come first to a reluctant
understanding of how the world really works these days: That what a
desperately impoverished communist outpost sitting next to a
capitalist hotshot needs most is not an enemy to rail against but a
partner to join futures with. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (Moving in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS (Will move in `e' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-FILMS (Undated) _ Stanley Kubrick's death last spring,
followed by the release of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' revived a
long-running argument among critics and fans about whether Kubrick
was one of the most important contemporary filmmakers or merely
among the most self-important. The debate shows no signs of ending
any time soon. By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   JACOBI-THEATER (Undated) _ The truth about Derek Jacobi, one of
the most emotionally potent British classical actors of his
generation, is that he has never known how to take a bow. He
loathes being singled out for approval. Audiences at ``Uncle
Vanya,'' the new Roundabout Theater Company production in which
Jacobi makes his first Broadway appearance in more than a decade,
will easily spot him during the curtain call: he's the one looking
as if he'd rather be doing his taxes. By Peter Marks. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-SOUNDS (Windhoek, Namibia) _ Every composer, conductor,
musicologist and critic ought to be forced to spend time in places
like West Africa. The shrinkage of stature would both alarm and
instruct them. By day there is the overwhelming silence of the
bush. At night one hears the community and the competition. Anyone
pondering the meaning of art might give a listen to the birds and
animals of the Okovanggo Basin. The sounds they make are both
warning and welcome, but mostly they are acts of self-expression
and thus self-preservation. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-COUNTRY (Undated) _ As Nashville, the music machine,
has become bigger and blander, Nashville the city _ along with its
kindred planet in Austin, Texas _ has become the center of an
increasingly diverse and intriguing array of American music rooted
in country with strains of folk, rock, bluegrass, rockabilly and
blues. By Peter Applebome. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   UNTRENDY-ART (New York) _ ``Greater New York,'' at P.S. 1
Contemporary Art Center is a spirited affair that rounds up enough
youngish artists (146 in all) to start a day camp. The 2000
Biennial at the Whitney Museum of American Art, despite its
broader, cross-the-country sweep, is similarly well-stocked with
unfamiliar names. The latest art-world trend is untrendy artists.
By Deborah Solomon. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   (This story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLES &LR;  (Will move in ``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JEANS-FASHION (New York) _ Jeans are back, and they have left
Woodstock decidedly behind. They are the season's biggest fashion
trend, and the trendiest part of the trend, dirty denim, reflects
the rest of our instant theme park culture: it has been dirtied for
you in advance _ prestained, preburnt or prepainted. By Alex
Witchel. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   DIAMOND-JEWELRY (New York) _ While it's true that the diamond
has never gone out of style, this season the ultimate rock _ which
happens to be April's birthstone _ has transcended its own
perennial appeal. Diamond jewelry is so much in vogue that even the
engagement ring has become a fashion item. By Hadley Davis.
</P>
