<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7221 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-FUEL-2TAKES-$ADV1     04-14 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FUEL-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHICKEN, THE EGG AND THE REIGN OF GASOLINE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Once upon a time, just after the Persian Gulf war
and the oil-price spike it caused, the government came up with yet
another plan to reduce American dependence on imported oil.
</P>
<P>
   The big idea was to promote alternative fuels for vehicles. The
plan Congress passed in 1992 was intended, by the far-off year of
2000, to replace 10 percent of the gasoline and diesel fuel used by
cars, pick-ups, vans and sport utility vehicles with something not
made from oil. By 2010, it was supposed to replace 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has been a fairy tale. There are indeed about one
million cars and light trucks on the road equipped to run on
natural gas, ethanol, methanol, propane or some other substitute,
but hardly any of them ever do. The country has made only about an
eyedropper-full of progress for each gallon of gasoline or diesel
burned.
</P>
<P>
   Many advocates of alternative fuel blame the car companies. Car
companies blame the Energy Department. The Energy Department blames
Congress. And everybody, by and large, still uses gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Energy Department say they have tried hard to
make the 1992 program work, but that they were hobbled from the
start by weaknesses in the plan, contained in the Energy Policy
Act. ``It's like going after a grizzly bear with a fly swatter,''
said one Energy Department official, who asked not to be further
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever thought it would be easy. The authors of the plan
recognized the obvious, that no one would buy a nongasoline car
until its fuel was available at filling stations all over the
country, and that no one would build the filling stations until
there were cars to use the fuel. They tried to solve the
chicken-and-egg problem by tapping the buying power of large public
and private vehicle fleets.
</P>
<P>
   The law, passed by a Democratic Congress and signed by President
George Bush, required two categories of fleet owners _ the federal
and state governments, and companies that sell electricity and
natural gas _ to include a certain share of alternative-fuel
vehicles among their new purchases. The figure for the federal
government this year is 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the law contained a crucial compromise. It called for
vehicles that (italics)could(end italics) use alternative fuels,
not those that (italics)must(end italics) use them, to spare fleet
owners any danger of being held hostage by fuel suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, some 30 light-duty vehicle models _ sedans, station
wagons, minivans, pickups and sport utility vehicles _ are built to
run solely on some alternative fuel, usually natural gas or
propane. But ``sales are still stuck in the basement,'' said the
Energy Department official, accounting for fewer than 1 of every
1,000 light vehicles sold.
</P>
<P>
   A second, more successful provision called for stretching
gasoline supplies by adding filler chemicals to ordinary gasoline,
like Hamburger Helper to ground beef. But the most popular, known
as MTBE, proved to be a threat to groundwater supplies, and the
Clinton administration now wants to ban it.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of the law worked better; for example, energy use
per square foot in federal buildings has been cut by more than 20
percent. But that saves coal and natural gas, not gasoline. The
effort to diversify transportation fuel has had some success in
heavy vehicles like trucks and buses, but not in the light vehicles
that use most of the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   One giant hurdle is retail availability. Of the 145,000 gas
stations in the United States, only about 50 sell fuel that is more
than 10 percent ethanol. None are in Washington, so parked in the
garage beneath the Energy Department headquarters are three
ethanol-ready cars that have never seen any fuel but unleaded
regular. (The federal government is helping to open an ethanol pump
at a station near the Pentagon in Arlington, Va.)
</P>
<P>
   About 1,300 places have compressed natural gas, but most are bus
depots, United Parcel Service hubs or the like. Only a few dozen
are ordinary service stations. That creates a special problem,
because natural-gas vehicles typically go only about half as far on
a tankful as gasoline vehicles do.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some fuel companies tried to help; in the early 1990s, Amoco
added natural gas at 37 of its service stations at a cost of more
than $250,000 apiece. But sales were so slow _ the equivalent of 20
gallons of gasoline a day _ that the company gave up.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of the Energy Policy Act hoped that fleets would get
the ball rolling, and that high gasoline prices would lead to
demand for alternative fuels. But they were wrong, partly because
for years the price of gasoline did not cooperate. Natural gas and
ethanol are roughly competitive with what gasoline was selling for
last year, and are notably cheaper than gasoline today. But
expectations are paramount, and most car shoppers today do not
believe that gas will remain expensive for very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The increased use of alternative fuels very much depends on
the price of gasoline,'' said Dan W. Reicher, assistant secretary
of energy for efficiency and renewable energy. ``At least today,
ethanol is a very competitive fuel.'' With a tax subsidy already in
place, he added, suppliers ``can make money at a price point
somewhat below the current price of gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   Except perhaps for electric cars, the technology needed for the
vehicles is mostly in place. ``We've proven they work,'' said Bill
Webster, director of fleet management at the General Services
Administration, which buys much of the government's car fleet,
including 27,000 alternative-fuel vehicles. ``The problem is, you
have to have an infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that Congress gave the Energy Department
authority to require local governments and big corporations to buy
alternative-fuel vehicles too, but the department has not done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was optional,'' said Lisa Cutler, a spokeswoman for the
department. ``We only had to do it if it was critical to meet Epact
goals,'' she added, using a shorthand name for the law.
</P>
<P>
   And builders of alternative-fuel vehicles say one reason so few
are on the road is that many government agencies that are required
to buy them simply do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a challenge,'' said Art Garner, a spokesman for
Honda, who said his company had spent millions of dollars to
develop a natural-gas-powered Civic that California says is the
cleanest internal combustion car made. ``The letter of the law is
not pursued very stringently,'' he said. ``Nobody's complied with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ford Motor, which makes the most natural-gas-powered cars,
said sales were nowhere near what they would be if everyone were
complying. Reicher said that the shortfall was only about 500 cars
and that the Energy Department had written letters to noncompliers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the public at large, voluntarily buying an
alternative-fuel car hardly makes sense on economic grounds.
Natural gas has been selling for the equivalent of 75 cents or so a
gallon, according to Gilbert P. Sperling of the Natural Gas Vehicle
Coalition _ attractive today but less so when gasoline goes for $1
or $1.10.
</P>
<P>
   For a typical household car or van, he said, ``you're paying
$5,000 more for a vehicle that uses only 500 gallons a year.'' For
buses that use thousands of gallons a year, he said, switching is
``a no-brainer,'' but for light-duty vehicles, ``we're not seeing
much activity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
