<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-QANDA15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Answers to queries small investors are asking amid shaky market
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here are some answers to questions that small
investors are asking about their personal finances in the wake of a
volatile stock market.
</P>
<P>
   SHOULD I GET OUT OF STOCKS?
</P>
<P>
   Many studies show that the best tactic for small investors is to
buy and hold. Panic almost always causes bad decisions. Your first
step should be to review why you bought each investment and how
long you intend to hold it. If that period is more than five years,
you can usually outlast a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   The experts advise you to stick with your plan, no matter how
scary the market is right now. ``You should not make radical
changes based on market bounces,'' said John Waelty, a spokesman
for Lutheran Brotherhood, a Minneapolis-based financial services
company. ``These decisions should be based on your own individual
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   SHOULD I LOWER THE PERCENTAGE OF MY INVESTMENTS THAT ARE IN
STOCKS?
</P>
<P>
   That depends partly on how you feel about risk and partly on the
confidence you have in your current financial plan. If things are
getting so scary that you might panic, you may need to cut back on
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But you should take baby steps. If you find that 60 percent of
your portfolio is in stocks, you might want to trim that allocation
to 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ARE SOME SAFER, OR AT LEAST STEADIER, INVESTMENTS?
</P>
<P>
   One choice is the government's I-bonds. The interest rate paid
on them is adjusted for inflation, and you can certainly expect to
get your investment back.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy I-bonds at the U.S. Treasury's Web site,
www.savingsbonds.gov, and you can use a credit card. Right now the
bonds are paying 6.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you think you might want the money back within the next six
months, a money market mutual fund is a good idea. You will get
regular interest payments, and you can buy and sell them as readily
as any other mutual fund. All of the major mutual fund families
offer money market funds.
</P>
<P>
   HOW DO I DEAL WITH THE STRESS?
</P>
<P>
   You can make sure your investments are diversified. If more than
5 percent of your money is in one stock, for example, you can
reduce your risk by selling some shares.
</P>
<P>
   Another technique is to focus on your long-term goals, not on
your short-term performance. That should help cut the temptations
of greed or fear. You might want to cut back on the number of times
you check on the prices of your investments. The more frequently
you look at the stock tables, the more likely you are to think you
ought to do something about those numbers.
</P>
<P>
   HOW MUCH RISK IS TOO MUCH?
</P>
<P>
   Everyone must answer that question for himself. One clue is
whether your investments keep you nervous all the time. One way to
test yourself is to imagine what would happen to your portfolio in
a steep decline. If the idea of a 20 percent drop makes you ill,
for example, you may shift some of your money to low-volatility
investments.
</P>
<P>
   Think also about when you will need the money. If it's within
five years, your investments should not be in stocks to start with.
</P>
<P>
   IS MY RETIREMENT PLAN SAFE?
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 74 years, large-company stocks have returned 11.4
percent a year. Chop that up into five-year periods, and the
chances of losing money are only one in 10. If you are years away
from retirement, the higher returns of stocks may be more
significant than the risk of losing principal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's long-term money,'' said Jan Holman, a market strategist
for American Express. ``If you're investing regularly, as you
should be, you're doing exactly the right thing. You should keep on
doing it, and hold on to what you have.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IF I'M RETIRING IN SIX MONTHS?
</P>
<P>
   A retiree should have one to two years worth of expenses in
cash, certificates of deposit or other readily available
investments. ``That's the position you want to be in,'' said
Holman. ``It gives you time to let the rest of your portfolio
recover and begin working for you again.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wouldn't recommend wholesale selling,'' she added. ``I'd
wait at least until Tuesday to see what happens. Monday is going to
be the land of margin calls.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT INVESTMENTS FOR MY KIDS' COLLEGE EXPENSES?
</P>
<P>
   How old are your kids? If they are close to college age, you
probably want the money in stable investments, such as certificates
of deposit. If they are pre-teens, you've got more flexibility. You
can consider staying with the usually higher returns from stocks,
despite the higher risks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
