<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a page and a half stories and graphics
on Friday's dramatic stock market fall.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks went into free fall on Friday as
investors had to digest surprisingly bad news on inflation and the
fear of higher interest rates. The beleaguered Nasdaq index plunged
a near record 10 percent while the Dow Jones industrial average and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell more than 5 percent each. The
fall ended the worst week ever for the Nasdaq composite. Almost no
company survived unscathed. All 30 stocks in the Dow fell while all
but 16 stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 index were down. The impact of the
decline is even greater because it comes on the back of several
weeks of wild daily market swings and the plunge of the Nasdaq
earlier this week into bear market territory. By Jonathan
Fuerbringer and Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics and photo NYT19.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Floyd Norris looks at the
relationship between the stock market and the economy as a whole
and the implications of Friday's big market losses.
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-LOSSES (Mountain View, Calif.) _ Caught in the capricious
swings of a volatile stock market, HearMe, an Internet company, has
had a remarkable ride since it went public a year ago. But nothing
compares to the last week. Last April, the day the company went
public at $18, its stock jumped to $51 before settling at $36. But
its chief executive, Paul Matteucci, son of a butcher and a man
with street-wise sensibilities, politely declines to acknowledge
the opening-day peak. But those opening-day numbers seem a distant
memory. With the Nasdaq ebbing into bear territory, HearMe's stock,
at $20 a week ago, went into free fall this week, closing at $12 on
Thursday and trading as low as $7.50 on Friday. No matter that one
analyst says HearMe, which makes software for voice chat over the
Internet, is clearly a stronger company than it was a year ago.
Faced with volatility that makes or breaks fortunes in a heartbeat
and for no easily discernable reason, employees and executives in
the high tech industry have found creative ways to cope with what
they cannot control. By Matt Richtel. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ For weeks the accelerating inflation
rate was confined to gasoline and energy, but in March it spread to
other areas of the American economy, the government reported
yesterday. This suggests that the robust demand generated by the
stock market had finally given business the leverage to raise
prices and make them stick. The announcement of the inflation
breakthrough _ in the form of an 0.7 percent increase in the
Consumer Price Index _ came from the Labor Department an hour
before the stock markets opened, and contributed to the huge
sell-off. By Louis Uchitelle. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
