<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-COWBOYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Season hasn't started, and Cowboys already are behind
 &HT;    By Rick Cantu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ By the time the Washington Redskins rake in two
of college football's elite players in today's NFL draft, Jerry
Jones and the Dallas Cowboys' scouting staff will just be rolling
out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a bench-mark day for the Redskins. With the second
and third picks of the first round, they are expected to take two
of the following: Penn State linebacker LaVar Arrington, Penn State
defensive end Courtney Brown, Alabama offensive tackle Chris
Samuels and Florida State wide receiver Peter Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   Any combination of those players will be a winning hand for
35-year-old Daniel Snyder, the fiery and controversial owner of the
Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 miles away in Valley Ranch, the braintrust of the
Cowboys will be watching the clock, wondering who will be available
with the 49th pick. With no first-round choice in their possession,
it's going to be a long day for the boys in blue and silver.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, the Redskins officially will surpass the
Cowboys in overall talent and potential.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins represent Snyder _ young, aggressive, hungry. The
Cowboys represent Jones, whose glory days have gone by.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, the Cowboys traded their first-round pick for
Seattle wide receiver Joey Galloway, who, with the possible
exception of Warrick, is better than any receiver coming out of
college.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway is a good addition for Dallas. Combined with Rocket
Ismail, the Cowboys have one of the best receiver tandems in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   If Dallas receives a healthy contribution from receivers Jason
Tucker, former Texas Longhorn Wane McGarity and former Tennessee
tight end Jackie Harris, the Cowboys will be fun to watch on
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal is to keep up with the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   With slick maneuvering the past two years, former Washington
general manager Charley Casserley _ now with Houston's expansion
franchise _ found a way to give the Redskins two of the top three
picks this year. One came last season when New Orleans Coach Mike
Ditka struck a deal with the Redskins to ensure Ricky Williams
would become a Saint.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you very much, said the Redskins, who had no interest in
Williams anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Washington slid down a spot in the 1999 draft, took Georgia
cornerback Champ Bailey, and now is in line to pick one of Penn
State's All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   When Snyder gained ownership of the Redskins, he fired people in
almost every department, the first indication he would do whatever
it takes to build a winner. Although his team won the NFC East,
Snyder was steamed because the Redskins lost twice to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   That might not happen again soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins made another good move this spring by signing
future Hall-of-Fame defensive end Bruce Smith. He lends leadership
for a team that is this close to becoming a real Super Bowl
contender.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Redskins made Jeff George the most expensive
insurance policy in the league. He will be a backup to Brad Johnson
_ at least for now _ and earn $18.5 million over four years. Daniel
Snyder will not let money become an issue in building his empire.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has had a similar attitude in Dallas, but this year he's
playing with empty pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway will be a good player in Dallas, but he's only
compensation for Michael Irvin, who will never play again because
of a spinal injury. Fullback Daryl Johnston is only a memory. Deion
Sanders no longer will be seen in prime time, at least not in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas does not have a choice in the first and third rounds
today. Jones hinted this week the Cowboys might trade their
second-round pick to gain additional picks in the late rounds. If
Jones can find an impact player after the second round, more power
to him.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Cowboys are plugging holes to stay above
water. They re-signed linebacker Dexter Coakley and safety George
Teague. They picked up cornerback Ryan McNeil in free agency to
replace Sanders. Former Indy quarterback Paul Justin replaces the
departed Jason Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   For every step the Cowboys take forward, they take one back.
</P>
<P>
   By many accounts, the Cowboys will use their first pick on a
cornerback Perhaps Tennessee's Dwayne Goodrich or Florida State's
Mario Edwards will still be on the board.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys draft a second-round cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins draft Arrington and Samuels.
</P>
<P>
   Case closed. The balance of power in the NFC East has shifted.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Rick Cantu at rcantu(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
