</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER-PRICE REPORT RENEWS FEARS OF INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: For list of market-related stories, see MARKET-ADVISORY-NYT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For weeks the accelerating inflation rate was confined to
gasoline and energy, but in March it spread to other areas of the
U.S. economy, the government reported Friday. This suggested that
the robust demand generated by the stock market had finally given
business the power to raise prices and make them stick.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the inflation breakthrough _ in the form of
an 0.7 percent increase in the Consumer Price Index _ came from the
Labor Department an hour before the stock markets opened, and
contributed to the huge sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markets move on emotion,'' said Richard D. Rippe, chief
economist at Prudential Securities. ``They were nervous coming into
the trading day, and traders seized on the CPI as justification for
continuing to be bearish.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief concern is that rising inflation will encourage the
Federal Reserve Board to raise interest rates by even more than the
quarter-point increases that Alan Greenspan, the Fed's chairman,
has promised over the next two or three months to slow the economy
and ease stock prices down. Rich stock portfolios financed much of
the spending that has created so much demand and helped to push up
the inflation rate.
</P>
<P>
   Rising energy prices made the biggest contribution to the
increase in the overall inflation rate, the largest one-month jump
since last April. Gasoline prices alone rose 11 percent, to $1.59.4
a gallon, on average, the highest level _ ignoring inflation _ ever
recorded by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   What caught the market's attention, however, was the ``core''
inflation rate, which measures all price increases except those for
energy and food, which are considered too volatile to provide a
clear picture of inflation. This core rate rose 0.4 percent in
March, double the monthly increase over most of the past two years.
Not since January 1995 has the core rate risen so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to draw any grand conclusions from this core
number,'' said Edward Yardeni, chief economist at Deutsche Bank
Alex. Brown. ``Whether it signals an inflection point or is simply
the result of a number of aberrations, no one can say yet. I am
more in the aberration camp.''
</P>
<P>
   The increases were fairly widespread. Furnishing, renovating and
repairing a home, for example, grew more costly in March, perhaps
because families cashed in stock or borrowed against their
portfolios to upgrade their homes. Hotels and resort rates also
rose smartly. ``You have a lot of people with a lot of money, and
they apparently want to take time off and vacation,'' said Patrick
Jackman, a senior economist in the bureau division that produces
the price index.
</P>
<P>
   Rising wages in these industries may also have helped to nudge
up the inflation rate, analysts said. Certainly labor costs played
a role in March's 0.5 percent increase in medical-care costs. Most
of that was a result of higher doctors' fees, although hospital
charges also rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tight labor markets are almost certainly beginning to have
some impact on consumer prices,'' said Chris Varvares, a partner at
Macroeconomic Advisers LLC, in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Airline fares jumped 4.6 percent in March, pushed up by the cost
of fuel, airlines say. And tobacco prices jumped, primarily because
of increases in cigarette taxes, especially a 55-cent-a-pack rise
in New York state. And vehicle prices rose, mainly because General
Motors canceled a $500 rebate on most of its vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the still-booming stock market helped to sustain the
demand for new cars, but if this week's sell-off continues, auto
sales are likely to fall, analysts said, prompting car companies to
step up discounts, and generally easing the pressure on prices.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Everything could change in the next few weeks,'' said Edward
Hyman, president of ISI Group Inc., a Wall Street investment firm.
``The market is getting crushed, and if demand weakens with the
market, pricing power is going to be crushed, too. This morning the
report I got from our auto survey showed that luxury car sales in
the New York City area were as good as they could possibly be. That
cannot last without a strong stock market, and the car companies
will respond with discounts.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of 1999, the core inflation rate was only 1.9 percent,
but with last month's jump the average over the previous 12 months
moved up to 2.4 percent. When food and energy are added back, the
12-month moving average in the overall price index has gone from
2.7 percent in December to 3.7 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   That is well above the inflation target of roughly 2 percent
that has guided Fed policy in recent years. If the higher inflation
rate endures, the Fed will almost certainly continue to push up
rates, probably by a quarter of a point at a time at its
policy-making meetings every six weeks. The next is May 16.
</P>
<P>
   But if stock prices keep falling or fail to rebound, that would
play a big role in Fed thinking. Greenspan has said he would cut
rates if he thought a market sell-off was endangering the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that another Fed rate increase is no longer
as inevitable as it seemed early this week,'' Yardeni said. ``The
Fed does not like to act in periods of market uncertainty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
