<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7239 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WASHINGTON-PROTEST-HN     04-14 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-PROTEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WASHINGTON POLICE PLAN TO AVOID VIOLENCE OF SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vowing to avoid the violence that erupted last year
in Seattle, police in the nation's capital took control of the
city's sidewalks and streets Friday to thwart demonstrators' plans
to block traffic and shut down a joint meeting of the International
Monetary Fund and World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan police Chief Charles Ramsey promised to give the
protesters ``a chance to speak'' but insisted that the IMF and
World Bank have a ``constitutional'' right to hold their meeting,
scheduled for Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These protesters have no right to come to our city and chain
themselves together and block traffic, nor do they have the right
to stop anybody from going into or out of a building,'' Ramsey told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Han Shan, a spokesman for Mobilization for Global Justice, an
umbrella group that has helped organize the protests, pledged that
the Sunday and Monday demonstrations would be nonviolent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for trouble, but we want our message to be
heard,'' he said in a small park across the street from the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Shan said ``a large number'' of protesters were receiving
special training Friday for the protests. He would not detail the
tactics they plan to use, but said, ``It could be a very
interesting couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 10,000 activists are expected to stage sit-ins and
create human barricades to try prevent IMF and World Bank delegates
from reaching their meetings Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning a dump truck deposited four tons of manure
outside a World Bank building. Driven by a man dressed in a cow
costume, the rented truck was festooned with signs saying ``World
Bank: Meat Stinks'' to protest bank loans to developing countries
where animal research is conducted. Police quickly cleared the
scene and arrested the driver and his passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank provides long-term loans for economic development
projects in poor countries while the IMF arranges short-term loans
directly to countries in sudden economic crisis _ often imposing
severe austerity measures on them in return for the aid.
</P>
<P>
   The diverse groups of protesters are also calling on the lending
organizations to push for greater environmental protection,
workers' rights and wider distribution of wealth, especially
through debt forgiveness for poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent protesters from blocking delegates from attending the
meeting, police have closed most streets around the World Bank and
IMF buildings, allowing only pedestrians and authorized vehicles in
the four-block area.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, police have set up barriers to allow four entry and
exit points around the lending institutions' buildings for
delegates' cars. So if protesters want to block vehicles from
entering or leaving, they must cut off all four roads around the
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it gives the cars four ways (in and) out instead of
one, which makes the protesters' job a lot harder,'' Metropolitan
Police Sgt. Michael Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Metropolitan police, joined by U.S. Park Police and
federal security officers, stood on downtown street corners as
other officers patrolled the area by car and bike. Several police
vans and buses also were parked around the IMF and World Bank
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they hoped that the arrest Wednesday night of seven
people who were delivering special materials to be used for
blockading streets would help keep the roads clear Sunday and
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The materials _ metal and plastic tubes, chains and chicken wire
_ could be used to construct so-called ``lock boxes'' or ``sleeping
dragons'' that protesters use to chain themselves together to shut
down streets.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, protestors had driven two vehicles from the
Maryland suburbs to D.C. with about 300 tubes and other equipment,
which police seized.
</P>
<P>
   Used in the protests last December against the World Trade
Organization in Seattle, the tubes allow demonstrators, linking
arms inside the pipes, to form human chains. The tubes are wrapped
in chicken wire, covered with tar and overlaid with duct tape _ all
designed to foil police efforts to saw through them.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey admitted that the tubes are ``very effective'' but said
his department has formed a special unit that includes
firefighters. The unit has equipment that can extricate victims
from car wrecks or any protesters using the lock boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is prevent what happened in Seattle,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Security at the White House also was extremely tight. Uniformed
Secret Service guards patrolled the front lawn of the mansion,
ready to grab anyone who was able to climb the 10-foot iron fence.
</P>
<P>
   Park Service police patrolled the sidewalk in front of the fence
and Metropolitan police maintained a large force on Pennsylvania
Avenue and streets surrounding the White House compound, located
two long blocks from the World Bank and IMF buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Police also patrolled Potomac River bridges linking Northern
Virginia with D.C. The patrol was designed to thwart any effort to
blockade the spans during rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Last November and December in Seattle, protestors, many of whom
are in the nation's capital this week, shut down the opening
ceremonies of the World Trade Organization's annual meeting. The
Seattle demonstrations, televised worldwide, quickly turned
violent. Police sprayed tear gas and fired rubber pellets at many
peaceful protesters but failed to stop window-smashing and looting
by a relatively small group of vandals less than a block away.
Damage was estimated at several million dollars, and 600 people
were arrested. Seattle police Chief Norm Stamper, criticized for
his handling of the protests, resigned. To avoid a similar event,
Washington's Metropolitan Police Department has been preparing for
the World Banks-IMF protests for months. Nearly 1,500 officers took
a special daylong course to train for the demonstrations. They
watched videos of how Seattle police lost control and practiced
scenarios such as how to handle 5,000 protesters trying to block a
major street.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of officers from federal and other local area law
enforcement agencies are standing by in case they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Police here also purchased $1 million worth of riot gear for the
Sunday-Monday demonstrations, including helmets with neck
protectors and arm, chest and shin guards. In addition to service
weapons, officers are carrying gas masks. Some will bear arms that
can shoot rubber bullets or deliver tear gas. However, officers are
forbidden from launching any tear gas without orders from Ramsey or
Metropolitan Police Executive Assistant Chief Terrance Gainer.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the police precautions, protesters have managed to
cause minor disruptions around the city such as the dump-truck
incident Friday morning, which was staged by People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
