<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS15-C     04-14 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-FALCONS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons low on selections, options
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the NFL had an emergency room for wounded teams,
the Atlanta Falcons might be there today.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves and the Falcons are still ailing from last
year's wreck of a draft-day trade.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that deal, Reeves, who repeatedly says a team
must build through the NFL draft, will be out of action as the
first round rolls by with his team on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   And the bleeding gets worse.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven players on the Falcons' roster pre-date Reeves'
arrival in 1997, but he won't be re-making the roster much this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   His team has six picks, one each in rounds two through seven, a
drop from the nine choices that Reeves had in each of his first
three years as coach.
</P>
<P>
   The damaging blow came on draft day last year, when Reeves
traded the team's first-round pick in this draft for Baltimore's
second-round pick in that one.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons used that pick to select tight end Reggie Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly caught eight passes, and the Ravens own this draft's fifth
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, don't expect the Falcons to trade up from 37th
overall in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of things usually cost you a lot,'' Reeves said.
``We paid dearly last year. But if there's something that would
help the team, we'd consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL's salary cap requires that teams keep a lot of draft
choices, because youngplayers cost less.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, 20 of the 27 players the Falcons have drafted in
three years under Reeves are on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end O.J. Santiago, linebacker Henri Crockett and guard
Calvin Collins are starters from the 1997 draft. From 1998,
linebacker Keith Brooking _ a first-round choice _ and right tackle
Ephraim Salaam start.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Patrick Kerney, the team's first-round pick in
1999, is expected to start. And Bob Hallen, a second-rounder in
1998, might start.
</P>
<P>
   If so, then more than a quarter, seven out of 27, drafted under
Reeves would be starting. That percentage is near the NFL average.
``It's even more important now (that a team draft well), because in
this system ... you can't sign all your veterans,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On-the-job training has gone by the wayside. If you had the
choice, you would rather keep your core players and work young guys
in slowly, but that's not the way it works.''
</P>
<P>
   What Reeves has done is similar to what has happened to two
rivals in the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Saints, perennial cellar dwellers, and the
defending Super Bowl champion St. Louis Rams also hired new coaches
in 1997. Each team has just six players from before then.
</P>
<P>
   On the Saints, four are former first-round picks, and one is a
former fifth-rounder. The Rams have two former first-rounders, two
players from the second round and one from the third.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, teams get a bigger contribution from better draft
choices. It is another reason that Reeves is feeling the pain in
the 2000 draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons drafted only three of the seven players who preceded
Reeves to the team _ left tackle Bob Whitfield (first round in
1992), running back Jamal Anderson (seventh round in 1994) and
defensive tackle Travis Hall (sixth round in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Terence Mathis, kicker Morten Andersen, punter Dan
Stryzinski came as free agents. Middle linebacker Jessie Tuggle was
undrafted out of college in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, just two players who started for St. Louis in the
Super Bowl, defensive end Kevin Carter and since-departed right
tackle Fred Miller, came out of the 1995 and 1996 drafts.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams got more out of recent draft choices, but they also
added vital pieces in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Marshall Faulk was acquired by trade, and
quarterback Kurt Warner was salvaged as a free agent a couple years
ago. Defensive tackle D'Marco Farr was undrafted out of college in
'94.
</P>
<P>
   There is no one way to build a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Rams' 41 draft choices the past five years, just 18 _ 44
percent _ are with the team. Nine of them start.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, the AFC champion, drafted 45 players the past five
years, and 30 of them are with the team, including nine starters.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two of the 38 players the Falcons drafted in the past
five years _ 58 percent _ are still with the team. Eight of them
start.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the quality not only of those eight but also of players
added as free agents and through trades that counts most.
</P>
<P>
   Free agency affords teams a way to correct for its draft
blunders _ at a price. It all comes down to personnel evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question (that) that's correct,'' Reeves said.
``Because if (draft choices) don't perform, they'll eventually be
gone. But you'd rather not go (the free-agent) route; it's not good
business. You'd rather do well in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
