<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE KINGS' A CROWNING EXAMPLE OF A BOLD, ENERGETIC MOVIE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `THREE KINGS'
</P>
<P>
   Among the many movies more deserving of a best-picture Oscar
nomination than clunky ``The Cider House Rules,'' none stands
taller than ``Three Kings,'' a bold, energizing triumph from
writer-director David O. Russell.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't your typical war movie, but then, the Gulf War wasn't
a typical war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Kings'' starts as it ends: with survivors frantically
regrouping.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunism amid the mayhem takes many forms, and for Sgt. Maj.
Gates (George Clooney) this means leading some soldiers (Mark
Wahlberg, Ice Cube, Spike Jonze) on an unauthorized mission.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal? Gold. They've pinpointed bullion that Sadam Hussein
stole from Kuwait and hoarded in desert bunkers.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking it, they're drawn into a protective role for citizens
subject to slaughter by vengeful Iraqi soldiers. Greed then wars
with the demands of human survival.
</P>
<P>
   This strongly acted, politically charged adventure is riddled
with as many laughs as bullets, though the humor comes in weird,
twisted ways.
</P>
<P>
   With Simpsons dolls on the hoods of jeeps and jeans and cell
phones among the loot, ``Three Kings'' is spurred by the madness of
modern war in a world grown smaller through media scrutiny and
cross-cultural pollination.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Warner, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE INSIDER'
</P>
<P>
   Filmgoers avoided this Oscar contender because it sounded like
the world's greatest ``duh?'': A man (Russell Crowe) who was fired
by a tobacco giant blows the whistle to ``60 Minutes'' about the
company's cover-up of tobacco's harmfulness.
</P>
<P>
   But the actual true story is far more complex, as are the media
machinations involving ``60 Minutes''' failure to at first follow
through on the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider'' features a remarkable performance by Crowe as
the lonely, courageous David facing a corporate Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   But it's often sidetracked by the star-powered showboating of Al
Pacino as a ``60 Minutes'' field producer.
</P>
<P>
   Pacino may be a great actor who commands every scene, but that's
the trouble: He gets too many scenes, and the movie shouldn't be
about him. Rather, it should be about Crowe's Jeffrey Wigand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Insider'' shifts so much toward a CBS focus that it's
surprising the network balked at its creation. If anything, the
film lionizes ``60 Minutes'' by presenting it as a journalistic
paragon (albeit a flawed one) so far beyond any other that the New
York Times looks minor league.
</P>
<P>
   On the dark side _ or, at least, a self-protective one _ is
Christopher Plummer as newsman Mike Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Vain and bullying, Plummer is great, but even he is less
villainous and more sensibly pragmatic than the film allows, once
you consider the hysterical preachiness of Pacino's endless tirades
about media integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-minus
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Touchstone, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $32.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THREE TO TANGO'
</P>
<P>
   This comedy of confusion hinges on the premise that architect
Matthew Perry is misconstrued as gay, but its snickering,
embarrassed approach toward sexuality is distinctly retro.
</P>
<P>
   Perry and partner Oliver Platt hope to win a big contract from a
philandering, jealous tycoon (Dylan McDermott). While dangling the
carrot, the businessman picks Perry as an allegedly safe companion
for his mistress (Neve Campbell).
</P>
<P>
   When Perry falls for her but can't tell her he's straight,
predictable complications ensue.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking to his wry and hapless ``Friends'' schtick, Perry tries
too hard, but at least he doesn't play gay with silly mannerisms.
Campbell and McDermott have no discernible characters to play.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the film does have snappy repartee, amusing turns by Platt
and two rival architects (Bob Balaban and John C. McGinley) and an
end-credit wrap-up that's a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-minus.
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Warner, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $24.98
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `SUPERSTAR'
</P>
<P>
   Among the movies spawned by ``Saturday Night Live'' sketches,
this one is traditional.
</P>
<P>
   That's not a good thing. It means it's fitfully funny but
doesn't play well at feature length.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Shannon portrays Catholic schoolgirl Mary Katherine
Gallagher, who's prone to bizarre mannerisms and pines for a jock
(Will Ferrell). She tries to become a ``superstar'' to catch his
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon tries to make her troubled character perversely
endearing, but she's inconsistent. The same girl who innocently
longs for her first kiss has lascivious encounters with trees and
violently assails her rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Also unfunny in view of recent school tragedies is the way
``Superstar'' makes light of kids' cruelty to each other. In real
life, this is serious business; here, it's a running joke.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-plus
</P>
<P>
   1999, PG-13, Paramount, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.99
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `ARISTOCATS' ON DVD
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Paris-set ``The Aristocats'' just made its DVD debut
($29.99) and also has returned to VHS ($22.99).
</P>
<P>
   Tapes include a ``Fun With Music'' booklet. Discs offer that
booklet and, much like ``Tarzan,'' an interactive read-along
feature, a trivia game and the theatrical trailer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
