u a BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0415-COX     04-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0415-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S RELATIVES LAUNCH NEW LEGAL ATTACK
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A day after a tense showdown and a surprise reprieve,
the fight over Elian Gonzalez boiled Friday with a new legal attack
and a simmering debate over a controversial videotape of the boy
made by his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the child's Florida relatives opened a new front in
their legal war, filing a motion in a Washington, D.C. federal
court seeking to block Elian's return to Cuba until the government
certifies that the communist island nation is in compliance with
the U.N. Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   If the 6-year-old shipwreck survivor is returned to Cuba, he
``would face the risk of being persecuted for having sought asylum
in the United States,'' lawyers for Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro
Gonzalez, wrote in their pleadings.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the matter was set for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a different court, lawyers for the Justice
Department stepped up their attack, asking the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta to order the Miami family to turn the
boy over to his father until the court rules in a lawsuit stemming
from the case.
</P>
<P>
   In their filings, government lawyers told the court that Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, has promised not to return with his
son to Cuba until a hearing, now set for May 11 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear if the Atlanta court would rule on the matter
over the weekend or wait until early next week.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, tensions subsided, a marked contrast to Thursday when
the Miami relatives defied an order by Attorney General Janet Reno
to hand the boy over to be reunited with his father. Fears that
federal marshals would come for Elian prompted thousands of Cuban
exiles to pack the Little Havana neighborhood near the Florida
family's house, with many vowing to form a human chain to stop the
removal of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Torrential rains on Friday kept the crowds much smaller,
although more than 100 people huddled under a large blue tarp and
dozens of umbrellas late in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father remained in the Washington area Friday, where he
has been living at the home of a top Cuban diplomat since arriving
in the United States April 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Joan Brown-Campbell, former head of the National
Council of Churches and a key supporter, told reporters that
Gonzalez has been unable to speak with his son for several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Miami family has complete control over access to his son
and that's real hard for him to take,'' she said. ``He has tried to
talk to Elian by telephone numerous times, three times in my
presence. He gets an answering machine that's full.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez reportedly was seething with anger over a videotape
made by his Miami relatives showing his son defiantly telling his
father he doesn't want to return to Cuba. The family released the
tape to a Spanish-language television network early Thursday, and
it quickly became a hot topic of conversation on television and
radio programs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed on NBC's ``Today'' program Friday, Immigration and
Naturalization Commissioner Doris Meissner called the tape ``deeply
disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., also interviewed on the show,
was outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unconscionable that they would use that child in this
way,'' she said. ``The child was brainwashed. They're doing to him
what they're accusing Castro of planning to do to him.''
</P>
<P>
   A family attorney, Spencer Eig, denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This family was tired, frightened and insulted by the constant
badgering and threats of INS,'' Eig said. ``How is that exploiting
him?''
</P>
<P>
   The escalating rhetoric seemed to dim hopes that a compromise
might be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant to take the boy without the family's cooperation, Reno
has offered to take both sides to a secure, neutral location where
they could live in separate quarters for one or two weeks, sharing
custody of Elian while they work out their differences.
</P>
<P>
   But the two sides can't agree on who would have custody of Elian
at the start _ and the end _ of such a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports on Friday that the government has
prepared a plan to extract the boy from the Little Havana home if
the Miami relatives don't cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take action in a way that's appropriate when we're
ready,'' Meissner said, noting that the family is now in violation
of the law by ignoring Reno's order.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Eig responded that the family would stand aside and not
interfere if the government takes Elian, but they also would not
assist in the act or take the boy elsewhere to be handed over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This family will not be the deportation officers for the
INS,'' he said. ``They won't relieve INS of its moral
responsibility in enforcing this order.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams can be reached by e-mail at:
mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
