<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: THERE IS NO THIRD SENATE VOTE ON BUDGET COMPROMISE.
INFORMATION UNAVAILABLE AT TIME OF PRESS. SEE NEXT WEEK'S VOTE
CHART. WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 227.
WASHINGTON, April 14 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: BUDGET
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on April 7 approved, 51 to 45, a five-year, $1.8
trillion budget plan for fiscal year 2001. The measure, which would
cut taxes $150 billion over five years, would provide spending for
defense, education and prescription drug benefits for Medicare
recipients. Supporters said the bill ensures fiscal discipline
while freeing up money for tax relief. Opponents said the tax cut
was too large. A ``yes'' vote favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: TAX
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Tuesday failed to advance a plan that would repeal
the federal gasoline tax. In a 56 to 43 vote, the plan failed to
receive the 60 votes needed for a floor vote. Supporters said the
plan would help consumers by reducing gas prices at the pump.
Opponents said the plan would jeopardize important highway and
transportation projects. A ``yes'' vote favors the plan.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER:
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y Y
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y Y
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: GUNS
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 358 to 60, a plan to offer $100
million in financial incentives for states that impose a five-year
minimum sentence on people who use guns while committing violent
crimes or drug trafficking offenses. The spending, which requires
that states implement a public awareness campaign against gun
violence, would be offered to applying states over a five year
period. Supporters said the plan would dramatically reduce gun
violence. Opponents said the grant was too vague and smaller than
what is needed to reduce violence nearly one year after the
shootings at Columbine High School. A ``yes'' vote favors the plan.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: PROPERTY
</P>
<P>
   The House on Tuesday approved, 424 to 0, a plan that would make
it harder for the federal government to seize property from people
suspected of drug-dealing and other crimes. Supporters said the
plan would protect innocent people victimized by wrongful seizures.
There were no opponents to the bill. A ``yes'' vote favors the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: AGREEMENT
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 220 to 208, a five-year, $1.8
trillion budget compromise for fiscal year 2001 that finalized
plans already approved in the House and Senate. The measure would
offer tax cuts of at least $150 billion over five years, and as
much as $215 billion if the economy continues to grow. The budget
also allocates spending for defense, education and prescription
drug benefits for Medicare recipients. Supporters said the budget
plan would help eliminate the national debt, provide needed tax
relief, and boost education, defense, and health research spending.
Opponents said the budget plan offered large tax cuts at the
expense of important social programs. A ``yes'' vote favors the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
