<HEADER>
A7253 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FREAKNIK-DEAD-COX     04-14 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAKNIK-DEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freaknik leaves Atlanta cold
 &HT;    By John McCosh
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Freaknik didn't go Underground Atlanta this year. It
didn't go to Lenox Square mall. And it wasn't to be found along
Peachtree Street.
</P>
<P>
   The college students who clogged Atlanta's streets with
party-mobiles for most of the past decade apparently are sunning
themselves on the beaches of Galveston, Tex., this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place used to be packed three years ago,'' said Keith
Bruce, who arrived Friday with about 20 friends at Lenox Square's
food court from Minneapolis, Minn. ``Now just look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   What he saw in the mall's atrium Friday afternoon was a mix of
serious shoppers dressed for business, window shoppers pushing
strollers and a few groups of bored-looking young men in search of
something to do.
</P>
<P>
   If Atlanta wasn't a ghost town Friday, it was about 100,000
students short of Freaknik's peak in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Fleeting signs of Freaknik, conventionally known as Black
College Spring Break, included vendors selling Freaknik 2000
T-shirts. One shirt declared ``It's all about the Benjamins.'' But
not many $100 bills appeared to be changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   Underground Atlanta, also a Freaknik hotspot in previous years,
was fairly busy for a Friday afternoon, with older tourists and
families strolling through. Security guards remarked that even
Hooters, one of the few public places where flesh was showing in
downtown Atlanta, didn't attract a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Galveston indicate that Freaknik hasn't
disappeared, only relocated across the Mississippi. With a promoter
funding security and clean up, the city is expecting somewhere
between 250,000 and 500,000 people to converge on a 50-block
stretch along a sea wall for an organized party scheduled to last
all weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
