u i BC-REDCROSS-ISRAEL-515&AMP;A     04-14 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDCROSS-ISRAEL-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EMBLEM FOR RED CROSS WOULD ENABLE ISRAEL TO JOIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The Red Cross has decided to adopt a new emblem, in
addition to its red cross and red crescent, to clear the way for
Israel to join after 50 years of exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, taken at a two-day summit of governments and Red
Cross representatives, followed pressures from the American Red
Cross to admit Israel's equivalent relief-services organization,
the Magen David Adom (Red Shield of David), whose symbol is a red
six-pointed star.
</P>
<P>
   At its founding in 1949, the International Committee for the Red
Cross adopted three symbols _ the red cross, the red crescent, and
Iran's red lion and sun, which was dropped in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross has staunchly resisted adding new national or
religious symbols, insisting that each new member adopt the red
cross or the crescent. Some members are said to have specifically
resisted the entry of Israel into the movement.
</P>
<P>
   The new emblem under consideration is a red diamond. Although
details have yet to be worked out, it is envisioned now that
Israel's emblem, like those of any other national society that
wanted to change its symbol, would be an inset in a corner of the
diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Organizations could also use a combination of symbols, which is
now forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   Although it did not block the plan, the American Red Cross
argued that it was unnecessary, because the International Committee
of the Red Cross, which is responsible for civilians in war zones,
already has the authority to admit Israel's group without the
drawn-out process that approving a new emblem will entail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a consensus _ minus one _ to proceed,'' said Lawrence
Eagleburger, a former top U.S. diplomat, speaking on behalf of the
American Red Cross. He said it was ``morally wrong'' to exclude
Israel's relief organization. ``We've fought this for years. It's
gone on long enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To make the point, the American Red Cross last month withheld $5
million in membership dues to the Swiss-run ICRC and an additional
$350,000 to the International Federation of Red Cross and Red
Crescent Societies, which cares for disaster victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Red Cross has to ask itself whether it is
prepared to be as active in a general institution that is doing
things that are improper or not justified,'' Eagleburger said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross, he emphasized, would work, if necessary,
directly with country aid groups in humanitarian emergencies _
raising the possibility of a split in the Red Cross movement, which
now includes 188 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, some Red Cross officials were defiant. ``We're
prepared for a little poverty rather than just doing what they
want,'' said one, who asked not to be identified. These officials
insisted that they must move deliberately to bring all countries on
board to change the emblem and admit Israel, but others argued that
delay would be used to keep Israel out.
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak Lior, an Israeli foreign ministry official attending the
meeting, said it would be up to the country's relief society to
decide whether to accept a new symbol. ``It's not an easy
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Israeli relief group did not send a representative to the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the emblem controversy is concern that if Palestine is
declared a state, its relief group _ which uses the red crescent _
will quickly become an official Red Cross member while Israel
remains on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross said it would hold the ICRC president,
Jakob Kellenberger, ``to the promise he made to the American Red
Cross and members of the United States Congress to invoke a safety
net if this diplomatic approach fails to grant immediate membership
to MDA (Magen David Adom) by the end of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
