<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW-WEALTH15-COX     04-14 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-WEALTH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market dive hasn't hampered spending by wealthy, retailers say
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For wealthy consumers, flush with stock-market gains
but hammered by Friday's sell-off, the hangover is probably just
setting in.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the stock market's recent jitters haven't had much
impact on purchases of pricey homes, boats, cars and jewelry, said
Roger Tutterow, co-director of Kennesaw State University's
Econometrics Center. But if it lasts, ``it could have a significant
impact on consumer spending.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that the market is eroding away. ``We haven't seen a
correction of this duration and intensity. Option babies are
depending on the stock market to make payments on their
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, retailers say other factors are making it too early to
tell if people are scaling back luxury purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other things interrupting people's schedules _
school vacations, Easter, Passover _ and we have to take account of
them,'' said real estate agent Bill Kramer, whose listings at Metro
Brokers Better Homes and Gardens include houses priced from
$475,000 to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people definitely will think twice before sticking their
necks out,'' he added. ``There was all that euphoria; people with
lots of money. Some of that has eroded, but others still make a lot
of money. So far, no one has specifically told me that they were
going to delay buying.''
</P>
<P>
   But even before Friday, sliding stock prices had undermined the
plans of at least one potential home buyer in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Vawter of Jenny Pruitt &AMP; Associates said he had a house
under contract that was to have closed in June at just under $1
million. ``The other agent said the buyer's stock had gone down and
he couldn't close.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely will be people who hold up decisions to see
how things go. In (the summer of) 1998, when the market tanked,
sales slowed down,'' said Kramer. ``The same probably will happen
now, and April and May sales won't be as much as March.''
</P>
<P>
   Early April is also a slow time of year for luxury auto sales
because of the tax season, said several Atlanta-area dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to get their tax returns in and get their payments
behind them,'' said Bill Florence, general sales manager at
Hennessy Lexus in Atlanta. ``Certainly a lot of people would have
to be looking at the stock market, and if they had a lot of losses,
they would be delaying some purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   He quickly added, ``So far our sales are still on track for our
objective this month. If (the market) continues to go down, down,
down, it will certainly have a bearing on our business. But
hopefully we'll see a rebound and that would (encourage) people to
buy big ticket items.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is a slowdown in sales, it would most likely be
for entry-level vehicles, said David Smith, general sales manager
of Atlanta Classic Cars, a Mercedes-Benz dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers of entry-level luxury cars tend to be new-money people,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very, very affluent are usually not going to change their
car style,'' he said. ``If the chairman of Home Depot takes a hit,
he's not going to start driving a Honda.''
</P>
<P>
   At Troncalli Jaguar, sales manager Bill Clark said next week
will give a glimpse of the market's influence on business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business will likely pick up next Monday, Tuesday or
Wednesday,'' he said. But he conceded that much of the Jaguar
clientele is ``pretty heavily tied to the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off one of its best sales totals for March, the boating
sales staff at Brown's Bridge Marine on Lake Lanier is not feeling
the pain of the stock market, said brokerage manager Mark Cochran.
``We've been really very busy'' selling boats $100,000 and up.
</P>
<P>
   One area jeweler that sells pricey items said it may be a while
before they see another nouveau riche customer like the one who
splurged recently on a $30,000 diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Still, customers seem oblivious, perhaps because they were
shopping Friday and not watching stocks tumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen a drop-off,'' said Greg Knox, owner of Knox
Jewelers.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Queen, a manager at D. Geller &AMP; Son, said, ``Traffic has
picked up double today because most customers have already filed
(their taxes).''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Renee DeGross, Tammy
Joyner, David McNaughton and Gene Tharpe contributed to this
article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
