r s BC-FBN-DRAFT-BROWNS-COX     04-14 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BROWNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cleveland may select Brown for defense
 &HT;    By Sean McClelland
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEREA, Ohio _ With talk of trading the No.1 pick in today's
National Football League draft all but dead, the Cleveland Browns
are once again, for the second straight year, on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because they seem to have established a better rapport
with Penn State defensive end Courtney Brown's agent than with
those representing Penn State linebacker LaVar Arrington, the
Browns apparently are set to make Brown the first player chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Team president Carmen Policy remained cryptic late in the week,
saying, ``My feeling is that we will exercise the pick and use it
to select a defensive player.'' Formally eliminated from contention
with those words was Florida State receiver Peter Warrick, once
seen as the likely No.1, but who now could fall to the Cincinnati
Bengals at No.4. Policy, careful not to tip his hand in light of
ongoing contract negotiations with Brown and Arrington, would not
be more specific.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems now that only an overwhelming proposal from the New
York Jets _ the only team with four first-round picks at its
disposal _ or some freak occurrence would dissuade the Browns from
selecting Brown, a 6-foot-5, 270-pounder with 4.58 speed in the 40,
unerring quarterback radar and a wingspan the length of Dikembe
Mutumbo.
</P>
<P>
   Stating the case for retaining the pick rather than dealing it,
Browns general manager Dwight Clark said, ``Talking to people
around the league, it's clear that when you have a chance at a
blue-chip player, which both of these guys are, it's tough to turn
that down.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington is tempting. The Browns love his on-field demeanor, to
say nothing of his incredible athletic ability. But does he want to
play for Cleveland? Questions were raised last week when he
practically advised the Browns to select Brown. Arrington seems to
have his heart set on falling to the Washington Redskins at No.2
and joining a Super Bowl contender.
</P>
<P>
   While Arrington's maturity has been questioned, the biggest
knock on Brown is that he's a bit quiet and might be too nice.
Chatty and charismatic he isn't. However, he has been the best
defensive lineman in college football the past two years, according
to many scouts and draftniks. Some think he can be a better
all-around end than Kevin Carter, who helped the St. Louis Rams win
the Super Bowl. Can he match the impact Jevon Kearse made last
season as a rookie with the Tennessee Titans? That's asking a lot,
but the Browns are also investing a lot and, at this stage of their
development, can't afford to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   They probably made the right choice last year, tabbing Tim Couch
No. 1 and leaving Akili Smith and Ricky Williams on the board.
Couch took over as the starting quarterback in Week 2 and proved
tough, talented and durable. ``We're going through the same
process,'' coach Chris Palmer said. ``And, hopefully, we'll be
right again.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the Browns definitely would be pleased with something
resembling last year's haul, which included five eventual starters
and several other players who stuck around and contributed. They
have 14 total picks. After the No. 1 overall selection, they lead
off every round except the sixth. That pick went to Miami in the
Karim Abdul-Jabbar trade. They have two picks in rounds three,
four, five and six, then four in the seventh and final round.
</P>
<P>
   With the first pick in the second round, No. 32 overall, the
Browns are likely to select the best receiver available. They would
like to take Jerry Porter from West Virginia, but could settle for
Arizona's Dennis Northcutt, who doubles as a return specialist. If
they were to address their crying need for a tight end, Anthony
Becht of West Virginia is almost certain to be there if Miami's
Bubba Franks is not.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle rounds, the Browns aim to address needs at running
back and offensive line. They also are in the market for a big
cornerback, possibly with the intention of moving starting corner
Daylon McCutcheon, one of last year's draft prizes, to nickel back.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Sean McClelland at seanmcclelland(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
