<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-KNIGHT-GARECRUIT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta recruit still headed to Indiana
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The night Indiana coach Bobby Knight made his at-home
visit to Westlake High School forward A.J. Moye, Moye's mother,
Beverly Hines, made a presentation of her own to the legendary
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Hines grabbed her son by his shirt collar, jerked him and looked
at Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `If I'm at a game and I see you touch my son like
this, I'm coming out of the stands, and I'm coming after you,'''
Hines said.
</P>
<P>
   Knight replied, ``And well you should.''
</P>
<P>
   Moye, this year's Mr. Georgia Basketball, has spoken highly of
Knight and his program since signing with Indiana in November. That
position is unchanged, even though a two-man committee of Indiana
trustees investigate former players' allegations of physical and
emotional abuse by Knight. This week, a videotape showed Knight
grabbing former Hoosier Neil Reed by the neck at practice in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did see the footage. I mean, I'm not really too much
worried,'' Moye said from a hotel room in Winston-Salem, N.C.,
where he will play in the ACC/USA Hoops Challenge today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still want to play for Indiana, and I really want to play
for coach Knight. He's really a class act. He showed me a side a
lot of people don't see. He cares about me as a person and not a
ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Moye all but solidified his decision to sign with Indiana after
Knight's home visit in September. One of Moye's friends, Travis
Davenport, died that morning, and Knight was there to comfort him
with encouraging words and a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just supporting A.J.'s decision,'' Hines said. ``When
Bobby Knight was in my home, he was the epitome of warmth. But time
will tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Newton, a former Mays player and current Indiana freshman,
is a friend of Moye, and the two often talked about Knight. ``Jeff
said coach Knight was cool,'' Moye said.
</P>
<P>
   Moye told about the time that Newton arrived 20 minutes late for
a film session early in the year. Knowing Knight's reputation,
Newton froze up in expectation of the coach's wrath. Instead, he
was given a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Coach Knight) has been under heat like this before,'' Moye
said. ``When he threw the chair. There was that time when it looked
like he head-butted a player. He gets aggressive and impulse takes
over. The only reason he gets like that is because he wants the
best out of his players.''
</P>
<P>
   But Moye understands that there is a limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like discipline. I've been able to thrive under it,'' Moye
said. ``But I won't let anyone take a violent act against me. And I
wouldn't give him a reason to. There's only one person that can put
their hands on me _ and that's my mom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
