<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7277 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-B     04-14 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV16-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMPETER'S PARADOX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 16, 2000)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all of the talk about the ``new economy,'' the government
case against Microsoft Corp. reads surprisingly like a page from
tales of the old economy. The plot, for instance, is pretty much
the same as Robert Altman's 1971 classic tale of earlier boomtimes
in the Pacific Northwest frontier, ``McCabe and Mrs. Miller.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, gambler John McCabe (played by Warren Beatty) sets
up a saloon/bordello in a lumber town and mining camp not too far
down the coast from Seattle. Like any dealer, says the Leonard
Cohen soundtrack, ``he is looking for a card so high and wild he'll
never need to deal another.''
</P>
<P>
   Determined to be his own boss, he nevertheless partners up with
Mrs. Miller (Julie Christie,) who agrees to be his manager. The
boom goes forward; the establishment prospers.
</P>
<P>
   One day a pair of polished businessmen arrive in town. They are
from the mining company, they explain, and they are authorized to
make a cash offer for McCabe's business from ``one of the most
solid companies in the United States.'' McCabe is drunk. In loutish
fashion, he tell them no. The next morning he sobers up and tries
to negotiate for twice the price that they have offered. It is too
late. They hire an implacable killer.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, this is the oft-repeated complaint against
Microsoft, except that nobody gets killed. Instead, entrepreneurs
in the target zone get a meeting with Bill Gates. ``I can buy 20
percent of you or I can buy all of you or I can go into this
business myself and bury you,'' he says -- most famously to America
Online chairmman Steve Case (as describd in Kara Swisher's book,
``AOL.Com'') but literally or figuratively to many other
competitors in many other instances.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign to crush Netscape in the Intrnet ``browser wars''
that began in 1994 is the case the government chose to try -- and
proved, to the satisfaction of US District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion about the nature of the offense arises -- not
least of all in Bill Gates' own mind -- because of the broad
rhetorical framework in which such antitrust complaints
traditionally are framed. When the Sherman Act was passed in in
1890 -- just about the time in which ``McCabe and Mrs Miller''
isset -- Congress took the position that no elaborate definition of
``restraint of trade'' was necessary: the courts would know it when
they saw it.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since then, a loose shorthand has evolved at the
juncture of economics, law and journalism which holds that the
anticompetetive practices harm consumers by stifling potential
innovation. That has led many in the Microsoft case to observe the
obvious good the company has done by standardizing software for
persnal computers and ask where is the harm? Aftr all, innovation
is proceeding briskly in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Microsoft is such an anticompetetive monster,'' Robert
Samuelson wrote the other day, ``why has the New Economy become (at
least by reputation) become so competitive that it raises
efficiency and lowers inflation?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that it is the new technologies that do the work
and that big businesss arise to implement them. Nearly sixty years
ago, the economist Joseph Schumpeter put his finger on the paradox
at the center of the politics of antitrust. ``Capitalism, Socialism
and Democracy'' is a wounded bear of a book (``Can capitalism
survive? I do not think it can.'') But it contains some of the the
clearest descriptions of the processes of growth and development
ever written.
</P>
<P>
   ``The modern standard of life of the masses evolved during the
period of relatively unfettered `big business,''' Schumpeter wrote.
``If we list the items that enter the modern workman's budget, from
1899 on, (and) observe the course of their prices...we cannot fail
to be struck by the rate of the advance which, considering the
spectacular improvement in qualities, seems to have been greater
and not smaller than it ever was before...
</P>
<P>
   ``Nor is this all. As soon as we...inquire into the individual
items in which progress was the most conspicuous, the trail leads
not to the doors of those firms that work under conditions of
comparatively free competition but precisely to the doors ofthe
large concerns -- which, as in the case of agricultural machinery,
also account for much of the progress in the competetive sector --
and a shocking suspicion dawns upon us that big business may have
had more to do with creating that standard of life than with
keeping it down.''
</P>
<P>
   How? Why? Because much of the monopoly profits those firms
charge are plowed back into extending the business, building plant
and and capacity, creating ever-larger netorks of users through
marketing, performing research and development to improve the
product -- for a time, at least. That's the story of the railroads,
of farm machinery, of steel and oil. Measured in terms of the labor
necessary to buy a certain carefully defined consumption bundle,
the cost of living fell dramatically during the years of the great
monopolistic trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean the government was wrong to bust them up? Would
we have been better off if John D. Rockefeller and Andrew Carnegie
had been free to continue to pursue their ruthless system-building
ways?
</P>
<P>
   Of course not. The antitust laws are about the concentration and
abuse of power among Big Businesses. They are about the kind of
injustice that forms the basis of the plot for ``McCabe and Mrs.
Miller.'' Corporations are indispensible engines of progress, and
one of the ways they achieve efficiency is by imposing standards,
but sometimes they overstep their bounds. Today, as at the end of
the 19th century, the limits of society's willingness to tolerate
the kind of routine intimidation and low-level violence that can
(but needn't) go into building a successful business empire have
been reached -- at least in court.
</P>
<P>
   (Whether Microsoft's atonishing attempt to overturn the verdict
in the court of public opinion remains to be seen. Last week the
firm admitted that it had hired Ralph Reed, former head of the
Christian Coalition and a close adviser to GOP presidential hopeful
George W. Bush, to conduct a high level national lobbying
campaign.)
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is an extraordinary corporation. No student of its
methods is more acute or more level-headed than Michael Cusumano of
Massachustts Institute of Technology's Sloan School of Management.
He is co-author of ``Competing on Internet Time: Lessons from
Netscape and its Battle with Microsoft'' and ``Microsoft Secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Gates must bear the brunt of the blame for creating and
continuing this mess,'' Cusumano wrote the other day in the Wall
Street Journal. ``Microsoft is an extension -- some 30,000 people
strong -- of his unique personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Gates and other Microsoft people are extremely smart,
hardworking and relentless, And they understand the business of
mass-marketing software like no one ever has. At the same time,
they are arrogant, insecure and oblivious to how the world views
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insecurity comes from the knowledge that high-tech markets
change quickly, advantages are fleeting, and Microsoft as a company
has been lucky.... But the list of ways in which Microsoft used
Windows as a hammer is much too long....
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has not changed its aggressive behavior from the
days when it was a small company struggling to survive in the world
of IBM and minframe computers, fighting to fend off Apple, Lotus
and Word Perfect. Microsoft and Mr. Gates did not grow up soon
enough, so the judge and Justice lawyers have intervened with
``adult supervision.''
</P>
<P>
   The main difference betwen the New Economy and the old is that
in the New Economy, no one gets killed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
