<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAMING OF LIBERAL ECONOMIC ADVISER SEEN AS BELLWETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Foreign investors in Russia were buoyant this week
after President-elect Vladimir V. Putin appointed a respected
liberal as his main economic adviser and announced that his
government intends to lower taxes on businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The news was especially welcome because Putin, who will be
inaugurated as Russia's president in three weeks, has yet to unveil
his economic program, and his few statements and actions on the
subject have often seemed contradictory and designed primarily not
to offend anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took the appointment of Andrei Illarionov, one of
Russia's most respected economists, as a sign that Putin's program
may turn out to be decidedly pro-free market.
</P>
<P>
   United Financial Group, a Moscow-based brokerage, called
Illarionov's appointment ``an encouraging sign which opens the
possibility of change in economic policies and the acceleration of
reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Illarionov has advocated low taxes, balanced
budgets, and less bureaucratic regulation of the economy. He has
also long been a staunch opponent of foreign loans to Russia, and
has derided the government's practice of printing money to finance
deficits as ``counterfeiting.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of former President Boris Yeltsin's cabinet in the
early 1990s, Illarionov eventually resigned, saying the
government's policies were leading to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Friday, Illarionov offered his recipe for
reviving Russia's economy in the simplest possible terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't steal, don't print false money, don't have a budget
deficit, don't borrow, pay your debts, and don't have unreasonable
regulations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Illarionov said Russia has a chance to end a decade of economic
decline if Putin seizes the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   He said Russia's economy could grow by 8 to 10 percent a year if
``serious reforms'' are implemented. The growth rate was 3.2
percent last year, and the most optimistic official forecasts
project 5.2 percent growth for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Illarionov declined to specify what reforms were necessary. A
special task force is working out Putin's long-term economic
strategy and is expected to unveil the result after the May 7
inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Illarianov, however, took the media to task for labeling him an
``ultra-liberal,'' a term associated here with Western-style market
reforms. he said his ideas were simply common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are seen elsewhere as normal sensible ideas are for some
reason considered ultra-liberal in our country,'' he said. ``Our
political and economic assumptions are so distorted that perfectly
sensible economic ideas are seen as extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Illarionov's protestations demonstrated the dilemma economic
reformers face in Russia today.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, a few well-connected businessmen took
advantage of their political contacts to become fabulously wealthy,
while most Russians became destitute. As a result, terms like
``liberal'' and ``market'' have become synonymous in the public
mind with ``theft'' and ``poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts here are divided on whether Putin is willing or able to
break the grip of a group of politically-connected tycoons, known
as the oligarchs, who control much of Russia's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Most said, however, that the president-elect is likely to pursue
steps like lowering the tax burden, reducing government
regulations, and protecting the rights of investors.
</P>
<P>
   But Putin will likely present these policies to the public as
pragmatic steps to restore Russia's cherished status as a world
power, they said. His image as a tough-talking former KGB spy, they
added, will make it easier for him to pursue a liberal economic
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin's main goal in life is to reposition Russia as a world
power, and the only way he can do this is to reform the economy and
attract investment,'' said Eric Kraus, chief strategist for Nikoil
Capital Markets, Moscow investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is now no reasonable doubt that Putin will take a more
liberal line than had been expected,'' he said. ``He just won't
call it liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraus and others said Putin's call for lower taxes is further
cause for optimism. The Kremlin has said it will present to
parliament later this month a simplified tax code that lowers rates
and closes loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses in Russia have long complained that a high tax burden
and a labyrinth of complicated laws leave them at the mercy of
predatory bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can by no means allow the tax burden to grow,'' Putin said
Thursday. ``Our aim is quite different: to make all legislation
more transparent, more comprehensive, more efficient. We can by no
means allow tax rules to lead to more pressure on small and
medium-sized businesses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
