<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7285 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV16-NY     04-14 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHINA PACT, EXECUTIVES SENSE A HORNET'S NEST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 100 chief executives applauded mildly when Gene Sperling,
the White House economic adviser, finished his pitch for the China
trade agreement. Sperling had been preaching to the choir: no one
wants Congress to ratify the agreement more than the nation's top
business executives. But their first question to him afterward
revealed a concern that, in backing the trade bill, they are
stepping on a hornet's nest.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to know what John L. Sweeney, head of the AFL-CIO,
would have told them if he, rather than Sperling, had addressed
this gathering of the National Association of Manufacturers in
Miami last weekend. Labor unions oppose the bill, which would
upgrade China's trade status and open it to more American exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sweeney's general view would be that China is a
country that puts labor organizers in jail, and we don't want to do
business with a country that does that,'' Sperling replied.
</P>
<P>
   No problem so far _ the chief executives agree that labor rights
are violated in China, as are civil rights and environmental
protections. But while unions and environmentalists want rules
written into the agreement, corporate America argues that open
trade will force reform.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. If that were the only issue, Congress would probably
approve the trade agreement when it comes up for a vote in the week
of May 22. But it is not the only issue. What Sperling said next,
trying to explain Sweeney, is the hornet's nest for a growing
number of chief executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a dynamic economy like ours, there are dislocations, and
even with 4.1 percent unemployment a lot of people are hurt by job
loss,'' Sperling said. ``Trade and globalization have become the
whipping boys for these issues, whether they are related or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations in Seattle last November, at a World Trade
Organization meeting, and those scheduled for Washington this week,
at a meeting of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund,
focus attention on this pain. Globalization has almost certainly
made America more prosperous, as corporate lobbyists for the China
bill argue vociferously.
</P>
<P>
   But public sentiment appears to be building against an open
global marketplace that fails to protect labor, civil rights and
the environment, and some chief executives are acknowledging that
this sentiment cannot be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are fearful of an antibusiness attitude, and they are
trying to avoid it,'' said Daniel Yankelovich, chairman of DYG, a
polling organization that often surveys corporate thinking. ``They
are trying to be on the right side of this issue. And the irony is
that, in a booming economy, you can still get people worked up
about globalization.''
</P>
<P>
   An incipient reaching-out was evident in interviews with chief
executives at the World Economic Forum in Davos, Switzerland, in
January, not long after Seattle. Leaders of the demonstrations took
part in the Davos discussions. So did Lewis B. Campbell, chairman
of Textron.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my dealings with unions over many years,'' he said, ``I
have found that when you discard out of hand their views, you are
making a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell proposed gathering representatives of business,
academia, unions and environmentalists into a new forum to debate
trade policy. ``If this institution were inclusive of all global
interests, and everyone had a fair voice, there would not be a need
to demonstrate,'' he said, adding that the WTOwould have to
consider the institution's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing executives in Miami reflected this thinking,
or at least some did. ``We have to get out the view _ perhaps
through a forum that includes all sides _ that yes, there are
issues with trade, but over all the economy has benefited,'' said
James H. Keyes, chairman of Johnson Controls and of the
manufacturers' association. ``Free trade has created jobs, and also
cost jobs, but the jobs gained get buried under the publicity given
to the jobs lost.''
</P>
<P>
   No compromise is afoot. Is that bad? Would the prosperity that
has come with increasingly open borders be damaged if trade
agreements included standards for civil rights, labor and the
environment?
</P>
<P>
   No. Standards _ the normal rules of a democracy _ have not been
obstacles to trade. The real danger is in fighting too hard against
standards, only to have free trade deteriorate, said Dani Rodrik, a
Harvard economist. ``Anti-dumping duties reappear, Europe turns in
on itself, China gives up on the World Trade Organization.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what America's executives are beginning to recognize. Or
as Rodrik put it: ``Companies may be learning that they are better
off with moderate rules than with constant harassment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
