<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITING SYSTEM FILE WILL STOP DRIVE-CHECKING AFTER A REBOOT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Windows 98 being what it is, I often have to shut down my
computer after it locks up. When it boots back up, Norton Disk
Doctor starts to run in DOS. I really don't want this to run and
check all my files. It takes forever. How can I prevent it?
</P>
<P>
   A: In theory, you're always supposed to use the Shut Down
command when you exit Windows. But since Windows 98 is prone to
lockups, sometimes you have to bite the bullet and reboot.
</P>
<P>
   When Windows is not shut down correctly, it automatically
launches upon restarting an application called ScanDisk that checks
to make sure your file system is not corrupted. ScanDisk does a
cursory check and then gets out of the way, letting Windows
continue booting. It normally doesn't take very long.
</P>
<P>
   When you install Symantec's Norton Utilities, or Norton
SystemWorks, it installs an MS-DOS version of Disk Doctor and
replaces Windows' own ScanDisk. While the Norton version is more
thorough, it also takes a lot longer to process the drive. On a big
drive, it seems like an eternity.
</P>
<P>
   If you do a custom installation of Norton Utilities, you can
tell it not to replace ScanDisk. But since you've already installed
the Norton product, your best bet is to edit a system file called
MSDOS.SYS and tell Windows not to scan the drive at all.
</P>
<P>
   Use Notepad to open MSDOS.SYS in the root folder of your C:
drive. Look for a line that reads: &QL; 
 &QL; 
AutoScan1 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Change the 1 to a 0, save the file and exit Notepad. Reboot.
</P>
<P>
   Beware: MSDOS.SYS is a crucial system file, and if you make a
mistake or change the wrong thing, it can cause major headaches.
Make a copy of the file before making changes.
</P>
<P>
   The next time you have to restart Windows without properly
shutting down, you won't get the Disk Doctor scan. But you should
manually check the disk soon after using the Windows version of
Disk Doctor that comes with Norton Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whenever I boot up either Netscape Communicator or Internet
Explorer, the home page goes to someplace called GoHip. I know how
to change it back to my usual home page (CNN), but it bothers me
that this happens. It only does it when you boot up the computer
and run either browser for the first time. After you change the
default, it stays that way until the next reboot. I think a family
member clicked on something that allowed that script to be loaded
when the browsers are booted up from the start. Any idea how to get
rid of it?
</P>
<P>
   A: The site GoHip.com, a search engine, urges people to
``enhance'' their browsing experience by downloading a plug-in.
Part of its setup is that it changes your startup page to GoHip.
</P>
<P>
   However, the usual method of resetting your startup page back to
your original preference doesn't ``stick.'' This has infuriated a
lot of people, and GoHip has taken some heat for it. I've had quite
a bit of e-mail on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   GoHip has posted on its Web site a small program that will
remove the plug-in and restore your home page to its original
setting. Get the program at
www.gohip.com/removebrowserenhancement.html.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
