A7290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW-HEALTH15-COX     04-14 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-HEALTH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companies counting on Healtheon/WebMD stock as currency face
losses
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The plunging stock market might make technology
companies think twice about accepting public stock as currency.
</P>
<P>
   And companies such as Atlanta-based Healtheon/WebMD, which often
have used their publicly traded stock to buy their competition,
might find themselves with thinner wallets if the market continues
to crater.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon/WebMD is trying to move health-care related
transactions to the Internet by linking doctors, patients and
insurance companies. It also is developing a site for consumer
health information.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon has been using its stock to buy companies to flesh out
its products and services, starting with the merger of Healtheon
and WebMD last May, placing a market capitalization of almost $20
billion on the company. Between partnerships and acquisitions,
Healtheon/WebMD has made more than 80 deals in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Three companies that recently took Healtheon/WebMD stock as part
of deals will find themselves _ if the stock doesn't rebound _
getting much less than they bargained for. Based on Friday's
closing price of $18.32, Healtheon's market cap is about $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Its purchases earlier this year of Envoy, OnHealth Network and
CareInsite are pending. The deals had no ``collar,'' which means
they are worth whatever Healtheon's stock is worth.
</P>
<P>
   Economist Wayne Gantt said that if the stock market continues to
drop it will impact the ability of companies such as Healtheon to
grow by acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to have a negative effect on a lot of the
companies that have been using a currency that is less than what
they previously thought,'' he said. ``It's not going to entirely do
away with it. As this sort-out continues, some of the companies
will survive _ the ones that ultimately start showing earnings
streams.''
</P>
<P>
   In late January, Healtheon agreed to use 35 million shares of
its stock, and $400 million, to buy Envoy, a unit of Quintiles
Transactional. Then, Healtheon shares traded for a little more than
$65. They have fallen almost 72 percent since.
</P>
<P>
   What was in January a deal valued at $2.1 billion in stock and
$400 million in cash is now worth $641 million in stock, and $400
million cash, based on Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, Healtheon made two deals in three days. They
first agreed to buy Medical Manager for $5.4 billion in stock.
Healtheon shares have dropped 67.6 percent since.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Healtheon said it was using 4.6 million of its
shares, then selling for $67.87 1/2, to buy OnHealth Network for
$312 million. The deal now is worth $84.3 million based on Friday's
closing price.
</P>
<P>
   The deal last May that brought Healtheon and WebMD together sent
Healtheon's shares surging. Healtheon/WebMD shares hit a 52-week
high of more than $126 on May 20, the day the merger was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
