u a BC-CUBA-BOY-BOS &LR;      04-14 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SEEKS RIGHTS PROTECTION FOR REFUGEE BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Both sides in the tug-of-war over Elian Gonzalez
maneuvered feverishly for advantage in the courts Friday, even as
the federal government heated up its rhetoric by accusing the boy's
family here of acting illegally and of engaging in ``child
exploitation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives, who have tried several legal arguments
during their effort to retain custody of Elian, Friday added
another: They asked the US District Court in Washington to prevent
the Immigration and Naturalization Service from returning the
6-year-old to his homeland until the US government certifies that
Cuba complies with the UN Declaration of Human Rights and is ``no
longer engaged in `systematic, gross violations of human rights.'
''
</P>
<P>
   District Judge Henry Kennedy said he would hear arguments on the
case next Wednesday, then decide whether to let it proceed.
Attorneys for Elian's relatives argued that he needs the court's
help because, if he goes back to Cuba, he would face ``the risk of
being persecuted'' and would be ``politically indoctrinated to a
much larger extent than others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department fired its shots in the custody battle
Friday not in Washington but Atlanta. There, responding to an
injunction issued Thursday that temporarily bars Elian from leaving
America, the department argued that the Miami family members lack
the standing to ask for court intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The department's 61-page brief to the 11th US Circuit Court of
Appeals described Elian's great-uncle and current guardian, Lazaro
Gonzalez, as ``a mere distant relative.'' It also said that the
elder Gonzalez was seeking a judicial remedy with ``unclean
hands,'' since he had already violated a government order to
surrender custody of Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the department struck out at the Miami relatives, it
offered them a carrot: a guarantee that Elian will stay in the
United States for as long as it takes for the legal process to play
out -- but only if they turn over custody of the boy to his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez. An accompanying letter from Juan Gonzalez'
attorney said he had agreed to comply with those terms.
</P>
<P>
   The court in Atlanta issued the temporary stay Thursday in
response to a request from the boy's family for a permanent
injunction. The court ordered the government to issue its response
by Friday morning and told lawyers for the relatives to submit
their rebuttal by Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on whether the three-judge panel will hear the case
is expected within a few days, and the Justice Department has
informally promised not to try to remove Elian from Lazaro
Gonzalez' home during that time. The department could theoretically
do so, since the injunction does not address who Elian's guardian
should be as long as he stays in the United States, but US
officials evidently don't want to further inflame an already heated
atmosphere since they believe they'll ultimately prevail in court
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The INS commissioner, Doris Meissner, not only sounded confident
of victory Friday but strongly indicated that federal authorities
soon intend to take custody of Elian, one way or another. His
relatives ignored an order from Attorney General Janet Reno
directing them to relinquish the boy two days ago, so he could be
flown to his father outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take action in a way that's appropriate to the situation
when we're ready,'' Meissner said on NBC's ``Today'' program.
</P>
<P>
   The INS spokeswoman, Maria Cardona, used even stronger language.
She implied that the federal government not only intended to get
Elian, but also might take legal steps against the relatives with
whom he has been living since he was rescued off the coast of
Florida nearly five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a stage when Lazaro Gonzalez has failed to comply
with an INS order, so we have now moved to implement an enforcement
action plan,'' said Cardona. ``He has broken the law.''
</P>
<P>
   She was particularly harsh in her assessment of the family's
decision to make and release a home video of Elian telling his
father that he wanted to stay in this country. ``I think it was the
most appalling child manipulation and child exploitation,'' Cardona
said. ``I thought it was shameful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we needed another reason to immediately move to reunite
Elian with his father, this was certainly it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though rain poured down on the area Friday, more than 100
Cuban-American supporters of Elian's relatives continued their
vigil outside the family home. Standing under large tarpaulins that
kept out most of the water, the protesters repeated their resolve
to prevent federal agents from removing the boy before all legal
efforts have been exhausted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
