<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7309 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      04-14 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS WIDOW REPEATS ACCUSATION AGAINST HEART SPECIALIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Frequently breaking down in tears, Donna Harris-Lewis
Friday repeated her longstanding assertion that Dr. Gilbert H.
Mudge Jr. had diagnosed her late husband with a benign fainting
condition, not the life-threatening heart disorder that ultimately
caused the Celtics star's death.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony, as it did last year, contradicts Mudge's claim
that he, the Lewises, Celtics representatives, and Brigham and
Women's Hospital officials agreed to conceal the second, more
worrisome diagnosis of a heart problem from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Rossman, Harris-Lewis's attorney, asked her if Mudge had
ever given her or her husband any indication that Lewis suffered
from a life-threatening arrhythmia, an uncontrolled fluttering of
the heart that can cause death.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' replied Harris-Lewis, testifying for the first time in
the retrial of the medical malpractice lawsuit stemming from her
husband's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Reggie was discharged,'' she said, ``he was discharged
with a diagnosis of neurocardiogenic syncope,'' a benign fainting
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis sued Mudge, Lewis's chief cardiologist, for
negligence after her husband died. A first trial ended in a hung
jury last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under stern cross-examination by Mudge's attorney, William J.
Dailey Jr., Harris-Lewis faced a barrage of questions suggesting
that Lewis failed to take his medication regularly and violated
Mudge's orders not to exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis denied both accusations, explaining an apparent gap
in Lewis's prescription refills by saying that a Brigham nurse gave
Lewis an extra supply of medication when he was discharged from the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   And although Dailey produced a note from Mudge cautioning Lewis
that, ``We need to touch base before you exercise again,''
Harris-Lewis insisted that Mudge put no restrictions on Lewis's
physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination Harris-Lewis frequently responded that
she had no ``clear recollection'' of events and needed to review
documents to ``jog'' her memory.
</P>
<P>
   During direct questioning by Rossman, Harris-Lewis echoed her
testimony from last year, describing Lewis's excitement at being
drafted by the Boston Celtics in 1987, an achievement she said
``surpassed his wildest dreams.'' She mentioned Lewis's
philanthropic work, such as urging young people to ``stay away from
bad influences, (like) drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   And she recounted the shock of being told by the Celtics team
physician after Lewis's first collapse in April 1993 that he might
have a life-threatening heart condition. That was ultimately the
conclusion reached by the ``Dream Team'' of doctors who evaluated
Lewis at New England Baptist Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to explain Lewis's abrupt transfer to Brigham and Women's
Hospital against medical advice, Harris-Lewis said she and her
husband were frustrated by a lack of communication at the Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   And in testimony that moved at least two jurors to tears,
Harris-Lewis described her reaction upon learning that her husband
had collapsed and died while shooting baskets on July 27, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a state of shock,'' she said. ``He was every bit of
what a woman could want in a man, and more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
