<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7311 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-GAMBIA-WWII-VETS-ART-     04-14 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMBIA-WWII-VETS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A WAR IN FAR-OFF BURMA CHANGED AN AFRICAN AND HIS LAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FARAFENNI, Gambia _ It was late when the old man returned home
from evening prayers. During the day the sand-covered street had
been busy, but the dust settled as people withdrew into their
houses and courtyards. The moon would not come out this night, and
soon the neighborhood, save his house and perhaps another one with
a generator, would sink into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the old man's courtyard, children were playing and women
were preparing dinner. But seeing an unannounced visitor, the old
man, Cpl. Bakary Dibba, a World War II veteran in his 80s, ushered
him inside his house.
</P>
<P>
   Around Farafenni, a border town in the interior of this tiny
West African nation, Dibba is known as the last survivor among the
10 local men who fought in the British army against the Japanese in
Burma. World War II changed Africa forever, in great part because
the European colonial powers drafted hundreds of thousands of young
men like Dibba from the remotest corners of their African colonies
and sent them to places they never knew existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I had heard that a great war was being fought,''
Dibba said, sitting in an armchair in his starkly furnished living
room, where a single weak light bulb hanging from the ceiling cast
faint shadows against the blue walls. ``But we never knew we were
going to fight in that war. I did not know there was a place called
Burma. It's only when we reached Burma that we realized we were to
fight in the World War.''
</P>
<P>
   A clear moral imperative may have guided U.S. and British
soldiers as they fought in Europe and Asia. But for many African
soldiers _ fighting as they did for their colonial masters, the
same men who talked of battling the racist regimes of Nazi Germany
and Japan _ there was deep ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1939, to hear Dibba tell it, when some British
officials came here for one week searching for volunteers. The a
highway that now goes through here had not yet been built, and
Farafenni was only a village of several hundred farmers.
</P>
<P>
   At one rally, Dibba recalled, African drums were played to stir
up enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after there was no volunteer,'' he said, ``they started to
use force so the youths would go. The chief went to each compound
and demanded one volunteer. When they saw you, they would just grip
you and take you.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he and an older brother volunteered, the only 2
among the 10 young men who went to war. ``We knew we were going to
be forced,'' he said, ``so we decided to join.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man was between 16 and 20 years old, already with a
young bride named Binta. He did not know the year of his birth,
though he remembered the exact weight _ 70 pounds _ he was able to
carry in military gear and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The conscripts from Gambia were sent for training to Nigeria,
Britain's largest colony in West Africa. The other colonies, Sierra
Leone and Ghana, then known as the Gold Coast, also sent men. The
four colonies provided a total of 167,000 soldiers organized into
seven brigades, according to the British historian Basil Davidson.
Hundreds of thousands more were recruited by the British in East
and Southern Africa, and by the French in their colonial
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Time passed. Dibba and the others sailed for India. There was
more training at barracks near Delhi and then Calcutta. The size of
the cities astonished him. ``I realized that some people are
completely white in India and some are colored, and they have very
long hair,'' he said, excavating his memories from 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized there are Hindus as well as Muslims,'' added Dibba,
who until then had heard only of Muslims, like himself, and
Christians.
</P>
<P>
   Away from Africa, young men from different ethnic groups worked
together for the first time for a common cause, just as they did in
the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
   ``All tribes were mixed together _ Wollof, Mandinka, Fula,''
said Dibba, who is Mandinka. ``We did not have any problems because
of our tribes. We were together.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dibba took off his slippers and leaned back in his armchair. His
family had gathered outside the living room window, peering inside.
His youngest child, Yusupha, 4, clambered onto his lap. The child
was born to Dibba's 20-year-old wife, the youngest of his three
wives.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With their training completed, Dibba and the others were driven
to northern Burma. Then they hiked for two days through jungle and
mountains. On the way, 10 men died drinking water from a lake that
Japanese soldiers had poisoned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Japanese forces had conquered Southeast Asia and had
overrun Burma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never knew anything about the Japanese people,'' Dibba said.
``In Burma, I realized these people were called the Japanese
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then many of us realized for the first time that it was a real
war. There was no way out. Nobody could escape back to Africa. We
had to fight. There was no day or night. We were fighting all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting lasted three years for Dibba. In that time, a
British officer passed on a message from Farafenni that Binta, his
wife, had died of meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a couple of months after Japan's surrender in August
1945, Dibba was back in Farafenni. He has never left since. But the
experiences that he and the other veterans brought back to Africa
helped transform the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Africa's participation in liberating Europe from the Nazis and
Asia from the Japanese strengthened the continent's push for
independence. In the signing of the Atlantic Charter of 1941,
Roosevelt persuaded a reluctant Churchill to accept as one of the
postwar goals that the Allies would ``respect the right of all
peoples to choose the form of government under which they will
live.''
</P>
<P>
   The message of Africa's independence leaders _
self-determination, pan-Africanism _ found a particularly receptive
audience among veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Four decades after most of Africa gained its independence, Dibba
seems to have retained his ambivalence toward World War II. He
keeps his three medals at the bottom of a big trunk, and had
trouble digging them out. They needed polishing, he said, almost
apologetically. He is not held up here as a hero, as a World War II
veteran in the United States would be.
</P>
<P>
   Dibba's 30-year-old son, Kebba Dibba, looked surprised when he
was asked whether he considered his father a hero. ``I don't think
war produces heroes,'' Kebba said. ``We don't need to look for such
heroes. He did it and that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was getting very late. The old man had already changed into
his pajamas. He was tired.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the same, the British, the Japanese; they were
fighting all for the same thing _ sovereignty,'' Bakary Dibba said.
``I don't regret fighting for the colonial masters. But at the end
of the day, they are all the same. They are all doing business
together now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7312 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MEDIA-WILLES-BOS &LR;      04-14 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-WILLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS SEE SHAKEUP AT LA TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what one observer called ``the denouement of the whole (Mark)
Willes era,'' reports circulated Friday that the editor and
publisher of the Los Angeles Times were being ousted by the paper's
new owners, the Chicago-based Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   None of the parties would confirm that story Friday. But the
Times reported that when the Tribune Co. formally takes control,
Times editor Michael Parks would be replaced by Baltimore Sun
editor John Carroll, and publisher Kathryn Downing by Orlando
Sentinel publisher John Puerner. The Sentinel is owned by the
Tribune Co. while the Sun is part of the Times Mirror empire.
</P>
<P>
   The $6.4 billion sale of Times parent company Times Mirror to
the Tribune Co. stunned the media world when it was announced last
month. The Tribune's tender offer to purchase shares of Times
Mirror stock expires Monday, after which time official change in
control can take place.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of Parks's and Downing's impending departures were not
unexpected after the last few tumultuous years for the Times under
the stewardship of Willes, the Times Mirror chief executive.
Willes, who also took the post of Times publisher in 1997, became
known for cutting jobs, for his professed desire to blow up the
``wall'' between business and editorial departments, and for his
goal of increasing Times circulation by an astounding 500,000.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, veteran Times editor Shelby Coffey III resigned
and was replaced by Parks, who had risen to prominence as a foreign
correspondent. Last June, Willes was succeeded as publisher by his
protege Downing.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, when the Times' decision to share ad revenues with
the new Staples Center sports arena triggered an uproar over
journalistic ethics, the episode was largely viewed as an
indictment of the Willes philosophy that imperiled both Downing and
Parks. In a post-mortem he wrote on the Staples fiasco, Times media
writer David Shaw was critical of Downing's judgment and Parks's
failure to protect editorial integrity, and blamed the ``diminished
standards'' on Willes's watch. When the Times' sale to the Tribune
Co. was announced, Willes indicated he would be leaving the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Former Times publisher David Laventhol said the management
shakeup ``closes the loop in the sense that the Times has its top
management in place for the future.'' While expressing his
admiration for Parks, Laventhol added that ``John Carroll is a
wonderful choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The much-respected Carroll, who has been the editor of the Sun
since 1991, was being discussed as a successor to Bill Kovach as
curator of Harvard's Nieman Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Puerner, publisher of The Orlando Sentinel since 1993, is viewed
as an up-and-comer at the Tribune Co., where he has worked since
1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7314 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MARKET-IPOS-BOS &LR;      04-14 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-IPOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE IPOS SCRUBBED AMID PLUNGING STOCK PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As US stock markets went into freefall Friday, several dot-com
companies hastily scrubbed or delayed plans for initial public
offerings of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Among many other companies now exploring alternative options for
financing was Furniture.com Inc., an online furniture retailer
backed by CMGI Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com not only put its IPO on hold, but laid off 29
workers, or nearly 15 percent of its work force, in Framingham,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to attract new customers, Furniture.com had been
offering free deliveries. Now, it plans to impose some delivery
fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is looking for e-commerce companies to become much
more focused on the bottom line,'' said a Furniture.com spokesman,
Don Goncalves. ``We've gone function by function throughout the
business with an eye to fast-forwarding our path to profitablity.''
</P>
<P>
   Also putting off a planned IPO Friday was Zefer Corp., a Boston
consulting firm that specializes in Web strategy. Zefer had hoped
to raise $58.5 million in an offering managed by Credit Suisse
First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking at a stock market that just continues to
deteriorate, day after day,'' said William Seibel Jr., chief
executive. ``The worst thing we could do was take a great company
out in a skittish market.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bloomberg News, more than 25 companies have
canceled IPOs or secondary stock offerings in the last month, as
the technology-heavy Nasdaq Stock Market headed south.
</P>
<P>
   The number of IPOs had reached record levels early this year,
Bloomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Media Holdings Inc., the cable television unit of Hallmark
Cards Inc., was among the companies that canceled offering plans.
It had been hoping to raise as much as $260 million.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 companies, though, including AltaVista Co., which runs
a popular Internet search engine, and 360networks Inc., which is
building a North American fiber-optic network, still plan to go
ahead with IPOs next week.
</P>
<P>
   With the Nasdaq Composite index swooning in recent weeks, some
companies in the high-flying IPO class of 1999 have lost two-thirds
of their value, most notably Commerce One Inc. and Internet Capital
Group.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nasdaq's sharp decline has poisoned the climate for
companies that had been looking to raise money by selling stock to
the public, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   In a worst-case scenario, wholesale cancellations of IPOs could
cut off the oxygen to a generation of start-up dot-coms struggling
to survive. That would not just hurt young companies; it would also
be bad news for investment banks, which earn fees for managing
IPOs. And there would likely be a ripple effect through equity
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Certicom Corp., a Canadian maker of secure-transaction software,
canceled its immediate plans for a $316 million IPO that was to
have been managed by Robertson Stephens Inc., a unit of FleetBoston
Financial Corp. of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   When it released first-quarter earnings this week, FleetBoston
said Robertson Stephens was part of the reason why earnings were up
22 percent over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
