u f BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-14 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPPING OUT WITH A WHOLE GIGAHERTZ 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speed has always been the driving trend in the development of
the personal computer. From the beginning, its creators sought ways
to make it much faster, and users applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Now microprocessor capabilities have reached a new, higher
mountain top: 1 gigahertz, which is the equivalent of 1,000
megahertz. It's a goal the processor industry has been racing
toward for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you can buy a 1-GHz PC, is it worth it? Given the state
of the art in modern computing, does anyone really need a computer
that fast?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, as always: It depends.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at one of the fastest consumer PCs you can buy _
and some thoughts on why you might or might not want to:
</P>
<P>
   Presario 5900Z-1GHz _ $3,050, Compaq Computer Corp.: Advanced
Micro Devices was the first chip maker to reach the vaunted 1-GHz
speed milestone, edging out market leader Intel Corp. by just a few
days. Compaq has opted to go with AMD's 1-GHz Athlon processor
instead of Intel's Pentium III model.
</P>
<P>
   I reviewed a Presario 5900Z with a 700-megahertz Athlon chip in
October (see www.chron.com/cs/CDA/story.hts/tech/370363), and there
have been only minor changes made to the system since then. One of
them, though, is indicative of a change in attitude on the part of
Compaq that's to be applauded. More on that in a moment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MACHINE LOADED FOR ACTION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1-GHz model I tested came with 256 megabytes of memory; a
40-gigabyte hard drive; a 10X DVD-ROM drive and an 8x4x32
rewritable CD-ROM drive; a Creative Labs 3D Annihilator Pro
graphics card with 32 MB of video memory; a SoundBlaster Live!
Value audio card; a 56K fax modem; and a 10/100-megabit Ethernet
card. Other than the sound card _ which is a subset of the standard
SoundBlaster Live! _ there's nothing wimpy about this machine, and
that includes the price. That $3,000-plus does not include a
monitor or speakers.
</P>
<P>
   So why would anyone want a 1-GHz processor? Certainly, if you
use your computer for basic tasks _ e-mail, Web surfing, word
processing, entertainment software, simple games _ then you don't
need it. It's more than overkill for most users.
</P>
<P>
   But if you lay high-end games, work with large graphics or audio
files, need speech recognition capabilities or work in software
development, you need all the muscle you can get. And this machine
has it.
</P>
<P>
   The timedemo feature in id Software's Quake III Arena game has
become the de facto standard among power-hungry PC users for
testing just what a computer can do. It stresses the processor,
memory component and the graphics system and reports back the
results in the average number of frames displayed per second.
</P>
<P>
   With the graphics settings on Normal, the Presario 5900Z-1GHz
scored an impressive 95.8 frames per second. Ratcheting up the
settings to High Quality, it came in at 83.8 fps. On the custom
settings I normally use to play _ 1,024-by-768 resolution, with all
the eye candy turned on _ it hit 55.2 fps. These are the highest
numbers of any machine I've tested _ as well they should be!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
USER-FRIENDLY FEATURES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is obviously a great gamer's machine, but it also should be
of interest to anyone who wants to work with desktop video. It is
one of the few PCs out there that comes with a built-in IEEE 1394
port, aka FireWire. Most digital video cameras sold today can
connect to this kind of port, making it easy to get movies into
your PC for editing.
</P>
<P>
   The 1394 port is right on the front (there's another in the
back) so it's easy to plug in your camera. Compaq also includes a
copy of MGI Software's VideoWave III, an excellent program for
editing video on a PC.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that buyers of this level of computer want just one
thing _ raw speed _ Compaq has made a major change in how it loads
software on the PC. The company is notorious for having all kinds
of software running in the background on its consumer PCs, from
virus checkers to programs that auto-download patches.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq still includes those programs on this computer, but
leaves them turned off by default. When you first turn on this
computer, you are running a basic Windows 98 SE installation. It's
up to you to turn on the features Compaq normally considers a
convenience, but which can rob system performance and conflict with
other software. The system comes with instructions for doing so,
but an all-in-one control panel would be more helpful.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it should be with all consumer computers, and
Compaq's taken the right step by giving users a choice. Here's
hoping other makers of consumer PCs follow its lead.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, I used a monitor from Compaq's commercial division,
the TFT8020, with this system. This is an 18-inch, flat-panel, LCD
display that doesn't come cheap _ $3,400.
</P>
<P>
   The 8020 is aimed at the financial and medical markets, as well
as anyone who wants a state-of-the-art, flat-panel screen. Unlike
most LCD monitors of this size, the bezel around the screen is
relatively thin, giving this a pleasing look.
</P>
<P>
   The screen is bright and very easy to see even from an angle,
with a standard resolution of 1,280-by-1,024 pixels. The monitor
accepts inputs from both digital and analog video sources, so it
can be used with almost any video card, and adjusts automatically
to the type of video signal it's receiving.
</P>
<P>
   It's an excellent monitor, but obviously not priced for the
masses. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
