<SLUG> BC-AHOLD-PEAPOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH CONGLOMERATE RESCUES PEAPOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peapod Inc. found a savior Friday in Stop &AMP; Shop's parent, the
Dutch supermarket conglomerate Royal Ahold NV, which will pay $73
million for a controlling interest in the ailing Internet grocer.
</P>
<P>
   Following the announcement, Peapod shares rose nearly 28 percent
on the Nasdaq Stock Market, closing at $3.1875.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy, particularly after the past several weeks,'' sand
Andrew Parkinson, acting chief executive and founder of Peapod,
which is based in Skokie, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 30 days, Peapod's struggles have reflected the
struggles of online retailers. After spending millions of dollars
on advertising and warehouses, many failed to make a profit and
line up new funding.
</P>
<P>
   After Peapod raised $58 million in an initial public offering
three years ago, its rapid-fire growth turned the company into the
largest online grocer. It now delivers deli meats, baked buns and
other grocery items to more than 130,000 customers in Boston and
other US markets.
</P>
<P>
   Peapod executives had hoped that investors would bring another
$120 million to the table. But the funding vanished after chief
executive William Mally resigned in March, due to health reasons.
Analysts have also cited high prices and growing competition as
reasons to eschew the online grocery industry.
</P>
<P>
   Ahold's investment clearly gives Peapod ``a second lease on
life,'' said Jeff Siegel, an analyst with Ormes Capital Markets in
New York. ``Without that, it's pretty likely that they would have
gone bankrupt.''
</P>
<P>
   Peapod lost $29 million on $73 million in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   Operating as a stand-alone company, Peapod is expected to play a
key role in Ahold's Internet strategy. The online grocer currently
serves nine markets, including Boston, where it has a relationship
with Ahold's Stop &AMP; Shop division. Those delivery services will
eventually be expanded to the Washington, D.C., area and to other
markets in which Ahold operates.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Ahold will provide space in its stores and
warehouses, supplying Peapod with groceries. With Ahold's
resources, ``there is now the potential for Peapod to grow faster
in a profitable way,'' said Hans Gobes, an Ahold spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Ahold operates five chains with more than 1,000 stores: Stop &AMP;
Shop; Giant Food of Landover, Md.; Tops; BI-LO; and Giant Food
Stores of Pennsylvania. The Dutch grocer's US sales reached $20.3
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the agreement, Ahold will purchase securities
convertible into Peapod common stock at $3.75 per share. Ahold will
own 51 percent of Peapod and have warrants to purchase up to 75
percent of the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
