<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-TECHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECH STOCKS DEALT ONLY A GLANCING BLOW, OBSERVERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Market-Worst)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's ferocious stock market backlash has bloodied the
high-flying tech stocks that have defined the ``new economy.'' But
company officials and investment experts say it's only a flesh
wound.
</P>
<P>
   Technology incubator CMGI Inc. of Andover, Mass. saw its stock
fall to $52.0625 on Friday, down more than 44 percent in one week.
But CMGI got off easy compared to Internet content-delivery company
Akamai Technologies Inc. of Cambridge, Mas., and Sycamore Networks
Inc., a Chelmsford, Mass. maker of optical networking equipment.
Shares in each of these companies lost more than 55 percent of
their value in the past seven days. Akamai slid from $145.69 to
$64.88, while Sycamore stock declined from $115.50 to $51.
</P>
<P>
   After months of warnings that tech company earnings couldn't
begin to justify their huge stock valuations, the recent selloff
seems like a nightmare come true. Still, there's no sense of panic
among the market makers.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cook, money manager at Munder Capital Management of
Birmingham, Mich., says tech companies are actually becoming
sounder investments, as more of them move to tighten up their
business practices and start delivering real revenues and earnings.
``As a matter of fact, the fundamentals of the businesses are
tending to get better, not worse,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   That's also the way CMGI spokesman Bill White sees it. ``We've
got plenty of cash,'' said White, ``we've got plenty of marketable
securities.'' And, he added, CMGI has a multilayered strategy that
should see the company through market downdrafts.
</P>
<P>
   White said that his firm's 16 operating companies, including the
Internet advertising company Engage Technologies Inc., will provide
$1 billion in revenue in the fiscal year ending July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should exit the year 2000 with a revenue run rate of $2
billion,'' he added. That's real money, enough to ensure CMGI's
viability, even if its falling stock price will make it harder to
do future acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Appledorn, also of Munder, cites CMGI as evidence that
investors are bailing out too quickly. ``I'll guarantee you that's
not 20 percent less of a company than it was yesterday,'' Appledorn
said. ``They're throwing a lot of babies out with the bath water
here. This is not a very discerning or discriminating market.''
</P>
<P>
   Akamai spokeswoman Karen Converse agreed. She echoed comments
made this week by Akamai chairman and chief executive George
Conrades that his company is the victim of a vicious shift in
market momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business is solid,'' said Converse. She pointed to this
week's deal with streaming media pioneer RealNetworks Inc. to help
broadcast audio and video over the Internet as proof that Akamai is
continuing its rapid growth. ``We're chugging away,'' Converse
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got one of the leading technologies that allow
Internet content to be delivered faster to end users,'' said Bill
Garrahan, who tracks Akamai for Lehman Brothers in Washington, D.C.
``We think they have a solid business model, providing part of the
base structure of the Internet. They should be a very successful
companies in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   But last week, few investors seemed interested in the long term.
When will that change?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a lot of good fundamental earnings
announcements'' from tech companies, said First Albany Corp.
analyst Ullas Naik, ``and it's going to take fortitude on the part
of institutional investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Naik said that a few days ago, he thought tech stocks were
already on the inexpensive side. ``Now, I think it's ridiculously
cheap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
