<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7334 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-WITH-BATTELLE-     04-14 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-BATTELLE-ART-$ADV6-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING WITH NICHOLAS S. BATTELLE: STANDISH SMALL CAP
TAX-SENSITIVE EQUITY FUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036 or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nicholas S. Battelle is fond of fly-fishing for lunker bass in
Boston Harbor and loves to tour the Berkshires on his motorcycle, a
1998 Triumph Thunderbird with 900 cc under the tank. But ask him
where his mind wanders as he frolics amid New England's natural
bounty, and he acknowledges: ``I think about work.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry David Thoreau, Battelle is not. But as portfolio manager
of the $263.3 million Standish Small Cap Tax-Sensitive Equity fund,
he has a work ethic that has produced some smart returns. The fund
gained 55.6 percent a year, annualized, for the three years through
March 31, compared with 35.2 percent for its category of small
growth funds, according to Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As its name suggests, the fund aims to minimize taxes. Its
annualized tax-adjusted return, assuming a 39.6 percent tax
bracket, is 55.3 percent over the same period _ just 0.3 percent
below its outright return. That compares with a tax gap of 2.4
percentage points for its peer group.
</P>
<P>
   The fund has a minimum investment of $100,000, so interested
individuals may want to consult a financial adviser, who can pool
clients' assets to help meet the requirement.
</P>
<P>
   In picking stocks, Battelle said from his office in Boston, ``we
look for small capitalization, aggressive-growth companies that
deliver high-octane growth, focusing on new companies with large
future potential.'' These are mostly companies with market
capitalizations of $300 million to $2.5 billion in the areas of
technology, business services and technology-related health care.
</P>
<P>
   With such a leaning towards new-economy stocks, it is no
surprise that the fund has not escaped the recent Nasdaq sell-off;
it fell 8.7 percent from March 10 through Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Batelle, 57, says his methodology is tried and true. ``Call
it old-fashioned security analysis,'' he said. ``Our stock-picking
process is more organic than systematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other money managers, he does not use computers to
screen company financial data. Instead, he works closely with the
fund's three analysts in look for companies with annual growth of
at least 20 percent _ but not necessarily profit growth. Because
two-thirds of the fund's companies are unprofitable, growth can be
measured in a variety of other ways. For Internet companies, they
consider customer volume and sales growth and evaluate business
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   They talk to management to assess a company's competitive
strength _ reviewing its products, product cycles, technology and
marketing. Battelle particularly likes companies that are only
beginning to gain market share but whose sales growth is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Any major changes in the portfolio's 70 or so stocks, he said,
must be approved by at least two of the four people who work on the
fund.
</P>
<P>
   He generally sells a stock when its price jumps 20 percent to 30
percent higher in a month than the overall market, or when it
exceeds 5 percent of the fund's assets. He may also sell when he
sees fundamental changes in the company or its industry.
</P>
<P>
   Selling can be tricky, given the fund's emphasis on minimizing
taxes. When a stock's price falls at least 20 percent below its
initial cost, it is usually though not always sold; the loss can be
used to offset gains in other stocks. The fund sold Great Plains
Software at $44 a share on Monday, generating one such loss; it had
bought the stock on March 1 at an average price of $67.
</P>
<P>
   The fund did not distribute any gains to shareholders in 1996,
1997 or 1998, but Battelle anticipates some gains this year, as he
has sold many stocks he bought at low prices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite last week's sell-off, he remains bullish on small
stocks. ``We've done the correcting, and much of the damage is
done,'' he said. ``I feel good about the prospects of small-cap
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Battelle sees bargains among some biotechnology companies, radio
broadcasters and even business-to-business Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent slump in its stock price, he likes Gene
Logic, a Gaithersburg, Md., company that builds genomics reference
databases, which map the human genome.
</P>
<P>
   The company is rapidly signing up subscribers among big drug
companies, researchers and health care organizations, he said,
calling its market opportunity ``open ended.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Subscriptions are high-octane revenues,'' he said, because
once they build the database and absorb marketing costs, additional
subscriptions are almost pure profit.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects the company to break even in 2002. He bought the
stock at $56 in January, before the technology sell-off; it now
trades at $25.4375, and Battelle has recently added to his
position.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is the CoStar Group of Bethesda, Md., which
maintains an online database of commercial real estate that is used
by brokers and corporate relocation managers. Subscriptions are
growing 60 percent a year, Battelle said, and the company will soon
offer online property auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Battelle bought shares in January 1999 at $18.56; they now trade
at $27.375. He expects the company to break even at the end of
2001.
</P>
<P>
   He also likes iGate Capital of Oakdale, Pa., an information
technology consultant that once specialized in solving Year 2000
computer problems. It now designs and builds Internet and intranet
systems to link company operations, customers and suppliers, he
said, and is an incubator for Internet businesses. Describing its
market opportunity as ``unlimited,'' Battelle expects initial
public offerings for seven of its nine subsidiaries this year.
</P>
<P>
   He bought the stock in January at $26.34. Despite the market
sell-off, the shares trade at $32.50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
