<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7344 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-NY     04-14 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: STOCKS' TAILSPIN MAY QUICKLY HURT ECONOMY, BOTH OLD
AND NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET and MARKET-ADVISORY-NYT) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The U.S. economy boomed as the stock market,
particularly technology stocks, soared to unprecedented heights.
Now, with those stocks suddenly much lower, will the economy cool
off quickly?
</P>
<P>
   Some economists think so. ``We are going to find that this tech
wreck and Nasdaq crash will have a much more immediate impact on
consumer spending than the interest rate hikes the Federal Reserve
has given us,'' said Ed Yardeni, the chief economist of Deutsche
Bank Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that forecast turns out to be true depends on psychology
at least as much as it does on economics. After all, even after
losing a quarter of its value this week, and a third since it
peaked barely more than a month ago, the Nasdaq composite index is
still higher than it was in November. Other stock indexes have
suffered much less damage.
</P>
<P>
   The booming stock market has clearly aided the economy, as
investors who felt wealthier spent more. The anticipation of higher
stock prices also helped. One survey late last year showed that the
typical investor expected the stock market to average 19 percent
annual gains for the next decade, a figure that is in line with
recent experience but far larger than long-term growth of the
economy is likely to support. Investors who believed that could
have felt less need to save, since their investments were likely to
keep rising. If that psychology changes, it could have an immediate
dampening effect on consumer spending, which has been rising
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retracement so far takes away only a small part of the
increase in financial asset values over the last few years,'' said
Henry Kaufman, an economist who runs his own money management firm.
He said it was likely to have ``only a modest economic retarding
influence,'' but added that a key ingredient would be whether the
latest market turmoil changed expectations about future gains.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, it was largely taken for granted that the
so-called new economy was largely immune to higher interest rates.
The stock prices of many older companies had come under pressure
after the Federal Reserve began raising interest rates last June,
on the expectation that such increases would eventually slow their
business. But the high technology part of the stock market soared
at an unprecedented rate. It was noted that few such companies had
borrowed large sums, meaning that they were not directly affected,
and it was thought that demand for their products would continue to
be strong even if the old economy faltered.
</P>
<P>
   However, the sudden weakness of the stock market may have a much
more direct impact on the new economy. Robert Barbera, the chief
economist of Hoenig and Co., noted that initial public offerings
and venture capital investments, most of them related to the
Internet, had brought in $150 billion for hundreds of new companies
since the beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that money was spent with the older technology
companies, as the new companies bought computers and software and
communications equipment. If the initial public offerings market is
now going to stop bringing in money, as appears likely unless the
market quickly turns around, that source of revenues will no longer
be available to companies such as Intel and Compaq and Lucent
Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact on the real economy will be faster than people
expect, and concentrated in technology,'' Barbera said.
</P>
<P>
   When the stock market crashed in October 1987, many economists
assumed that a recession would follow. The market was viewed as a
leading indicator of the economy, and surely a fall as large as
that one indicated a deep economic problem.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it didn't. In retrospect, the severity of the 1987
crash reflected market imperfections more than economic realities.
Many institutional investors thought they could protect themselves
by selling stock index futures when prices fell. But so many did so
that the selling overwhelmed the market, and sent prices down even
further.
</P>
<P>
   After that crash, the Federal Reserve immediately changed its
policy and began to lower interest rates. The New York economy, far
more dependent on Wall Street than other regions were, did suffer
to some extent. But most of the country continued to grow until a
brief recession arrived in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed also moved to cut interest rates when world stock
markets plunged in 1998, after the Asian crisis and Russia's
default on some of its debts alarmed investors. There was talk of a
worldwide recession, but it did not materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as in 1987, the Fed has been raising interest rates in an
effort to slow the economy. But it is not at all obvious that
Chairman Alan Greenspan will again reverse course. The release
Friday morning of the Consumer Price Index report, which was far
worse than expected and helped to accelerate the selling of stocks,
was viewed by some economists as providing a reason that the Fed
might decide to raise rates by half a percentage point, rather than
the quarter-point that was expected, at its meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, it is likely that the Fed will not stop raising
rates until there is clear evidence that something _ whether rising
rates or a plunging stock market or a combination of the two _ is
slowing the economy significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Another economic issue that could arise concerns the dollar.
Thanks in part to surging consumer demand, the United States has
been running a record trade deficit. That has not hurt the dollar
because foreigners were willing to invest those dollars back in
this country, many of them in stocks. If the flow of foreign money
into American investments slows, that could put the value of the
dollar under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no assurance that the recent decline of the
stock market will continue. Investors have responded to many falls
since 1987 by seeking to buy during the dips, and headlines about
plunging stock prices soon gave way to articles about new highs for
major indexes. This week's fall of 7.3 percent for the Dow Jones
industrial average was the worst since the index fell 7.6 percent
in the week ended Oct. 13, 1989. On the following Monday, the Dow
leaped 3.4 percent, and the fears were soon forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   That could happen again. But if it does not, one of the factors
that has pushed the economy to new heights will have been removed.
At a minimum, that means slower growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
