<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-LEGAL-NYT &LR;      04-14 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-LEGAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGAL ASPECTS OF ELIAN GONZALEZ CASE ARE CUT AND DRIED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CUBAN-BOY) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The legal battle over Elian Gonzalez turns on a narrow question
of law that makes the political fight over whether the boy should
be raised under communism virtually irrelevant to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   That question is who has the power to make decisions for the
6-year old child in deciding whether to seek political asylum in
this country, legal experts said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's father has said he does not want to seek asylum for
Elian but the boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, filed an
application in Elian's name on Dec. 10. He then sued when
immigration officials refused to accept the application.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is who speaks for the child,'' said Linda Silberman,
a professor at New York University Law School and an expert on
international child custody issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country,'' Silberman continued, ``we treat family
relationships as sacred. We don't go looking at whether people are
poor, at what people's political views are, and we only intervene
in a family when there is a very high threshold of proof that a
child is in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   The case centering on the asylum issue reached the federal
appeals court in Atlanta after a decision in federal court in Miami
went against the boy's Miami relatives. It has become the main
legal battleground in the case.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the suit that a judge on the appeals court issued a
temporary order on Thursday barring Elian's father from taking the
boy back to Cuba until the full court could review a request by the
Miami relatives to keep Elian in the United States while the court
considers their case.
</P>
<P>
   Most other issues that have been swirling in the news media and
politics _ including the question of what is in Elian's ``best
interests'' _ are peripheral and are expected to be swept aside as
the appeals court begins its examination of the case, legal experts
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez is contesting a March ruling in favor of the
federal government and the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, by
U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore in Miami. He ruled that
immigration officials had the power to decide, as they did this
winter, that the father, not the great-uncle, spoke for Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The father had told immigration officials in Havana in December,
``He should be returned immediately to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The immigration officials' decision, Moore said, was based in
part on two interviews they conducted with Gonzalez in Cuba in
December. The officials found no evidence that Gonzalez was an
abusive father, the judge said, which would be a ground to deprive
him of the presumption that he speaks for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said Congress had given immigration officials sweeping
powers to make such decisions and had sharply limited the power of
courts to review those decisions. Only when immigration officials
abuse their discretion, for example, by making decisions that have
no basis in fact, can courts overturn the rulings. The judge held
that in Elian's case there was no abuse of discretion by
immigration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the Miami relatives have asserted that the
father cannot speak freely because he is under the control of the
Castro government. When U.S. officials met with Gonzalez in Cuba,
they tried to assess whether he was able to answer freely by giving
him written questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   He answered that he was offended that the Miami relatives were
``questioning my paternity rights.'' The Miami relatives have said
such answers cannot have been freely made because the Castro regime
is authoritarian.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said it was standard in cases of small children
for their parents to speak for them. ``A bedrock principle of the
Constitution is that strangers and even relatives have no right to
interfere with a parent's right to custody of his or her child,''
said Michael R. Masinter, a professor of constitutional law at Nova
Southeastern University Law Center in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said there is no absolute age when children are
considered able to make decisions like whether they will seek
asylum. In one much-publicized case in 1980, a Ukranian immigrant,
Walter Polovchak, was considered old enough to seek asylum at age
12, even though his parents wanted him to return to Ukraine. But
the experts said they knew of no case where a child as young as 6
was considered mature enough.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said Friday that the legal posture of Elian's case has
been confused in public commentary about it.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the Miami relatives, for example, have advocated
that the decisions concerning Elian should be handled by a Florida
family court. They have said that is because a family court judge
would consider the ``best interests of the child,'' a legal
standard typically applied in state courts when there is a contest
over the custody of a child between two parents.
</P>
<P>
   That position gained support in early January, when a Florida
circuit court judge, Rosa Rodriguez, issued an order in favor of
the Miami relatives. But this week, a new state judge in the case,
Jennifer Bailey of Miami-Dade Circuit Court, said the boy's
great-uncle had no legal standing even to raise the question of
what would be in Elian's best interest. Florida family law holds
that he is too distant a relative to make a claim against the
father, she ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey also said the immigration official's decision to defer to
Elian's father's wishes superceded any state court power in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Further confusing the legal picture, the Miami relatives also
filed a separate suit in federal court in Washington Friday
asserting that Elian would suffer human rights abuses by the Cuban
government ``for having sought asylum'' if he were returned.
</P>
<P>
   Michael C. Dorf, a professor at Columbia University Law School,
said that would be a difficult suit for the Miami relatives to win
because it would give anyone who is dissatisfied with a decision
denying an asylum application a human rights claim. In addition,
Dorf said, the Washington court would be reluctant to wade into a
case that is already before the federal appeals court in Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
