<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-PAYOUT-615&AMP;ADD-N     04-14 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-PAYOUT-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD RESTRUCTURING TO STRENGTHEN FAMILY'S CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Ford Motor Co. on Friday announced a complex
revamping of its ownership structure, including the payment of a
$10 billion special dividend _ the largest ever by a U.S. company _
and the issuance of additional stock to the Ford family, cementing
its grip on the world's second-largest industrial corporation.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is designed to let Ford distribute nearly half of its
$24 billion cash hoard, one of the largest of any company in the
world, while minimizing taxes for its shareholders and giving the
Ford family greater financial flexibility, particularly for estate
planning.
</P>
<P>
   But the big cash disbursement could leave Ford somewhat more
vulnerable in a recession, although the company will still have as
much cash after the special dividend as General Motors has now.
</P>
<P>
   The dividend may limit somewhat Ford's ability to undertake
further large acquisitions; Ford bought Volvo Cars a year ago and
agreed last month to buy Land Rover from BMW. But Jacques A.
Nasser, Ford's chief executive, said that the company would not
rule out further deals.
</P>
<P>
   The recapitalization plan unveiled Friday is a delicate balance
between the interests of Ford Motor's public shareholders and the
interests of Henry Ford's descendants. Big institutional
shareholders and Wall Street analysts have been urging Ford Motor
since the mid-1990s to disburse some of its enormous cash hoard by
buying back stock.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ford family has always resisted share buybacks,
insisting on dividends instead because of the special class of
stock that the family holds.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford family holds all 71 million shares of the company's
Class B stock, along with a small number of the company's 1.1
billion common shares. Under rules that were designed to preserve
family control and were drafted when the company went public in
1956, the family holds 40 percent of the voting power at the
company as long as it continues to own at least 60.7 million shares
of the Class B stock _ even though the Class B shares make up only
6 percent of the company's overall equity.
</P>
<P>
   If the family sells too many shares of its Class B stock,
whether to pay estate taxes, cover personal expenses or simply
participate in a stock buyback, then the family's influence
shrinks. If the family's holdings fall to between 33.7 million and
60.7 million shares of Class B stock, the family wields only 30
percent of the voting power. And if the family's holdings fall
below 33.7 million shares then all special voting privileges are
lost.
</P>
<P>
   When Class B shares are sold outside the family, they revert to
common stock. Under Friday's plan, each holder of Ford's common or
Class B stock will be given a choice of receiving $20 a share in
cash or additional common stock.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Ford Jr., Ford's chairman and one of Henry Ford's 13
great-grandchildren, said that the members of the Ford family would
take additional stock for all of their Class B stock. Most if not
all family members would put the additional distribution into the
family's voting trust, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The extended family faces the problem of covering estate taxes
while preserving family control of the company upon the eventual
deaths of Henry Ford's two surviving grandchildren, Josephine F.
Ford and William C. Ford Sr., who are in their mid-70s. Friday's
arrangement will give the family $1.42 billion worth of common
stock to sell without touching their Class B stock.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor is reissuing its common and Class B stock as part of
the recapitalization, allowing the $20 special dividend for other
shareholders to be taxed at the lower rates for capital gains
instead of the higher rates for income taxes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ford Motor said that after the recapitalization, it would also
spin off its wholly owned auto-parts subsidiary, Visteon Corp., by
distributing all of the shares to all holders of common and Class B
stock. Visteon has $19 billion a year in sales, of which $17
billion are to Ford.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Ford Jr. said that he would definitely retain the
Visteon shares he received, and other family members were also
likely to keep them, providing another big asset for the family to
sell someday while safeguarding the Class B shares.
</P>
<P>
   The family had partially addressed the estate-tax problem in
1998, when Ford distributed to shareholders its 80 percent stake in
Associates First Capital Corp., a consumer lending business.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials said that their plan would not require special
approval by the Internal Revenue Service or the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Willens, a tax expert at Lehman Brothers not involved in
putting the deal together, agreed with that assessment. He said
that the special dividend would easily be the largest ever paid,
and that the overall deal did not appear to favor the Ford family
at the expense of other shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Girsky, an auto analyst at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
said that the distribution of common stock to the Ford family would
also align the family's interests more closely with those of other
shareholders in the future. The family will henceforth have common
shares to tender in any future stock buybacks by Ford Motor, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market welcomed Ford's plan, bidding up its stock
immediately after the morning announcement even as the rest of the
market plunged, although Ford shares also began to fall by early
afternoon and closed at $52.25, down $2.1875. But Standard &AMP;
Poor's, the credit-rating agency, lowered the rating on Ford's
long-term debt to A from A-plus, saying that Ford would have less
of a cash cushion for making bond payments.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has talked frequently in interviews over the years about
his desire to pass on the family's leading role at Ford Motor to
his children and grandchildren someday. Although hostile or
friendly approaches by potential merger candidates have sometimes
forced special dividends and share buybacks at other companies,
Ford said that the company was not under outside pressure and that
the family's role would continue to prevent this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal has always been, and will be as long as there is a
Ford family, to keep Ford an independent entity,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
