<HEADLINE>
LORD OF THE RINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lord of the Rings: The official Web site of the movie being made
from the beloved fantasy trilogy. &QL; 
Where: www.lordoftherings.net &QL; 
What's cool: The addition to this site of a two-minute trailer of
early shots from the movie, now less than halfway through 14 months
of shooting in New Zealand, with a December 2001 release date,
attracted a whopping 1.7 million downloads its first day. With more
than 1,200 visual effects shots (for comparison, ``Star Wars:
Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' had 1,000; no one else is even
close), the movie should be a treat for the eyes. The trailer
certainly is. You'll wish you had (or be glad you have) a fast
broadband connection, and you'll need the free Apple QuickTime
browser plug-in (available at the site) to view it all, but it's
worth it. It looks great. Be careful about that address, however;
www.lordoftherings.com takes you to a site owned by another
company, with little now but a long list of links (also useful for
hardcore fans) of other Lord of the Rings sites. &QL; 
Features: Other than the trailer from New Line Cinema, there's not
a ton of other stuff here yet, but there is a place to submit
questions for an ``Ask the Director'' segment, a brief audio
interview of director Peter Jackson, and overpriced editions of the
book with a special authenticated letter from Jackson. There's also
a program that dresses up your Web browser with various Ring
motifs. Give your Web experience that Straight Outta Moria look
that sets every Orcsta's heart a-thumpin'. &QL; 
You'll like this if: You want to know how you'll be spending your
Christmas 2001 holidays. &QL; 
---Think your Web fave is good enough for Site of the Week? Send
your suggestions to davidbloomearthlink.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
