<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-STOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD ON THE STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street did a lot Friday to solidify its growing reputation
for volatility, and everyone better get used to that fact of life.
In the process, the market erased a noticeable amount of worry
that, as Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan likes to remark
from time to time, stock prices had an irrational quality. There's
nothing like a falling market to make price-earnings ratios look
more reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's sharp drop in the Dow Jones Industrial Average, 616
points, liquidated about 6 percent of overall market value. It's an
impressive figure but one that pales alongside the 20 percent
plunge of Oct. 19, 1987, the worst single-day drubbing the market
had taken since the 1929 crash. Wild swings up and down in the
markets have become almost normal, thanks to widely shared
professional investment thinking coupled with the ability to make
buy-and-sell decisions in the twinkling of an eye. Computer
appraisals of markets and automated decisions further accelerate
the process. Those realities will not go away, and they virtually
guarantee future lurches up and down.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive has been the decline of the NASDAQ index, driven
primarily by sharp drops in high-tech names that have lost their
allure. Now off more than 30 percent from their highs of earlier
this year, these stocks have gone through more than a correction _
they have been pummeled. The bear is prowling among them. Painful
as that has been, the unreasonable values placed on companies
barely getting started in markets that are extremely competitive
made the selloff almost inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, prices begin to look very attractive, and there
is a lot of money eager for bargains _ or what look like bargains
after falls of this magnitude. The rush back into the market is apt
to be just as swift as the rush from it. Modern Wall Street is not
a quiet zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
