<HEADLINE>
INFLATION'S TOLL ON INFLATED MARKETS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miami, Mass., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than $2 trillion in investor wealth got
vaporized last week. It was the worst week in Nasdaq history, and
one of the worst in Wall Street's.
</P>
<P>
   While the stock market's ascent into the stratosphere in recent
months had been breathtaking, the speed with which this fortune
vanished was nothing short of stupefying. After the government's
announcement on Friday that the Consumer Price Index for March
showed broad and troubling increases, stocks across the board
collapsed. The Dow lost 5.66 percent, while the Nasdaq plummeted
9.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CPI kicked the market when it was down,'' said Christine
A. Callies, chief equity strategist at Credit Suisse First Boston.
``Investors had decided that valuations in tech were too inflated
and needed to be adjusted. When the report came out, investors
decided that the market P/E had to come down, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is growing at a 3.7 percent rate, year over year. Tony
Crescenzi, a bond strategist at Miller Tabak, said investors were
troubled by higher housing costs _ up 0.4 percent _ and medical
costs, which rose 0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report could be an anomaly,'' said James L. Crawford,
portfolio manager at Trevor Stewart Burton &AMP; Jacobsen in New York.
``But when you look back over the past year, inflation has been
creeping up. Most people wrote that off to oil, but those folks who
have been saying inflation is nonexistent have to rethink here.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a silver lining in these ominous clouds, some
investors may hope that the decline in stock prices means that the
Federal Reserve will be less aggressive in raising rates in coming
months. Not so, said Stephen S. Roach, chief economist at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a long way to go to rein in an economy that is
growing 6 percent-plus in the past six months and going full steam
ahead in the spring,'' he said. ``Mr. Greenspan cannot afford to
take his foot off the brake in this climate.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Nasdaq composite has fallen 34 percent from its March
10 high, the broader Wilshire 5000 index _ which Alan Greenspan,
the Fed chairman, watches as a proxy for the overall market _ is
down only 15.4 percent from its peak of March 24. As a result,
Roach said, he expects the Fed to raise rates one-quarter point in
May, again in June, again in August _ and possibly more.
</P>
<P>
   Callies says that while the Nasdaq has been mauled, the broader
market will not necessarily follow it into bear-market territory.
``The market was never as good as the Nasdaq made it look,'' she
said on Friday, ``and today it is not as bad as it looks, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors looking to hide amid the turmoil should consider
old-fashioned value stocks, Callies said, including shares in
metals and paper companies, and energy service and exploration
concerns. Crawford likes consumer companies that have been beaten
down, like Gillette and Colgate-Palmolive, and real estate
investment trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation frightened investors on Friday, but Roach said the
movement in prices was still modest. A more important shift was in
the levels of risk that investors seem willing to take. ``Valuation
does matter in the stock market,'' he said. ``We're getting down to
more reasonable levels in some of the more overvalued pieces of the
market. But with the fundamentals of the economy intact and
inflation signs minimal, stocks can find a level and hold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
