<HEADLINE>
THE RIGHT NOT TO REPRODUCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 16, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Medicine's breakthroughs have brought joy to many previously
infertile couples by helping them bear children. But these
procedures have also brought on difficult legal and ethical
dilemmas. One of these led recently to a sensible, if limited,
decision by the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled that a divorced husband could block his ex-wife
from becoming pregnant with a stored frozen embryo the couple had
created during fertility treatments. Even though the husband had
signed no fewer than seven documents saying that his wife could
make use of the couple's stored embryos if they separated, the
court wisely respected the divorced man's wish not to be made a
father against his will.
</P>
<P>
   The February ruling was followed recently by the court's written
opinion. Justice Judith Cowin wrote that ``respect for privacy and
liberty requires that individuals be accorded the freedom to decide
whether to enter into a family relationship.'' We agree.
</P>
<P>
   There have not been many court decisions in any state on issues
like this one, but those that exist have tended to uphold couples'
agreements as being enforceable contracts. Still, as Robin Charo,
professor of law and medical ethics at the University of Wisconsin,
notes, in the other cases upholding the agreements did not mean
obliging anyone to become a parent unwillingly.
</P>
<P>
   At age 44, the unnamed woman in the case has limited options for
becoming a mother again (the couple did have twins with in-vitro
fertilization), so it is easy to understand her resolve to have the
agreements enforced. Still, the most recent was signed in 1991,
before the birth of the twins. The issue comes down to whether we
as a society want to give greater weight to the right to become a
parent or not to become a parent.
</P>
<P>
   On that, the court was clear: ``As a matter of public policy, we
conclude that forced procreation is not an area amenable to
judicial enforcement.'' Plainly, the court is feeling its way
cautiously in an area that will provide it _ and society _ many
more difficult, anguishing questions to address in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
