<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BENJERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE CREAM ECONOMICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 16, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The words cash and cachet come from different linguistic roots,
but they often go hand in hand. That link is not lost on Unilever,
the multinational consumer-products corporation that has just
bought up Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade, the Vermont ice-cream company
with a social conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics trumpet the company's sale to the $45 billion Anglo-Dutch
monolith as a triumph of cutthroat capitalism over down-home,
tie-dye economics. But Unilever would be as nutty as Ben &AMP; Jerry's
Rainforest Crunch if it did not live up to the promises it has made
to maintain the social and environmental agenda established by Ben
Cohen and Jerry Greenfield when they started out in a converted
gasoline station in Burlington in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers pay Ben &AMP; Jerry's premium prices not just because of
the products' high fat content and whimsical names, but also
because they know that the company buys its milk from Vermont dairy
farmers _ at above-market prices _ to support family farming and
sends a chunk of its profits to a range of charities. That's the
cachet that distinguishes Ben &AMP; Jerry's from Haagen-Dazs.
</P>
<P>
   Another retailer who has made this formula work is Patagonia,
the outdoor clothing maker. Based in California, the firm also has
New England roots _ its founder, the rock-climber Yvon Chouinard,
grew up in a French-American home in Lewiston, Maine. A cult-like
following developed for Patagonia gear both because of its quality
and because the company devotes a percentage of its sales to
save-the-Earth causes, not least the recent successful effort to
destroy the Kennebec River dam in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   Just how serious Unilever is about pursuing Ben &AMP; Jerry's
traditional causes can be seen in one provision of this week's $326
million deal: If any Ben &AMP; Jerry's board members think the
corporation is not maintaining the mission and decide to sue,
Unilever will pay their legal fees. Indeed, Ben Cohen says he will
look at ways to improve Unilever's overall record of protecting the
environment. Strange things can happen when Big Business mixes with
the Grateful Profitable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
