<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEETCENTER LAUNCHING CRUISE TO PLACATE BIG-TICKET FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It will be a combination Schmooze Cruise and Love Boat.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at the FleetCenter, fearing the worst after the Bruins
and Celtics went into the tank, will take some of their customers
on an all-expenses-paid cruise to Bermuda in September. The reason
is to try to keep these people in their seats _ literally _ and
keep them putting their dollars into the FleetCenter's vault.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have the kind of year (financially) we thought we
were going to have,'' said FleetCenter CEO Rich Krezwick. ``We were
counting on both the Celtics and Bruins to play at least two
playoff games each, and in the process keep their fans excited
about the future. That didn't happen. Now we have to try to keep
them happy some other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's Krezwick's problem: When the FleetCenter opened five
years ago, many customers who purchased luxury suites averaging
more than $100,000 per year signed five-year leases. Those leases
are up, and if the people decide not to re-up, which they could
well do after the two stinkers the Celtics and Bruins submitted
this season, then the FleetCenter will take a big financial hit.
</P>
<P>
   It will be more of the same next year with the preferred seat
licenses. Before the building was opened, preferred seats, which
run anywhere from $11,000 to $14,000 per year, were sold in three-,
six-, or nine-year packages. The six-year licenses expire next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to do everything we can to keep these people
happy, and with us,'' said Krezwick.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the FleetCenter chartered a cruise ship for a week
trip to Bermuda, paying back customers for the Celtics games missed
because of the NBA lockout, and running up a tab of more than $2
million in the process. This year they won't take the whole boat,
but they will spend more than $1 million trying to keep the
possible defectors aboard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, your humble servant went to Buffalo for an
important late-season Saturday game between the Jets and Bills.
Three hours before kickoff, YHS went to the field looking for Bill
Parcells and through the fog saw a figure in the distance. It
wasn't Parcells. It was Keyshawn Johnson, already in uniform, while
the rest of the team hadn't left the hotel yet. I asked Parcells
about it and remember his response.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my years of coaching, (Keyshawn) is the only player I
ever had that beat me on the first bus to leave for the stadium,''
Parcells said. ``When I get on, he's already sitting there. When we
get to the stadium, he doesn't hang around shooting the breeze, or
reading the paper, he's into his uniform, out on the field ready to
go. This guy is all football player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets did not want to let Johnson go. They know he is one of
the best players in the league. He catches, blocks, doesn't make
mistakes, stays in great shape, and wants the ball when the game is
on the line. However, even though Johnson has just four NFL seasons
under his belt, he will turn 28 next season.
</P>
<P>
   Keyshawn had two years remaining on his original Jets contract.
He signed a six-year deal and the Jets gave him a huge bonus to
sign for that long with no loopholes. As I remember it, the Jets
offered a four-year deal, a five-year deal, or a six-year deal with
the bonus money going up with each year. Johnson took the six, but
after four he wanted more money and out of the contract, and the
Jets, strapped for cash, couldn't give it to him.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets could have forced him to play out the final two years
of his contract, and then made him their franchise player. But they
didn't want to keep hearing about Johnson's contractual problems or
having him hold out of training camp, so they decided to take the
two first-round picks Tampa Bay put on the table. Tampa allegedly
gave him a record-breaking eight-year, $52 million contact. But
upon inspection, it is really a five-year deal for $25 million,
with $13 million up front in bonus money. Some $27 million of the
deal is in the final three years, when Johnson will be in his
mid-30s, and he'll never see that money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harry Sinden believes Ray Bourque may get his wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to take one team now to win the Stanley Cup, it would
be Colorado, and mainly because of Ray,'' Sinden said. ``He's been
the missing piece for them. They had a lot of good players, but
they are playing at a higher level now because Ray is there. He is
the best player in hockey for leading by example on the ice. Ray is
not a rah-rah guy, but once he gets on the ice there is no one that
tries to play the game better than he has. The style of game they
are playing in Colorado is more conducive to Ray's skills than the
kind of hockey we played with the Bruins the past year. Colorado
has a positive, aggressive kind of game. We were backing up all
year, and playing without any confidence. My only concern about
Colorado winning it all is Patrick Roy. He's either great or lousy
in the playoffs. If he's great, I think they will win it all, and
Ray will have a big part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden feels the four best teams in hockey are all in the
Western Conference _ Colorado, Dallas, St. Louis, and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever wins in the West, should beat the East winner,''
Sinden said. ``But more upsets happen in hockey than any other
sport in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East is more difficult to predict. I still think the
best-balanced team is New Jersey, and I give them the best chance,
but they haven't played well lately. Washington has been the most
consistent team in the East for quite a while. Ottawa, Toronto,
Philly, Buffalo are all capable of pulling an upset. Any one of
these teams has a goalie who gets real hot and they could be
playing in the (Stanley Cup) finals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino on the NBA playoffs: ``I liked the Lakers to win it
all before the season started, and I still do. They have really
matured as a team this season. The only team that can give them any
trouble in the West, in my opinion, is San Antonio. But if Tim
Duncan's knee injury is serious their chances are diminished. When
they are healthy, they are a good club. I don't know what has
happened to Portland. They should be better than they are but I
can't explain the way they have played.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the East, I think it will come down to Indiana and New
York. The Pacers have the most depth and the greatest home-court
advantage in the league going for them. (Their) new building is
something. It creates a college kind of atmosphere with the Pacer
fans. Go to one of their games and you think you are at the ACC
tournament. If they get to a seventh game at home against the
Knicks in a playoff series, home court will be big for them. I
think Indiana is the only team in the East that could beat the
Lakers. I'm not saying they would, but with their depth, and their
shooting ability, if they shot the ball well for the whole series
they could do it. They're not that great on defense, so they have
to be very good on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bill Russell is everywhere. When Pitino was down and out
emotionally after his team lost a tough game to the 76ers last
week, Russell showed up in the Celtics' dressing room and spent 90
minutes with Pitino after everyone had left the building.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino told friends later: ``It was one of the nicest things
that has ever happened to me. Here was one of the greatest ever to
play the game, sitting there all the time trying to cheer me up.
I'll never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forty years ago Ron Burton was the first player ever drafted by
the Patriots, and he hasn't stopped running since. Saturday night
will be honored by the Salvation Army at the Berklee Performance
Center in Boston for the tremendous works of charity he has done
across Massachusetts for four decades.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
