<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SOCIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVING SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 16, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A recent report by the trustees of Social Security concluding
that the system is on sound financial footing for the next three
decades ought to quiet talk that it needs to be radically
transformed. Instead, Congress should focus on improving benefits
for people who must retire early and have few resources except
their monthly Social Security checks.
</P>
<P>
   A bill signed by President Clinton last week will not address
that problem. The law allows workers between the ages of 65 and 69
to earn whatever they can and still collect Social Security
benefits. Under the old law, their Social Security checks would be
reduced if they earned more than $17,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and congressional leaders were congratulating themselves
on a major achievement, but it is no such thing. The $17,000 limit
was scheduled to go up to $30,000 in two years in any event. The
unlimited earnings exemption will mainly apply to people earning
high incomes, and it is unclear how many will take advantage of the
change.
</P>
<P>
   This new law will not have any effect on the solvency of Social
Security. In the old system, anyone who delayed collecting payments
until age 70 would get a higher monthly check. This feature is
retained in the new law, which will still give many seniors an
incentive to wait until 70.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore had a better idea for improving the
system when he urged that special attention be paid to widows and
widowers.
</P>
<P>
   Women on average live 20 years after age 65; men only 16 years
more. Under present law, if the husband dies first, the wife loses
the smaller of the two Social Security checks, often nearly half
the family's monthly income. Gore would guarantee that these widows
(and widowers) would receive at least 75 percent of that amount. It
is a sensible proposal that would provide a much-needed financial
cushion for women in the last years of life.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's other proposal would compensate people who care full-time
for children for the lost wages that would otherwise help them get
higher Social Security benefits in retirement. It would only
produce $600 or so in additional money a year, and much of that
would go to people who already have enough saved for a comfortable
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not put a price tag on either proposal, but plans to
finance them by paying down the national debt, using the money that
would otherwise have gone for interest payments. Even with the good
news on Social Security finances, all that money will be needed to
pay the benefits already in place for the baby boomers. His first
proposal is worth the extra money; his second is not.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the vice president have a solution for one of the major
problems in the system: how to better provide for those who must
retire on reduced benefits at age 62 because they are no longer up
to the strain of physically demanding work. Most of these jobs do
not pay much, and these people often depend on Social Security as
their primary means of support in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   One way to help these people is to raise benefits for low-income
workers, as long as they have worked at least 40 to 45 years. This
condition would focus extra resources on people who started work
just out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   This change would require more money, and few political leaders
are talking about the best way to raise that: an increase in the
amount of income subject to the payroll tax, which now cuts off at
$76,200. During the last two decades, the pay of high-income
workers has gone up far more than people earning modest wages. Some
of this money ought to be redistributed to help those in less
lucrative careers.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees of the Social Security system now estimate that
they can provide full benefits until the year 2037 without making
changes in the existing schedule of eligibility or payments. This
estimate is inherently flawed by the long time period it must
cover. If the economy grows faster than the trustees expect, the
system can continue making full payments indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   In case it does not, Congress needs to adjust the benefit levels
and retirement criteria slightly to keep the system solvent. And it
should invest a small portion of the trust fund in the stock
market, which usually produces a far better return than the
interest on US government bonds, where the Social Security surplus
is now invested. As Congress adjusts the system to prepare for the
retirement of the baby boomers, it should keep in mind those
Americans who must retire early because they are no longer up to
their jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
