<SLUG> BC-MARKET-IPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS' TUMBLE LIKELY TO DAMPEN IPO MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET and MARKET-ADVISORY-NYT) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The initial public offering market, on fire for the
last 15 months, will probably cool off a great deal in the wake of
the market's sharp slide.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the market stabilizes and begins to rise soon, two things
will happen quickly: the volume of offerings that come to market
will decline and the quality of the companies that successfully
sell stock will improve.
</P>
<P>
   The market's downdraft ``will put a big bump in the road,'' said
Kathy Smith, portfolio manager of Renaissance Capital's $100
million IPO Plus Aftermarket Fund.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the sell-off, ``the market will be a lot more
discriminating'' about the deals it will buy. ``You won't see
so-called story stocks, companies with an idea but no financial
results. Only the better companies will get through the window,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than attempt to sell new stock into a falling market,
companies and their investment banks are choosing to postpone the
deals.
</P>
<P>
   In the week just completed, just under half of the 50 initial
public offerings and secondary stock offerings were priced.
</P>
<P>
   ZEFER Corp., an Internet consulting and services firm that has
been in business for two years, was one company that chose to delay
its offering. And the company seems in no hurry to come to market
until conditions are noticeably better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan to go public was driven by a great market opportunity
rather than a need for cash,'' said Bill Seibel, ZEFER's chief
executive. ``Unlike many companies, we have the luxury of going out
in three weeks or three months or nine months.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the stock market declined ZEFER had been on track to
price 4.5 million shares, a little less than 10 percent of the
total stock outstanding, in a range of $11 to $13 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Before ZEFER comes back, valuations in the market ``would have
to be a little better,'' Seibel said, ``and the volatility would
have to decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two companies are on the calendar for next week,
according to Renaissance Capital. As of late Friday, four have
already been postponed and more may follow.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a quick improvement in the market, Smith estimated that
about 25 percent of the 300 initial public offerings scheduled for
the balance of the second quarter will not get done.
</P>
<P>
   ``And another 25 percent will get done at greatly revised terms
to attract investors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Underwriters are guardedly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe a number of deals will be priced over the next
couple of weeks in spite of the most difficult overall market
environment we have seen in some time,'' said Mike Curtis, a
managing director in equity capital markets at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter.
</P>
<P>
   A key test of demand for yet another technology company will
come early next week, when AltaVista plans to sell 14.8 million
shares at $18 to $20 a share. The company runs a popular Internet
search engine. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter is the lead underwriter
for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, market corrections have always drained life out of
the initial public offering market. But since the crash in 1987 the
downturn in activity has not lasted long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Significant stock market corrections see equity underwriting
fall from the peak quarter to the bottom quarter by well over 50
percent,'' said Guy Moszkowski, an analyst who covers Wall Street
firms for Salomon Smith Barney. ``A decline of 50 percent or more
is not out of the question. I think we are in for something like
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
