<HEADER>
A7394 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-CHURCHES-HNS &LR;      04-14 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CHURCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SLAMS BUSH IN CALLING FOR GUN BAN IN PLACES OF WORSHIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Democratic presidential contender Al Gore called
for the banning of guns in all places of worship Friday as he
sought to remind voters of Texas Gov. George W. Bush's gun-control
record and two recent church shootings in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning a three-day California trip, the vice president said
he would support legislation introduced by a number of Democratic
senators that would prohibit the use of firearms in churches,
synagogues and mosques, and places where school events are held.
</P>
<P>
   In pushing the additional gun-control measure, Gore tried to
underscore the differences between himself and his Republican rival
on a campaign issue that Democrats believe will work in their favor
in the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Governor Bush's record on gun violence; lax
enforcement of gun laws, more concealed weapons, guns in churches.
America deserves better,'' Gore said in prepared remarks for an
address at a youth community center in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has generally not backed stringent gun-control measures and
in 1995 enthusiastically signed into law a measure that allows
people to carry a concealed weapon in Texas
</P>
<P>
   Two years later the governor signed off on a change to that law
that allowed those with permits to carry concealed weapons to bring
them into places of worship unless those facilities specifically
posted signs banning firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of bringing guns into church rose to the forefront
after two gruesome incidents in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In September a man fatally shot seven people in a Fort Worth
church before killing himself. And in March a man wielding a gun
walked into a church in the Houston suburb of Pasadena and wounded
a former lover and three others before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded to Gore's attack by noting that the
vice president's native Tennessee approved a concealed weapons law
in 1994, which they said was similar to Texas law and allowed
citizens to carry guns in churches. They claimed the measure was
sponsored by Gore's longtime friend, state Sen. Roy Herron.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said that
if Gore was really opposed to concealed weapons laws ``why didn't
he speak out when a concealed carry law was passed in his home
state of Tennessee, where residents can also carry guns in
churches.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush officials justified the 1997 changes to the Texas law
giving church officials discretion on whether to allow guns on the
property. They said many ministers who lived on church grounds were
concerned that they could not protect themselves and their families
if they could not carry a gun.
</P>
<P>
   In his address at the Washington United Youth Center in San
Jose, Gore also touted a number of other crime control measures,
including ensuring that federal law enforcement officers are not
used for other purposes, hiring of 50,000 more community police
officers, and stiffening penalties for those who commit violent
crimes in front of children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was later scheduled to attend a Democratic National
Committee fund-raiser in nearby Atherton, where the party hoped to
raise $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   He then was expected to fly to Los Angeles where he will join
President Clinton on Saturday night at a Hollywood fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
