<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-IMF-PROTEST-ART-975(2     04-14 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-PROTEST-ART-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON PROTESTERS NOTABLE FOR THEIR DIFFERENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Protesters for global justice call their
headquarters a convergence center, and the abandoned downtown
warehouse does seem to attract all kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Propped up against a mound of backpacks and surrounded by the
remnants of a donated macrobiotic lunch is James Osborne, a
23-year-old self-described ``transient'' from St. Louis. Osborne
said he took a Greyhound Bus to Washington because ``someone told
him'' about destructive pipeline projects and bad trade policies.
``I believe there should be no leadership and no organization,'' he
said, though he rejected the label of anarchist.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, David H. Richardson, a 57-year-old Ph.D. economist
at the U.S. Department of Labor, checks the schedule for civil
disobedience actions intended to shut down the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund. Richardson is a shop steward of the
American Federation of Government Employees, and says he worked
hard to persuade the national union to endorse the officially
sanctioned portion of the demonstrations scheduled for Sunday,
which it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor is at the point that it needs support from outside the
movement,'' said Richardson, looking a little like a headmaster in
a high-school playground. ``Globalization brings a lot of different
people together.''
</P>
<P>
   If they accomplish nothing else, this week's series of protests
against the financial institutions and in favor of debt relief for
the Third World do seem likely to confirm Richardson's observation.
Globalization and the backlash against it bring disparate people
together. The cry to temper the march of capitalism around the
globe comes from voices as diverse as the Catholic Church, a cell
of anarchists and many people and organizations in between.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether this unlikely coalition of protesters
and interest groups is, like so many grains of sand blown together,
liable to scatter once its members make a collective point or
achieve individual goals. Or, as some leaders hope, whether it is
the foundation of a new social movement that will apply sustained
pressure on national governments and international institutions to
rewrite the rules of globalization and limit the power of
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Though some environmental groups began pressuring international
financial institutions to become more ecologically sensitive two
decades ago, the movement is still in its infancy. The big bang for
American organizers came only a few months ago, during the Seattle
protests against the World Trade Organization, when they took
credit not only for befuddling police but also for contributing to
the collapse of world trade talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington protests, which began last Sunday with a quiet
rally for debt forgiveness and will culminate this Sunday with an
effort to prevent world finance ministers from attending the spring
meetings of the World Bank and the IMF, are the second big test for
the movement. While it is having some social and political impact,
its main achievement is probably logistical: uniting groups with
different agendas around a common cause and attracting new
recruits, especially college students and unionized workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met some steelworkers and we bonded right away,'' said
Margareta Lelea, 20, a sophomore at the University of
California-Davis. The agricultural development major, who stuck a
green star on her face for ``ecological awareness,'' came early to
Washington to attend nonviolence training seminars at the
convergence center. It is the first major protest she has attended,
though she sympathized with those who opposed NATO's bombing of
Kosovo last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought of union people as interested in the same
issues, but they are,'' she said. ``There's all kinds of
interconnections being made. Without interconnections there's no
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   The joke among lieutenants who pulled together the protest is
that there are as many 501-C-3s in their ranks as there are people,
a reference to the IRS form that independent, nonprofit groups must
file each year. The movement against the World Bank and the IMF is
in some way less a mobilization of the masses than a convention of
nongovernment organizations _citizens groups that have individual
agendas, fund-raising campaigns and, in many cases, leaders with
large egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we got people together is that we let everyone
represent their group. They don't have to join our group,'' said
Kevin Danaher, a founder of Global Exchange, one of the groups
instrumental in igniting the protests in Seattle and Washington.
``Is a lot easier for people to compromise when they don't really
have to subordinate their egos.''
</P>
<P>
   Danaher is 49 years old, tall and bald with a white goatee. He
traces his roots as a protester to the anti-apartheid movement in
the 1980s. More recently, he has led campaigns against Nike,
persuading the company to improve conditions for foreign factory
workers, and Starbucks, in which he successfully urged the coffee
chain to sell coffee produced under the TransFair ``fair trade''
label that claims to share profits with farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Danaher is a smooth talker who has traveled the country,
speaking at scores of campuses as a kind of Paul Revere for
globalization's woes. ``We have to put the life cycle ahead of the
money cycle,'' is a phrase he uses often. But he says he is just an
adviser to the protests against the World Bank and IMF.
</P>
<P>
   To hear him describe it, the movement has thrived in part
because it rejects the straight-jacket of a typical political or
social movement, with its leaders and head offices and official
strategies. That allows groups to flow in and out without draining
the movement as a whole. Greenpeace, one big player in the world of
environmental activism, used to campaign against the World Bank and
IMF, but has no official role in this weekend's events.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial lieutenants of the Mobilization for Global
Justice, as the Washington protests were named, have used the
Internet to connect environmental, religious, labor and student
groups that would otherwise not be in regular contact, some 500 of
them in total.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of citizens groups autonomously coordinating
strategy has proved its effectiveness. A Rand Corp. study for the
Pentagon detailed how Mexico's Zapatista rebel movement in 1994
used media-savvy tactics _ a ``social netwar,'' the study dubbed it
_ to generate support abroad for its campaign against the North
American Free Trade Agreement. The study said swarms of independent
citizens groups can prove far more effective than the hierarchical
movements when combating established institutions because they
can't easily be ``decapitated.''
</P>
<P>
   Danaher admires the Zapatista model. ``We also have a
mosquito-bite strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the movement's strength, but it is also a weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the main backers worry that the movement's successes to
date have been purely tactical _ headline-grabbing civil
disobedience and a flair for organization. They fret that the
coalition could blow apart as quickly as it came together.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the strains are showing. Though religious groups are
one of the main forces behind debt relief, they have refrained from
any direct involvement in the demonstrations this Sunday. Instead,
they scheduled their own rally last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Oxfam and Greenpeace, two the best-known names in social and
environmental activism, have severed formal ties to key umbrella
coalitions of protesters, though members of both groups are still
participating in the protests. The split came about partly over
goals. Oxfam officials, for example, say they have made progress
trying to reform the World Bank, and getting government to agree to
debt relief. Global Exchange, in contrast, wants the bank and fund
abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much of this has been about tactics, getting all these
groups together and keeping things moving,'' said John Sellers, of
the Berkeley, Calif.-based Ruckus Society. The observation is
especially poignant coming from Sellers, a Greenpeace veteran who
moved to the Ruckus Socity several years ago. He runs training
camps around the country to teach varied protesters the mechanics
of civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   Over a beer at a Washington bookshop-cafe one recent evening,
Sellers seemed unsure whether the movement could sustain its
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if we're going to have a center of gravity we have to
figure out really what we want and where we go from here,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
