<SLUG> BC-GORE-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CALLS FOR A BAN ON WEAPONS IN CHURCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Vice President Al Gore said Friday that if he
were elected president he would support a ban on weapons in
churches and other places of worship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houses of worship have always been sanctuaries, and they
should remain that way,'' Gore said. ``I say that pistols have no
place in our pews. If I'm entrusted with the presidency, I will
fight for a national ban on guns in churches, synagogues, mosques
and all places of worship as well as places where school events are
held.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a ban has little support in Congress. But Gore's objective
was to publicize the fact that Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, his
probable Republican rival for the presidency, had signed a law
allowing gun owners to carry concealed weapons into churches. About
20 other states, including Gore's home state of Tennessee, also
allow guns in churches.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign immediately pointed out that Gore never
objected when Tennessee passed its law in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore was really opposed to concealed carry and guns in
churches, why didn't he speak out when a concealed-carry law was
passed in his home state of Tennessee, where residents can also
carry guns in churches?'' Ari Fleischer, Bush's spokesman, said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign hopes that calling attention to the fact that
Bush signed such a law will help scare suburban swing voters away
from Bush. In an indication of his attempt to appeal to
independents and Republicans, Gore praised Republicans like Gov.
George Pataki of New York who have supported gun control measures.
And, mindful of the large numbers of hunters and sportsmen in swing
states like Pennsylvania and Michigan, he said repeatedly that he
would not interfere with their rights. But he made his announcement
in California, which has been in the vanguard of clamping down on
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic senators plan to introduce a nonbinding resolution
banning guns in churches before the Million Mom March, to be staged
May 14 in Washington to protest gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his comments at the beginning a three-day campaign
swing across California. His trip was primarily a money-seeking
venture, with excursions into the cash seas of Silicon Valley and
Hollywood bringing in more than $5 million at three events.
</P>
<P>
   His first stop was at the home of Jesse Singh, the chief
executive of the BJS Group, a distributor of computer components.
About 140 people, most of them Sikhs celebrating the Sikh New Year
Friday, paid $1,000 each to listen to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The event was the final fund-raiser in Gore's drive for about
$34 million for his own campaign. But he still has plenty to raise
for the Democratic National Committee, which has set a goal of $100
million. He made a dent in that goal Friday night with a
fund-raiser that was expected to bring in $2.6 million. That event,
hosted by Joel Hyatt, a business professor at Stanford University
and son-in-law of former Sen. Howard Metzenbaum of Ohio, was
attended by nearly 100 people, who paid up to $100,000 for their
tickets.
</P>
<P>
   His third fund-raising event was scheduled for Saturday night in
Hollywood with President Clinton, their first outing together since
Dec. 9. That event is expected to raise more than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his announcement on guns in the gymnasium at the
Washington elementary school here in front of members of City Year,
a national youth service organization and a branch of AmeriCorps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will fight to protect America's families by launching the
most aggressive and comprehensive anticrime strategy that our
nation has ever seen,'' Gore declared, with Gov. Gray Davis of
California standing at his side.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a ban on guns in churches, Gore said he would
create a special trust to set aside federal money for crime
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that while Bush has called for better enforcement of
gun laws instead of gun control, Texas had lax enforcement. He
suggested the governor was in the clutches of the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
