u s BC-OLY-EQUESTRIAN15-COX     04-14 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-EQUESTRIAN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Florida town pinch-hitting as site for equestrian trials
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOXAHATCHEE, Fla. _ Planning for an unexpected influx of
Olympian hopefuls and their finely tuned horses comes down to small
details _ the flagpoles, the flowers, the finger food _ and big
ones: seating the spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Equestrian Team decided in March to move the Olympic
dressage trials from its New Jersey headquarters to Palm Beach
County because the West Nile Virus, which attacks people and
horses, had reappeared in the Northeast. The sudden move spurred
local hosts and organizers into a trot to get ready for the big
event, set for May 13-14 and May 20-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just beavering around out here,'' said Mary Ann McPhail
of Horse Park at Equestrian Estates, where the nation's top 12
riders will vie for four Olympic team spots and two alternates.
``We're doing all the things we usually do for a big show, plus a
little extra. This is for the Olympics, and we want it to be
special.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be special for spectators _ the USET isn't charging
admission to the trials, except for a limited number of
``preferred'' seats under the cover of a tent with the added perks
of drinks and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   That will cost $20 per day, or $30 for a two-day pass for each
weekend. Preferred seats can be requested by telephoning the USET
headquarters at 908-234-1251.
</P>
<P>
   For those who don't want or can't get tent seating, Horse Park
will have hundreds of folding chairs set up around the main show
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Dressage (pronounced dre-SAZH) is known as the figure skating of
horsemanship. The horse does intricate step patterns, gaits and
maneuvers, controlled by the rider with nearly imperceptible
movements.
</P>
<P>
   The trials will start with a test ride of the course at 8 a.m.
each day, with competition beginning at 8:30. The 12
horse-and-rider teams will perform a series of required maneuvers
at specific locations in the arena, while five judges score their
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   On the final day, May 21, the horses will perform freestyle
programs to music, but must include all the required movements in
the performance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
