<HEADER>
A7409 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MARKET-FREEFALL-BOS &LR;      04-14 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-FREEFALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS EXPERIENCE HISTORIC DECLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stocks were pummeled Friday as this year's roiling market
collapsed in response to reports of rising inflation and the advent
of a bear market in technology shares. The three major stock
indexes suffered the biggest point declines in their history.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq Stock Market, home to most of the country's most
important technology companies, concluded its worst week ever, a
selloff that spread in waves to the entire market. The trigger was
a government report issued Friday morning that said consumer prices
spiked last month and may force the Federal Reserve to raise
interest rates again in May.
</P>
<P>
   The slide accelerated as the day wore on, a dramatic finale to a
week in which the Dow Jones industrial average lost 7 percent of
its value and the Nasdaq Composite index lost a record 25 percent.
Technology stalwarts such as Intel Corp. and Microsoft Corp. and
Internet startups went into freefall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the bust side of the (economic) boom,'' said Allen Sinai,
president of Primark Decision Economics, a Boston consulting firm.
``This is a severe, not unexpected, and huge correction _ and
possibly a bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   As investors tried to unload shares into an already shaky
market, buyers of stock virtually disappeared, an ominous sign of
what's to come Monday, Wall Street experts said. The Dow's
617.78-point drop was steeper than the 1987 stock market crash,
though the percentage decline of 5.66 percent was far below the 20
percent drop on Oct. 19, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq, which fell every day last week, has never had such a
rough time. The index sacrificed 355.49 points, falling to 3321.29
_ that is, 1125 points below its level a week ago. Friday's
percentage decline of 9.66 percent was the tech index's biggest
one-day drop since the 1987 crash, a time when Nasdaq was not
nearly as important in the financial markets as it now is.
</P>
<P>
   An 83.20-point decline, to 1357.31, in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index _ a measure of the performance of the broader market _ was
also its biggest ever. All but one of the index's 88 industry
groups dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street experts said myriad forces spurred an exodus from
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In an ominous sign, nobody was buying Friday. Not mutual fund
managers, who had been responsible for the Nasdaq's remarkable
snapback from the brink in recent days. Not technology-stock
addicts whose portfolios were under water. And certainly not
conservative investors with much to lose in a treacherous market.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Nasdaq, you've gotten into a liquidity trap,'' said Jay
Suskind, head of trading for Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co., a regional brokerage
firm in New Jersey. With buyers ``drying up,'' investors ``sell the
liquid names that trade in the Dow to meet their margin
requirements or to raise cash.''
</P>
<P>
   And investors of all stripes were selling stocks to raise money
for steep tax bills, due Tuesday, on gains scored during the
market's unprecedented rise last year. Unable to sell tech stocks,
investors were forced to sell stocks in other companies and
contributed to the Dow's rout.
</P>
<P>
   Selling by speculators all week continued Friday. Speculation
has caused the Nasdaq to spike up and down in recent months as
borrowing against stock holdings to buy shares rose to a record
$278.5 billion last month. Last week, these investors were no
longer jumping in to buy tech stocks each time one lost value and
instead were selling shares to cover margin calls.
</P>
<P>
   Datek Online Brokerage Services in Iselin, N.J., reported Friday
that margin calls _ requirements that investors in declining stocks
put up more cash _ were ``in the thousands,'' said spokesman
Michael Dunn. When the market is rising, margin calls are sometimes
no more than ``a handful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really bad,'' said Mark Minervini, chief investment
strategist for Quantech Research Group in Connecticut. ``People are
going to think about it over the weekend, and they are going to get
scared we'll get another down day and they're going to sell. It's
starting to push people out of the market entirely.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology, financial, retail, and manufacturing _ no industry
was spared during a day in which traders were dumbfounded by a
flood of orders to sell.
</P>
<P>
   More than six stocks fell for every one that rose on the New
York Stock Exchange, where trading of 1.3 billion shares was the
Big Board's eighth-most active day. On the Nasdaq, 2.5 billion
shares changed hands, the second-most on record.
</P>
<P>
   It was what Wall Street experts said Friday was predictable
fallout from a technology market that ran up 86 percent in 1999 and
was destined to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Leading tech stocks down Friday were Qualcomm, which fell
$21.125 a share, and Intel, which dropped $10.625. It was a
disastrous ending to a week in which dozens of tech stocks dropped
more than 25 percent, including Oracle Corp., National
Semiconductor Corp., Nortel Networks Corp., EMC Corp. and Cisco
Systems Inc. Some smaller companies, including CMGI Inc., Sycamore
Networks, and Firepond Inc., fell by half during the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq now stands at two-thirds of its March 10 high of
5048.62 and has returned to levels last seen in November. But could
fall more, analysts said. Everyone seemed to agree tech stocks were
wildly overvalued _ and they still are, according to said Ned
Riley, chief investment strategist for State Street Global
Advisers, division of State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's rout, share prices for the Nasdaq's top 100
stocks were still 90 times earnings of the companies. The Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500 index, by comparison, was valued at closer to 13 times
earnings. ``Nasdaq has further to fall,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could go down to 3000,'' said Michael Browne, head of
European equities for Chase Global Asset Management Inc.
</P>
<P>
   For technology, April has been a cruel month: Five of the
Nasdaq's 10 biggest percentage declines occurred this month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the stock market will remain fragile at least
until the Federal Reserve meets May 16 to set interest rates. The
fed may boost rates another half-point in response to the US Labor
Department's report Friday that consumer prices accelerated in
March. A 0.7 percent rise in inflation was the CPI's biggest
monthly increase in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The market's freefall dates to April 3, when a court decision
went against Microsoft Corp. in the software company's antitrust
case. Since then, troubles have compounded: In sympathy with
Microsoft, tech stocks across the board tumbled, the economy
continued to show signs of overheating, and investors grew
increasingly jittery as pessimism spread.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the impact of Friday's rout on the economy is
unclear. Primark's Sinai said a plunging market presents ``a
serious risk'' of recession. A decline in stocks could damage
consumer and business confidence and undermine a decade-long
economic expansion that has been fueled by both.
</P>
<P>
   But Nicholas Perna of Perna Associates in Richfield, Conn., said
the market's drop may preempt the need for another round of
interest-rate increases by Fed chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the big things he'd been complaining about was how the
wealth effect was making the economy grow too fast,'' Perna said.
``The wealth effect works both ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
