<HEADER>
A7413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-FAIR-BOS &LR;      04-14 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-FAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET ME AT THE E-FAIR? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, April 17, 2000)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1964 Unisphere, the 1939 Trylon and Perisphere, and other
World's Fair collectibles just went up in value: The United States
has announced it will not participate in this summer's world's fair
for the first time in their 149-year history. Corporate America's
lack of interest in Expo 2000, to be held in Hannover, Germany, is
ironic given the global economy; the expositions have traditionally
been showcases for the achievements of industrial technology. This
year, business decided it had better ways of flashing its wares to
an inquisitive public: The Internet strikes again.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers had no luck raising the $40 million it would have
taken to set up an American pavilion, even though they approached
most of the top corporations (US law allows no public money to be
used for such a venture). Instead, a modest Web page will be put on
the Internet to celebrate America's cultural achievements.
</P>
<P>
   That bodes ill for any repeat of America's own great fairs and
for their dramatic symbols. The 1939 New York World's Fair
epitomized the yearning for dramatic structures that set majestic
themes for such events. In Brussels, nearly 20 years later, the
Atomium expressed the great hopes for peaceful exploitation of
nuclear energy _ tarnished a bit in the execution. Seattle followed
with its Space Needle, New York again with the Unisphere in 1964-65
and Montreal produced Habitat, a marvelous jumble of irregularly
shaped dwellings that drew a stunning 50 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th century fairs _ London's Crystal Palace in 1851, the
Philadelpia centennial fair in 1876, and Chicago's Columbian
exposition on the 400th anniversary of the ``discovery'' of
America, all celebrated strides in technology that reshaped the
world forever.
</P>
<P>
   Never again? The pace of life and of change has accelerated
still more, and the world may no longer have time to assemble
exhibits that can be outdated before they are completed. It is a
shame, as there is nothing like a world's fair to stir the
imagination and turn futuristic fantasies into warm memories of
epic grandeur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
