<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD SCRAMBLE OF TRADES EXPECTED IN THE OPENING ROUND OF THE NFL
DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Psychics who populate late night television could not
accurately predict what will happen in Saturday's National Football
League draft. Let the trades, mind games and hyperbole begin.
</P>
<P>
   Are the Jets moving up, down, or sideways? Do they keep their
four first-round picks? Do they package them and make a run at
Cleveland's top selection? Or, as expected, will the Browns
finalize a contractual agreement with Penn State defensive lineman
Courtney Brown before the draft begins at noon.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, the agent for Brown, Marvin Demoff, was in
intense negotiations with the team. League officials believe that a
deal will be reached early Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's deal might likely be a long-term contract that is not
drastically different from the one signed by last year's No. 1
overall pick, quarterback Tim Couch. Brown's contract is expected
to be in the seven-year, $45 million range with a signing bonus of
between $12-$13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's probable selection by Cleveland is the only thing that
seems mildly solidified. The rest of the first round is expected be
a wild scramble of trades and near-trades. The phone lines of teams
in the NFL will be burning hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of trades that have already happened is rare in our
league's history, and those trades will continue on Saturday,''
said Ernie Accorsi, the Giants' general manager. According to a
league official, even the Giants considered a trade, speaking to
the Baltimore Ravens about their fifth pick. The Giants were
interested in acquiring Virginia running back Thomas Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the top 10 to 13 spots in the first round is
volatile,'' Accorsi continued. ``The reason why is the talent is
very good, and a lot of teams are scrambling to get into that top
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Each team in the Top 10, a league official said, has been
contacted about trades either from another team in the top 10, or
from teams outside of the first 10. Cleveland, Washington (2
selections), Cincinnati and Baltimore _ teams that own the first
five selections _ have all considered accepting trade deals to go
lower in the draft, only to, for now, rebuff those talks.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Jets have dealt wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson to
Tampa Bay for two first round picks, then made another trade with
San Francisco, which means New York has the 12th, 13th, 18th and
27th picks. The Jets are clearly the draft's superpower.
</P>
<P>
   Where things stand now overall in the draft is uncertain.
Baltimore is considering staying at the fifth spot and taking
Florida wide receiver Travis Taylor with the fifth pick and either
Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis or a defensive lineman with the
10th selection. However, the Ravens have received numerous offers
from teams for the fifth pick, and may yet still trade it on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals also continued to listen to trade offers Thursday
night. The Philadelphia Eagles, selecting sixth, have called
several teams about moving into the top five, but also have called
teams outside of the top 10 about moving down. What they do today
depends on what happens immediately ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   Quite simply, there is a feeding frenzy. Teams know there is a
scramble to move all over the draft board, and no one wants to be
left out of the mix. It is the NFL's version of musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally when there is a lot of talk about how there will be a
lot of trades, nothing ends up happening,'' said Accorsi. ``But
this time where this is smoke I definitely think there is fire.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
