<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-LOSSES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT IN THE GYRATIONS OF A VOLATILE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MARKET; see also MARKET-ADVISORY) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. _ Caught in the capricious swings of a
volatile stock market, HearMe, an Internet company, has had a
remarkable ride since it went public a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Priced at $18, its stock went as high as $51.25 that day, but by
the next day it was trading as low as $36.375. Its chief executive,
Paul Matteucci, son of a butcher and a man with street-wise
sensibilities, chooses not to acknowledge the opening-day peak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shot up to 51 for 10 minutes,'' he said. ``We think of the
high as $36.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that perspective helps soften the blow dealt this week.
With the Nasdaq ebbing into bear territory, HearMe's stock, at $20
a week ago, went into free fall. It closed below $12 on Thursday
and traded as low as $7.50 Friday before ending the day at $8.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that one analyst says HearMe, which makes software for
voice chat over the Internet, is clearly stronger than it was a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a climate that can alter a company's prospects in the course
of a trading day for no easily discernible reason, employees and
executives in the high-technology industry have found creative ways
to cope with _ and tune out _ what they cannot control.
</P>
<P>
   Executives must manage expectations of investors, partners and
acquisition candidates, sometimes uncertain of the company's value
from one day to the next. They must calm employees unsure whether
they will have enough for the down payment on a house and who are
besieged by job offers from competitors.
</P>
<P>
   A look inside HearMe illustrates how one Silicon Valley company,
and its rank-and-file employees, cope financially and emotionally
with being caught up in the market's volatility.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, many of the company's 250 employees, working in
two buildings just down the block from Netscape at the center of
the Silicon Valley universe, simply refuse to look at the stock
price. They decline to calculate their net worth. Like a mantra,
they stress over and again how much they like their colleagues,
product and mission, as if saying it enough times will mask the
fluctuation in their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to look at the stock price until the end of the
day,'' Matteucci said. ``If I happen to see the stock price on my
browser, I try to forget it as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockwise, what matters, he insists, is how the company's shares
perform relative to its competitors'. He preaches to employees that
if they focus on ``building products for great markets,'' the stock
price will follow. And he notes that the company, which had $6
million in revenue and a $6.1 million net loss in the fourth
quarter of last year, still has $60 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci said 90 percent of his employees realize that it is
pointless to be distracted by the stock price, while the other 10
percent _ ``including some very key people'' _ get to hear his own
story of youth and the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   He tells them he spent eight years at Adaptec, a company that
makes PC cards, joining just after it went public at $10. The stock
languished at $5 for much of his time there, but rebounded
dramatically, and he later sold his shares at more than $200, on a
split-adjusted basis.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story that might be worth hearing in and around the
cubicle of Nate Wright. Wright, 26, who joined the company in
December as a manager of Web content partnerships, has seen his
fortunes _ at least on paper _ fall with those of the company. Its
stock was trading in the high 30s as recently as December, but now
Wright's stock options _ the right to buy a set number of shares at
a given price, around $25 in his case _ are worthless.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other guys were making fun of me for my strike price,''
Wright said, laughing, as if they were making fun of a bad haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Wright belongs to a breed of young workers who give both
lifeblood and fits to high-tech companies. They bring crucial
skills, but some feel something is wrong if they are not the next
millionaire, said Jim Schmidt, HearMe's executive vice president
for engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, at his third startup, does not hide his interest in
cashing in. While many others here play down this week's stock
slide, Wright, downing Mexican food and Mountain Dew in the
cafeteria, said, ``Yeah, I pay attention.'' John Alexander, the
human resources director, periodically deflects these concerns,
when the stock dips. He said he reminds employees that it takes
four years for employee stock options to vest fully anyway.
</P>
<P>
   To maintain confidence among employees and investors, Matteucci
has not sold any of his 1.2 million shares, including options.
``I'd like to be in a position to sell 20,000 shares a quarter,''
he said. ``But I don't like to sell when people are watching and
it's this volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the gyrations are not without material impact. For
example, HearMe has made two key acquisitions this year, and the
stock's volatility had an effect on both.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the company negotiated to acquire Resounding
Technologies, whose software lets people talk directly from PC to
PC, rather than through a server. During negotiations, HearMe's
stock dropped to $10, then started climbing. Resounding executives
would say, ``The stock rose 3 points today; what caused that?''
Matteucci recalled. ``We told them what we knew, which wasn't a
whole lot.''
</P>
<P>
   During negotiations in February and March to purchase AudioTalk,
the stock was again fluctuating. To compensate, the sides built
into the negotiations a clause to fix a rough dollar value to the
transaction, rather than a number of shares.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it is a little clearer why the stock is fluctuating.
During a December roller coaster ride, the stock started at 17,
rose into the mid-30s, then dropped into the 20s. But in that case,
the moves seemed tied to a new product and distributions
announcements, while the drop seemed tied largely to a falling
market, said Matt Finnick, an industry analyst with Thomas Weisel
Partners in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Finnick said HearMe was a much stronger company than it was a
year ago, when it went public as Mpath Interactive. And this week's
steep fall, he said, cannot be traced to anything it is doing
wrong. ``It's the market,'' he said. ``It has nothing to do with
the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, the stock falls on good news. It did so on Jan. 19,
after the company announced better-than-expected revenues. ``We
went down,'' Matteucci said, shrugging. ``I have no idea why.''
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it was no surprise that Friday, with Nasdaq down
almost 10 percent and HearMe losing a third of its value, he was
focused on other things. ``I haven't checked the price yet,'' he
said just after the final bell, trying to tune out the cacophony of
a cascading market. ``Do I want to know?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
