<SLUG> BC-GORE-HOLLYWOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD OPENS ITS ARMS _ AND POCKETS _ TO GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bill Clinton has long been treated like a star by
Hollywood's movers and shakers, who have opened their gilded
pocketbooks and glamorous homes to the charismatic president.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Clinton's understudy, Al Gore, is angling to move up to
leading man, some of Tinseltown's biggest names appear ready to
shower their affection on the presumptive Democratic presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Clinton will be the main attractions Saturday night at
a Democratic Party fund-raiser in Beverly Hills hosted by David
Geffen, Steven Spielberg and Jeffrey Katzenberg, the trio that
heads DreamWorks production company whose most recent movie,
``American Beauty,'' swept the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   At what DreamWorks spokesman Andy Spawn called an ``intimate
dinner for 125,'' the Democrats anticipate collecting $2.5 million,
with the entertainment industry stars and moguls shelling out
between $25,000 and $100,000 a piece to see and hear the president
and his possible successor.
</P>
<P>
   The star-studded event at the Greystone estate, a 12-acre spread
where the movie ``Ghostbusters 2'' was filmed, is an indicator that
Hollywood's affinity for Democrats has not changed all that much
this election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee spokeswoman Jenny Baucus called
the rare joint appearance by Gore and Clinton ``a symbolic passing
of the torch.'' But Baucus also played down the importance of
Hollywood dollars in the upcoming election saying, ``We enjoy
support all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the Hollywood dinner, Clinton and Gore will be stumping
in Silicon Valley, helping the party raise more money from the
high-tech wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance with Gore at the DreamWorks event, however,
may also be a way of helping the vice president mend fences with
some in the entertainment industry, who were furious with the vice
president' wife, Tipper, for leading a campaign in the mid-1980s
against lewd and violent rock lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure Hollywood is as comfortable with Gore as they are
with Clinton. They don't know him as well as Clinton and what they
remember about Tipper's crusade makes them uncomfortable,'' said
Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a political analyst at the Claremont Graduate
Schools in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   But Spahn said the tension between Gore and the industry is
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was 15 years ago. A lot has changed since then,'' said
Spahn. ``There has been a lot of dialogue. Certainly the vice
president and Mrs. Gore have taken a very responsible approach to
the issue of violence in America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood endorsements have proven a financial windfall for
the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Democrats raked in $2.6 million in entertainment
and media contributions, known as ``soft money,'' or unrestricted
giving to political parties, according to a study by Common Cause.
Geffen, Katzenberg and Spielberg, who hosted a Democratic
congressional fund-raiser at the same location last year, forked
over a total of $238,000 to the party in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Republicans received a total of $804,220 for the
year from the entertainment industry.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's presidential campaign also scored well in the trendy
90210 Beverly Hills zip code, where he received $285,350 in
restricted campaign donations compared to $149,876 for Bush,
according to breakdown of giving from Jan. 1999 through January of
2000 prepared by the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Empire mogul Hugh Hefner as well as actors Candice
Bergen, David Caruso, Jack Nicholson and producer Aaron Spelling,
who developed the steamy teen TV hit ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' all
chipped in to help Gore.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republicans do receive their share of contributions
from Hollywood executives who believe in playing both sides of the
political fence.
</P>
<P>
   And although GOP politicians have long mocked Democrats' link to
liberal Hollywood, their presidential candidate George W. Bush last
year was well received at a cocktail reception attended by a number
of high-profile studio executives and actors, including Warren
Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   However, David Horowitz, a conservative activist in Hollywood,
said that Bush's move to the right in his primary against John
McCain dampened enthusiasm for the Texas governor among Hollywood
Republicans whom, he said, tend to be more libertarian than
socially conservative in their ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was on a real roll in this town until then,'' Horowitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Khachigian, a California-based Republican consultant who
worked with McCain, said that aside from a number of outspoken
conservatives, such as Charlton Heston and Tom Sellick, he does not
expect Hollywood to cross over in large numbers to the GOP this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are mostly on the left,'' he said. ``The kind of money
they have is obscene, and the big government programs with the big
taxation does not affect them and assuages their consciences.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the industry who may have had past qualms about Tipper
Gore's anti-lewd lyrics campaign say the Republicans have not been
better on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Rosen, president of the Recording Industry Association of
America, noted that in 1997 Bush approved a measure that would have
banned state investment in companies that produce objectionable
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not like Tipper is the bad guy and George Bush is the
good guy,'' said Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas amendment, aimed at curbing ``gangsta'' rap music, was
attached by a state senator to an appropriations bill that was
signed by Bush. It was later thrown out by a state court judge in
Austin who ruled that the music amendment could not be hitched to a
bill that dealt primarily with unrelated matters.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen and others said that many in the music and movie industry
base make their political choices on issues unrelated to their
careers and tend to favor the Democrat's positions on such issues
as abortion, gun control and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   But back in 1988, when Gore first ran for president, his wife's
crusade clearly hurt him among the Hollywood set. In 1985 Tipper
Gore, upset at the music her then-teen daughter Karenna was
listening to, joined a number of spouses of lawmakers and Cabinet
officials to lobby the recording industry to place parental warning
labels on records with particularly violent or pornographic lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   The music industry and rock musicians, led by Frank Zappa,
condemned the effort, which was highlighted at a bizarre Senate
hearing, where musicians such as Dee Snider of Twisted Sister
squared off with then-senator Gore over the meaning of song lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later when Gore sought the Democratic presidential
nomination a number of liberals shunned him as the backer of
censorship. Tipper, who was mocked as a prudish scold,was often
greeted cooly on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   But as evidence that times have changed, Snider recently said
that he would vote for Gore, although he acknowledged his choice
had more to do with his disdain of the Republican alternative.
</P>
<P>
   And the late Zappa's widow, Gail, has been a big fan and donor
to the Democratic Party, contributing $114,000 in soft money last
year.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats benefit financially from the Hollywood backing,
it is unclear whether such high-profile support translates into
more votes either in the all important state of California or
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Gore adviser Bob Shrum said the splashy DreamWorks fund-raiser
was not intended to sway voters in a state and city that is
accustomed to celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   But others say that the Hollywood glamor can rub off on the
candidate, particularly if it helps him get on the local news in
the tough Southern California market, where politics generally
ranks far behind highway chases and animal stories in news
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Standing next to Barbra Streisand and David Geffen can help
turn out the cameras,'' said Dan Schnur, a Republican political
consultant who recently worked on the McCain campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
