<HEADER>
A7421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CLINTON-ATLANTA15-COX     04-14 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ATLANTA15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Impromptu stops take political edge off Clinton visit to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All they expected was to see the limousine drive past.
Or maybe a wave from inside the tinted windows.
</P>
<P>
   But then the big black car stopped. As a tall, gray-haired man
emerged from the back seat, a cheer erupted from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton had come to Holy Innocents' Episcopal School
in north Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing,'' said Molly Collins, a senior at the
1,500-student school, after shaking the president's hand. ``School
has pretty much stopped for the day. We kind of skipped class.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's impromptu stop _ impromptu to the degree that Secret
Service agents had time to erect temporary plastic poles and yellow
police tape for a makeshift rope line before the president arrived
_ was just a small part of his nine-hour tour of Atlanta on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Clinton used an 11 a.m. speech to the national
Education Writers Association to highlight his support for tougher
public school standards. In an exclusive residential neighborhood
near Holy Innocents', he helped U.S. Rep. Cynthia McKinney (D-Ga.)
raise $300,000 for her re-election campaign (and took an indirect
swipe at the Confederate emblem on flags in Georgia and other
Southern states.). At a hotel near Hartsfield International
Airport, he feted U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) on his 60th birthday
_ and helped him raise $500,000 in campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   The extended visit reflected that Clinton's time in office is
drawing short. His remarks throughout the day sounded as though he
were delivering valedictory addresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in 25 years I'm not running for
anything,'' he told the 300 people at McKinney's fund-raiser. ``And
I'm OK with it _ most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   He used his speech to the writers association to review the
accomplishments of his administration. And he told McKinney's
supporters _ many of whom were black or natives of foreign
countries _ that he had tried to improve relations between people
of different ethnicities.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the McKinney event that Clinton criticized the use of
Confederate emblems in state flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's Atlanta, the home of more international companies than
any other American city, and we're still fighting in the South
about whether there should be a Confederate flag,'' Clinton said.
``There's something wrong with this picture.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not specifically mention Georgia's flag, however. His
comment came after Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes, who has declined to
take a position on changing the state banner, had left the event.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lewis party, Clinton recalled meeting the long-time civil
rights leader a quarter-century ago when both worked on former
President Jimmy Carter's campaign. Lewis told the then-29-year-old
Clinton stories of the civil rights marches of the '60s, including
one at Selma, Ala., where Lewis was beaten by state troopers as he
tried to cross the Edmund Pettus bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how quickly time passes,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Lewis has forgiven those who attacked him, Clinton
said, teaches him valuable lessons as he prepares to leave office.
Like Lewis, Clinton said, he hopes to forgive ``those who beat us
up, at least with words.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political purposes of his Atlanta visit, Clinton
found time to mingle with ordinary Atlantans _ at least those lucky
enough to be bystanders during his pre-arranged appearances.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the McKinney fund-raiser, at the home of a
physician and his wife, Clinton crossed the street despite a chilly
drizzle to greet several neighbors. Nine-year-old Jackson Davis
handed the president a photo of Air Force One, and Clinton
autographed it for him.
</P>
<P>
   At Holy Innocents', students clad in navy blue shirts and khaki
shorts or pants lined the road. Clinton joked with one student
about his role in the school play, and shook hands with dozens of
children before getting back in his limousine.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children will remember this forever,'' said school
librarian Barbara Berryman, standing amid a group of kindergarten
students.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Dana Tofig contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
