<HEADER>
A7426 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-1STLD     04-14 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HEALTH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-830(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL NEGOTIATORS REACH TENTATIVE AGREEMENT ON HMO
APPEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to rewrite and to expand by 350 words) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a breakthrough, House and Senate negotiators
said on Friday that they had reached a tentative agreement on an
appeals process for patients denied care by health maintenance
organizations, a major issue in legislation to define patients'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, patients could obtain ``an independent
medical review'' of any decision in which an HMO denied care or
coverage on the ground that a particular service was not medically
necessary or was experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Patients could also obtain an independent review whenever an HMO
concluded that a particular item or service was not a covered
benefit. The review might be done by lawyers if it involved only
the interpretation of an insurance contract. But it would be done
by doctors if it involved a medical question _ whether, for
example, a surgical procedure was purely cosmetic or was needed to
correct a medical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement does not resolve several other contentious issues
still before the conference committee negotiators, but it is the
most significant agreement Democrats and Republicans have had on
the patients' rights legislation to date.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest such issue is whether patients should have a federal
right to sue HMOs for injuries caused by the delay or denial of
care. But negotiators said that a well-designed appeal process, by
resolving disputes promptly, could reduce the number of lawsuits.
Moreover, the agreement suggests that the conferees have begun to
develop a fragile sense of trust and cooperation that may help them
resolve the stickier issues.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and HMOs, foes in the debate over patients' rights,
reacted favorably to the agreement. In separate interviews, Dr.
Thomas R. Reardon, president of the American Medical Association,
and Karen M. Ignagni, president of the American Association of
Health Plans, said they were encouraged by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a step in the right direction,'' Reardon said. Ignagni
said Congress ``appears to be calling for a system driven by
scientific evidence and the best medical practice,'' not just by
the opinion of a patient's treating physician.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, the Oklahoma Republican who is chairman of the
conference committee, said, ``This is a substantive, significant
agreement that will guarantee patients have access to an
independent medical review if a plan denies them health care.''
Under the agreement, Nickles said, patients in ``every
employer-sponsored plan in the country'' _ 125 million people _
would have the right to an independent review of health plan
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   After six weeks of negotiations, Republicans and Democrats from
the House and the Senate issued a detailed summary of what they
called a ``bipartisan bicameral agreement'' on the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
   Patients would pursue their appeals by going to an ``independent
external review entity,'' which could be a unit of a medical school
or a nonprofit corporation. This entity would then select one or
more doctors to do the actual reviews. The doctors would have to be
experts in a field relevant to the patient's case.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cautioned that it was an agreement in principle, a
conceptual agreement, to be translated into legislative language
over the spring recess. Lawmakers are still haggling over the
criteria to be used in deciding whether the denial of a claim can
be appealed. But Democrats confirmed that the conferees had made
substantial progress on one of the most important provisions of the
legislation to define patients' rights.
</P>
<P>
   A number of states have laws or regulations that require managed
care plans to have some type of ``external review'' procedure so
patients can challenge a denial of care or coverage. In general,
HMOs, state officials and consumer groups say the appeal procedures
have worked well. Reviewers rule in favor of patients in about half
the cases, for insurers in the other half.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers say the appeal procedures can raise the standard of
medical care, by requiring doctors to heed the views of outside
experts when deciding whether a particular treatment is
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives like Nickles and liberal Democrats like Sen.
Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts found they could agree on the
proposition that medical decisions should be made by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ernie Fletcher, R-Ky., a member of the conference committee
and a family doctor, described the agreement as ``a major
bipartisan breakthrough.'' Under the agreement, Fletcher said, ``if
your HMO denies the care you need, you will be able to appeal, thus
ensuring that medical decisions are made by physicians, not by
insurance bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement sets forth a wide range of factors that would have
to be considered by medical reviewers. Specifically, it says, their
decisions would be based on a patient's medical condition and
medical records; ``valid, relevant scientific evidence and clinical
evidence, including peer-reviewed medical literature''; and the
consensus of experts on what treatments were appropriate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The agreement includes these provisions:
</P>
<P>
   _Patients could appeal if the denial of a benefit created a
significant risk to a patient's life or health, or if the value of
the benefit exceeded ``a significant threshold'' to be specified by
the government.
</P>
<P>
   _A patient filing an appeal could be required to pay a $50 fee.
The money would be refunded if the patient prevailed. Low-income
people would not have to pay the fee.
</P>
<P>
   _The Department of Health and Human Services would set standards
to ensure that reviewers had no conflicts of interest and no
financial incentives to rule in a particular way.
</P>
<P>
   _The decisions of independent medical reviewers would be binding
on HMOs and other health plans. The plans could not appeal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. Michael A. Stocker, president of Empire Blue Cross and Blue
Shield in New York, said his company had been allowing patients to
appeal the denial of health care services for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legal challenges to Empire have substantially decreased over
the last few years,'' Stocker said. ``I'd like to think that's
partly because of the external review process, which gives patients
a sense of assurance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
