<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dueling With Dollars (or Francs, at the Least) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   France's two battling billionaires are at it again. Like boys
boasting the better stamp collection, Bernard Arnault, the chairman
of LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, and his archrival, Francois
Pinault, who owns the Au Printemps department stores, have a
history of wanting what the other covets. Last year, Pinault won
their fight for control of Gucci. Also last year, when Pinault
plunked down $1 billion for Christie's, Arnault bought the smaller,
but still fine auction house Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   So few people were surprised last week when Arnault announced
that he was paying $3.8 million for the exquisite French art
magazine Connaissance des Arts. The main attraction for Arnault?
Maybe that Pinault also coveted it. But then the two have also
faced off over prized collectibles. In 1995, in a legendary bidding
war, they competed at the Paris auction house Drouot for a
magnificent 18th-century secretary in Japanese lacquer by one of
the great makers of the age, Bernard van Risenburgh. That time,
Arnault won, too, for roughly $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   _John Tagliabue &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Economist in Demand &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in six years, Paul Krugman, economist and
author, is changing universities, joining Princeton and leaving the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``I am surprised at myself
that I am doing this,'' Krugman said. ``My wife and I did not want
to make a change now, but there was the offer on the table, and we
asked ourselves, `Would our lives be a little easier?'''
</P>
<P>
   Krugman, 47, will have a joint appointment as a professor in the
economics department and at Princeton's Woodrow Wilson School. His
wife, Robin Wells, 41, also an economist, will do research at
Princeton in the theory of the firm. Krugman is a columnist for The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   At Princeton, he will teach three courses every two semesters _
half his load at MIT. His appointment, effective this summer,
carries the same salary, he said, as at MIT, between $150,000 and
$200,000 a year. Wells will also have a lighter load, but roughly
the same five-figure salary as at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Krugman's parents recently moved to a retirement community near
Princeton, and being closer to them was one reason for his move. He
is their only child. The Krugmans left MIT for Stanford in 1994,
then returned in 1996. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Louis Uchitelle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking His Jet and Going Home &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warren A. Stephens, chairman of the company whose holdings
include the Stephens Inc. brokerage firm, has this message for the
University of Arkansas: Move any football games back from Little
Rock, my hometown, to Fayetteville, your more remote hometown, and
I won't let you play with my jets any more.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the Razorbacks have divided their games between
Little Rock and Fayetteville. The costs of renovating the
Fayetteville stadium prompted the school to move about a game a
year back from Little Rock to Fayetteville, effective this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephens says that moving even a game a year dashes his own
plans for fixing up the Little Rock stadium. No longer will
Stephens underwrite the post-game shows that supplement the coach's
salary, nor will his firm's six jets ferry coaches on recruiting
missions. As Stephens put it, ``The whole level of our support for
the Razorback program is up for review right now.''
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Barnes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hero of Versailles? It's New York &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best place to find businesspeople to support repairs to
Versailles, where Louis XIV's gardens were blasted by storms last
Christmas? Try New York. And so last week more than 100 guests
including Richard and Kathy Hilton (as in the hotels); Lawrence
Herbert, chief executive of Pantone Inc. and his wife, Michele; and
the investor Peter Price and his wife, Judy, raised several hundred
thousand dollars to mend the estate, as well as to keep up Claude
Monet's Giverny. At the Carlyle hotel, this slice of mostly
American royalty was welcomed by Prince and Princess Michael of
Kent, sipped vintage Taittinger in the Versailles Room, then dined
in the Trianon Room.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, unlike Europeans, have a tradition of giving and the
right to deduct it. American charities support everything from the
Tate Gallery to the Amsterdam Concertgebouw orchestra. ``Our
American system rewards us for being generous,'' said Barbara de
Portago, a New York business consultant and the dinner's prime
organizer, who grew up at Versailles, where her stepfather was
curator.
</P>
</TEXT>
