<SLUG> BC-U.S.-AFRICA-TRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCORD IN CONGRESS ON HELPING AFRICAN AND CARIBBEAN TRADE
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite and expand by 500 words. Eliminates one byline.)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House and Senate leaders have reached broad
agreement on a bill to give African and Caribbean countries
wide-ranging trade benefits intended to help their flagging
economies by opening new markets.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker J. Dennis Hastert and the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott, R-Miss., personally intervened Thursday night to resolve
differences that had deadlocked the measure for months. Left
unresolved, the impasse could have imperiled a landmark accord to
grant China permanent normal trading privileges that the House is
scheduled to vote on next month.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators still have to work out many details
in the bill, which would reduce or eliminate tariffs and quotas on
a wide range of goods made in sub-Saharan Africa, Central America
and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters voiced confidence that the House and Senate would
approve the bill when Congress reconvenes early next month. Last
year, the Senate approved the bill, 76-19, after the House had
passed it, 234-163.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton strongly supports the measure, which would be
the first major trade-promotion agreement enacted in the United
States since the North American Free Trade Agreement in 1993, a law
that established duty-free commerce among Canada, Mexico and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is a win-win proposition for the United States and
for our friends in Africa and the Caribbean Basin,'' Clinton said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The House agreed to grant many of the same duty-free benefits on
apparel and textiles to 24 Caribbean and Central American countries
that will be extended to 48 African nations. The House had not
included the Caribbean in its bill mainly because lawmakers from
textile states and those with many union constituents argued that
exports from that region would threaten American jobs. The American
Textile Manufacturers Institute said Friday that the deal could
harm 600,000 workers in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate dropped a requirement that limited duty-free status
to clothing made with fabric, thread or yarn from the United
States. But in a concession to textile makers, the agreement
initially caps the volume of duty-free goods at 1.5 percent of
textile imports. That cap grows to 3.5 percent over eight years, to
encourage foreign investment in fledgling African markets.
</P>
<P>
   The poorest African countries would be eligible for duty-free
treatment with no restrictions for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the measure argue that it would increase economic
growth on a continent where U.S. trade is relatively small. Last
year, American merchandise exports to Africa totaled $6.7 billion,
while imports amounted to $13.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republican leaders worked out the major sticking points
Thursday night. But the deal still has to be formally approved by
negotiators from each chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement marks a significant milestone for a strong and
meaningful trade mechanism in the African and Caribbean Basin
regions,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the Ways and
Means Committee, which oversees trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles B. Rangel of New York, the senior Democrat on the
committee, said: ``This bill will make a significant difference in
the lives of millions of Africans. It will create jobs in Africa
and jobs in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics said that multinational corporations would exploit
African workers and that the compromise failed to address crucial
issues like debt relief and AIDS in Africa. ``This bill is worse
than no bill at all,'' said Rep. Jesse L. Jackson Jr., D-Ill., who
opposed the original House bill.
</P>
<P>
   Some other Democrats who supported the House bill, like Jim
McDermott of Washington and William J. Jefferson of Louisiana,
grumbled that the compromise might fall short of what they could
accept.
</P>
<P>
   That is significant, because both legislators have indicated
their support for the China trade deal hinged on a satisfactory
outcome for the Africa measure, which they say has been receiving
short shrift from the White House and congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Nailing down an acceptable Africa bill could swing three to five
critical Democratic votes for the China measure, said Rep. Robert
T. Matsui, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, anticipating dissent from textile-state senators, strongly
endorsed the deal, saying, ``These are free-trade provisions that
will help business and industry in America, everything from cotton
to retail to textiles to yarn.''
</P>
<P>
   One provision, to create a mechanism to retaliate against unfair
trade practices committed against the United States, was included
as a favor to Carl H. Lindner, an Ohio executive and big political
fund-raiser whose Chiquita Brands International is locked in a
trade war with Europe over bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision for American garment makers, including Fruit
of the Loom, a big political donor to both Republican and
Democratic causes, would cut the cost of manufacturing apparel in
the Caribbean with yarn and fabric from the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
