<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-TAX-ERROR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK TELLS CLIENTS ABOUT TAX-SOFTWARE GLITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block sent overnight letters to 3,080 customers on Friday,
warning them that income-tax payments that they authorized the
Internal Revenue Service to take from their bank accounts would not
be made, because of a software error.
</P>
<P>
   The affected taxpayers must mail their payments to the IRS,
which is reviewing its records to determine whether to waive late
fees or penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Those affected filed their federal income-tax returns
electronically, using the company's Tax Cut software or its online
version. They owe the Treasury $1,000 or more, which was to be
debited from their bank accounts, said Gene Goldenberg, senior vice
president for software and e-commerce at Block, which is based in
Kansas City, Mo. About 18 million taxpayers use Block software or
tax preparers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The software read the comma in amounts of $1,000 or more as
the end of the line,'' Goldenberg said, ``so if you owed one
thousand in taxes, only $1 was taken from your bank account.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company would pay any penalties or interest that the
Internal Revenue Service assessed these customers.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS asked Block for the Social Security numbers of the
affected taxpayers so it could flag the accounts to review whether
late fees and penalties should be waived, Goldenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have dealt with every single person affected,'' Goldenberg
said, sending each one both e-mail and an overnight package that
included a stamped envelope for mailing the payment. ``There have
been similar problems with software in the past, and we have worked
with the IRS, and they have rarely, if ever, penalized anyone if
there was a problem with the software.''
</P>
<P>
   The IRS, in a statement, said affected taxpayers should mail a
check and include the letter from Block that came in the overnight
mailing.
</P>
<P>
   Tax forms and payments must be postmarked by April 17 except in
parts of upstate New York and New England, where the deadline is
April 18 because Monday is Patriot's Day, a holiday in
Massachusetts, where those taxpayers file their returns.
</P>
<P>
   Block learned of the problem on Tuesday from a customer whose
bank account was tapped for only $1 on April 3, Goldenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fixed the problem, and anyone who files now and
authorizes the IRS to debit their account on a specific day will
have the full amount paid,'' Goldenberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
