<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-VARGAS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS TO RISK IBF TITLE, UNBEATEN RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LAS VEGAS _ We'll know a lot more about Fernando Vargas after
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The undefeated junior middleweight from Oxnard has had an
impressive career so far. He won the IBF championship at 21 _ the
youngest to do so _ and has defended three times.
</P>
<P>
   However, he hasn't faced an opponent like Ike Quartey, his
opponent tonight at Mandalay Bay Resort and Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey, from Ghana, Africa, is one of the most feared fighters
on the planet. He's quick and strong, he has a left jab that would
make Larry Holmes jealous, he's as fierce as they come and he's
experienced. In other words, he's the type of opponent who could
make or break a young fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one came up to me and asked whether or not I wanted to
fight him,'' Vargas said. ``!ital!I wanted to fight him. I feel I
can beat this kind of guy. I have the skills, the power.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take fights like this, you have to take risks if
you want to be a star.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas (18-0, with 17 knockouts) would seem to have significant
advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey (34-1-1, 29 KOs) has fought only once _ against Oscar De
La Hoya in February of last year _ in 2 years. His focus has been
on his business interests in the capital city of Accra, not on
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   What has Vargas been doing? He's had a career: All of his fights
have taken place in that time span.
</P>
<P>
   No one can blame Quartey, 30, for the inactivity. Scheduled
fights with Pernell Whitaker, Felix Trinidad and De La Hoya fell
through during that period, although he ended up fighting and
losing a close decision to De La Hoya. Still, one wonders how it
will affect the former welterweight champ.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey dismisses the issue, pointing to a strong performance
against De La Hoya after a 14-month hiatus. Even Vargas' camp has
downplayed it, saying repeatedly that they expect a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   However, they lick their chops in more candid moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an obvious advantage, !ital!too obvious,'' said Eduardo
Garcia, Vargas' trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas also might have a physical edge: This will be Quartey's
first fight at 154 pounds, at which Vargas has fought his entire
career. Quartey dismissed that issue, too, saying he has had
difficulty making 147 and will be stronger _ and better _ at 154.
</P>
<P>
   Someone mentioned that De La Hoya, a 147 pounder, put Quartey
down twice and wondered whether the heavier Vargas might be even
more powerful than his Los Angeles-area rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Quartey said. ``I think I'll be stronger
than Vargas at 154.''
</P>
<P>
   Quartey's principal advantage is his experience.
</P>
<P>
   He has fought and beaten Oba Carr and Vince Phillips, drawn with
rugged Jose Luis Lopez and lost to De La Hoya. Vargas' best
opponents were Yory Boy Campas and Ronald ``Winky'' Wright, a
talented left-hander who lost a disputed majority decision to
Vargas in the champion's last fight in December.
</P>
<P>
   One cannot help but to think of the Trinidad-David Reid fight in
March, in which Trinidad, moving up to 154, pummeled the young,
overmatched Olympic teammate of Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   Quartey predicted that ``we're in for the same thing'' tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who has he fought?'' Quartey said. ``He hasn't fought anyone.
. . . Oscar is better than he is. He fought better fighters, he's
better, quicker. He's far better than Vargas.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Vargas scoffs at such a suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   He's coping well with ``personal problems'' he said hindered his
performance against Wright, has pushed his assault case aside for
now and really !ital!has never been in better shape: He hired a
personal trainer and has redesigned his body.
</P>
<P>
   To him, that all adds up to a victory and matchup with Trinidad
later this year that could define his career and net him a lot more
than the $1.35 million (to Quartey's $1.25 million) he'll make
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drives me? Superstardom,'' Vargas said. ``That's what I
want. And this fight can give it to me.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
