<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RETURNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESISTANCE TO RETURNING LONG CENSUS FORM IS RISING 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing concerns in Congress that the questions in
this year's census are intrusive, Census Bureau officials said
Friday that they saw new, worrying signs that many people were
refusing to complete and return the longer version of the form.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau's latest figures show that 65 percent of all
households that received the short version of the form had returned
it, compared with 51 percent of those that received the longer
version.
</P>
<P>
   That 14-percentage-point gap differs markedly from the results
of the 1990 census, when the gap was only six points. In 1990,
after households that did not return the forms were visited, the
gap closed to 4.5 points.
</P>
<P>
   The long form, which has 53 questions, is mailed to one in every
six households. It seeks data on a variety of subjects, including
income, education and disabilities. The short form has only eight
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials did not draw a direct connection between the
shortfall in households completing the long form and the recent
comments of lawmakers on Capitol Hill who have suggested that the
questions in the form are intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Senate passed a resolution urging that people who
refuse to answer particular questions on the census not be
prosecuted, though it was doubtful that anyone would be charged
with the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is concern among census officials that the privacy
debate might lead some people to refuse to fill out the long form.
</P>
<P>
   The results compiled from the long forms are considered vital to
both the government and private companies. Data from the long form
is also used in developing key economic indicators, including the
Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the long form was a major blemish on what
otherwise was a good week for the Census Bureau. Earlier this week,
census officials announced that the overall mail return rate for
census forms had reached 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strong 62 percent,'' said Kenneth W. Prewitt, the
census director. ``I think we're in reach of getting to 65 percent
before we close down this part of the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   If that trend holds, census officials will have made good on
their desire to halt the long-term decline in mail-back response
rates that had dropped to 65 percent in 1990 from 83 percent in
1970, the first year the forms were mailed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
