<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7440 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-TECHNOLOGY-$ADV16     04-14 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TECHNOLOGY-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO REACH FOR THE ASPIRIN, OR THE PHONE?  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.J., Calif.)   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not a prerequisite, but to persevere as an investor in
technology stocks these days, it helps to have some masochistic
tendencies.
</P>
<P>
   No, wild swings in the prices of companies with four-letter
stock symbols are not new. But the speed with which the current
decline has occurred, and the wide, deep swath it has cut, have
made the slide in the Nasdaq market over the last month
particularly painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks that were way overvalued are giving that up, and that
is appropriate,'' said Lise Beyer, director of Internet/Net media
research at Credit Suisse First Boston. ``But others that are
generating cash are getting hammered. We are throwing the baby out
with the bath water.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say that markets, while usually efficient, are often
not rational. And the irrationality currently on display in
technology stocks has created pockets of opportunity for the right
kind of investor.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody considering bottom-fishing in the suddenly chilly waters
should take into account a couple of none-too-reassuring factors.
Foremost among them is that at these levels, many technology stocks
still carry major downside risk. Even if the market is at, or near,
its bottom, a rebound may take months or longer to get under way.
</P>
<P>
   And it is also a good time to remember that because the tide is
not necessarily flowing in your favor, picking high-quality stocks
_ not the cheapest ones _ makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some stocks are really beaten up, but you can come back to
them because they have really good growth stories that are
intact,'' said Kevin Landis, portfolio manager at Firsthand Funds,
a $6.2 billion, technology-focused fund family.
</P>
<P>
   Beaten up might understate the case. Many of these stocks have
been flogged raw.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that from its March 10 peak, the Nasdaq composite index
is down 34.3 percent, a decline that comes close to matching the
slide that occurred in the late summer and early fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That decline masks (italics)really(end italics) deep holes in
segments of the Internet space, as well as biotechnology.
E-commerce stocks aren't worth mentioning: they were pummeled in
January and have yet to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Three equity trusts, called Holdrs, introduced early last month
by Merrill Lynch, are indicative of the extent of the decline. The
trusts, which are traded on the American Stock Exchange, are
baskets of specific kinds of Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Since it peaked at $111.625 on March 11, the Internet Holdr
consisting of business-to-business stocks has declined by more than
69 percent. Merrill's Internet infrastructure Holdr has lost 62
percent of its value since its peak on March 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet architecture Holdr _ a basket that includes big
companies like Cisco Systems, IBM, Hewlett-Packard and Dell
Computer _ has done the best of the three. That group peaked on
March 27. Since then it has declined by just over 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one strategy would be to buy one or more of the
Holdrs, or a technology sector fund for that matter, and hope for
the best. But that means forfeiting the opportunity to cherry-pick
the stocks that are likely to bounce back strongest from the
technology meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is down, and down big,'' said Paul Cook, co-manager
of the Munder NetNet fund. ``When that happens and things bottom
and start to come back, the companies that outperform tend to be
the better companies, the ones with profits.''
</P>
<P>
   David G. Dietze, president of PointView Financial Services, a
Summit, N.J. money management firm, said the strategy of buying
blue-chip technology stocks that have been pulled down along with
the rest is not only sound, but one that he follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was buying Intel on Wednesday, and Cisco,'' he said. ``And I
would still buy Oracle and Sun Microsystems.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the established companies she follows, Beyer said companies
like Yahoo, Intuit and America Online are ripe for a turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are companies that have fundamentally good businesses,''
she said. ``It seems like they are due for a bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these companies _ and the rest of the technology
group _ could fall further. Some portfolio managers are in no rush
to buy stocks right now. ``We have been thinking all along that it
would take four to six weeks to digest the run-up we had from early
February to the middle of March,'' said Dennis McKechnie, who
manages the Pimco Innovation fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury is still out on how much more we have to go on the
down side,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, his fund has been selling more stock than it has bought
over the past week. Among the stocks it shed was Vignette, a
business-to-business software company. But McKechnie said he had
been adding to positions in cell phone vendors and semiconductor
manufacturers, buying companies like Nokia, Qualcomm, Micron
Technologies and Applied Materials.
</P>
<P>
   There is a case to be made, of course, that despite the steep
slide in many of these stocks, valuations are still very high.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kerschner, chief market strategist at PaineWebber,
reiterated that point on Wednesday. In a note to clients, he said a
group of stocks he calls the ``new new industrials'' _ a collection
that includes Internet infrastructure companies like Exodus
Communications and Verisign, business-to-business companies like
Ariba and Internet Capital Group and Internet architecture concerns
like Ciena and Juniper Networks _ are still overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new new industrials could fall by another 33 percent
before even aggressive assumptions would put their valuations on a
par with established large-capitalization technology stocks,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock
Letter, said the aftershocks from the current slide could last
awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like it is going to be a V-shaped bottom,'' he
said. ``We had a correction in the Internet stocks last summer, and
in biotechs in 1992. But this time the enthusiasm infected so many
areas that when it ended and came apart, a whole lot of people got
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Murphy said he has been buying little pieces of
biotechnology companies in recent days. ``Start with the bigger
names like Biogen, which has come down pretty sharply,'' he said.
``But these stocks are so volatile, they could be down another 20
percent over the next couple of weeks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
