<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7442 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-BROKERS-ART-$A     04-14 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BROKERS-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROKERS FIND RISK IN RIDING A WAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the new economy, stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Once-stodgy financial firms have jumped onto the technology
wave, adding an extra element of risk and unpredictability to their
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   No longer the high-yielding havens they once were for investors
fleeing a downturn, the biggest banks are now susceptible to sharp
reversals _ even without a sudden change in interest rates. And the
fortunes of the biggest securities firms, long seen as a weather
vane for the overall stock market, are now clearly tied to the
gyrations of the most volatile technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is treating the brokers different than other
financials, like insurance companies or banks,'' said Jeff Morris,
who manages the Invesco Financial Services fund in Denver. ``It is
treating the brokers as a proxy for the IPO market for tech
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the middle of March, he added, other financials seem to be
``lumped in with the old-economy stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   That divergence has been especially pronounced on the Nasdaq's
darkest days. Last week, when the Nasdaq composite sank more than
25 percent, shares of major Wall Street firms also plunged, while
bank stocks held up well or, in a few cases, rose.
</P>
<P>
   Among the securities firms, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter dropped
$16.8125 for the week, or 20 percent, to $67.75. Goldman Sachs fell
$19.75, or 19.3 percent, to $82.75.
</P>
<P>
   As the leading underwriters of initial public offerings and
other stock sales by technology companies, Morgan Stanley and
Goldman Sachs have gained the most from the Internet stock boom _
and they stand to lose the most if it is ending. Investors are
starting to worry that earnings estimates for the brokerage sector
were built on optimistic assumptions about a nonstop bull market
for new issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the quarter's business was already in the books,''
said Richard Strauss, an analyst who follows financial stocks for
Goldman Sachs. ``But from this point a lot will depend on what
happens to Nasdaq over the course of the next week.'' Still, he has
a 12-month price target on the stock of $95.
</P>
<P>
   If Wall Street firms start reporting disappointing earnings,
said Judah Kraushaar, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, ``it would be
the first time in almost a decade that the brokers would show
notable deterioration in earnings momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   But major investment banks and brokerage firms are not the only
financial stocks that are tethered to the Internet sector. Much of
Citigroup's recent profit gain has been provided by its Salomon
Smith Barney securities unit. Chase Manhattan, one of the nation's
biggest commercial banks, derives a growing share of its revenue
from underwriting technology stock issues through its Chase/H&AMP;Q
securities unit and from investing in private companies through its
venture capital arm, Chase Capital Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Connections to the new economy have weighed on the shares of
those companies, while the prices of smaller, more traditional
banks have been rising from depressed levels. ``In the last four
weeks or so, the banks have had a very good bounce off their lows,
most visibly the regional banks that were underperforming,''
Kraushaar said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the fuel for that rally has been ``money looking for a
home, trying to find a bit of a defensive play,'' Kraushaar said.
But he has been warning investors that the bank-stock rally may not
last long, because it has been driven more by the relative safety
of bank stocks that were trading at 8 or 10 times earnings than by
fundamental improvements in the banks.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who considers himself a growth investor, does not own
many bank stocks. Those he does own are either broadly diversified,
like Citigroup, or dominate market niches.
</P>
<P>
   He likes Bank of New York, for example, for its efficient and
profitable securities-processing business. His other favorites
include Charles Schwab, for its combination of Internet-based
brokerage and a national branch network.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pounding the table for regional banks, Kraushaar has
been recommending Chase and Citigroup for the very reasons that
those stocks have become riskier: He thinks that they can use their
huge balance sheets to finance further incursions into Wall
Street's traditional businesses, which he believes will adapt
quickly to shifts in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   He says Chase and Citigroup, which closed on Friday at $78.875
and $58, respectively, can hit $100 and $75 in 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of potential investment-banking business out
there in old-economy industries,'' Kraushaar said.
</P>
<P>
   Investment banks essentially act as efficient fee-seeking
missiles. Joan Solotar, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
said that for much of last year there was a strong correlation
between the stocks of Wall Street firms and the consumer commerce
companies that were popping up over the Internet. When the fever
for those business-to-consumer ventures died down, the brokerage
stocks started moving in rhythm with the new hot segment _
business-to-business Internet companies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The correlation seems to be between the brokerage stocks and
the narrow segment that's dominating the underwriting backlog,''
Solotar said. ``Last year, that was B-to-C, now it's B-to-B.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as investors keep pouring money into some sector of the
new economy, investment banks will benefit from underwriting fees
and trading commissions, analysts said. The biggest threat to
earnings? An economic slowdown that snuffs demand for stocks and
dampens trading activity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
