<HEADER>
A7445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-ABORTION-NYT &LR;      04-14 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES CONCERNED BUSH MAY CHOOSE ABORTION MODERATE AS
RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Gov. George W. Bush positions himself closer to the political
center, prominent religious conservatives are expressing concern
about signals he has sent that he might consider a running mate who
supports abortion rights. Should he make that choice, several
religious conservatives said, he would lose.
</P>
<P>
   No one interviewed explicitly criticized Bush for making
overtures to party moderates. And some said the Texas governor
would continue to benefit from conservatives' desire to wrest the
White House from the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But reactions to Bush's campaigning with Gov. Christie Whitman
of New Jersey, a supporter of abortion rights, and Gov. Tom Ridge
of Pennsylvania, who has urged the Republican Party to modify its
anti-abortion plank, suggest that the party's presumptive nominee
could alienate a group that is a major constituency of the party.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, James Dobson, a nationally known
psychologist whose radio broadcasts reach five million Americans,
said Bush would forfeit the support of many conservatives if he
chose a vice-presidential candidate who favored abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just going to stay home,'' said Dobson, president of
Focus on the Family, a nonprofit religious organization that
produces a syndicated program on marital and child-rearing issues.
He added that said many religious conservatives would not vote for
Vice President Al Gore, whom they consider ``anathema.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, the former head of the conservative Family Research
Council who briefly sought the Republican presidential nomination
himself, said he believed rumors that Ridge ``is on the shortest of
short lists are true.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge's public statements about the need to change the party
platform, coupled with the belief that he could be Bush's running
mate, ``looks disturbingly like a trial balloon,'' Bauer said,
adding, ``That's why I found it disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   During the primary campaign, Bush tried to dodge the question
whenever he was asked whether he would accept a running mate who
supported abortion rights. But late last month, in an appearance
with Whitman, he seemed to indicate that he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good people can disagree on the issue, and I understand
that,'' Bush said then. ``I mean, I'm standing up here with a
friend of mine. We disagree on some aspects of the issue. That
doesn't mean we can't be pulling for the same thing -- being on the
same team. And I respect Governor Whitman's views and I respect her
as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Since March 7, when he beat back a challenge from Sen. John
McCain of Arizona by winning presidential primaries in major states
like California, Ohio and New York, Bush has sought to identify
himself with a constituency broader than the Republican
conservatives he relied on in earlier primaries.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Bush met for an hour with a dozen gay Republicans
at the governor's mansion in Austin, Texas, although he emerged
from the meeting to say he continued to oppose gay marriage. So
far, the response from conservatives to that meeting has been
muted.
</P>
<P>
   The religious broadcaster Pat Robertson, a Bush supporter, said
in a brief statement that a president must represent ``all the
people'' and should not be criticized for listening ``to the
concerns of any segment of the population.'' Criticism would be
appropriate, Robertson added, only if that person embraced ideas
that went against ``his own deeply held convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Rev. Jerry Falwell a Baptist minister whose
former organization, Moral Majority, inspired many religious
conservatives to take part in politics, said in an interview that
he had no problem with Bush's meeting with gay Republicans,
Whitman, Ridge ``or any American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out of the gay session yesterday still saying, `I
oppose same-sex marriage,''' Falwell said. He also said he would be
``greatly surprised'' if Bush chose a running mate who supported
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would cost him the election,'' Falwell said. He added that
he had promised Bush his support and would still vote for him under
such circumstances, and could not support either Gore or Pat
Buchanan, who is seeking the Reform Party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would vote for him,'' Falwell said of Bush. ``But I could
not ask my constituents to follow me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
