<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7449 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      04-14 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL HOLDING FOUR PICKS, JETS POISED TO MOVE UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-DRAFT, FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Jets concluded a frantic week of trades and
telephone calls still holding four first-round picks and still
seeking an opportunity to move up in Saturday's National Football
League draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets now hold the 12th, 13th, 18th and 27th picks in the
first round, but could be poised to make a draft-day deal to move
into the top 10. The Jets picked up the 12th pick on Thursday
night, obtaining it from San Francisco in exchange for the 16th
pick in the first round and the 48th selection, in the second
round.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for that deal may have been the Jets' interest in
selecting defensive end Shaun Ellis of Tennessee, said several
National Football League team executives. Ellis is the second-rated
defensive end in the draft, behind the presumed No. 1 pick in the
first round, Courtney Brown of Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   According to the executives, the Jets were concerned that Green
Bay, which has the 14th pick, would select Ellis. So the Jets made
the deal with San Francisco to give themselves two picks before
Green Bay goes on the clock, leaving them with the flexibility to
use one pick on Ellis and one to fill another need. Ellis, 6 feet 4
inches and 280 pounds, is the pass-rush specialist the Jets
desperately need after having one of the weakest pass-rushes in the
league last season.
</P>
<P>
   In the 3-4 defense the Jets are expected to use, the pass
rushers are usually outside linebackers. Still, Ellis had 8 1/2
sacks and 11 tackles that resulted in yards lost last year and
although he is heavier and slower than some of the other top
defensive ends in the draft, acquiring him would alleviate one of
the Jets' most pressing concerns in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, who have spoken to teams above and below them in the
draft order about trades, could still use one or more of their
picks to pull off a trade and move into the top 10 Saturday. If
they do, they might try to grab a top-flight receiver, like Plaxico
Burress of Michigan State or Travis Taylor of Florida, to replace
Keyshawn Johnson. The Jets have inquired about Cincinnati's No. 4
pick in the first round in an attempt to move into position to take
Peter Warrick of Florida State, the top receiver in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible trade partner is the Baltimore Ravens, who are
holding a veritable auction for the No. 5 pick. Friday, Brian
Billick, the Ravens coach, said that the Ravens would hold off on
trading the pick, if they do complete a trade, until Saturday,
because there were so many suitors who were jockeying for position.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers, who hold the No. 8 pick, have also heard from
several teams including the Jets and would be open to making a
draft-day deal, according to Pittsburgh's director of football
operations.
</P>
<P>
   This is expected to be an extremely trade-heavy first round and
the Jets, with their unprecedented four first-round picks, will be
major players, even if they choose to hold firm with their current
picks. The Jets have already been rebuffed by the Browns in an
attempt to trade up to the first overall pick. Although that
scenario seems dead now _ the Browns are deep in negotiations with
the agent for Brown _ the bid is indicative of the Jets'
willingness to wheel and deal.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, is a critical draft for the Jets organization,
not just because it has the ability to stockpile young talent with
so many picks, but because it is coming off a tumultuous week in
which Johnson was traded. The Jets' needs are numerous, including a
tight end and free safety in addition to the obvious interest in
acquiring a pass-rusher and a wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Because this is a deep draft for receivers, the Jets could wait
until the middle of the round _ letting Warrick, Burress and Taylor
go by _ before selecting Dez White of Georgia Tech, Sylvester
Morris of Jackson State or Ron Dugans, who was overshadowed by
Warrick at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
