<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MARKET'S BREATHTAKING PLUNGE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial in its editions of
Saturday, April 15:
</P>
<P>
   Economists have warned for years that stock prices are
unrealistically high, needing to fall by about a third, by one
prominent estimate, to regain financial sense. But no amount of
warning could take the fright out of Friday's record drops in all
major stock averages. Investors lost about $1 trillion Friday.
Besides the horrific blow to personal wealth, there is the added
threat to the health of the overall economy.
</P>
<P>
   How important an event Friday's plunge proves to be depends on
how much the market bounces back next week, and on other factors as
well. Will people reduce their spending enough to trigger a
recession? Will businesses, finding it harder to raise money on
Wall Street, cut back investment plans, delivering a blow to
long-term economic growth? On these scores, there are firm reasons
to remain optimistic. Stocks lost an astounding 23 percent on a
single day, Oct. 19, 1987. Friday's major averages dropped between
5 and 10 percent. Yet even the 1987 debacle caused relatively
little hardship on Main Street. Under the shrewd leadership of Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve kept the economy growing. Greenspan
is still in charge of the Fed, and he has the tools to make sure
that Wall Street and Main Street do not rise and fall in lockstep.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the stock market decline portends for the economy, the
sheer size of Friday's losses was stunning. The index of 30 stocks
that make up the Dow Jones industrial average fell a record 618
points, more than 5.5 percent. That is about 65 points more than
the previous record. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index, a more
representative sample of American stocks, lost a record 83 points,
almost 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest losers Friday were owners of Nasdaq stocks,
especially technology stocks. The Nasdaq lost a record 355 points,
or almost 10 percent. The index is off about 35 percent in the past
month alone. Many will regard the drop in technology stocks _
Microsoft has lost more than $200 billion in value from its peak,
Intel about $100 billion _ as an inevitable correction. Often
prices have little connection to the profits these companies can be
expected to earn anytime soon. Some investors might have convinced
themselves that technology stocks operate by a different set of
financial rules. But this week, ordinary algebra reasserted itself.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about finding a single, decisive explanation for the
plunge. Everyone will seize a favored candidate. The important
point is that when stocks lose touch with their economic moorings,
anything _ an ugly inflation report, as occurred Friday, or a
judicial blow to a prominent company like Microsoft, which
triggered an earlier slide _ can frighten investors.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent past, investors have taken falling stock prices as
a golden opportunity to buy, so stock prices have quickly
rebounded. No one can know if that pattern will reappear when the
markets open on Monday, but every study of stock prices is
reassuring. Take any reasonably long-term period, and stock
investments do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   As a political footnote, it is worth adding that Vice President
Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas will be watching the
markets closely. Both Bush's tax-cut proposal and Gore's health and
education plans depend on surplus revenues. A good chunk of the
current surplus has been supplied by a boom in tax revenues from
capital gains. A downturn could affect not only productivity and
pocketbooks, but the way politicians and voters behave later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
