<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRENZY OF SELLING IN STOCKS CAPS A DISASTROUS WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Investors turned away from stocks in a sharp wave of selling
that closed one of the worst weeks in the history of U.S. markets.
The catalyst was a Department of Labor report showing that core
consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in March, more than economists had
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index plunged 355.49 points, or 9.7
percent, to 3,321.29, finishing the worst week in its history with
a 25.3 percent loss. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 617.78
points, or 5.7 percent, to 10,305.77. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index slid 83.95 points, or 5.8 percent, to 1,356.56.
</P>
<P>
   A BREATHER FOR A HOT ECONOMY?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy boomed as the stock market, particularly
technology stocks, soared. Now, with those stocks suddenly much
lower, will the economy cool off quickly? Some economists think
consumer spending will slow, but that will depend on psychology as
much as economics.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE GLITCH AT H&AMP;R BLOCK
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;R Block warned 3,080 customers who used the company's
tax-preparation software that payments they authorized the Internal
Revenue Service to take from their bank accounts would not be made,
because of a software error. The affected taxpayers must mail their
payments to the IRS, which is reviewing the accounts to determine
whether late fees or penalties should be waived. The company said
it would pay any penalties or interest.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE BACKS NASDAQ PUBLIC OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Members of the National Association of Securities Dealers voted
overwhelmingly to turn the Nasdaq stock market into a for-profit
company. The approval clears the way for the association to sell
Nasdaq by September.
</P>
<P>
   AGREEMENT REACHED ON TRADE BILL
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate leaders have reached agreement on a bill to
give African and Caribbean countries wide-ranging trade benefits
intended to help their flagging economies.
</P>
<P>
   NEW LEADERS AT LOS ANGELES TIMES
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times is about to be turned over to new
leadership. According to editors briefed by top newsroom leaders,
Michael Parks, the editor, will be replaced by John S. Carroll, the
editor of The Baltimore Sun. The publisher, Kathryn M. Downing,
will be replaced by John Puerner, the publisher of The Orlando
Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESSES CAUTIOUS ON ZIMBABWE
</P>
<P>
   The South African Chamber of Business urged its 40,000 members
this week to delay any new investment in Zimbabwe, its
crisis-ridden neighbor. Hundreds of farms in Zimbabwe have been
raided in recent weeks by black squatters, raising concern about
the country's important agricultural sector and heightening fears
about the political situation.
</P>
<P>
   SAO PAULO FACING A DEBT CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   In Sao Paulo, Brazil, Mayor Celso Pitta is embroiled in a
scandal that includes an estranged wife, accusations of vote-buying
in the city council and a questionable loan worth nearly $500,000.
Yet the most pressing crisis is that the city is facing the
prospect of drowning in about $4 billion in debt that it cannot
repay.
</P>
<P>
   BMW GETS A COUNTERBID FOR ROVER
</P>
<P>
   BMW of Germany said that it had received a counterbid for its
money-losing Rover division from a British consortium seeking to
rescue the Rover name and thwart plans by Alchemy Partners, a
venture capital firm, to turn the company into a niche producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
