s f BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     04-14 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING DEFENSIVELY AS THE BEARS THRASH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note sub byline. Questions may be italicized.)  
(ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT29 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After soaring 86 percent last year, the Nasdaq composite has
plunged by one-third in just five weeks _ a bear market by any
definition but one that some people say is nearing its end. After
all, much of the technology on which investors are betting when
they buy popular Nasdaq stocks seems to also have the effect of
shortening market cycles, allowing excesses to be wrung out in days
or weeks instead of months or years.
</P>
<P>
   That is the optimistic view. Other people contend that this
remains treacherous territory and that things could get
considerably worse. One of them is Douglas R. Cliggott, the United
States equity strategist for J.P. Morgan. He took time Friday
morning to discuss Nasdaq valuations and some alternative areas for
stock investment. Following are excerpts from that conversation: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A lot people think we are close to a bottom in the Nasdaq,
but you don't agree. Why? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Even at 3,500 or so we're still almost 1,000 points above
where we were in mid-October. The stocks are at extraordinarily
high levels. The Nasdaq's probably trading _ even if we're very
generous and say tech earnings can grow 25 percent a year _ at a
price-to-earnings-growth ratio between 6 and 7. Some companies
warrant that, but does tech as a whole? The answer is an
unambiguous no.
</P>
<P>
   Our rough-and-ready approach is that at the 3,000 level we would
think of going back to a neutral on technology, and in the
2.000-to-3,000 range, that's what we'd consider a really true new
buying opportunity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. So you can say you saw this downdraft coming? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We were early. But it was inevitable. Looking back to the
1970s, there have been only two years when the Nasdaq, if it got
very far away from its 200-day moving average, didn't have a
pullback. In the summer of '98, the moving average broke and
brought the Nasdaq back to its trend. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. With the latest inflation report, more interest-rate
increases seem likely. Do you agree with those who minimize the
effect of higher rates on technology companies? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. No. Tech is very vulnerable to higher interest rates for
three reasons. Capital spending of most companies buying high-tech
equipment is now significantly higher than their cash flow, meaning
they have to borrow. Investors who buy tech stocks have been using
debt; not just buying on margin but maybe instead of taking money
out of the market to buy that new sport utility vehicle they get a
home-equity loan. And a higher risk-free return, such as on
Treasury bonds, leads to a lower fair value for stock prices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are there any technology stocks you like now? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We're quite defensive. The only grouping we recommend
investors be overweighted in is information technology services and
computer services. Two companies that are very strong and have very
reasonable valuations are IBM and Computer Sciences. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would you say that the market generally has been, or will be,
gravitating toward what you might call brand-name technology and
away from junk technology? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'd call this conservative, reliable tech rather than
high-stakes tech. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You have a 50 percent allocation to stocks _ and 25 percent
each to bonds and cash _ so where does this money go? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. What we've been doing is recommending that investors increase
their exposure to consumer staples such as foods, pharmaceuticals,
household products and beverages _ groups that have been generally
out of favor since '97. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Are people taking this advice _ to turn to these traditional
favorites that have lagged so badly? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There's been a fair amount of skepticism because, except for
the drugs, these companies have been delivering disappointing
earnings. But we think that this stemmed from four factors, all of
which have reversed or are in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Revived consumer spending in other parts of the world should be
kicking in just about now. Second, a shift from a very strong
dollar to a flat-to-weaker dollar. Third, we're starting to see
improved pricing for these companies, a modest 2 percent to 4
percent, but the trend is up, not down.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, consumer staples lag when corporate earnings are
accelerating and we think they're right at the peak now. The next
four to six quarters will give you weaker year-over-year growth.
That's exactly when you want to own pharmaceuticals and consumer
staples. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Which specific companies do you favor? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We like Bristol-Myers and Schering-Plough. In household
products we like Procter &AMP; Gamble; if you liked it at 100 you've
got to love it at 65 _ and we do. In food and beverages we like
General Mills and PepsiCo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
