<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CASUAL DRESS, ALL-BUSINESS ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a bright, brisk afternoon in Midtown Manhattan,
Peter Warrick and four other soon-to-be National Football League
rookies met the news media Friday at a predraft event at
Gallagher's Steak House.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL had brought in five expected stars of Friday's draft:
LaVar Arrington and Courtney Brown, the Penn State defensive stars;
Virginia tailback Thomas Jones; Alabama offensive tackle Chris
Samuels; and, of course, Warrick, Florida State's brilliant wide
receiver-punt returner. The five athletes took turns talking about
the drama of being drafted, the thrill of a knowing a dream was
about to come true: playing professional football.
</P>
<P>
   While the others wore suits and ties, Warrick was dressed
casually. He wore a brown outfit with a matching fisherman's hat _
front bill turned up _ and a piece of jewelry around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   On any other day, in any other city, Warrick's wardrobe might
have been out of place. But on this day and in this city, they were
congruent. The pattern on Warrick's suit was of airplanes. Some New
York football fans might say they were Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick's choice of clothes _ with the airplane pattern _ could
be interpreted as a message to the Jets: Warrick is your man.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick laughed. He said that was not why he wore the outfit.
But he also said he wouldn't mind playing in New York, for the
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Keyshawn's gone, I'd like to play here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I was more curious to hear how a promising young receiver, just
entering the league, was affected by a player of Johnson's stature
being effectively booted out of a place he wanted be _ New York.
Johnson was certainly stunned by the trade to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   While he said he was happy to get the $56 million contract,
Johnson also said, ``I guess no one is invincible.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a most telling reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he just felt like he couldn't believe they traded him
because he did so much for them,'' Warrick said Friday. ``He was
probably thinking `Why did they trade me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The episode has not been lost on Warrick. ``You see a lot and
you learn a lot and you make your choices,'' he said. ``If they
trade Keyshawn, they'll trade a lot of people. That's the way it
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, more than any of the other players at Gallagher's,
knows that no one is invincible. He discovered the hard way how
funky things can get when a name becomes scandalized.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick spent most of the afternoon answering questions about an
ill-fated shopping spree at Dillard's last fall. The incident, in
which Warrick pleaded guilty to misdemeanor petty theft after
underpaying for clothes by more than $380, got him a two-game
suspension, generated a season of terrible publicity and most
likely cost him the Heisman Trophy. He might also slip a notch in
the draft, but because so many teams passed on Minnesota's Randy
Moss two years ago because of character issues, this time around
clubs may be less inclined to mix church and state when they draft
someone of Warrick's caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they pass me over, it's going to be real exciting,'' he
said. ``Believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   The shopping episode and the subsequent publicity have allowed
him to approach the news media, the draft and the reality of
professional football less as a starry-eyed dream than as a
high-profile business opportunity with a lucrative upside.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, as evidenced by Johnson, everything is temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Every team is looking for something. The Jets are looking for an
eraser, someone to help rub out any trace of a mistake they made by
trading a Pro Bowl receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick, like Johnson in 1996, is coming off a record
performance in a bowl game. Johnson caught 12 passes for 216 yards
and a touchdown as Southern California defeated Northwestern in the
Rose Bowl. Last January, Warrick scored a Sugar Bowl-record 20
points, catching two touchdown passes, running a punt back for a
touchdown and scoring a 2-point conversion to lead Florida State to
a 49-26 victory over Virginia Tech for the national championship.
Warrick could be the eraser the Jets are looking for. Or the spark
of hope for Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't the fastest man in the world, ``but what I do
is make plays every Saturday and, hopefully, now on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   The most fitting imagery of the day was at Gallagher's entrance,
where slabs of ribs and steaks are dry-air cured in an aging box.
The meat was different shapes, different sizes _ and raw.
</P>
<P>
   The other players may not have seen a connection. I'll bet
Warrick did; maybe that's why he dressed so casually.
</P>
<P>
   Why wear suits to a slaughterhouse?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
