<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON RULES OUT MISCONDUCT PROBE OF GENERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon's inspector general Friday dismissed
all accusations against Lt. Gen. Claudia J. Kennedy, who has
accused another Army general of sexual harassment, according to a
senior Pentagon official.
</P>
<P>
   The one-week inquiry found that there was ``no basis
whatsoever'' for the accusations made by a retired Army officer who
sent an electronic message to the Pentagon on April 7 accusing
Kennedy of personal misconduct during the 1980s, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was found,'' the official said. ``There is no there
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon refused to identify the retired officer who made
the accusation against Kennedy, the highest ranking woman in the
Army, just weeks after it was disclosed that she had filed a
complaint accusing another general of groping her in her office in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation against Kennedy had further upset senior Army
officers already divided over the first sexual harassment complaint
brought by one Army general against another. Kennedy's defenders
said they were not surprised that the accusations were groundless,
saying they were a predictable attempt to undermine her case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely classic _ we've seen this in every single
case where a woman has stepped forward and made an allegation and
gotten any kind of notoriety,'' said Susan Barnes, a lawyer who has
represented military women who have brought sexual harassment
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Several women officers praised the Pentagon for quickly handling
the inquiry into the accusations against Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very crucial that this was taken care of quickly,''
said one woman who is a senior officer. ``Most of us recognize that
these things happen, and there is a tendency to blame the victim.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy filed her complaint against Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith
last August _ accusing him of sexual harassment four years earlier
_ after she discovered that he had been appointed deputy inspector
general of the Army and would have responsibility over such cases.
</P>
<P>
   The Army refused to comment on her accusation or discuss the
investigation of Smith.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official said, however, that the Army inspector
general, Lt. Gen. Michael Ackerman, is still interviewing witnesses
in that case, which is complicated because Kennedy did not make a
complaint at the time of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   And without a complaint in his file, Smith appeared to be a
credible candidate for the post of inspector general, said one Army
official.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Kennedy's said Friday that she has told them in the
last week that she expected accusations to be made against her once
the case became public.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an e-mail to me she basically said that she expected it to
get nasty,'' said one officer.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn P. Foote, a retired Army brigadier general, said that
Kennedy told her at a lunch this week that no one should worry
about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I'm tough as leather; they're not going to hurt
me,''' Foote said.
</P>
<P>
   The division over the case extends to Congress where Kennedy's
motives have been questioned. Last week Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind.,
said the timing of her complaint seemed ``to make her look
vindictive.''
</P>
<P>
   A supporter of Kennedy's, Rep. Carolyn B. Maloney, D-N.Y., said
Friday that she was asking the secretary of the Army for a status
report on the changes recommended by a senior review panel three
years ago to ``eliminate sexual harassment within the ranks and to
support those victims of sexual harassment who chose to come
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to the furor, several professional organizations of
women in the military are preparing a reception for Kennedy next
month to honor her before she retires this year. One organizer said
the women wanted her to be remembered for much more than the sexual
harassment case she filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
