<HEADLINE>
FORTUNATE FIVE WILL DOMINATE FIRST ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never in the history of the National Football League have so few
held the future of so many in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, when the jousting for the best available college
talent gets under way at noon, five teams will control 40 percent
of the draft. The New York Jets, with four picks, will be in charge
of the first round and what they do will set the tone for the rest
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, Baltimore, San Francisco, and Seattle have two each,
giving this lucky fivesome 12 of the 31 first-round picks. Teams
like the Patriots, Atlanta, Dallas, Miami, New Orleans, San Diego,
and Tampa Bay, who traded their first-round selections, can only
wait.
</P>
<P>
   If there are no last-minute deals, here is how the first round
might go:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. Cleveland &QL; 
DE Courtney Brown, Penn State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Everything you want in a top pick. He's smart (4.0 high school
grade-point average) and a tremendous worker. He also has great
quickness and an 86-inch wing span. Should be a force in the league
for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
2. Washington &QL; 
LB LaVar Arrington, Penn State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arrington is a speed rusher from the outside and the Redskins
are trying to rebuild their defense. They picked up All-Pro Bruce
Smith in free agency and putting Arrington behind him, or on the
opposite side, will give them a pass rush they haven't had since
the days of Joe Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
3. Washington &QL; 
OT Chris Samuels, Alabama &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 325 pounds, he's very physical. Moves well for such a big
man. Alabama fans say he is the best offensive lineman in school
history. They must have forgotten a guy named John Hannah. When
Samuels gets to the Hall of Fame, they can make the comparison. &QL; 
 &QL; 
4. Cincinnati &QL; 
WR Peter Warrick, Florida State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warrick is the most explosive player in the draft. He would give
the Bengals a tremendous outside 1-2 punch with Carl Pickens. Some
say the Bengals will trade Pickens during the draft if they get
Warrick, but general manager Mike Brown says no. However, the
Kansas City Chiefs were talking about a trade for Bengals running
back Corey Dillon, who has been saying he doesn't want to play in
Cincinnati anymore. Brown reportedly asked for a first- and
third-round pick in the draft. The Chiefs reportedly were only
willing to offer a first and fifth. Marvin Demoff, Dillon's agent,
has been talking to other teams, including Baltimore, trying to get
them interested in trading for Dillon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
5. Baltimore &QL; 
RB Jamal Lewis, Tennessee &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens were still debating this pick Friday night. Coach
Brian Billick would like to take Lewis. Others in the organization
prefer Corey Simon here, gambling they could get Lewis at No. 10.
Billick would prefer a running back and then a wide receiver. But
after losing veteran defensive tackle Larry Webster to a drug
suspension this week, the Ravens are seriously considering Simon.
Green Bay has offered Baltimore multiple picks, and it is believed
the Packers would move up to get Simon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
6. Philadelphia &QL; 
DT Corey Simon, Florida State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have to do something about their defensive front.
They couldn't stop anyone a year ago, except the Patriots, and
although they would like to pick a wide receiver here, they are
leaning toward Simon, an extremely productive college player. If
the Eagles don't grab Simon, there is a possibility they will trade
down with the Jets, who would take Michigan State receiver Plaxico
Burress. &QL; 
 &QL; 
7. Arizona &QL; 
RB Thomas Jones, Virginia &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals lost Adrian Murrell in free agency, and he is was
the only runner they had who could make a play on his own. Jones,
the best breakaway threat in the draft, will give them a chance to
improve a running game that was at the bottom of the league. &QL; 
 &QL; 
8. Pittsburgh &QL; 
WR Plaxico Burress, Michigan State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burress is the Steelers' first choice, but if he is gone, they
will take Marshall quarterback Chad Pennington. Burress is 6 feet 6
inches, can leap over tall buildings, will block, but is supposed
to have a bit of an attitude problem. The Steelers took a receiver
(Troy Edwards) with their first pick last year, and will do so
again if they believe it will help beleaguered quarterback Kordell
Stewart. &QL; 
 &QL; 
9. Chicago &QL; 
LB Brian Urlacher, New Mexico &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the Bears are enthralled by Burress, they need more
help on defense. Urlacher appears to be the type who could line up
_ and make plays _ at several positions. &QL; 
 &QL; 
10. Baltimore &QL; 
WR Travis Taylor, Florida &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The second half of the Ravens' plan. They were great on defense
in 1999 but struggled on offense, which is why Billick is looking
for explosive players. If the Ravens choose Simon fifth, they will
take Lewis with this pick and hope to get a receiver later. &QL; 
 &QL; 
11. New York Giants &QL; 
RB Ron Dayne, Wisconsin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have been telling everyone they like Alabama running
back Shaun Alexander here, but Dayne will be the choice if the
board breaks down this way. He is not the big-play threat Alexander
is, but he is a power runner, in the mold of Jerome Bettis, who
would make defenses respect the line of scrimmage and not play pass
all the time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
12. New York Jets &QL; 
LB John Abraham, South Carolina &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This starts the Jets' roll. They would like to get a wide
receiver, pass rusher, defensive back, and offensive tackle or
tight end with their four first-rounders. If they move up, it will
likely be to get a receiver like Burress. &QL; 
 &QL; 
13. New York Jets &QL; 
OT Stockar McDougle, Oklahoma &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This could set up the Jets with a great offensive line in the
future. Two Jets, Randy Thomas and Ryan Young, made the NFL
All-Rookie team last season. &QL; 
 &QL; 
14. Green Bay Packers &QL; 
DE Shaun Ellis, Tennessee &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Packers continue to rebuild their defensive line. With
Vonnie Holliday inside and Ellis outside, the Packers could again
be dominant up front. Gilbert Brown has virtually eaten himself out
of the league, so defensive line has become their top priority. The
Packers have offered three picks to Baltimore to move up to the
fifth spot, reportedly to take Simon. &QL; 
 &QL; 
15. Denver Broncos &QL; 
TE Bubba Franks, Miami &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos traded down to this spot figuring they could still
get the tight end they need, and Franks is the best available.
Denver coach Mike Shanahan has said Franks is just about the best
blocking college tight end he has ever seen. However, when Shanahan
traded to this spot, he didn't expect to see Pennington on the
board. There could be a surprise here. &QL; 
 &QL; 
16. San Francisco &QL; 
QB Chad Pennington, Marshall &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers have traded down twice to get to this spot, picking up
second-round picks from Washington and the Jets. San Francisco
general manager Bill Walsh has said he hopes to turn his two
first-round picks into five second-rounders and then select five
players who can start the rebuilding process. However, if
Pennington is at this spot, the trading will stop and he will be
the pick. &QL; 
 &QL; 
17. Oakland &QL; 
LB Julian Peterson, Michigan State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are praying Peterson drops this far. Their biggest
need is a pass-rushing linebacker. They could go for a defensive
back at this spot if all pass rushers are gone. But owner Al Davis
has a history of trading up to get what he feels will be a star,
rather than taking a player later he really doesn't want. &QL; 
 &QL; 
18. New York Jets &QL; 
WR Dennis Northcutt, Arizona &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the way the Jets might go if they don't get Burress.
They need someone to replace Keyshawn Johnson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
19. Seattle &QL; 
OL Chris McIntosh, Wisconsin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle needs to rebuild the offensive line to give Mike
Holmgren a better chance to succeed with his West Coast offense. &QL; 
 &QL; 
20. Detroit &QL; 
RB Shaun Alexander, Alabama &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lions use this choice to attempt to replace Barry Sanders.
Although Alexander is more of a power runner, the Lions need him to
help their play-action passing game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
21. Kansas City &QL; 
CB Ahmed Plummer, Ohio State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs have been trying for two weeks to make a trade. They
desperately want a running back. They tried to move up to get Jones
or Dayne but couldn't get it done. They tried to trade with
Cincinnati for Dillon but couldn't get it done. Defensive back is
their next need and they say they will take Plummer, a cover guy. &QL; 
 &QL; 
22. Seattle &QL; 
CB Deltha O'Neal, California &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This time, Holmgren goes defensive. O'Neal is highly regarded
and could be a surprise pick above this. The Jets and Lions have
some interest. &QL; 
 &QL; 
23. Carolina &QL; 
OL Travis Claridge, Southern Cal &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A surprise first-rounder. Panthers coach George Seifert said he
would select almost anyone above him on their board if they fell to
him. He was hoping McDougle, McIntosh, or O'Neal would be here. The
Carolina staff coached Claridge in the Senior Bowl and liked his
toughness. &QL; 
 &QL; 
24. San Francisco &QL; 
LB Keith Bulluck, Syracuse &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers would like to trade down, but if they stay put it will
be Bulluck or Erik Flowers, a pass rusher from Arizona State. &QL; 
 &QL; 
25. Minnesota &QL; 
LB Darren Howard, Kansas State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vikings coach Dennis Green says it will be an agonizing decision
between Howard and Boston College's Chris Hovan. Green will tell
you Hovan plays harder than anyone in the draft but he plays
inside, and they need more of an outside pass-rushing threat, which
Howard could be. &QL; 
 &QL; 
26. Buffalo &QL; 
CB Rashard Anderson, Jackson State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bills will be thankful Anderson is still on the board. Their
biggest need is a cover corner. Even though they might prefer
Plummer or O'Neal, they'll still make this move. If all three are
gone they'll consider Anderson's college teammate Sylvester
Morris. &QL; 
 &QL; 
27. New York Jets &QL; 
TE Anthony Becht, West Virginia &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Their 1998 starter at tight end, Kyle Brady, left for
Jacksonville via free agency before last season. Their '99 starter,
free agent Eric Green, was a bust. Tight end is a huge need and
they like Becht a lot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
28. Indianapolis &QL; 
DL Chris Hovan, Boston College &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Colts need defense and Hovan fits into what they like to do.
General manager Bill Polian is saying his prayers that Hovan will
still be there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
29. Jacksonville &QL; 
OL Cosey Coleman, Tennessee &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars' biggest needs are at guard, which is where Coleman
fits in the NFL, and wide receiver. Jacksonville will likely go for
a receiver in the second round. &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. Tennessee &QL; 
DE Erik Flowers, Arizona State &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Titans coach Jeff Fisher says his team doesn't have any glaring
holes and will pick the best player available. Fisher was hoping
one of the highly rated offensive lineman might drop to this spot,
but that's not likely to happen, so he'll go with Flowers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
31. St. Louis &QL; 
OT Adrian Klemm, Hawaii &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Klemm fits a need. The Rams lost two of their Super Bowl
starters on the offensive line to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Seahawks free agent defensive tackle Sam Adams is the
wild card in this draft. Baltimore and Green Bay were trying to
sign him so they wouldn't have to use a first-round pick on a
defensive lineman.
</P>
</TEXT>
