<HEADLINE>
SHAME ON ELIAN'S RELATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The quickly shrinking credibility of the Miami relatives
of Elian Gonzalez approached the vanishing point with the release
Thursday of a loony home video that purports to prove the little
boy wants to stay here permanently.
</P>
<P>
   In this farce taped in his bedroom, he defiantly insists he
wants to stay, calls Attorney General Janet Reno an ``old lady,''
and declares that if his father wants custody he'd better move to
the United States. It neatly encapsulates much of the harm he is
suffering at the center of this legal morass.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure all those sentiments were entirely the product of his
own youthful mind. I'm sure he hated Cuba every day that he lived
there, and has been dreaming of life in the United States for years
and years. I'm sure that those around the family who say he was not
coached, who are shocked that anyone might even suggest that he was
encouraged to make this speech, are all telling the truth. I'm sure
all the people around him are thinking of nothing but the best
interests of Elian, as they so tirelessly declare.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who really cared about this boy would want to reunite him
with his surviving parent and would not tolerate the three-ring
circus that has grown up around him. Anyone who cared about him
would not allow him to be interviewed by Diane Sawyer, much less
would they release some propagandistic video to bolster their claim
to custody.
</P>
<P>
   Elian is 6 years old, but he is no fool. He has been to Disney
World and been kowtowed to by one local politician and celebrity
after another. He spends each day surrounded by a huge cheering
section keeping vigil for him, and he can't appear in a window
without dozens of cameras clicking. Of course he doesn't want to go
anywhere. Why would he?
</P>
<P>
   He is too young to understand the transitory nature of celebrity
or to have heard of Andy Warhol's universal 15 minutes of fame, but
he knows he is being treated as he never was before.
</P>
<P>
   It is ludicrous to think that a small child is capable of making
such a large decision as what country he should live in. But his
lawyers and family continue to suggest that the call should be his,
while twisting and corrupting this child they claim to hold so
dear.
</P>
<P>
   On and on this has dragged, and the one thing that has become
steadily more clear is how little it has to do with the boy who
loves playing on the swingset in his backyard. The political
baggage this case has acquired is merely annoying, but the
willingness to use this child as a pawn is sad.
</P>
<P>
   The claim of the Miami relatives that this is a family matter is
being laughed out of one courtroom after another. A Florida family
court judge in Miami declared Thursday, for the second time this
week, that she has no jurisdiction in the case. Meanwhile, the
Justice Department, which so far has shown the collective spine of
a bowl of Jell-O, argued in court papers that the Miami relatives
should be forced to relinquish control before their appeal for an
asylum hearing is even heard in an Atlanta appeals court. That
seems like a minimal requirement to me.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives seem overwhelmed by the symbol Elian has become. A
few months ago, they were a poor immigrant family scraping by; now
they are celebrities _ and in their own community near-deities.
Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro, and cousin Marisleysis have cheering
sections, even fans. I'm convinced that their refusal to listen to
reason has much to do with the disappointment their new admirers
would suffer if they gave in now, and their reluctance to give up
the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazaro and Marisleysis, however unsophisticated, are at
least adults. Now Elian has been turned into a television performer
too, in a cheap bid to manipulate public opinion. His childhood
becomes steadily more perverted every day. He may hardly remember
what it was like to be a little boy by the time this is over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
