<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7479 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-RIM-TECH-ART-$     04-14 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-RIM-TECH-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT WATERLOO, A TECHNOLOGY STOCK'S RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT24 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glee has been replaced by a quiet gloom. Where there was
unchecked optimism there now creeps fear. Worst of all, monumental
profits have turned to stunning losses.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the mood along the fault lines of the Nasdaq stock quake
_ on Wall Street, of course, and in Silicon Valley. But the shock
waves are hardly confined to the capitals of commerce and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   There are anxious digerati in the heartland, too, in places like
Waterloo, Ontario, the low-key city 90 minutes southwest of Toronto
that is home to Research in Motion Ltd., one of the hottest _ now
coldest _ Nasdaq stocks of the year.
</P>
<P>
   RIM, as it is known, is a 16-year-old company that became an
overnight sensation early this year thanks to its BlackBerry
interactive pagers, beloved by the gadget-minded. Public only since
February 1999, RIM has lost three-quarters of its value, or roughly
$8 billion, in the last six weeks. Most of that was on Wednesday,
after it warned that its marketing costs would rise markedly in the
year ahead. Analysts lowered their earnings estimates, and the
stock fell 63 percent on the week.
</P>
<P>
   Although RIM's rise and fall has been spectacular, it is only
the latest in a long line of highflying Nasdaq stocks that have
dropped to earth in recent days, with investors demonstrating a
positively old-fashioned concern about fundamentals like costs,
sales and earnings.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the drama surrounding Research in Motion's movement
makes it something of a microcosm of the overall Nasdaq stock
market, and Waterloo _ without reading too much into the town's
name _ a microcosm of Nasdaq investors.
</P>
<P>
   As RIM's shares were rising _ they climbed from $9.25 last April
to $175.75 in February _ the company naturally became the talk of
its hometown, population 90,000. The move made billionaires out of
its co-chief executives, James Balsillie and Michael Lazardis.
</P>
<P>
   It also set fire to the local real estate market, just as the
bull market in technology stocks has done in New York and Silicon
Valley. The highest price paid for a home in the Waterloo area this
year was the roughly $960,000 that was paid _ in cash _ by a
Research in Motion employee just weeks ago, according to Helen
Alpaugh, an associate broker at Re/Max Twin City Realty. That
amount was more than double the average price for so-called
executive homes in the area.
</P>
<P>
   After RIM successfully raised $150 million in a secondary
offering of stock in October, the company held a lavish party to
celebrate its fantastic good fortunes. RIM invited 1,800 people to
the event at Lulu's, a local nightclub, according to Kevin Crowley,
a technology reporter at The Kitchener-Waterloo Record, a regional
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The guests included employees, friends and students from the
nearby University of Waterloo, which produces many technology
entrepreneurs. Entertainment was supplied by the Barenaked Ladies,
a white-hot Canadian rock group whose hits include a ditty called
``If I Had a Million Dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   RIM's rocketing stock also generated a flood of charitable
donations. Barely a month ago, when the shares were near their
peak, two computer programmers gave $13 million in RIM stock to the
Kitchener-Waterloo Community Foundation _ the largest contribution
it ever received, according to one board member.
</P>
<P>
   As luck would have it, the foundation sold the shares almost
immediately, cashing in near the top.
</P>
<P>
   The only unpleasantness surrounding Research in Motion's climb
over the last few months was a malady known about town as RIM envy.
It was a local version of the split in the overall market between
the haves _ those who invested in Nasdaq stocks _ and the
have-nots.
</P>
<P>
   In doughnut shops and fast-food places around town, people were
constantly moaning about having missed out on the Big Move.
``People really got caught up in the story,'' Crowley said. ``It's
the emblem of the high-tech industry: the volatility, the glamour
and potential profit for shareholders here.''
</P>
<P>
   According to locals, the stock's spectacular rise drew new,
unsophisticated investors into the market. Robert C. Caldwell,
principal at the Caldwell Capital Corp., a local independent
brokerage firm, had a ringside seat for the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in town bought the stock,'' Caldwell said.
``We've got shares on our books from the issue price and all the
way up. Most individuals have been holding it, tending to view it
as a long-term investment.''
</P>
<P>
   After the big decline in the middle of the week, the mood of
those investors was subdued, he said. ``We're not all that
surprised that there's been some profit-taking,'' he added. ``We're
surprised at the depth of the profit-taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, RIM envy has disappeared. A local financial
adviser said reports from inside the company told of a somber mood
among employees. Neither Balsillie nor Lazardis returned calls
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   To the outside world, many Research in Motion workers are
putting a brave face on the stock's devastating decline. Liam Bali,
manager of Curry in a Hurry, a local restaurant favored by young
RIM employees, said they did not appear to be worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pretty aware that stocks do fluctuate,'' he said.
``They are very firm in their technology. They are expecting their
stock will increase tenfold within the next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Denizens of the Internet chat rooms where the stock has been
popular are not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man it sure hurts hitting the bottom,'' began a Wednesday
posting by a company fan using the moniker ``Me loves money'' in a
Raging Bull chat room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been buying the whole way down but am now nearly all in
and have no more pesos to bring to the party,'' the post said.
``Where are we going from here?''
</P>
<P>
   Another Wednesday post read: ``It not only hit bottom, but dug
another six feet down. It's going to be a long summer people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
