<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH FUND RAISING TOPS $80 MILLION; GAIN FOR DEMOCRATS; FALWELL
REGISTRATION EFFORT; AD ON NUCLEAR WASTE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSH FUNDS TOP $80 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   After spending nearly $70 million to secure the Republican
presidential nomination, Gov. George W. Bush has continued his
record-shattering fund-raising pace by exceeding $80 million. The
Bush campaign raised about $6.9 million from March 1 to April 6,
more than three-quarters of its goal of raising $10 million in
March and April, a campaign spokesman, Scott McClellan, said
Friday. Bush's campaign treasury received a significant boost by
the campaign's new emphasis on Internet fund raising. A blizzard of
solicitations sent by e-mail has helped raise $1.6 million online.
</P>
<P>
   GAIN FOR DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   In the race for control of Congress, most nationwide polls are
showing Democrats and Republicans fairly even. In the latest, a
Zogby America Poll conducted April 1-4, Democrats came out 4
percentage points ahead of Republicans when voters were asked which
party's candidate they expected to vote for in their district.
Zogby has shown a tie in this poll for the last several months, and
two weeks ago found the Democrats with only a 1-point advantage.
The Democratic candidate was the preference of 38 percent of the
842 likely voters surveyed nationwide, and the Republican was the
choice of 34 percent. Since there is a 3-point margin of sampling
error for each party, the 4-point difference is still not
statistically significant.
</P>
<P>
   FALWELL IN REGISTRATION EFFORT
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell has begun a voter registration drive that
he says is intended to enlist millions of religious believers as
voters. Falwell, an independent Baptist minister who founded the
former Moral Majority in 1979 to get religious conservatives
involved in politics, calls the effort People of Faith 2000. Its
advisory committee includes the Rev. Paige Patterson, president of
the Southern Baptist Convention, and Richard Viguerie, the
conservative direct-mail specialist.
</P>
<P>
   AD ON NUCLEAR WASTE BILL
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Nevada continued to make hay out of the House
Republicans' insistence earlier this week that President Clinton
sign a bill creating a national nuclear waste disposal site in the
state, running a new radio ad portraying Gov. George W. Bush as
sympathetic to both the plan and the nuclear power industry. The
commercial says nuclear power concerns have given Bush ``hundreds
of thousands of dollars'' and notes that Republicans voted
overwhelmingly for the plan, though it is opposed by many Nevadans,
including the Republican candidate for Senate, John Ensign. Bush
has not detailed his position on the plan, but Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., and Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, have said they
believe he favors the measure. President Clinton has promised to
veto it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
