<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMW-ROVER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH CONSORTIUM MAKES COUNTERBID FOR ROVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (subs next to last graf to give stock prices in dollars as well as
euros) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ BMW AG of Germany said Friday it had received a
counterbid for its money-losing Rover division from a British
consortium seeking to rescue the Rover name and thwart plans by the
venture capitalist firm Alchemy Partners to turn the company into a
niche producer.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium's most prominent member is John Towers, a former
chief executive of Rover in the early days of its ownership by BMW,
which bought the company for $1.2 billion six years ago in what
became a nightmare investment of losses. Last year Rover lost $1.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Towers, Rover's chief executive from 1994 to 1996, did not
return calls to his business headquarters in the English Midlands,
where he runs a privately held components company called
Concentric. The consortium is thought to include Rover dealers and
labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   However, Juerg Dinner, a BMW spokesman in Munich, said Towers'
bid was received Friday _ just days after an exploratory meeting
between Towers and BMW executives _ and would be examined.
</P>
<P>
   Dinner indicated that the new bid _ for which no financial
details were immediately available _ was for the same troubled
Rover plant at Longbridge near Birmingham as last month's bid by
London-based Alchemy Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Alchemy has said that it plans to phase out the Rover brand,
with thousands of job losses, and begin producing a much smaller
number of sporty sedans under the MG name.
</P>
<P>
   The BMW spokesman said exclusive negotiations with Alchemy were
expected to end soon. ``If the new bid has substance, we may
discuss it after the conclusion of the Alchemy negotiations,''
Dinner said. Some German analysts, however, suggested that the
counter-bid had only limited chances of success because BMW's
negotiations with Alchemy were so far advanced.
</P>
<P>
   BMW was said by people with knowledge of the Alchemy deal to
have offered the Longbridge plant to Alchemy at virtual fire-sale
prices, free of debt and with net assets valued at $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   News of Alchemy's plans for job reductions sent shock-waves
through the plant's 9,000-employee work-force and provoked a bitter
spat between BMW and the British government. It also spurred the
government to offer a $203 million aid package for the region
around Longbridge, where tens of thousands of jobs in the supply
industry depend on the the auto plant.
</P>
<P>
   British officials made no secret of their approval for the
counter-bid, but said there was no direct government involvement in
it. They also said they believed the bid would extend Rover's life
as a mass volume automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Byers, Britain's trade and industry minister, said
Towers' proposals for the Longbridge plant ``offers a better
prospect than perhaps anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Nagle, a spokeswoman for Byers, said the British
government had always said it would prefer Rover to remain as a
volume car-producer. She said the British government would consider
supporting Rover financially if Towers' bid were successful.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   British newspapers have reported that Towers wants to use the
Longbridge plant to manufacture a new, midrange Rover car _ the R30
_ and to take over production of a revamped Mini car which BMW had
planned to keep on producing itself. BMW's deal with Alchemy last
month was combined with a separate agreement to sell the Land Rover
sport utility vehicle division to Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Alchemy said the company had no direct knowledge
of the counterbid and planned to conclude its negotiations with BMW
by the end of April. Reflecting investors' worries that the
counterbid could slow BMW's disposal of Rover, BMW shares fell 1.2
euros ($1.1532), or 3.74 percent, to close at 30.9 euros ($29.6946)
in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Auto industry analysts said, the consortium could need to come
up with an offer of around $1.3 billion to take over the R30 and
the Mini from BMW. But there was no immediate confirmation of this
from either BMW or the consortium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
