<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MET-CESNOLA-ART-1350(     04-14 1434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-CESNOLA-ART-1350(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MET TAKES SKELETONS OUT OF CLOSET AND TELLS THE STORIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ADV: Photos NYT 30-32 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KARL E. MEYER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It hasn't happened quickly, to be sure, nor as wholeheartedly as
some might wish, but the Metropolitan Museum of Art seems to have
come clean about the checkered practices of its first director,
Luigi Palma di Cesnola, from his extralegal collecting to his
mix-and-match melding of ancient sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   Four new galleries permanently display about 600 impressive
antiquities that Cesnola unearthed in Cyprus while he was United
States consul there from 1865 to 1876, and the presentation is as
interesting as the collection. The wall texts, the new catalog and
especially the descriptive captions attest not only to a shift from
artifice to authenticity in public taste but also to a greater
measure of truth-telling about museum policies.
</P>
<P>
   Cesnola sold some 35,000 pieces to the Metropolitan in 1873-76
for around $60,000, and in return the museum trustees agreed to
hire him as director, a post Cesnola held from 1879 until his death
in 1904. Yet in his hunger for fame, Cesnola sutured together
different pieces of sculptures and lied about the location of his
finds and the treasures he uncovered. So though the collection is
the finest of its kind outside Cyprus it has for the most part
languished in storerooms, an awkward token of discredited
make-believe and shady methodology.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while these latest revisions to the record seem to
represent a clear movement from fraud to truth, the idea of what
constitutes authenticity in art has often been as much a function
of taste as of history.
</P>
<P>
   In art history, indeed, the color of truth is often gray. As
John Onians, author of ``Classical Art and the Cultures of Greece
and Rome'' (1999) and director of the Britain's World Art Research
Program in East Anglia, put it in an interview: ``Once
restorations, however debatable, become part of cultural history,
they acquire their own interest and value. For evidence, simply
look into the works of Francis Haskell.''
</P>
<P>
   Haskell's magnum opus, ``Taste and the Antique: The Lure of
Classical Sculpture'' (1981), written with another Oxford scholar,
Nicholas Penny, documents the pervasive influence of restorations.
For example, the hands and feet, the arms and legs, of such
celebrated works as the Laocoon, the Dying Gladiator, the
Discobolus and the Apollo Belvedere are in varying degrees
conjectural implants. But for the inability of restorers to agree,
limbs would probably have been attached by the Louvre to the most
famous of female torsos, the Venus de Milo.
</P>
<P>
   Louis XIV commissioned a complete set of plaster casts of the
finest antique sculptures in Italy, initiating a craze that
persisted into the 20th century. No English country house was
deemed complete without its gleaming copies, so that classical
sculpture was considered inseparable from a white pallor. Novelists
alluded to these carvings as if they were sacred relics. In Henry
James' ``Portrait of a Lady,'' the American Isabel Archer finds
herself alone in ``the glorious room, among the shining antique
marbles'' in the Roman Capitol, where she rests her eyes on ``their
blank beautiful faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence the zeal with which restorers at the British Museum
scrubbed off the color that once tinted the Parthenon sculptures,
according to the latest edition of William St. Clair's ``Lord Elgin
and the Marbles'' (Oxford University Press, 1998). The museum has
now adopted a firm restoration policy of marking each modern
addition, going so far that one curator there fears that it is too
hard for the viewer to imagine how pieces looked before.
</P>
<P>
   The debate about authenticity and what constitutes a true
representation of past art is long-running. Arguments broke out in
1880 soon after the Met unveiled the Cesnola collection at the
museum's grand opening in its new quarters in Central Park. A
French art dealer, Gaston Feuardent, sneered that the restorations
were incompetent or fraudulent, resulting in a protracted lawsuit
in which Cesnola prevailed. Nonetheless even his defenders were
uneasily aware that he was a fabulist with a zestful delight in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   With his great cape, pince-nez and walrus mustache, Cesnola had
the bearing and breeding of a soldier of fortune. Born of lesser
nobility in the Italian Piedmont in 1832 and trained as a Sardinian
cavalry officer, he fought briefly in the Crimea and Italy's wars
of independence before immigrating to the United States around
1858. When the Civil War broke out, Cesnola made his mark as a
cavalry colonel, and later claimed that Lincoln orally promoted him
to general only days before the President's assassination. A
general's gilded epaulettes thereafter adorned Cesnola's portraits,
and at the museum he was called general.
</P>
<P>
   After the war Cesnola won a political plum, the American
consul's office in Cyprus. The island was part of the Ottoman
Empire, which however otherwise poor was rich in antiquities.
Cesnola secured a permit, or a firman, for excavations in Cyprus,
assembling a collection that he shipped to Britain in 1872 in a
timely evasion of a Turkish ban on the export of antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   While still consul, he courted buyers in Britain, France,
Germany, Russia and the United States. When the Met made the
winning bid, Cesnola returned to Cyprus for further campaigns,
discovered the Kourion Treasure and published an imaginative
account of his discoveries, ``Cyprus: Its Ancient Cities, Tombs and
Temples'' (1878). But Cesnola, aware that his prizes were carved in
limestone rather than marble, and in an eclectic style, used glue
and chisel to give them a more classical flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Marangou, a young Cypriot archaeologist, asserts that much
of Cesnola's collection was smashed in transit and imaginatively
glued together by Cesnola with the help of a German cabinetmaker.
In her spirited volume on Cesnola's ``Life and Deeds,'' published
by the Popular Bank in Nicosia to coincide with the gallery
opening, she argues that Cesnola's aim when possible was to give
sculptures a spurious association with the temple of Aphrodite,
near where the goddess was said to have emerged from the sea, even
adding cult objects like mirrors to statuary.
</P>
<P>
   In the Metropolitan's new galleries, the hallmark is understated
candor. The provenance of most works is phrased ``Said to be from
...'' since Cesnola scorned excavation records. Running like a
doleful leitmotif through the catalog are such comments as
``Cesnola's `restorations' have drastically altered this unusual
sculpture'' and ``these heads may not have originally belonged to
the bodies.'' All traces of color _ once covered with a wash or
otherwise scrubbed out to accord with prevailing taste _ are now
noted.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIMS)
</P>
<P>
   Some art historians would have preferred going further, removing
all modern accretions and using wires rather than plaster when
necessary, as is the current practice at the Louvre. This is the
view of Joan Breton Connelly of New York University, who wrote her
doctoral dissertation on the Cesnola collection. Although she
complimented the galleries as ``great and glorious'' in a telephone
interview, she said that she would have purged all of Cesnola's
supposed improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Noble, an authority on classical pottery and a former
vice director of the Metropolitan, praised the candid labeling and
the chronological arrangement that shows how Greek, Persian and
Egyptian styles mixed in the Cypriot melting pot. ( Noble was
famous as a scourge of fakes, once saying: ``All forgeries are like
vampires. They should have a knife driven through their heart.'')
He did however, have a kinder word for Cesnola's alleged
overcleaning, since in Noble's view excavated pieces are often
stained by lime or root marks, and their cleaning can be justified.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even Marangou praises the new candor of the installation, adding
that she hopes it will help rebut the canard that Cypriots showed a
mercenary indifference to their island's ancient art. She points
out that it was not peasants but the Metropolitan trustees who
approved the sale at auction of as many as 20,000 pieces from the
Cesnola collection in the 1920s. The auction is described in the
new Cesnola catalog but is not mentioned in the gallery wall texts.
Old reflexes, it would seem, die slowly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
