<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN_UPSETS-LADN-(SLAN     04-14 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN_UPSETS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS OUT OF IT ALREADY? DON'T BE SO SURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Not even the kids with posters of Luc Robitaille and
Rob Blake on their bedroom walls think the Kings have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   The team claims it is not down, but it is down a game to the
mighty Detroit Red Wings, who didn't even need their best player,
Steve Yzerman, to beat the Kings 2-0 to open this best-of-seven
series.
</P>
<P>
   Kings management has asked the crowd to wear black for Games 3
and 4 back in Los Angeles. Fans must be wondering if they will be
dressing for a funeral.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Kings dressing room before Friday's practice at Joe
Louis Arena, a player stood with a story to tell. Kelly Buchberger
was playing for the No. 8-seed Edmonton Oilers in April 1997.
Across the ice were the Dallas Stars, two years away from a Stanley
Cup but the top team in the Western Conference that season.
</P>
<P>
   What happened next, when the Oilers came back after losing the
first game in the first round to pull off one of the most stunning
upsets in NHL postseason history, is the reason teams play 82 games
to get here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of similarities,'' said Buchberger, who came
over from expansion Atlanta in March to bolster the Kings'
character. ``We thought we matched up well against the Stars in
Game 1, and we knew we had really taken it to them physically. I
mean we played every shift like it was our last. I don't think they
knew we had that in us.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years earlier, the Oilers were gushing with talent when
they took a 5-0 lead into the third period against the Kings in
Game 3 of Round One, a game that became known as the ``Miracle on
Manchester.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Kings tie the game in the final five seconds of
regulation, but they won it in overtime on a goal by Daryl Evans
and went on to take the best-of-five series. Edmonton advanced to
the finals the next year then won five of the next seven Stanley
Cups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't go into the third period thinking we were going to
win the game,'' said Evans, now a Kings broadcaster. ``We just
wanted to outplay them the final 20 minutes and try to get a little
momentum for the rest of the series. Just think, we were 48 points
behind Edmonton during the regular season. How's that for an
underdog?''
</P>
<P>
   When Game 2 is played at 11 a.m. this morning, Yzerman is
expected to be in the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   It is uncertain whether Buchberger's words can close the gap on
a team that scored 108 points during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings know they got the Red Wings' attention. Scotty
Bowman was upset that the Red Wings, who had the league's best
power play, went 0 for 6 with the man advantage and didn't put it
away until Sergei Fedorov's empty-netter in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Buchberger said he wasn't sure Dallas had that kind of respect
when the team's met three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton rebounded to win Game 2 4-0, but the series was kind of
a yawn. The turning point came at the end of Game 3 when the Stars
blew a two-goal lead with three minutes to play in regulation.
Edmonton tied the game, then won at the 9:15 mark of overtime on a
goal by _ Buchberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were devastated,'' he said. ``You could see it in their
eyes. They were the overwhelming favorite, but suddenly they were
vulnerable. This was supposed to be easy for them. But we were the
team with the focus. They never recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Stars came back to win the next game, just as
Edmonton did after returning from Evans' ``Miracle.'' But the
mental approach changed for both favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember Edmonton in our year was on their way to
being maybe the greatest team of all time,'' Evans said. ``But they
found out we could score on them. It was like we knew something
they didn't. That bothered them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, however one clear difference between the Stars and
Oilers and these Red Wings. Those teams had not won the Stanley
Cup. Detroit has won it two of the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means there isn't much they haven't seen,'' said
Buchberger, who won two Stanley Cup rings with he Oilers. ``But we
know they haven't seen us at our best yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
