<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNFB-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA HEARS FROM CSUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the eve of the Cal State Northridge football
team's spring scrimmage, coach Jeff Kearin was 2,000 miles away,
testifying before the NCAA's infractions committee.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin and at least three CSUN officials _ interim president
Louanne Kennedy, athletic director Dick Dull and faculty athletics
representative Tom Shannon _ appeared at the committee's
closed-door hearing in Indianapolis Friday. However, all that is
assumed because the NCAA has issued no press release and it won't
acknowledge the hearing took place.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is one of the final steps in the NCAA's
investigation into the school's handling of its inquiry into the
football program last summer that resulted in the firing of coach
Ron Ponciano, the forced resignation of assistant Rob Phenicie and
self-imposed penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano and his lawyer, Scott Campbell, also were scheduled to
answer questions for the infractions committee. Ponciano contends
in his settlement claim for wrongful termination that the
university's report, released last August, is ``flawed as it is
long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2206EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TRIBUNE-CARROLL-645&AMP;A     04-14 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIBUNE-CARROLL-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES TIMES TO GET NEW PUBLISHER AND EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Md., Fla., Ky.)   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times, whose newsroom staged a revolution last
year against the newspaper's leadership, will be turned over to new
leadership soon after the merger of its parent company, Times
Mirror, with Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   According to editors briefed by top newsroom leaders on Thursday
evening, Michael Parks, the editor, will be replaced by John S.
Carroll, the editor of The Baltimore Sun, another Times Mirror
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher, Kathryn M. Downing, will be replaced by John
Puerner, who is president and publisher of The Orlando Sentinel but
has been working with Tribune and Times Mirror executives in recent
weeks reviewing The Los Angeles Times' operations.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear when the formal announcement of the new
appointments will be made, because the $8 billion merger deal is
not complete.
</P>
<P>
   But whenever the announcement comes, it is clear that in pairing
Carroll and Puerner, Tribune executives are arranging a marriage of
a highly respected figure in the old media world and an energetic
apostle of the possibilities of new media.
</P>
<P>
   Puerner, as publisher of The Orlando Sentinel, has worked with
the editor, L. John Haile, to turn The Sentinel into a showcase of
the Tribune's ambitions in multimedia reporting and news delivery.
At the age of 49, he is fluent in the Internet language, say
executives who know him well. Last fall, he helped engineer a
partnership intended to bring The Sentinel's news to Central
Florida users of Sprint's high-speed Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Tall and courtly, Carroll made his reputation in a world where
dot-com companies were still unknown. Now 58, he has pursued a
reporting and editing career based on intense scrutiny of public
institutions and resistance to intimidation from those who disliked
his work, including the U.S. military in Vietnam and University of
Kentucky basketball fans.
</P>
<P>
   In 27 years of editing, Carroll has helped journalists win six
Pulitzer prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Acel Moore, an associate editor at The Philadelphia Inquirer who
credits Carroll, his former city editor, with helping bring him and
a colleague a 1977 Pulitzer Prize for investigative reporting,
said, ``He's a man who will genuinely guard and protect
journalistic integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The moves are apparently intended, at least in part, to calm the
still-simmering resentments at The Los Angeles Times over the
decision of Downing to share revenues from a special issue of the
newspaper's Sunday magazine with the Staples Center, the sports
arena that was the focus of the magazine's coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Parks has said he learned of the Staples Center decision, for
which Downing apologized, after the magazine was printed, but he
made no move to scuttle the issue or inform readers of the deal. He
later said he regretted his failure to act.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore early this year, after the Nieman Foundation
curator Bill Kovach announced that he was stepping down, it became
clear that Carroll, who had been the top editor at The Sun since
1991, and was a top editor in Lexington, Ky., for 12 years before
that, was mulling over his future.
</P>
<P>
   By early last month, Carroll had made plans to let his
publisher, Michael Waller, know that he was talking with Harvard
University about becoming the Nieman curator, and planned to accept
if the job was offered, said a person familiar with Carroll's
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Then on March 13 came the announcement of the $8 billion merger
between Tribune Co. and Times Mirror. Now Jack Fuller, the
president of Tribune Publishing, needed to hear Carroll's news.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller did not want to hear it. Within three weeks, the person
said, Fuller made his counteroffer. Carroll was asked to leave The
Baltimore Sun, with its 385 journalists and a circulation of
315,000, to become the editor of The Los Angeles Times, with its
more than 1,000 journalists and a circulation of 1,078,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At The Times, the enthusiastic reviews of Carroll's former
colleagues heartened many journalists who were still sore from the
series of shocks that the past six months had brought. Some, like
John Arthur, a managing editor, made a point of praising Parks as
``an excellent editor'' who had endured ``difficult
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, who declined to be identified, worried that two
Easterners from smaller papers would have trouble understanding the
complexities of their newspaper and of Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-TURNER-NYT &LR;      04-14 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-TURNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBERT TURNER, 64, ADVISER TO MARTIN LUTHER KING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ind.)   By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Albert Turner, a civil rights leader and adviser to the Rev. Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr., died on Thursday in Selma, Ala. He was 64.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's heart stopped while he was being prepared for an
operation to stop abdominal bleeding, said his brother, Robert.
</P>
<P>
   Turner helped lead the voting rights march from Selma to
Montgomery, on March 7, 1965. Stick-wielding state troopers turned
the peaceful protesters back on the Edmund Pettus Bridge over the
Alabama River in a confrontation that became known as Bloody
Sunday. Protesters were beaten, chased and tear-gassed. Turner,
wearing a cap, can be seen in contemporary photographs of the front
lines of marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the events of that day, Turner said in an interview:
``I fell down and ran. Then I fell down again and ran some more.''
</P>
<P>
   J.L. Chestnut, a Selma lawyer and longtime friend of Turner,
said, ``Whenever there was something of unusual danger, and nobody
wanted to, you could count on the fact that Albert and John Lewis
would lead it.'' Lewis later became a Democratic congressman from
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who was Alabama field secretary for the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference at the height of the civil rights
movement, was chosen three years after the march to lead the mule
wagon that carried the body of King at his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a sharecropper, Turner was born on Feb. 29, 1936, in
a four-room shack outside Marion, Ala. He was the fourth of 12
children. He studied bricklaying and later graduated from Alabama
A&AMP;M. In July 1963, with the help of a federal injunction, Turner
and about 40 others registered to vote at the county courthouse in
Marion. Lawsuits surrounding these efforts to register formed a
model for President Lyndon B. Johnson's voting-rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do not know of a single individual in Alabama who has
given more to the political progress of African-Americans in this
state than Albert,'' Chestnut said. ``Albert would hide the fact
that he would have a college degree, because he was trying to reach
always those people at the bottom. Martin understood that, and
that's what endeared Albert to Martin, and why Albert was the point
man in Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Evelyn, Turner was cleared of voter fraud in the
1980s, when prosecutors charged them with altering absentee ballots
collected from rural blacks.
</P>
<P>
   After the ``not guilty'' verdict, President Ronald Reagan
nominated Turner's prosecutor, Jefferson B. Sessions, to the U.S.
District Court in Alabama. The nomination died in the Senate
Judicial Committee after concerns were raised about the voter-fraud
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indictments come because blacks have gotten too well
organized for political empowerment in the Black Belt of Alabama,''
Turner said at the time he was acquitted. ``They didn't spend a
million dollars because they think a few old folks' ballots were
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Turner, an insurance salesman, served on the
Perry County Commission, where he was active in preserving adequate
health care in the county, where many hospitals serving rural
communities are closing. He was also on the search committee to
find a new police chief for Marion, the county seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very smart and knowledgeable about politics in this
area of Alabama,'' said another commissioner, Charles LeCroy. ``He
supported everything King advocated, and he brought his people up
socially, economically and politically during his time in office.
He'll be missed by people here in Perry County.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner is survived by his wife; three sons, Barrett of
Indianapolis, Eric of Birmingham, Ala., and Albert Jr. of Marion; a
daughter, Eldra Marcus of Tuskegee, Ala.; nine brothers and
sisters, and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
