<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7494 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CANADA-CINAR-ART-3TAK     04-14 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CINAR-ART-3TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAKE-BELIEVE WORLD, ON SCREEN AND OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent as NYT25 to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 16)  
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In ``Arthur,'' America's most popular children's
cartoon show, Buster is a floppy-eared rabbit who loves playing
detective. But if ``Antenna Ears'' could hop off the drawing boards
here at the Cinar Corp., he would run into a rich trove of
mysteries without leaving the company's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, why did Ronald Weinberg and Micheline Charest,
Cinar's husband-and-wife founders, shovel $122 million _ the
equivalent of one year's revenue _ into an obscure Bahamas
investment fund last year without telling their board? Why did
Cinar put the name of Micheline's sister Helene on 115 cartoon
episodes she did not write, earning Cinar about $650,000 in
royalties that later had to be repaid? And did Cinar, as some
politicians contend, falsely credit Canadians for the work of
American scriptwriters to get Canadian government subsidies?
</P>
<P>
   Although Buster and his classmate Arthur, an 8-year-old
aardvark, neatly solve mysteries by the end of a half-hour episode,
the questions about Cinar remain unanswered more than a month after
word of the Bahamas investments became public. That news wiped out
three-quarters of the company's market value before trading was
suspended in Canada and on Nasdaq. Angry shareholders have filed
class-action lawsuits, and the company is under investigation by
securities watchdogs and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the answers, presumably, could come from Weinberg and
Charest, who started the company in 1976, shortly before moving
here from the United States to pursue a dream of making nonviolent
cartoons. But on their lawyers' advice, they aren't saying much.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of misinformation has come out since last October,''
Weinberg, 48, said by telephone Thursday from the couple's home in
Montreal's exclusive Westmount neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   In another brief conversation Friday afternoon, Charest, 46,
said, ``It has been very frustrating not to be able to talk.'' Amid
the furor, she has resigned her positions on the boards of Quebec's
largest supermarket chain, Canada's largest telephone company and
North America's largest printing company.
</P>
<P>
   Reports say Cinar is up for sale, though its fate will be
determined by the couple, who remain on their company's board and
who jointly control 62 percent of the voting shares. Cinar's new
bosses have brought in psychologists to counsel depressed workers.
</P>
<P>
   But they say work on new cartoon series is under way _ and
officials of WGBH, the Boston public television station that is
co-producer of ``Arthur,'' promise that new episodes will be on the
air this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we are sitting here on our knees is not accurate
at all,'' said Peter Moss, president of Cinar Entertainment, the
company's production unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The founders got in a big mess,'' Moss said. ``But that is
something happening at the corporate level. The creative level of
the company is as strong as ever. They fell. We didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``Arthur,'' other animated and live-action series that
Cinar sells to programmers in 150 countries include ``Wimzie's
House,'' ``Are You Afraid of the Dark?'' and ``The Busy World of
Richard Scarry.''
</P>
<P>
   The squall buffeting Cinar has exposed more than skulduggery
behind the scenes of the outwardly benign world of children's
television. As regulators in Washington decide whether to renew an
arrangement that speeds the listing of Canadian companies on
American exchanges, the Cinar scandal has given fresh life to
worries that Canada has lax oversight of publicly traded companies.
</P>
<P>
   And in both Hollywood and Montreal, a growing center for
``runaway'' film and animation productions from the United States,
the affair is opening a debate over Ottawa's policy of giving
multimillion-dollar subsidies to support the production of Canadian
movies and television shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make an interesting movie one day _ but not a
cartoon, because too many investors have been burned, because the
reputation of Canada's leading stock exchange has been called into
question,'' said J. Richard Finlay, a management consultant who
runs the Center for Corporate and Public Governance, a private
policy research organization in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Cinar's woes are just the latest to tarnish the reputation of
the Toronto Stock Exchange, Canada's leading stock market.
Companies that have collapsed in scandal under Toronto's watch are
Bre-X Minerals Ltd., a prospecting company; Livent Inc., the
theater company founded by the producer Garth Drabinsky; and YBM
Magnex International Inc., which the American authorities accused
of having links to the Russian Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinar is bad because we had the benefit of all those previous
disasters, and yet we see the same recurring problem: a company
board dominated by insiders,'' Finlay said.
</P>
<P>
   Until March 6, four of the nine members of Cinar's board were
insiders: the founders; Marie-Josee Corbeil, who remains executive
vice president of Cinar Entertainment; and Hasanain Panju, who was
the company's senior executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   On that day, the company announced that Weinberg and Charest had
resigned their executive posts _ though not their board seats _ and
that Panju had been fired and kicked off the board. Though Cinar's
new management initially blamed Panju for the offshore dealings, a
company spokeswoman, Suzan Ayscough, later said Weinberg signed
several of the transfers.
</P>
<P>
   Charest was also aware of the transfers, according to an
affidavit filed in a Bahamas court by Nicholas Martin Hodson, a
fraud investigator in Toronto for Ernst &AMP; Young, Cinar's auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Panju, who declined to be interviewed, has acknowledged his role
in transferring some of the money, but said through his lawyer that
he did nothing wrong and that all of the money invested in the
Bahamas would be returned to Cinar. Jacques Rossignol, the lawyer,
said that he was preparing a wrongful-dismissal suit against the
company and asserted that Panju was being made a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the one sacrificed for this,'' Rossignol said.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto exchange has guidelines intended to guarantee
independent, outside control of company boards, including the
recommendation that an independent director serve as chairman. At
Cinar, Charest held that post until last month, when she was
replaced by Lawrence P. Yelin, a Montreal lawyer and longtime Cinar
director.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Exchange officials declined to comment on Cinar's problems. But
David Brown, chairman of the Ontario Securities Commission, one of
the two Canadian regulatory agencies investigating Cinar, warned in
a speech in late March that Canada ``faces the prospect of falling
behind'' Britain and the United States in making boards independent
of management.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could open a corporate credibility gap _ one that could
erode confidence in Canadian board practices and undermine
investment in Canada,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be an especially untimely development, given that in
Washington, the Securities and Exchange Commission is reviewing the
status of a unique, nine-year-old arrangement that gives virtually
automatic SEC approval to securities documents prepared in Canada
according to American guidelines. In those nine years, Canadian
companies have raised more than $150 billion through debt and
equity issues in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The comment period on the plan closed last summer, and SEC
officials will say only that the agreement is still under review. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Bloc Quebecois members of parliament made their
accusations last fall that Cinar was slapping ``made in Canada''
labels on American cartoons, the company ordered Ernst &AMP; Young to
conduct an internal audit. It led in unexpected directions, and on
Feb. 18, the board was briefed for the first time on the Bahamian
fund transfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard `Norshield, Norshield, Bahamas,''' recalled one of
the outside board members, who asked not to be identified _ and the
directors, this person said, asked, ``What's that all about?''
</P>
<P>
   The explanation from the auditors was that $122 million in
corporate funds had been invested secretly with Norshield
International Ltd., a Bahamas affiliate of the Norshield Financial
Group, a Montreal investment house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt betrayed; we were lied to,'' this board member said.
``Emotions ran quite high.''
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to save his position, Weinberg sent a letter on March
2 to Norshield in Nassau _ marked ``urgent, urgent, urgent'' _
demanding that the money be transferred to Cinar's account with a
Canadian bank there, according to Hodson's affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Norshield refused, saying that the money, plus any investment
gains, would be returned gradually this year as investments
matured, with the final payment scheduled for Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the money, they continue to manage the money, and
they will pay it back on time,'' said William Urseth, a Norshield
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But Cinar's new leadership remains suspicious, noting that the
company had to go to court in the Bahamas late last month to force
Norshield to disclose where the money was invested.
</P>
<P>
   ``What investor do you know of that won't show the client where
his funds are invested?'' asked Barrie Usher, the former insurance
company executive brought in to be president and chief executive of
Cinar after the founders stepped aside.
</P>
<P>
   That suit has been suspended, however, and Norshield is now
giving the Cinar board an inventory of the investments. Both sides,
now bound by a confidentially agreement, will say little more.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Dent, an analyst who follows the Canadian entertainment
industry for Yorkton Securities in Toronto, remains skeptical. ``If
there was nothing going on except conventional investing, I don't
know why the people in the Bahamas were so reluctant to reveal
details,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such skepticism about Cinar and its business dealings was in
short supply until very recently. Dazzled by a share price that
leapt an average of 50 percent a year in the late 1990s,
journalists and investors seemed to have forgotten to ask the tough
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Canadian Business magazine wrote glowingly: ``If you
missed out on Disney, one of the best investment opportunities of
the century, consider Cinar Corp. This Montreal production house
delivers big _ and consistent _ payoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article a few months earlier in Maclean's, Canada's
leading news weekly, David McFadgen, an entertainment analyst with
Griffiths, McBurney &AMP; Partners, called Cinar ``an incredible
success story.'' Reached after the stock collapse, he said: ``How
were we supposed to know? We rely on their auditors. We can't go in
and audit their books.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the flow of cash over a year's time to the Bahamas was
not detected by Ernst &AMP; Young, which declined to comment on the
episode.
</P>
<P>
   Although a Cinar news release has termed the Bahamas investments
``unauthorized,'' relations between Cinar and Norshield have been
close for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Marleau, who served on Cinar's board from 1993 to 1998,
is president of Palos Capital, a merchant banking firm in Montreal
that is part of Norshield Financial. Last November, Mario Ricci,
who as Cinar's vice president for operations signed off on several
cash transfers to the Bahamas, left to become Norshield Financial's
vice president for finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can say this looks cozy, but not to me,'' said Dale
Smith, the chief financial officer of Norshield Financial. ``It's a
free world. People are allowed to move from one company to another
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Marleau and Ricci did not return telephone messages seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   As part of what often seems an uphill effort to promote Canadian
cultural identity, Ottawa doles out millions of dollars annually to
support film and television production by Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   And Cinar has been a major beneficiary. In 1998, the last year
for which the company has issued complete financial reports,
Cinar's total government subsidies equaled its profits _ about $15
million. From 1993, the year Cinar went public, through 1998, the
company received about $50 million in subsidies, substantially more
than its reported total earnings of about $37 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Royal Canadian Mounted Police is trying to determine
how much, if any, of those thin profits came from fraud.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
