<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7496 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-CANADA-CINAR-ART-3TAK     04-14 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-CINAR-ART-3TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MONTREAL: from fraud.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The agency's investigation began after opposition lawmakers used
their parliamentary immunity to levy accusations on the floor of
the House of Commons in October. They say Cinar had illegally
obtained federal tax credits by claiming Canadian authorship for
scripts that in fact had been written by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The implications for Cinar were huge. If American work was
passed off as Canadian, television networks here could demand
refunds. By law, they must broadcast a daily quota of Canadian-made
programs, which invariably are more expensive than imported ones.
Even the tax write-offs that Cinar took for donating to museums the
original artwork of supposedly Canadian-made cartoons could be
called into question.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Cinar officials sought to deflect the parliamentary
accusations, saying they were motivated by partisan politics.
Indeed, Cinar has cultivated good relations with Canada's ruling
Liberal Party. A Liberal senator, Jack Austin, sits on the board,
and Micheline Charest has been an important Liberal Party donor and
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   But just before Christmas came the first confirmation that Cinar
was giving credit for scripts where none was due.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 23, Charest wrote a check to reimburse European
television customers for royalties they had paid her sister Helene
for scripts she had not written. Helene Charest, a stockbroker in
Quebec City, did not return telephone messages, though
investigators say she has cooperated with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did speak to Helene Charest, and she was straightforward
and she admitted that she never wrote any stories or any scripts at
all,'' said Sgt. Pierre-Yves Carrier, a Mountie spokesman in
Montreal. The Mounties are continuing to investigate the
allegations that the true authors of many Cinar scripts have been
Americans, not Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   Hinting at what that investigation will conclude, Cinar said on
March 10 that it would have to revise its financial statements for
the last three years, ``for issues related to tax incentives,
disclosure of related party transactions and unauthorized
transactions.'' The restated financials will be ready at the end of
May, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for shareholders in the class-action suits argue that
misrepresentations by Cinar inflated share prices. ``From 75 to 90
percent of their net profits were composed of tax credits,'' said
one of the lawyers, Paul Unterberg, of Unterberg, Labelle, Lebeau &AMP;
Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations of cronyism are ricocheting through government
circles and Canada's tight-knit entertainment world. Carrier said
the Mounties had received ``zero cooperation'' from the government
agency that verifies Canadian content, the Canadian Audio-Visual
Certification Office. The agency says it can surrender the tax
documents that the Mounties are seeking only after a crime is
formally charged.
</P>
<P>
   Quebecois opposition members of parliament also contend that
Cinar developed a cozy relationship with Telefilm Canada, the
nation's largest source of federal film subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   At least two executives have moved from jobs at Cinar to
positions at Telefilm, or vice versa. And Gilles Duceppe, leader of
the Bloc Quebecois, has contended that Thomas LaPierre, son of
Telefilm's chairman, Laurier LaPierre, was falsely credited with
scripts for a Cinar situation comedy called ``Chris Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Basile, spokeswoman for Telefilm, said the elder
LaPierre would not comment on the accusation, adding: ``It's an
allegation. Nothing is proven.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the appearance of chumminess has fueled calls in the United
States and Canada for tighter controls, or outright cuts, in
Ottawa's film subsidies. Critics say the local industry has grown
beyond its infancy and can walk on its own two feet.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration on Thursday in Los Angeles, members of the
Motion Picture Screen Cartoonists union contended that tax
subsidies were helping lure jobs to animation studios in Montreal
and Toronto. Citing the Cinar affair, a union news release said
that exporting of jobs to Canada was ``putting American screen
cartoonists out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   In Montreal, where local and expatriate film and animation
productions generate about 30,000 jobs and nearly $1 billion a year
in revenue, The Gazette newspaper recently published an editorial
titled ``The Sins of Cinar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be clear by now that tax credits are an invitation
to plunder the public treasury,'' wrote The Gazette, the city's
English-language daily. ``The best outcome from the Cinar scandal
would be an end to the liberal practice of dishing out public money
to film companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Business, rebounding from its boosterism of a year ago,
wrote in a recent editorial titled ``Hollywood's Welfare Bums''
that Ottawa's subsidy program ``doesn't even pay effective lip
service to the ideal of promoting Canadian culture _ you know,
Canadian stories, by Canadians, for Canadians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a subsidy, plain and simple, paid to companies such as
Cinar,'' the editorial said. ``Now, does that sound like an
effective use of your tax dollars?''
</P>
</TEXT>
