<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-GLOBAL-PROTESTS-     04-14 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GLOBAL-PROTESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: STOPPING THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, April 15:
</P>
<P>
   In Washington this weekend, a disparate gathering of protesters
will be rallying against what they view as the malign forces of
economic globalization.
</P>
<P>
   The dissidents' message is sometimes confused and misplaced,
especially in wanting to dismantle essential institutions like the
World Bank, the International Monetary Fund and the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters, who call themselves the Mobilization for
Global Justice, also represent a popular response _ misguided but
heartfelt _ to a worldwide economic transformation that is not
fully comprehended even by the experts. To be sure, some interest
groups are trying to manipulate public concern for their own
advantage. But it would be dangerous to ignore a growing popular
unease over these trends and the need for broader educational
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dramatic stock market decline on Friday, the fact
remains that the United States has on balance benefited from the
unbridled flow of capital, goods, people and information that is
called globalization.
</P>
<P>
   The dislocations felt by American workers have been far
outweighed by the benefits of cheap imports, low inflation and
expanding opportunities for American businesses overseas. Abroad,
the poor countries benefiting from expanded markets outnumber those
hurt by them.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the new world order has created hardship in
declining or newly uncompetitive industries. Some nations see
globalization as a code word for American domination. Many fear
that the World Bank, IMF and WTO are pursuing the interests of an
American-led elite, to the detriment of the poor and the
environment. Critics on both the left and right have begun to
question whether the world would be better off without these
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the institutions that manage the world economy must be
more sensitive and transparent. But their real challenge is to help
everyone understand that there is no realistic _ or beneficial _
way to reverse or even slow the forces that are driving the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Just as American businesses have begun to discover that in the
world of an Internet-driven economy the old rules have to be
scrapped or adjusted, so countries around the world will have to
learn to adjust to the new market forces if they want to harness
them to their advantage. Underdeveloped countries have to learn
that capital is voluntary, and does not flow to countries that do
not obey its rules.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Cold War, there have been at least four
major currency crises that threatened to destabilize regional
economies: in Europe in 1992-93, Mexico in 1994-95, East Asia in
1997 and Russia and Brazil in 1998. Each had the potential for
spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The critics descending on Washington argue that the IMF and the
World Bank sometimes made these crises worse, while their defenders
assert that without the difficulties inflicted, the crises would
have grown worse. One thing is certain. There will be more crises
to come in the years ahead. The institutions that handle them need
to be reformed, not weakened.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-globalization protesters invoke the tactics and styles
of the 1960s. But a closer analogy may be early struggles over the
burgeoning of capitalism in the 19th century. It was then that
disputes between owners and workers and about public costs and
private gain led to an age of ideological conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Today's struggle has the added element of changing definitions
of national sovereignty. Indeed, poor countries are not the only
worriers. Europeans are also increasingly wary of American demands
to open their economies to American products. As boundaries become
more economically irrelevant, one question is whether people will
seek refuge in their national identities or in the familiar if
transitory comforts of placards, chants and street theater in
places like Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Yet today's global economic drama is deeply familiar to students
of American history _ how to reconcile the demands of economic
growth and opportunity with the need to preserve fairness,
stability and the health and welfare of each country's citizens. It
is today a challenge without borders. Meeting it calls for more
sophisticated international institutions, not a retreat into
nostalgia and economic nationalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000414.0443 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7499 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-U.S.-CHIEF-400&AMP;AD     04-14 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-U.S.-CHIEF-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCE OR ELSE, NEW CHIEF TELLS USOC 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The bottom line. Those were the first _ and appropriate
_ words that Norm Blake, the aggressive new chief executive officer
of the U.S. Olympic Committee, used to describe his opening meeting
Friday with the leaders of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's goal is to make the USOC run like an efficient and
self-reliant corporation answerable only to the bottom line and the
top podium. Within the next three years, sports that are not
producing medals will be forced to develop other means of
financing.
</P>
<P>
   When he presented his 39-page business plan to the 19 voting
members of the executive committee Friday, Blake said that many of
the members were stunned by the force and immediacy of his plans.
Nonetheless, they voted unanimously to agree in principle to his
proposal. In a luncheon meeting Saturday, the committee is set to
reaffirm Blake's plan and give him the go-ahead to restructure the
USOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is there is a commitment to become more a
performance-oriented organization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who has been on the job for 60 days, admitted that in not
being able to consult with all the constituents of the umbrella
organization _ which includes 45 national governing bodies of the
different Olympic and Pan American sports, community-based
organizations and athletes _ he gave an impression of trying to
railroad his plan into approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no choice,'' he said. ``If you want to initiate change,
you need to build up momentum. If you try to do things
incrementally, the inertia of a situation overcomes it, then it
never gets going.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next 45 days, before the next board of directors meeting
in June, members will have a chance to refine the basic principles
of Blake's plan. But the strategy is in place. In July, Blake said
he will begin negotiating business plans with the winter sports
organizations to determine how much financing they will receive.
After the Sydney Olympics, by mid-October, he hopes to start
negotiating business plans with the summer sports.
</P>
<P>
   The 45 national governing bodies rely on the USOC for between 6
and 85 percent of their funds. The committee will increase the
funds for some groups, and decrease it for others. In addition,
Blake plans to cut as many as 70 jobs to streamline the
bureaucracy. ``It will be three years from now before the full
effect of the new dynamic is in place,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To transform the committee into a viable business that will
attract other corporations as sponsors and improve medal
performance, Blake plans to name a chief financial officer, and
hopes the respective governing bodies install a CFO as well. Each
governing body will have an account management team that will work
on joint marketing plans.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Locke, the executive director of USA Triathlon and a
member of the USOC transition team, said he believes the majority
of the executives support Blake's initiatives, especially because
he seems willing to evaluate each sport on the merits of its
individual business plans. ``He's not taking a cookie-cutter
approach and we like that,'' Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   Sports that do not participate in the Olympics, but only in the
Pan American Games, such as racquetball, are in danger of having
their USOC funds reduced, Blake said. Other sports that are on the
cusp include table tennis, team handball and the biathlon.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the bottom line, a sport like volleyball or men's
soccer has the potential to win only one medal, yet it uses a lot
of resources for its staff and athletes. The USOC does not want to
support a struggling sport unless that sport can show it can go out
and raise money on its own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
