<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW SCRIPTURE HAS INSPIRED POETS, FROM DONNE TO MILTON TO AUDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jews preparing for Passover and Christians intent on the coming
Holy Week cannot be expected to pay much heed to the fact that
April is National Poetry Month. But perhaps they should.
</P>
<P>
   Christians _ and not only Christians _ could find sustenance,
for example, in Peggy Rosenthal's ``The Poets' Jesus,'' just
published by Oxford ($29.95). It is a short, reader-friendly
account of how poets have rendered Jesus, primarily from the 19th
century to the present, from William Blake's Jesus as Romantic
poet-hero to Ranier Marie Rilke's Jesus as disillusioned anti-hero;
from the political, revolutionary or sometimes imperialist Christ
of Third World poets to the ignored or exiled Jesus of Czeslaw
Milosz; from the absent Jesus of the Welsh priest-poet R.S. Thomas
to the surprisingly present Jesus of Denise Levertov, Kathleen
Norris and Annie Dillard.
</P>
<P>
   The book is also, in passing, a swift overview of the last two
centuries of Christian theology and Western culture. A few of the
chapter titles tell the story: ``Jesus as Christ and More: The
First Eighteen Centuries.'' ``Jesus as Romantic Hero.'' ``Sliding
Into Modernism: Jesus Pale and Shrunken.'' ``Crisis of the
Secularized West: Postmodernism's Jesus as Antihero.'' ``Jesus
Absent.'' ``Jesus Present.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Poetry has always been a privileged medium through which a
culture talks of, and to, its gods,'' Rosenthal writes. ``Poetry,
that is, searches and stretches language to probe the questions of
life's ultimate meanings that people everywhere have asked. Even
where Jesus of Nazareth is not claimed as Incarnate God, even where
that claim is dismissed out of hand, he still engages poets.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal was a co-editor, along with Robert Atwan and her
husband, George Dardess, of ``Divine Inspiration: The Life of Jesus
in World Poetry'' (Oxford, 1998). That anthology, in turn, sprang
from ``Chapters Into Verse,'' a two-volume collection of poetry in
English inspired by the Bible, edited by Atwan and Laurence Wieder
and published by Oxford in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   They are rich sources for seasonal reading, along with ``The
Gospels in Our Image: An Anthology of Twentieth-Century Poetry
Based on Biblical Texts'' (Harcourt Brace, 1995), edited by David
Curzon. Is there a major poet, whether devout or defiant, who has
not been inspired by Scripture? Here are Donne and Milton,
Wordsworth, Byron, Dickinson, Yeats, Pound, D.H. Lawrence, Dylan
Thomas, Pasternak, Borges, Paul Celan _ the range is enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Poets fill out the moments that Scripture telegraphs, give life
to the figures that appear and drop from sight: Pharaoh's daughter,
Pilate's wife, Barabbas, Magdalene.
</P>
<P>
   The second stanza of Anna Akhmatova's brief ``Crucifixion,''
translated by Stanley Kunitz and Max Hayward, goes simply:
</P>
<P>
   Mary Magdalene beat her breasts and sobbed,
</P>
<P>
   His dear disciple, stone-faced, stared.
</P>
<P>
   His mother stood apart. No other looked
</P>
<P>
   Into her secret eyes. Nobody dared.
</P>
<P>
   Another Russian poet, Yevgeny Vinokurov, jolts readers with an
unexpected pieta: a six-line evocation not of Mary but of ``The
Mother of Judas'' _ yes, he must have had a mother _ weeping at the
feet of her hanged son.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there is no book like ``The Poets' Jesus''
focusing on the Israelites' exodus from slavery. The first volume
of ``Chapters Into Verse,'' covering the Hebrew Scriptures,
includes just a handful of related poems, many of them (since the
anthology is of English-language poetry) written from a Christian
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Wieder, a poet and translator of the Psalms who is preparing a
one-volume paperback version of ``Chapters Into Verse'' for
publication next fall, could not think of major contemporary poems
specifically taking off from the events commemorated at Passover,
although, he said, ``any time people are talking about shaking off
tyranny or liberating themselves, they are talking about Exodus.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about contemporary poets' treatment of Jesus' suffering
and crucifixion, Rosenthal mentioned how many simply feel ``we've
lost our ability to pay attention to the Passion,'' a result not
only of secularism's challenge to religious beliefs but also of
``the distractedness of modern life.''
</P>
<P>
   W.H. Auden diagnosed that distracted condition in ``Horae
Canonicae,'' she said, the cycle of poems that he wrote from 1949
to 1954 and organized according to the ``canonical hours'' that
structured the daily prayer of monks, nuns and priests.
</P>
<P>
   The poems are permeated with the sense that civilization, with
all its social roles and competencies, unavoidably rests on sin,
error, routine and victimization: ``For without a cement of
blood,'' Auden writes, ``no secular wall will safely stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, at the heart of the cycle are the hours between noon
(``Sext'') and 3 p.m. (``Nones''), when Jesus was thought to have
been dying on the cross. Jesus is not mentioned by name, only ``the
victim'' and ``this dying.'' (Indirection, Rosenthal notes, is the
homage that contemporary religious poetry typically pays to
secularity, as though modern disbelief can be overcome only by a
flanking movement and not frontally.)
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, ``the blood/ Of our sacrifice is already/ Dry
on the grass,'' Auden writes, but ``we are not prepared'' _ ``what
shall we do till nightfall?'' The crowd disperses. ``The hangman
has gone to wash, the soldiers to eat:/ We are left alone with our
feat.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite alone. ``The shops will reopen at 4,'' the poet
continues, and there is time for a soothing nap, and ``time/ To
misrepresent, excuse, deny,/ Mythify, use this event/ While, under
a hotel bed, in prison,/ Down wrong turnings, its meaning/ Waits
for our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, much more to Auden's ``Horae Canonicae.''
For Rosenthal, it is one of many contemporary poems declaring that
while Jesus or, equally, the God of Moses ``is very much present,''
as she puts it in her book, ``it is we who are absent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
