<HEADLINE>
AT TALLADEGA TRACK, EXPECT SPEED, PATIENCE, NERVE (AND RAIN?) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Talladega Superspeedway is long and it is
wide. To get a feel for it, just think of driving on the outside
with cars racing four across.
</P>
<P>
   Think rush-hour traffic, except everybody is pressing the
accelerator as if living beyond the moment is not a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talladega is the most nerve-racking experience that you can go
through as a driver,'' said Tony Stewart, last season's Winston Cup
Series rookie of the year. ``The concrete wall was about a foot
away from me and the guy on the inside of me was about three or
four inches away from me. I can only imagine what the middle two
guys felt like. You've got guys behind you. You've got cars in
front of you. You've got cars beside you, and you're running 195
mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Stewart was exaggerating. Chances are the pack was
only going 175 to 185 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't seem to get settled down and get in a rhythm,''
he said. ``It's not about what you and your car can do. It's about
what everybody else is doing to you and your car.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise that Stewart, part of the Joe Gibbs Racing
Team, has learned that patience is imperative in Sunday's race.
Especially since it involves the use of restrictor plates, which
uniformly inhibit speeds, making it virtually impossible for
someone to run away from the field.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor may be thrown into Sunday's race: rain.
Persistent gloomy weather has an impact on racing. On Thursday,
qualifying for Sunday's event was wiped out by inclement weather.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was not as bad. A steady drizzle stopped in the
afternoon, and qualifying commenced an hour later than scheduled.
Still, the times suffered.
</P>
<P>
   In an aborted session that was to be continued Saturday morning,
Jeremy Mayfield's top speed of 186.969 mph. was the slowest here
for a potential pole-sitter since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers are expected Saturday, with the possibility of
more rain Sunday. In the 31-year history of the track, only two
Winston Cup races were postponed a day by weather, in 1978 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Mayfield in qualifying was Bill Elliott, who had a
186.936 run. Elliott on Sunday will become the 12th driver, six
still active, to start his 600th Nascar race.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett , the defending series champion, posted a 186.747,
nosing out the crowd favorite, Dale Earnhardt, for a third place
start.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt is seeking to win his third straight race here. The
Intimidator has won nine races here, more than twice as many as any
other driver.
</P>
<P>
   Among the gloomier faces was that of Jeff Gordon, who is without
a victory this season after winning three overall titles since
1995. His 184.136 lap left him far back in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a rocket ship,'' Gordon said. ``We've just got some
things we have to work on. We'll do that and get better.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
