<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON SAYS SURPLUS SHOULD GO TO DEBT, NOT TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTBURY, N.Y. _ Highlighting what has emerged as perhaps the
sharpest policy difference between them in the Senate race, Hillary
Rodham Clinton asserted Friday that New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's call for deep, across-the-board tax cuts financed by the
national surplus was a threat to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton said, the surplus should be used primarily to
pay off the national debt, and she offered a plan to do that by
2013.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, taking a position that closely tracks President
Clinton's posture in congressional budget talks, said that she
would support using only $250 billion of the projected $746 billion
surplus for tax cuts, and that the reductions should be directed at
specific groups, like first-time home-buyers and parents putting
children through college.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Giuliani, answering questions about Mrs. Clinton's
proposal at a news conference at City Hall, said he would support
sizable cuts in personal and capital gains tax rates. Although
Giuliani declined to endorse any specific plan, he clearly sided
with congressional Republicans who are pushing a tax cut plan that
could be twice as large as that advocated by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered her views on taxes, the national debt and the
surplus _ subjects that seem likely to shape many congressional
elections this year, including the one in New York _ in a speech in
which she sought to present herself as the fiscal conservative in
the race for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeatedly assailed Republican tax proposals as
``risky,'' as she offered herself as a lifelong advocate of fiscal
discipline and approvingly noted her husband's successful effort to
eliminate the deficit during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be _ and I will be _ a steady and strong voice for
fiscal discipline and a balanced budget in the United States,''
Clinton, the Democratic candidate for Senate, said to 1,300 people
who turned up for a breakfast here sponsored by the Long Island
Association, a Commack-based business group. ``I grew up with a
father who didn't believe in credit cards, who paid cash for our
house. And I have a hard time breaking those habits, and will put
them to work in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani told reporters in Manhattan that he believed that
sizable reductions in both the income and capital gains tax rates
would be a boon to New York state's economy, and would be
particularly helpful upstate, which has suffered economic decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best way to help upstate New York,'' Giuliani said.
``If you want to help upstate New York cut some of the taxes,
particularly the income tax, where we disproportionally pay it, and
you're going to leave money in the upstate economy, that then can
be used for more jobs, more commercial activity, more economic
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Their remarks Friday underscored a strong point of disagreement
between two candidates who share a number of similar views. With
his comments, Giuliani signaled that he _ like his party's presumed
presidential candidate, George W. Bush _ believed that cutting
taxes was an issue that held sway with voters, notwithstanding
evidence in polling and some recent political contests that it is
not as potent an issue as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, to some extent, is embarking on a fairly unorthodox
route in her campaign: running against a tax cut. That said, her
emphasis on eliminating the $3.5 trillion debt is part of her
continuing effort to portray herself as a moderate Democrat, at a
time when Giuliani has sought to present her as far more liberal
than most New York voters.
</P>
<P>
   There is a dispute between Republicans and Democrats about the
size of the projected 10-year surplus; Clinton, like her husband
and most Democrats, embraced the lower figure of about $750
billion. Of that, she said, 40 percent, or $350 billion, should go
to paying off the national debt, with $250 billion for tax cuts.
The remaining $150 billion, Mrs. Clinton's aides said, would go to
financing various programs, like a prescription drug plan for
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In offering her proposal, Clinton _ using language that echoed
much of what the president has said _ asserted that the tax cuts
proposed by the Republicans would undermine the prosperity that the
first lady said was the result of the economic policies of the last
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not support a tax cut that would force us to abandon
the force of fiscal discipline and spend the surplus before we have
paid down the debt,'' she said. ``We all know that some of the
noisiest voices in our country are those who say we should spend
the surplus on a large, untargeted, across-the-board tax cut. You
know, the road to risky tax cuts may appear to be easy _ and it
certainly has short-term political gain attached to it _ but it
will, inevitably and ultimately, lead to exploding deficits and a
return to the higher interest rates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
