<SLUG> BC-CAR-RACER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM COME TRUE FOR QUINTANILLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From the motocross tracks of Southern Texas to the
streets of Southern California, Rolando Quintanilla has taken a
road less traveled to open-wheel racing.
</P>
<P>
   But ask the Pepperdine sophomore from Calabasas what the two
types of racing have in common and he'll rattle of a laundry list
of similarities between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are cooperation and teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned how to win a championship and I learned how to work
with a team,'' the 19-year-old Quintanilla said between practices
at Phoenix International Raceway in preparation for the Indy Lights
season opener on Sunday during the Grand Prix of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   An Indy Lights rookie, Quintanilla tasted success early in life,
winning a 50cc Texas state motocross championship when he was 9.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Quintanilla has risen through the ranks of the U.S.
Formula Ford 2000 series and various SCCA divisions before landing
a seat in an Indy Lights car for Conquest Racing in last year's
California Speedway race.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his debut was less than auspicious _ he finished
18th after his day ended with a collision with David Pook _
Quintanilla earned a full-time ride with the team for the 2000
campaign. He joins veteran Indy Lights drivers Felipe Giaffone and
Chris Menninga on the Conquest Racing team owned by Eric Bachelart.
</P>
<P>
   Bachelart has decided to treat Quintanilla with kid gloves for
this weekend's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expects too much from him and I don't want to put any
pressure on him,'' Bachelart said. ``My expectations are for him to
race clean and get some points. With three cars in the race, I have
different expectations for each driver. For Rolando, I want him to
finish the race. I want him to be running up front by the end of
the season. I think I have to put more pressure on him every time
and he has to progress all year.''
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't come as a surprise that Bachelart is going to be
patient with his young rookie. The two are practically family.
Quintanilla's father, Roberto, and Bachelart raced against each
other on the Indy Lights series in 1991. It was at the Denver Grand
Prix, where both the elder Quintanilla and Bachelart finished on
the podium, that Roberto told Bachelart that he was going to retire
at season's end and focus on his son's racing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a long-term relationship with his father,'' Bachelart
said. ``I remember giving Rolando a picture with my autograph on it
that day. We know each other very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the Long Beach race has been a little frustrating
for the Mexican-born rookie. Testing at Phoenix and Sebring
International Raceway in Florida, as he has been doing for the past
few weeks, has helped Quintanilla get familiar with his car. But
the conditions he has been practicing under can't be duplicated to
match the ones he'll have to battle on the temporary road course at
Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   In Quintanilla's favor, he at least knows the odds are stacked
against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting and nerve-wracking at the same time,''
Quintanilla said. ``This will be the first street course I have
competed on in Indy Lights and it will be close to home. A lot of
people will be behind me down there. I want to do well and I am
hoping that I do well. But I know I am the youngest driver out
there. I know it will be a surprise if I do well. I just don't want
to run before I learn how to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Bachelart echoed Quintanilla's attitude toward racing at Long
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be silly to think his car can win this year,''
Bachelart said. ``I want to build up his confidence. For me,
Rolando is the future. He's very young and he's very talented. But
I want him to progress every time we go to race.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to competing in the season opener in front of a home
crowd, Quintanilla will have the added pressure of racing for an
owner who is a past Indy Lights champion at Long Beach. Plus, he is
the first second-generation driver to compete in Indy Lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally, being in Indy Lights and racing in Long Beach, is a
dream come true,'' Quintanilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Landing in Southern California was a dream come true as well.
Quintanilla said he wanted to come to L.A. mainly for two reasons.
First, he was to go to school at Pepperdine, the same school his
sister attended and graduated from. Second, he wanted to be close
to go-kart tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I graduated from high school, I was racing shifter
karts,'' Quintanilla said. ``Most of the races were in California,
and Southern California has a lot of tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   School is as important to Quintanilla as his racing career. He
is majoring in international business and political science and has
aspirations of being an Indy Lights team owner some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``School is a lot of fun,'' he said. ``It keeps me focused when
I'm not driving.''
</P>
<P>
   If Quintanilla can have a successful season, he will be driving
for long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My long-term goal is to drive as long as my sponsors can
support me,'' Quinatnilla said. ``The doors of the world aren't
exactly closing for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
