<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-BENGALS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bengals covet Warrick
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The Cincinnati Bengals enter today's NFL Draft with
disgruntled Corey Dillon and Carl Pickens still on the roster, but
the club is full of optimism that Florida State wide receiver Peter
Warrick will join the club with the No.4 overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cleveland Browns tap Penn State defensive end Courtney
Brown with the first pick and the Washington Redskins grab Penn
State linebacker LaVar Arrington and Alabama left offensive tackle
Chris Samuels at Nos.2 and 3, look for the Bengals to take Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lippincott, director of pro/college personnel, said he'd
consider doing somersaults and back flips in the ``War Room'' at
Spinney Field if the Bengals land Warrick, who would join
quarterback Akili Smith in an exclusive club of potential No.1
overall picks spurned by the Browns in back-to-back drafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most explosive, exciting player in college
football,'' Lippincott said. ``He's an excellent route runner. He's
got phenomenal hands. But probably even better than all that, he's
so exciting after he makes the catch. He's got those running
back-quick instincts that just make him very, very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Bruce Coslet feels equally as strong about the
electrifying 5-foot-11, 194-pound Warrick, who in nine
regular-season games in 1999 caught 71 passes for 934 yards (a 13.2
average) and eight touchdowns. He also rushed for three TDs, scored
on a 75-yard punt return and threw a 35-yard TD pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's exciting,'' Coslet said. ``You get the ball to him 10
times and he's going to score twice. A lot of people say he's not
fast enough. He's fast. He's quick as heck. He's an exciting punt
returner. He's got great hands. He's a pattern technician. He's
just a heck of a player, a big-time player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be disappointed if he's there (at No. 4),''
Brown added. ``I think he's good. He's a top-line college prospect.
If he's the one we end up with, we would be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL _ having undergone an offseason of turmoil with
Baltimore linebacker Ray Lewis and ex-Carolina wide receiver Rae
Carruth facing murder chargers _ has placed a great deal of
emphasis on character issues leading up to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is particularly so this year because of all that
has happened,'' Brown said. ``We're all familiar with the different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to Warrick's personal baggage. He and teammate
Laveranues Coles were arrested last fall for purchasing more than
$400 worth of designer clothing for $21.40 at a Dillard's
department store with the help of a clerk. Coles was booted off the
team, while Warrick served a two-game suspension and pleaded guilty
to misdemeanor petty theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think character is a problem for him,'' Brown said.
``I know what his run-ins have been and I think he has faced up to
them, and my opinion is that he'll be OK for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN reported the New York Jets were trying to ship three of
their four first-round picks (Nos. 13, 18 and 27) to the Bengals in
exchange for the fourth pick, where New York would select Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to teams, but do I have anything to report? No, I
don't,'' Brown said. ``We haven't made a deal and that's where it
stands right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured the Bengals will get plenty of telephone calls from
teams who want to move up. The Philadelphia Eagles, at No.6, and
Jets, whose first pick comes at No.12, admire Warrick.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bengals stay put, look for them to select a cornerback,
safety and running back as insurance in case Pro Bowler Dillon _ a
restricted free agent who vows to sit out the first 10 games of the
year _ isn't traded. They'll also add depth to the offensive and
defensive lines.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: Brown is building the team around Smith, who needs
protection and weapons to succeed in his first full season as
starting quarterback in new Paul Brown Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the key for us,'' Brown said. ``If he can get up and
running, we will surprise people. We will be better than people
might suspect. That's the most important thing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
