<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-L.A.-SCHOOL-CORTINES-     04-14 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-SCHOOL-CORTINES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `PIED PIPER' IS SHAKING UP THE SCHOOLS IN LOS ANGELES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT27 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ramon C. Cortines does not put much stock in the
trappings of power. His spotless desk at the Los Angeles Unified
School District headquarters is not in the spacious
superintendent's suite, but in a small ascetic office just down the
hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's graaaaand,'' Cortines said of the bigger office
before adding matter-of-factly: ``And I'm not the superintendent.''
</P>
<P>
   But in just over three months as interim superintendent of the
nation's second largest public school system, Cortines has shown
himself to be quite comfortable with the exercise of power. He was
brought in to shake up a system in crisis, and he has.
</P>
<P>
   In a hundred days, he has moved to end the practice of social
promotion, to scrap construction of a costly half-built high school
on a toxic former oilfield and to make a new reading program and
new professional training mandatory. And this week, a school board
that has seldom agreed on anything voted unanimously to adopt his
plan for reorganizing the district into 11 semiautonomous units in
an effort to bolster local control and improve student performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's here as a change agent,'' said one board member, Caprice
Young. ``That's why we picked him.''
</P>
<P>
   In a career in education spanning nearly 45 years, Cortines has
taught English and social studies; held senior jobs in the federal
Department of Education; and run school systems in California _ in
Pasadena, San Jose and San Francisco _ and, for two tumultuous
years, in New York City. But he insists he will not stay in Los
Angeles beyond July 1, when a nationwide search is to have produced
a permanent superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm getting old,'' said Cortines, a trim, dapper man
who will turn 68 in July but who works out every day in his home
gym in Pasadena and fills his glen plaid suit with the grace of a
man half that age. ``In the last year and a half, I have really
learned to enjoy the free time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to notice. Cortines still routinely arrives in the
office before 6 a.m., holds his first meeting by 6:30 and is at
headquarters, or just as likely, visiting schools, parents and
teachers, until well into the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a Pied Piper,'' said Kam Kuwata, a political manager
who has known Cortines since he was assistant superintendent in
Pasadena in 1970 and Kuwata was a student government leader in the
midst of a crisis over busing. ``Wherever he went, he got a few
more people involved around him. He has an unquenchable thirst for
information, and a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines calls the Los Angeles assignment ``the most difficult
one I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like today,'' he said in an interview, ``I was dealing with
the problem of several early childhood programs that don't talk to
each other. And that's been encouraged. It took me about three
weeks to find that there was a planning office, because it had
fallen out of favor.''
</P>
<P>
   He might not be here to see the outcome of the most delicate
challenge: contract negotiations with the teachers' union. The
school board voted this week to begin bargaining with a raise of
about a third of what the union was seeking, along with an offer of
merit pay for teachers who improved their students' scores on
standardized tests, which the union opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in merit pay, and I've never used the `m'
word,'' Cortines said, noting that his preference would be for a
system that rewarded the staff of entire schools that improved
their performance. He acknowledged that standardized tests were
just one way to measure student achievement. But with dozens of the
district's 790 schools ranking at the bottom in a recent statewide
rating system, Cortines said, ``You've got to tie this to some sort
of assessment, instead of getting into this debate, `Is it perfect,
does it measure what is taught?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you,'' he said sharply, ``what that says to me is
that nobody wants any accountability and they want the status quo,
and I think that's insidious racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Cortines knows about defying expectations. His biological mother
was a Mexican-American from San Antonio. ``I was a bastard child,
and you know, she wanted better,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He was adopted by a couple in San Francisco. His father, of
Castilian Spanish descent, was the head salad chef at the Plaza
Hotel on Union Square, and his mother, of British ancestry, worked
at the Kaiser shipyards in World War II. They were neither rich nor
well educated, but insisted that their son visit museums, take
piano lessons, and attend the San Francisco Symphony's Saturday
children's concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents told me that I came home in the fourth grade and
said I was going to be a teacher,'' Cortines recounted, but added
that even now, he does not know quite why. ``I guess it was a good
experience for me.'' To this day, when schoolchildren ask what he
does, he replies, ``I'm a teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the days when the worst thing he and his schoolmates did
was play hooky from the symphony were gone for good. He insists
that schools must stop scapegoating children and parents for poor
performance, and instead do whatever it takes _ like Saturday
classes, coordination with community groups and experiments with
vouchers _ to improve learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kids need to be able to know and do is very different
from when I grew up,'' he said. ``We're never going to go back to
the two-parent family. Just because middle-class, middle-aged
people like me think it's not right if you don't have it the way it
was when we were young, let me tell you: That's not the way it's
going to be. The question is, how do you maximize the potential of
that child, using the community resources that are there?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
