<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 14, 2000 -- BARZUN-CULTURAL-HISTORY --
Jacques Barzun was one of the founders of ``cultural history.'' For
nearly 50 years he taught history at Columbia, eventually becoming
its provost, and led legendary seminars with Lionel Trilling. He
has written over 30 books, translated nearly a dozen more, and now,
at the age of 92, he has finished an epic chronicle of his
historical forays, a survey of 500 years of Western cultural life.
Barzun in his Manhattan apartment earlier this month during an
interview. (Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NASSAU COUNTY, N.Y. -- April 14, 2000 -- NY-PAROLE --
Since the early 1990s, parole rates for violent felony offenders
have plummeted. Over the same time, parole rates for non-violent
felons stayed relatively steady at about 75 percent for first-time
applicants. Experts say the change in parole policies is part of a
national trend. In part, this has been encouraged by Congress's
truth in sentencing legislation. However, states have also
instituted tougher parole policies for violent offenders. Probation
officers and members of Nassau police check the van of a parolee
during a surprise visit as part of Operation Night Watch last year.
No contraband was found in the van and the man was allowed to
continue on his way. (Vic Delucia/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- April 14, 2000 --
GORE-MEADOWLANDS -- Bill Shaheen is the most vocal leader of an
alliance of 84 organizations and municipalities fighting efforts by
a Virginia-based developer, and major Democratic contributor, to
fill in 90 acres in the heart of the wetlands to build Meadowlands
Mills, a glitzy 2.1-million-square-foot shopping mall. Shaheen, 54,
a former rock and jazz drummer and taxi dispatcher, on the disputed
field. (Scott Shepard/Cox News Service)
</P>
