<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-BREWERS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves find cure in Brewers
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The Brewers were the perfect solution for the
Braves, off to their worst start since 1996 at 4-5 after being
swept in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers started 24-year-old Steve Woodard, who hadn't won a
game since July 1999. They're minus four players acquired in recent
trades, all on the disabled list. And they're playing in front of a
brick and steel reminder of a year's delay in construction at
Miller Park, which sits just beyond center field.
</P>
<P>
   So it wasn't the Cubs and the cold. It was mild in Milwaukee and
the Braves took full advantage with a 6-3 victory, their first win
since leaving Turner Field on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After being stunned in three games by the Cubs, the Braves were
perfectly content to get back to the status quo, moving to 7-1 in
County Stadium since the Brewers joined the National League in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   It was the site of possibly the worst start of Tom Glavine's
career last May. But Friday was about as far removed from that as
it gets. While he equaled the number of runs allowed in each of his
first two starts (two) to the first two batters of the game,
Glavine allowed one run over the next seven innings to collect his
second win of the season. Kerry Ligtenberg and Mike Remlinger
finished, with Remlinger getting the final out for his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Quilvio Veras and Reggie Sanders, both of whom entered the game
hitting .200, broke out at the plate. Sanders, who had been moved
from second to seventh in the order for the game, doubled and
scored a run to tie it at 2 in the fourth inning. Veras doubled to
drive in the go-ahead run in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Javy Lopez underscored their work with a two-run home run to
left off Curtis Leskanic in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   While Glavine settled down, the Braves had drawn even on a
double and a run each from Andres Galarraga and Sanders. Woodard
lost his 2-1 lead on a mistake in the fourth when he gave Walt
Weiss a breaking ball to hit with two outs and Glavine on deck.
Weiss connected for a single to right, with Sanders scoring from
second to tie it at 2.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga set the tone for a little offensive awakening from the
newly tinkered Braves lineup when he ripped a double past Jose
Hernandez. He scored by forcing the issue on Bobby Bonilla's bloop
hit to left, drawing a wild throw from left fielder Geoff Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, meanwhile, allowed only two singles to catcher Henry
Blanco and a walk to Charlie Hayes over his next five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
