<HEADLINE>
ACHING FOR A VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ On Wednesday, it was an allergic reaction
that caused red spots to pop up on his body. A day later, he was in
bed most of the day after catching a cold.
</P>
<P>
   As strange as it might sound, there is no better way for Adrian
Fernandez to attack a CART FedEx Championship Series race weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time I feel sick, I do something good on
the track,'' said the 34-year-old Patrick Racing competitor from
Mexico City. ``Right now, my body is aching.''
</P>
<P>
   However, even with the aching body, Fernandez managed a big
smile after winning the provisional pole position for the 26th
running of the Toyota Grand Prix of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is some work to be done, Fernandez is the
quickest driver after posting a best-lap time of 68.636 seconds at
an average speed of 103.223 miles per hour on the revamped 11-turn,
1.968-mile circuit on the streets of Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a special moment for me,'' said Fernandez,
whose only previous pole position was in 1998 at the U.S. 500 at
Michigan Speedway. ``I'm happy to get the (provisional) pole
position and think we can hold it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who was also the fastest in a morning practice
session, will lead the fastest drivers from Friday's session in the
final qualifying today at 2:30 p.m. The slower drivers from Friday
will begin their final qualifying effort at 1:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the track is better than it's ever been,'' Fernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new section, which comes after the drivers circle the
parking garage adjacent to the Aquarium of the Pacific and proceed
east on Shoreline Ave. before darting on to Pine Ave., should
create some more excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track gives you more time to enjoy the circuit,'' said Max
Papis, the third-fastest qualifier who pilots the Ford-powered Team
Rahal Reynard and is the early points leader after winning the
season-opener in Miami. ``Last year's circuit was too many twists
and turns and a little place to pass. Passing is going to be better
in the race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
