<HEADLINE>
FOXSPORTS.COM OFFERS NIFTY BASEBALL SEARCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a time to be a fantasy baseball geek.
</P>
<P>
   By launching its handy Sports Geniuses Sports Search this week,
FoxSports.com has provided virtual nirvana for the fantasy-baseball
enthusiasts or trivia buffs who hound the newspaper sports desk.
</P>
<P>
   Users accessing the search (sportssearch.foxsports.com) can
simply type in a question about a major-league team or player from
1876 to the present and get an instant answer.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, ask it anything. It has millions of answers.
</P>
<P>
   What was the Rangers' wins and losses for 1996? Up pops the
answer with links to the team's pitching statistics for '95-96. Of
course, it can be stumped. It can't give you former Rangers general
manager Tom Grieve's nickname (answer: Tag).
</P>
<P>
   The search is programmed to find such data as a player's uniform
number, the park surface he plays on, detailed pitching information
_ everything except what he thinks about riding on a New York
subway.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Geniuses Sports Search might remind online users of Ask
Jeeves (ask.com), the all-purpose search site that accesses
hyperlinks to specific questions. But because it actually gives
answers instead of a list of links related to the question,
FoxSports.com's newest feature is better than Ask Jeeves.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Ziering, president and founder of Waltham, Mass.-based Fact
City, developed the search feature because he was frustrated that
he couldn't get quick answers to simple questions on other sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this, you can get answers back without spending a lot of
time looking,'' Ziering said.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint news release, the two companies cited an analyst's
opinion that a fact-finding search engine kept users on the site of
origin. It beats the ``traditional way of where you go to a page,
go to another page and on and on,'' said Danny Greenberg,
FoxSports.com senior vice president. ``With this, you simply type
in the keywords.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports Geniuses Sports Search is part of FoxSports.com's
continuing upgrade of baseball content. News Digital Media,
FoxSports.com's parent company in New York, recently acquired Stats
Inc., a company in Chicago that manages and provides sports
information content and analysis.
</P>
<P>
   With Stats Inc. on board, FoxSports.com is carving a big niche
with baseball content, taking on rivals TotalBaseball, ESPN.com and
CBS SportsLine. And it should get even better with FoxSports.com's
plan to release an online baseball almanac in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership also means the development of search sites for
other sports, such as college basketball, college football and
professional golf, by the fall, Ziering said.
</P>
<P>
   That would be geek heaven.
</P>
<P>
   BYTES: SportsYA! (www.sportsya.com), an interactive Spanish- and
Portuguese-language sports portal based in Miami, has signed Clyde
Drexler, Nadia Comaneci, Mark Spitz and Janet Evans _ all former
Olympians _ to provide online commentary. ... As if Charles Barkley
didn't get enough air time, his Internet-only talk show debuted
last week on Nike's Web site (www.nike.com//cbn). Once you get
through all the necessary video plug-ins, users can watch Barkley
interview guests in front of a live audience in Las Vegas. ... The
San Francisco Giants obviously benefit from Silicon Valley. Nearly
half of all the Giants' single-game tickets were sold on their site
(www.sfgiants.com).
</P>
<P>
   COOL CONTEST: Here's a way to keep track of bonuses in
major-league baseball: TodaysSports.com Auction Prize Program. Fans
bid on baseball memorabilia and can earn cash bonuses if the player
associated with that item reaches a predetermined goal. For
example, the winning bidder on the Rafael Palmeiro-autographed bat
will win $50,000 if the Rangers first baseman wins the 2000
American League batting title.
</P>
<P>
   CHATTING ON THE RUN: Jerry Dunn, a 54-year-old runner from
Spearfish, S.D., who plans to run 200 marathons in 2000, is
scheduled to chat live from noon to 1 p.m. Monday on Active.com
while he runs the Boston Marathon. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
