<HEADLINE>
TIGER TIME NO BONANZA FOR SPORT OF GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Wall Street
Journal used this week's post-Masters tournament lull to explore an
irony discussed occasionally in this space since golf's Tiger era
began.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tigermania has made golf more popular as a spectator sport, but
the emergence of Tiger Woods as the game's supernova is not
translating into a playing boom or a business bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   The particulars of my columns on the subject were in the same
vein as those analyzed by The Journal story. Of the 26 million
Americans who last year played 530 million rounds, only 5.4 million
golfers played more than 25 times. These avid golfers were
responsible for about 60 percent of the industry's $30 billion
annual revenue. The 1999 numbers aren't much different from 1998's,
or 1988's for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders say the lack of growth is due to a failure to
do a better job of marketing the game to potential golfers who need
schmoozing and coaxing. The industry's lagging fortunes are
especially discouraging given the high expectations generated by
the arrival of the charismatic Woods in 1996 and his
record-shattering Masters triumph the following spring.
</P>
<P>
   A Fortune magazine headline proclaimed, ``Tiger! Now the Sky's
the Limit for Golf _ the Game and the Business.'' If anything, it
has been just the opposite for the business end of the game. Many
equipment companies have failed, and the survivors have seen sales
plummet along with their stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   What went wrong? Nothing really. Golf is as difficult as it is
enchanting. The Scots invented the game many centuries ago. It's
been said of these dour people that they're born expecting very
little comfort during their passage through this vale of tears and
are seldom disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem golf faces is an apparent obsession by course
developers and their financial backers with pricey layouts amenable
to promoting residential development.
</P>
<P>
   Although golf in the Kansas City area seems to be faring
reasonably well, signs of this problem abound locally. My
perception is shaped by two factors. One is a golf fanaticism that
leads me to play 85 to 100 rounds a year. More recently, however,
has been the experience of writing a book about public golf in
Kansas City, to be published by The Star in six weeks or so.
</P>
<P>
   My ``research,'' as my colleagues snickeringly characterize it,
involves playing all publicly accessible area courses. Too many of
the recently developed courses, even those undertaken by
municipalities, have been conceived as high-end, high-cost
operations. They're inordinately expensive and intimidating for
average golfers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, most of Kansas City's older courses, publicly
and privately owned alike, are unpretentious, highly playable
layouts affordable by the working-class and seniors with limited
incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward cities pushing pricey golf layouts to encourage
developers to do the heavy financial lifting is antithetical to the
interest of most community residents. Part of it is ego and part
economics, and it works against the interests of the local golfing
community as well as the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Golf's inherent difficulty works against its becoming a game for
the masses, but course development trends guarantee its stasis.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
