<SLUG> BC-DIPTUBE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY LAW FIRM FILES OBJECTIONS TO WATER HEATER SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A Kentucky law firm
is challenging a settlement to fix millions of defective water
heaters, claiming that it falls short of protecting the consumers
it is supposed to help.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bishop and Wilson, a Louisville law firm, filed its objections
at the U.S. District Court in Kansas City, where a hearing is
planned for next week on whether the settlement should receive
final approval.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm, according to the court filing, plans to argue that
the settlement fails to meet the standards of fairness and adequacy
for a class-action lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers have ``not been adequately represented by the present
class counsel,'' according to the Bishop and Wilson filing.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Phalen, co-lead counsel in the lawsuit, said Thursday that
a reply to the Bishop and Wilson allegations would be filed with
the court Friday. A copy of the document, however, was not
available Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which received preliminary approval in November,
involves about 14 million water heaters made by the country's
largest water heater manufacturers. It spelled out a campaign to
notify consumers about the problem and a system to reimburse them
for repair costs.
</P>
<P>
   The water heaters contain a defective plastic pipe called a dip
tube, which can break apart, causing diminished supplies of hot
water. As the tube disintegrates, it can also plug faucets and
plumbing with plastic chips. The defective tubes were made by
Perfection Corp., which then sold them to the water heater
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Next week's hearing in Kansas City comes as 24 state attorneys
general appear near their own settlement with the water heater
manufacturers and Perfection Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the very final stages,'' said Chris DeWitt, a
spokesman for the Michigan attorney general, whose office is
leading the settlement talks.
</P>
<P>
   Details of what might be in the settlement were not disclosed.
But it is assumed it will focus more on any alleged violations of
consumer protection laws and any penalties or fines that should be
assessed against the companies involved.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the settlement of the class-action lawsuit dwells
on repairing the water heaters. U.S. District Court Judge Howard
Sachs in Kansas City gave his preliminary approval to the
settlement last November, which allowed the repairs to begin. He
now must decide whether the settlement should get final approval.
</P>
<P>
   The firm of Bishop and Wilson claims that it shouldn't. Among
the settlement's deficiencies, it says, is that not enough has been
done to notify consumers who have to request the repairs. About $3
million was spent publishing notices about the settlement in
various publications, but the Kentucky law firm claims that more
needs to be done to directly notify consumers who have the
defective water heaters.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop and Wilson also claims that since no estimates are made
about the total value of the settlement, there is no way to
determine whether the $5.6 million in fees being sought by lawyers
representing consumers in the case is justified.
</P>
<P>
   The administration of the settlement's repair program has not
been without its glitches since it began in November. Consumers had
difficulty receiving claim forms and delays in receiving the
repairs. Those problems, administrators said, were fixed.
</P>
<P>
   But many consumers say various problems still exist. Rex Newbold
of Shawnee, Kan., for instance, recently received a letter from the
settlement's administrators that said his water heater had been
bought at Home Depot, which supposedly didn't sell water heaters
with the defective dip tubes.
</P>
<P>
   The letter puzzles Newbold. His water heater isn't the brand
that was sold by Home Depot. The water heater also was in his home
before 1997, when Home Depot entered the Kansas City area market.
Only the builder of Newbold's home, however, can say where the
water heater was purchased, and he hasn't returned Newbold's
telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``About all I can do is wait,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
