<HEADLINE>
KINGS INTEND TO GET MORE OFFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Los Angeles Kings spent nearly an entire workout
Friday on drills designed to attack the Red Wings zone.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit dominated between the blue lines in Thursday's 2-0 loss
and Kings coach Andy Murray said that would not happen this
afternoon in the second game of the best-of-seven first-round
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be much better there,'' he said. ``What we need to do
right now is simple. Score goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though top forwards Ziggy Palffy and Bryan Smolinski were
playing their first game after serious injuries, the Red Wings
limited the Kings' two top lines to just one shot in the first two
periods and none by Glen Murray for the entire game.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille probably had the Kings' best scoring chance with
a blast from the point at the 13 minute mark of the third period.
Palffy also had a good chance late but was pulled down by Sergei
Fedorov.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Murray said there would be no lineup changes, instead
working the players in three-on-two drills for almost an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to keep the pressure on,'' said Ian Laperriere. ``Just
like we did all season.''
</P>
<P>
   During the year, the Kings went 2-2-1 against Detroit and used
their size and mobility to cause matchup problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Red Wings bottled up the Kings and made it
difficult to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our toughest first-round opponent,'' said Steve
Yzerman, who is expected back after missing Thursday's game with
the flu and a tender knee. ``They're a better team than their
record indicates. You watch their team closely and they're a big,
strong team, well organized and well coached.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Quick whistles: The Kings will fly back to L.A. immediately
following today's game. The players switched hotels on Friday after
loud construction made it difficult to sleep before Thursday's
game.... Jim Nill, assistant GM for the Red Wings, has been
mentioned as a candidate for the vacant Calgary job.
</P>
</TEXT>
