<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' NEWMAN PUTS ON A SHOW, BUT MAGIC IS NOT UNDONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Johnny Newman did practically everything
imaginable in the second half on Friday night to help the New
Jersey Nets end their season-long losing streak at eight games. He
hit 3-pointers while hands blocked his vision, short jumpers while
being hounded by opponents, and driving layups while under duress.
</P>
<P>
   But Newman's 27 points in the second half were not enough to
lift the injury-depleted Nets over the Orlando Magic. Getting 45
points from its starting backcourt of Darrell Armstrong (23) and
Ron Mercer (22), the Magic prevailed, 96-88, handing the Nets their
12th loss in their last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring 15 straight points for the Nets, the 36-year-old Newman
cut a 77-68 deficit to 84-83 with four minutes 17 seconds
remaining. After the Magic answered, the Nets' Keith Van Horn
scored on a runner to cut the lead to one point again. But the
Magic, behind two jumpers by Armstrong, scored six straight points
to pull away.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn scored 25 points, including 18 in the first half, and
had 17 rebounds for the Nets, who never led. In a dominating
performance, Ben Wallace grabbed 20 rebounds for the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Nets, the Magic did not have to search for
motivation. With four games remaining at the start of the night, it
was tied with the Milwaukee Bucks for the eighth and final playoff
spot in the Eastern Conference. Milwaukee, which played Charlotte
on Friday night, owns the tie breaker, having whipped the Magic by
a combined 41 points in their three meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Don Casey did not try to sell his team on the spoiler's
role, though. Instead, he reminded them that the Nets had not won
since the Magic all but ended their faint playoff hopes with a
103-97 victory on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since we lost to them, we've lost eight in a row,'' Casey
said before the game. ``So there might be a little revenge, get
even, whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   But returning the favor would be difficult with Stephon Marbury
and Kerry Kittles on the sideline for their sixth and fifth
straight games, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn did his best to help the Nets overcome early on,
carrying the Nets in the first quarter with 10 points and seven
rebounds. The Nets were fortunate that he was on target, because
the rest of the team combined to make only five of 18 shots in the
first quarter. Behind Van Horn, the Nets trailed by 24-20 heading
into the second quarter, despite allowing the Magic to secure an
outrageous 22 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn received some help in the second, as Elliot Perry
scored six points and Lucious Harris added eight to keep the Magic
from pulling away. Though the Nets never took the lead, the deficit
never swelled past six points, and the Magic led by 45-39 at
intermission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
