<SLUG> BC-BANK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY LOST FOR ALMOST 30 YEARS FOUND IN FORMER BANK'S NIGHT DEPOSIT
BOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For almost three
decades, David Haake's $45 cash deposit hid from human eyes,
trapped inside the metallic guts of a night deposit drop box at the
former Metropolitan Bank at 75th Street and Troost Avenue.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The evening of Nov. 21, 1971, Haake slipped his cash into an
envelope, pulled the drop box open and dropped the money in. At the
time, he was 17 years old and working at a pet store for $1 an
hour. The $45 was for 45 hours of cleaning cages, stocking pet food
and sweeping floors.
</P>
<P>
   The evening was his girlfriend's birthday, so he was in a hurry
to celebrate with her. He didn't notice that he'd put the envelope
in the wrong place _ instead of dropping it in the check drop slot,
he had put it in the night deposit drop. One was made for
envelopes; the other for money bags.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later bank officials didn't believe the teen-ager
when he complained that his cash deposit was missing. Eventually,
he forgot all about it.
</P>
<P>
   A few other checks disappeared, too: a check for $1,000 from the
pet store, the Menagerie Inc., dated May 27, 1974; a check for $125
from Carol Edelman, written March 13, 1974; and a $1,050 check from
Harry's Supermarket, dated Jan. 12, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   And the years passed. Haake wouldn't see his money again until
this week _ almost 29 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Bank moved. Other banks moved into the building at
7530 Troost Ave. The last bank moved out in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1999, Bob Wood &AMP; Associates Inc. Realty bought the
colonial style building and moved in.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened in September, the company decided to use the
drive-through teller window during the day and the check deposit
night slot as a convenience for its tenants after hours. In March,
they switched to the bottom night drop box because the slot wasn't
big enough for keys or contracts. The system seemed to work well,
until a few tenants began complaining that they dropped off their
checks but weren't credited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't believe the first one,'' said Brian Bucksner, vice
president of the company. ``But when the number of tenants grew to
five and a few of those were very good paying tenants, I knew
something was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Bucksner investigated by peering inside the drop box.
He spied the corner of a white envelope peeking from underneath the
gray metal plate _ the same inner plate that lifts and pushes
whatever is inside the box every time the drop box is closed.
</P>
<P>
   He called a safe company, which dismantled the drop box hours
later. That's when the mystery of the disappearing rent checks was
solved.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, only a few know what dramas were played out
when the checks first disappeared so many years ago. The checks are
now worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Only one check's owner was found: Fred Ausdenmore, 70, the
co-owner of the Menagerie, who had written the $1,000 check.
</P>
<P>
   Ausdenmore, now retired from his pet store, laughed when told
about the found check and about his former employee, David Haake,
who also lost a deposit. But he couldn't recall if the store's lost
check caused any of his employees' paychecks to bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We transferred money from our business account into the
payroll account,'' he said. ``But I sure don't remember losing
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucksner contacted the five rental clients whose recent checks
were found. And for now, the night drawer is still dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mechanism plate was strictly designed for bags of money,''
he said, ``but the safe company is going to redesign it so that it
will accept checks and money orders safely. But no, we never accept
cash.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Haake, now 46, of Olathe, Kan., getting back his $45
makes for a nice story for him and his wife, the girlfriend whose
birthday it was that fateful evening.
</P>
<P>
   Haake plans to give the money to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She ends up with most of my money anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
