<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CHIEFS RUNNING BACK, TWO OTHERS ARRESTED ON DRUG CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and RANDY COVITZ  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Former Kansas City Chiefs running back Bam
Morris and two others operated a marijuana trafficking ring
financed in part by the team's kick returner, Tamarick Vanover,
according to a federal criminal complaint unsealed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Chiefs President Carl Peterson announced the team
had cut Vanover.
</P>
<P>
   The documents released Friday charged Morris and two associates
with conspiring to transport more than 200 pounds of marijuana from
Texas into Missouri and Kansas. Morris appeared in U.S. District
Court in Kansas City on Friday to face the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   Morris' agent predicted his client would be exonerated.
</P>
<P>
   The records allege that before Vanover pleaded guilty to a car
theft charge in a related case last February, he admitted to an FBI
agent that he had given Morris $40,000 to buy marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for Vanover's cooperation, prosecutors agreed not to
charge him with further crimes arising out of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson announced Vanover's release in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last month, I indicated that I would continue to weigh the
facts as they became known to me as a federal case involving
Tamarick Vanover continued to evolve,'' Peterson stated.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson said he had reviewed the federal records and ``found it
necessary to terminate him as a member of the Kansas City Chiefs.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Peterson announced his decision, Vanover's lawyer,
Michael Yonke, had declined to comment on the charges against
Morris and his client's cooperation with authorities. Yonke could
not be reached for comment Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Also charged with Morris, 28, of Cooper, Texas, were Dewayne
Calvin Bryant, 28, of Dallas, and Robert Corey Myers, 22, of
Warrensburg, Mo. They were charged with one count each of
conspiring to obtain and distribute marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant is in custody in Texas, while Myers remains a fugitive,
said FBI spokesman Jeff Lanza.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, each of the defendants could face up to 40 years
in prison and $2 million in fines. Morris' case
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who retired from the Chiefs after last season, made a
brief court appearance Friday morning after FBI agents arrested him
about 5 p.m. Thursday at the Overland Park, Kan., home of a friend.
U.S. Magistrate Judge John T. Maughmer ordered Morris held in
federal custody until a bond hearing next week.
</P>
<P>
   Shackled at his hands and feet, Morris said nothing during the
hearing. Afterward, Morris' lawyer declined to comment on the
charge, saying he had not yet reviewed the government's evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Lavenstein, Morris' Baltimore-based agent, said he thought
Morris would be exonerated and pointed at Vanover.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very obvious on the face of this affidavit that Tamarick
Vanover is not only attempting to save his (rear) from going to
jail, he's trying to save his NFL career,'' Lavenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Stephen L. Hill Jr. acknowledged that Vanover's
cooperation has been helpful. But he declined to comment on the
disparity between the charge to which Vanover pleaded and the
conduct cited in Friday's records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're satisfied with Mr. Vanover's cooperation at this time,''
Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest allegations are part of a federal drug-trafficking
and stolen-car investigation that has resulted in charges against
at least 26 persons in California, Missouri, Tennessee, Florida,
North Carolina and Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Vanover's former personal assistant, Gregory D. Burns, also is
facing drug trafficking charges. Court records show he, too, is
cooperating with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The charge against Morris offered new insights into Vanover's
role in the alleged conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   According to the records, Vanover acknowledged in three
interviews with FBI agent Larry Tongate that he wrote Morris a
$70,000 check on April 2, 1999. Most of that money was to be used
to buy marijuana in Texas, Vanover said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vanover stated that $30,000 of this money was a personal loan
to Morris,'' Tongate wrote in an affidavit. ``Vanover stated that
Morris was to use the remaining $40,000 to purchase 100 pounds of
marijuana at $400 per pound.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanover also said he had been in telephone contact with Morris
and Bryant to arrange the shipment of marijuana from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   When the dope arrived, however, Burns complained that the
shipment did not weigh 100 pounds and was of poor quality. Burns
told FBI agents later that he eventually sold the marijuana to
Myers and a partner in Warrensburg, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   Burns also said he had misappropriated money that Vanover had
intended for drug purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Once, investigators said, Vanover had transferred $35,000 to
Burns' bank account for a drug purchase. But instead of using the
money to buy marijuana, Burns spent it on legal fees related to a
March 1999 Louisiana arrest for cocaine possession, records said.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the complaint alleges that Morris and the others
conspired to distribute more than 200 pounds of marijuana. Morris'
past
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Morris was convicted for possession of at least five
pounds of marijuana in Rockwall County, Texas. Though Morris did
not serve any jail time for that conviction, he served three months
in prison in 1998 for missing probation meetings related to the
drug conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sumrow, criminal district attorney for Rockwall County, said
his office already has moved to revoke Morris' probation. He said
he also would ask the federal courts in Missouri to hold him in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``A warrant has been issued,'' Sumrow said. ``We will formally
file our motion to revoke on Monday. He is not eligible for bond in
Texas, and we will ask the court (in Missouri) to honor our
statute.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is a two-time offender of the NFL's substance abuse
policy, which led to four-week suspensions at the beginning of the
1996 and 1997 seasons. After signing with the Chiefs in 1998,
Morris underwent weekly drug tests by the NFL and monthly tests by
the authorities in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The new charges stem from an April 1999 traffic stop in Leawood,
Kan., in which Morris and Bryant were found in a stolen Ford
Expedition that contained marijuana residue, court records said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, no drug charges were filed, and Rockwall County
authorities decided not to revoke Morris' probation.
</P>
<P>
   Vanover, who signed a restructured contract on Feb. 29, had been
a regular participant in the Chiefs' off-season conditioning
program that began two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Though cut from the Chiefs, Vanover could be picked up by
another team.
</P>
<P>
   The league has been following developments involving Vanover,
said Greg Aiello, vice president of public relations for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Aiello could not comment on Vanover's specific situation, but he
said players could face discipline for drug-related violations of
law, according to the NFL's substance-abuse program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players being involved in drug-related incidents can trigger
the mandatory evaluation and treatment phase,'' Aiello said. ``You
don't have to wait for a conviction. That is not a punitive action.
That's an attempt to address a problem...for reasonable cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't assume he's not already in the program.''
</P>
<P>
   (30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
