<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NSYNC-(TRIMS)-NYT     04-14 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NSYNC-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MOLTING OF A BOY BAND: 'N SYNC SPREADS ITS WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ko) 
 By JON PARELES    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until last month 'N Sync was the second-banana boy band, seen
almost universally as a Backstreet Boys knockoff. They had followed
an accelerated version of the Boys' game plan: grooming by Trans
Continental Management in Orlando, Fla., material from the same pop
factories that serve the Backstreet Boys and Britney Spears and an
album released first in Germany, yielding European hits and then a
big American payoff. A 1998 Christmas album, ``Home for
Christmas,'' garnered additional sales but not much more respect.
</P>
<P>
   Then 'N Sync's third album, ``No Strings Attached'' (Jive), sold
1.1 million copies in the United States the day it was released,
March 21. Within a week it had sold 1.3 million more, and it has
now passed 3.8 million. The group's entire national tour, which
reaches Madison Square Garden on July 25, is already sold out.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync is, for the moment, the biggest thing in pop: the
people's choice at the cash register. This time, 'N Sync is after
more than popularity. It has reached that inevitable career moment
when, believe it or not, it hopes to be taken seriously for its
artistic ambition.
</P>
<P>
   The sales statistics are a tribute to Jive Records' skill at
building anticipation for ``No Strings Attached.'' The first
million fans bought the album on the strength of a single (``Bye
Bye Bye'') and its video, along with Internet song previews and
mostly 'N Sync brand recognition: the expectation that ``No Strings
Attached'' would not be very different from the band's 1998 album,
`` 'N Sync,'' which has sold 7.9 million copies in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Fans awaited more sweetly harmonized ballads, chiming uptempo
pop tunes and shy but ardent promises of love. In its marketing 'N
Sync retained the pop-pinup style that got the group this far.
What's in the package, however, is a little different. ``No Strings
Attached'' is, for one thing, the first boy-band album with a song
about video cybersex, ``Digital Get Down,'' a clear indicator of
post-pubescent consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync has developed artistic aspirations right on schedule.
Three albums into their career, in 1967, the Monkees demanded to
choose what they sang and a chance to play their own instruments.
After two albums, the Spice Girls started to release solo projects.
A.J. McLean of the Backstreet Boys has lately taken to performing
with his own band as Johnny No Name.
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult, maybe impossible, for teen-age idols to be
content with mere fame and wealth; they want recognition on their
own. No matter how lucrative a fabricated pop product is, rock's
mythology insists that performers can't simply be mouthpieces for
shadowy control-room authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Stars are supposed to mean what they sing, to be expressing
themselves, not following orders.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the egos of young men who hear thousands of girls
screaming their names can't help expanding. Inevitably they want to
unleash their own grand concepts.
</P>
<P>
   So 'N Sync made a break. In legal wrangling that ended with an
undisclosed settlement last year, 'N Sync severed its contract with
Trans Continental Management and switched labels, leaving RCA for
Jive. 'N Sync didn't stray very far; it held on to its manager and
mentor from Trans Continental, Johnny Wright, and moved to the
label that also releases the Backstreet Boys and Britney Spears.
</P>
<P>
   The shake-up was enough for 'N Sync to proclaim its newfound
self-determination; the cover of ``No Strings Attached'' shows five
cute young men who don't want to be puppets any more.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that they're unassisted. On ``No Strings
Attached,'' 'N Sync still draws on Swedish and German songwriters
that they share with the Backstreet Boys. This time, however, Veit
Renn collaborates with JC Chasez of 'N Sync, while the group's main
lead singer, Justin Timberlake, helped write and produce ``I'll Be
Good for You.'' In interviews, 'N Sync's members have insisted that
they chose the album's producers and songwriters themselves.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   They are clearly determined not to simper so much. `` 'N Sync''
and ``Home for Christmas'' were split between smoothly pumping
synthesizer tracks and the style of Babyface Edmonds, with an
acoustic guitar wafting across gently swaying rhythms. The ballads
soothed adults while cozying up to teen-agers, and they landed 'N
Sync on so-called adult contemporary radio stations as well as Top
40 outlets. It's the key to long-running pop sales; young fans rush
out to buy the album immediately while older ones wait for it to
sink in.
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync hasn't entirely jettisoned that approach _ what, and
give up a potential market? _ but its quieter songs don't arrive
until halfway through ``No Strings Attached,'' and there aren't
many of them. 'N Sync now wants to punch up its sound, moving
closer to the staccato impact of hip-hop. If parents don't like it,
they can skip to ballads like the a cappella ``I Thought She
Knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Flush with artistic freedom, 'N Sync heads straight for the
past: specifically the 1980's rhythm-and-blues that sought to
balance pretty melody atop hip-hop's street-level beat. Like the
Rolling Stones discovering 1950s Chicago blues, 'N Sync has latched
onto the highly synthesized, jigsaw rhythms of 1980s phenomena like
Michael Jackson, New Edition and Zapp. In a direct tribute to the
new jack swing of the 1980s, 'N Sync remakes Johnny Kemp's 1988 hit
``Just Got Paid'' with its original producer, Teddy Riley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bye Bye Bye,'' is the opening salvo of 'N Sync's new
pugnacity. Though the vocal harmonies could have been set to a
ballad, the song gives a girlfriend the heave-ho amid choppy
double-time drums and whooshing electronic chords gleaned from
``Thriller.'' Not that the group stays angry; most of the album is
full of the usual boy-band come-ons, as 'N Sync vows to provide
endless love and heal broken hearts.
</P>
<P>
   To be up to date, it borrow's TLC's songwriter and producer,
She'kspere, for ``It Makes Me Ill,'' a put-down of a rival. But
there's also a would-be wedding song in the group's old
sticky-sweet style: ``This I Promise You,'' by the 1980s pop
hitmaker Richard Marx.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly rampant creativity, and 'N Sync's voices are
pallid compared with those of Boyz II Men, Jodeci or Dru Hill. But
at least Chasez's collaborations show glimmers of nuttiness. The
cyberleer of ``Digital Get Down'' arrives with the vocoder-filtered
voices that Cher revived in ``Believe.'' And in ``Space Cowboy,''
amid sputtering electronics and a chorus stolen from George
Clinton's ``Atomic Dog,'' 'N Sync sings about ignoring millennial
prophecies and heading for ``heavenly bodies'' in space instead.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In its own cautious, mild-mannered way, 'N Sync is straining at
the limitations of the boy-band format, trying to add acceptable
levels of personality to its pop commodity without offending too
many consumers. It didn't turn the Monkees into geniuses, either,
but you can't blame a boy band for trying. Next: public squabbles,
tabloid exploits, solo albums, obscure years and a reunion tour
where old fans can bring their children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-14-00 2359EDT &QL; 
